<HEADLINE>
STARS PLANNING AN AVALANCHE OF PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Stars don't just smell blood. They saw it.
</P>
<P>
   It was spilling from Colorado Avalanche defenseman Adam Foote's
face early in Game 2 on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The series is even, but the teams might no longer be.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars took a hit in Game 1 when first-line winger Brenden
Morrow was lost for the season with a fractured right ankle. But
the Avalanche is bloodied and limping, with its top three
defensemen injured only two games into the best-of-seven Western
Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Foote, who has a fractured orbital bone, will not play in Game 3
tomorrow night. Ray Bourque has missed the past four games with an
injured left knee. Sandis Ozolinsh has what the team is calling a
``bruised foot.''
</P>
<P>
   They are the Avalanche's skating wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are planning as if all three Colorado defensemen will
play, but they also know the Avalanche could be the worse for wear.
The Avalanche has only five other defensemen on its roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly don't want to let them off the hook in any
way,'' Stars winger Kirk Muller said. ``We've got to keep getting
it in there and working hard and grinding it out. They're down in
numbers where they've got to use everybody. I think it's important
that we just try to maintain pressure. That's the big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avs' top defensive pairing of Foote and Bourque hasn't been
together since the second period of Game 3 of the Western
Conference semifinals, when Bourque was injured in a loss to the
Detroit Red Wings. Now, with Bourque expected to make his return
tomorrow night, Foote is out.
</P>
<P>
   Only 2:42 into Game 2, Foote was hit under his right eye by the
stick of Stars winger Jere Lehtinen, who was following through on a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   It is a painful injury to the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Foote is Colorado's most physical player with 49 hits, and he
was logging 27:37 of ice time a game before his injury. Foote and
Aaron Miller, who replaced Bourque, helped hold the Stars' first
line to nine shots in Game 1, including only three in the first two
periods combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam Foote is to Colorado what Derian Hatcher is for us,''
Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk said. ``He's a physical
presence, and every time he's on the ice, you've got to watch out
for where he is. He gets a chance to bump you, he's going to do it.
He knew in Game 1 that he had a good chance of containing Mike
\RModano\S, and that's exactly what he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to our advantage that he's not in there, although you
don't ever want to see a guy with a serious eye injury go down.
It's unfortunate that it happened, and hopefully he can return.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars intend to go out of character in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Usually a passive team at the start of road games, the Stars
will try to keep Colorado on its heels, which considering that the
Avs have feet and knee problems, is not the place they want to be.
The Stars are expected to aggressively attack goalie Patrick Roy,
which is what they did in the first 11 minutes of Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really can't let off any bit,'' said Modano, who had no
goals and three shots in Game 1 and two goals on seven shots in
Game 2. ``We have to keep going at them hard, playing the same way.
We really can't afford to let off and give them any time to
recover.''
</P>
<P>
   In losing to the Avalanche, 2-0, in Game 1, the Stars were in
Colorado's zone for 26 minutes, 42 seconds. But they managed only
24 shots, including only 11 in the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' forecheck returned in Game 2, and they got 34 shots,
including 17 in the second period, when Modano's two goals gave
them the lead. The Stars won, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in Game 2 we did a much better job of getting in and
getting on the puck,'' Muller said. ``In Game 1, we kind of sat
back a bit too much. ... We're more effective if we play the way we
did in Game 2, where we're putting pressure on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people talk about our team, they mention defense and all
that. But I think what we'd like to try to do is try to create
pressure like that over 60 minutes and try to wear teams down.
That's a big point of our team.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
