<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE HELPS KIDS MASTER FINANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Assisted by an Internet-savvy elementary school
student, California State Controller Kathleen Connell introduced
her office's Web site for children Wednesday at Balboa Elementary
School.
</P>
<P>
   The site, called ``Kids Sense,'' incorporates sounds, animated
figures and games in an effort to teach children about money,
government and personal finance.
</P>
<P>
   At the site, located at www.sco.ca.gov, children can learn how
much they can earn through a savings account and how to create a
personal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Connell launched the site during a visit to the school in
suburban Northridge, which her son attends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a new economy and the fact that we're
minting new millionaires each day,'' Connell said. ``The sooner
they learn how to invest and save it and spend it prudently, the
better they can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Connell, the state's chief financial officer, introduced the
site via a live Webcast from the school's library.
</P>
<P>
   Students helped by demonstrating how to navigate the site and
asking questions about how it works.
</P>
<P>
   She answered questions from students as well as some that had
come in through the Web site. One written question asked whether
someone without a powerful computer could use the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you have access to the Internet, you will be able
to use this Web site,'' Connell said. ``We had kids around the
state help us. It's meant to be lively and interactive.''
</P>
<P>
   The students receive instruction in how to use the Internet as
part of their regular studies, said Linda Gurian, the school's
technology coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``They learn how to research using the Internet,'' she said.
``It's a very good supplement to what they're doing in school.
We're really trying to incorporate technology into the
curriculum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
