<HEADLINE>
TWO STARS FORWARDS MISS PRACTICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dallas Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner and
center Guy Carbonneau did not practice yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner, who has missed one game in the playoffs _ Game 3
at San Jose _ missed yesterday's practice nursing some aches, while
Carbonneau just took the day off.
</P>
<P>
   In Langenbrunner's place, Jon Sim practiced on the second line
with Joe Nieuwendyk and Scott Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an opportunity with both guys to do extensive off-ice
training really from yesterday to today to tomorrow to have them at
100 percent,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``Jamie and
Carbonneau were at 85 or 95 percent starting the series.''
</P>
<P>
   So, was it Langenbrunner's shoulder, or the mysterious
all-encompassing flu bug?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. It's somewhere between the waist and the head. ... This
will be as good as Lags has been in the playoffs,'' Hitchcock said.
``\RFor\S Carbo, this is just a day off because of old age and
stuff like that.'' \Nsubheds:Long layoff Yesterday being Wednesday,
Game 3 should have been played.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Tina Turner concert in Denver, however, the delay
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am no different than any other player in the league; I think
they drag it out quite a bit,'' Stars defenseman Dave Manson said.
``I would rather be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the Stars have some momentum after playing four
solid periods _ the third in Game 1 and all three in Game 2 _
maintaining it could be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like the last four periods we did play pretty good
hockey,'' Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher said. ``We can't use
\Rthe delay\S as an excuse. We have to put it in our minds \Rthat\S
we have to come out Friday night the same way we did ... whatever
night it was we just played.'' \Nsubheds:Conn Smythe envy Stars
center Mike Modano has never won the Hart Trophy, or Selke Trophy
or any regular-season award in his 11-year NHL career.
</P>
<P>
   He has plenty of others _ including a ``Pass, Punt, Kick'' award
when he was 8 _ and some high school trophies. Sure, they all mean
something, but there another one that really wants.
</P>
<P>
   The Conn Smythe.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, yeah \Rit's bigger than the Hart Trophy\S,''
Modano said. ``The trophies we gain now in the playoffs _ the
Stanley Cup, the Conn Smythe _ I think those outweigh any
individual trophies you can get as far as the regular season. I
think it would be something that would be very rewarding for a long
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
