<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-DOMINICAN-ELECTION-1S     05-18 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-ELECTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION DECLARES VICTORY IN DOMINICAN ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS 2nd and 6th grafs with updated vote totals; SUBS 7th graf
with three new grafs on reaction to voting)   
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ Tantalizingly close to an
outright majority, Hipolito Mejia declared himself the winner of
Tuesday's presidential elections, vowing to ensure that the
Dominican Republic's poorest residents no longer remain bystanders
to the economic boom of the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   His exuberant declaration _ which came more than 12 hours before
the electoral council said Wednesday night that he had 49.85
percent of the vote with 99 percent of the ballots counted _ sent
thousands of supporters to the streets waving the party's white
banner as they danced to a symphony of honking horns.
</P>
<P>
   In a gleeful jab at their rout of the ruling Dominican
Liberation Party, whose policies of privatization and modernization
have been slow to benefit many of the country's poor, Mejia's
supporters triumphantly brandished straw brooms, cutting the air
like sabre-waving conquerors.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia, an agronomist, businessman and cabinet official in the
late 1970s, insisted that the government had to increase spending
on health, education and housing, as well as find ways to help
beleaguered farmers. He said the time had come to make sure that
the country's phenomenal economic growth of approximately 8 percent
in recent years provided tangible benefits to the majority of its
citizens. He also invoked the memory of the late Jose Francisco
Pena Gomez, who had been his party's beloved leader for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we will do will be for the benefit of the hungry masses
of the country,'' he said at an early morning meeting with his
party's leadership. ``What Pena wanted, we will fulfill.''
</P>
<P>
   The premature celebrations were criticized by supporters of the
Dominican Liberation Party, who had wanted their candidate, Danilo
Medina, to face Mejia in a runoff. While Mejia's supporters had
taken to the streets, the final tally was delayed as exhausted
members of the electoral council took a five-hour break to get some
sleep. The Dominican Liberation Party, or PLD, and the Social
Christian Reformist Party of the country's longtime former
president, Joaquin Balaguer, garnered 24.9 and 24.6 percent of the
vote respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The celebratory mood, however, turned violent Wednesday night
when shots were fired near the headquarters of the Dominican
Liberation Party. Witnesses said the shots came from a car that was
flying the banner of the Dominican Revolutionary Party. Security
men from the Liberation Party returned the fire. No one was injured
and the car sped off after glancing off a parked car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mejia made a mistake by proclaiming himself the winner so
early,'' said Julio Cesar Quello, a vice secretary for the PLD.
``Now their people have been drinking all day and they are beyond
his control.''
</P>
<P>
   Mejia's supporters said their candidate's wide margin should be
acknowledged by their opponents as a de facto victory and that they
should spare the country the time and expense of a June 30 runoff
by conceding defeat. Late Wednesday night, Dominican Liberation
Party supporters were still waiting for the final tally before
making any announcement about their intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Several times throughout the day, Mejia insisted that he would
reach out to his opponents' supporters and include them in his
government. But in a televised interview, Mejia also said his
background put him in a good position to reassess the effects of
the current government's economic priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to confront the corruption and lack of planning,'' he
said. ``My strength is in finance and management and the reordering
of public affairs. I expect to be an institutional president who
will not go outside of the legal framework. I will properly manage
the finances of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some officials of the opposing parties said the vote
was affected by mismanagement by electoral officials who had
misdirected voters to incorrect polling places, teams of
international observers said they had not detected any
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, one observer said it was ``unconscionable'' that
the tally had been delayed so long.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dominican economy was the fastest growing in Latin
America last year, the policies of the current president, Leonel
Fernandez, had alienated many voters who felt they were being
harmed. Supporters of Medina acknowledged that the benefits of
Fernandez's policies have trickled down slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government process of privatization was necessary,'' said
Felix Rodriguez, an elementary school teacher and PLD supporter.
``But it affected hundreds of families who were not able to find a
place in the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Medina was also hurt by his own perceived colorlessness,
failing to inspire enthusiasm among some members of his own party,
who would have preferred another candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is an economy that under Leonel Fernandez grew to be an
example for Latin America, so why did the government's candidate
not rise higher?'' said Bernardo Vega, a former Dominican
ambassador to the United States. ``When Danilo spoke, he did not
excite the people. His speeches were more like he was talking to
the Chamber of Commerce about foreign investment and
macroeconomics, and the masses did not want to hear that.''
</P>
<P>
   What mattered most to Mejia's supporters was the sorry state of
their personal economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rich say there is economic growth,'' said Felix Bonilla, a
chauffeur. ``But the only thing growing are their pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most jubilant of Mejia's many supporters were women
and homemakers, many of whom had turned out in large numbers on
election day to put an end to what they said were years of high
food prices and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Juana Espinosa, a nurse who said she could not find a hospital
job, sat outside her beverage stand a few feet away from Mejia's
party headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people wanted a real government to bring them work, not
just pretty words,'' she said. ``The women have seen how there has
been inflation in the kitchen and in caring for their children. We
deal with that and we saw we were on the precipice. If you do not
have enough to feed your children, there is nothing you can change.
But you can change the government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
