</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMNNYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CAN RILEY GIVE WHAT HEAT NEEDS? 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Pat Riley walked into his team's locker room on
Wednesday morning and talked the brave Game 5 talk, as only he
could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love these games,'' he announced to his team, sounding like
Robert Duvall smelling napalm in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The war to defend home court was a go. Game 5 simply had to be
won. The Heat was on for the coach's alter ego, his beleaguered
boss, Riley the organization almighty.
</P>
<P>
   It was time, once and for all, for Alonzo Mourning to justify
Heat president Riley's anointing of him as a franchise player. Time
for Dan Majerle and Tim Hardaway to show they had something left in
their once golden strokes. Time for Anthony Carter and Bruce Bowen
to say thank you, Riles, for this ticket to the big time. They all
owed him and they all saved him from having to go back to New York
on Friday night to face humiliation and elimination on the Madison
Square Garden floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made shots,'' Riley said with the coolness of a coach who
had diagrammed them all, after the Heat held serve, won Game 5 by
87-81 here on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Majerle made two late fourth-quarter 3-pointers, one from so far
out it looked as if it had an American Airlines boarding pass. The
well-traveled Bowen stuck a three-ball from the left corner with 35
seconds left and the Knicks down three. Hardaway dragged his
painful foot through a 10-point, 2-assist bonus of a third quarter
and the rookie Carter made more improbable plays. Jamal Mashburn
continued his breakout spring and Mourning, well, the defensive
player of the year managed to not foul out until less than a minute
remained and the Heat at least was in position to win.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Knicks are one defeat away from losing it all to Riley's
roster of has-beens and wannabes, to a team 99 percent of New York
was so sure was not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Rhetorical bromides aside, more playoff series are won on the
telephone lines than the front lines. While no one ever doubted
Riley's ability to motivate his team to play and play hard, we
waited for evidence on Wednesday night that a Miami group shaped in
the image of his blue-collar core could stare down its former
reflection, reshaped and upgraded, and not blink.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to get over the hurdle and if it's New York, it's
New York,'' Riley said. ``We have a good team. We have built a good
team.''
</P>
<P>
   He, more than anyone, realized the time had come for his team to
prove it by holding serve at home, or shut up for good. Riley had
already tried talking and taunting his team past the Knicks. He
betrayed his friendship with Jeff Van Gundy for a desperate plea
two years ago. He's railed against Mourning's fraternizing with
Ewing. He had to apologize Tuesday for his bad joke about sending
the Gestapo after relocated Knicks fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you get later in the series, it really comes down to
performance,'' he finally admitted. ``The players have to
perform.''
</P>
<P>
   And these are the players he acquired, after leaving New York to
run his own show, the fashion step for the power coach. From that
particular species, we have already seen the crashes on different
levels this year of Jimmy Johnson, of Rick Pitino, of Bill
Parcells. Say this for Phil Jackson: he resented coexisting in
Chicago with Jerry Krause, but he didn't let front-office control
stand in the way of his chance to coach Kobe and Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   The one-man operation has not exactly produced electrifying
results. Coaching is like deadline writing, the emotions running
too high and the perspective too narrow to make the appropriate
revisions. So while Riley the coach has worked wonders in Miami,
Riley the personnel maven has left questions that still must be
answered, in all likelihood, right back here Sunday in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there could be something to that,'' Riley said
recently, when asked if he, as president, may have undermined
himself as coach. ``But we tried to acquire Mitch Richmond. We
tried to acquire Latrell Sprewell. We stepped up to the plate and
were told no, no, no, no.''
</P>
<P>
   For those scoring at home, it still takes four ``nos'' for
elimination from this round. The Knicks are in trouble, as deep as
it gets in a seven-game series. They were out rebounded again on
Wednesday night by 10. Allan Houston was locked up again by
Majerle. With all that, they have lost three games by a combined 11
points. Bill Russell's blessing aside, Mourning still can't get
through a hot playoff night without punishing himself with silly
fouls. The Heat survived on Wednesday night, answered the
questions, but just for Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Riley the coach smelled blood. Riley the recruiter was relieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
