r a BC-LAPD-RAMPART-LADN     05-18 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-RAMPART-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAYOR SAYS FEDS WON'T SUE CITY OVER LAPD REFORMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Staff Writer Alexa Haussler contributed to this story) 
By BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The U.S. Justice Department has backed off its
threat to sue Los Angeles and will work with city officials to
reform the LAPD while preserving local control, Mayor Richard
Riordan said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't going to be any lawsuit,'' Riordan said in an
interview with the Daily News. ``Washington doesn't want a lawsuit
with the (Democratic National) Convention coming up; the city
doesn't want a lawsuit. I think we can work things out
constructively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to let them run the department, but we're not
scared to have other people come in to help either.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lann Lee, the Justice Department's acting civil rights
chief who is spearheading the federal effort, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Department spokeswoman Kara Peterman said the government's
position is consistent and that it wants to work out a ``voluntary
settlement'' that would avoid ``contested litigation.'' The
department remains authorized to sue if the negotiations fail,
Peterman said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear, however, whether the Justice
Department would consider voluntary compliance without a consent
decree signed by a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Justice Department threatened to sue, alleging
a ``pattern and practice'' of civil rights by the LAPD, a majority
of the City Council declared it would support a consent decree that
could lead to appointing a federal monitor of the department and
make it subject to review by a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of losing a measure of local control over the
LAPD prompted criticism and led Riordan to meet with Lee and with
``numerous other people,'' before reaching his conclusion that the
threat of litigation has been eased.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my judgment, of which I'm totally confident,'' Riordan
said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor declined to disclose who on the federal side of the
matter had offered the assurances.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's comments came hours after Lee met for the first time
with the city's negotiating team in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, in a brief interview with the Daily News, confirmed the
talks would continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed procedural items and we will meet again,'' Lee,
the acting assistant attorney general for civil rights, said as he
was leaving the downtown Federal Building.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who rocked city leaders with a May 8 demand for a consent
decree in lieu of a lawsuit alleging a ``pattern or practice'' of
police civil rights violations, declined to say whether the
department has modified its position.
</P>
<P>
   A source, however, said federal officials during the negotiating
session seemed emphatic about getting the consent decree.
</P>
<P>
   City Attorney James Hahn said after the meeting that he's still
assuming the threat of a lawsuit is real, even as he expressed
optimism both sides were committed to a cooperative effort in
addressing LAPD reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking him at his word,'' Hahn said of Lee's initial
threat of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, I also think they're interested in working cooperatively
toward a mutually-acceptable resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   A source said the city left open all its options during the
initial negotiating session by requesting that Lee detail the
LAPD's deficiencies as a condition for talks on remedies
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Martin, the mayor's chief of staff and his designee on the
negotiations team, said the federal team promised to clarify their
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll hear more specifics,'' Martin said. ``They've
indicated they'll provide us with more specifics. But I've heard
from other (jurisdictions) these specifics are not always
forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's notification to the city that it faced a civil rights
lawsuit accused the LAPD in broad terms of a pattern of ``excessive
force, false arrests, and unreasonable searches and seizures.''
Much of the investigation was founded on the LAPD's own internal
reviews, punctuated by the Rampart corruption scandal, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD spokesman Cmdr. David Kalish deferred comment to the
Mayor's Office.
</P>
<P>
   City Council members, who ultimately would decide whether to
contest the Justice Department in any legal proceedings, were both
optimistic and a bit bewildered by the mayor's pronouncement.
</P>
<P>
   East Los Angeles Councilman Nick Pacheco said he would embrace
an agreement in which local control of the LAPD is a condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this'll be good for the city for us to get into some
sort of relationship that's going to make things happen,'' Pacheco
said. ``I'm not interested in turning over the management, the
discipline or the deployment of our police officers to an outside
agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Central Los Angeles Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas said he was
caught off guard by the mayor's remarks, and was concerned about
Riordan working within the city's negotiating parameters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is anything going on to undercut the working group,
then I have a substantial difficulty with that,'' Ridley-Thomas
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Police Protective League, representing 9,500
police officers, on Wednesday objected to the negotiations because
the union doesn't have a seat at the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not sit idly by while our careers, reputations and
working conditions are negotiated away by people unfamiliar with
the nuts and bolts of real police work,'' PPL President Ted Hunt
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0011 </DOCNO>
