r a BC-BRUSHFIRE-THREAT-LADN     05-18 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUSHFIRE-THREAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA RESIDENTS FIRED UP BY THREAT OF BRUSH FIRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With wildfire season starting next week, several
homeowner groups said Wednesday that firefighters are not prepared
to stop a brushfire of New Mexico proportions and must lease
water-dropping planes sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragic wildfire that consumed Los Alamos in New Mexico
should serve as a wake-up call for officials in California,'' said
Gordon Murley, president of the San Fernando Valley Federation,
which represents 20 homeowner groups in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters said they are prepared for this brush fire season,
which will begin May 25 in Los Angeles and is expected to be
particularly severe because of two years of less-than-normal
rainfall after an El Nino winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year's a concern because the weather forecast is for
above-average temperatures throughout most of the summer,'' said
Herb Spitzer, assistant chief in the Los Angeles County Fire
Prevention Bureau's Forestry Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``This forecast looks more severe and potentially more
aggressive for wildfires.''
</P>
<P>
   However, firefighters said the SuperScooper water-dropping
planes are not always the best weapon and would not have helped in
New Mexico because of high winds there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 100 percent prepared. If for some reason there is a
wildland fire, we are ready 365 days a year to deploy helicopters,
camp crews, fire engines, bulldozers,'' said Battalion Fire Chief
Thomas Page, the director of the Air Operations section of the Los
Angeles County Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Hillside dwellers disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want an armamentarium that will keep fires very small,''
Murley said during a news conference with representatives of other
San Fernando Valley homeowner groups.
</P>
<P>
   Murley called on state and local officials to use SuperScooper
firefighting planes from spring to the fall, rather than only
during the fall months when fires typically are the worst. The
SuperScoopers can dump 1,600 gallons of water and return for more
from oceans, lakes or reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many homes do you have to burn down before you could have
bought one airplane?''
</P>
<P>
   The SuperScoopers have been used in recent wildfires including
the Old Topanga blaze, and the county and city are expected to
lease two of them again this year. During the past fire season, the
planes' stay in Los Angeles was extended through January because of
the hazardous conditions.
</P>
<P>
   This year is expected to be at least as dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't received the rain. We think it's prudent to be
prepared. We could start getting fires here,'' said Louis Blumberg,
a spokesman for the California Department of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
   The state will officially open its fire season Monday, which is
about the same as last year. Los Angeles city and county fire
departments will declare their fire season next Thursday, also
about the same as last year.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular concern, fire officials said, are the communities
bordering the Santa Monica Mountains and Angeles National Forest,
and steep inaccessible hillsides filled with dry chaparral.
</P>
<P>
   ``The green grass is drying out. It's like a fuse that is easily
ignited and can quickly spread the fire,'' Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters argued that while the SuperScoopers are helpful in
some fire battles, they are not always useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any tool you have. They are good for certain
applications: for flatland fires where there's no wind. They have
some difficulty in mountainous terrain where there is some wind,''
Page said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer added that helicopters are more effective for use in
winds.
</P>
<P>
   And the SuperScoopers are pricey to lease from Quebec, Canada,
officials said, at a cost of $9,511 daily just to be idle at Van
Nuys Airport. If they go into use, an additional $544 per hour
charge is added, along with fuel and oil costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so expensive. During the rainy season, there's nothing
for them to do,'' Page said.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowner groups countered that fire officials wind up spending
more money in cleaning up fire catastrophes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably spend more in a year cleaning up after fires than
buying a fleet of SuperScoopers,'' Murley said.
</P>
<P>
   And what kind of price tag can you place on human lives, the
homeowners asked.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Morris, whose home is nestled in Topanga's Fernwood
section, said he's unsure whether he'd be able to escape flames. He
also called for improved year-round fire protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am terrified that we are as vulnerable as Los Alamos. We
need more protection,'' Morris said at the morning news conference
in Sylmar. ``Mother Nature doesn't read the calendar. A fire can
break out at any time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
