<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8582 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      05-18 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS LEAVING THEIR SELF-CONTROL AT TURNSTILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Two nights ago, some funny fellows at Wrigley Field
rapped Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter on the head, ran off with his
ballcap and instigated a melee in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The National League game between the Cubs and Dodgers needed a
10-minute timeout before things settled down. Thus, Dodgers
outfielder Gary Sheffield was talked out of his fighting ``Iron
Mike'' pose and a trifecta of so-called fans were hauled off to the
hoosegow.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime later that night, the Dodgers' Todd Hundley hit a
game-winning homer and we were left to ponder whether or not:
</P>
<P>
   A. Fans are out of control.
</P>
<P>
   B. Players are out of control.
</P>
<P>
   C. Sports is out of control.
</P>
<P>
   D. The world at large is out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is probably all of the above, unless you're the prime
minister of Turkey, who only Wednesday was forced to call upon
violent rioters in Copenhagen to settle down in time for the UEFA
Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports should be an initiative for friendship, not for
fighting,'' Turkish leader Bulent Ecevit said after Turkish and
British soccer fans clashed in bloody fights.
</P>
<P>
   Friendship, not fighting. This is an excellent concept,
something that was perhaps idealistically scribbled on a stone at
Mt. Olympus before the first Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the modern age _ edgy, with more attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps when the Prime Minister returns to Earth, he'll take a
look at sports sections more closely and see that, like our larger
society, sports is reflecting a more antagonistic, us-vs.-them,
self-righteous mindset.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mindset that comes from all quarters, including fans,
players, owners, the media.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, unlike what happened between soccer ``fans'' in
Denmark, no knives were wielded at Wrigley Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   However, the free flow of beer, testosterone and a few
temptingly low brick walls around the visiting team's bullpen no
doubt lend to the occurrence of such messy scenes.
</P>
<P>
   As ticket prices rise, as athletes make more money, as the
divide between players and fans widens, the flashpoints for
``combat'' can flare up.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the real question is: What were Kreuter and his
teammates doing running after the idiot pranksters in the first
place?
</P>
<P>
   As Cubs manager Don Baylor put it: ``You can't go into the
stands. No matter what they throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, baseball's executive vice president of baseball
operations, Sandy Alderson, emphasized this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is never any excuse for going into the stands,''
Alderson said. ``It is not acceptable; it exposes players and other
uniformed personnel to risks and liabilities. At any level, it is
not a tolerable response.''
</P>
<P>
   It is tough to expect all sports fans to behave with decorum and
civility. And as the Jackson 5 used to sing: One bad apple (or
three or a dozen) don't spoil the whole bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the actions of a few ugly ``fans'' can mar a game or
series.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Philadelphia, a bunch of bozos dumped beer on the
court as Game 3 of the NBA playoff series between the 76ers and
Pacers wound down. The ugliness continued until 76ers coach Larry
Brown grabbed the microphone and asked for order to be restored.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Philly is to sports civility what Bobby Knight is to
sports civility.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Brotherly Love is, after all, a town that cheered
Michael Irvin's career-ending injury; that booed Santa Claus; that
made battery-throwing an art form; that hurled a full beverage cup
at an opposing coach recently as he attempted to congratulate the
Flyers on advancing in the Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia does not have a corner on boorish behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman may be retired from professional sports, but his
provacative, me-first, push-the-envelope, whatever-it-takes-to-win,
borderline-psychotic tendencies are still around.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker and Bobby Knight share discouragingly similar
inabilities to see how their actions _ and how their stunning lack
of true contrition _ adds to the level of intolerance or
combatitiveness in sports.
</P>
<P>
   But with each incident, fans grow increasingly more skeptical of
where the line on civility and decorum is drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they've done much to honor that line. In the past nine
months, we have witnessed: Houston Astros right fielder Bill Spiers
being attacked from behind by a fan at Milwaukee's County Stadium;
Denver Broncos defensive back Dale Carter sporting a blackened
right eye after being hit by a metal object thrown by a (BEGIN
ITAL) Broncos (END ITAL) fan; and, of course, a fan run to the
mound at Dodger Stadium to moon Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   In reaction to fans' skepticism, anger and resentment, players
retreat deeper into their well-paid, exclusive cocoons. In turn,
they grow more wary and testy of taunting fans.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, league officials are forced to bolster rules and step
up security forces. This way, when the next skirmish takes place,
prescribed penalties can be handed down.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks back, baseball's new penalty czar, Frank Robinson,
executed his respected authority by fining a record 16 players and
coaches for a total of 82 games for monster brawls between the
Tigers and White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was given tremendous credit for coming down so hard, so
fast. Baseball needed to crack the whip, get everyone in line.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, like the NBA, NFL, NCAA and everything else out there
charging fans big money, needs to affirm that law and order exists
in its house.
</P>
<P>
   Though it does nothing to lower ticket prices or player
salaries, it might do something to help bolster fans' faith in and
respect for the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, they used to play basketball in cages.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to separate players and angry fans that way,
although higher walls and chicken-wire covers on visiting team
bullpens are good ideas.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
