<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISARCINA'S STATUS: SURGERY STILL AN OPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Shortstop Gary DiSarcina met with Anaheim Angels
manager Mike Scioscia, general manager Bill Stoneman and trainer
Ned Bergert for nearly an hour in Scioscia's office before
Wednesday's game to discuss DiSarcina's options.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, on the disabled list with a sore right shoulder, is
considering whether to have surgery on the shoulder. Surgery would
likely cause him to miss the rest of the season. If he decides to
rehab the shoulder without surgery, there would be no guarantee of
a full recovery and the timetable for his return would be unknown.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina saw a vascular specialist and an orthopedic specialist
in Chicago this week, but the Angels are not releasing the results,
calling the tests inconclusive. But it is apparent DiSarcina is
aware of the nature of the injury because there are no plans to see
any other doctors, and the decision is now in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you miss games and have to go on the DL, it's a
concern,'' DiSarcina said. ``But now there's more concern than I
originally thought.''
</P>
<P>
   There is speculation that DiSarcina has a muscle tear in the
back of the shoulder, but that might be only part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I make a decision, there's not much to talk about,'' he
said. ``I'm not at that point (surgery) yet. It's in the mix. I
don't want to say something now and change my mind later.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Finally called up: The Angels called up Keith Luuloa from
Triple-A Edmonton to back up starter Benji Gil at shortstop. Luuloa
has spent the past six-plus seasons in the Angels' minor-league
system but had not reached the big leagues until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He was passed over twice previously this season when DiSarcina
went to the disabled list. The first time, the Angels called up
Keith Johnson, even though Luuloa was starting at shortstop at
Edmonton. The second time, the Angels called up Trent Durrington,
who is a second baseman but was already on the 40-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first move was kind of mind-boggling,'' said Luuloa, who
is one of three Hawaiian-born players in the majors. ``I was
playing every day, and (Johnson) hadn't played yet. I was unsure of
what was happening. The second one, I understood because there was
no roster spot open.''
</P>
<P>
   Luuloa, who was hitting .241 with two homers and 13 RBI for
Edmonton, can also play third base, second base and left field.
</P>
<P>
   __ Belcher update: Pitcher Tim Belcher threw off the mound
Wednesday for the first time in nearly three weeks. Belcher, who is
recovering from offseason elbow surgery, threw fastballs only for
10 minutes and said he felt fine. He'll throw off the mound again
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never be able to show up at the park and fire (the
ball),'' Belcher said. ``My elbow will never be 100 percent again.
But I'm still confident I can come back and be healthy and
productive.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Dubious ranking: When the Orioles' Cal Ripken grounded into a
6-4-3 double play in the third inning Wednesday night, it marked
the 320th time in his career he has grounded into a double play,
tying Hank Aaron for the most in major-league history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
