<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY HAVE NO GROUNDS TO REVOLT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ It's time for the San Francisco Board of
Supervisors to wake up and not smell the coffee.
<P>
   They vote to protect the civil rights of the fat, the skinny,
the non-traditionally-aligned-of-sexual-or-ientation and other
persecuted minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the city's smallest, most misunderstood minority:
the java-free?
</P>
<P>
   As Matt Berryhill points out, the entire world discriminates
against the nondrinker of coffee. It is such a marginalized group
that its existence is not even acknowledged. There is not even a
common word or term for these people, like teetotalers.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every business provides coffee for its employees, usually
for free. If you don't drink it, you're not only on your own for
refreshments, you're out of the office social/gossip loop, and
guess who they're talking about 'round the coffeepot. Mr. Smug with
his hoity-toity metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   You stop by Jiffy Lube, hey, have a cup on us. No, sorry, we
don't provide free soda, sport drinks or Kool-Aid.
</P>
<P>
   Want to get together? Let's go have coffee. You don't drink
coffee? Well, call me when you start, we'll get together.
</P>
<P>
   At gatherings and meetings, in the waiting rooms of your doctors
and shrinks, there's never a complimentary help-yourself pitcher of
margaritas.
</P>
<P>
   No waitress ever hovers over your table asking if she can top
off or freshen up your Clamato juice. But coffee, she'll pump it
into your mug through a garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Paul Quihillalt (cq)  &LR; predicts the next group
seeking protected status will be unphotogenic columnists.
</P>
<P>
   At least I drink coffee.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST, WE HAD the telecommuter, working out of his or her home
office, swinging deals in his or her underwear, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   The next step in the evolution of cool is Starbuck Chuck. He
turns business wheeling and dealing into performance art. It's a
bold new world of self-importance.
</P>
<P>
   At the Carmel Roasting Co., Daryl Glen observed a 30ish man with
a neat goatee, wearing bathroom slippers and what looked like
jammie bottoms. He sat at a table, his laptop up and humming,
sipping from his to-go cup and yammering on his cell phone about
magazine advertising.
</P>
<P>
   But he got some bad looks from customers who were contemplating
their novels, so he took his phone out to the sidewalk, where he
paced and dodged dog-walkers as he conducted his meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Either a New Wave hipster or a guy whose wife and boss both
kicked him out.
</P>
<P>
   THE INVASION of SoMa by the dot-commers is not only running some
old traditional businesses out of the neighborhood, it's also
chasing away some New Agers who are providing vital services.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Dalldorf, publisher of Celebrator Beer News, notes that the
popular 20 Tank Brewery, at 316 11th St., just across from Slim's,
is closing soon. He says the place is going great, but not great
enough to cover the 350 percent rent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Mourns Tom, ``Do not go gentry into that good night ...''
</P>
<P>
   And tanks for the memories.
</P>
<P>
   THIS COULD be your big break. Or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   The movie ``Nutcracker'' is being shot around town, starring
David Hess, whoever he is, and featuring former local DJ Darian
O'Toole.
</P>
<P>
   Friday (1 to 7 p.m.) they're shooting at Harry Denton's
Starlight Room, high atop the lovely Sir Francis Drake. If you show
up in semi-formal attire, you might wind up as background in the
flick.
</P>
<P>
   It will cost you $25, since it's a charity/fund-raising thing,
but remember that the cast members of ``Friends'' will each make
$750,000 per episode, and you're only a heartbeat away from that
kind of action.
</P>
<P>
   THE MUMMY in ``The Mummy'' movie wasn't brought back to life
with burning tania leaves, as reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's  &UR; tanna  &LR; smoke that gets a mummy up and shuffling,''
corrects Michael Conklin.
</P>
<P>
   Tanna leaves can either be ``smoked'' or drunk as tea. Huang-po
Chen adds, ``Tania was not smoked or drunk, she was kidnapped.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone's a comedian.
</P>
<P>
   FOR A REAL San Francisco experience, there's always Vegas and
its S.F. knockoffs.
</P>
<P>
   My travel guru, Seymour Seitz, reports that the Postrio in Las
Vegas' Venetian hotel features legendary North Beach bartender
Cassidy Feggan. And the Bellagio hotel has an Aqua, general-managed
by Tony Angotti, formerly of Stars.
</P>
<P>
   It was Angotti who once said of the proposed casino on Alcatraz,
``Can't think of anything sorrier than a seasick slots loser.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MOST depressing thing about the movie ``Battleship Earth''
is the scenario that 1,000 years from now, our planet will have
done some serious backsliding in personal grooming and hygiene.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the critics are trashing the movie, although for a
sci-fi cartoon it's really not bad, and John Travolta is a great
supervillain. You do have to get beyond a few quirks, like cavemen
becoming overnight fighter-pilot aces.
</P>
<P>
   I had one problem. Travolta and his evil alien cronies, who are
bigger and stronger than the earthlings, keep grabbing them by the
neck and choking them, and I kept expecting the president of
Indiana University to appear and give Travolta one last chance to
clean up his act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
