r n BC-QUACKENBUSH-SENATE-SF     05-18 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH-SENATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL WANTS INSURANCE CHIEF APPOINTED, NOT ELECTED
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Over the objection of some consumer groups, a plan
to return the position of state insurance commissioner to an
appointed post was unanimously approved Wednesday by a state Senate
committee.
</P>
<P>
   If ultimately approved by voters on a statewide ballot, the
constitutional amendment would make the state's top insurance
industry regulator an appointee of the governor, as was the case
before 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``The authority to impose fines on the people (the commissioner)
regulates and simultaneously receive campaign contributions from
those entities, I submit to you, is a conflict,'' said state Sen.
Jackie Speier, D-Hillsborough, the author of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Speier said the idea for the measure stemmed from investigations
by the Legislature and the attorney general's office into the
actions of the current commissioner, Chuck Quackenbush, who Speier
said has received $6.4 million in contributions from insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush, a Republican, has been under fire for allowing
insurance companies to duck as much as $3 billion in fines by
contributing $11.6 million to a nonprofit foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Bill Lockyer has gone to court to block further
spending by the foundation, which was ostensibly created to aid
victims of the 1994 Northridge earthquake, but has yet to spend any
money on victims.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the foundation has spent $6 million. Half it went to
earthquake preparedness television commercials featuring
Quackenbush, and the remainder to a variety of
nonearthquake-related entities, including $263,000 that went to a
football camp attended by two of Quackenbush's children.
</P>
<P>
   Speier has another bill to ban creation of such foundations
without court or legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, a constitutional amendment returning the
commissioner's post to an appointed position would not affect
Quackenbush, since the amenment would only take effect after his
term expires in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Speier's proposal to make the commissioner a gubernatorial
appointee was called ``misguided'' by a representative of the
Foundation for Taxpayer and Consumer Rights.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was created by the backers of Proposition 103.
Approved by voters in November 1988, Proposition 103 rolled back
insurance rates by 20 percent and made the commissioner's job an
elected post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had the opportunity to elect two different
commissioners,'' said Doug Heller, a spokesman for the group. ``It
has turned out that one of them is particularly corrupt. If you had
a rash of pickpockets, you wouldn't outlaw wallets.''
</P>
<P>
   But Speier argued that only 12 insurance commissioners
nationwide are elected and that the commissioner's job is largely
regulatory in California.
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. Gray Davis and lawmakers created the Department of
Managed Care to regulate health maintenance organizations last
year, Speier said, they didn't make that regulatory post an elected
position.
</P>
<P>
   Her argument won support from Republicans on the Senate
Elections and Reapportionment Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor ought to appoint all these regulatory positions,
and the governor ought to be held accountable, whoever that
governor is,'' said state Sen. Chuck Poochigian, R-Fresno.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional amendment, SCA 19, must be approved by two
more Senate committees and win a two-thirds vote of the full Senate
and Assembly before it can be placed on the next available
statewide ballot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8587 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-ACLU-SCHOOLS-SFCHRON &LR;      05-18 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACLU-SCHOOLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ACLU SUES STATE OVER PUBLIC SCHOOL CONDITIONS  &HT;     By MEREDITH MAY 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Citing cases of children studying in moldy, rat-infested
portables  &LR; portable classrooms without books or trained teachers,
the American Civil Liberties Union sued the state of California
Wednesday, claiming it has failed on its promise to provide an
equal education for all public school children.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing 46 children in 18 urban school districts
across the state said low-income children of color are getting
shortchanged because they do not have the basics enjoyed by their
suburban peers _ textbooks to take home, teachers with experience
and bathrooms that work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not sleuths. We didn't have to hire private
investigators to find these conditions in schools,'' said Mark
Rosenbaum, lead attorney and legal director of the ACLU's Southern
California office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is well known to the state, and that is the basic
problem. There is no accountability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action lawsuit filed in San Francisco Superior Court
asks for a court order requiring the state to provide an immediate
infusion of books and supplies, credentialed teachers and a
maintenance overhaul to all California schools lacking bare
essentials, in addition to the specific districts listed in the
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit cites educational troubles in schools in San
Francisco, Oakland, San Pablo, Richmond, Fresno, Monterey Park and
Los Angeles. One student in Los Angeles said he has watched 20
movies in class this year, including ``The Sixth Sense'' and
``Nightmare on Elm Street.'' Other classrooms relied on history
texts that say the Soviet Union is still in existence.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys want the state to come up with a basic set of
requirements each child must have to learn, then inspect and ensure
those standards are met, similar to a settlement the ACLU worked
out with the state in March over rundown conditions in the Compton
schools.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the ACLU sued the state in 1997 for failing to
improve the rock-bottom Compton district, four years after bailing
it out with a $20 million loan and the appointment of a state
administrator. The state pledged to fix bathrooms within 24 hours
of reported problems, broken windows within 72 hours, ensure
textbooks in all core classes, and that teachers earn state
credentials within two years of being hired.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, state Superintendent of Public
Instruction Delaine Eastin said she was not ready to talk about the
lawsuit, because her legal staff had not had the opportunity to
examine the claims and meet with the ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis referred all calls to Eastin's office.
</P>
<P>
   Though Davis will send a record $3.6 billion to the state's
8,000 schools this year _ half of that with no strings attached _
ACLU attorney Catherine Lhamon said it is too little, too late to
solve inequities that have bankrupted a generation of low-income
children.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to students such as Laurel Clemens of Kennedy High
School in Richmond, who has had a dozen advanced placement (AP)
English teachers in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her whole class refused to take the AP English exam because
they didn't feel they were prepared,'' said Laurel's mother,
Michele.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher Shannon Carey tried unsuccessfully to get her fourth-and
fifth-graders at Stonehurst Elementary School in Oakland exempted
from the standardized state test this year because of their stress
and wasted learning time.
</P>
<P>
   During the winter, rain dripped on their heads, and her class
was moved to a hallway, then the auditorium and finally a portable
with a noisy special education class. The students have not had the
peace of mind to study, Carey said.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Williams, 12, added his name to the lawsuit, saying he is
not learning anything by doing homework of photocopied worksheets
at Luther Burbank Middle School in San Francisco. There is no text
to refer to or help him study at home for tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``In social studies class, we don't even have books, so we just
read the newspaper or watch current events on TV,'' he said. ``And
there are ants crawling all over the water fountains, and ceiling
tiles falling from the gym roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Lili Malabed and her colleagues at Bryant Elementary School in
San Francisco also lack books and run into problems when they
exceed their monthly copier budget trying to make homework
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a public school kid when Prop. 13 passed (in 1979), and
I remember all the doomsday predictions about the future of public
education back then, but I had no idea _ no idea _ it would be this
bad,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
