<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8591 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-WESTFINALS-HNS &LR;      05-18 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WESTFINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal drop-steps his way into the lane and
flicks a one-handed jumper in off the backboard as if he were
tossing out a crumpled wad of paper.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But could he have moved so easily against the similarly enormous
Arvydas Sabonis? Could he have found room to move with Rasheed
Wallace closing?
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen steps back and nails a series-clinching
3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   But would Ron Harper have given him the room? Would Kobe Bryant
have long since flown in circles and pump-fakes around Pippen,
rendering him dizzy and shaken when the last minute arrived?
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry injects energy and athleticism. But would Brian
Grant have beaten him pillow-soft?
</P>
<P>
   Damon Stoudamire speeds through defenses. But would he be able
to outquick Bryant?
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers strut through another home-court triumph. But the
Trail Blazers own a victory at Staples Center and know they can
come back for more.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers prove themselves too young and athletic for
the Jazz. But the Lakers are every bit as young and athletic. The
Blazers have no one to match up with Bryant. The Lakers have no
answer for Wallace. The Lakers have the NBA's best record and its
Most Valuable Player. The Blazers have rolled through the playoffs
more impressively.
</P>
<P>
   For every weakness, there is a strength; for every answer, a
question.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the Lakers have gone, the Trail Blazers have followed.
A championship won without a victory over the other would not be
tarnished. But it could never be as complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the series we predicted all year long,'' Lakers coach
Phil Jackson said of the NBA Western Conference finals, which begin
Saturday in Los Angeles. ``This is the one that's been going on
here from day one in the Western Conference. It's fitting it should
be like this.''
</P>
<P>
   More than fitting, the Western Conference title could be worth
the NBA championship. If the Lakers and Trail Blazers were hesitant
to make that claim, there is evidence to support such an
assumption.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had the league's best record at 67-15. The Blazers
were next at 59-23, and they have the best record in the postseason
this year at 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   They split their four games this season, each winning once on
the other's home court. In four games against the Lakers, the Trail
Blazers averaged 89.8 points. In four games against the Blazers,
the Lakers averaged 89 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a great series,'' the Lakers' Harper said.
``This is going to be a fun series. These are two teams that had a
fun year.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Portland's Greg Anthony, ``The showdown will be here. I
think it will be everything everyone expects.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers expect an emotional, physical series. Though this
might not qualify as any sort of revelation, it could be a key to
their performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to go out and fight,'' Horry said. ``You
never know what can happen in a series. You have to jump on a team
early and keep them down. You're going to have two teams, No. 1 and
2, battling hard. Everybody's going to have their emotions out.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than O'Neal and their oversized starting backcourt, the
Lakers in general and Horry in particular are not terribly
physical. But the Lakers have proved to be at their best when
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   If the first two rounds of the playoffs have shown anything, it
might be that the Lakers do not often feel threatened. They were so
far ahead of the field in the regular season that they headed to
the playoffs carrying the label of unbeatable. But they have been
beaten _ twice by Sacramento and once, in an ugly rout, by Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers insist, however, that their image should not be
damaged. But regardless, they say, they don't need the image to win
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always going to judge you, especially here in LA,''
Horry said. ``You can't really fault us for losing on the road.
It's the playoffs. Since we won at home, we're supposed to go on
the road and have a cakewalk. People forget that people have pride.
They have their crowd behind them. It's different. Your comfort
level is different on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have to do is defend our home court, go out, play hard
and do what we have to do. People are like, when we lose a game
that it's the end of the world. Everybody loses a game once in a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Harper maintain, however, that the Lakers are not
yet the sort of experienced, honed team that can go through
playoff-caliber competition without hitting a few potholes. Harper
says the Lakers still need more killer instinct. Jackson cites
maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play one good team every four games in the NBA, you
can rise to the occasion playing that team and run off a couple
strings during the course of the year,'' Jackson said. ``I know it
looks that way. We had some (winning) streaks of 18, 19, 16 games.
That makes for a dominant season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the playoffs, you're playing good teams. We (Jackson's six
world-champion Bulls teams) were much more mature as a basketball
club. That takes some time.''
</P>
<P>
   But both Jackson and Harper seemed also to be saying that the
Lakers exposed nothing more than a weakness in concentration. Up
2-0 on the Kings and 3-0 on the Suns, they seemed to lose interest
and perhaps struggled to get it back. That should not be a problem
against an opponent they truly respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we set goals, we accomplish them,'' O'Neal said.
``Whenever we're put to the task, it will carry us through. We
don't have it all the time. You have to develop that (mean streak).
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be pumped up to play Portland. We want to do the same
thing we've been doing, take care of business at home, get one or
two at their place, and we'll be fine. We match up with them very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The mean streak _ Jackson called it a sense of urgency _ showed
defensively. It could almost make the series with Portland take on
the look of the low-scoring Eastern Conference slugfest between the
Heat and the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Tuesday if the Lakers would have to shoot better than
36.3 percent _ their figure in the series clincher against Phoenix
_ to beat the Blazers, Jackson replied: ``No. Did you see Portland
play?''
</P>
<P>
   But before it could be assumed Jackson was seeking to stick it
to the Trail Blazers, or even playing his latest mind game, he
rushed to defend Portland as his team must in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played two games (against Utah), the last two, that
weren't so pretty themselves,'' Jackson said. ``But that's what
happens when you get to slugging it out in the playoffs. Playing
the same team over and over again _ soon it becomes
confrontational. It becomes a real struggle out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Lakers have shown an ability to take over games on
the defensive end, most stunningly against Phoenix on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers pounced on the Suns' guards when they came around
screens, a favorite Portland tactic. They challenged shots and
attacked passers. When Rodney Rogers headed for the hoop in the
third quarter with the game very much decided, O'Neal slammed him
so hard the 76ers might have been fined another $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were more aggressive on screens,'' Jackson said. ``We
played through on picks. We challenged the ball and made passes
difficult. We had our hands in the face of shooters.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers do not really have an answer for the Trail
Blazers' strength, Wallace and Grant rotating at power forward.
LA's weakness was clearly exposed by the Kings' Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' Cliff Robinson was more of a jump shooter. But Sabonis
is one of the few centers big enough to battle O'Neal defensively
yet deft enough offensively to bring him away from the basket,
removing his ability to shut down the lane as he did Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal averaged 20.5 points and 13 rebounds, both well below his
season averages, against the Trail Blazers. Sabonis averaged 10.8
points and seven rebounds against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Smith
</P>
<P>
   But for all their depth, the Trail Blazers really do not have an
answer for Bryant. Pippen is still disruptive in passing lanes,
though he is not near the defender on the ball that he was in the
Bulls' early championship runs. Steve Smith does not have the
quickness to defend Bryant away from the basket. Bryant averaged
24.3 points against the Trail Blazers this season, making 55.6
percent of his shots.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blazers contend the numbers and matchups are not the
point. While the Lakers must get big performances from O'Neal and
Bryant, Portland can get scoring from a wide variety of sources,
making individual statistics misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen disappeared offensively in the middle three games of the
Jazz series, but he was the offensive star and late-game hero in
the clincher. The Lakers did beat the Trail Blazers in their Feb.
29 showdown for first place in Portland, but that was with Grant
out with a foot injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figure we're going to go with depth,'' Smith said. ``What
helps for us (is if) you take away one thing, you've got to give up
something. You want to double-team me, you've got to give up a jump
shot to some big man or to other guys who can shoot. If you want to
trap the pick-and-roll, (Sabonis) can hit the jump shot. If you
want to play Rasheed by a single coverage, he's going to score. We
go to whatever the go-to play is or wherever we see a
disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   It is exactly that mix of strengths that makes this year's
Western Conference finals so intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
