<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY TIED IN SAN JOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ Life with Luis Hernandez will add excitement and
energy when the Mexican standout makes his anticipated debut with
the Los Angeles Galaxy Saturday at the Rose Bowl against D.C.
United. However, life without Hernandez, Clint Mathis, Joey
Franchino and Roy Myers proved too much for the Galaxy in San Jose
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   After absorbing constant San Jose pressure, the Galaxy managed
to keep their unbeaten record intact, thanks mainly to the
goalkeeping of Kevin Hartman, who was challenged constantly for the
first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman matched a career-high 10 saves, allowing the Galaxy to
escape Spartan Stadium with a 0-0 draw after 90 minutes and two
overtimes in front of 12,692.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hartman was superb,'' said Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid.
``Defensively, we have to play tough right now because we're in a
series of games where we're playing Wednesday, Saturday, Wednesday
and trying to work on a new forward combination with the arrival of
Hernandez. But yeah, Hartman made a big difference, he really
stepped up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman, who was the outstanding goalkeeper in the MLS in 1999,
hasn't been challenged much this season, but he earned his salary,
especially in the last 20 minutes, coming up with three huge saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave up quite a few chances,'' said Galaxy defender Greg
Vanney. ``We were too spread out, guys weren't getting close to
guys or getting enough guys forward. Kevin's not asked to make that
many saves every night, but tonight he was and came through for
us,''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy had their chances too, but they couldn't find a
rhythm offensively or defensively.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Galaxy's (5-0-5, 20 points) third consecutive tie,
dropping them behind Western Division leader Kansas City (8-0-2, 26
points), which beat D.C. United 2-0 Wednesday. San Jose (2-5-3)
failed to win for the fifth consecutive match.
</P>
<P>
   The turf was noticeably long at Spartan Stadium, which proved to
be a neutralizer for the Galaxy's speedy attack. San Jose officials
said recent rains allowed the turf to get thick, but Schmid didn't
buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they own lawn mowers in San Jose, but it's an
embarrassment,'' said Schmid. ``Maybe they have to keep it that way
because of some disease in the grass or the city of San Jose
requires it too be that long. But, certainly, it's an embarrassment
to force teams to play on a field with grass that high. If they
want to make the game slow down and look less entertaining, then
you leave it long. Obviously, it was left long to slow us down.''
</P>
<P>
   After Schmid started to cool down, he praised his team for
remaining unbeaten despite the loss of three starters and all the
distractions his team faced the last week and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everything our team has gone through, the guys have been
amazing with their morale and what they've been able to sustain,''
said Schmid. ``Every week we're throwing guys up there like Zak
Ibsen and Adam Frye who haven't played forward before.''
</P>
<P>
   After a brief pause, Schmid took a stab at MLS in the wake of
losing three starters for Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we've fallen back in the pack (of MLS teams) and that's
what they (MLS) wanted,'' said Schmid. ``I'm sure it makes everyone
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibsen nearly finished a Cobi Jones cross in the eighth minute,
but he misfired from close range to spoil an early chance.
</P>
<P>
   After the Galaxy controlled the first 10 minutes, San Jose
started applying pressure. Earthquakes midfielder Richard Mulrooney
shot from 20 yards, but Hartman tucked it away, making a diving
save in the 12th minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
