<SLUG> BC-NIEVES-TRIAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY HEARS OF NIGHT FOUR SISTERS DIED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ A 15-year-old boy testified Wednesday that his
mother sealed windows and doors at their Santa Clarita house
northwest of Los Angeles before smoke from a fire killed his four
sisters in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In shocking testimony, David Nieves said he obeyed his mother,
Sandi Nieves, when she told him and his sisters to sleep in the
kitchen for their first-ever slumber party.
</P>
<P>
   As the children dozed off, David saw his mother use wooden
dowels to block kitchen windows and a sliding glass door, the boy
told a San Fernando Superior Court jury at his mother's murder
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up coughing _ I couldn't breathe because smoke around
me was stinging my nose and eyes,'' said David, who was 14 when the
fire occurred in Seco Canyon on July 1, 1998. ``There was a lot of
coughing from me, my sisters and my mom. I asked my mom if we could
leave and go outside but she said, `No. It could be coming from
outside.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Deputy District Attorney Beth Silverman asked
the boy why he stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed her, and I trusted her,'' David said.
</P>
<P>
   Nieves, 36, faces the death penalty if convicted of any of the
four counts of first-degree murder and special circumstances for
the death of her daughters.
</P>
<P>
   She is also charged with the attempted murder of David and with
arson.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend she killed to exact revenge on two
ex-husbands who were fathers to the children, including the four
killed _ Nikolet Amber Nieves, 12; Rashel Hollie Nieves, 11; Kristl
Dawn Folden, 7; and Jaqlene Marine Folden, 5.
</P>
<P>
   Nieves' attorneys contend she was despondent over financial
matters, including her failure to become a police officer. And she
does not know what happened that night or who started the fire,
according to Los Angeles County Deputy Public Defender Howard Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Waco has repeatedly complained that he has been barred by police
and prosecutors from interviewing David prior to trial.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager said he has met many times with authorities and
admitted that police and prosecutors let him know what types of
answers and questions they expected.
</P>
<P>
   David said he does not know who set the fire. However, he said
he saw a gasoline can in his mother's bedroom, the one prosecutors
say she used to start the fire.
</P>
<P>
   David testified he objected to sleeping in the kitchen, but that
his mother insisted.
</P>
<P>
   When he woke up the first time, he said, his mother made Nikolet
throw up where she was sleeping rather than go to the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told us to put our faces into the pillows and covers to
breathe,'' David said. ``I thought that it would prevent us from
breathing in the smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   David said he passed out but awoke later, went to the bathroom
to vomit and found that the carpet was burned on several floors,
including in the children's bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind was blank and I didn't know what to think,'' he said,
adding that when he looked at his sisters, ``they were laying there
with foam coming out of their mouths. I thought they had just been
drooling that night, so I laid down and passed out.''
</P>
<P>
   David said he asked his mother what was going on when he awoke a
third time. ``She didn't give me an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   David said he sat on the living room couch with his mother until
paramedics arrived. They took him outside and said his sisters were
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' said David, who remained straight-faced and
unemotional throughout his testimony.
</P>
</TEXT>
