r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLAN     05-18 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS RALLY PAST ORIOLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ For the second time in less than a week, Scott Spiezio
won a game for the Angels with a hit, his ninth-inning single off
Baltimore Orioles closer Mike Timlin scoring Tim Salmon with the
winning run in a 8-7 Angels victory before 17,697 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio broke his bat on the game-winner _ not quite the same as
his game-winning homer Sunday, but just as effective nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels rallied from deficits of 3-0, 6-3 and 7-4. Darin
Erstad, who had his 22nd multihit game of the season, had a two-run
single in the eighth inning to tie the game at 7. Troy Percival
pitched the ninth to get the win.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus also had two hits for the Angels, including his 11th
home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few weeks ago, Angels pitcher Scott Schoeneweis said he
didn't read the sports section of the newspaper. ``I read the money
section and the front page,'' Schoeneweis said after going 4-0 in
April.
</P>
<P>
   He might want to include the help-wanted ads in the classified
section, considering the way he's pitched lately.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Schoeneweis' spot in the rotation is safe, what with
injuries, illnesses and lack of production besetting other
starters. But he is not getting the breaks he got in April, though
he was spared his third consecutive loss Wednesday because the
Angels rallied to tie the game in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis gave up seven runs (six earned) and 10 hits in
six-plus innings. After going 4-0 with a 3.43 ERA in his first six
starts, he is 0-2 with a 10.38 ERA in his last three starts.
</P>
<P>
   ''His command has not been quite as crisp his last couple
outings,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said before the game. ''The
teams he's faced were disciplined clubs, and he got behind in the
count.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Schoeneweis gave up six runs in an 8-2 loss to the
Mariners, and nine runs in a 13-11 loss to Texas going into
Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are adjustments he's going to have to make,'' Scioscia
said. ``He's still getting a feel for that. That's what experience
does for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles jumped on Schoeneweis right away, as Brady Anderson
and Mike Bordick opened the top of the first with singles. Delino
DeShields followed with a grounder to short, but he beat out the
relay to first and stayed out of the double play, which proved to
be the key to the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle drove in the first run of the inning with a
sacrifice fly, then Jeff Conine and Cal Ripken added RBI doubles
for a 3-0 Orioles lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels matched the three in the bottom of the first, but
missed out on a chance for more. Erstad doubled and scored on a
double by Adam Kennedy. Then Kennedy scored when Mo Vaughn reached
on an error by Conine at first.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon drove in Vaughn with a double to tie the game at 3.
One out later, Glaus and Scott Spiezio walked to load the bases.
But the inning ended abruptly when Bengie Molina grounded into an
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis found trouble in the second inning by walking
Charles Johnson and allowing a single to Rich Amaral. Anderson then
laid down a bunt that was fielded by Schoeneweis, who looked at
third, but then threw late to first, loading the bases with none
out.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis nearly got out of it, getting Bordick and DeShields
to pop out. With the count 2-2 to Belle, Schoeneweis threw a pitch
at the knees and on the inside corner, but homeplate ump Rich
Rieker called ball- three.
</P>
<P>
   Belle hit a slow roller to third where Glaus tried but failed to
bare-hand the ball. Belle was safe at first with an infield single,
and with the runners moving on the 3-2 pitch, two scored to give
the Orioles a 5-3 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
