<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8595 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     05-18 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHARLES Barkley has hobbled off into the sunset, his putter in one
hand and a cocktail in the other. For 16 seasons, the Chuckster did
everything a basketball player could possibly do except make
himself a beloved presence in a visiting arena or win a
championship.
</P>
<P>
   His Utah peers, John Stockton and Karl Malone, are assured of
the same fate. Although both are under contract to return to the
Jazz next year and will presumably come back _ considering the
level they performed at this season, why not? _ their chances of
ever claiming an NBA title have most surely slipped from slim to
none.
</P>
<P>
   Portland killed their lingering hopes Tuesday night, eliminating
Utah 4-1 in the Western Conference semifinals. Thus, Stockton
stands 0-for-16 and Malone 0-for-15 in the banner-hanging
department.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's probably nothing Utah's management can do, short of
arranging a hit on Shaq and Kobe, to give Malone, 36, and Stockton,
38, any kind of viable opportunity for another championship run in
2000-01, much less beyond. It's over, and it's rather sad, no
matter how angry the Mailman and his trusty sidekick have made us
in Houston over these many years.
</P>
<P>
   They've plunged numerous daggers through the Rockets' hearts,
none more hurtful than the nothing-but-net Stockton trey at the
buzzer to terminate Houston's playoff run three springs ago one
round shy of a desperately longed-for summit meeting with Chicago.
Goodness, how we loathed Stockton for that shot.
</P>
<P>
   And also Malone, on general principle, for all the bruises he
left on our heroes with his lethal elbows. Stockton's Clark Kent
persona and squeaky-clean image belied a clever mean streak, too.
Pound for pound, he has long set the most painful pick in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if we're going to lament the imperfect Barkley's empty
trophy case _ please don't, he requests, because he refuses to _ it
seems only fair that we feel a measure of compassion for the great
Jazz duet.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon and then Clyde Drexler would be made whole
during Michael Jordan's dropout seasons, banishing Utah en route
both times. But when the Jazz returned the favor back-to-back in
1997 and 1998, the colossus of Jordan had returned to thwart them
at the finish line. Although Utah stayed competitive in both Finals
against the mighty Bulls, you know what's said about coming close.
Either you win or you don't, and they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, Barkley, Malone, Stockton, Olajuwon and Drexler all came
into the NBA in 1984 or 1985 as first-round draft choices. Each
will enter the Hall of Fame the moment he becomes eligible. But
obviously, Michael's majesty dwarfed that of the others, and his
six championships personally ensured Barkley, Stockton and Malone
would be shut out.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, opposite of Sir Charles, is on the record as saying that
never claiming a ring will haunt him to his dying day. Stockton,
always taciturn, ever inscrutable, has long declined to verbalize
whatever pain he feels. But a defining image of his frustration
would be displayed the night Utah bowed to Seattle in the 1996
Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz was aboard its private jet awaiting takeoff. Box
lunches were served, and the players, having accepted their fate,
had begun joking and laughing among themselves. Except for
Stockton. He suddenly bolted from the plane, then walked 30 yards
across the tarmac, where he stood with his hands in his pockets
staring into the night.
</P>
<P>
   From the day Stockton became Utah's full-time point guard, it
was evident he and Malone would develop a special yin-yang
chemistry. But the Jazz's supporting cast has always been flawed in
some way. For all of Stockton's playmaking pizazz and Mailman's
multitasking, it took Utah five seasons to finally escape the first
round, then seven more to reach the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Malone holds the record for most times being voted to the
All-NBA first team _ 11. Only Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, who held on for
20 seasons, and Wilt Chamberlain, who played mostly in the
no-defense era, have scored more points in the NBA's history. This
season, Malone was still able to average 25.5 points and 9.5
rebounds per game.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton, of course, holds the career assist record, and despite
the miles on his undersized body, he continues to run an offense as
efficiently as any point guard 10 years his junior. Jason Williams
throws more showboat passes in a single game than Stockton will in
an entire season, but which of them would you rather have surveying
the court, ball in hand, with the clock ticking down?
</P>
<P>
   Although the Jazz has stumbled collectively, Malone and Stockton
should hardly be branded failures individually. Genius can be its
own reward, and sometimes that must suffice.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
