<SLUG> BC-BKN-NELSON-MAVS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON NELSON TO COACH MAVERICKS NEXT SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Don Nelson will return as the Mavericks' coach next
season, with a formal announcement coming by the end of this month
or early next month.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks owner Mark Cuban said yesterday that he has talked to
Nelson about returning, but the details have not been finalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see Nellie leave with a ring under his belt, and I
think we can get there,'' Cuban said from London, where he is
vacationing.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has coached 22 seasons in the NBA, but has never taken a
team to the NBA Finals. However, with the Mavericks improving in
the second half of the season, Cuban said the team is ripe to take
the next step _ but only with Nelson as its coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought there was someone better out there, I would tell
him so and we would go after them,'' Cuban said. ``But I don't
believe there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said the Mavericks' top players _ Michael Finley and Dirk
Nowitzki _ want Nelson to return. The Mavericks won 16 of their
final 21 games last season, and had the NBA's best record in April
at 9-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks finished 40-42, their best record since 1989-90,
when they were 47-35.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to build on \R16-5/40-42\S ,'' Cuban said. ``I expect
this team to improve, and I expect us to make it to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the Mavericks' April 19 game against Minnesota was
his final one as a coach. He wanted to return only as general
manager. He has been vacationing at his off-season home in Maui,
Hawaii, and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is expected back today. Cuban, meanwhile, said he won't
return to Dallas until the end of the month. At that time, he plans
to resume contract negotiations with Nelson, who turned 60 on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One source expects Nelson to return as coach. ``Nellie loves
money, and Cuban has a lot of it,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said he was impressed with Nelson's performance in the
second half of the season. He said he expects to have a business
relationship with Nelson ``for a long, long, long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nellie has been my partner in this effort,'' Cuban said.
``It's important to me that he gets the chance to build upon last
season's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nellie is a Hall of Famer, and he deserves the same respect
and reverence I give the players. More importantly, I think he is
an incredible coach, and the players want him back.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban would not say whether newly hired assistant coach Sidney
Moncrief will eventually succeed Nelson as the Mavericks' head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nellie likes what he brings to the mix,'' Cuban said. ``He
knows Nellie and his systems, and he can contribute from his own
experience as a player in this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to groom all of our coaches to contribute in new ways,
and give them all a chance to gain new responsibilities. Sidney
Moncrief will get those chances as well.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
