<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, May 18.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-LOBBY (Washington) _ Lobbyists for high-tech
industries are working furiously to support the China trade bill.
By Lizette Alvarez. High tech industries are lobbying furiously for
the trade vote.
</P>
<P>
   SAINT-TROPEZ (Saint Tropez) _ Even on a cold, rainy spring day,
the tourists find their way to the beach that made this resort so
famous. There is little to hint of the fierce battle for control of
one of France's major tourist attractions that is going on behind
the scenes. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-VICE-PRESIDENT (Taipei, Taiwan) _ Annette Lu says Taiwan
is an ``independent sovereign state.'' She thinks President Clinton
ought to invite the leaders of Taiwan and China to hash out their
differences at the White House. And when asked whether there are
two Chinas _ a proposition that outrages Beijing and sends most
officials here into semantic contortions _ she does not miss a
beat: ``I would say so.'' Is it any wonder that the new government
of the president-elect, Chen Shui-bian, seems eager to silence its
outspoken vice president-elect? By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-SCHOOLS (Macy, Neb.) _ Even in a nation used to hearing
stories about battered public schools, those in Indian country
stand out. Last year, the average student here at the Omaha Nation
Public School scored in the 15th percentile on national
standardized tests, and almost half scored below the 10th
percentile. The obstacles the Omaha Nation School wrestles with are
echoed in Indian schools around the country. Now, the White House
and others are starting to go after this problem. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIET-HYPERTENSION (Undated) _ A controlled study shows that
lowering sodium intake along with a high calcium diet known as DASH
is effective in combatting hypertension. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   DOMESTIC-VIOLENCE (Undated) _ Confirming a long-standing trend
in crime and society, a new Justice Department report shows a
continuing, steep drop in killings attributed to domestic violence,
particularly among blacks. Among blacks, the biggest drop is for
men killed by women, which has actually gone down about 71 percent
since the 1970s. (The number for women and men used to be about
even.) But there is one disturbing trend to emerge from the
department's annual report _ the numbers for white women have gone
up slightly. The face of domestice violence in America is now
largely a problem of attacks on white women, a major shift that
sociologists and law enforcement officials are just starting to
grapple with. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIOXIN-CANCER (Undated) _ In the draft of a report to be
released in June, the EPA lists dioxin as a ``human carcinogen.''
By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NOMINATIONS-POLL (Undated) _ Americans have little sense of
power over the presidential nominating process, with only a fifth
of them saying primary voters chose Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
and Vice President Al Gore as the candidates for President, the
latest New York Times/CBS News Poll shows. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUNDS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ This week, while the leaders of
the mutual fund industry munch shrimp and sip chardonnay at their
annual gathering in Washington, Steven Wallman will be 15 miles
away in Vienna, Va., plotting to take the finger food out of their
mouths. Wallman, a former securities regulator with an appetite for
reform, is increasingly irritated by the burdens the typical mutual
fund puts on shareholders. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   ELEPHANTS-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Last month, delegates met to
consider revisions to the treaty governing trade in endangered
species. Four southern African nations wanted permission to sell
their stockpiles of ivory, amassed mostly from culling herds of
elephants in their national parks. They promised to plow the
revenue back into conservation programs. The southern African
effort, which was vehemently opposed by Kenya, failed. Economists
take two distinct approaches to the problem of preserving
elephants. By Virginia Postrel.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ With its shrinking population,
declining industrial base and notoriously cold, snowy winters,
Buffalo has had its share of image problems for years. But local
officials and civic boosters insist that the city and its environs
do not deserve their unfortunate reputation. They are announcing a
major promotional campaign aimed at proving that the climate
upstate is just fine, for people and for businesses, too. By
Bernard Stamler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONCERT-MASTER (New York) _ What does a concert master do? Met
Opera's retiring master set a standard. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   FILMS-CANNES (Cannes) _ Though one could lose several nights'
sleep just trying to see all of the films in competition at this
year's Cannes Film Festival, there are great movie finds outside of
the main event. By Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-BIRTHDAY (Rome) _ On May 18th the pope turns 80, a
milestone that also falls in a Holy Year of the Roman Catholic
Church, and the Vatican has prepared a day-long religious and
musical extravaganza. Among the chief conspirators in the
celebration is Gilbert Levine, a Jewish, Brooklyn-born conductor,
who is so comfortable inside the Vatican he refers to audiences
with the pope as ``going upstairs.'' By Alessandra Stanley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HUNTS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Hunts in Dreams,'' by Tom Drury
(Houghton Mifflin). By Richard Eder.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HOLMES-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``Murder Rooms: The Dark
Origins of Sherlock Holmes.'' By Julie Salamon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
