<P>
   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN-BOTANIC-GARDEN (New York) _ Trying to see through the
gates, shuddering at the sound of jackhammers and buzzsaws,
worrying about 85-year-old cherry trees dangling their roots in the
drained pond. It was like pacing the halls during a beloved's
interminable operation. But now the vigil is over and all us
worrywarts can relax: the Brooklyn Botanic Garden will reopen its
Japanese Hill and Pond Garden next Wednesday, and the patient never
looked better. By Ann Raver.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT7,8) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NJ-CITY-OF-LEARNING (Paterson, N.J.) _ ``Trees. I would like to
add trees,'' reads the legend on a simple map of a street in
Paterson, N.J., drawn in colored pencil by a freshman high school
student who lives on it. Green trees have been swirled onto the
black and white street, like the rotations of a wand. Urban
solutions can be this simple _ so simple in fact that a child can
discover them. Through an innovative plan called the ``City of
Learning,'' Paterson, a city of 170,000, largely Hispanic and
African-American, is giving public school children not only the
tools to understand its urban problems, but the chance to solve
them. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNER-CAMERAS (Undated) _ The toy-like I-zone and its
instant-camera siblings, the larger Popshot and Joycam, mark a
radical departure for Polaroid, whose success in the 1960s and 70s
was based on technological innovation. Now its innovations are
coming from design, according to David Laituri, Polaroid's manager
of design strategy, who offered a peek at Polaroid's future. By
Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBS-ARCHITECTURE (Prospect Heights, Ill.) _ There are places
architects fear to tread, and suburbs that are chockablock with
colonials, ranch houses, McMansions and good-taste design
committees often give them pause. ``I didn't think there was
anything you could really do in the suburbs,'' said Doug Garofalo,
a Chicago architect. But the suburbanites who have come calling on
his firm haven't played into the Ozzie and Harriet stereotype. By
Joseph Giovannini.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
