<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHAT-NOW?-SIERRALEONE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA LEONE CIVIL WAR MAY NOT YET BE OVER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This timely 425-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By RUPERT CORNWELL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The seizure of Foday Sankoh is a heavy, but not necessarily
fatal, blow for the Revolutionary United Front which, hours before
its leader was taken, was skirmishing with British paratroopers
only a dozen miles from Sierra Leone's capital, Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh's capture undoubtedly deprives the Sierra Leonean rebels
of their leader and most charismatic commander, who was technically
vice-president of the coalition government of Tejan Kabbah set up
following the September 1999 Lome peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But it was far from clear Wednesday night whether the eight-year
civil war was finally drawing to a close.
</P>
<P>
   One theory was that the rebel effort will now disintegrate and
factions of the RUF will switch allegiance to the government.
Others fear a new commander could emerge, and that the savage,
anarchic struggle will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relations between Sankoh and his troops are complex,'' one
diplomat said, acknowledging the fluidity of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sankoh was taken into custody _ possibly betrayed by some
of his nominal supporters _ rebel strength was put at 10,000 to
15,000, plus unknown numbers of child soldiers and other
sympathizers. This is well down from the estimated 45,000 army
whose units came within an ace of capturing Freetown 16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the pre-dawn clash between paratroopers and some 40 rebels,
coupled with a second attack on United Nations peacekeepers at Port
Loko north of Freetown, suggests that, far from being on the
retreat, as some reports had suggested, the RUF continues to be a
threat to the capital, and more than a match for many of its
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the presence of British troops, and a U.N. force
beefed up by the arrival of Nigerian troops, several bargaining
chips remain in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate consists of the 350 U.N. peacekeepers held
hostage upcountry. It is not known whether these are being held by
one group or by separate, perhaps rival, rebel units.
</P>
<P>
   The RUF still controls the diamond mines in the north and east
of Sierra Leone, the country's economic lifeblood. It also has
bases in neighboring Liberia, whose president Charles Taylor will
be a vital party to any peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. envoy, the civil-rights leader Jesse Jackson, is heading
to West Africa to meet Taylor and other regional figures. But the
Sankoh episode could make it harder to secure the hostages'
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a stumbling block in the negotiations,'' a
spokesman for Taylor said. ``Sankoh was a key part of the Lome
agreement.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this timely 425-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
