A8601 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-CYBERSLEUTHS-IHT-NYTS     05-18 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSLEUTHS-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBER-CRIMEBUSTERS ARE ON THE CASE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 750-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald
Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By BARRY JAMES  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   PARIS _ It has been little more than a week since the FBI opened
an Internet site to enable people to report fraud and crime on the
World Wide Web, and already it is inundated.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.ifccfbi.gov, received 3,700 complaints in its
first three days, ``which was surprising considering the system is
not well known,'' said the FBI deputy director, Thomas Pickard, at
the world's first international conference on cybercrime here.
</P>
<P>
   Although major villainy like child pornography on the Internet
and rogue programs like the ``ILOVEYOU'' virus grab the headlines,
Pickard's observations were a reminder that like an iceberg, the
vast majority of cybercrime is invisible.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of it, he said, is $300 scams that victims put down to
experience and never report or that get low priority on police
blotters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lack of detection is a major problem, which is aggravated by
lack of awareness on the part of potential victims,'' the Japanese
chief delegate, Toshinori Kanemoto, told the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it is about time that governments as well as industry
act to implement a policy for education and awareness building
about Internet security.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickard said the new reporting center on the Internet should
help the FBI track down crooks who operate across state and
national boundaries _ like the scam artist who he said sold
``autographed'' Mickey Mantle baseball cards to uncounted numbers
of sports fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd been real, I'd probably wanted to have bought them
myself,'' Pickard said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows the true impact of crime on the Internet. For
example, estimates of the damage caused by this month's e-mail
virus varied widely. ``We were surprised at the very high valuation
put on those losses,'' said Henri Serres, whom the French cabinet
appointed as its data security chief.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, the virus attack was a warning of the
damage that could be caused by ruthless criminals, and could be
positive if it made people more conscious of the dangers.
</P>
<P>
   The conference here is a first attempt to identify the problem
in its global dimensions and offer some solutions for the July
conference of industrialized nations in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day Paris meeting, ending on Wednesday, brings
together government officials, law enforcement officers and
representatives of private industry from the Group of Seven
industrialized countries and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   It also offers delegates a chance to discuss divergent
approaches to the problem. While the United States favors a
hands-off approach and the greatest possible degree of
self-regulation, the Europeans see more room for government action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our common interest to restrain the excesses of an
unfettered freedom,'' said the French prime minister, Lionel
Jospin, in his opening remarks to the conference on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans also distrust what they see as a cowboy attitude
toward privacy in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The French interior minister, Jean-Pierre Chevenement, rejected
the notion that private data about consumers should be freely
traded, or that merchants or governments should have unrestricted
power to snoop into private lives.
</P>
<P>
   He warned that societies must preserve their fundamental values
and be vigilant that ``the new technologies do not become a
universal instrument of control and enslavement.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology industry representatives were dismissive of a
European Union proposal that Internet operators, such as service
providers, preserve customer and traffic data for three months in
case it is needed in crime investigations.
</P>
<P>
   David Aucsmith, chief scientist at Intel Corp., said the sheer
volume of data flowing around the Internet made it practically
impossible to store everything.
</P>
<P>
   Serres said government involvement in the Internet would not be
so necessary if industry did more to create a secure environment,
which Aucsmith described as ``a partly correct statement'' since
companies have been trying to get people online and make the
Internet as user-friendly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is natural tension between security and ease of use,''
he said, while acknowledging that as far as security goes ``we
could have done better.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevenement said that France would make combating cybercrime one
of the priorities of its six-month presidency of the European Union
starting in July, and would organize another major conference on
the subject at Poitiers, France, in November.
</P>
<P>
   He said France would support a convention on cybercrime drafted
by the Council of Europe in Strasbourg, which proposes permanent
points of contact between governments to deal with the problem and
establish extradition procedures. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 750-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
