<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8603 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-18 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALAMA BRILLIANT AS MARINERS BLANK TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Meanwhile, it was a rather notable night for John
Halama as well.
</P>
<P>
   On the night the Mariners signed Rickey Henderson, Halama
pitched his best game of the season and second career shutout to
beat Minnesota, 4-0, Wednesday and complete Seattle's three-game
sweep of the Twins. If any coaches want to teach young players how
to pitch, a videotape of Halama's game would be a good start.
</P>
<P>
   Halama, 7 years old when Henderson stole his first base in the
major leagues in 1979, held the Twins to four singles, walked no
one and faced only 29 batters, two more than the minimum. He threw
just 87 pitches, 57 for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, 87 pitches. And if that doesn't sound impressive,
you weren't watching Halama's previous start when he threw 84
pitches and retired only 12 batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was simply an outstanding job,'' manager Lou Piniella
said. ``He was throwing strikes, changing speeds, using both sides
of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   The best game of Halama's career? ``It's a short career,'' the
pitcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and Halama has struggled at times with his control, as most
inexperienced pitchers do. He walked six in his previous start,
against Oakland, including four in the fifth inning when he didn't
retire a batter.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella said he hoped Halama learned something from the poor
outing, and the lefty did. Facing a less disciplined lineup than
Oakland's, he allowed only four Minnesota batters to reach base
safely and only one runner to get to second base _ and that was on
a balk with two outs in the ninth inning. Two of the four batters
who singled were quickly eliminated on double plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I didn't want to walk anybody,'' said Halama, who
improved his record to 5-0. ``I wanted to get ahead of hitters and
make them put the ball in play right away. I would rather take a
beating out there than walk anybody. I really worked on locating
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's come a long way since last year as far as his command,''
Minnesota DH and ex-Mariner Butch Huskey said. ``He showed a little
bit of command last year, but when he can throw his curveball for
strikes like he did tonight, that's impressive command. He kept us
off-balance all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama struck out only two batters, but that's not his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You strike out people and your pitch counts gets up there. I
try to stay away from that,'' Halama said. ``I just wanted to put
the ball in play. Whether they're groundouts, flyouts or home runs,
I just want to make them put the ball in play.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama got all the run support he needed from familiar faces.
Alex Rodriguez extended his hitting streak to 13 games with two
singles and scored a run. John Olerud singled home one run and
doubled home another. Edgar Martinez homered well over the left
field fence to increase his team-leading RBI total to 45.
</P>
<P>
   So all in all, it was the sort of night when Seattle appeared to
need little additional help, let alone perhaps one of the greatest
leadoff hitters in history.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Seattle doesn't play the Twins every night, either.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had lost five of their past seven games and their
division lead before the series, but, as usual, the Twins proved
the perfect tonic for a struggling club. Not only did they never
lead in the series, they never came close. They lost 14-0 Monday
night, trailed 9-1 in the fourth inning Tuesday and never got going
against Halama Wednesday night. Martinez in particular hammered the
Twins, homering three times and driving in nine runs.
</P>
<P>
   The game ended Seattle's longest stretch so far without a day
off, and despite some rocky moments, the Mariners wound up in
pretty good shape. They went 7-6 in the 13 games and finished it
right where they began it _ in first place with a 1{-game lead.
Seattle has Thursday off, then begins the Rickey Era during a
three-game series against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an excellent leadoff hitter,'' Halama said. ``His record
speaks for itself as far as what he'll do out there on the field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
