<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-DEFENSE-WOES-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YET ANOTHER BLOW FOR U.S. DEFENSE INDUSTRY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 675-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald
Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JOSEPH FITCHETT  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   PARIS _ The British government's decision to equip its air force
with European-made missiles and military transports was a major
setback for the Clinton administration's hopes of getting European
support for flagging U.S. defense industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe Wins,'' Le Monde newspaper said jubilantly in a
front-page headline Wednesday, describing the deal as proof that
Prime Minister Tony Blair's government has rallied to more
independent defense capabilities in Europe, a theme long championed
by France.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the outcome more broadly, British and other European
analysts drew different conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the deal underlines mounting transatlantic
competitiveness in armaments as Europe puts together stronger
companies through cross-border consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   It also showed that Britain's involvement in defense matters in
the European Union will require France and Germany to do more to
modernize their own military forces _ or risk seeing Britain revert
to closer ties with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In offering to buy Airbus Industrie military transport aircraft,
a project still on the drawing board known as A400M, the Blair
government stipulated, as Defense Secretary Geoff Hoon said in
Parliament, that ``we hope that we can sign a contract for the
A400M urgently, but this must be based on realistic figures for
purchase.''
</P>
<P>
   London has thus confronted Paris and Berlin with the need for
big investments fast to build the European cargo plane. France and
especially Germany may be unable to afford both Airbus's civil
project, a superjumbo to compete with Boeing's 747, and the
military transport.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may turn out to be an opportunity for the U.S.
suppliers,'' an industry source said. Lockheed-Martin has C-130Js,
the new Hercules, already in service with the Royal Air Force, and
the British announcement Tuesday included a lease for giant C-17
Globemasters, widening Boeing's presence in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the setback for Washington was unmistakable. It
was only the second time that the European members of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization have purchased a non-U.S. weapons
system for themselves. The first was the British-German-Italian
Tornado warplane developed in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   That was the predecessor of Eurofighter, which will now be armed
with the Meteor air-to-air missile manufactured by a branch of
European Aerospace, Defense &AMP; and Space Co., a multinational
consortium in which French and German companies have a majority.
</P>
<P>
   The ramifications of the deal _ for the missile and for cargo
planes to be built by Airbus _ go beyond the $7 billion price tag
on Britain's purchases. Commercially, the potential global market
will be worth 10 times that figure, industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing disappointment, the Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said
that ``it was a setback in that we had offered the British an
opportunity to work cooperatively.'' Raytheon Co., the U.S.
competitor, had promised to improve its air-to-air missile with a
major British work share.
</P>
<P>
   But British officials privately said that the Clinton
administration had brought too little influence to bear, too late,
to forestall a European surge in defense industries.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. companies, including Raytheon, seen as unchallengeable two
years ago as they emerged from massive consolidation, have shown
signs of weakness.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a Blair aide said in private, London shares doubts
in Europe about President Bill Clinton's power to deal with
Congress on export controls for U.S. technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Meteor missile, as standard European equipment in the
future, will not necessarily impair European warplanes' ability to
fight alongside U.S. aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, its technical prowess is designed to compensate
for weaknesses in the Eurofighter warplanes, which lack advanced
features, notably stealth, of current U.S. aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the deal will be felt primarily in terms of
heightened transatlantic industrial rivalry, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a European tilt in this order, but it does not mean
that Britain has adopted a permanent industrial policy based on
some political bias in favor of Europe,'' according to Charles
Grant, head of the Center for European Reform, a think tank in
London. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 675-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
