<HEADER>
A8686 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV21-C     05-18 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: OF WAR AND TRUTH
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 21.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One cool and bright Sunday morning in February
1991, some pilots and soldiers of the 101st Airborne (''Screaming
Eagle'') Division joined in an outdoor religious service at their
forward base in Saudi Arabia, some 10 miles from the Iraqi enemy
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, the 101st mounted what remains the biggest
helicopter assault in the annals of warfare. In 100 hours of
one-sided combat, the division reached the southern bank of the
Euphrates River, having taken thousands of Iraqi prisoners without
losing a single Screaming Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   The 101st had been led to expect fierce resistance by Saddam's
Revolutionary Guards, with many combat causalities. It was with
those anxieties in mind that Maj. Sonny Moore, the brigade
chaplain, asked his camouflaged flock to open their Bibles to the
Book of Revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Moore read: ``And I saw as it were a sea of glass mingled with
fire: and them that had gotten the victory over the beast, and over
his image, and over his mark, and over the number of his name,
stand on the sea of glass, having the harps of God.''
</P>
<P>
   That desert observance came to mind the other day as I read
Seymour Hersh's 25,000-word report in the New Yorker magazine on
the actions of the 24th Infantry Division (Mechanized) in the
waning days of the Persian Gulf war. Along with the 101st (Air
Assault) and 82nd Airborne Divisions, the 24th comprised the XVIII
Airborne Corps. With help from the French, this force mounted the
famed ``left hook'' against the hapless Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hersh's article ran, retired Gen. Barry McCaffrey, who
had commanded the 24th in the Gulf war, and who now commands the
anti-drug program in the White House, mounted a pre-emptive strike.
He alleged to New Yorker editor David Remnick that Hersh was
concocting a false revisionist history of how the war had ended.
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue that carried Hersh's account of alleged U.S.
war crimes, Remnick wrote: ``The United States government, in its
determination to avoid the chaos and protest of Vietnam, controlled
reporters' access to the Gulf battlefield to an unprecedented
degree. ... (Reporters), to their dismay, found themselves forced
to do their reporting from briefing rooms in Saudi Arabia and the
Pentagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Sad and true. Yet, with pluck and luck, journalists eluded
military minders and found their way to the war zone. Some
divisional commands, notably the Marines and the 101st, even
welcomed our presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unsettling that we cannot come to closure on a chapter
of history as recent as the Gulf war,'' observes Daniel Schorr,
senior news analyst for National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt, if Hersh could have been there among the
warriors, rather than having to marshal their recollections nearly
a decade later, he would have been able to write an unquestionably
definitive account. Had more reporters been on the scene, it's
quite possible that some events might have unfolded differently.
</P>
<P>
   Even though such an open coverage policy serves the national
interest, it has yet to be adopted. If I'm around for a future
conflict, I'll be sure to carry the Bible that Moore inscribed to
me in the desert as a ``special man on a special mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
