<HEADER>
A8706 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN21-COX     05-18 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bush's gamble with your retirement
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the details will redeem it, but at first blush George W.
Bush's much-touted plan looks more likely to deform than to reform
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the pending GOP presidential nominee with boldness in
taking on the issue outside the usual formulas. The baby-boomer
crush can't be willed away by ignoring it.
</P>
<P>
   Without substantial change, the Social Security Trust Fund will,
by current estimates, be exhausted by 2037. Revenues into it could
cover only about 70 percent of the obligation.
</P>
<P>
   Any fix will be painful. Either benefits will have to be
reduced, or payroll taxes increased or benefit ages raised or some
combination of all-of-the-above. Or...
</P>
<P>
   Or the program will have to be radically refigured to somehow
sustain retirement incomes levels otherwise. Bush is proposing
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would let workers use 2 percent _ for starters _ of their
Social Security payments for private investment. If the economic
winds prove fair, and if they invest either cannily or luckily,
most workers should be able to retire with maybe $300 a month more
than they would get from straight Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Bad luck in stock or money markets could financially strand
retirees. Bush says he would hedge the system against that, but in
a bit of a political shell game, he is withholding those and other
details until specific legislation is drafted after, he says, he is
elected.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, you will have to make Bush president to see just
what he's talking about. Buying a pig in a poke is an inelegant but
apt description of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   What Bush is certainly not talking about is reforming Social
Security. Even if most workers came out a bit ahead, taking away 2
percent of payments into the system would hurry the fund's fatigue
to 2023.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, by holding current and imminent retirees harmless,
Bush is betting the appeal to young workers will draw him more
votes than fiddling with the system will cost him.
</P>
<P>
   Could be. Young workers have grown up with overnight wealth
popping up all around them like morning geysers. Why put money into
some stodgy old trust fund when you could be soaring?
</P>
<P>
   And they have been soured on Social Security by longtime
opponents of it claiming it's so doomed they'll never get a dime
back, when in fact the system can be sustained indefinitely with
periodic _ though, as noted, sometimes ouchy _ updatings, as we
have been doing all along.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security, it is worth remembering, is not an investment
scheme. It is an insurance policy, with emphasis on the ``social.''
It hedges all of us _ and indemnifies the society we share _
against the possibility and consequences of dire elderly poverty.
</P>
<P>
   It has succeeded magnificently. There still are elderly poor,
but the desperate poverty of the aged that once shamed the nation,
and the lifetimes of anxious uncertainty that accompanied that, are
gone.
</P>
<P>
   There's something to be said for the ``security'' in Social
Security, too.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He writes from
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
