<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT SEEING EYE TO EYE ON GUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those moms marching against America's gun culture on Mother's
Day called to mind a session I had with a pistol-packing
optometrist a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   All I wanted was an eye exam and a prescription. What I got in
addition to those services was an earful of his waxing hot about
his misinterpretation of the Second Amendment and the wonders of
his new laser-sighted 9mm security blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of other gun fanatics around the country, the
good eye doctor insisted that the Constitution's authorization of
armed state militias gave him the right to keep arms. He had bought
deeply into the National Rifle Association's Second Amendment
mumbo-jumbo.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Legislature, of course, had provided him with a legal
way to carry his handgun from place to place concealed. He didn't
need a permit to have it in his office, although his wearing it in
a holster there under his smock was suspect.
</P>
<P>
   He unholstered the weapon and let me heft it right there. It
felt good, that piece. Well-balanced. Not too heavy, but worthy of
a manly grasp. Nothing like the unwieldy .45 I had wielded so
ineffectively in the Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just line up the red dot where you want to hit and squeeze. Go
ahead,'' he said. I heard the click and imagined the devastation.
It was exhilarating. I just knew that I could really blow away some
menacing tin cans with that fancy hardware.
</P>
<P>
   The experience, however, was also a little scary. It is, after
all, a bit unsettling to have a guy who is armed and waiting for
Armageddon about to fuss around with your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   So I didn't bother at that time to try to explain to him the
historical context in which the Second Amendment evolved _ how it
has no relevance to individual gun ownership today and very little
relevance to anything else now that the National Guard has replaced
the state militias.
</P>
<P>
   My well-protected optometrist went on to tell me about how he
made his corner of that shopping strip safe, how the police didn't
worry about that area because they knew he was there and that he
had taken the training that gave him the license to tote heat.
</P>
<P>
   Since that eye care center was located on a thoroughfare that
bordered a predominantly African-American neighborhood and a
Hispanic neighborhood, I wondered about the roots of the eye
doctor's motivation for packing iron while dilating pupils.
</P>
<P>
   But I concluded that he wasn't a racist. He would be an equal
opportunity shooter if the occasion arose. That was what really
troubled me about him. I suspected that a threatening intruder
would make his day.
</P>
<P>
   I could not help but speculate about how many more people in the
states that allow individuals to carry concealed or openly have
that same kind of mind-set. I suspected that he was not unique. But
I didn't leap to the hasty conclusion that a large percentage of
the licensed-to-carry crowd are bent that way.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that episode today, I have concluded that my erstwhile
(meaning not anymore) optometrist was a victim of the gun
industry's successful campaigns during the past half century to
glamorize and glorify its products.
</P>
<P>
   The gun folks have been abetted enormously in their brainwashing
efforts by the movie industry, which has made gun violence a
pervasive element of its repertoire and has made killing seem
almost casual behavior, devaluing human life and transforming
characters who mow down scores of other fictional people into
heroic figures.
</P>
<P>
   Gun industry snake-oil pushers also have succeeded in wrapping
their products in bunting by knowingly perpetuating the Second
Amendment fraud and thereby persuading gun enthusiasts that they
are upholding some grand constitutional principle by opposing gun
control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   It is well, then, that the Million Mom March has not ended with
the events of last weekend. A Million Mom March Foundation is to be
formed to keep up the pressure for more gun control legislation and
the enforcement of that already on the books. At the same time, the
foundation will provide the public with information on how its
representatives in Congress stand on gun issues and the extent of
their support from the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's educational efforts will ultimately prove more
significant to the cause of curbing gun proliferation in this
society than the actual legislation that Congress now is
considering as a result of the march.
</P>
<P>
   Such pressure will go far toward deglamorizing guns, dispelling
the gun culture mystique and reducing the number of guns that are
available to tempt troubled children, criminals, emotionally
damaged grownups and oddballs like my erstwhile optometrist.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
