<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8755 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-$ADV21-CO     05-18 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MORE TRADE WITH U.S. LIKELY TO SPEED CLOSINGS, LAY-OFF AT
CHINESE FACTORIES
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The way Chinese factory workers see it, lay-offs loom
inevitably in their future, regardless of any vote by the U.S.
Congress or whether China joins any world trade bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run factories they work at are dinosaurs left-over
from the era of the planned economy and will most likely not make
it in the era of global economic competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only result from joining (the World Trade Organization) is
China will lay off a huge number of workers,'' said a 43-year-old
worker at the Beijing Textile Machine Factory, who declined to give
his name. ``I'm already facing being laid off. Joining WTO will
only make it sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   As the U.S. Congress prepares to vote on permanently normalizing
trade relations with China _ which President Bill Clinton says is
necessary to allow the United States to benefit from a far-reaching
trade accord securing China's entry into the WTO _ all that
laborers here see is a rapidly-changing economy that is leaving
them behind as it further opens its 1.2 billion-consumer market to
the world.
</P>
<P>
   What were once pillars of the Marxist economy are now just dead
weight as China readies itself to join the ``club'' of global
trading powers. The government has been aggressively pushing
state-owned enterprises to either shut down or make a profit and
has closed thousands of money-losing factories.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.2 million textile workers have already lost their jobs
in the last two years. With reforms in other industries, such as
steel and coal mining, the number of laid-off workers will reach 12
million by the end of the year, according to government estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Such wrenching change has been difficult for millions of
middle-aged workers in China who came of age in the era of the
``iron rice bowl'' and still look to Chairman Mao Zedong for
ideological guidance. The state provided not just a job but took
care of their housing, medical care, schooling and food
distribution as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Textile Machine Factory looks as though its walls haven't
been painted nor its machinery updated since it opened in 1958. The
only way it has kept itself alive is by slicing off its property
piece-by-piece and going into the lucrative real estate market. A
few of its buildings are rented to an exclusive private school
where diplomats and expatriates send their children. Another large
block has given way to three high-rise apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Some of its laid-off workers have gotten janitorial or other
temporary work in these new ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he knew when he would be laid off, the 43-year-old
worker, who has been at the factory since he was 18 and makes about
US$50 a month, replied: ``That's in the hands of the factory
officials. One day they'll tell you they don't need you and just
kick you out and send you home.''
</P>
<P>
   His bitterness is mild compared to the anger of other workers
around the country who haven't been paid in months or even years.
Scattered protests and other disturbances have been reported with
growing frequency.
</P>
<P>
   One worker tried to give an American reporter the upside of
globalization. Liu Jiuwang, 44, who has been painting machines at
the factory for 20 years, said accession in the WTO would be good
for Chinese consumers as they could buy a wider variety of goods at
lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``More foreign brands will enter China, and I can choose whether
to buy products from Japan or Singapore or Malaysia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But with a monthly salary of US$60, it is unlikely Liu can often
take advantage of such a selection. He said it will take him two
years to save for a computer for his teen-age daughter ``if we're
not picky about what we eat or drink.''
</P>
<P>
   With their future uncertain, many workers did not seem ready for
the new world economy. A 48-year-old worker who has been at the
textile machine factory for 30 years said he didn't know what he
was qualified to do after he is laid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``My niece works at (a high-tech) company,'' said the worker,
who declined to give his name. ``Her generation thinks we should do
it all. But my generation thinks we shouldn't do any of it. We're
different generations. We have nothing to talk about. We grew up
under Chairman Mao's principles.''
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   headlines.yahoo.com/FullCoverage/World/China/ for the latest
headlines on China.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
