<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8770 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-CHILDHOOD-FEARS-HNS &LR;      05-18 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDHOOD-FEARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NOTHING TO FEAR BUT FEAR ITSELF, UNLESS YOU'RE A CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STACIE ORSAGH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Like many kids, Mia Balderas sleeps in her own
bedroom, with a nightly routine of story time, prayer and turning
on the night light.
</P>
<P>
   But as shadows creep across walls and tree branches scrape
against the house, her 5-year-old imagination runs wild.
</P>
<P>
   There is a reason parents find themselves back in the bedroom to
read one more story, tuck the kiddo in one more time or bring
another glass of water to a suddenly thirsty child: fear. Fear of
the bogeyman, fear of noises or simply fear of the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents remember encounters with the bogeyman or in the
Mexican-American culture, El Cucui, the fictitious monster that
lurks under children's beds. Now parents must help their own
children cope with certain fears.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling fear is a normal part of children's development and
should not be seen as unusual, said Ed Gerwell, a San Antonio
psychologist who treats both children and adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear teaches young children to avoid certain dangers in
reality,'' he said. ``The unknown is an insecurity in children;
they don't have adult capabilities and experiences of security.''
</P>
<P>
   Not being able to control things is a struggle for children, and
parents are key to alleviating these qualms. According to Gerwell,
insecurities need to be conquered for the child to be successful in
overcoming the fears, and parents are the security blankets
children look to for comfort. Children look to parents to protect
them, said Roger Tripp, a licensed professional counselor at
Christus Santa Rosa Hospital in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is most important for parents to act in control of the
situation,'' Tripp said. ``Telling the child, `I am here, I will
help,' will reassure them.''
</P>
<P>
   Parental attitudes set the stage for children's reactions. Anger
toward a child makes him or her more uneasy, Gerwell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child is already afraid. If a parent gets angry it only
scares the child more,'' Gerwell said. ``This tends to make the
child feel like he is doing something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Rene and Liz Balderas try their best to help Mia and her two
younger sisters cope with the nightly apprehensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mia doesn't know about the bogeyman or the cucui, but she
feels very threatened at times,'' Rene Balderas said. ``A fear
still exists within her, regardless of what we have and have not
told her. I guess it is real easy to believe in bad things.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerned parents have discovered that following a routine
alleviates the stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't just throw her in her room, turn off the light and
say goodnight,'' Rene Balderas said. ``It is a slow transition, we
wind down for bedtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming fears helps children develop a sense of independence
and self-sufficiency. Once children learn to hone their self-help
skills, self-confidence grows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that parents avoid ridiculing the child.
Approach the feelings as very real,'' Gerwell said. ``At times they
are struggling and these fears are very real, very potent.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking through the challenge with the child and not leaving her
suspended in the fear will give the child more confidence, Gerwell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing between genuine fear and not wanting to go to bed
can be tricky but setting bedtime rituals can help. Gerwell
explained there is no harm done in returning to the bedroom to
check on the child, but the parents need to be careful how to
approach the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can create more of a problem by taking them into your
bedroom,'' the psychologist said. ``You need to handle it
reasonably and keep them in their environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it can be more serious than expected. If a child is
seriously impaired because of certain fears, a professional should
be contacted. Fears could be coming from real situations that
parents may not be aware of.
</P>
</TEXT>
