<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8776 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-18 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ASKING QUESTIONS IS A TWO-WAY STREET IN JOB INTERVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How can you go into a job interview, give all
the right answers and still come out a loser? Maybe you didn't ask
the right questions.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who don't ask any insightful questions can come
across as uninterested or self-absorbed, which is hardly what you
are trying to convey to an interviewer. Besides, you should want to
know the answers to certain questions merely for the sake of
self-preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Here are five questions you should get answered before accepting
any job offer:
</P>
<P>
   What do people dislike most about working there? So that you
don't come across as negative, this might be something you want to
find out through networking rather than your official interviews,
but you ought to know about the main skeletons in the company
closet before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Is management arrogant? Is back-stabbing common? Is there high
turnover or are there lingering disputes? Do people laugh when you
mention work-life balance?
</P>
<P>
   The company might well be wonderful, but if all you hear are
positives, you are getting snowed. If you don't think so, consider
San Francisco. It's one of the world's favorite cities, but any
resident could quickly list a dozen of its faults, including the
San Andreas.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's perfect. No company is, either.
</P>
<P>
   Think about one question you can ask the interviewer that shows
that you've done your research and thought about how you could help
the company. The more insightful the question, the better.
</P>
<P>
   Remember: This should be a question that shows you've done your
research _ not that you haven't. If the answer to the question
could be found easily by checking the company's Web site, it's the
wrong question.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful, too, that the question doesn't come across as
arrogant, as if the company should have implemented some policy
three years ago. You want to come across as sincerely interested,
not smug.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you were going to work for a car maker. ``Is the company
planning to add an SUV to its line?'' might be a good, sincere
question. ``Why doesn't the company sell an SUV?'' asks the same
thing, but can come across as judgmental.
</P>
<P>
   Does the company value diversity as much, or as little, as you
do? Again, this might be something you'll answer more through
networking than through your formal interviews.
</P>
<P>
   If diversity is important to you, try to talk with high-ranking
women and minorities to learn about the corporate culture. If you
can't find any of them, you might already have your answer.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there are high-ranking minorities and women, don't just
assume that the company values diversity. If you shove everyone
into the same mold, you don't have a diverse organization, no
matter what your employee demographics say.
</P>
<P>
   Are people from different backgrounds encouraged to share ideas,
or is everything run from the top down? Does the company encourage
flexibility and work-life balance, or is everyone single, under 30
and working 80 hours a week?
</P>
<P>
   Diversity can come in a lot of forms, and so can bigotry. Some
people would never think about saying an ethnic slur, but wouldn't
think twice about stereotyping dot-commers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some people think diversity is an overblown
buzzword. If you are more comfortable around people who think and
act the same way you do, you might prefer an organization that
downplays diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Where will the company be 10 years from now? You can land a job
with a lot of companies, but don't count on a career unless that
company has a plan for the future. If no one can tell you how the
company will be stronger 10 years from now than it is today, stop
and think about whether you might be in a dead-end career.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean you should turn down the job, but don't think
it will last forever.
</P>
<P>
   Do you understand exactly what the company is offering? In the
era of stock options, this is a more crucial question than it used
to be.
</P>
<P>
   How much extra value are those options adding? Do you get to
keep them if you leave the company? What happens to them if you are
laid off? What happens if the company gets sold instead of going
public? Are you protected if the company runs out of cash?
</P>
<P>
   Before you leave your current job for the new one, make sure you
have the offer in writing. That provides at least a little
protection from any misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
