<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-CBS-SKED18-COX     05-18 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CBS-SKED18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Chicago Hope,' `Now and Again' get ax
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ CBS will put a big bet down on Bette Midler in the
fall, giving the star her own sitcom at 8 p.m. Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   The downside: ``The Bette Show'' has to go up against ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish `Millionaire' wasn't there. So does Bette,'' Leslie
Moonves, president of CBS Television, said Wednesday. ``We think
she's big enough to hold her own.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Bette Show,'' Midler plays an entertainer named Bette
Midler who is very much like herself, but with a college professor
husband and a teenage daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Also coming on CBS this fall, in a schedule announced Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Fugitive'' (8 p.m. Fridays), a revival of the old TV
series (and film). Tim Daly (``Wings'') plays Dr. Richard Kimble,
and Mykelti Williamson (``Forrest Gump'') is Lt. Philip Gerard, the
cop trying to capture him as he hops from city to city. The pilot,
produced by Warner Bros., is reportedly the most expensive TV pilot
ever made, at more than $6 million for the action sequences. (Drama
pilots generally cost in the $2 million range.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Yes, Dear'' (8:30 p.m. Mondays), a sitcom about two young
couples with different views on parenting (one's neurotic, one's
blase). No big names (Anthony Clark, Jean Louisa Kelly) in this
one.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``C.S.I.'' (9 p.m. Fridays), a crime drama with William
Petersen (``To Live and Die in L.A.'') and Marg Helgenberger as
forensic investigators.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``That's Life'' (8 p.m. Saturdays), which Moonves calls a
``charming and whimsical'' hour drama about a 30-ish New Jersey
woman (Heather Paige Kent) who leaves her blue-collar life to go to
college. Ellen Burstyn and Paul Sorvino play her parents.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The District'' (10 p.m. Saturdays) stars Craig T. Nelson
(``Coach'') as the police commissioner of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Welcome to New York'' (8:30 p.m. Wednesdays), a comedy about
an Indiana weatherman trying to hold his own at a New York
television station. The show loosely parallels David Letterman's
life, and comes from his production company.
</P>
<P>
   One surprising renewal on CBS' schedule is ``City of Angels,''
the Steven Bochco hospital drama with a predominantly
African-American cast. As the only black drama on television,
``Angels'' was No. 2 this season among black households (UPN's
``The Parkers'' is No. 1), but still has not caught on with white
viewers. Despite lukewarm ratings, Moonves renewed the show, and
will move it to 9 p.m. Thursdays. ``Obviously there's a lot of
attention being paid to it, but it's a good show or it wouldn't be
on our schedule,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gone from the CBS schedule: ``Chicago Hope,'' the long
troubled medical drama; ``Now and Again,'' the quirky Friday night
romantic drama that never quite caught hold with audiences;
``Martial Law,'' the kung fu series starring Sammo Hung; ``Early
Edition''; and ``Ladies Man,'' the Monday night sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ellen DeGeneres Show,'' a sketch-variety show similar to
the old ``Carol Burnett Show,'' is still in development. Moonves
said it will be a midseason replacement show.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be no remake of ``The $64,000 Question'' in an attempt
to jump on the ``Millionaire'' bandwagon. Moonves said the pilot
``just wasn't that good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Movies and miniseries coming next season on CBS include:
``Blonde,'' a semifictionalized life of Marilyn Monroe, based on
Joyce Carol Oates' novel; ``An American Tragedy,'' a look at O.J.
Simpson's ``Dream Team'' of lawyers (in which Simpson barely
appears), produced by Barry Levinson and Tom Fontana
(``Homicide''); ``Haven,'' a true story starring Natasha Richardson
as an Oskar Schindler-type who rescued 1,000 people during the
Holocaust; and ``Jewel,'' an adaptation of Bret Lott's best seller
(and Oprah Book Club pick) starring Farrah Fawcett and Cicely
Tyson. The previously announced live staging of ``On Golden Pond''
with Julie Andrews and a docudrama about the Elian Gonzalez case
are also in the works for next season.
</P>
<P>
   New shows for Pax TV
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling Pax TV network said Wednesday it would introduce
three new series later this year. ``Mysterious Ways,'' co-starring
Rae Dawn Chong, is about a professor driven to uncover the
mysteries behind uncanny occur-
</P>
<P>
   rences. ``The Rumfords'' is believed to be the first prime-time
series to mix cartoons and live-action comedy. ``Encounters With
the Unexplained'' is a reality series that explores some of the
mysteries of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Country music singer Billy Ray Cyrus will star in ``Doc,'' a
series about a country doctor who moves to Manhattan, but it won't
debut on Pax until next winter.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and UPN deliver their new schedules today.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Associated Press
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
