<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANCY-GRILLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GRILLS: KEEPING UP WITH THE JONESES' MAY COST MEGABUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALTA, N.Y. _ John Michaels is designing the ultimate barbecue
station.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels, the president of a home-building company, is in the
process of outfitting his Lake George summer residence with
state-of-the-art gas and charcoal grills.
</P>
<P>
   He has selected the top-line Beefeater gas grill, a
stainless-steel model from Australia that is the sport-utility
vehicle of outdoor grills. It has four separate 18,000 BTU
cast-iron burners and includes a wok burner. Michaels is having the
grill, which retails for as much as $3,569, built into stonework on
his deck.
</P>
<P>
   But he figures he will do most of his cooking in the Big Green
Egg, a new heavy-duty ceramic smoker and grill that uses lump
charcoal. A clay material product made in Atlanta, the Egg is
designed for slower cooking at lower temperatures. It costs
approximately $500, depending on the size.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels, who estimates his new barbecue station is going to set
him back $6,000 or so, intends to include a refrigerator cooler for
clams that will also be built into the stonework.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my regular house, I do almost all of my cooking with gas,
which I associate more with suburbia. But at the camp, I prefer to
use charcoal as much as possible,'' he said. ``The cheaper model
grills work all right, but you end up replacing them every few
years. In the long haul, this will save me money, I hope.''
</P>
<P>
   In the age of conspicuous consumption, high-end grills are in _
and getting higher and higher every year.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least a half-dozen different companies making
super-premium outdoor grills that cost $2,500 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The back yard has become a very big investment area for
families,'' said Donna Myers, a spokeswoman for the Barbecue
Industry Association and publisher of The Backyard Barbecuer
newsletter. ``One thousand to $2,000 grills are not considered even
very expensive anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for a moment, the possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Williams-Sonoma 48-inch stainless-steel grill cart, which
comes with an electric plug-in rotisserie. Cost: $4,995.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Grand Cafe 3000, by Grand Haul. It features cast brass
burners and infrared flavorizer bars, along with a built-in side
burner. Cost: $2,489.
</P>
<P>
   _ The bulky DCS (Dynamic Cooking Systems), with its
porcelain-plated grill grates, 693 square inches of cooking area
and 79,000 BTU. Cost: $4,465.
</P>
<P>
   _ The premium grill from Weber, the Budweiser of barbecue
companies. Weber-Stephen Co.'s Summit 650 is so powerful it uses
only natural gas to fire up the six burners stoking 75,000 BTUs. It
will handle everything from turkeys to baking a cake. Cost: $3,389.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Myers notes that the high-end market constitutes a
small percentage of the more than 8 million gas grills sold
annually in the United States (compared with 5 million charcoal
grills, a complete reversal from a decade earlier, when charcoal
outsold gas almost 2-to-1).
</P>
<P>
   There are many gas grills available for under $200, but the
fastest growing segment of the market, according to Myers, is
grills that sell for $400 to $800.
</P>
<P>
   Ducane makes a solid grill in the $600 range, and the Weber
Genesis line is in the same ballpark. As are many others.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the grills that sell for almost 10 times as much.
</P>
<P>
   Just think, Father's Day is right around the corner. And you
still have time to get to the bank and take out a second mortgage,
if a top-line grill is what you are after.
</P>
</TEXT>
