<HEADER>
A8792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-SPAETZLE-HNS &LR;      05-18 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAETZLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR A NEW TWIST ON NOODLES, TAKE A HINT FROM GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LISA STEVENS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tonight for dinner, you're in for a German treat.
</P>
<P>
   Spaetzle, a staple of southern Germany, is taking center stage
as the side dish. Forget the rice and potatoes. These tiny noodles
or dumplings made with flour, eggs, water and salt, are so
delicious, they'll fly off your plate. In fact, the literal
translation of spaetzle is ``little sparrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The dough can be firm enough to roll out and cut into strips or
soft enough to be pressed through a sieve or colander. Add spaetzle
to soups or serve as side dish to beef, poultry, pork or fish. The
noodles are great for soaking up meat juices, sauces and gravy.
</P>
<P>
   Toss with butter or sour cream, pan-fry with a little butter and
onion or saute the spaetzle in olive oil and chopped garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Other serving suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cheese spaetzle: Heat cooked and well-drained spaetzle in a
frying pan with butter. Stir in 4 to 5 tablespoons of Swiss cheese.
Top with sliced onions browned in butter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spaetzle and eggs: Brown cooked spaetzle in butter. Beat two
eggs, add chopped herbs (such as thyme, chervil or parsley) and
pour over spaetzle in the frying pan. Stir and heat until the eggs
are set.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kraut spaetzle: Drain 1 1/2 pounds sauerkraut. Mix sauerkraut
with a small chopped onion and brown in frying pan with butter. In
a separate pan, fry 1 cup cooked and well-drained spaetzle until
golden brown. Just before serving, combine all the ingredients. Top
with bacon bits, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mushroom spaetzle: Toss warm spaetzle with sauteed sliced
mushrooms. Sprinkle with grated parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spaetzle Italiano: Saute prosciutto, pancetta or pepperoni
cubes in butter. Add spaetzle and heat thoroughly. Serve with
tomato sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   SPAETZLE NOODLES
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   Sift flour, salt and nutmeg together in a bowl. Pour eggs and
1/4 cup water into middle of flour mixture, beat with a wooden
spoon. Add enough water to make the dough slightly sticky, yet
keeping it elastic and stiff. Using a spaetzle maker or a colander
with medium holes, press the noodles into a large pot full of
boiling salted water. Cook noodles in the water about 5 minutes or
until they rise to the surface. Lift noodles out and drain on paper
towels. Brown noodles in melted butter over low heat. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   KASESPAETZLE (SPAETZLE CHEESE NOODLES)
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   3 onions, sliced in small rings
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces Emmentaler or Swiss cheese; grated
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 cups spaetzle noodles, cooked
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chives, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Heat butter in frying pan, add onions, and brown lightly. Toss
cheese with dry mustard. Add cooked noodles and cheese to cooked
onions; mix well. Place mixture in an ovenproof casserole. Bake at
300 degrees for 20 to 30 minutes or until hot and bubbly. Sprinkle
top with chopped chives before serving.
</P>
<P>
   _ From recipeswenzel.com
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   SPINACH SPAETZLE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 6 servings)
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 (10-ounce) package frozen chopped spinach, thawed and squeezed
dry
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons margarine or butter (1/4 stick)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup almonds, optional, see note
</P>
<P>
   In 6-quart saucepot over high heat, heat 4 quarts water to
boiling. Meanwhile, in medium bowl, with spoon, beat flour,
spinach, eggs, milk, nutmeg, 1/2 teaspoon salt, and 1/2 cup water
until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce heat to medium; over simmering water, with rubber
spatula, press mixture through spaetzle maker (or colander or
grater with large holes). Cook spaetzle 2 to 3 minutes until tender
but firm, stirring gently so spaetzle doesn't stick together; drain
well in colander.
</P>
<P>
   In nonstick 12-inch skillet over medium-high heat, heat
margarine or butter, parmesan, pepper, and 1/2 teaspoon salt until
margarine melts. Stir in spaetzle; heat through.
</P>
<P>
   Note: For variation, add 1/4 cup slivered almonds with the
spaetzle, heat through.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving without almonds: 285 calories, 11 grams protein, 44
grams carbohydrate, 7 grams fat, 75 milligrams cholesterol, 515
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from Good Housekeeping magazine
</P>
</TEXT>
