<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCEPTUAL ART FINDS A HOME ON EBAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've all heard plenty about the eBay hucksters, the folks who
try to pawn off just about everything but a bridge in Brooklyn.
Last week, it was the sensitive guy hawking the ``100 percent
genuine raft used by Elian.'' This week, it's the henpecked
``husband'' unloading a painting because his ``wife'' hates
abstract images that resemble the work of modern master Richard
Diebenkorn (wink, wink).
</P>
<P>
   I mean, really. Would you offer $135,805, sight unseen, to an
art dealer who goes by the name ``golfpoorly?''
</P>
<P>
   The eBay con artists get all the attention, but what about the
lesser-known eBay artists? That's right. There is a new breed of
artist using the Internet auction site as a forum for creative
expression. Their work is hard to categorize; it's a combination of
conceptual art and performance art, sort of like a digital
happening in cyberspace. Where else can an artist reach a potential
audience of millions? What better place to make a wry comment on
our materialistic consumer culture?
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, sometimes it's hard to tell the serious artists from
the salesmen. Consider Lot 31: a postcard of a goat nursing a baby.
Was this recent sale an artist's attempt to exorcize childhood
scars or simply somebody getting rid of tacky stuff?
</P>
<P>
   Cyber artist Jeff Gates is definitely earnest about his auction
oeuvre. Last year, he posted an unusual item on eBay: his
demographics. Art world folks were impressed with his statement
about the value of art and the nature of privacy, but serious
bidders had no interest in the statistics of a middle-aged artist
and bureacrat. So Gates, who heads the new media initiative at the
Smithsonian's National Museum of American Art, turned the original
auction page into a framed art print and tried to sell that. Alas,
no takers. But Gates made his point. ``I'm interested in
advertising and how things get branded and sold,'' he says. In a
world where everything is up for sale, including our personal data,
how do we place a value on art?
</P>
<P>
   And what is art, anyway? Some eBay artists are using the
Internet to thumb their noses at the art establishment. The
collaborative RTMark, best known for switching the voiceboxes in
Barbie and GI Joe dolls a few years back, was invited to
participate in the Whitney Biennial this year; the group auctioned
off four tickets to the glitzy Whitney gala and then used the
proceeds ($8,400) to fund its anti-corporate activism.
</P>
<P>
   A group of students at the California Institute of the Arts got
some unexpected results when they tried a similar form of
experiment. The artists, who called themselves Akshun, auctioned
off their space in the school's art gallery on eBay last fall. They
were simply critiquing the elitist gallery system; they didn't
expect to stir up trouble with the State Department. It turns out a
group of dissident artists in North Korea were the lead bidders for
the space. The only problem? The sale was illegal under the Trading
with the Enemy Act. Sweet irony, that.
</P>
<P>
   Conceptual artist Cary Peppermint (yes, that's his real name)
hasn't exactly created an international incident with his eBay
experiments, but he is deliberately provocative. In one piece, he
claimed to be auctioning off nude photos of his ex-girlfriend. As
the auction proceeded, he posted titillating (but not quite nude)
photos on the site. The model in the photos wasn't really his
ex-girlfriend, but Peppermint says he felt guilty anyway, as if he
had exploited someone. ``I ended up operating under the thesis that
whoever fakes an illness, ends up staying in bed,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Peppermint is continuing his eBay exploits; earlier this year,
he auctioned an item called ``Use Cary Peppermint as a Medium.''
For $107.50, the winning bidder, artist Tim Whidden, received the
right to tell Peppermint what to do in a performance piece. So a
few weeks ago, Peppermint masqueraded as Whidden at a lecture at
Bard College; in front of a rather perplexed audience, he gave a
long tirade about Jennifer Love Hewitt before he was interrupted by
the real Tim Whidden.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing new about artists dissing the art establishment,
and it seems somehow appropriate to throw such statements into the
digital bazaar, along with the gizmos, the gadgets, and the garage
sale leftovers. But let's not take this too seriously and start
using the language of the art world to describe this passing fancy
as an emerging school of eBay art. ``It's a temporal aesthetic,''
explains Peppermint. ``I'll walk away when the time is right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Jeff Gates's work is at www.outtacontext.com, and Cary Peppermint's
work is at http://www.artnetweb.com/peppermint. For the goat
feeding the baby, see www.eBayTreasure.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh my goodness. Another Internet ``first!'' The folks at
www.AtomFilms.com have launched a ``total immersion'' film; called
``The Arrival,'' the film uses a technology that enables viewers to
choose the camera angle as they watch. It's still fairly primitive;
as you watch the film, it's easy to spend the whole time looking
out the window of a car or gazing at the floor. The film does have
a cute surprise ending; let's just say it concerns the death of Old
Media.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, www.Ifilm.com has recast itself as a search engine
and portal for online film in an attempt to differentiate itself
from other entertainment sites. The site will provide a guide to
its competition, including Atom Films, Shockwave, DEN, Wirebreak,
and Urban Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They call this convergence? A squishy foam foot that you can
squeeze during periods of high anxiety? Fox.com sent over this
little toy to promote its new Web site, www.peggysfeet.com. The
site was a companion to Sunday's episode of ``King of the Hill,''
which is about, well, Peggy Hill's big feet. The site is mildly
amusing, but it isn't exactly a major breakthrough in the merging
of the Web and television. But the foam foot is cute: I wonder how
much it will sell for on eBay?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-18 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S SELF-INFLICTED WOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; sometimes use this space to defend Microsoft Corp. against
the US Justice Department. I do so for three reasons:
</P>
<P>
   --Much of the case against Microsoft is bogus.
</P>
<P>
   --To the extent that the company has done wrong, dismantling it
is a grossly disproportionate response.
</P>
<P>
   --And finally, why bother? If Microsoft continues its recent
idiocies, it will end up eviscerating itself.
</P>
<P>
   First there's the antitrust case, which the company could have
settled painlessly a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Love Bug virus that attacked millions of
Microsoft-based computers worldwide, because Microsoft
intentionally left dangerous security holes in its products.
</P>
<P>
   And now comes Microsoft's legal threat against Slashdot, one of
the Internet's most respected technology sites. The company's
behavior is as clueless as it is brutish. Here's the story:
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows about the free Linux operating system, the most
famous open-source product, but there are many others. Kerberos,
for instance, is a data protocol designed to let people communicate
with computer networks without worrying their data might be
intercepted by bad guys. It was created at MIT, which freely offers
it to any software companies that want to add it to their products.
Kerberos has become quite a hit with businesses that rely on
versions of the Unix operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, sensibly enough, added Kerberos support to its
high-end corporate operating system, Windows 2000. But in standard
Microsoft fashion, the company also wanted to ``improve'' it, by
adding features to Kerberos that would make it work better with
other Microsoft products.
</P>
<P>
   People in the open source software community howled, and not
without reason. According to the notorious ``Halloween documents''
leaked to the public in 1998, Microsoft considered this very tactic
to undermine the popularity of open source software products like
the Linux operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft could add open source features to its own products,
but make changes in them. The open source features would still work
with other companies' products, but would work even better with
other Microsoft products. This would give Microsoft customers a
reason to stay loyal.
</P>
<P>
   The US Justice Department, suing Microsoft for antitrust
violations, said the Kerberos move was an unfair tactic to maintain
Microsoft's dominance of the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   They're correct, except for the ``unfair'' part. Microsoft has
every right to improve on existing products in ways that give them
an edge on rivals. As long as Microsoft's Kerberos still works with
other versions, I figure they're in the clear.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Microsoft promised to publish the details of its
changes to Kerberos. That would give other software makers a chance
to make their products compatible with Microsoft's.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's Kerberos document featured a bizarre legal
notice that said, in effect, ``Everything you read here belongs to
Microsoft. Don't try it at home.'' Microsoft published the data as
a ploy to show its ``openness,'' but ordered open source
programmers to act as if they'd never seen it.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when the popular Slashdot Web site published the
Microsoft document with the copyright warning removed, Microsoft
e-mailed Slashdot and threatened to sue if the offending materials
weren't removed. So far, Slashdot has refused. Perhaps it's eager
to see if Microsoft, a company on the verge of being ripped apart
for antitrust violations, would be stupid enough to pick a fight
over Kerberos.
</P>
<P>
   For a mature response to open source software, consider IBM
Corp.'s decision to offer Linux on its S/390 mainframes, the
machines that run banks, factories and the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   IBM will provide full corporate-grade support for Linux running
on its top-of-the-line hardware. Big Blue has had to upgrade Linux
to work on mainframes, but it's giving away its improvements at no
charge. Indeed, IBM has teams of programmers writing new and better
open source software, and giving it away.
</P>
<P>
   It's not altruism, of course. IBM makes its money selling
computer services, and can afford to give away software to get a
foot in the door. It's the same gambit Microsoft used with its Web
browser. Microsoft was right to do it, no matter what the courts
say. And IBM is right to embrace Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Microsoft reacts to the open source challenge with an
unseemly blend of spite and panic. When you're as self-destructive
as Microsoft has been in recent years, a court-ordered breakup
begins to seem almost academic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
