<HEADLINE>
NEXT STOP: GIBSON'S 1.12 ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ On the eighth date of Pedro's Baseball Tour, the star
of the show arrived at work as he normally does. He was
well-dressed: black shirt, black pants, and a gray jacket. And
after being told, teasingly, that his short afro was similar to
Fred Sanford's, he teased his own hair until it was slicked back
into a style that a young Billy Dee Williams once perfected.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez looked good at SkyDome, even though he didn't
feel it. ``A bad day,'' he replied, when asked to critique his
performance. ``A bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   If Martinez continues to have bad days like this, he will easily
win his second consecutive Cy Young Award and first MVP trophy. He
shut out the Blue Jays for seven innings, striking out six. He hit
two batters, walked three, and never allowed anyone to reach third
base.
</P>
<P>
   You could say he played to the crowd of 20,078. They were quiet
and so was he. This was the mellow side of Pedro. There was not
much tension in the temperature-controlled air. Maybe if the dome's
roof had been left open, the outside chill would have made fans
squirm a bit more. But you often got the feeling you were in an
antiseptic pitching laboratory, observing the work of the famous
scientist, Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox won the game, 8-0, and finished their two-city road
trip with a 6-1 record. Martinez is now 7-1 with a 0.90 earned run
average. He has allowed one run in his last 32 innings. He said he
knew in the bullpen that his fastball wasn't working, so he would
have to rely on his other pitches. That's exactly what he did, and
the Blue Jays still couldn't handle it. Dave Stewart, Toronto's
assistant general manager, anticipated a great Martinez
performance. Stewart, one of the best pitchers of the late 1980s
and early '90s, said that he believes Martinez can finish with an
ERA below 1.12. The last man to do that was Bob Gibson, in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   And (itals)this(unitals) was a bad day?
</P>
<P>
   No one left the park asking for refunds. The only consistent
noise came from a fan sitting on the first-base side. He yelled
insults at Martinez in the first. He softened his criticism in the
third. By the fifth, he was as quiet as the Toronto bats. He
finally resigned himself to watching science like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez looked Raul Mondesi up and down and noticed that the
slugger's body language seemed to say ``I'm having trouble seeing
the ball.'' So he threw Mondesi vexing curveballs and struck him
out. Long before that, Martinez went to the bench and sat next to
his big brother, Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you feel?'' Ramon asked his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good. Actually, I feel fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon didn't completely agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a little slow,'' he said. ``You need to pick up the
tempo.''
</P>
<P>
   So Martinez decided to work quicker. On a ``bad'' day, the
advice was helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things a lot of people might not understand,'' Pedro
Martinez said. ``Those are big reasons I would like to have Ramon
all the time. (Pitching coach) Joe (Kerrigan) never said anything
to me. Ramon picked it up right away. He said, `You have to pick up
the tempo and get a groove going. You might feel great today, but
you're not looking too good. So you have to pick up the tempo, get
a little rhythm going. Get them to swing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Martinez spoke of a flawed release point. There were
glazed looks as he explained his technical breakdowns. Really, a
lot of people with backstage passes for the Martinez Tour couldn't
see what the major problem was. They just wanted to see the small
man with the minute ERA.
</P>
<P>
   There was such a media overflow that Martinez had to hold a
press conference in a football locker room. He is such an
attraction now that he is affecting how you approach your weekly
schedule, isn't he?
</P>
<P>
   You probably know that he next pitches Tuesday. What are you
doing Tuesday? If there is a man or woman you want to impress, you
might want to consider taking them to see Pedro at Fenway. You'll
invite them to see Pedro, they'll see that Pedro is cool and, since
it was your idea, you will be cool, too. Trust me. (I should be a
dating counselor.)
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is pitching on the 28th of this month and will
certainly be featured in some pre-Memorial Day parties. He will
most likely pitch June 8 at Fenway against Einar Diaz and the
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   He is a man people want to see. Even on bad days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to talk about guys who can match `it,' there are
only two guys in the game who can do `it': Randy Johnson and
Pedro,'' Stewart said. ``So if you're asking me if anybody has a
chance, I say yes. Those guys are the only two.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' is Gibson's 1.12. It is a body-of-work accomplishment. It
says, simply, that you were very good every time you took the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the talent for it,'' Stewart said. ``Just look at the
talent. You can take him back to the 1960s and he would be one of
the best. You can put him in the year 2020 and he is going to be
one of the best pitchers there. No doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is that good, even on his worst days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Michael Holley is a Boston Globe sports columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
