 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (a and e coding)  
 BAY STATE YOUTHS, PARENTS FEEL JOY, PAIN OF GAME-SHOW MANIA  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SANDY COLEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For much of the increasingly game-show-mad nation, it
was the kiddie version of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' But
for students at the Sage School in Foxborough, it recently became a
bittersweet lesson in the pain of losing and labeling.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters for Fox-TV's ``Battle of the Child Geniuses: Who Is
the Smartest Kid in America?'' _ which aired last week with 10- to
12-year-olds competing for bragging rights and $300,000 _ came to
the area earlier in the spring on a nationwide search for
contestants.
</P>
<P>
   Academically gifted students at the Sage School got a sharp
taste of what it's like to go brain-to-brain with equally
intellectual peers.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen pupils tried out. Four passed a required written test
with college-level questions given by the show's production staff
members, who came to the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``After taking the test, there were a lot of tears because they
figured out they didn't do as well as they thought they would,''
said Diane Asci, a spokeswoman for the show. ``We reassured them
that this is only a game; it's nothing like a college transcript.
This is just for fun.''
</P>
<P>
   After the four finalists did taped interviews, just one was
chosen to appear on the show: Eric Bair, 12.
</P>
<P>
   Before an audience of 10 million viewers, Bair (who was not
available for comment) lasted 10 minutes before he was eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   No one was forced to try out for the show, school officials and
parents point out. And, they emphasized, the tryout was just for
fun. Still, academically gifted students (they hate the word
``genius'') set extremely high expectations for themselves. When
they fall short, there is hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Sage principal Katherine Windsor said the game-show tryout was
nevertheless a learning experience. ``It allows us to process with
our children what happens when you are disappointed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, in its search for contestants, the Dick Clark-owned
production company that created the show sold it to schools as
simply a search for ``America's brightest'' children. Later on,
however, the show was retitled, ``Battle of the Child Geniuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fox network Web page played up that angle even more,
challenging Web site visitors to take the qualifying test that
``would leave most adults crying for their mommies!''
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Anne Smart said she might not have wanted her son,
Michael, to compete for a spot on the show had she known the word
``genius'' would be in the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like that label,'' she said. ``We want him to feel as
much like a normal child as anyone else . . . That label means a
person who knows the answers to all the questions all the time and
that you'll always do well. That's not something you want to put on
a 10-year-old child.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he was one of the four finalists, Michael seems to have
kept the experience in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't nervous. I knew it didn't have to do with school or
anything,'' he said. The qualifying test ``was a fun test because I
knew it wasn't going to matter.''
</P>
<P>
   And Michael made the decision to try out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we went into it as a family was it will be a great
experience and what happens, happens. We didn't put a lot of weight
to it,'' Anne Smart said.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Stearns's son took the test but didn't make the final cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test was really, really hard. I didn't think it would be
that hard,'' said 11-year-old Brian Stearns, who said he was
disappointed but would try out for the show again if producers
return.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Rosenstein, executive director for the National
Association For Gifted Children, said there's nothing wrong with a
little competition, since the world revolves around it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the child lost at baseball or football would anyone be
upset? Academic competitions aren't all that different,'' he said.
``Kids win and kids lose. Parents have to understand what they are
getting into.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``what you don't want to do is exploit children,''
Rosenstein said. ``You don't want to use bright kids to do a TV
show if a child can't get something from it _ win or lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Debra Alioto is glad her son, 11-year-old Matt, made the list of
potential contestants. She said she would have cheered him on if he
made it _ but after hearing about the show, she is equally happy he
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buildup to it, the commercial and the music that was used,
it was daunting. To me they were emphasizing the wrong thing and
putting all this pressure on the kids watching and the kids in
it,'' said Alioto, who said she tries to teach her son the
difference between being a smart person and a wise one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a society of who's the best? Who's the brightest? . . .
What does that say about everybody else?'' she said. ``I'd rather
he be happy and kind than the smartest person in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
