<HEADLINE>
HUGH HEFNER UNLIKELY TO MAKE A NAME FOR HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ A van pulled up to the Pimilco stakes barn Wednesday
morning bearing a thoroughbred named Hugh Hefner, who had been
shipped from California to race in Saturday's Preakness. The
question is: Why?
</P>
<P>
   It might be harsh to call Hugh Hefner a lowly ``Cal-bred'' _ but
not by much. He has won two races, both restricted to horses bred
in his home state, has a career record of 6-2-2-0, and a mere _ for
this level _ $167,055 in earnings. He appears to have a bit of
talent, but why the Preakness?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make some money,'' said trainer Marty Jones.
``We think he can run good, and Eddie owns the stallion and the
mare. It would be a real big score if his horse jumps up and wins
the race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie,'' is Ed Nahem, who owns Hugh Hefner as well as his
sire, Bertrando, handicap champion in 1993, and his dam, Personal
Victory. Nahem exited the van resplendent in a black-and-white
print shirt and Panama hat. His attire befits a man who made his
money as an art and antiques dealer, lives in Hollywood, and calls
his stable, modestly, King Edward Racing Stable. And, yes, he is a
friend of Playboy magazine founder Hugh Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   But racing isn't a beauty contest, and being surrounded by
glamour isn't going to do Hugh Hefner, the horse, any good when the
gates open for the Preakness and real stars, such as Kentucky Derby
winner Fusaichi Pegasus, take over the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had put the Preakness in our long-term plan,'' said Jones.
``We thought he'd win the Snow Chief (a stakes race for California
breds at Hollywood Park April 30), but he finished second. After
that we hemmed and hawed, but we thought he'd run a big race,
anyway, and we'd give him a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   After Hugh Hefner captured the Cal Sire Stakes at Santa Anita in
October, Nahem and Jones, who is the son of retired trainer Gary
Jones, decided to enter him in the $1 million Breeders' Cup
Juvenile at Gulfstream Park. The move turned into a disaster, as
Hugh Hefner finished 13th in a 14-horse field at 50-1. The only
thing about the appearance that caused a stir was when Hugh Hefner,
the human, showed up. Don't expect him at the Preakness, however;
there's not enough glitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse has come a long way in the last couple of months,''
said Jones, who trains approximately 20 horses, many of them owned
by Nahem. ``He's a lot better than he was in Florida. He's matured,
and the blinkers (which were added after the Breeders' Cup) have
helped him move forward. We didn't get a chance to see the real him
in Florida. Whether he can make a difference in the Preakness, I
don't know. But the owner was very involved in the decision to come
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning the Preakness is a difficult goal in any year, but this
year there is real bear in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fusaichi Pegasus is a super horse,'' said Jones. ``If he goes
out there and runs his race, we're all running for second money.
But he's a horse, and the favorite doesn't always win.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is easy to criticize Hugh Hefner, he does have good
early speed and will be a pace factor over the mile and
three-16ths. The problem is Preakness entrants Hal's Hope and High
Yield have as much, if not more, speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a speed horse,'' said Jones, who has given Victor
Espinoza the mount. ``There is a lot of speed in this race, but we
won't take him out of his style. He'll be on the pace. The break is
always important to our horse. He has to break cleanly to have a
chance. Hopefully, he'll get out good, and get a good position. I
hope they don't go that fast (the Derby horses, led by Hal's Hope,
blazed 6 furlongs in 1:09 4/5). I hope the jockeys can slow it down
a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're asking for a lot here. It's a very tough
race. He's going to have to improve significantly just to be
competitive. But, hey, anything can happen. He's a nice horse, he's
doing well, and we want to give him a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
