<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAUR-REVISIONISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVEALING DINOSAURS' SOFTER SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steven Spielberg should consider remaking ``Jurassic
Park.'' It turns out the velociraptor _ the nasty little dinosaur
with the sharp teeth, hook claws, and taloned feet _ had feathers.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence sits just a few blocks from Spielberg's Central
Park West apartment, at the American Museum of Natural History in a
display of dinosaur bones from the Gobi Desert of Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
   Other images have also been dispelled.
</P>
<P>
   The oviraptor _ once thought to have snatched other dinosaurs'
eggs (its name means ``egg thief'') _ now turns out to have sat in
a nest, hatched eggs, and protected them from predators. Other
species of dinosaurs may have nurtured their children.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the show _ with all its wishbones, head-crests,
peculiar nasal passages, and especially those nests and feathers _
strengthens the growing notion that many kinds of dinosaurs did not
become extinct but evolved into birds.
</P>
<P>
   Why they had feathers is unclear; they couldn't fly. Mark Norell
and Michael Novacek, the museum's chief paleontologists and
co-leaders of the Gobi dig, say the feathers might have been
insulation. Novocek speculates ``they might have been for some
sexual ritual.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this suggests that dinosaurs were gentle. ``They're
mean,'' Novacek emphasized. ``They're just also fairly elegant.''
</P>
<P>
   These scientists speak more confidently than anyone could have a
few years ago, because the Gobi _ a 500,000-square-mile stretch of
barren sand and mountains that they have been exploring for 11
years now _ turns out to be the world's greatest treasure-trove of
fossils from the Cretaceous Era, the late phase of dinosaur rule 80
million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On display until Oct. 29, when they go back to Mongolia, are the
fossils of whole skeletons: grown dinosaurs, baby dinosaurs, even
dinosaur embryos _ all as discovered, most of them intact. ``We're
trained to look for chunks of fragments, pieces of a jaw or a tail,
and to be very content with that,'' Novacek said. ``Complete
skeletons _ you just don't find that.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't mere bragging. Charles Scheff, curatorial associate
at Harvard University's Museum of Comparative Zoology, who has seen
the Gobi collection, Wednesday called it ``an unparalleled
excavation'' that ``throws a whole different light'' on dinosaur
anatomy and behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The bones are in such pristine condition because they have been
under deep sand dunes, beneath the reach of scavengers. Apparently,
they were buried alive in a avalanche brought on by heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   They are being found now because only in the past 10 years has
Mongolia, situated between Russia and China, reopened its borders.
In the 1920s, the Gobi hosted great dinosaur digs by Roy Chapman
Andrews of the Museum of Natural History. Then Stalin forced the
expulsion of foreigners. Although nominally independent, Mongolia
was closely aligned with the Soviet Union; when the Soviet Union
collapsed in 1991 and democratic reforms spread, the new Mongolian
government invited the museum back in.
</P>
<P>
   The show's centerpiece is the ``fighting dinosaurs,'' possibly
the most famous fossils ever, unearthed by Polish and Mongolian
scientists in 1971 but never before seen in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the complete skeletons of a velociraptor and a
protoceratops, locked in combat. The velociraptor is jabbing its
foot into the neck of the protoceratops, which is biting the
velociraptor's arm.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has also built dioramas of how various dinosaurs may
have appeared. They look like birds _ strange birds, but birds.
</P>
<P>
   The show appears at a fertile time for dinosaur fans. Chicago's
Field Museum Wednesday unveiled ``Sue,'' the largest Tyrannosaurus
rex ever assembled, from bones found in South Dakota. This week,
Walt Disney releases its computer-animated film, ``Dinosaur.''
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials here say the timing is happenstance. The
exhibit was planned months ago, as part of a Mongolia Festival
organized by that country's UN mission.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is tempting to view the show's revisionism as part of
broader trends. In the 1920s, when Andrews unearthed some of these
species, a brute form of Darwinism prevailed and dinosaurs were
considered pea-brained monsters who beat the daylights out of one
another until their own stupidity rendered them extinct. So, when
Andrews saw the fossil of a dinosaur clutching some eggs, he took
it for a thief and called it ``oviraptor.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a more relativistic age, when we shirk from judging
primitive cultures on our own terms, and when dinosaurs are seen as
victims of a meteor, is it mere coincidence that the oviraptor
emerges as a caring mom?
</P>
<P>
   Norell insists it's pure science. Modern methods reveal that the
embryos inside the eggs are of the same species as the dinosaur on
top, and new fossils show the dinosaur clutching the eggs in a
manner clearly protective, not aggressive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
