<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-INSIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE.COM HOPES MEDIA TYPES WILL DIG IN FOR DATA, DIRT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past six months, the media world has been abuzz about
Inside.com, an online entertainment news service. Members of the
media, after all, can't resist a good story about, well, members of
the media. And Inside's cofounder Kurt Andersen has certainly
raised interest and eyebrows with his knack for the controversial
quip: He's been going around calling the competition ``a skeptical
dinosaur'' and claiming in print that raising money for the venture
was ``as easy as getting laid in 1969.''
</P>
<P>
   But after all the verbal fisticuffs and foreplay, most folks
were caught off guard when a ``sneak preview'' of the site appeared
quietly last week with little fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   So what's inside Inside.com? In its first few days, the site
broke the story about salary negotiations with the cast of
``Friends'' (which is of life-or-death importance to six actors,
their network, and their fans) and published a report on a power
shakeup at the Washington Monthly, no doubt of interest to a small
circle of true insiders. The site also offered an astrological
forecast for Napster cofounder Shawn Fanning (a Sagittarius, for
those who care) and let users vote on who has more power, Steven
Case or Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those features _ the silly and the serious _ are still
displayed prominently on the site, which is so laden with headlines
and charts that it's hard to tell what is old news and what has
been recently updated. The design is a murky sea of black and gray
reminiscent of those ``dinosaurs'' called newspapers; the home page
is as busy as a lottery outlet on the eve of a mega-jackpot
drawing.
</P>
<P>
   And the entire venture is something of a gamble. The burning
question here is: Will anyone be willing to pay for this mix of
news, gossip, data, and horoscopes?
</P>
<P>
   Its high-profile editors Andersen (cofounder of Spy and former
editor of New York) and Michael Hirschorn (former editor of Spin)
are betting that people in the entertainment industry will pay $199
a year (or $19.95 a month) for access to the site. Yet the common
wisdom is that nobody pays for content on the Internet, unless it's
pornography or The Wall Street Journal, respectively, of course.
The online magazine Slate scrapped its subscription attempt after a
year, and it is still losing fistfuls of money. Likewise, online
publications like TheStreet.com and and Salon.com haven't exactly
made a killing after lackluster initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   So why should Inside.com succeed where others have failed? In a
word: data.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the dish and the dirt, Inside aims to crunch numbers
that are of particular interest in the entertainment business. ``We
want to go way off the deep end with the depth of our data, so that
you could roll around in the stuff for hours,'' says Hirschorn.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, users can roll around in yesterday's Nielsen ratings,
last weekend's box office grosses, and last week's Internet traffic
figures from Media Metrix. The site also publishes actual sales
figures from Barnes and Noble, which were featured on the site this
week, along with a news item about the book chain's latest Internet
strategy. So far, most of this data is available in other places,
but Hirschorn says that Inside is building gigantic databases and
that the site will eventually offer more extensive data.
</P>
<P>
   But is that enough to make industry insiders subscribe?
Certainly, thousands of media types hustled to sign up for the
30-day free trial, even though technical problems made it necessary
to fill out the registration form several times. Slate editor
Michael Kinsley was one of the first media people to check out the
site, and for now, he's giving it the benefit of the doubt. ``I
wouldn't say it's a sure thing, but they could succeed where we
failed,'' he says, pausing. ``On the other hand, Warren Buffet's
famous line when someone said that they had learned from their
mistakes was that the idea is to learn from other people's
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But still, the founders didn't have any trouble raising $28
million in venture capital (and if Andersen is to be believed, they
had a darn good time getting it). They also attracted a staff of
seasoned reporters from top print publications; natch, they all
have stock options in the parent company, Powerful Media Inc. The
staff has broken a few stories and turned out straightforward
stories, but so far, the site lacks the edge and the attitude one
might expect from the cofounder of Spy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoops are terrific, but paying your investors from scoops
could be a formidable challenge,'' says Steven Gaydos, executive
editor of Variety, Inside's chief competitor. ``I remember the old
Jimmy Durante line, `Everybody wants to get in the act.' God love
'em. That line was quoted in Variety in about 1932.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, media types wanted at least a look at the act. When the
site appeared a week ago without any advance notice, it was
instantly bogged down with traffic _ and technical glitches. Since
then, features like the Inside Dope and the Daily Digest have been
updated, but many of the stories on the home page haven't changed
since Day One.
</P>
<P>
   And the failure to update the site could be a make-or-break
factor in the subscription model. ``Most news sites start out very
different from each other in the morning, but by the afternoon,
they are all the same,'' says Richard Tofel, vice president of
corporate communications for Dow Jones &AMP; Co., which publishes the
Wall Street Journal. ``That's not a great recipe for convincing
people to pay.'' WSJ.com has 438,000 subscribers who pay $29 to $49
a year for access to the site, which is updated round the clock
with reports from the Dow Jones news service.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal has a captive audience of business readers, many of
whom are able to expense their subscriptions. You could argue that
Inside.com has a similar audience: Media moguls have an
unquenchable thirst for news and gossip about their own. Just
witness the pre-launch hype for Inside.com. ``It was
embarrassing,'' admits Hirschorn.
</P>
<P>
   Whether insiders will pony up for the Inside dirt is anyone's
guess, but people are paying attention. James Ledbetter, New York
bureau chief of The Industry Standard, put it this way: ``Even if
they fail, it's going to be fun to watch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
