<HEADLINE>
HANGING WALLPAPER IS AN ART, NOT A SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best thing about hanging wllpaper is that it is instant.
</P>
<P>
   Once up, it is there for all to see and enjoy; there is nothing
you have to touch up, paint, stain, varnish, or do.
</P>
<P>
   It is the be-all and end-all of decorating, and really can be
kind of fun. It is not science. But don't let anyone tell you it is
not an art.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you'll have to do a few things before getting to the
fun part. For instance: remove the old paper, wash off all the old
paste, and prepare the wall. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shop alone &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first fun part of the project is picking out the paper. This
is best done alone. Picking a pattern and color by committee or
with a spouse is not worth the aggravation.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of papers _ and coverings _ is huge. Most
manufacturers are calling their product wallcoverings, because many
are not paper at all.
</P>
<P>
   There are patterns and colors for every taste and every foible.
Designs are whimsical, funny, colorful, elegant but never serious,
sober but never dour, cartoony, thematic. You name it, there is a
covering out there to fill the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the borders, in just as great a variety as the
coverings themselves. Not to mention matching fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Wall coverings are expensive, so it's a good idea to do one
room, not trying to redo the entire house in one fell swoop.
</P>
<P>
   How much to buy: Determine the area of the wall to be covered
and divide by 32, which is the number of square feet in a single
roll. For instance, suppose a wall is 8 feet high by 10 feet long,
multiply 8 by 10 to get 80 square feet. If there are four such
walls in your room, multiply the 80 by 4 to get 320. Divide by 32
to get the 10 rolls that you need. Add two rolls for waste and good
measure. When measuring, ignore windows and doors in the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Coverings are sold in double and triple rolls, but don't worry
about buying too much; it is better to buy too much than too
little, because you can return unused rolls. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The tough part: stripping &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now for the tough part: removing the old paper. If the old paper
is sticking properly, you may not have to remove it. You can
usually apply one layer over one layer; there is no rule of thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Some papers are strippable; that is, you can grab a corner and
pull it off dry. Wall-Tex coverings and other non-paper coverings
can come off this way.
</P>
<P>
   But many papers need to be stripped by steaming or wetting. You
can rent a steamer that will make short, neat work of removal. Or,
use hot water with a stripping additive. Put down tarps to protect
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, here's the rub: Most modern coverings are vinyl-coated and
impervious to water or steam. So they must be scored, to allow the
steam or water to penetrate to the paste. One way to score paper is
to scrape the wall with a hand saw, making many marks, one for
tooth in the saw. Stores sell scoring tools.
</P>
<P>
   If the wallpaper is painted, you also have to score the paint
film to allow the steam or water to penetrate. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pray for plaster &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before starting, hope that the wall under the old paper is
old-fashioned plaster, or a plaster skimcoat. Coverings will come
off easily from these finishes. But it is almost impossible to take
the paper off plasterboard or drywall if it has not been painted,
without creating many gouges and torn drywall paper. If that
happens, the only thing to do is fill them with joint compound and
sand smooth. Then paint the walls, to avoid future disasters.
</P>
<P>
   There are many tools out there for stripping paper. Usually a
wide putty knife will suffice, but in stubborn cases, and where you
need more precision, a razor-blade scraper will work best.
</P>
<P>
   After removing the paper, wash walls to remove excess paste. If
the paste is vinyl, it will be hard to remove, so you must make a
detergent solution and wash vigorously. Scraping the softened paste
with a wide putty knife hastens removal.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can get to the fun part. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A battery of tools &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You need a battery of tools: tape rule, scissors, utility knife
with spare blades, long straight edge, long spirit level, pasting
table, marking pencil, and a smoothing brush. If you are using a
paste, you need a paste bucket and a pasting brush.
</P>
<P>
   What about pre-pasted coverings? In the early days of pre-pasted
papers, they were not very reliable, and old-time paper hangers
used paste anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But the papers have come a long way in 40 years, and pre-pasted
papers are quite reliable, needing only wetting to activate the
paste. A wetting tray usually accompanies pre-pasted paper, or you
can buy your own.
</P>
<P>
   Now you're ready.
</P>
<P>
   But first, be sure to size the walls with a glue size. It's a
glue, applied to the walls to make the new paper more easily
adjusted, make it stick better, and make it easier to remove.
</P>
<P>
   Always hang paper vertically. In houses, ceilings and floors are
seldom level, so do not line up the paper with either, nor with a
corner, which is unlikely to be plumb (vertical). Intead, line it
up vertically to itself. To do this properly, the first strip must
be vertical. Then, all others will be.
</P>
<P>
   Start hanging paper in a corner, one behind a door, because when
you go around the room and come to that corner with the paper, it
won't match. But it won't show.
</P>
<P>
   To hang the paper vertically, measure the width of the strip;
say it is 24 inches wide. Measure 23 1/2 inches from a corner and
make a mark on the wall at ceiling level. Make a vertical mark from
that mark to the floor. Use a spirit level to make sure the mark is
true.
</P>
<P>
   This technique allows the paper to turn the corner by half an
inch; any more and you will get wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   Cut strips of paper a few inches longer than the height of the
wall. Wet the prepasted strip according to instructions. If the
paper is not prepasted, use the paste recommended by the maker.
</P>
<P>
   Lay the strip face-down on the pasting table, and paste the
bottom half or two-thirds. Then fold the bottom half over on
itself, and bring the top half or so onto the table for final
pasting.
</P>
<P>
   Any flat surface will make a good pasting table.
</P>
<P>
   When you hang the paper, apply the top securely, smoothing off
in the right position, then unfold the bottom and apply that. Trim
top and bottom with a utility knife. When the knife tears the paper
instead of cutting it, change blades.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth off the paper with the wide smoothing brush, working out
bubbles. If the bubbles persist, pull up the paper where necessary,
but not the entire strip, and start smoothing all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Wipe the strip with a wet sponge to remove any paste that got on
the face of the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Keep hanging strips, and be sure to line up the pattern. Hang
strips until you come to a window. Then, apply a strip, letting it
overlap the window frame, and cut it roughly around the window,
leaving plenty of fudge paper. Then you can tuck the paper against
the window casing, and cut it to fit. Do the same along the top and
bottom of the frame.
</P>
<P>
   Do the opposite as you approach the other side of the window. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Turning the corner &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you come to a corner, you will discover a narrow space,
narrower than the width of the strip. So, cut the strip vertically
as wide as the space plus half an inch. Hang the strip. Save the
piece you cut off; it will match the part that turned the corner.
Make sure that this strip is vertical; check it with the spirit
level.
</P>
<P>
   Ah yes, there is always one more thing. Paper manufacturers also
make borders, for use as cornices and crown molding at the top of
the walls, and sometimes as a chair rail.
</P>
<P>
   Use 'em or not.
</P>
<P>
   When you finish with the last piece, there is nothing else to do
but clean up and enjoy your magnificent job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
