<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8814 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      05-18 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRYSLER'S PT CRUISER LOOKS LIKE A HOT ROD, BUT ISN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a startled bellow that emanated from deep in the
recycling shed at my local landfill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, will ya look at that!'' cried Alice, major domo of
all we recycle or discard in my little town.
</P>
<P>
   I have driven Jaguars and Porsches and Mercedes Benzes to the
landfill, cars that approached six figures in cost. Alice never
looked up. That was until I rolled in with the Chrysler PT Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Alice was not alone in her attraction to the hot little car
because there is no defined demographic slice drawn to the Cruiser.
It draws admirers the way a magnet draws iron filings, pulls them
across generations, from spirited automotive enthusiasts and those
who rarely glance at cars except as things of utility.
</P>
<P>
   It's a retro rig, reminiscent of the 1930s and '40s _ ``An Al
Capone car,'' Alice called it, though I look at it and see 1930s
Chrysler Airflow: upright windshield, high roof, high doors,
bulging fenders. The PT Cruiser _ minivan, truck, car depending on
your own point of view _ is a rounded departure from a trend,
breaking away from the boxy minivans that have become so uncool the
way the Airflow streamed away from the rectangular cars that were
so prevalent before its appearance.
</P>
<P>
   If the New Beetle was, well, the new Beetle, then the PT Cruiser
is the new minivan.
</P>
<P>
   It's got a minivan feel when you sit inside. High seats (and a
remarkable driver's seat that goes straight up and down for better
view), a nose that slopes away so you feel you are looking down at
the road, and a cavernous feel inside a cabin that is as
utilitarian as you will find. Chrysler claims it has 26
configurations and I couldn't find them all, but know this: The
rear seats split 65/35; you can fold them down; you can take them
out; the rear window ledge drops when the seats are folded down to
form a flat cargo area; the front passenger seat folds down and you
can carry 8-foot two-by-fours, a ladder, or skis in the space.
</P>
<P>
   It's got storage bins where most cars don't even have places.
Pockets and nets and sliding drawers throughout. It's almost as if,
inside, you are sitting in an appliance rather than an automobile.
</P>
<P>
   All this, while maintaining a retro feel with oval inserts in
the dash that match the exterior color, a tall, white-knobbed stick
shift in the standard, black-on-white gauges, and sturdy pillars
rising to a high ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Most switches are at center dash, even the switches for the
front windows (odd, I thought). Switches for the rear windows are
on the back of the center console (odder, I thought, and
inconvenient for the driver who has to reach back for them).
</P>
<P>
   There is ample leg- and headroom and the rear seat is a
veritable couch. The front buckets could use a bit more length
under the thigh, but they were firm and well sculpted and held well
on the sides in corners. Not, of course, that you'll be rolling
your PT Cruiser at high speeds on twisting roads. It's not made for
that. It's a cruiser with a small ``c'' in the performance sense.
</P>
<P>
   It's got a 2.4-liter, DOHC, four-cylinder engine that used about
21 miles per gallon in 10 days of testing. It's no rocket off the
line, and though it looks like a hot rod, it's not. What it is is a
front-wheel-drive transporter that felt remarkably like Volkwagen's
New Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   As tall as it sits, it cornered quite well, with limited sense
of body roll. Fully loaded (two adults, three children), its engine
was not challenged on steep hills and it held its own in speedy
commuter traffic.
</P>
<P>
   There are rumbles that Chrysler will be offering a turbocharged
version of the Cruiser and that added touch could make this a
superb little car. As it is, I can just picture the aftermarket
aficionados lined up to take a crack at the fine base Chrysler has
provided.
</P>
<P>
   Suspension in the PT Cruiser is independent up front with
struts, coil springs, and antiroll bar. The rear (avoiding struts
that would intrude on interior cargo space) has a rigid axle with
trailing arms, antiroll bar, and coil springs.
</P>
<P>
   At a base price of somewhere under $16,000, it is a fine
purchase, though I'd certainly fork out the extra dough for ABS and
traction control. There is also word that some dealers (will they
never learn?) are gouging on the price despite warnings from
headquarters that they shouldn't be. If you run into gouging, let
me know.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler plans to sell 150,000 PT Cruisers in the first model
year, and should have no problem doing so. Before the first one
ever hit a showroom they had nearly 400,000 inquiries from
prospective buyers.
</P>
<P>
   What Chrysler is selling here is not a feat of engineering. It's
Neon-based but better than the Neon, though certainly not as hot a
car as it looks. Its performance is just OK, and I cannot imagine
it with the automatic transmission. The long-throw, five-speed
standard is just the tranny for this rig and I suspect an automatic
would plod when coupled with this engine and the ton-and-a-half the
Cruiser weighs.
</P>
<P>
   No, what is being offered is an image, a feel, a sense of the
past with a great whiff of today's technology and dependability
tossed in.
</P>
<P>
   It may look hot, but this is about coolly cruising the open
road, windows down, radio blasting, a highway happening that
crosses generations. It is about rolling into a burger joint on a
hot summer evening, sticking a surfboard over folded-down seats and
heading for the beach, or cruising dark stretches of road until you
find that all-night diner.
</P>
<P>
   It's about a rig that can haul all you need for your college
dorm room, transporting kids and groceries in a
soccer-field-to-supermarket shuttle on a Saturday morning, about
nostalgia that won't break down.
</P>
<P>
   Does it work? Go ask Alice.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches
</P>
<P>
   --The yoke-like door handles, front and rear, that you can grab
with a whole hand. No looking for just the right cranny in which to
slip two fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances
</P>
<P>
   --Nice armrest folds down for the driver. Why no armrest for the
front-seat passenger?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
