<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-90210-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A FOND FAREWELL FOR CHILDHOOD AND `90210' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRISTI L. GUSTAFSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For 10 seasons, they've looked good, bed-hopped
and driven expensive foreign cars. They've dated, graduated, been
hired and fired, survived shootings, diseases and family strife.
</P>
<P>
   They're the gang on ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' and I've spent
nearly half of my 22 years watching them. But that all ended when
``90210'' made its long goodbye Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The series became a ritual for me from the first episode. I sat
on the edge of my best friend's waterbed _ right there in Averill
Park, N.Y. 12018 _ in anticipation of what she predicted would be a
``hunk-filled'' show after seeing the first advertisement. Because
of its title, I thought it was a police sitcom (where's Eddie
Murphy?), but humored her and watched the show's premiere.
</P>
<P>
   This was anything but an hour of boys in blue. Instead, these
kids were everything my 12-year-old self wished I could be when I
grew up. They were, in a word, glamorous.
</P>
<P>
   My friend and I were perfectly situated in the show's
demographic. The characters, four years older than we were, made
the challenges and traumas of our still-distant high school years
seem as enjoyable as a cruise down Rodeo Drive in Mondale, the
classic Mustang owned by Brandon (Jason Priestley).
</P>
<P>
   As the years passed, their friendships remained intact despite
lying, cheating, betrayal and worse. They dealt with issues I never
had to face in my rural high school: racism, condom distribution,
violence, where to get the BMW fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Who could forget Brenda Walsh (Shannen Doherty)? The at-times
resident villain who left ``90210'' after the fourth season is
still committing evil: She failed to return for a guest appearance.
She was replaced by Valerie (Tiffani-Amber Thiessen) and shortly
after, Gina (Vanessa Marcil), but neither stirred things up and
created as much controversy as Brandon's twin.
</P>
<P>
   ``90210'' has had many brag-worthy special appearances. Hilary
Swank appeared in one story arc, long before she forgot to thank
her husband after winning the Oscar. The long list of guest stars
included Burt Reynolds, Matthew Perry, Barry Bonds, Dom DeLuise and
Vivica Fox, while musical performers such as the Rolling Stones,
Christina Aguilera, the Goo Goo Dolls and, yes, Debbie Gibson also
appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday nights became sacred. I would take the phone off the
hook _ not that my friends would dare call _ and when I got a
part-time job I made sure the schedule never interfered with my
midweek view into the lives of the West Beverly High students. I
couldn't risk taping the show, unless I watched it before school.
Everyone, from my peers to the teachers, would be talking about
what they had seen the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Before I go any further, I'd like to make a few things clear: I
know the acting on ``90210'' wasn't top-notch. OK, at times it was
flat-out bad. I figured out early on that these characters' lives
were more unrealistic than Michael Jackson's.
</P>
<P>
   But I still became a loyal fan and follower from that first
season, the days when Brandon and Dylan's (Luke Perry) sideburns
were as coveted as a chance in the hot seat on ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   What was it that kept us glued to the set for all these years,
following the lives of a bunch of rich and often stuck-up kids
living in an endless summer without bad hair days, acne or peer
pressure? You could say it was a show about hair. And you could be
right.
</P>
<P>
   But there was more. Maybe it was wish-fulfillment: the sun and
the warmth, the beautiful bodies and faces, the fashion, the nice
cars and prosperous parents, the comfort and cool of the Peach Pit
After Dark _ the club that's somehow able to snag top performers
like Collective Soul and the Barenaked Ladies. For an hour each
week, it could all happen.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't quite paradise. There were two cancer scares, several
rapes, drug and alcohol abuse, among many other things. Still,
these traumas were usually solved within an episode or two, and few
things _ no matter how tragic _ were mentioned again (unless it was
an anthology episode).
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the one problem the gang can't get around:
growing up. Finally, the tan, buff California kids are facing the
real world. They're almost all paired off, responsible or
career-minded (Dylan excepted). Boooooorring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beverly Hills 90210'' has come to its end. Its heroes and
heroines have reached a point in their lives where there are very
few fresh shocks left. After near-death experiences, pregnancies
and miscarriages, car crashes, AIDS scares, infidelity and enough
one-night stands to fill 10 sleazy motels, there's nothing left but
the rigors of early middle age. Do we really want to see these
characters start to go bald?
</P>
<P>
   We already have. We don't want to go there.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I watched, needing answers, closure. I wanted to feel as
if I'd have a chance to bid a proper farewell to my former role
models. But my VCR might get hold of the final episode before I do.
</P>
<P>
   After all, I'm not in high school anymore. I've graduated from
college, too _ where the campus didn't begin to buzz until after 9
p.m. on Wednesdays. I do not want to be these people when I grow
up.
</P>
<P>
   I am grown up, and it's time to say goodbye to my childhood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
