   WORLD-BRIEFS (Various datelines) _ Short news items from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _  &UR; General &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' news category)
</P>
<P>
   NH-DEATH-PENALTY (Concord, N.J.) _ The New Hampshire Senate on
Thursday is expected to pass legislation, already approved by the
House, to abolish the death penalty. While the governor is expected
to veto the measure, and nobody is on death row in the state, the
move is part of a growing national reconsideration of the fairness
of capital punishment. No state has abolished the death penalty
since the Supreme Court permitted its reinstatement in 1976. By
John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-TYCOONS-INTERNET (Hong Kong) _ From Taiwan to Thailand,
some of Asia's most powerful families have started a blizzard of
online ventures. Whether their core businesses are in property,
telecommunications or banking, Asia's tycoons are seizing on the
Internet in hopes of expanding their reach and making even more
money. At the same time, however, the Internet is transforming the
way business is done in East Asia. With its emphasis on speed,
openness, and collaboration, the Internet is challenging
traditional Asian values of prudence, financial opacity, and family
control. Decisions, which used to be made by the patriarch behind a
veil of secrecy, are being pushed down the ranks as Asian companies
embrace Silicon Valley-style management. So despite their
chameleon-like adaptability, Asia's tycoons may have trouble making
the leap into cyberspace, critics say. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-TECH-TALENT (Manila) _ The Philippines may be the
place that gave birth to the ``I love you'' virus that shut down
hundreds of thousands of computers around the world. But it is also
where one of the first patches to prevent the virus was developed.
Indeed, the whole episode has swung spotlight on the country's
swelling pool of high-tech talent. European and American employers
are increasingly seeking out computer savvy Filipinos. And there is
now a surprisingly lively Internet start-up scene in a country
where the average annual income is a little more than $1,000 and
where fewer than 1 percent use the Internet. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT-WORLDCOM (Washington) _ Following developments in the
Justice Department's review of Worldcom's proposed $115 billion
acquisition of Sprint. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   3M-SCOTCHGARD (Chicago) _ Followup on 3M's announcement that it
will stop making and selling most Scotchgard products because of
research that shows that a chemical ingredient lingers for years in
the environment and the human body. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   BOO-BANKRUPT (London) _ The decline and fall of Boo.com, an
online fashion sportswear retailer that opened for business just
six months ago. The collapse of Boo.com, the first major failure of
a European Web retailer, came after the company failed to secure a
further $30 million from its investors, which included J.P. Morgan,
Benetton and Bernard Arnault. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EUROPE (Undated) _ European Union antitrust investigators
raid Coca-Cola Enterprises in London and at its Belgian unit as
part of an investigation into possible abuses of dominant position
in its distribution practices. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   GUGGENHEIM-1900 (New York) _ The Guggenheim's ``1900: Art at the
Crossroads'' is a wacky exercise in historical simulation, the
excuse being a new century. It is hard to remember the last time so
many bad pictures were in one place at one time, unless you
consider eBay a place. But the show no doubt will be as popular in
New York as it was in London. There is no underestimating the
public's taste for kitsch. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE-IMMERSION (Undated) _ Five years ago, at a stationery
store on the Left Bank, I picked up a copy of Paris Match, fished
in my pants pocket for some francs and walked toward the counter, a
smile of fear frozen on my face. As my brain locked, I croaked out
this sentence to the old woman at the counter: ``Je voudrais
acheter le magasin, s'il vous plait.'' The common word for magazine
is magazine (mah-gah-ZEEN), not magasin (mah-gah-ZAA). I had asked
to buy the shop. And so it went. For 10 days in Paris I was a
helpless prisoner of my past: four years of undistinguished high
school French and one semester at college. I could make my way
through a French newspaper, but conversation was out of the
question. Until now. No longer the 98-pound-weakling of
bilingualism, I have persuaded myself that it is possible to
function confidently, perhaps even thrive, in another culture. I am
a graduate of language immersion. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
