<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING, AT LAST, HOW TO LET LOVE IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My brother made plans to spend some time with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take the dogs for a walk on the beach and get a chance
to talk without other people around,'' Ken said. Since he did this
without any prompting from me, I was flattered in an uneasy sort of
way. In the past, we've been so busy judging each other that we've
tended to avoid one-on-one conversations, but we're moving into a
new stage of our relationship now, and even I could see this was an
important step.
</P>
<P>
   Ken showed up on a Saturday afternoon, and as we stood in my
driveway, my neighbor David came out of his house with his dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to walk the dogs. Want to come?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda,'' my brother whispered from behind me, ``what are you
doing? I wanted us to be together without anyone else there.''
</P>
<P>
   I apologized. I was able to cancel the invitation, but not to
keep from hurting Ken's feelings. I couldn't believe my own
perversity.
</P>
<P>
   I'd shrug my impulse off as a simple act of friendliness if I
didn't know that my mind has this habit of trying to avoid
responsibility. In some recess of my psyche, I had to know what I
was doing, which was pushing Ken away and dampening his enthusiasm
for a more intimate relationship. I'd dashed cold water on his
overture, but why?
</P>
<P>
   Some part of it is habit, I think. We get used to the particular
distance we maintain from others and resigned to the grip of the
familiar. The relationship may not be as pleasurable, alive, or
satisfying as it might be, but it's predictable in its frustration
or aggravation or sadness. There's a certain comfort in the
thought: Nothing will ever change . . . and so I don't have to
change either. This eliminates the chance of bumping up against
some new shortcoming, having to reexamine past judgments, or,
worse, having to admit you've been unfair in the past.
</P>
<P>
   I also felt a certain indignation: Who did my brother think he
was, changing rules in midstream? I felt a certain unease: What was
he looking for? I felt a certain fear: What if he were
disappointed? As the story unfolded, I've come across two other
questions that took me by surprise. Could I respond? Am I capable
of loving Ken back?
</P>
<P>
   This is what happened next. My brother attended our family
Passover Seder two weeks later. A few of us were in the kitchen
cleaning up, and Ken said to my husband, ``I love my sister.'' I
stopped and turned, dishcloth in hand. ``I love your sister, too,''
my husband said. Immediately my heart began pounding and my mouth
went dry. It would have been no big deal if they'd said they
appreciated my cooking or had thanked me for directing our Passover
play, but this wasn't gratitude, an emotion I'm comfortable with.
They were saying they loved me.
</P>
<P>
   I took a deep breath. I deliberately tried to allow all that
love in. After all these years of being a wife and mother, you'd
think I'd be an old hand at this, but being the target of approval
and affection makes me uncomfortable. Intellectually I was pleased.
I knew in my head that Jack and Ken meant what they'd said, but
emotionally I hit a wall I seem to have built to keep love out. I
think I'm good at giving love, at saying the words and performing
the acts that demonstrate the depth of my caring, but when I'm the
object of love, there's a flatness where joy ought to live, a
``does not compute'' sign right where I ought to be turning
cartwheels.
</P>
<P>
   I dismiss the love others so generously give me. As soon as it
gets inside, I negate it.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable, I suppose. I was told I was loved as a
child, but what I felt was anxious and unprotected and unsafe. I
never responded with a flood of soothing emotion, or a feeling of
total relaxation, or a warmth in my bones and blood and brain. I'm
also a carbon copy of both my parents, who fiercely refused to
accept love themselves. Is that reversible? Can you learn to feel
loved as an adult? Is the ability to receive love like a dormant
seed that can withstand any drought until rain finally falls, or
has some window of opportunity closed forever in my soul?
</P>
<P>
   I have a pretty good idea of my shortcomings and my strengths,
but I suspect my entries in both categories are irrelevant when it
comes to how satisfying or frustrating it feels to be in a
relationship with me. There's a paradox in my life, an insight that
makes it imperative that I break this pattern: If you polled the
people who care about me most, you would probably find that my
least lovable trait is how stubbornly I resist their loving me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
