<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGFREE-DORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT KERR HALL, FRESHMEN SAY NO TO ALCOHOL, DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hip-hop briefly blares from a room the size of a
spacious walk-in closet. A couple stands whispering intimately on
the stairwell between the fifth and sixth floors. A pair of female
friends giggle as they take turns talking on a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   This is about as exciting as it gets one weekday evening at Kerr
Hall, a Northeastern University dormitory filled with 120 freshmen
who have signed a ``lifestyles agreement'' pledging not to use
tobacco, alcohol, or drugs. If they do, they're out.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking state laws and campus policies against alcohol, drugs,
and noise may be the unwritten rule at other residence halls, but
not at Kerr, where sounds, as well as substances, fall under
scrutiny. Quiet time here begins at 11:30 p.m. on weeknights and
1:30 a.m. on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go over to the other dorms at night and it's louder,'' says
Kerr resident Lea Swink, 18. ``People run through the hallways.
There's banging. There's loud music. The floor is shaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Swink, who saw high school friends almost lose their lives to
drugs, is one of an increasing number of students nationally
seeking haven in substance-free dormitories. They're young people,
like Swink, who have witnessed the destruction of drugs and
alcohol. They're athletes seeking a healthy environment and
students who have tired of the excesses found in other dorms.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr Hall, which is also known as the Wellness Hall, opened in
1990 in a small housing complex with 69 students. The dorm soon
moved to larger building. By last fall, it was housing its full
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago only a smattering of universities across the
country offered such living quarters. By last year, 62 percent of
the schools responding to the Harvard School of Public Health
College Alcohol Study said they offered alcohol- and drug-free
housing.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike in the past, students choosing to live in places
like this are no longer met with taunts of ``loser,'' according to
Kerr Hall residents and university officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hear the nerd thing or the geek thing,'' says Jeannie
Lawton, a residence director who oversees Kerr Hall and other
residences at Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of their peers and they're doing this and it's OK
they're choosing it,'' she says. ``There've been no incidents that
I know of in the last three years where someone has said, `I've
been beaten or I've been verbally abused' because of their choice
to live here.''
</P>
<P>
   Swink's roommate Megan Peterson puts it this way: ``It's not
like high school where they make fun of you. It's your choice,
whatever you want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Sommer, 19, transferred to Kerr Hall, the only dorm on
campus that doesn't allow smoking, because he couldn't endure
living with a roommate who smoked. Meaghen Shaw, 19, is on the
track team and wants to stay away from any substance that will
compromise her physical performance.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's roommate, Sarah Dobson, 19, has a more sobering reason
for staying clean. She saw the devastating effects of drinking at
the age of 7 when her older brother battled alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Melanie Grandy, a 20-year-old transfer student from
Colby College, have simply experienced the hedonism of living in
liberal housing and have had enough. Colby's environment was so
permissive, Grandy recalls, that students were having keg parties
in the basement of her dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got really boring after a while,'' she says, then asks
rhetorically: ``Is there anything else we can do at school?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, say residents of Kerr Hall. Grandy spends her free time
visiting the Museum of Fine Arts, wandering along Newbury Street
and going to dinner parties. ``Filling up Friday and Saturday
nights is not a problem,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The dorm holds programs on eating disorders, stress relief,
campus housing options, and relationships. There are outings to
baseball, hockey, and basketball games. There's even a trip being
planned to New York.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, Kerr Hall residents also go to clubs and attend
parties. What happens if someone offers a drink?
</P>
<P>
   Swink says she simply answers, `` `No, I'm not drinking
tonight.' And they never really question it. They never push me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even from the cocoon of Kerr Hall, Swink has seen the groups of
drunken students who wobble home from parties, grabbing onto each
other to keep from falling. She knows students who eagerly search
for people over 21 to buy them liquor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here they have this freedom,'' she says. ``It's all a game.
It's like, `Look what I did.'' And their Mom and Dad are not around
to say, `No.' ''
</P>
<P>
   While Kerr Hall may not experience as much vandalism or noise as
other residence halls, it's not without its minute dramas. The loud
hip-hop music coming from one open-doored room gets knocked down a
few decibels as soon as Michelle Baker, 21, a fourth-year student
working as a resident assistant, casts a disapproving glance at the
offender during her evening rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Baker points out portions of the 6th floor walls scarred by a
student's punches. She also checks the garbage cans on each floor
for beer bottles. Because of Northeastern's housing crunch, some
residents didn't chose to live in a substance-free dorm. A few
subsequently moved out when other housing became available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some obviously do'' drink, says Baker, ``but they're usually
smarter about it than the general population.''
</P>
<P>
   That, apparently, is not smart enough. This school year, about
five people were transferred from Kerr Hall to less restrictive
dorms because they had violated the ``lifestyles agreement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8828 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-18 1807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING, SPORTS _ STRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Little League season in full swing, Day Thomson finds
herself increasingly anxious at her son's games. ``He feels kids
are mad at him if he messes up. He's starting not to want to go and
to have what I think are mythical stomachaches,'' she says. ``My
heart bleeds for him.''
</P>
<P>
   That his team is 0-3 so far doesn't help. Unlike his younger
sister, who cheerfully says of her losing soccer team ``We
stink!,'' and then talks about how much fun it is to play with her
friends, Thomson's son is losing enthusiasm for the team and the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 20 million children in the United States play
organized sports. That's terrific: ``Children learn life lessons
from sports,'' says child psychologist and researcher Shari Young
Kuckenbecker. ``They become socially skilled from teamwork and
cooperation, and they develop habits that will keep them healthy
and fit as adults.''
</P>
<P>
   What's not so terrific is that 30 to 40 percent of them drop out
each year, never to return to sports at all, says sport
psychologist and professor Ron Smith of the University of
Washington. Of those who start an organized sport before they are
6, 70 percent drop out by 13, says Fred Engh, president of the
National Alliance for Youth Sports, an advocacy organization for
safe and fun sports.
</P>
<P>
   Concern that youth sport programs are inappropriate and turning
kids off has fueled a spate of books, the most recent of which is
Kuckenbecker's ``Raising Winners'' (Random House). It's also
fueling a nationwide examination of youth sports:
</P>
<P>
   In southern Maine, middle schools recently voted to eliminate
all end-of-the year tournaments. The National Middle School
Association is also eyeing a no-tournament policy and discussing
restructuring middle-school sport programs so children of all
ability levels can participate. At the American Youth Soccer
Organization, a recent recommendation to coaches urges short-sided
play, so that teams are smaller (three players per team for 5- and
6-year-olds, five players for 7- and 8-year-olds, seven for 9- and
10-year-olds) and thus offer more learning opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reordering the priorities
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who runs a program that's trained 20,000 coaches in
developmental approaches, predicts nothing short of a sea change.
``There's an increased awareness that what kids need
developmentally from sports isn't what they are getting,'' he says.
He is coauthor of ``Way to Go, Coach!'' (Warde).
</P>
<P>
   The problems begin early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four- to 7-year-olds join a team because they like the
activity but mostly they want to be with friends. Sports is social
for them,'' says Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Parents tend to have a different agenda, typically hoping early
team participation guarantees an edge, if not stardom and a
scholarship, down the road, he says. That leads to a competitive
atmosphere, sometimes as early as third grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you have tournaments, championships, and traveling
teams, it's inappropriate pressure and not as much fun for kids,''
says Connecticut sport psychologist Shane Murphy. He is the author
of ``The Cheers and the Tears'' (Jossey Bass).
</P>
<P>
   What he prefers to see in soccer or baseball, for instance, is
what he calls progressive play, where children are on the same team
for a year or two but rotate from one coach to another to work on
specific skills. There might be minigames to hone skills but no
playoffs or tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pressure points
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are several kinds of pressure kids feel:
</P>
<P>
   --Social. Even a team's weakest player who gets little playing
time will enjoy a team as long as it's fun to be with the coach and
teammates, says educator Ed Brazee of the University of Maine, a
specialist in middle-school sport education. ``Kids are happy just
to be in the mix,'' he says. But if star players are allowed to
dominate and weaker ones feel left out not just of the game but
also of the socializing, it stops being fun. It's also no longer
developmentally appropriate for any of them, even the stars. ``It's
one of the reasons it's so important for coaches to work to create
respect for each kid and team spirit,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   --Physical. A child of any ability level continues to have fun
as long as she is learning new skills and seeing improvements. ``It
doesn't matter if she's a nonstar as long as she has a sense of
accomplishment,'' says Kuckenbecker. What tends to happen, however,
is that less-talented kids don't get appropriate help with skills
and lose a sense of personal accomplishment while talented kids are
pushed beyond their developmental levels. In one study of 1,100 6-
to 8-year-olds, Engh says, 49 percent were unable to perform
minimum skills of catching, throwing, or kicking. In other words,
he says, ``half the kids don't have the skills they need to play
the game we design for them.'' Engh is the author of ``Why Johnny
Hates Sports'' (Avery, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   --Parental. Six- to 9-year-olds typically don't pay attention to
how much time they're on the bench or what the score is. Parents
do. When we complain about lack of playing time, unfair coaching,
or poor playing by another child, we color our child's ability to
go back to that team as a full team player, says Kuckenbecker.
Murphy says star players feel an additional pressure: ``Even if
you're very supportive, when you get up at 5 a.m. and drive 45
minutes for a traveling team, a child can't help but conclude,
`This is very important to Dad.' Because all kids want to please
their parents, that translates to, `Am I good enough for Dad?' ''
That worry can eventually overwhelm their emotional coping skills.
</P>
<P>
   When children feel these pressures, they get bored or unhappy
and want to quit. That's not necessarily bad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Variety of experiences
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's developmentally in the best interest of a child under 10
to experience a variety of sports,'' says Murphy. The more sports a
child plays, the more diverse are his social experiences and
physical opportunities. It also makes him better able to know what
he really likes and where his skills lie.
</P>
<P>
   Engh sees no reason a child under 10 shouldn't drop a sport,
even mid season. ``If he's unhappy, let's say because the game
feels dangerous, it's a kind of emotional abuse. What's the
point?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Kuckenbecker agrees it's OK to move from sport to sport, but not
mid-season. The best life lessons can get learned when the going
gets tough, she says. Ask enough questions to figure out what is
making him so unhappy: ``Tell me about the coach''; ``Tell me about
the kids.'' Then help him learn from it: ``I know you like to be
the best. You're best in lots of things and you're good at this. No
one can be best at everything, but you can still learn a lot. I
admire someone who does that.''
</P>
<P>
   At any age, a child will have bad games. Getting into the car
with her after one of them can be tough: Depending on how invested
we are, we have our own feelings to deal with, not to mention her
mood, which can be ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get into a play-by-play of the game,'' says Murphy.
``When a kid blows it, she knows it. Going over it only makes her
feel worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Take your cues from listening and watching her. Kuckenbecker
shares a strategy she used with her three daughters: ``Sometimes
the best thing to do is put your arm around her and say nothing.''
Later, give her a chance to vent: ``I can see you're upset. Tell me
about it.'' Validate her judgment _ ``OK, you blew it, you passed
to your opponent'' _ and empathize: ``I know how lousy you feel.''
The more skilled a player, the more likely she is to be unhappy
because she knows what she should have done.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The big picture
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kuckenbecker tells parents to focus on the big picture, not on
the specifics: ``I really liked the effort you made in the first
quarter,'' or, ``You looked really strong when you made that play
at first.'' A favorite message of Murphy's is ``All kids make
errors/all teams lose. The difference between a good player/team
and a bad one is learning from mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Most kids move on quickly from error and loss. When frustration
spills over into other activities, ``help them distinguish between
emotion and behavior,'' says Murphy. ``Just because he has negative
feelings from the game doesn't give him the right to torment his
sister.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do good feelings entitle him to act like a brat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing worse than a kid who scores the winning goal
and thinks he's so cool, he hands his sports bag to Mom to carry.
And then Mom carries it! That's what really gets me!'' says
Kuckenbecker. ``These kid are not royalty,'' she reminds parents.
``Our obligation is to support the kid who feels low and temper the
one who's feeling too high.''
</P>
<P>
   Day Thomson's son, meanwhile, is starting to feel differently
about the season. In one recent game, he made a great play. The
team still lost, but it didn't seem to matter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
NURTURING GOOD SPORTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --De-emphasize winning by asking, ``Did you have fun?'' If she
offers the score, fine; if not, don't ask.
</P>
<P>
   --Remind the star who's gloating at his three-point winning
shot, ``You made that shot and it was great, but don't forget the
whole team played a great game just to get to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   --Be gently honest with the nonstar who complains that he spends
too much time on the bench: ``Some of these kids have already gone
through puberty, they're bigger and stronger.'' Or: ``You haven't
played for as many years. You're still learning.''
</P>
<P>
   --Before a game, remind her of previous successes. Research
shows that being in a positive mood helps the brain connect with
peak motor performances, which makes a person play better.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't ignore it if your child throws equipment, uses bad
language, etc. Tell him: ``I know you may have some feelings
welling up inside you, but that's not acceptable behavior. You need
to find some other way to get them out.''
</P>
<P>
   --By middle-school ages, specializing in a sport can lead to an
imbalance and oversaturation. If she plays soccer from September to
June and wants to play in the summer, that's fine, but stay away
from a camp where soccer is what they do all day.
</P>
<P>
   --Help a nonstar feel good about himself by finding something
he's doing better today than he did two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   --It's up to a coach, not a parent, to tell a child what he did
wrong in a game or a play.
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recommended reading if your child is going to
overnight camp for the first time: ``The Summer Camp Handbook,'' by
Christopher Thurber and Jon Malinowski (Perspective Press).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Barbara F. Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
