<HEADLINE>
STAIN, DON'T VARNISH, OAK THRESHOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How can I treat the new oak threshold on my front entry? Can
I varnish it?
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD GATELY, Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Do not varnish it. If you do, it will look great for a few
months, then will likely fade and peel, requiring regular
maintenance. Instead, paint on a semitransparent stain. It comes in
earth colors, so pick a color, apply one coat, and forget about it
for three years. Then, if it shows wear, clean it and apply another
coat. Just one coat is needed each time, and there's no peeling.
The stain will dry overnight.
</P>
<P>
   While semitransparent stain is designed for exterior house
walls, it can be used for thresholds and outside decks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My condo is in an old school, in a street-level basement with
no part underground. I am getting a lot of moisture; the rug feels
damp, and rust spots are appearing, from metal chairs on the rug.
How can I dry things out?
</P>
<P>
   PAT ERVIN, Jamaica Plain, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The key is to dehumidify. In summer, or at least in April,
May, June, September, and October, ventilate the condo by leaving
windows open (and secured) to allow water vapor buildup to
dissipate. That vapor comes from breathing, cooking, and washing,
but also from ground moisture rising through the concrete floor
until it meets the cool rug and condenses into water. The rug is
not at fault; it allows water vapor to go through it, which is
good; if it were a vapor barrier, it would trap moisture under it,
making things worse. In July and August, when it is humid all over
the Northern Hemisphere, venting will not do much good; that is
when you use a dehumidifier. The situation should not be as bad in
winter, with the heat on.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rust spots, you can get those out with a product
called Whink, sold in hardware stores and supermarkets. Then put
rubber cups or other nonrusting protection on the chair legs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My basement shower drain backs up just a few times each year,
but without warning. The toilet and sink are not sluggish. There is
no backup anyplace else in the multilevel house. The backup is
enough to cover the bathroom floor, and the water, which is really
sewage, gets under the marble threshold and soaks the rug outside
the bathroom. The plumbing goes to a sewer line in front of the
house. A plumber took a look and could not figure it out. Can you?
You're my last chance. The drain is buried under the concrete slab.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any way to prevent the water from getting out of the
bathroom? It is only 1/4-inch deep and does not go over the marble
threshold, but under it. I am getting tired of cleaning and
disinfecting the rug whenever this occurs. I never hear any
gurgling when the drain drains. It never occurs when someone uses
that shower.
</P>
<P>
   DESPERATE, in Westwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's a guess, but I think it is due to the design of the
drain: I think the shower drain is going into the main drain at
right angles to the main or nearly so, not gradually as it should.
Then, when water from other drains (not the shower) flows past this
shower drain, some of it backs up. This could happen when large
amounts of water are going down the main drain, as from a
dishwasher or washing machine that pumps the water out. It also
could happen when water running down the shower drain collides with
water flowing in the main.
</P>
<P>
   If this is so, a fix is difficult because the drain should be
dug out of the concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, you might be able to keep the water in the bathroom
during a backup by sealing the marble threshold. To do so, lift it
and apply an adhesive caulk, near the edges of the threshold so
that it oozes out when you press the threshold back in place. This
assures a tight seal. It is a jury rig, but may help until you fix
the backup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8830 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-REHABBED-COMIC-ART-BO     05-18 1637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REHABBED-COMIC-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 COMIC TEDDY BERGERON READY AT LAST TO MIX COMIC, SOBER SIDES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Last month, on ``The Tonight Show,'' host Jay Leno
asked guest Rosie O'Donnell about her start in comedy. O'Donnell
told the story of how she she lied to the manager of a Boston
comedy club in the early 1980s, and told him she was a headliner
from New York. The manager was glad because their scheduled star
was so drunk he couldn't perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who was that?'' asked Leno.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy B,'' O'Donnell replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah,'' said Leno, ``Teddy B.''
</P>
<P>
   Teddy B is Teddy Bergeron and they both knew Teddy's story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's long and complicated,'' says the Wellesley-born Bergeron,
who has alternated appearances in comedy clubs with trips to
alcohol rehab for the better part of two decades. ``But I think I'm
finally on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with dates at Nick's Comedy Stop together with sets in New
York at Stand Up New York, the Comedy Cellar, and Dangerfield's,
Bergeron, who once glimpsed stardom, is mounting another comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever said there are no second acts in American life was
wrong. Bergeron has made it through a hellish second act. And he's
in the middle of the third. Many of his friends, in and out of show
business, hope it is a comedy, not a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Through several interviews with Bergeron and many of his friends
and colleagues, a portrait emerges of a comedian nearly done in by
depression, alcohol, and, some say, success.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't begin that way. On Sept. 13, 1983, a bright and
youthful Bergeron made his debut appearance on ``The Tonight Show
Starring Johnny Carson.'' Bergeron took to the TV stage as if he
were born to it. His timing was impeccable, his delivery assured,
his material timeless. When Carson invited him to the couch to sit
with Liberace, it seemed as if the Boston comic's future was as
bright as could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't red hot, he was white hot,'' says performer Bruce
Smirnoff, who has known Bergeron since they both started out in
comedy in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, after refusing to return calls from the three
major networks, all of which wanted to sign him up, and snubbing
the William Morris Agency and a hive of other talent
representatives, Bergeron dragged himself into the Improv in
Hollywood. Network executives had staked out the club, waiting to
put in their bids. But when Bergeron showed up, hardly anyone
recognized him. He was drunk, disheveled, and dirty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe it was the same guy,'' says Smirnoff.
``Forty-eight hours after being one of the hottest talents to debut
on `The Tonight Show' he was worse than a pariah.''
</P>
<P>
   Life on the road _ the only life a stand-up comic knows _ is
filled with isolation and loneliness, and every night there are the
sound and smell of alcohol. It was tough for Bergeron.
</P>
<P>
   He racked up so many DUIs that he says he can't drive in any
state in the union. Once, after he showed up intoxicated in a Texas
club, the owner had him jailed for fraud. Within minutes, dressed
in orange prison garb and cardboard slippers, he had his fellow
inmates in hysterics. The guards, sensing there might be trouble,
pulled out their billy clubs and moved on Bergeron. Within seconds,
he had them laughing uproariously. They let him out.
</P>
<P>
   The next night, police arrested him again. Public drunkenness.
</P>
<P>
   Through most of the 1990s, Bergeron (no relation to former
Boston TV host Tom) spent more time in recovery than he did on
stage. At various times he lived on his mother's couch, at the
Homeless Veterans Shelter in Government Center, the Pine Street
Inn, and on Revere Beach. He begged for money. He wandered through
bars in Boston downing other people's unattended drinks. Bergeron
even knew the alcohol content of various mouthwashes and cough
syrup. It got so bad that a Los Angeles acquaintance recalls a time
when Bergeron poured high-octane gas through a loaf of bread to get
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed he couldn't take success,'' says Smirnoff. ``That
was the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an enemy that Bergeron is ready to take on again _ and
this time he thinks he has the weapons to win.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, at Nick's Comedy Stop, Bergeron gave an appreciative
audience a glimpse of his talents. From his patented parody of the
Roman gladiator movies (a character from ``Spartacus'' goes to a
singles bar) to jokes about alcoholism that cut close to his own
story, the 47-year-old veteran seemed as vigorous and fresh as if
he were just starting out. As with most great comedians, most of
the comedy comes in the telling, not just the tale. His skit about
a tone-deaf pitchman for a book promising instant piano and
songwriting skills remains as absurdly funny today as it did on the
Carson show.
</P>
<P>
   Off to the side, he had placed an inconspicuous tape recorder
that he uses to record each performance. While the audience howled
their appreciation, Bergeron wasn't satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd give it a C-plus,'' he says. ``I don't like a stage that
high. It puts you above the audience and I'm not really comfortable
with that. I like to interact with the audience.'' On his way home
that night (he recently rented an apartment in Quincy), he listened
to the tape _ carefully dissecting the timing, the response,
perhaps finding a word here or there or a rhythm that would punch
everything up a notch or two _ searching for any tiny detail that
would help him to get back on top.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, at the Pilsudski Polish American Club in
Southbridge, Bergeron is on the dance floor. The audience surrounds
him on three sides and he is on their level. The way he likes it.
</P>
<P>
   Later, over coffee, Bergeron tentatively takes a few
uncomfortable steps into the past. He is as nervous as he is before
a performance. His eyes stare off to the side and he's a bit jumpy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got tossed out of four high schools,'' he says. ``There was
never anything in the schools for me.''
</P>
<P>
   After a two-year stint in the Army, where Bergeron put on shows
at Fort Dix, N.J., during the latter stages of the Vietnam War, he
entered Bunker Hill Community College, where he performed and
produced a mock version of ``The Tonight Show'' in 1974. ``We had
400-500 people at those shows,'' he says. ``They were good.''
</P>
<P>
   After several days with Bergeron, one thing is clear. When he
has a microphone in his hand, he is transformed _ and it is amazing
to see. Even though he is a veteran performer with more than 20
years in the business, he is as nervous as a novice before a show.
Whether performing at Dangerfield's on New York's East Side or at a
Little League benefit in Central Massachusetts, he gets jittery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always like this,'' he says. ``Always.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happened to the promising comic? Why has life been so
difficult?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the environment that fed Bergeron began drying
up. During the 1980s comedy boom, it seemed that every Chinese
restaurant had a small stage and ``gong shows,'' contests that held
out a bit of prize money for contestants who didn't get gonged by
the audience. A comic could make a couple of hundred bucks a week.
But the early '90s hit comedy hard. Clubs closed up and those that
stayed open cut their rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy never fit into real life,'' says his friend and fellow
entertainer Dave Andrews. ``He was the black sheep of the family.
There was pressure on Teddy from the beginning. For a long time
Teddy was depressed and angry. He hated everyone. I just hope he
stays the course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think alcoholism is a disease,'' says Bergeron, who
has tried everything from group therapy and Alcoholics Anonymous to
the Seventh-day Adventists. ``The disease I had was depression. It
was terrible and it went away with a few drinks and a performance.
If I wasn't depressed, the alcohol never would have gotten to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergeron pauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time in my life everything was in a big fog,'' he
says, between sips of coffee. ``I was chasing rainbows. It was all
blurry.''
</P>
<P>
   While some friends and club owners got fed up with Bergeron's
irresponsible actions _ borrowing money and not repaying it and
showing up drunk for comedy dates _ others didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Clarke, Lenny's brother, was one of the ones who was
always good to me,'' says Bergeron. ``I could always count on him.
And the guys at Nick's helped me. And now, Kelly and Larry.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and Larry are Kelly Jones and Larry Lee Lewis. Jones, who
fell in love with Bergeron a couple of years ago in Maine, and
Lewis, a good-natured entertainer and former stripper's agent who
cut a deal to produce Bergeron's work and provide financial
assistance, are the comic's biggest fans. They form a support group
that Bergeron never had before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the guy,'' says Jones. ``He's been through a lot, but
we've been working together. When he's not drinking, he's the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think he's the funniest guy I've ever seen,'' says
Lewis. ``I know he's going to make it and we'll all profit from it.
He's just too good not to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, at New York's Comedy Cellar, Jerry Seinfeld,
who was in to do a set, stayed late to see Bergeron. After the
show, just before Seinfeld hopped into his double-parked Porsche,
he told Bergeron that he loved his act. A few nights earlier, Robin
Williams saw Bergeron at Stand Up New York and said pretty much the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   And, while Bergeron appreciates the response, he knows that a
few kind words won't get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to keep working,'' he says. ``I'm working.
Making money. It means everything to me. It is what I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
