<HEADER>
A8831 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-ART-BOS     05-18 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THE RUNDOWN ON RHODODENDRONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say the word ``rhododendron'' and many people think of a
blob-like evergreen with pink June flower trusses that's overlarge
and overplanted. Sadly, rhododendrons have suffered a bad rap
because a limited number of bor-ing old varieties dominate the
suburban landscape.
</P>
<P>
   So what's so great about rhodies?
</P>
<P>
   Low maintenance tops the list. Forget about fertilizing or
deadheading. Water them the first year until they're established.
Then ``you don't have to look at them again unless a tree drops on
them,'' says C.J. Patterson, a member of the Massachusetts Chapter
of the American Rhododendron Society.
</P>
<P>
   But of course you'll want to look at the flowers, which bloom in
shades of blue-lavender, purple, red, orange, or yellow (as well as
pink). Though most tolerate shade, not all are large or evergreen.
And many deciduous types, which are called azaleas, keep blooming
long after June; few other shrubs come in as many colors and sizes,
and with as many bloom times.
</P>
<P>
   Rhododendrons are, in fact, the perfect shrub for older or
overcommitted gardeners who don't want to get on their knees
anymore to weed out and divide perennials, but who want to keep
collecting new plants for the thrill of variety.
</P>
<P>
   A new propagation method called tissue culture is bringing more
varieties of rhododendrons (and other plants) to market sooner.
``It now takes 10 years to get a new cultivar into the trade
instead of 40,'' said Patterson. ``But people still don't realize
what's available.''
</P>
<P>
   The society's plant sale, featuring many new and rare
rhododendrons at very reasonable prices ($8-$35 for small plants),
will help change that. It will be part of an all-day conference May
27 aimed at introducing nonmembers to all aspects of rhododendrons.
The event will include a flower show where blooms of many of the
varieties for sale will be on view, as well as lectures on such
topics as selection, buying, and planting based on local
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Species azaleas, grown from seed from wild plants, are also much
more available than they used to be and are prized for their subtle
delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes more sophistication to appreciate wild azaleas, and
their new popularity shows that American gardeners are learning how
to see,'' says Patterson, whose favorite rhododendron is a wild
Japanese species, R. metternichii var. hondoense, which has
silver-white new leaves with a pink stripe down the middle. ``They
look like bunny ears.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Planting secrets
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trick to success with rhododendrons is to plant them right.
People often plant them too deep, says Dick Brooks, a former
president of the national organization. ``I had a rhododendron I
didn't like, so I tossed it, and it happened to land in my woods
right side up and put down roots. Today it's the happiest
rhododendron in my garden.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a great increase in southern-grown container plants at
home and garden megastores. ``One problem is that they're often
grown in a soilless mix which forms a dry core around the plant
that refuses to absorb water, so the plant dies of thirst. When you
take them out of the pot you have to wash off as much of the
soiless mix around the roots as you can with a jet of water from a
garden hose before you plant them,'' says George Hibben, who has
planted 150 rhododendrons in his garden.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Hibben uses clippers or a knife to butterfly and splay
pot-bound roots like a leg of lamb to get them heading outward.
Such roughing up sounds brutal, but it benefits most plants whose
roots have reached the walls of a container and started circling
around.
</P>
<P>
   Hibben makes a mix of half garden soil and half pine bark
minichips to replace the soilless mix. ``Don't use mulch, use
chips. And don't use peat moss because once it dries out, it
resists rewetting just like the soilless mix.'' He digs a hole
twice the diameter of the container because rhododendrons are
shallow-rooted and spread outward rather than down.
</P>
<P>
   Hibben then builds a cone in the bottom of the hole, using his
bark-chip/soil mix, and fills the hole with water. After the water
sinks in, he sets the rhododendron on the cone so it is raised 1
inch higher than the surrounding garden and spreads the roots out
over the cone.
</P>
<P>
   Hibben finishes by filling in the hole with more bark-chip/soil
mix, watering again, and then mulching around the plant with a
2-inch layer of pure bark chips. He's always careful to leave a
couple of unmulched inches around the shrub's trunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greer's Guidebook to Available Rhododendron Species and
Hybrids'' is a good beginner's guide to the rhody universe. It's
available at the Society book sale for $20 or from Greer Gardens,
1280 Goodpasture Island Road, Eugene, OR 97401-1794; telephone
541-686-8266.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
