<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8833 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     05-18 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE STREET, ABOVE THE CLOUDS, HAS INVESTORS SMILING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a tough time for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks have lost their luster. The Federal Reserve is
raising interest rates, all but guaranteeing the economy will slow
down. So where do you go to find companies that will perform well
in a difficult environment?
</P>
<P>
   For many investors, the answer seems to be State Street Corp.
Its stock is up more than 50 percent this year, and this week it
hit an all-time high of $116. The stock closed Wednesday at
$112.4375.
</P>
<P>
   About 125 analysts and money managers gathered at State Street
headquarters in Boston Tuesday to hear the company tell its story.
They liked what they heard. It is the story of a financial services
company that is growing rapidly but has very little exposure to
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the few financial stocks that can boast
accelerating revenues and lessened credit risk,'' said Steven
Wharton, an analyst with Loomis Sayles who attended the
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   State Street long ago stopped being a bank. Over the past 20
years it has morphed into a company that provides a range of
services to pension funds, mutual funds, and other institutional
investors. It is a hard business to understand and explain.
</P>
<P>
   The results are much easier to describe: State Street does well
year after year. The company has reported double-digit growth in
earnings per share for the past 22 years. Itsearnings have risen an
average of 18 percent annually for the past five years and 17
percent over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Does the word ``consistent'' come to mind? A $1,000 investment
in State Street stock in 1985 would be worth $28,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   The stock began running up in March and got another pop in April
when State Street announced its earnings had risen 24 percent in
the first quarter, well above Wall Street estimates. The 24 percent
growth also caught investors' attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've traded in our eight-cylinder car for a 12-cylinder car,
and we're firing on all 12 cylinders,'' chief financial officer
Ronald O'Kelley told reporters the day the earnings were released.
</P>
<P>
   State Street is benefiting from a variety of global trends: the
increase in stock trading, increased stock volatility, the growth
of 401(k) style pension plans, and the never-ending need for faster
and better information.
</P>
<P>
   State Street supplies a big percentage of the mutual fund prices
printed each day in the Globe and other newspapers. The trend
towards daily pricing is spreading globally, and the time needed to
process trades is shrinking. Cranking out all those numbers
requires an enormous investment in computing power. It is an
investment that many firms don't want to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies are asking themselves: Where can I go to
avoid investing zillions of dollars in systems?'' said Jean Melo,
chief investment officer at Vaughan Nelson, a Houston
money-management company.
</P>
<P>
   The answer for many is State Street. On Monday, Pacific
Investment Management Co., a large West Coast money manager, agreed
to outsource all its accounting and record-keeping services to
State Street.
</P>
<P>
   State Street has been trying to get Wall Street to think of it
as a technology company, rather than a financial services business.
It has tried, with modest success, to get technology analysts to
cover the company.
</P>
<P>
   One small coup: Wired magazine this month has a glowing piece
about State Street's computer operations. That kind of buzz makes
it easier to hire young techies. More importantly, technology
stocks command much higher price/earnings multiples than financial
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   What are the risks for State Street? The biggest would be a
global slowdown in trading or a major global correction in stock
prices. The company figures that for every 10 percent decline in
stock prices, its revenue falls 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, during the biggest corrections in recent years _
the selloffs following the Asian and Russian financial crises _ the
losses from falling prices were more than offset by gains from
increased volatility, O'Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   Another risk: State Street stock has had a big run-up. Analysts
say the once-undervalued stock is trading for something like a
reasonable price. ``I would not be surprised to see it take a
breather,'' said Steven Wharton of Loomis Sayles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most of those attending Tuesday's session came away
impressed and upbeat about State Street's future. Said Thomas
Goggins, one of the managers of John Hancock's Financial Industries
Fund, ``I didn't hear anything that would prevent them from having
excellent quarters for the rest of this year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
