<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8834 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-COLLEGE-DRINKERS-ART-     05-18 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-DRINKERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MAKING THE GRADE IN MARGARITAVILLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DICK LEHR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Mainly, it's fun,'' says Angela White.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love margaritas!'' adds her roommate, Karen Walicki.
</P>
<P>
   The two Northeastern University sophomores, both 21, are talking
candidly about their drinking. They drink regularly, though, they
say, rarely excessively. It's a way to let go after exams or to
loosen up and meet new people.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they've seen peers out of control at bars or parties. And
yes, they're aware that tragedy, like the 1997 death of MIT
freshman Scott Krueger, can come from college drinking. But tell
them a recent Harvard study's definition of a binge drinker and
they're brought up short. A woman who finishes four or more drinks
in a row at least once in two weeks is a binge drinker, according
to the researchers, as is a man who has five drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of describes what we do,'' says White, flashing a look
of disbelief at her roommate. They belong to the 44 percent of
college students the Harvard School of Public Health survey
identifies as binge drinkers, but the label, White and Walicki say,
just doesn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the person,'' says White, ``and it's about
balance. If you can go out and drink and get your work done and the
drinking isn't a chronic thing where you have to get drunk all the
time, I don't think drinking is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   This, then, is their drinking story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karen Walicki grew up in Middleton, N. Y. ``I didn't drink at
all in high school. I never went to parties. I was a big nerd.''
She began drinking wine during her first year at a community
college, before transferring to Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   White, meanwhile, grew up in Canada outside of Toronto, where
the minimum drinking age is 19. She had her first drink, a beer,
she says, when she was 16 and in high school.
</P>
<P>
   The two met and became friends last year and now share an
off-campus apartment with two other students. Walicki is majoring
in physical therapy. White's major is cardiopulmonary science. They
don't drink much on weekdays, they say. Maybe a beer while watching
television. Or they'll have a drink if they go out to dinner on a
weeknight.
</P>
<P>
   It's toward the end of the week when the imbibing begins. If
flush with money, they'll wander down to clubs on Boylston Street,
such as the Cactus Club. Closer to home, they go to Our House.
``Some of our friends are 19, so we might go to the clubs on
Thursday when our friends can get in too, when it's `18-plus,' ''
says White.
</P>
<P>
   What about fraternity houses?
</P>
<P>
   Both wince. ``I've only been to one frat party in two years
here,'' says Walicki.
</P>
<P>
   ``None,'' says White.
</P>
<P>
   A typical night out might start with a ``warm-up'' drink in the
apartment. It's cheaper to get started that way. Then around 11
o'clock they'll head out in a group. ``There's usually at least
four of us and we don't go with guys, although sometimes we run
into people we know,'' says White. They favor beer and mixed
drinks, like margaritas.
</P>
<P>
   The point? To have fun. ``To go out and meet other people,''
says White, ``like people who live around the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Walicki: ``It's mainly to get out and away from school and
your major. In school, all you talk about is classes and I can't
take it any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The booze and bar scene accelerates socializing. It's a fast,
high time that contrasts sharply to the slow motion and more inward
social scene they say they'd find at a coffeehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more likely to talk to you if they've had a couple
of drinks,'' says White.
</P>
<P>
   There are indeed times when they get ``trashed'' or ``wasted.''
Maybe it's right after exams and weeks of studying when, notes
White, ``it's time to break out.'' Maybe it's to celebrate a
birthday or other special occasion. That's when a morning hangover
is the memento of the night before. ``The next day you say, `I'm
never drinking again,' '' says Walicki.
</P>
<P>
   On those nights, says Walicki, the drinking ``gets more
hard-core _ like doing shots.'' The last time that happened was in
April when Walicki took White out to celebrate her 21st birthday.
The evening went like this: The roommates had their first drink at
Friday's with three couples and then, says Walicki, the couples
``pooped out on us.'' (``The last time we go out with couples,''
laughs White.) The women headed over to the Cactus Club for several
rounds of drinks with names like Long Island Iced Tea and Kamikaze
and at least one shot of tequila. It was a night of mixing liquors.
</P>
<P>
   They hooked up ``with some dude,'' says White, but even though
he treated them to a drink they didn't like the way he hovered.
``We were trying to get away from the guy,'' says White. So they
left. Their new companion followed and joined them in a cab. The
women headed over to Punter's, a bar popular with Northeastern
students, and, as they expected, they ran into ``guys we knew and
the guy following us kind of just got scared off.''
</P>
<P>
   By 3 a.m. the roommates were back at their apartment, staring
mindlessly at the TV and crashing.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, says Walicki, ``needless to say, I didn't feel
well.'' The night, all in all, was fun and a success, even if they
spent part of it eluding a persistent suitor.
</P>
<P>
   Overindulgence is about the only thing they sometimes regret.
``Mainly I might feel sick, but we don't really ever get that out
of control,'' continues Walicki. Over time they seem to have
developed ground rules for ensuring their safety, and neither has
ever had a regrettable sexual liaison stemming from too much booze.
``Usually we make sure if one of us says, `I'm gonna drink
tonight,' another one of us will stick to one or two drinks to
watch out, and make sure it goes okay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys at the clubs,'' adds White, ``can be grabby and
aggressive, and we're always looking out for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Walicki nods and offers an example: ``If I see some guy seems to
be bothering her, or putting his hands on her and trying to kiss
her, I'll jump in and get her away. I might start dancing with
her.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other rules: ``If four of us go out together we come
home together,'' says White. ``No one brings any one home.
Basically we don't pick any one up at bars.'' It's not as if they
hashed out these strategies ahead of time. They say it simply
developed this way naturally, a reflection that ``we all kind of
come from the same family types.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just our understanding, to respect each other and
trying to be safe,'' says White.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking, they say, is fun. If it's not chronic and extreme
drinking, what's the big deal? Says Walicki: ``My mom says, Don't
give me a reason not to trust you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly,'' says White. ``My parents know I drink, but they
also know I'm pretty much under control, that my priorities are
right, that school comes first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1335EDT &QL; 
