<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8838 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-SLEEPWALKING-ESSAY-TE     05-18 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALKING-ESSAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DO SOME UNDERTAKE NOCTURNAL AMBLINGS? EXPERTS ARE IN THE DARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In July 1969, about the same time Neil Armstrong took man's
first steps on the moon, I engaged in an unusual little excursion
myself. I was 11 years old then and at Boy Scout camp. On my first
night in the wild, I woke up barefoot and alone in the middle of
the Minnesota woods, dressed only in my underwear, with not a clue
as to how I got there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really done it this time,'' I said, or something to that
effect.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rather lonely, unnerving feeling, as you might expect.
Somewhere in those woods was the tent I had abandoned in my sleep.
How long I stumbled around in the darkness before I located another
tent, I don't really remember. A long time, it seemed. I do recall
that a fellow Scout seemed surprised to find me at his tent door,
in the middle of the night, in my underwear, asking to borrow a
flashlight. I doubt anyone has been more happy to feel the inside
of a sleeping bag than I was when my impromptu wilderness hike came
to an end.
</P>
<P>
   But that was only the most perilous of the nocturnal ramblings
of my boyhood. There were several others, maybe dozens, up and down
the stairs at home, for the most part. Once I ended up in a
neighbor's garage. Then there was the night, again in the summer of
1969, again the first night of a summer camp, when I felt a tugging
at my shoulder as I slept in the bottom bunk of a crowded
dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy. Buddy,'' another camper whispered, somewhat
desperately, but trying to avoid waking the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' I replied, groggily.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in my bunk,''
</P>
<P>
   ``Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in my bunk.''
</P>
<P>
   I pondered this for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' I said. ``Sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   I slipped out of his bed and he slipped in. Somewhere, in the
darkened dormitory, there was an empty bunk with my name on it. To
this day, I have no recollection how I might have found it.
</P>
<P>
   The other day at the office, we were swapping sleepwalking
stories. I'm rather proud to say that not one could hold a candle
to mine.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   EYES OPEN, MIND MOSTLY ASLEEP: What could possess a boy to
undertake an unconscious ramble in the north woods? My inquiry
might be a bit tardy _ by 30 years or so _ but having been recently
reminded of that singular adventure, I decided to try to find out.
After several calls to sleepwalking experts across the country, the
answer was this: No one really knows.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say, almost apologetically, that there has been little
research on the topic, that is, the sort of sleepwalking undertaken
by about 15 percent of all children, and 10 percent of all adults.
It's just not that big a deal, they say, hardly worth millions in
medical research dollars that could be spent on more pressing
issues. Most kids who sleepwalk outgrow it, and don't hurt
themselves or others. Most sleepwalking is not linked to other
psychological problems. ``Benign'' is the word most commonly used.
(Tell this to an 11-year-old who wakes up in his underwear in the
middle of the woods.)
</P>
<P>
   So, where the causes of sleepwalking are concerned, we are left
with best guesses. The prevailing theory is that sleepwalking
events most commonly occur during Stage 3 sleep, a phase somewhere
between nodding off and the famous REM (rapid eye movement) phase,
when we dream. In Stage 3, a person is completely out, his mind and
body both pretty much gone. Zonked, I believe, is the clinical
term. The sleepwalker, for some reason, apparently suffers a
partial interruption of this state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like you activate mobility, but you don't engage
the mind,'' says Edgar Lucas, a sleep expert in Fort Worth.
``You've awakened the motor system, but the brain stays in a
primitive, deep, nonfunctioning state. We don't have any idea why
that occurs. We do know that you may change from one stage to
another on a normal night, and do that 50 to 75 times.''
</P>
<P>
   The sleepwalker wanders with his eyes open, to the bathroom, for
cookies, to catch reruns of that night's Sportscenter, but has no
recollection of that activity. Sleepwalkers generally do not run
into walls or trip over furniture, ``so apparently the visual
system does have some input,'' Lucas says. ``But the blank stare
that you get says the person is not hearing what you're telling
them. They're operating at a very primitive level.''
</P>
<P>
   The tendency to sleepwalk is likely genetic, experts also say.
Stress can increase the likelihood of sleepwalking episodes. It was
probably no coincidence that my summer camp wanderings took place
on the first night away from home. Athletes are more prone to
sleepwalk on the night before a big game. Alcohol doesn't help.
Sleep deprivation either.
</P>
<P>
   But again, in almost every case, sleepwalking is no big deal.
Parents are advised to pick up objects that sleepwalking children
could stumble over. A night light or two would help. Gentle coaxing
is generally all that's needed to get a sleepwalker back in the
sack. Experts particularly caution parents against overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want this child to think they've got some kind of
morbid psychological problem,'' Lucas says. ``Assure them that they
will outgrow it. Treat it as a normal variation that can occur in
some kids.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FOR SOME, A NIGHTMARE: As long as we're on the topic, there's
another sleep disturbance worth mentioning, one that resembles
sleepwalking but isn't. It is called REM sleep disorder, a
potentially dangerous malady in which sleepers can act out dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that during REM sleep, our brains are more active
than during wakefulness. It is then that dreaming occurs.
Fortunately, every muscle except those used in breathing are
briefly paralyzed during the REM state. That paralysis often
produces the terrible dream sensations of being unable to run from
an attacker, or sinking in quicksand. But the benefits of REM
paralysis far outweigh the fright.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few individuals who, for some reason, fail to
paralyze the body when they go into a dream episode, or only
partially do so, and when those individuals go into dreams they can
act it out,'' Lucas says.
</P>
<P>
   One patient, Lucas recalls, dreamed of running down a hillside
and attempting to leap a hedge. He landed on his dresser and
knocked out his front teeth. Another saw snakes in a dream, and
hurt a foot kicking a wall. A third dreamed of steer-wrestling, and
his wife became the steer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw a hammerlock on his wife and threw her down,'' Lucas
said of the patient, who was strongly encouraged by his spouse to
seek medical help. ``The thing is, most often this happens to older
men who are fairly docile and good-natured _ the last guys you'd
suspect would do something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The condition is treatable with medication, Lucas says, a muscle
inhibitor that helps keep the rodeo out of the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   JUST WALK ON BY: I am grateful for this information. For years I
wondered if my strange, zombielike adventures as a child
foreshadowed Norman Bates-like behavior later on. But no. A normal
variation in childhood, I'm now told.
</P>
<P>
   Yet I would have been glad to have this reassuring knowledge
that night in the woods, or in the dormitory, or that late night
around the same boyhood time when my next-door neighbor heard
something in her garage. Upon investigating, she found me rummaging
around, again in my underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Tim,'' she said, quite kindly. ``What are you doing
here?''
</P>
<P>
   At the time I had no good answer. Now I do. Today I could say,
``A partial interruption of Stage 3 sleep. But don't worry. It's
normal.''
</P>
<P>
   And that would have explained everything.
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Madigan is a writer for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call him at (817) 390-7544. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
