<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8842 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-18 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BIG LABOR'S ANTI-CHINESE BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WILLIAM WONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ In a matter of days, Congress will vote on
whether China should have permanent normal trade relations with the
United States. My first thought is about the history behind it.
</P>
<P>
   There are strange bedfellows on both sides. In favor of China
getting what was once called ``most favored nation'' trade status:
the Democratic president, his vice president (also a presidential
candidate) and some Democratic representatives; a majority of
Republicans in Congress; leaders of business and agricultural
interests; and the probable Republican presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side: organized labor, environmentalists, human
rights activists, many congressional Democrats, anti-Communist
conservatives and hate-mongering Reform Party presidential hopeful
Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   It is the opposition of organized labor that evokes the
historical lesson for me.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go back about 125 years right here in San Francisco. ``The
Chinese of America,'' a book by Jack Chen, is my guide.
</P>
<P>
   A depression was on hand, following the euphoric and expansive
economy of the 1860s. Included was completion in 1869 of the
transcontinental railroad, which Chinese laborers helped build.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the new railroad brought to California from the East
Coast thousands of white Americans seeking work. Throw into the mix
thousands of Chinese workers whose jobs _ building the railroad _
were eliminated. Unemployed and frustrated, white workers and their
newly formed ``anti-coolie'' organizations (the United Brothers of
California, the Anti-Chinese Union of San Francisco and the
California Workingmen's Party) went looking for a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Gompers, the legendary president of the American
Federation of Labor, wrote in his pamphlet ``Some Reasons for
Chinese Exclusion'': ``. . . racial differences between American
whites and Asiatics would never be overcome. The superior whites
had to exclude the inferior Asiatics, by law, or if necessary by
force of arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Denis Kearney, founder of the Workingmen's Party, ``pledged to
fight against corrupt government, capitalists and monopolists, but
mostly he attacked the Chinese immigrants for working for
starvation wages and robbing Americans workers of jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Kearney who invoked in San Francisco's torchlight rallies
the famous lines ``The Chinese must go!'' And ``They are stealing
our jobs!''
</P>
<P>
   That battle cry symbolized the anti-Chinese political campaign
that spread from San Francisco all the way to Washington, D.C.,
culminating in the Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to May 2000. The Chinese Exclusion Act has long
been repealed. Chinese-Americans have become an integral part of
America. Some are members of labor unions that may or may not
oppose the China-trade bill. The successors to Gompers no longer
scapegoat ethnic Chinese workers in this country.
</P>
<P>
   How they feel about Chinese laborers in China is another matter.
American labor leaders are in high dudgeon over Chinese laborers in
China who they feel will steal jobs from American workers if
Congress grants China ``permanent normal trade relations.''
</P>
<P>
   American labor leaders don't trust the captains of American
industry they feel will export jobs to China and other less
developed countries. That is not altogether fanciful paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   Globalization has meant, among other things, capital chasing
cheap labor _ wherever it is. But globalization has also embraced
market economic principles. Even the leaders of communist China use
capitalistic methods to uplift the country's historically
impoverished millions.
</P>
<P>
   While seeking to protect American jobs, American labor leaders
are missing a salient point. If China gets permanent normal trade
relations status, American companies will benefit because China's
huge market will be more open than it has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   That means more export business for American companies, which
means continuing work for American workers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though ethnic Chinese people in this country and in China
are better off than we were in the late 19th century, I am chilled
by the faint echo of anti-Chinese scapegoating embedded in the
politics of contemporary American labor leaders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
