<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8851 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-DINOSAUR-TEX     05-18 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DINOSAUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DINOSAUR' ROCKS: DIGITAL WIZARDRY WILL AMAZE YOUNG AND OLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Walt Disney Pictures decided to venture into the uncharted
waters of feature-length computer animation, it stuck out a
tentative toe by approaching the brightest minds already in the
field. This led to a brilliant collaboration with director John
Lasseter and Pixar Animation that produced both ``Toy Story''
movies and ``A Bug's Life.''
</P>
<P>
   But the House of Mouse is never truly content unless all
production can be done within the comforting shadow of its
omnipresent ears, so Disney took the next step and created its own
digital studio.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Dinosaur,'' opening Friday, and it's one of the
most visually stunning breakthroughs in computer animation since
the medium first reared its clunky, complicated, cubist head.
</P>
<P>
   Combining computer-generated characters with live-action
backgrounds and enhancing the mix with special-effects wizardry,
``Dinosaur'' has a breath-taking scope and vision all its own,
almost a perfect marriage of fact and fantasy. For devotees of
digital animation _ still very much in its infancy _ the
improvements on display here in texture, musculature and facial
articulation are staggering. But to the film's inevitable audience
of wide-eyed, slack-jawed young viewers, the leathery, lumbering
characters are simply awesome.
</P>
<P>
   The story, as if this thing really needs one, centers on a young
iguanodon called Aladar. With Disney's inimitable knack for
unforgettably stirring ``Once upon a time ...'' beginnings (see
``The Lion King'' or ``Tarzan''), the tale begins with a pteranodon
snatching Aladar from his herd while the dino is still in his egg
and _ after staggering aerial views and a sweeping score _
eventually depositing him in the back yard of a group of
inquisitive lemurs.
</P>
<P>
   Far from his own kind, the lonely young reptile (given voice by
D.B. Sweeney) is raised as part of a family of monkeys, which
includes the motherly Plio (Alfre Woodard), the grandfatherly Yar
(Ossie Davis) and the equally lonely, unattractive hairball of a
monkey, Zini (Max Casella).
</P>
<P>
   The happy clan is driven from their island paradise by an
onslaught of fiery meteors in a sequence spectacular enough to
rival the explosive climax of six Jerry Bruckheimer actioners
combined. While the gang explores the desolate regions of a distant
shore, Aladar finally encounters his own kind in a massive herd of
migrating creatures in search of a Utopian nesting ground.
</P>
<P>
   He wastes no time in befriending the herd's weaker misfits, a
Mrs. Potts-type character called Baylene (Joan Plowright), the last
of the mammoth brachiosaur species, and an aging styrachosaur named
Eema (Della Reese). Aladar stern rejection of the herd's ``survival
of the fittest'' credo catches the attention of an attractive
female iguanodon named Neera (Julianna Margulies) but also puts him
at odds with her brother, Kron (Samuel E. Wright), the cold-hearted
taskmaster leading the migration.
</P>
<P>
   But Aladar and company have concerns bigger than Kron. With no
water in sight, marauding raptors waiting to attack and a pair of
blood-thirsty carnotaurs in pursuit, the little group discovers
that if they are to pull through, they'll have to do it together.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who caught the soaring opening sequence in theaters _ it
was distributed as a teaser trailer _ might be caught off guard
when the creatures of ``Dinosaur'' actually start talking. It's a
crucial moment in the film, and after the captivating but entirely
mute introduction to the story, it's a bit jarring. But even Disney
would be hard-pressed to pull off a feature done entirely in
pantomime. It's a credit to the talents of the vocal performers
that the characters shine through so well, all without sacrificing
the dignity or believability of the creatures speaking.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this isn't a nature documentary, despite its slavish
attention to detail. It's a Disney film, which means audiences
should be able to suspend disbelief long enough forgive the movie
its more fantastical moments. Sure, real dinosaurs probably didn't
have the ability to problem-solve or form interspecies support
groups or _ with brains the size of walnuts _ ``talk.''
</P>
<P>
   But realism is a relative term, so put away your persnickety
paleontologic complaints and sit back and enjoy ``Dinosaur'' for
what it is: an amazing entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Dinosaur''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Ralph Zondag, Eric Leighton
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: The voices of D.B. Sweeney, Alfre Woodard, Samuel E.
Wright
</P>
<P>
   Length: 84 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ dinosaur violence and scary business
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
