<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ARAB-MARKET0519-COX     05-18 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAB-MARKET0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jerusalem's Arab market _ get your bargains here!
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ From inside his shop in the ancient walled Old City
at the crossroads of the world, Sammy Zatar spits salted watermelon
seeds to the floor and watches the full spectrum of humanity stroll
by.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the morning until late at night, the parade never
stops. In the space of a half-hour last month he watched a bearded
and bowlegged Arab dwarf push a wheelbarrow full of butchered sheep
heads past two Eastern Orthodox nuns dressed head to toe in black
and white.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, three 6-foot-something blonde Scandinavian women
almost tripped over a group of short, dark, barrel-chested
Colombian pilgrims kneeling on the floor, intently studying sets of
bongo drums. Four teenage Israeli soldiers with black machine guns
slung across their backs squeezed past two Yeshiva students dressed
in the black and white clothes their ancestors began wearing in
16th-century Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Zatar, 42, moustached and bemused, watched it all with an
expression that seems perpetually on the cusp of a smile.
</P>
<P>
   He has been here since he was 12 years old, when he dropped out
of school to help his father in this store. Store may not be the
right word; it's a shop, really, a glorified stall abutting
hundreds just like it. The walls are so close together a tall man
can touch both sides with his arms outstretched _ if, that is, he
can find any empty wall space. Drums, jewelry, dresses, menorahs,
bowls, cups, candles, Turkish coffee pots, sabers and stuffed
animals hang off hooks from the ceiling. Some are stacked
precariously on shelves. The walls are almost hidden.
</P>
<P>
   As is the tension. Certainly it's here. Passing through this
beehive of a market made of scores of crooked and twisted alleys
running for hundreds of yards are pedestrians who believe some of
the people they are shopping next to should be resettled _ or even
eradicated. More than 200 Israeli security cameras installed for
the Pope's visit in March tape every move of shoppers and
shopkeepers.
</P>
<P>
   If a Holy War erupts, chances are good it will start here, in
Jerusalem, and the heart of Jerusalem is the Old City, and the
heart of the Old City is the Arab market. In the heart of the
market is where Zatar spits his watermelon seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Within half a mile of where he stands, churches, mosques and
synagogues mark the places where traditions say Jesus rose from the
dead, the Prophet Mohammed arrived on his flying horse Buraq from
Mecca and ascended to heaven, and God spoke to the Jewish patriarch
Abraham. Crusades have been waged and blitzkriegs launched to prove
these stories true.
</P>
<P>
   Within blocks of Zatar's shop, world history has lurched in
dozens of directions, sometimes at knife point, sometimes elevated
by mystical ideas delivered by prophets. A bronze plaque on the
cobblestones proclaims in English, Hebrew and Arabic that the
stones of the alley were laid by the Romans in the third century
but the market itself likely predates Christianity. Indeed, the
durability of the market is proof that while religions come and go,
armies win and lose and dynasties rise and fall, shopping and
haggling remain eternal.
</P>
<P>
   And eternally challenging. To sell anything in this little
laboratory of humanity a salesman first has to understand his
customers. A dozen languages are spoken at every turn. Asked the
tools of his trade, Zatar pointed to his head. He speaks not just
his native Arabic, but Hebrew, English, Spanish, French, German
and, though he doesn't include it on his litany of languages, a
little Afrikaans.
</P>
<P>
   How much is a little? Enough to make a sale.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: She's blond and attractive and walking down the
slightly sloped bustling alley when she hesitates, just a bit, to
look more closely at a necklace hanging on a dusty black velvet
display at the edge of Zatar's shop.
</P>
<P>
   Though she could easily be Scandinavian or German or Dutch or
American, Zatar calls out in Afrikaans and the woman looks up and
smiles. Bingo. He says something else and she laughs. Zatar is over
to her side in an instant, taking her by the arm and insisting she
enter his shop, share his coffee, talk about that beautiful
one-of-a-kind necklace he has now placed in her hands.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, after she's paid $18 _ down from an asking
price of $50 _ she is asked what her new friend said to make her
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Hello, my name is Dennis and I play tennis and I
think you are the most beautiful woman in the world,' '' she says,
smiling. ``What could I do? How many times does someone say that to
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, in the Arab market, if you're a woman, the odds are
pretty good you'll hear something like it at least once. Here,
salesmanship is practiced the old-fashioned way, with drama,
conversation and more drama. Necessity dictates shop owners sell
the sizzle, not the steak. Almost anything Zatar sells, a stall 50
feet away offers as well, and maybe cheaper. To make a sale is to
make a friend, and to do that, Zatar tries to figure out what
nationality people are, what language they speak and what he can
say that will make them laugh _ or at least acknowledge him _
before they have passed the 10-foot-wide entrance to his shop and
moved into the next guy's territory.
</P>
<P>
   Zatar is a master. Sometimes he is blunt: ``Poland, Poland!
Poland! He yells to a group of Slavic-looking tourists. ``Russia,''
one yells back. ``Ah! Russia Russia, Russia'' he yells in response,
undaunted, trying to get them to look back. Nope. Too late.
</P>
<P>
   Other times he is suave: ``I love the woman from Espana!'' he
coos in Spanish to a dark-haired woman he is guessing is Spanish.
Oops, Italian. ``She should be Spanish,'' Zatar mutters.
</P>
<P>
   The dance of a sale here is sometimes delicate and sometimes
rude but always theatrical.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are making me poor!'' he cries to one German tourist who
refuses to pay $40 for a curved, foot-long dagger. ``I have a
family to feed,'' he pleads with Japanese teenage boy to whom he
sells a plastic bongo drum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, come to my house for dinner tonight,'' he begs his
South African friend.
</P>
<P>
   How many dinner invitations has he offered in his 30 years in
the souk (Arabic for market)? ``A thousand a day, but to her I
meant it the most,'' Zatar says. ``She is my favorite.'' None has
ever come home with him, though he insists his wife and six
children would love the company.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you bargain with a man like Zatar? ``Cheerfully,'' he
says. ``And then be a good guy, pay me what I want.'' Indeed,
Americans often do. Americans _ who typically have their
nationality written all over them in brand-name shoes, pants and
shirts _ usually have little or no experience haggling and are
among the worst bargainers in the market. Germans run a close
second. Jews from the former Soviet Union _ and Israel is flooded
with them _ are among the toughest.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Jacobson is proof. Jacobson lives in Pittsburgh but
grew up in Azerbaijan. She is looking for a dress to bring back
home, something unusual, she says. Her mother, Rachel, waits
patiently outside the shop _ it's too small to wait inside _ while
Jacobson tries on dresses. As a doctor in Baku, Rachel Jacobson
earned $180 a month and learned to make it stretch. She passed her
savvy on to her daughter, along with her philosophy on haggling:
``Life is not to work and get nothing.'' If her daughter has a hard
time bringing Zatar down to a reasonable price, Rachel Jacobson
says she will lend a hand.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no need. The long, purple, handmade velvet dress
that Zatar originally asked $50 for is finally purchased _ after 30
minutes of courtship _ for $10.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's good,'' Zatar says as Jacobson and her mother walked
away. Then with a shrug, ``I invited her to dinner but she didn't
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
