<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8854 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MARKET-TIPS0518-COX     05-18 0269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-TIPS0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To market, to market... (But read these tips first.)
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin and Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Look impoverished, like a hostel-dwelling archaeology student.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go to a store where prices are fixed to see how much things
cost.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never offer a price. Just indicate his price has to be lower.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep various amounts of small bills in different buttoned
pockets _ $5 in one, $20 in another _ so you can pull it out like
that's all you have.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't feel guilty. You don't want it, end of story.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't be bulldozed by someone shouting at you. Tune him out
and concentrate on the merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you really want something, don't show it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Decide immediately what you will pay. Street salesmen are
quick to take advantage of indecision.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you don't want something, just say no. Do not say, ``No,
it's the wrong color,'' or ``No, it's too big.'' The seller thinks
this means yes.
</P>
<P>
   _ The first price is typically double or triple or more of what
the seller will accept. Don't think that first inflated price
indicates what the object is worth, what the seller is willing to
accept or what you should offer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Remarks of quality and rarity by the seller should be ignored.
Determine for yourself how well-made something is.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wondering how low the salesman will go? Walk out. You can
always come back.
</P>
<P>
   _ Men traveling with women should defer to their almost
invariably superior sense of how to get a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
