<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8855 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-LISTON0519-COX     05-18 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LISTON0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A hard knock life
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sonny Liston was white America's
stereotypical nightmare: a large, illiterate black man who came
through the door promising pain and delivering retribution. He had
a long police record, he terrified black people, especially Floyd
Patterson, as much as white, and he didn't give a damn what anybody
thought of him.
</P>
<P>
   Once, he was asked what he thought of when he was fighting.
``Kill him,'' he said. ``I always say kill him when I'm in the ring
with a white boy. You got to knock 'em out to win. You won't get
the decision. I try to knock 'em all out, white or black.''
</P>
<P>
   All his life, Liston was in trouble with the law, but it was
usually fairly small-time stuff _ suspicion of theft, failure to
appear on a summons, speeding, larceny. There were also a couple of
thefts, and the pistol-whipping of a cop, not to mention the
occasional rape. During one five-year period, he amassed 14
arrests.
</P>
<P>
   He first put on boxing gloves while in prison, which he always
said he rather liked _ Sonny even scared the other convicts. He had
fists that measured 14 1/2 inches around, and he didn't beat his
opponents, he decimated them. As with the young Mike Tyson, the
aura of fear around Liston meant that lots of opponents were
defeated before they got in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Tosches' hyped-up style works well with certain kinds of
biographical subjects _ gangland stuff, especially. But Tosches
does Tosches whether it's appropriate to his subject or not, as
with his strenuously high-voltage biography of Dean Martin, a man
who broke a sweat only on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   But Tosches and Sonny Liston? That's a marriage made in pulp
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Devil and Sonny Liston'' is less a conventional biography
than a study guide for someone else's more comprehensive book.
Tosches firmly establishes that Liston was completely the creature
of Frankie Carbo _ a pal of Bugsy Siegel's and a stone killer _ and
Blinky Palermo. The mob had so much of Liston that he actually
owned only about 10 percent of himself.
</P>
<P>
   He also lays out Liston's drinking problems and his abuse of
women, whether prostitutes or other men's wives.
</P>
<P>
   Tosches believes that Liston threw both his fights with Cassius
Clay, and, looking at the films, it's hard to disagree. In the
first fight, this one-man wrecking crew gives up his title sitting
on his stool. His shoulder was hurting, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second fight, we were asked to believe that Liston was
knocked silly by a little uppercut that wouldn't have fazed Jerry
Quarry, a punch thrown by a man who was never, at any time of his
career, a brutal knockout puncher.
</P>
<P>
   (There's one great line of dialogue, from a mobster who tells
Tosches that ``this guy didn't just take a dive _ he did a one and
a half off the high board.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Tosches ignores a valid counter-argument: Why would the Mob
have preferred Clay to Liston? Sonny may have been a thug, but Clay
was about to become Muhammed Ali and embark on a turbulent
socio-religious odyssey that meant he vacated the title for years.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Liston died sometime on the last week of December 1970 _
his body wasn't discovered for a week _ from what was a probable
drug overdose. Officially, he was 38, but he was almost certainly
at least 45, and maybe older. There have been suspicions of foul
play over the years, but Tosches doesn't seem to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Devil and Sonny Liston'' doesn't attempt to reclaim or
justify Liston, a man who was closer to the dark soul of boxing
than Ali. Tosches does assert something that's unassailably true,
about the way Ali co-opted dozens, even hundreds of mostly white
writers over the years:
</P>
<P>
   ``His tiresome and trying wit, his harmless and drably colorful
shows of playfulness, and his affected audacity were perfectly
suited for the media of the day . . . he became the darling of a .
. . white intelligentsia who sought meaning and metaphor in boxing
. . . Many of these writers, who could write no better than they
could fight, found in him a willing and suitable accomplice in
their conceits of the intellect and their deceit of themselves and
others. It was through Clay, and with his implicit approval, that
they were enabled to play out the marked deck _ the dream cards of
manliness, racial understanding, provocative sensibility, and bond
between writer and warrior _ that in reality were less of the soul
than of fancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosches has nailed something here, even though his
crystal-meth-and-bourbon prose style is as strenuous an attempt at
blue-collar authenticity as white boys with Ivy League educations
fluttering around Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Devil and Sonny Liston'' is valuable as a corrective to 30
years of Ali worship, but it's occasionally derailed by Tosches'
compulsion to out-write Thomas Wolfe:
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in this world was free: and all, slave and master,
victor and vanquished alike, were one, as chaff from the threshing
of man against man, the threshing not only of man's will to
enslave, but of will itself, and of willfulness itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's possible that some grad student is going to read this,
clutch his chest and fall to the ground uttering low moans of
animal pleasure, but this is outrageously overheated, hammy
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath Tosches' literary affectations is a good, clean,
valuable book struggling to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
