<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MILNER0519-COX     05-18 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MILNER0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ragin' Cajun talks politics, cooking and Sopranos in book
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ You would expect a book by James Carville to be
outspoken to the limit, especially if the subject is politics. If
so you won't be disappointed with Corporal Cueball's latest:
``Stickin' _ The Case for Loyalty.'' (Simon &AMP; Shuster)
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat surprising, however, is the fact that ``Stickin''
reveals a serious and semi-intellectual side of the well-known
Clinton mad dog strategist, who has become a celebrity in his own
right with his full-steam ahead and take-no-prisoners attitude
during his many TV appearances since Clinton was elected in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Carville turns his wrathfully articulate distaste on Ken Starr,
Revs. Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson and other far-right spokesmen
as a guest on most Sunday TV talk shows and other public
appearances, not hesitating to call them as he sees them in no
uncertain terms.
</P>
<P>
   The title of this book refers, primarily I suppose, to
Carville's loyalty to President Clinton during his series of
attacks the past few years, including the Republican impeachment
attempt and the endless series of charges brought by Ken Starr's
gang of prosecutors, and others around the country who seem to have
an obsessive hate for the twice elected Democrat president.
</P>
<P>
   But the native of Carville, Louisiana, also discusses loyalty in
general as a philosophical view of life and relationships inside
and outside one's family. It is a thoughtful and interesting book,
as well as a colorful and insightful view of politics, local and
national.
</P>
<P>
   And, as the jacket blurb declares, it wouldn't be a Carville
book if it didn't include some recipes for some good home cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Republicans Carville has some kind words for his
political enemies. For instance, he praises Reagan for ``sticking
by'' some of his associates when they encountered misfortune. In
this section of the book, Carville declares: ``Whatever the rights
and wrongs of David Stockman's actions, Reagan didn't fire him.
Now, at the risk of horrifying some of you, I'm going to concede
that there are occasions Republicans have stuck with a person.
Michael Deaver was deputy White House Chief of Staff until he quit
in May 1985...He became a lobbyist and had big legal problems when
he was charged with lying to a congressional subcommittee and a
federal grand jury. He had had a close relationship with the
Reagans for 20 years and they stood by him. Nancy Reagan was
especially close to Deaver. As the New York Times commented at the
time: 'That the relationship continues might come as a surprise in
light of Mr. Deaver's precipitous decline in influence in a city
with scant sympathy for those who fall from power if not from
grace.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carville even has a section on Shakespeare, the Sopranos and
Andy Griffith.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about every decent dramatic book,'' Carville writes,
``movie or play, is going to have a theme of conflicted loyalty.
Loyalty, or rather disloyalty is the very essence of drama...Take
all the stories in the Bible. Everyone who gets in trouble has been
disloyal to God. Look at Adam and Eve. When the deluge came and
Noah and his family were saved, there was a very, strong
message....Be loyal to God. (Of course, if we lived in Kansas, the
story is not a story, it is news, as it was literally true. It took
place three weeks ago last Thursday just before Star Wars Episode 1
opened. So take apart any great story and there's loyalty at it's
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Corp. Cueball goes on to declare that ``one of the reasons
Shakespeare is the greatest writer of all is that he covers
absolutely everything somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Movies and TV series about the Mafia are always popular, says
Carville, because their central theme is almost always about family
loyalty. ``The new family is (the TV series) The Sopranos, a show I
like myself. David Chase, the creator, when asked why people like
these stories, was quoted as saying, ``It has to do with loyalty.
And people identify oddly with The Family, which is odd when you
think about it. But I guess someone sitting at home watching an
informer get strangled with a length of phone wire thinking, 'Yeah,
Uncle Jimmy was a bit like that.'''
</P>
<P>
   I recommend this book, even if you're a Republican. Democrats,
of course, will enjoy it even more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
