<HEADER>
A8857 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-PRINCE0519-COX     05-18 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PRINCE0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Little Prince' to look (and sound) a little different
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Harcourt Brace will be bringing out a new
translation of Antoine de Saint-Exupery's enchanting ``The Little
Prince'' this summer. The original translation dates from World War
II and was done about the time the author disappeared over the
Mediterranean. The book has been selling about 200,000 copies a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The publishers have commissioned Richard Howard to do the new
translation, and he's tried to get away from the slight stiffness
in the original (``Come, let us go look at a sunset now'') without
getting slangy.
</P>
<P>
   While they were at it, Harcourt digitally remastered
Saint-Exupery's original illustrations to clean up the grime of
nearly 60 years of printing plates.
</P>
<P>
   For loyalists, Harcourt will keep the original translation in
print for a while and will also reprint the author's other books,
while Da Capo will issue Stacy Schiff's 1994 biography.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL PUBLISHING . . .
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the loose talk about Stephen King's online short story
``Riding the Bullet,'' lost in the backwash was the fact that St.
Martin's has been trying simultaneous print and digital publication
for some time.
</P>
<P>
   At the present time, 130 St. Martin's titles are available for
downloading, among them Donald Spoto's biography of Jackie Kennedy
Onassis and a forthcoming release of a collection of short stories
by Trevanian.
</P>
<P>
   The most successful of the e-books have sold between 500 and
1,000 copies apiece, with the next most popular selling about 250
copies. St. Martin's is sufficiently encouraged as to be aiming for
simultaneous digital and paper publication for all their books.
</P>
<P>
   You'll note that these sales figures don't come close to the
400,000 copies of the King story that Simon &AMP; Schuster moved,
suggesting that the sales of ``Riding the Bullet'' had more to do
with its exclusivity and King's renown than the wrinkle of
downloading new fiction.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's sales figures indicate they're nowhere near making
any money on e-publishing, but nobody wants to have his nose
pressed against the store window if digitalization wipes out
conventional commerce in 10 years' time.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, e-publishing means a smaller overhead compared
with conventional publishing, so the conglomerates are undoubtedly
hoping for a miracle sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I am still so amazed at the brazenness of people who only
remember you when you've gone into your fourth printing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dawn Powell
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
