 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, May 19:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ The Senate is expected to vote
Thursday on a July 2001 deadline for withdrawing American ground
troops from Kosovo. The legislation is an $8.6 billion military
construction measure, which also carries $4.7 billion for U.S.
operations in Kosovo, anti-drug efforts in Colombia and other
defense programs that have been labeled emergency spending. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BUSH (Washington) _ Exploring the tension between George
W. Bush's internationalist leanings and the congressional
Republican leadership on Kosovo, fast-track and, to a lesser
extent, China trade.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ Developments on the China trade bill
pending in Congress. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA-ERITREA (Dateline to kum) _ Ethiopia captures a key
town in Eritrea; 200,000 people flee. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-U.N. (United Nations) _ The Security Council
has imposed an arms embargo on Ethiopia and Eritrea in the hope
that it will spur the two sides toward a resumption of peace talks.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE (Freetown) _ Developments in the wake of the
capture of the rebel leader. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   GENE-ALTERED-FOOD (Paris) _ Anger is expressed in Europe at the
news that some genetically modified seeds accidentally imported
from Canada have been unwittingly used by farmers. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   DOMINICAN-ELECTION (Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic) _
Developments in the presidential election: Does leftist challenger
have a majority? By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  ``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-EXPLAIN (Washington) _ An explainer on Social Security,
with particular attention to these questions: How did the pension
program get into trouble? Why is everyone talking about fixes? Will
separate accounts work? What are other ways to put the program back
on track? By Richard W. Stevesnon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ The Interior Department
releases a preliminary report on the Park Service's wisdom in
igniting a ``controlled fire'' that ended up setting much of the on
fire. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   NH-DEATH-PENALTY (Concord, N.J.) _ The New Hampshire Senate on
Thursday is expected to pass legislation, already approved by the
House, to abolish the death penalty. While the governor is expected
to veto the measure, and nobody is on death row in the state, the
move is part of a growing national reconsideration of the fairness
of capital punishment. No state has abolished the death penalty
since the Supreme Court permitted its reinstatement in 1976. By
John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   TV-DR-LAURA (Undated) _ Sponsors are pulling ads off Dr. Laura
Schlesinger's new television program becauase of her criticism of
gays.media space. By Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STRESS-WOMEN (Undated) _ A new study that reviewed dozens of
other studies suggests that women may react to stress differently
than men, using a ``tend and befriend'' response, rather than fight
or flight. Most of the studies that determined the fight or flight
response were done on males. Now, a UCLA researcher says that if
you look at females under stress, they do not just fight or flee
but first look after their children and then look to friends for
support. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTRONOMY-AGENDA (Undated) _ A panel of astronomers, whose
recommendations are often followed, unveils its 10 year plan for
astronomy, which includes construction of a new giant telescope
that would be twice as big as Hubble. The priorties for the next 10
years include looking for earth-sized planets around other suns and
launching a fleet of new xray satellites to search for black holes.
By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-TYCOONS-INTERNET (Hong Kong) _ From Taiwan to Thailand,
some of Asia's most powerful families have started a blizzard of
online ventures. Whether their core businesses are in property,
telecommunications or banking, Asia's tycoons are seizing on the
Internet in hopes of expanding their reach and making even more
money. At the same time, however, the Internet is transforming the
way business is done in East Asia. With its emphasis on speed,
openness, and collaboration, the Internet is challenging
traditional Asian values of prudence, financial opacity, and family
control. Decisions, which used to be made by the patriarch behind a
veil of secrecy, are being pushed down the ranks as Asian companies
embrace Silicon Valley-style management. So despite their
chameleon-like adaptability, Asia's tycoons may have trouble making
the leap into cyberspace, critics say. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-TECH-TALENT (Manila) _ The Philippines may be the
place that gave birth to the ``I love you'' virus that shut down
hundreds of thousands of computers around the world. But it is also
where one of the first patches to prevent the virus was developed.
Indeed, the whole episode has swung spotlight on the country's
swelling pool of high-tech talent. European and American employers
are increasingly seeking out computer savvy Filipinos. And there is
now a surprisingly lively Internet start-up scene in a country
where the average annual income is a little more than $1,000 and
where fewer than 1 percent use the Internet. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT-WORLDCOM (Washington) _ Following developments in the
Justice Department's review of Worldcom's proposed $115 billion
acquisition of Sprint. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   3M-SCOTCHGARD (Chicago) _ Followup on 3M's announcement that it
will stop making and selling most Scotchgard products because of
research that shows that a chemical ingredient lingers for years in
the environment and the human body. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly column. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   BOO-BANKRUPT (London) _ The decline and fall of Boo.com, an
online fashion sportswear retailer that opened for business just
six months ago. The collapse of Boo.com, the first major failure of
a European Web retailer, came after the company failed to secure a
further $30 million from its investors, which included J.P. Morgan,
Benetton and Bernard Arnault. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EUROPE (Undated) _ European Union antitrust investigators
raid Coca-Cola Enterprises in London and at its Belgian unit as
part of an investigation into possible abuses of dominant position
in its distribution practices. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
