<HEADER>
A8858 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-INSIDE-MARKET0518-COX     05-18 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDE-MARKET0518-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tricks of trade yield bargains in the bazaar
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The arena is the souk, or market, and the
sport is haggling, the greatest international competition outside
of soccer. The prize: some unusual something at an incredibly cheap
price.
</P>
<P>
   But few Americans know how to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if it's the great Covered Bazaar in Istanbul
or the Khan al-Khalili, the enormous market of Cairo, the ritual of
negotiation is a must and the rules are the same. Back and forth,
back and forth until a figure is agreed upon. In the right spirit,
this can be more fun than sightseeing, and you get to know your
opponents along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few tips learned the hard way:
</P>
<P>
   Before you leave home, find out the best things to buy at your
destination _ wooden masks and sculptures in Africa, 18-karat gold
jewelry in Bahrain, alexandrite in Egypt, silver in Oman, and just
about anything in the Covered Bazaar in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, look like a tourist of impecunious means, a
struggling archeologist at best. Wear dusty and worn clothing and
no jewelry. Vendors are quick to notice an American's expensive
jogging shoes and watch.
</P>
<P>
   Go to a store where prices are fixed, and see how much things
cost before you go to a market. In Istanbul, go to a big carpet
store and pay attention to free demonstrations of how to tell a
hand-made from machine-made rug, then go to the bazaar or a
small-town market and buy a rug for much less.
</P>
<P>
   A good rule of thumb is to offer a third of the price and don't
go much beyond half. On rare occasions, it's worth it to go higher
for something that would be valuable back in the states.
</P>
<P>
   Keep various amounts of small bills in different pockets. If you
have $5 worth of currency in one pocket and the item you want is
$15, pull out the bills and say ``this is all I have.'' It cuts out
a lot of haggling time.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get emotionally involved. Salesmen often will try to make
you feel guilty. ``I showed you all of this and now you won't
buy,'' they'll say with hurt verging on disgust. Don't fall for it.
He showed it to you, you didn't like it and now you want to see
something else.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be bulldozed by someone shouting at you. Well-mannered
American women, particularly those stepping off tour buses at
tourist attractions, are prime prey. If they see you as a weakling,
they'll try to bully you. Tune out the hawking and concentrate on
the wares.
</P>
<P>
   If you really want something, don't show it. Keep easing out the
door until you get your price.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be afraid to leave if you and the seller hit a deadlock;
you can always come back. It's a good way to see how serious he is
about the price.
</P>
<P>
   Decide quickly what you will pay for the item. Street salesmen
are quick to take advantage of indecision.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want something, just say no. Do not say, ``No, it's
the wrong color,'' or ``No, it's too expensive.'' The seller thinks
this means yes. Say no and walk on.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about the salesman's family, his business and town. This
won't help you get a better price, but you'll learn a lot about the
people you came to visit, which is really more important than what
you buy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
