<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8861 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-ON-THE-BEACH-ART     05-18 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-ON-THE-BEACH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO THE BEACH: A NUCLEAR NIGHTMARE REVISITED 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Bryan Brown,
Rachel Ward and Armand Assante in scenes from ``On the Beach.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's 2006, and a nuclear holocaust has wiped out human life in
virtually the entire world. Only in Australia do people still
survive, playing out the string in a bleak countdown until trade
winds carry the deadly radiation their way, spelling the inevitable
end for the human race.
 &HT;    Sound familiar? It should.
 &HT;    In 1959 producer/director Stanley Kramer and an all-star cast
that included Ava Gardner, Gregory Peck and Fred Astaire brought
the same story _ Nevil Shute's novel ``On the Beach'' (1957) _ to
the big screen. Now Showtime cable network is updating the tale in
a three-hour-long movie that will air on May 28.
 &HT;    This time around, Armand Assante has the Peck role, Australian
actor Bryan Brown steps in for Astaire and Rachel Ward _ Brown's
real-life wife _ has the daunting task of making us forget Ava
Gardner's performance as Moira Davidson, the Australian adventuress
searching for true love as the curtain falls on the human race.
 &HT;    Shute wrote his novel in 1956, at the height of the Cold War.
The United States and the Soviet Union were nose-to-nose in a
nuclear stalemate, as American kids practiced safety drills in
their classrooms while their parents built concrete fallout
shelters in their backyards. The end of the world was a common
collective nightmare, even before the Cuban missile crisis of 1962
made it an any-minute-now scenario.
 &HT;    But surely times have changed. Nowadays the world is at peace,
so why reinvent this dark tale of gloom and doom?
 &HT;    ``Ninety percent of the time I keep the thought in my head that
it can't possibly happen and this is a nice old tale,'' says Jerry
Offsay, president of programming for Showtime. ``But unfortunately
I wake up and read that bombs are in the hands of the Russian
republics that don't have enough money and are thinking of selling
them to (accused terrorist Osama) Bin Ladn. And I read about China
stealing nuclear secrets.
 &HT;    ``So we believe this story is still relevant today,'' he says,
``and that this is the ultimate cautionary tale, hopefully
incredibly unlikely but clearly plausible.''
 &HT;    This time out the nuclear exchange is between the United States
and China, triggered by a crisis over Taiwan. Australian
screenwriter David Williamson, who wrote ``Gallipoli'' (l981) and
``The Year of Living Dangerously'' (l982), centers the story around
a love triangle which poises Moira between cynical Aussie scientist
Julian Osborne (Brown) and Dwight Towers (Assante), commander of an
American submarine, who has steered his vessel into Melbourne and
placed it under Australian command.
 &HT;    Towers and Osborne are then assigned to a desperate mission to
track down a faint radio signal that has been picked up from
Anchorage, Alaska. Are there survivors up north, or is it a cruel
red herring?
 &HT;    The story is less about that last-chance mission than it is
about the way in which the central characters have to learn to face
death, in their own ways and with their own senses of dignity.
 &HT;    Which is, of course, the point. Faced with the daunting task of
getting audiences to spend more than three hours watching the
ultimate in depressing tales, the producers opted for uplift over
despair.
 &HT;    ``The thing that made me want to tell this story was not the
fear of nuclear holocaust,'' says Brown, the Sydney-based actor who
has been involved in the remake for nearly a decade. ``For me,
that's the backdrop against which the human spirit thrives in this
state. This is a real positive story about how three people at the
end of the human race have to come to a decision about how they are
going to end those last days and what the end of the race means to
them. And they sort of come to it with massive dignity.
 &HT;    ``And I believe that the human spirit at its best is so
wonderfully dignified,'' he says. ``For me, this is a very positive
story.''
 &HT;    Throughout, the remake is gripping. Though the subject matter is
the ultimate nightmare and some of the scenes are heartbreaking,
once you start watching you won't be able to stop.
 &HT;    Needless to say, dealing with such profound issues led to a good
deal of soul-searching among the cast and crew during the weeks of
location filming in Australia.
 &HT;    ``It was the subject of conversation the whole time,'' Ward
says. ``What would you do in this situation? How would you choose
to lead what's left of your life? Would you go somewhere with your
family? Would you carry on as usual? Would you live in denial? What
would you do?''
 &HT;    Not everyone faces the end with dignity. There are harrowing
scenes of rampant lawlessness in the streets of Melbourne, as
society begins to come apart at the seams. Looting, killings and
sexual excess are rampant, while long lines of people wait to pick
up the poison kits that will let them end their lives when the
ravages of radiation sickness set in.
 &HT;    The end of the world finds people behaving as they always have,
in short, only more so.
 &HT;    ``Those who firmly believe in contributing to society and
maintaining civilized behavior would adhere to that to the very
end, I think,'' Brown says. ``There would be a willingness among
many to surrender life before abandoning morality and decency.''
 &HT;    The most decent of the decent here is Towers, who has lost
everything he holds dear _ his wife, his family and his faith in
his country. Having been part of the nuclear war machine which
ultimately brought about disaster, he struggles with a unique sense
of personal guilt.
 &HT;    ``To reconcile with his conscience, with his shame, he must
admit he was an accomplice in a terrible sin,'' Assante says
thoughtfully. ``He must accept that all of it was wrong. But once
that's done, how does he, how does anyone move on from that
dangerous precipice? How do you forgive yourself for your sins and
find a way to believe again in love and hope and redemption?''
 &HT;    That's a question which didn't go out of style with the Cold War
... and, Ward adds, the Cold War itself isn't as dead as some
people would like to think it is.
 &HT;    ``I think we all live in subconscious fear of something going
wrong with the world's nuclear arsenal,'' she says. ``This movie is
a poignant, timely wake-up call. Let us not forget _ this threat
exists.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``On the Beach,'' consult the
Showtime Web site at www.sho.com. And don't forget to visit The New
York Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate
for information on Hollywood Stars and other features. &QL; 
