<HEADER>
A8863 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-NOISE-SFCHRON &LR;      05-18 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOISE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Restaurant Workers' Hearing at Risk: Tests show that for those  who
work long shifts, the clatter's the matter  By Miriam Morgan 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Noisy restaurants may harm the hearing of their
employees, according to a new study by two University of California
at San Francisco audiologists.
<P>
   The researchers found that bartenders, servers and other wait
staff who spend eight hours at a time in noisy restaurants _ those
with decibel levels of 85 or higher _ may be at the same risk of
hearing loss as those who work in noisy factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noise levels can be high enough at peak hours so that workers
need to be taking hearing conservation measures,'' said UCSF
Director of Audiology Robert Sweetow, who is co-author of the study
with staff audiologist Lisa Tate. The report appears in the current
issue of Audiology Today.
</P>
<P>
   Diners do not run the same risk because they do not spend enough
time in noisy restaurants, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetow and Tate measured the noise levels of five San Francisco
restaurants for an hour using an instrument that allowed the
researchers to extrapolate the measurements to eight hours. The
restaurants, which the researchers did not name, ranged from 50.5
decibels to 90.1 decibels. The highest levels at any one time
ranged from 85.5 to 109.8 decibels.
</P>
<P>
   The California Office of Safety and Health Administration
restricts noise levels at industrial sites and factories to 90
decibels in an eight-hour shift. Workers cannot spend more than two
hours a day in a place where noise reaches 100 decibels.
</P>
<P>
   There are no such regulations for restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Health-related hazards are nothing new for restaurant workers.
Until smoking was banned five years ago, many workers complained
about the dangers of secondhand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, concerns about noisy restaurants have surged.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '90s, restaurateurs and architects say they began to
pay more attention to noise levels. And two years ago, The
Chronicle began measuring restaurant noise levels and including the
levels as regular components of dining reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The first wave of concern centered on diners, but now, the
audiologists say, workers should start to be aware of their
surroundings, too.
</P>
<P>
   Because servers cannot do their job wearing earplugs, Sweetow
suggests that workers in high-decibel environments take five- to
10-minute breaks each hour. That alone can provide significant
relief.
</P>
<P>
   But finding a way to step off the floor every hour simply is not
practical, some waiters and managers counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is physically impossible to schedule those sorts of
breaks,'' said Evan Chevalier, manager at LuLu (which measured last
June at more than 80 decibels _ one of the noisiest restaurants in
San Francisco). ``You can't tell a table their waiter is out taking
his decibel-reduction break.''
</P>
<P>
   Most waiters at LuLu work four- to six-hour shifts a day, he
said, and routinely get a break from the noise by stepping into the
back for a glass of water.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hill, co-owner of the new Mission Street restaurant Dine,
admits that noise can be a problem, but points out that his
employees already take frequent breaks and work short shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a closed kitchen. It is quiet in there. And that's
where they do all their ordering and hang out.'' Plus, he said, the
peak noise time is relatively short _ generally from 7 to 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hill is taking measures to lessen the noise level of his
restaurant (it measured between 75 and 80 decibels last month). He
has added foam padding under each table to absorb the sound bounced
back from the floor, and new acoustic ceiling panels are being
installed in July.
</P>
<P>
   At Garibaldis cq no apostrophe  &LR; on College (which measured 75 to
80 decibels in 1998), bartender cq  &LR; Suriyan Edwards said he and
other staff deal with bursts of intense noise by ducking into a
small room where the wine is stored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quiet in there,'' said Edwards during a post-lunch lull
at the Oakland restaurant yesterday. He said the noise has not
caused him any pain or hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   Co-owner Ann Hurley says none of her employees have complained
about noise-related health problems and said that the highest noise
levels come during the height of the lunch and dinner crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst time is from 7 to 8 p.m.,'' she said. ``And then it
just dies.''
</P>
<P>
   Cass Calder Smith, a San Francisco architect who designed LuLu,
Black Cat, Rose Pistola and the new Azie, also points out that
owners and designers are becoming more sensitive to the noise
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's clear that acoustics matter, and clients are willing
to spend more money on keeping noise levels comfortable,'' he said.
He points to the increased use of carpeting, and new materials like
fiberglass acoustical ceiling panels that can be custom-painted to
blend in with the design.
</P>
<P>
   At Azie, his latest restaurant (which measured at 75 to 80
decibels in February), live DJs and a powerful sound system that
can be adjusted for different parts of the restaurant provide
distraction from the usual clatter. But it also adds to the overall
noise level.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, noise is the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noise creates the atmosphere,'' said Azie General Manager
Joseph Hargrave. ``And I notice the servers really pick up when the
music is going.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Chronicle staff writers Michael Collier and Kim Severson &LR; 
 &LR; contributed to this report. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
