<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8864 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0519-CO     05-18 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    Music to paint by, and wise avoidance of auto repair
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I took off a few days recently to catch up
on honey-do's around the house: touching up woodwork inside and
out, washing windows, doing yard work and minor repairs. The first
order of business was to find appropriate music by which to paint.
</P>
<P>
   That's important. Music is absolutely necessary for painting,
which is a mindless activity that requires patience, some skill and
a high tolerance for noxious fumes.
</P>
<P>
   I made a part-time living in college as a painter, one of many
offbeat jobs I held to keep the wolves from the door. I delivered
pizzas, worked as a dog catcher, movie projectionist, unloaded
grain from a rail car, swept up chicken feet at a processing plant,
cooked steaks, spent another month working at a hatchery making the
daily run to the landfill with 55-gallon drums filled with baby
chicks deemed unfit to live, ran a record store and shot wedding
pictures. Usually I held more than one part-time job at a time.
Sounds hard now, but it didn't seem so at the time. My GPA suffered
but not enough to matter.
</P>
<P>
   The older I get the less willing I am to hire someone to perform
a task I can do myself. This is not because I am a skinflint. Far
from it. But I figure the money I save by mowing my own yard,
painting the trim, or cleaning the carpet can be spent to buy a
cool tool for the woodshop, maybe a few CDs, or another book.
</P>
<P>
   There are several areas that are strictly off limits. Plumbing
is one of them. Every time I have attempted a plumbing repair, it
has ended up costing me more than if I had called the plumber in
the first place. The other day, the garbage disposal was hung up.
Turned out three pennies were jammed inside. Not real complicated,
but it means each penny will cost about $15 by the time I pay the
service call. How three pennies, now rather mangled, got into the
garbage disposal is beyond me. Children are likely the key culprit.
They're always guilty of something.
</P>
<P>
   I'm willing to dabble in electricity to a limited extent. I can
install a ceiling fan, replace a light switch or wall outlet, but
anything more complicated than that requires someone with a
license. Electricity bites.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mess with cars, since I attempted to change the oil in
my 1978 Toyota 20 years ago and unwittingly drained the
transmission fluid instead. The first clue should have been when I
went to fill the crankcase back up with oil and it would hardly
take a quart. The second clue came when the transmission blew up
about 50 miles later. The result: A $600 lesson that God did not
intend me to be an auto mechanic, money that would have paid for
approximately 40 professionally done oil changes at 1980 prices.
</P>
<P>
   Chainsaws make me nervous. I am willing to cut down small trees
that have no chance of falling on anything important. But ever
since I worked at the Round Rock newspaper with the man who wrote
the screenplay to the ``Texas Chainsaw Massacre,'' I have not felt
the same way about chainsaws, which is the national tool of Deep
East Texas. Any tree bigger in circumference than a baseball bat is
best left to professionals.
</P>
<P>
   But stick a paint brush in my hand, and I'm heck on wheels,
honest genes from being the oldest son of a sign painter. But the
music has to be just right. For the latest foray, the soundtrack to
``Phantom of the Opera'' was perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Since no one was home but me, I cranked the sound up to
mega-decibel levels and drifted back a few years. It was a magical
night spent with my daughters in London watching a live performance
the day after after having toured the original Opera Garnier in
Paris, which formed the setting for the original book.
</P>
<P>
   I listened to the two-hour set twice, and the time flew. So did
the paint. Luckily, there are several products on the market that
clean up latex paint if it ends up in the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   Now I've returned to work with everything crossed off my list of
to-do projects. No doubt a new list is being compiled as we speak.
It's good to be able to relax again.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
