A8865 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0519-CO     05-18 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nader at it again for the Green Party
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ This time, according to Ralph Nader and the
Green Party, he's serious.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, the consumer advocate who forced Chevrolet to kill off
the Corvair automobile back in the 1960s, made a half-hearted run
for the presidency four years ago as a favor to the Green Party
folks. He said he'd spend no more than $5,000 and didn't campaign
much.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, 66, got less than 1 percent of the vote for his effort.
But this year, Nader is going all-out. He's raising money. He's
trying to get enough support to qualify for federal matching money,
which requires raising $5,000 in each of 20 states in contributions
of less than $250. He's even going out and making speeches, as he
did during a Texas swing in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party's message, Nader told a crowd in Austin, is
``very simple. It's to make the sovereignty of people over the
sovereignty of global corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he expect to win? No, if moving into the White House next
January is the goal.
</P>
<P>
   But Nader hopes to make enough of a ruckus charging that both
the Republican and Democratic parties are lackeys for corporate fat
cats that he can elbow into the presidential debates. There, he'd
stress the Green Party's environmental and other issues, such as
universal health care, public financing of elections and a living
wage. He says Microsoft honcho Bill Gates alone makes more money
than America's 120 million poorest folks.
</P>
<P>
   Nader and his backers will campaign in all 50 states and hope to
get on the ballot in at least 45. So far, they've qualified for 16
states. If Green Party candidates do well enough, they can get
automatic ballot status in some states for the next election. And a
5 percent showing nationally would give the party's nominee federal
matching money in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Ann McGeehan, director of elections for the Texas Secretary of
State's office, said the party must gather petition signatures from
37,380 registered voters who did not vote in this year's party
primary elections to qualify for the Texas ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens couldn't start collecting signatures until after the
March 14 party primary elections, and the petitions must be
submitted to the secretary of state by May 30. Party leaders hope
to get at least 60,000 signatures to be sure they have enough valid
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying for ballot status in Texas would allow the Greens to
field candidates in any race. The party hopes to field candidates
for four statewide offices.
</P>
<P>
   Getting more than 5 percent of the vote in any of those races
would automatically qualify the party to be on the ballot in 2002.
And they stand a good chance in at least three _ two Railroad
Commission seats and a Supreme Court seat _ where Democrats fielded
no candidates against Republican incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   While the Green Party might not have a huge effect on the
presidential election in Texas, where Gov. George W. Bush is the
Republican nominee and expected to win handily, Nader and the
Greens could cut into Democratic nominee Al Gore's lead in
all-important states such as California, where the Greens hold
three dozen local offices.
</P>
<P>
   Nader isn't the only person vying for the Green Party
nomination, to be decided at the party's convention in Denver on
June 24-25. Others interested include Jello Biafra, former lead
singer of the rock group The Dead Kennedys, who ran unsuccessfully
for mayor of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
