<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-TOURISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TOURISM REMAINS ROBUST IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNY STRASBURG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco continues to attract affluent
travelers as the city also reaps benefits from rebounding Asian
economies, according to survey results released by the San
Francisco Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   One in 10 hotel guests in San Francisco last year reported a
household income above $190,000, the bureau's latest numbers show.
The city's leisure travelers, who stay in hotels as well as with
friends and relatives, report average incomes of about $63,000
compared with the $50,000 national average.
</P>
<P>
   And to put overall visitor spending in perspective: On any given
day in 1999, there were about 146,000 out-of-town visitors in San
Francisco. Over the course of the year, they collectively spent
about $8,300 for every San Francisco resident, the bureau's study
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is San Francisco's top revenue-generating industry,
pouring $6.55 billion into the economy last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, hotel occupancy has been climbing steadily in San
Francisco even considering the addition of thousands of rooms in
the region. There are 31,101 rooms in the city, according to the
bureau.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, San Francisco had a record 80.7 percent hotel occupancy
rate, continuing its track record of topping the national average
by anywhere from 3 percentage points to 9 percent percentage
points, depending on the month, said David Bratton, marketing
research manager for the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel guests spent about $233 per day, including on the cost of
the hotel, with rooms averaging $155 per night.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau President John Marks said the single greatest challenge
facing San Francisco's tourism industry is expanding the runways at
San Francisco International Airport, a hotly contested issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are absolutely adamant about the reconfiguring of
runways,'' Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's telephone and hotel guest surveys highlighted
several other points:
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1999, visitor volume rose 1.6 percent over 1998, to 16.8
million travelers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Visitor spending stayed flat; a decrease in spending by
day-trip visitors from the San Francisco Bay Area was offset by an
increase in what hotel guests spent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Out-of-area visitors brought San Francisco its bacon: Those
travelers accounted for $5 billion out of the $6.55 billion in
total spending.
</P>
<P>
   _ About 57 percent of visitors were male and 43 percent female,
influenced by the male-dominated meeting and convention business,
bureau officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1420EDT &QL; 
