A8883 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     05-18 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH-SAVVY BOOK OFFERS VETERANS, ROOKIES A GUIDE TO INVESTING
ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LILA LAHOOD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fast-paced growth of new technologies, combined with low
unemployment and a vibrant economy, have bolstered interest in the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much new about the buying and selling of shares, but
the advent of the Internet has heightened the average investor's
savvy about specific companies and industries and the economy as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, the stream of technical jargon and broker
lingo can be intimidating. What many people are looking for is a
secure way to participate in this fast-paced field and a chance to
benefit from some of the big gains.
</P>
<P>
   Whether investors choose to work with a traditional broker or
trade electronically, the bounty of financial news and research
available online is an asset to be exploited.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Markman's ``Online Investing'' (Microsoft Press, 352 pages,
$24.99) offers clues to using those tools. Markham caters to the
veteran investor who lacks online experience and the tech-savvy
stock market rookie.
</P>
<P>
   For either kind of investor, Markman notes, choosing the right
stocks at the right time will never be effortless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job isn't as easy as doing nothing,'' Markman writes.
``But the digital age has improved and simplified few spins of the
life cycle more than the task of investing. I'd argue that human
relationships aren't better on the Net, and neither are sports,
art, or religion. Yet finding and rapidly assimilating financial
acumen is the kind of computational endeavor that is actually
better accomplished on the Internet than on paper, on the
telephone, or in person.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the ideas he covers are the basic how-to's of investing.
But the advantage is that he takes those fundamentals and shows
investors how to use them to make better decisions by sifting the
wealth of financial information available online.
</P>
<P>
   Markman offers detailed descriptions of several model
portfolios, including momentum models, growth investing models and
value investing models.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know what those are, don't worry. Markman explains
the various risk and benefit factors in a clear, easy-to-read
style.
</P>
<P>
   Markman, managing editor for the MSN MoneyCentral Investor Web
site and former executive news editor at the Los Angeles Times,
uses the MoneyCentral site in most examples using stock screening
engines and generating models. Readers should remember that other
sites are available.
</P>
<P>
   Markman guides readers through various ways of researching
stocks online. He gives concise reviews of several news and
financial sites, as well as newsletters, online bulletin boards and
chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   A section on finding Securities and Exchange Commission
documents online also gives readers clues about mining the often
weighty and cumbersome documents for useful information. He even
includes a clever tip on how to use a simple word-processing
program to pinpoint changes in second versions of multipage
filings.
</P>
<P>
   For prospective investors who are looking for more in-depth
analysis, Markman reviews the full range of quantitative measures
used to gauge company performance and stock values.
</P>
<P>
   He also discusses the role of analysts and which firms post
their reports online.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes time to buy, Markman offers several ways to
manage a model-based stock portfolio depending on the amount of
time the investor wants to spend tracking the market _ ranging from
a few hours a year to daily review.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
