A8892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NEWKITCHEN-TIPS-SUB-C     05-18 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWKITCHEN-TIPS-SUB-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION FOOD EDITORS
</P>
<P>
   Please do not use NEWKITCHEN-TIPS that was moved by Cox News
Service on Wednesday, May 17 for release on Thursday, May 18. The
text below subs for the original type and should be used instead.
If you have questions or need additional information, contact Cox
News Service in Atlanta at 404 526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   CLEANUP TIPS
</P>
<P>
   1. Plastic (polyethelene) cutting boards are more sanitary
because they are more impervious and you can put them in the
dishwasher. _ Marie Rama, co-author, ``Cooking for Dummies''
</P>
<P>
   2. Sanitize hardwood cutting boards from time to time by heating
in the microwave 60 seconds on high._ ``What Great Chefs Know That
You Don't''
</P>
<P>
   3. When wrapping leftovers, the hardest part is getting the
plastic wrap off the roll in a flat, smooth piece. It helps to
store the box of plastic wrap in the refrigerator. _ ``What Great
Chefs Know That You Don't''
</P>
<P>
   4. Keep a box of facial tissues near the stove to wipe up small
spills. They are quicker and cheaper than paper towels. _ Diana
Sturgis, quoted in ``1,001 Secrets of Great Cooks''
</P>
<P>
   5. If your lasagna spills over onto the oven floor, sprinkle
with salt, lift out what you can with a metal spatula and wipe the
rest with a sponge. _ James Beard, quoted in ``1,001 Secrets of
Great Cooks''
</P>
<P>
   6. Small self-closing plastic bags help with cleanup and
storage. Use them to soften butter or chocolate in a bowl of hot
water. Remove, knead until mixed, then remove from the bag by
snipping a small opening in one corner and squeezing out. They are
also indispensable for storage of small amounts of leftover tomato
paste or chopped onions or peppers.
</P>
<P>
   7. Clean as you go _ keep sink full of warm, soapy water and
pause once in a while to wash up.
</P>
<P>
   8. If you don't want to keep the sink tied up with soapy water,
wash items individually with one of the detergent-filled brushes.
</P>
<P>
   9. Line roasting pans with aluminum foil for easier cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   10. If your oven is not self-cleaning, try this: Preheat oven to
200 degrees, then turn oven off. Pour (apple) cup ammonia into a
small bowl and place on the center shelf of the oven. Close door
and allow to remain overnight. Open a window, then open oven door
and air out for 30 minutes. Wipe up the mess with warm, damp paper
towels.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``10,001 Food Facts, Chefs' Secrets &AMP; Household Hints''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
