<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8906 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES19-CO     05-18 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fate, dangerous vocation bring sorrow for the Pettys
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In their lifetimes, Lee, Richard and Kyle Petty,
grandfather, father and son, drove, or have driven, in 2,191 NASCAR
automobile races. In his lifetime, Adam, son, grandson and
great-grandson, drove in one. When he died last month, Lee Petty
was 86 years old. When Adam died on the track at Loudon, N.H., last
week, he was 19. Of such is the capriciousness of tragedy, of such
is the injustice of death.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Petty was the past, the foundation of stock-car racing's
model family. Adam Petty was the future, a loss not just to racing
alone, but to man in general, for he was as straight-laced as they
come, clear-eyed, clear-headed, ``a lad of mettle, a good boy,'' as
Shakespeare wrote it. Born to be the next ``King,'' succeeding to
the title held by the grandfather Richard.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is no more but in spirit, erased from this earth in the
most foul of fates.
</P>
<P>
   In time, these old eyes have seen one Petty or another suffer
through a series of horrendous crashes on the track. In June of
1949, I watched Lee Petty drive in the first NASCAR race ever run,
at a crude oval gouged out of red dirt, with jerrybuilt stands and
the fancy name of Charlotte Motor Speedway. One publication
reported that he finished 17th. He never finished.
</P>
<P>
   He had driven to the race in the family Buick from the home near
Randleman, not with sons Richard and Maurice, as in another report.
``I had two buddies along to help in the pits,'' he said a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the family Buick failed, he came to rest on a little rise
across the track, opened the door and sat there in a pose similar
to Rodin's ``The Thinker.'' Asked also years later what he had been
so deep in thought about at the time, he answered, ``I was thinking
what I was going to tell my wife where I'd been when I got home.''
</P>
<P>
   The seed was sown. The Pettys were rooted in racing. Twice, Lee
would win the national championship before there was a Winston Cup.
Seven times, Richard would win it. He was the first driver whose
winnings totaled a million dollars. It was a cause for celebration,
in 1974, if memory serves, after 15 years of hard riding. Now, they
let that much money slip through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   One time, at old Lakewood Speedway, Richard thought he had won
his first race, but crusty old dad roared into Victory Lane, such
as it was, beside him and challenged the scoring. Lee had it right.
Richard had to wait another day to win the first of his 200.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's career came to an end when he went over the wall at
Daytona in 1961. Miraculously, he survived, and, after four months
in a hospital, tried to drive only six more times. He then hung it
up and turned to bossing Petty Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Richard became the star: ``King Richard.'' It was a money-making
amalgamation.
</P>
<P>
   Richard's flirtations with death were many. He had a serious
crackup at the present Lowe's Motor Speedway and suffered a broken
shoulder. He has been upside down at Darlington. Twice in his last
season, he came hurtling down the stretch, at Daytona and Atlanta,
in a ball of flames, his car disintegrating, pieces of metal flying
in the air. Again, fate was on his side. No serious injury. The
message was there, though, and he gracefully retired while still in
one piece.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle's career has been less victorious, with his many
distracting ventures, and Adam became his project, not that the kid
needed much pushing. ``All I ever wanted to be is a race driver,''
he said in a television interview. ``I wouldn't know what to do in
real life.''
</P>
<P>
   The warm, beautiful smile was there. Sincerity etched in the
boyish face. Not many brothers would let a 14-year-old sister cut
his hair, which he did before Montgomery Lee left for England with
her dad for an equestrian event. It was on that journey that the
devastating news reached Kyle and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Losing a son in the prime of life is a crushing blow, and I can
speak to that. To lose a bright, wonderful, well-mannered son just
beginning to blossom in his father's image, is deeper than
heartbreak. Death has no conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Making headlines
</P>
<P>
   The future of Petty Enterprises: No one is sure how Adam Petty's
death will affect the future of Petty Enterprises, which has been
the biggest name in racing since NASCAR was founded. Richard Petty
already had moved out of the picture earlier this season. Kyle has
had a solid Winston Cup career, but he's spent the last three years
splitting time between his own driving and overseeing Adam's
blossoming career. Kyle says he won't run in The Winston this week
and will make a decision on the Charlotte 600 later.
</P>
<P>
   Bet the house on Humpy Wheeler: Lowe's Motor Speedway President
Humpy Wheeler has predicted the winner of The Winston eight times
in the last 12 years. This year, Dale Earnhardt Jr. is the choice.
``Some people may think I'm going way out on a limb, but The
Winston is the type of race that was made for Earnhardt Jr.,''
Wheeler explained. ``It's a no-holds barred, stand-on-the-gas race
that fits perfectly with his mentality and his driving style.''
Dale Jr. is not a surprise pick, considering he is the only driver
to win two races on the major-league circuit this season.
</P>
<P>
   Another penalty for ``bad'' gas: The funny gas continues to show
up in NASCAR, despite the strict penalty handed to Jeremy
Mayfield's team for rules violations. Chevy No. 3 crew chief David
Lackey and owner Ken Alexander were penalized for using
``unapproved'' fuel at the Richmond Busch race.
</P>
<P>
   An interview with Johnny Benson
</P>
<P>
   By Rick Minter
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last season, Johnny Benson gave up a ride in a
Roush Racing team car to drive for a relatively new team, Tyler Jet
Motorsports. Some questioned the move, but Benson nearly won the
Daytona 500 in his first points race in the No. 10 Pontiac. He is
21st in points with one top-5 and two top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you ever have second thoughts about leaving Roush Racing
to drive for an unproven team?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. I knew I needed to make a change. It ended up being a
pretty good situation. I had been over and walked through Tyler
Jet's shop a couple of times and it was a pretty nice place. They
were doing a lot of quality work over there.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've driven for multi-car teams and now a one-car
organization. What size team is best?
</P>
<P>
   A: Two-car teams are the best scenario. Two can work together
without too many conflicts. I'm not opposed to more than two, but
two is the best.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you hope to have accomplished at the end of this
season?
</P>
<P>
   A: You always hope you can win a race _ that's what this sport
is about. We hope to finish in the top 10 in points. It's going to
be awfully hard after missing the race at Atlanta, but it's still a
goal and we'll try to reach it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do the rules for determining provisional starting posititions
need to be changed?
</P>
<P>
   A: It depends on which side of the fence you're on. Being 11th
in points at Atlanta and having to go home is a pretty tough deal,
but you know the rules going in. At that point in the season,
provisionals were based on last year's points, and I wasn't there,
and it was the team's first full year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are your thoughts on the death of Adam Petty?
</P>
<P>
   A: To have someone so young with such a bright future ahead of
him die like this is a hard thing to swallow. My dad raced, and
that's how I got into this sport. It's hard to explain why we love
racing, and at times like this it's even harder. It's so rare for
this to happen in NASCAR because they have made the cars so safe in
recent years. Sometimes you get lulled into thinking it can never
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
