<HEADER>
A8911 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-CAR-NASCAR-WINSTON19-     05-18 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-WINSTON19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Winston: NASCAR'S all-star gala
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASCAR and Winston officials do everything in their power to
make The Winston all-star race one of the most exciting events of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The non-points race Saturday night in Concord, N.C., features
the top drivers on the Winston Cup circuit. As racing officials
have done in past years, the rules have been changed to encourage
more competition at Lowe's Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we all have to remember that we're in the
entertainment business, and as much as we'd like to be selfish in
the way we run races or whatever, the end result needs to be great
entertainment,'' Mark Martin said. ``And that's what we're able to
give 'em in The Winston.''
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Winston has increased the purse more than 30
percent to a grand total of $2 million. The winner will get a
minimum check of $500,000 and could make more through various
bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston has also changed its rules on qualifying because of
the rash of injuries on pit row this season. In past years, drivers
earned their qualifying positions based on the total time of three
laps, which included one four-tire pit stop after the first or
second lap.
</P>
<P>
   This year, drivers will begin qualifying with a two-tire change
and then complete three consecutive laps in the unique time trials.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen drivers, including race winners from 1999 and this
season's first 11 races, already have made the field for the big
event. The final two spots in the 20-car field will be determined
in two qualifying races.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of The Winston Open will earn a spot in the all-star
race. The Winston Open has been reduced from 50 to 30 laps,
honoring the lengthy partnership (30 years) between NASCAR and its
primary sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Racing officials also have come up with another way of
qualifying one more driver. Here's how: Those who finish on the
lead lap of The Winston Open _ other than the winner _ will earn a
spot in the No Bull Sprint. The new qualifying race lasts 16 laps.
</P>
<P>
   The main event is basically the same as past years: 20 drivers
will compete in three segments of 30, 30 and 10 laps. The only new
wrinkle is that NASCAR will use a complicated formula after the
first segment to determine whether or not to invert the order of
the top 12 finishing cars.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston's greatest moments ...
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The last lap of the 1992 Winston race was the defining moment.
A live TNN television audience watched in disbelief as Kyle Petty
in the No. 42 Mello Yello SABCO Pontiac battled Dale Earnhardt in
the No. 3 Goodwrench Chevrolet down the backstretch on the last lap
at Charlotte Motor Speedway. Going into turn three, Earnhardt slid
up the track and spun, forcing Petty to back off just enough to
allow Davey Allison in the No. 28 Havoline Ford to pull even coming
off turn four. They were wheel-to-wheel at the finish with Allison
taking the victory by a foot.
</P>
<P>
   Just past the start-finish line , Allison and Petty made
contact, forcing the No. 28 into the outside retaining wall and
into a shower of sparks. Allison's wrecked No. 28 went to victory
lane as he was transported to a local hospital. He returned to race
the next week in the Coca-Cola 600.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The 1987 running of The Winston is best remembered for the
``pass in the grass.'' Just one problem. It wasn't a pass. The
maneuver was actually a defensive move by Earnhardt. Bill Elliott
sat on the pole and dominated the first 125 laps of what was then a
two-segment all-star event. Earnhardt, who hit nearly every car on
the track that day, took over on lap 126 and held on for the final
10 laps. It was during this last 10-lap sprint that he ran all the
way into the grass in the dogleg to hold off Elliott, who was
driving the No. 9 Coors Ford. On the cool-down lap, Elliott pulled
alongside Earnhardt and turned hard into the Goodwrench Chevrolet
to show his disgust at the No. 3 car; but the Intimidator enjoyed
the spoils of victory _ the $200,000 winner's check.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The 1995 Winston ushered in NASCAR's new guard. A young Jeff
Gordon in the No. 24 DuPont Chevrolet already was having success in
his third full season. Veterans Darrell Waltrip and Earnhardt
started on the front row of the final 10-lap segment with Gordon
behind on the inside of row two. The two veterans raced
side-by-side on the first lap of the final segment until they hit
turn three. Waltrip went into the corner too hot in his No. 17
Western Auto Chevrolet and slid up into Earnhardt, forcing both
cars into the outside wall. Gordon drove to the bottom of the track
and was able to hold off Sterling Marlin for the victory in the
final 10 laps. This race marked the start of the special paint
scheme era. Earnhardt's Chevy had a thank-you note to Winston
adorning the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   ... and The Winston's lamest moments
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In 1990, Earnhardt led all 70 laps and finished .34 seconds
ahead of Ken Schrader, who was driving the Hendrick Motorsports No.
25 Kodiak Chevrolet. The day race had no lead changes. Several race
fans were spotted bringing out the cots for this snoozer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In 1991, Allison had the field covered and then some. Like
Earnhardt in 1990, he led every lap and finished 2.87 seconds in
front of Schrader. The cots resurfaced for this sleeper. Two
blowouts in a row in The Winston left the hierarchy scrambling to
make changes before the 1992 event. For starters, it was moved to
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
