<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8916 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-VOTERS-REAGAN-$ADV21-     05-18 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTERS-REAGAN-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR REAGAN DEMOCRATS, ONE LAST CHANCE TO MAKE A DIFFERENCE
 &HT;    840&AMP;add. For release Sunday, May 21.
 &HT;    With photos.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSEVILLE, Mich. _ The 2000 presidential campaign is likely to
be the last hurrah of the ``Reagan Democrats,'' the fabled swing
voters in the battleground states of the industrial Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are, quite literally, dying off,'' said Ed Sarpolus, head
of a Lansing, Mich., polling firm, EPIC-MRA. ``But they're still a
force. And while they still lean slightly Democrat, Al Gore is
going to have to battle George Bush for every one of their votes.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle this fall will be for the votes of the children and
grandchildren, too, because the progeny are just as weak in their
party allegiance as the original Reagan Democrats. ``You now have
two more generations that have grown up in households that taught
by example, switching back and forth from party to party,'' said
Sarpolus.
</P>
<P>
   As the political label suggests, the self-described Reagan
Democrats came to prominence _ that is, to the attention of
campaign strategists and pollsters _ with the election of Ronald
Reagan in 1980 and his re-election in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Reagan Democrats were Catholic,
blue-collar, middle-class union families, once a core constituency
of the Democratic Party, largely in the industrial states of
Pennsylvania, Ohio, Illinois and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   But they began to drift away in the late 1960s amid growing
cynicism about government and perceptions that the party was more
concerned with the rights of minorities than working families.
</P>
<P>
   They helped elect Reagan twice. Then they elected Reagan's vice
president, the elder George Bush, in 1988. But in 1992, perceiving
that Bush had little interest in their economic lot, they began
drifting back into the Democratic camp, lured by Bill Clinton's
promises to ``put people first.''
</P>
<P>
   Their return to the Democratic fold was completed in 1996 with
Clinton's re-election, dramatically illustrated here in Macomb
County, a collection of suburban Detroit blue-collar communities.
Clinton won 50 percent of the county's vote, compared to 40 percent
for Republican nominee Bob Dole, becoming the first Democrat to win
in Macomb since Hubert Humphrey in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Macomb County is legendary as the heartland of Reagan Democrats,
largely due to a study pollster Stan Greenberg did of disaffected
Democrats in 1984. Greenberg, focusing on Macomb, concluded that
``on this battlefield lay the ruins of the New Deal,'' leaving in
its place Ronald Reagan's America and all the uncertainties of a
new era.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Greenberg eventually became Clinton's pollster
and Macomb became a frequent stop for White House hopefuls. It is
the place where Bush labeled Clinton and Gore ``bozos'' in 1992,
and the site of Michael Dukakis's comical misadventures at a tank
factory in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the place where Gore, after nailing down the
Democratic presidential nomination this spring, began his series of
``school days'' _ day-long visits to schools to draw attention to
his proposed education policies.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg's focus was on people like Steve and Joanna Dygar,
voters who had long leaned toward the Democratic Party but who
voted for Reagan in 1980 and 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Steve was 51 years old, working as a telephone repairman, when
he first voted for Reagan. Joanna was 48, a housewife, with two
nearly grown children. Reagan ``just seemed to be a leader, strong
and kind of inspiring,'' Steve recalls. ``He cared about the little
guy. And things in Washington needed shaking up.''
</P>
<P>
   They were 63 and 60, getting ready for retirement, when they
first voted for Clinton. ``He seemed to care more about people and
families,'' Joanna recalls. ``And I thought it was time for the
younger generation to have their turn trying to straighten out
things in the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 71 and 68, the Dygars are not nearly as cynical about
government as they once were. They aren't too keen on the idea of
changes in Social Security, for example, although they would like
to see more services from Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   That's why ``you can expect to see a big fight over Social
Security'' in this campaign, said Democratic pollster Celinda Lake.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to union and government pension funds, the Dygars
are living off a stock portfolio that, despite the market
gyrations, is ``still more than we started with,'' said Joanna, the
family money manager.
</P>
<P>
   They give credit to Clinton for the economy. ``He did something
right,'' said Steve. But they don't extend the credit to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Dygars are officially undecided in this year's
presidential election. Steve is leaning toward Bush. He sees a bit
of Reagan in him _ ``a strong leader.'' Joanna, on the other hand,
likes Gore's experience. ``It's a safety factor,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As Catholics, they both expressed concern about the ``moral
drift'' of the country.
</P>
<P>
   And among Reagan Democrats, the blame for the decline in moral
values rests with Clinton and his marital infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should put one of those trigger safety locks on his
zipper,'' said 75-year-old John Buckley, a retired die worker and
longtime resident of Macomb County.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Reagan Democrats will punish Gore for Clinton's
indiscretions is unclear. But the lingering popularity of Sen. John
McCain, the vanquished reform candidate in the GOP presidential
contest, suggests Gore is partly blamed for the campaign finance
excesses in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's a good man,'' said Buckley. ``He just didn't
understand that you've got to get along and get into office before
you can change things.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the get-along-to-get-along nature of politics that is so
unappealing to the progeny of the Reagan Democrats, voters like
25-year-old Bill Cayl, a musician, who describes himself as ``right
square in the middle'' of the political back-and-forths of his
Macomb County family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics is too much of a game,'' said Cayl. ``And while
everybody's playing the game, nobody seems to be fighting for
regular people out in the country. This country is about freedom,
but the politicians seem to have forgotten about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayl has heard the older generations in his family talk almost
wistfully of John F. Kennedy and Ronald Reagan, and he wishes he
could vote for a presidential candidate of their caliber. ``Maybe
one of these guys running now could wind up like that,'' he said.
``I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
