<SLUG> BC-SMALL-TIME-CROOKS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEN'S BREEZIEST COMEDY IN YEARS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woody Allen's delightful new comedy, ``Small Time Crooks,'' is
``Take the Money and Run'' by way of ``The Honeymooners.'' It's
Allen's breeziest comedy in years, a lighthearted romp that
combines caper high jinks and social satire in an enjoyably
satisfying manner. To paraphrase Jackie Gleason's Ralph Kramden:
It'll send you to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Allen stars as Ray Winkler, an ex-con dishwasher who's always
scheming and dreaming about a better life. His beloved wife, a
one-time exotic dancer named Frenchy (Tracey Ullman), tolerates and
humors Ray's crazy ideas, although she's not above belittling him
when he goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   Ray: ``What if I told you you're married to a very brilliant
man?''
</P>
<P>
   Frenchy: ``I'd say I'd have to be a bigamist.''
</P>
<P>
   Frenchy wishes she were married to another man when Ray proposes
his latest brainstorm. He has noticed that a pizza parlor, two
doors down from a bank, is vacant and for lease. Ray wants to rent
the store and tunnel his way to the bank. He needs Frenchy to put
up the seed money and act as a front, selling her much-loved
cookies above ground while Ray and his cronies dig through the
basement.
</P>
<P>
   Even though things don't go quite as planned, Ray and Frenchy
wind up richer than their wildest dreams. (Allen throws us a couple
of delicious plot twists that we won't spoil here.) The problem is,
once they join the nouveau riche, Frenchy wants to transcend her
working-class roots and become sophisticated while Ray just wants
to eat cheeseburgers and watch baseball on TV.
</P>
<P>
   The first half-hour of ``Small Time Crooks'' contains some
terrific sight gags and very funny broad humor, along with
hilarious supporting turns from Jon Lovitz, Tony Darrow and Michael
Rappaport as members of Ray's dimwitted gang. (Rappaport, while
digging, wears his miner's hat backward, defeating its purpose, but
looking ``cool,'' nonetheless.)
</P>
<P>
   Ray and Frenchy's sudden wealth takes the movie into some
familiar, although no less enjoyable territory as Allen drolly
examines the differences between plain and expensive pleasures.
Hugh Grant joins the fun here as another schemer, albeit a
polished, sophisticated cad, who sees an opportunity to capitalize
on Frenchy's desire for a radical cultural makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Allen and Ullman make charming combatants; it's nice to see
Allen playing opposite an actress close to his age for a change.
Elaine May, playing Frenchy's dopey cousin, steals every scene
she's in, delivering witticisms that would dumbfound Yogi Berra.
It's a perfectly modulated comic performance, a delight in a movie
filled with a great many small pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
The film: ``Small Time Crooks'' (PG; language). &QL; 
The stars: Woody Allen, Tracey Ullman, Hugh Grant, Elaine May. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Woody Allen. Released by
DreamWorks Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
