<HEADLINE>
IT'S MOSTLY SPACE AND SPANDEX
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: UPN fall schedule below) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a homeless person persistently rattling a battered paper
cup containing a few coins at you, UPN reminded everyone it still
exists on Thursday, with an upfront presentation in New York of its
new fall schedule. The big news is the move of ``The Hughleys''
from ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the latest prospectus on the netlet:
</P>
<P>
   -- Strong points: Wrestling, which single-handedly saved the
network. ``Seven Days'' and ``Star Trek: Voyager'' have their
adherents. Monday's African-American comedies have their teeny
niche audience.
</P>
<P>
   -- Weak points: Pretty much everything else. Wrestling hardly
raised the bar for the network in terms of ratings on other
evenings or the perception that UPN stands for anything other than
Utterly Puerile Nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   -- New this fall season: ``The Hughleys'' and ``Girlfriends,''
both comedies. ``Freedom,'' a ``Matrix''-style high-tech thriller
from producer Joel Silver (``Lethal Weapon'') and ``Level 9,''
about an elite unit fighting cyber-crime will fill out the action
slots.
</P>
<P>
   -- Prognosis: The Viacom-CBS merger may have more of an effect
on UPN's future than its programming, which seems to come and go
without much regard from the rest of the world: Now that Paramount
owns the Tiffany Network, why would it want to hold on to the
Spencer Gifts of networks? And why would anyone else want to buy
such a money pit?
</P>
<P>
   Here's the UPN fall lineup: &QL; 
Monday
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m.: ``Moesha''
</P>
<P>
   8:30 p.m.: ``The Parkers''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m.: ``The Hughleys''
</P>
<P>
   9:30 p.m.: ``Girlfriends'' &QL; 
Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m.: Movie &QL; 
Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m.: ``7 Days''
</P>
<P>
   8:30 p.m.: ``Star Trek: Voyager'' &QL; 
Thursday
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m.: ``WWF Smackdown!'' &QL; 
Friday
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m.: ``Freedom''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m.: ``Level 9'' &QL;
</P>
