<HEADLINE>
FOX TURNS TO THE PROS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fox fall schedule below) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fox network, desperate to reverse the ill fortunes of the
current TV season, has turned to heavy-hitting showrunners _
including James Cameron, multiple Emmy winner David E. Kelley,
``X-Files'' mastermind Chris Carter and ``Sex and the City's''
Darren Star _ to entice viewers. The network revealed its fall
schedule Thursday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Duchovny's Fox Mulder will be back on the ``X-Files'' for half
of next season's 22 episodes for about $350,000 to $400,000 per
episode.
</P>
<P>
   Mulder is not expected to return to the series until the middle
of next season _ probably during February sweeps _ after being
abducted in this season's final episode, set to air Sunday. Co-star
Gillian Anderson will have a new partner next season to assist in
her search for Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the network's scorecard, along with an analysis of how
the new shows will abet current programming.
</P>
<P>
   Strong points: Fox does OK on Saturdays with ``Cops,'' and
better on Sundays with ``The Simpsons,'' ``Malcolm in the Middle''
and ``The X-Files,'' and Mondays with ``That '70s Show,'' ``Titus''
and ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Weak points: The rest of the week gives the network fits. There
was a compelling reason former Fox head Doug Herzog only lasted a
year: He yanked Chris Carter's ``Harsh Realm'' from the schedule
too quickly, engendering some bad blood with one of the network's
most successful producers, and every show introduced last fall is
but a memory. The midseason successes of ``Malcolm'' and ``Titus''
didn't come soon enough to save his job.
</P>
<P>
   The network lost two of its long-running successes this month _
``Party of Five'' and ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' _ and came
perilously close to losing ``The X-Files,'' as well. Oh, and
there's the small matter of chickens finally coming home to roost
where the network's cheesy reality programming is concerned with
the embarrassing Rick and Darva show.
</P>
<P>
   New this fall season: David E. Kelley now owns Fox on Mondays,
with his new teacher drama, ``Boston Public,'' opening for ``Ally
McBeal.'' James Cameron's post-apocalyptic,
battling-the-police-state thriller, ``Dark Angel,'' had better own
Tuesdays, as word is that the pilot is, befitting Cameron, the most
expensive in history for a TV show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't Ask,'' the ``Odd Couple'' update with John Goodman and
Anthony LaPaglia as housemates, gay and straight respectively, will
air on Wednesdays, followed by a family comedy that will no doubt
test the boundaries of very naughty stand-up comic Robert Schimmel.
Wednesday is also home to ``The $treet,'' a soap about the romantic
and financial chicanery of investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fearsum,'' wired paranormal shenanigans from the folks who
brought you ``The Blair Witch Project,'' and the horror anthology
series ``Night Visions,'' will haunt Friday's time slots.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduling changes this fall season: ``That '70s Show'' returns
to Tuesdays _ and how a show that's been moved around this much can
survive is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Midseason replacements: ``The Lone Gunmen,'' Chris Carter's
``X-Files'' spin-off about the loopy conspiracy theorists.
</P>
<P>
   Other programming: Throwaway specials will compete against NBC's
``Must-See Thursday'' (and, nowadays, ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'').
</P>
<P>
   Prognosis: Well, it couldn't get any worse. Nights of all-new
programming are always a tough sell, and Fox has two, on Wednesdays
and Fridays. Fox hasn't had much success expanding its sci-fi
programming beyond ``X-Files'' _ and NBC couldn't interest anybody
in its Saturday night ``thrillogy'' _ suggesting that Friday night
may remain a tough sell for Fox; Cameron's contribution will likely
succeed on the strength of the name brand (as long as they don't
let him write too much!).
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Cameron's ambitious and expensive venture,
this seems a much safer production schedule than the wacked-out
adventurousness that Fox is known for (and which last year inspired
its most high-profile flameout, ``Action''). At this point, winning
back viewers is the chief directive; edgy distinctiveness will no
doubt return at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup: &QL; 
!721!Sunday
</P>
<P>
   7 p.m.: ``Futurama''
</P>
<P>
   7:30 p.m.: ``King of the Hill''
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m.: ``The Simpsons''
</P>
<P>
   8:30 p.m.: ``Malcolm in the Middle''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m.: ``The X-Files'' &QL; 
Monday
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m.: ``Boston Public''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m.: ``Ally McBeal'' &QL; 
Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m.: ``That '70s Show'' (new day)
</P>
<P>
   8:30 p.m.: ``Titus''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m.: ``Dark Angel'' &QL; 
Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m.: ``Don't Ask''
</P>
<P>
   8:30 p.m.: ``Schimmel''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m.: ``The $treet'' &QL; 
Thursday
</P>
<P>
   Fox movies and specials &QL; 
Friday
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m.: ``Fearsum''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m.: ``Night Visions'' &QL; 
