<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-L.A.-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO EXCUSE NOT TO REGISTER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Want to have a voice in this year's elections? Aside from
contributing a few million dollars in soft money to the party of
your choice, you need to vote to have a voice. And to vote, you
need to register. And to register, well, the Internet has a way to
make speaking up a bit easier.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, ABCNEWS.com announced that it has cut a deal
with OnlineDemocracy.com to simplify the annoying process of
chasing down a registration card.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is one of the first for OnlineDemocracy.com, the
brainchild of a Florida anti-tax activist named David Biddulph who
hopes to do well by doing good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our first step,'' Biddulph said. ``Basically, we're
going to be building empowerment tools for the Internet for
improving the functioning of our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Go to ABCNEWS.com's political site (or
http://abcnews.go.com/sections/politics/Da
ilyNews/onlinedemocracy_register.htm) and you can register pretty
painlessly. For Californians, you fill out the registration
information online, then the site (snail)mails it to you on
postcard stock, to be signed, dated and (again, snail)mailed to the
Secretary of State.
</P>
<P>
   California is one of 21 states that won't let you print out the
filled-in card directly from your computer, Biddulph said. Four
other states _ New Hampshire, North Dakota, Wyoming and Wisconsin _
either don't require registration or allow it on the same day as
voting, and therefore don't need the service.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a big deal, but it does reduce the annoyances of
registration slightly. And Biddulph said he has talked with
California Secretary of State Bill Jones about legal and
technological changes that might make registration easier still in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think California is probably the state that's going to help
lead us into digital signatures and so forth,'' Biddulph said. ``I
met with Mr. Jones and I know in his heart he feels we should be
prudently moving forward. I do believe he's very interested in
using the technology of the Net to engage the citizenry and make it
more interactive.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there's a need for such a service. Biddulph said 16
million Americans a year register or re-register. And with election
participation rates plummeting, especially among Net-savvy youths,
a Web-enabled registration process may be the most effective way to
encourage them to get signed up.
</P>
<P>
   The service is free not only to Web users but also Web sites,
either those with co-branding agreements like that of ABCNEWS.com
or simpler affiliates' links, Biddulph said.
</P>
<P>
   His company hopes to make money in a novel way, by charging
politicians for e-mail access to those new registrants from the
site who opt to make their names available. The address information
on the registration can be used to ensure that politicians only
contact those who a) are voting constituents of their district and
b) want to be contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Biddulph said he has other plans to expand the ways e-mail and
the Internet can be used to build citizens' interest in and
connection with the people spending their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, a lot of sites will use this technology to make it
more approachable for people and their government,'' Biddulph said.
``We believe there's a lot of things an ordinary citizen can do to
make an impact.'' &QL; 
---One of the more interesting, if rarefied, publications in the
gaming business is gone, or nearly so. The last issue of PC
Accelerator, complete with a blank, black cover and the simple
words ``it's over,'' is hitting newsstands any minute now.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine tried to be ``the first lifestyle magazine for PC
gamers,'' with heavy emphasis on the high-end games, graphics
accelerators and computers of hard-core players, along with a
gratuitous smattering of photos of underdressed, overbuilt starlets
and occasional advice on the rest of the gamer's life.
</P>
<P>
   But after 22 issues, publisher Imagine Media is folding PCXL's
operations, and subscriptions, into PC Gamer magazine, and into a
new channel on Imagine's DailyRadar.com Web site. The magazine's
executive editor, Rob Smith, also will take over as editor in chief
of PC Gamer.
</P>
<P>
   At least the dead-tree publication is going out with style.
Among other dimming-of-the-day features is one about what they'd do
if they ran the gaming industry. Now there's a notion. &QL; 
---In the lead-up to last week's big E3 gaming convention, I
neglected to actually write about games that are already available.
Herewith:
</P>
<P>
   Thief 2: The Metal Age (Eidos Interactive) is an excellent
sequel to the sneaky 1998 smash hit, Thief. Once again, discretion
is the better part of valor (and gameplay) in an excellent, though
graphically aging, followup to one of the best PC adventure titles
of recent memory. Better swipe it fast (but leave some ducats at
the counter, please).
</P>
<P>
   Star Trek Armada (Activision) is a quite good Star Trek game, a
phrase that is not, despite nearly all previous evidence, an
oxymoron. The gameplay is pretty straightforward for a real-time
strategy title, with the standard gather-build-fight structure you
expect. But its deep-space setting looks terrific; it features
excellent balance between the well-differentiated races; and it is
actually, yes, a quite good Star Trek game. Be a Borg and
assimilate this one.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of games we like, during E3, the Academy of
Interactive Arts and Sciences recognized the best titles of last
year. The big winners, maestro:
</P>
<P>
   Game of the Year: The Sims, a simulation of you and me.
</P>
<P>
   Computer Game of the Year: Age of Empires II: The Age of Kings,
a simulation of life in ancient and medieval times.
</P>
<P>
   Console Game of the Year: Soul Calibur, the gorgeous fighting
game for Dreamcast.
</P>
<P>
   Online Game of the Year: EverQuest, the fantasy role-playing
game dubbed ``EverCrack'' for its addictive qualities.
</P>
<P>
   And though it didn't win one of the big four, Final Fantasy
VIII, another great role-playing game that approaches movie
quality, took home three awards, as did The Sims and Age of
Empires. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
