<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEATERS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHEATERS' PROSPERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `tonight' refers to Sat., May 20) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cheaters'' may be the most honest TV movie ever to come out of
Hollywood. In a land of sliding-scale equity where convenient
connections more often serve as hard currency than actual ability,
where virtually every actor _ and now, even writers and executives
_ lies about his or her age (and experience), where David Geffen is
just the latest mogul to merit a stout biography detailing his
every unethical behavior with an obsessiveness than can only mask
admiration, ``Cheaters'' may emerge as Hollywood's ultimate how-to
film.
</P>
<P>
   It's not about Hollywood, of course, not on the surface; it
actually offers a provocative, even subversive take on a 1995
scandal at a Chicago high school, painting it, not unfairly, as a
skirmish in the class warfare battles (one character calls it,
``the ultimate Affirmative Action'').
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Daniels stars as Dr. Gerald Plecki, a beleaguered
public-school teacher who can't even rally his lethargic charges to
get worked up about Satan's stirring paean to rebellion in
``Paradise Lost.'' He also heads up the school's equally
beleaguered academic decathlon team, which is routinely hammered in
competition by the students of a more privileged school. A copy of
the upcoming test lands by coincidence in his lap and, convinced
that he's merely leveling the playing field against a bunch of
prissy, moneyed mama's boys and girls, he passes it on to his team
_ if they're interested. They are. Can they keep quiet? They can't.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, Hollywood's go-to guy when you're casting a likable,
low-key Everyman, exudes the sort of weariness a middle-aged
teacher who lives at home with his mother must experience, along
with a sort of half-Herculean effort to conceal his beaten status
from his students. He delivers his monologues condemning the social
systems that tacitly encourage dishonesty just right _ not too much
bluster, not too much soaring rhetoric, just with a vaguely
impotent frustration that circumstances have reduced him to this
level.
</P>
<P>
   What ``Cheaters'' really has no patience for are the high-minded
hypocrites who pay lip service to honesty while sticking it to the
system in their own fashion. It casts Robert Joy, adept at playing
oily, sniveling sorts, as the snooty coach of the upscale school,
and notes, with ironic satisfaction, that a highly placed executive
in Chicago's school system, after decrying Plecki's behavior, was
later found guilty of tax evasion. It also notes that 80 percent of
all high schoolers have copped to cheating, and that half of them
don't consider it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   And as if the hallowed calling of journalism needed yet another
black eye, the movie thoughtfully takes an hilariously gratuitous
swing in the closing title cards: The underachieving guy who
weaseled on Plecki's team _ also among his sins is a predilection
for comic books and goofy, fashion-victim-looking hair _ plans to
become a reporter. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Cheaters.'' &QL; 
What: Docudrama about a controversial Chicago high school cheating
scandal. &QL; 
The stars: Jeff Daniels, Jena Malone, Paul Sorvino. &QL; 
Where: HBO &QL; 
When: 9 tonight; also May 23, 28, 31 and June 5, 8, 13. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
