<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, May 19.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUGGENHEIM-1900 (New York) _ The Guggenheim's ``1900: Art at the
Crossroads'' is a wacky exercise in historical simulation, the
excuse being a new century. It is hard to remember the last time so
many bad pictures were in one place at one time, unless you
consider eBay a place. But the show no doubt will be as popular in
New York as it was in London. There is no underestimating the
public's taste for kitsch. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE-IMMERSION (Undated) _ Five years ago, at a stationery
store on the Left Bank, I picked up a copy of Paris Match, fished
in my pants pocket for some francs and walked toward the counter, a
smile of fear frozen on my face. As my brain locked, I croaked out
this sentence to the old woman at the counter: ``Je voudrais
acheter le magasin, s'il vous plait.'' The common word for magazine
is magazine (mah-gah-ZEEN), not magasin (mah-gah-ZAA). I had asked
to buy the shop. And so it went. For 10 days in Paris I was a
helpless prisoner of my past: four years of undistinguished high
school French and one semester at college. I could make my way
through a French newspaper, but conversation was out of the
question. Until now. No longer the 98-pound-weakling of
bilingualism, I have persuaded myself that it is possible to
function confidently, perhaps even thrive, in another culture. I am
a graduate of language immersion. By Charles Strum.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
