</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8981 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-TEXAS-CONSERVANCY-HNS     05-18 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CONSERVANCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ECOLOGY GROUP ACQUIRES COVETED PROPERTY IN TEXAS HILL COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTOPHER ANDERSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOVE CREEK RANCH, Texas _ Baxter Adams, an ex-oil field
geologist and a former cattle rancher, proudly points out several
species of native plants and trees growing between a rugged
limestone canyon wall and a small creek that is as lovely as its
name suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a grand environment for plants to hide in,'' said
Adams, who rapidly evolved into an apple and maple tree grower
after he and his wife, Carol, purchased a 1,863-acre ranch near
Lost Maples State Natural Area two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steep canyons protect them from the weather, and there's
constant cold spring water,'' Adams said as he walked along the
clear waters of Love Creek Ranch, which has been compared favorably
by scientists to the popular state park a few miles to the west.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a great microcosm of the Hill Country,'' said Robert
Potts, director of the Nature Conservancy of Texas, referring to
the rolling and sparsely populated country to the west of Austin
and San Antonio. ``The biology of this place is very much like the
biology of Lost Maples. Our botanists say they're kind of sister
canyons.''
</P>
<P>
   All but about 400 acres of the ranch were purchased recently by
the San Antonio-based conservation group, which plans to use the
property to raise money, educate the public and demonstrate
ecologically sensitive land-use practices in hopes of saving some
of the diminishing Texas Hill Country.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Barwick, a land protection specialist for the nonprofit
organization, would not disclose the price at the request of the
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The land was purchased at a bargain price,'' he said. ``There
was a substantial gift from Carol and Baxter Adams.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal completes the group's year-old mission of acquiring a
large piece of property near San Antonio with significant water
resources and a diversity of Texas flora and fauna.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our flagship preserve in the southern Hill Country,''
Barwick said.
</P>
<P>
   Love Creek Ranch includes almost the entire headwaters of Love
Creek and more than 2 miles of creek frontage. It also includes
habitat for three endangered species: the golden-cheeked warbler,
black-capped vireo and Tobusch fishhook cactus.
</P>
<P>
   Adams turned his attention away from the vegetation and to the
canyon wall itself, where a rusty-looking brown belt separates two
layers of rock. ``That little line right there is where it
breaks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams explains that the line represents the point of contact
between two rock formations, the Edwards and the Glenrose, which
formed separately tens of millions of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The upper stratum of limestone, the Edwards, is jumbled and
appears as if it were born out of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something major happened,'' said Adams, noting that the rock
was formed in tropical waters as one of the Earth's tectonic plates
moved north across the equator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful rock. I've always loved the Edwards,'' Adams
said. ``And, of course, it's one of the great aquifers of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The smooth Glenrose rock below blocks percolation of rainwater
through the Edwards. The water instead escapes into Love Creek
through numerous seeps and springs, which keep the bottom of the
canyon at least a little wet year-round.
</P>
<P>
   The creek feeds into the Medina River, which recharges the
Edwards Aquifer. That's one reason the Nature Conservancy of Texas
was attracted to the property.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that a number of native plants, including some rare
ones, can be found on the ranch only because it has not been grazed
by livestock since Adams abandoned an early attempt to introduce a
handful of heifers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a rock garden when we bought it,'' said Adams, adding
that his cows nearly starved because the land had been worked too
hard for far too long. ``There just wasn't any grass on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most of the country out here it was just horrendously
overgrazed,'' he said. ``There had never been any rotation of
pastures. They started off, I'm sure, with cows and pigs and horses
and they ended up with sheep and goats.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Griffin, resource conservationist for the U.S. Department
of Agriculture, agreed that some ranchers in the region have
mistreated their land by allowing it to be overgrazed even though
it ultimately reduces their property's production and value.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin said people who want to live in the country but who have
little interest in farming or raising animals are purchasing many
ranches in Bandera County. In some cases, that could help land
recover to its more natural state.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the whole, I think things are probably changing somewhat
for the better here in this part of the Edwards Plateau,'' said
Griffin, cautioning that large, well-managed ranches are also being
subdivided into suburban ``ranchettes'' that could damage the
area's ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Sansom, executive director of the Texas Parks and
Wildlife Department, said ranchers and farmers are some of the best
stewards of the environment, but that many well cared for
properties are now falling into the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``A million and a half acres of Texas farm and ranch land
disappears every year to sprawl and to inheritance taxes and other
things that cause family lands to fragment,'' Sansom said. ``The
important thing right now is to preserve some of these large
ecologically important tracts while they're still there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he would have liked to have seen Love Creek be made
into a state park.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's a lot more difficult,'' he said. ``The Nature
Conservancy is much quicker on its feet and able to do things
without so many people's approval. It would have taken forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas ranks 49th in per-capita spending on state parks. An
estimated 97 percent of all land in the state is privately owned,
and the Legislature doesn't provide any money to acquire public
parkland.
</P>
<P>
   Sansom said the result is that the people will never see some of
the best and most environmentally important places in Texas because
they are being altered beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can take you to some places that are no longer there because
of that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Christopher Anderson can be reached by e-mail at
canderson(at)express-news.net)
</P>
