<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-18 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULLING TROPHIES OF THE BOOM YEARS OF SAUL AND GAYFRYD STEINBERG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain)   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enough years have passed since the roaring 1980s that it's
probably time for a television miniseries on the decade. What would
furnish the sets better than the antiques in the collection of the
swashbuckling tycoon Saul Steinberg and his wife, Gayfryd, who are
selling most of their decorative arts collection at Sotheby's on
May 26th.
</P>
<P>
   Until very recently the collection was in the Steinbergs'
37-room Park Avenue triplex, possibly the largest apartment in New
York, which they recently sold for about $35 million to Stephen
Schwarzman, president of Blackstone Group, the investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg acquired the triplex, built for John D. Rockefeller
Jr., in the 1970s for $275,000, Steinberg said. ``New York was in
trouble then,'' she said, ``and no one wanted to pay the
maintenance.'' The couple, working with the decorators Tom Collum
and Mark Hampton, spent the 1980s and '90s filling it with English
furniture, European artworks, silver and porcelain. The 293 lots in
the sale are expected to bring $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, looking for a brownstone, are not selling
everything, Steinberg said. ``We are keeping things that work on a
smaller scale,'' she said, including the furniture, Goya drawings
and objets d'art from what she calls ``Saul's John Soane-looking
library.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the British Neo-Classical architect John Soane, the
black library was decorated, Steinberg explained, ``with elements
from the Grand Tour, such as casts of Roman temples, rondels with
Roman gods, bas reliefs with ancient figures in procession, as well
as some 200 drawings and 250 cartons' worth of antique books.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Steinbergs are selling are the grand, overscaled pieces
that she calls ``palace furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a gutsy space that called for gutsy furniture,'' she
said. ``The space demanded it. The apartment was splendid in scale,
and after Mark Hampton's work there, it looked like it should: a
very grand place so Saul's Old Master pictures could be hung
properly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Steinbergs had different collecting interests. ``I loved
English furniture, French chairs and Chinese export porcelain,''
Steinberg said. ``Saul loved his pictures. He bought them without
knowing if we had a spare wall. He could live in a plain white room
if he had his pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, they bought their antiques together, often in
London. John Hobbs, a London dealer with offices in New York, sold
them pieces and occasionally advised them on acquiring things at
auction. To him, the most important piece in the sale is a George
II rococo mahogany dressing and writing commode attributed to John
Channon, circa 1765, which the Steinbergs bought at auction in
London. A companion piece is in the Victoria and Albert Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Channon (1711-1783) was a member of a family that made furniture
for the richest families in England. The commode is thought to be
one of a pair commissioned for Fonthill Splendens, a Palladian
mansion near Bath that was rebuilt after a 1755 fire by Alderman
William Beckford, heir to an immense Jamaican sugar fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbs recalled, ``When it came up for auction at Christie's 11
years ago, Gayfryd called me about it, and I told her to buy it
because she would never have a chance to buy something
categorically by Channon again.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles Hutchinson-Smith, one of the directors of Mallett, the
London antiques shop, said he thought the two commodes would have
been placed in ``the center of the room, back to back, to make a
real statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's said the commodes were probably made for either
Beckford's bedroom or the state bedroom, where the king and queen
would stay at Fonthill Splendens.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Lang, Sotheby's specialist in English furniture, said,
``It's the best example of the rococo period of this model in
England, where you really don't see such elaborate use of bronze
mounts.''
</P>
<P>
   The commode has an exaggerated serpentine top with two sets of
five drawers flanking a central niche, which has five smaller
drawers. Above the central drawers is a larger drawer with a leafy
bronze keyhole escutcheon. It is flanked by two large ormolu female
heads. They are nereids, or sea nymphs. Above the keyhole is a
bronze garland with different kinds of sea shells.
</P>
<P>
   The corners have winged satyr heads and front feet with
elaborate roroco scrolls. Between them are two scaly winged ormolu
dolphins, associated with the goddess Venus.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion Channon was the genius of his century,'' Hobbs
said. ``In terms of design and workmanship he was in a class of his
own. He was so innovative he left everyone else for dead. The
commode is one of Channon's major pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobbs pointed out that the Steinberg commode had been ``toned
down'' sometime in the past. When it came up for sale at Christie's
in 1989, some of the mounts were missing.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg recalled: ``We were hiking in Arizona, and John Hobbs
called to tell us to stay by the phone for the auction. We
discussed a limit on how much we would spend. Saul ended up buying
it for 1 million pounds, way above our limit. Then there was the
challenge of restoring it, which took a year and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Steinbergs got permission to borrow the twin at the Victoria
and Albert Museum and at enormous expense were able to recast its
mounts to replace their missing ones. ``The commode is absolutely
spectacular, even though half of it has been replaced,'' Hobbs
said. The estimate at Sotheby's is $3 million to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Equally over the top are two pairs of Grimsthorpe Castle side
chairs, circa 1755. Made of mahogany with some gilding, each has a
delicate pierced back whose top rail is adorned with a Chinese
pagoda and beautifully carved cabriole legs ending in scroll-carved
toes. The four are part of a set of six; Mallett currently has the
third pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go to the extremes of luxury and fantasy,'' said Giles
Hutchinson-Smith, one of the directors at Mallett. ``The chairs
were conceived as furnishings for a Chinese room and were meant to
show off incredible prosperity and power. They were made purely for
the drinking of tea. They are incredibly important in that they
predate Thomas Chippendale's Chinese-influenced furniture. They
show the beginning of a fantasy element, which blew away the
restraint of the George II style. They are thought to have been
made by William Hallett, whom George II called his `Chinese
mongrel.''' Each pair at Sotheby's is estimated at $200,000 to
$300,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Steinberg sale ``is extremely impressive,'' said Christopher
Gibbs, the London antiques dealer. ``It's a very unboring
collection of things. As a mixture, it was decidedly indigestible,
not calming in any way, but there are a lot of things to be
surprised by.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection goes on view Friday at Sotheby's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
