<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO RAINDROPS FOR REDFORD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes in Hollywood, there are happy accidents.
``Casablanca'' is one such film. If the studio had had its way, the
film probably would have been long forgotten. Instead, they got
Humphrey Bogart, Ingrid Bergman and an enduring classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' might have starred Steve
McQueen or Warren Beatty instead of a guy named Robert Redford, if
the studio had its way. It took the persistence of director George
Roy Hill, with the help of Paul Newman, to get Redford the role of
Sundance. The film ``changed my life,'' says Redford on a special
DVD edition released this week.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD, which includes interviews with Redford, Newman and
others, has some fascinating details on the making of the ultimate
and perhaps best buddy movie, which _ believe it or not _ opened to
bad reviews (critics!!!). But the public knew what it liked.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit for the film goes to Hill, who took William
Goldman's first script and gave it the right mix of comedy and
drama. Not only did audiences laugh at Butch and Sundance, they
cared about them. The film also played with our cinematic
perceptions of the West, beginning with a silent film and ending
with that famous freeze shot.
</P>
<P>
   With beautiful cinematography by Conrad Hall (who took home that
Oscar for ``American Beauty'' and who lends his voice to the film
commentary), this DVD is a treat for film buffs. One other note:
``Butch'' _ like ``Casablanca'' _ endured even with a silly song in
it. Art may be forever, but so is charm.
</P>
<P>
   !folo!The name's Brosnan ... : The latest James Bond adventure,
``The World Is Not Enough,'' is also out. Directed by Michael Apted
(``Coal Miner's Daughter''), the film tries to add depth and nuance
to 007's life. The results are only partially successful. Since
taking over, Pierce Bronson has added some weight to Bond without
sacrificing his cheekiness. Sophie Marceau as a complex love
interest and Robert Carlyle as a grotesque adversary are
interesting casting for the film. Even the plot, based on
post-Soviet geopolitics, is a cut above the usual Bond fare. But
when Denise Richards enters halfway through the film as a nuclear
scientist named Christmas, the move nearly nukes the movie.
</P>
<P>
   For 007 fans, James Bond Gift Set Part II was also released this
week. This is your chance to see how Sean Connery, George Lasenby
and Roger Moore stack up as the man who likes to have his martini
shaken, not stirred.
</P>
<P>
   !folo!'X'-extreme beginnings: OK, ``The X-Files'' will be back
next year in some form, but for those who want to see how it
started, the entire first season is now available on DVD. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
-- ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid: The Special Edition'' (Fox
Home Video) is $14.90 on VHS and $29.90 on DVD, which includes
commentary by director George Roy Hill, Hal David, Robert Crawford
and cinematographer Conrad Hall, a making-of documentary (45
minutes), interviews with Paul Newman, Robert Redford, Katharine
Ross, William Goldman and Burt Bacharach and a DVD-ROM interactive
history of Butch and Sundance.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The World Is Not Enough'' (MGM/UA) is $19.90 on VHS and
$34.90 on DVD, which includes a making-of documentary and ``The
World Is Not Enough'' music video by Garbage. The James Bond Gift
Set II on DVD is $149.90, and includes ``Dr. No,'' ``The Man With
the Golden Gun,'' ``Moonraker,'' ``On Her Majesty's Secret
Service'' and ``The Spy Who Loved Me.'' Each has audio commentary
by the director and key members of the crew and making-of
documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   -- The first season of ``The X-Files'' (Fox) on DVD is $149.98
and contains all 23 first-season episodes plus the pilot, 11
``Behind-the-Truth'' segments from F/X and interviews with series
creator Chris Carter about 12 of his favorite episodes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
