<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9005 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-HAMLET-TEX     05-18 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HAMLET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS NOT TO BE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time we get a good look at Ethan Hawke in Michael
Almereyda's bizarre, contemporary version of ``Hamlet,'' he's
wearing the tinted, black-rimmed glasses of an ``artiste.'' The
first person who came to my mind wasn't a melancholy Dane but a
pompous Irishman _ with the specs on, Hawke bears a faint
resemblance to Bono, the self-important lead singer of U2. This may
be a highly personal reaction, but it's appropriate because, like
Bono, this ``Hamlet'' is often pretentious, but likable in spite of
itself.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if you're in the right frame of mind, which isn't to
take this seriously but to look at it as more of an eccentric goof.
It's virtually impossible not to, with actors like Hawke, Bill
Murray, Kyle MacLachlan and Diane Venora wandering through
modern-day corporate New York, spouting Elizabethan dialogue as if
the movie were dubbed into a foreign language. Almereyda ruthlessly
trimmed Shakespeare's text, and the result is sort of like a
twisted greatest-hits package: ``Hamlet 2000 _ The Michael
Almereyda Mix.'' Some favorite moments survive the transition to
the present day, some don't, and many don't even make it into the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Hamlet is no longer a Danish prince but an American aspiring
filmmaker, played by Hawke as more surly dude than melancholy Dane.
His slain father is no longer a fallen king but the former
president of Denmark Corp.; playwright Sam Shepard, whose remote
grimness is perfect for the character, for some reason employs an
indeterminate East Coast accent in playing the father's ghost.
MacLachlan plays Hamlet's nefarious uncle Claudius, who murdered
Hamlet's father, married his mother and took over the family
business _ actions that fuel Hamlet's oft-muddled plans for
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the scissoring, Almereyda has managed to keep the
play's complicated plot of accidental deaths, intentional murders,
foolish fathers and vengeance-seeking sons intact. But in this
case, it hardly matters; what matters are the strange settings
Almereyda finds for Shakespeare's words and situations:
</P>
<P>
   Hamlet mutters the famous ``To be or not to be ... '' soliloquy
while roaming the action-movie aisles of an empty Blockbuster
Video, as the revenge drama ``The Crow'' plays on a screen in the
background (for some reason, Hawke sports a snowboard-slacker wool
cap during this and many other scenes). The play ``The Mousetrap,''
which Hamlet devises to ``catch the conscience of the king'' and
get Claudius to reveal his guilt, has been transformed into a
hilariously pretentious short film. The climactic sword fight,
which works about as well as the preposterous sword fight in ``The
Skulls,'' is interrupted by bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The actors play all this out with such straightforward
earnestness, your heart goes out to them. Murray, as the
wise/foolish advice-dispensing Polonius, comes off best, his blithe
personality meshing well with such a know-it-all character. The
normally reliable Julia Stiles, as the troubled Ophelia, comes off
worst, turning the character's hysteria into mere histrionics. As
for Hawke _ well, he's no Olivier. Or Branagh. Or even Gibson. His
natural passivity and talent for wounded romanticism would seem to
fit the role of a hero who just can't make up his mind, but his
moments of action and anger are jaggedly uneven, played not as if
he were out to avenge the death of his father but more as if he
were upset at someone for spilling Pepsi on his Nirvana CDs.
</P>
<P>
   For all that's wrong with the movie, it's strangely intriguing,
with a sort of gotta-watch-the-train-wreck appeal. Early reviews
have overreacted in so many ways, from those that call it
unwatchable malarkey to those who praise its, um,
``post-modernism'' (which must apply to a year 2000 that looks more
futuristic than the one we actually live in). They protest _ and
praise _ too much, methinks; it's merely a curiosity piece,
deserving neither accolades nor slings and arrows but simply mild
bemusement.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Hamlet''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Michael Almereyda
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Ethan Hawke, Kyle MacLachlan
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence and making its original author do backflips
in his grave
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
