<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DINOSAUR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUDDLY DISNEY CREATURES ARE EXTINCT IN SCARY, THRILLING
`DINOSAUR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B+  
 By William Arnold  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the field of animation at least, Disney is one brand name
that still stands for something. As hard as DreamWorks, Warners,
Fox and the rest of the Hollywood competition scramble, they just
can't seem to match it for innovation, imagination and quality.
</P>
<P>
   In the time it took Jeffrey Katzenberg and his DreamWorks to
come up with its thoroughly mediocre ``Road to El Dorado,'' for
instance, the Mouse House released two blockbuster animated hits _
``Tarzan'' and ``Toy Story 2'' _ and this weekend has a third
likely candidate for the honor in ``Dinosaur.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest computer-generated effort is something of a
departure, too. It's not a musical, and the cuddly aspects of its
characters have been tuned way down. Though it nods at the
conventions of the animated feature, it's also much more realistic
than usual for the genre, sometimes unsettlingly so.
</P>
<P>
   The title character is an iguanodon named Aladar who hatches
from an egg that somehow got kicked around the primeval landscape
in the opening sequence, and landed in a colony of warm-blooded
lemurs. Naturally, the lemurs raise the cute baby dinosaur as one
of their own.
</P>
<P>
   At the point where it looks like we're in for a cross between
``Barney'' and ``Tarzan,'' the film switches gears with a gigantic
meteor shower that devastates the planet, and sends the surviving
dinosaurs on a quest to reach their Eden-like ``nesting grounds''
to save their species.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, there are landslides, stampedes, a drought, a
dinosaur romance, and plenty of battles as the herd is constantly
pursued by a pair of giant-jawed, all-teeth carnisaurs and a pack
of velociraptors _ those lightning-fast and vicious critters we got
to know and fear in ``Jurassic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   By far the weakest part of the film is its ``human'' element:
the '90s jargon (``We're outta here''), the ``character'' voices
(provided by Della Reese, Alfre Woodard and Joan Plowright, among
others), and the de rigueur subplot in which Aladar challenges his
aging dinosaur leader to become head of the herd.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers have little or no interest in this aspect of the
movie, and have thrown in the cliches because they are expected.
Too bad they didn't skip the gags and one-liners, along with the
songs, and go the distance in making this an authentic dinosaur
world.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, ``Dinosaur'' is still one heck of an action adventure.
From its knockout opening sequence _ a pterodactyl flight through a
Cretaceous world filled with thousands of milling dinosaurs _ the
film is totally alive. And the computer technology is moving so
fast now that the effects seem even more eerily lifelike here than
in November's ``Toy Story 2.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinosaur'' is also a surprisingly scary movie _ even for
adults _ and quite violent for a Disney cartoon. It's rated a
benign PG, but very young children may be horrified by its vision
of a brutal, eat-or-be-eaten world. On the other hand, boys between
the ages of 8 and 13 should enjoy it so much they'll think they've
died and gone to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Dinosaur. Directed by Ralph Zondag and Eric Leighton. Screenplay
by John Harrison, Robert Nelson Jacobs and Walon Green. Voices:
D.B. Sweeney, Alfre Woodard, Ossie Davis, Joan Plowright, Della
Reese. Disney. 82 minutes. Rated PG for reptilian violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
