<HEADER>
A9020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOTION-FILM-REVIEW-NY     05-18 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTION-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LUMINOUS MOTION': TROUBLED MOM AND SON, SADLY ADRIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We'll have to wait till yesterday's here,'' goes the Tom Waits
song that accompanies the end credits for ``Luminous Motion,'' and
Bette Gordon's funny, unnerving new film casts a similar spell of
low-key dislocation. It begins with the voice of 10-year-old
Phillip (Eric Lloyd) reflecting on his earlier life as though it
were the distant past. ``Childhood feels like a ghost town,'' he
muses. ``It's hard to distinguish what's real from what's something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an accurate premonition of the dreamy odyssey that
follows, but it may seem a bit much coming from the mouth of a
late-20th-century American boy, even one as precocious and
introspective as Phillip. There is a quality of earnest, overripe
literariness to the script _ adapted by Robert Roth and Scott
Bradfield from a novel by Bradfield _ that, at least early on,
holds the audience at arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like a quality of landscape,'' Philip says, musing on
the nomadic life he leads with his mother (Deborah Kara Unger), and
while Lloyd reads the words with the right tone of wistful rue,
it's not clear that he knows what they mean. Is that any way to
talk about your mother?
</P>
<P>
   But the voice-over _ a technique, once taboo among serious
filmmakers, that has lately become all but ubiquitous _ is a crutch
the movie quickly, and wisely, puts aside. We get a better sense of
Philip's melancholy inwardness, his blithe innocence and his
inscrutability from studying Lloyd's chubby, expectant face. And
the relationship between mother and son is too charged and too
subtle to be conveyed on screen in mere prose. The story _ nuanced,
shocking and slippery _ requires more than a literal-minded
transcription of the novel, and Gordon performs the alchemical feat
of turning it into visual poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luminous Motion'' tells Philip's story and his mother's
simultaneously, and its emotional pivot is their mutual pain at the
discovery that the two stories are not the same. For Philip, their
life on the road, drifting between motels and diners in a red
Impala cluttered with old science textbooks and glass figurines, is
a state of perfect symbiosis. He is blind to his mother's
desperate, reckless sadness as she ricochets through a series of
one-night stands, petty thefts and bottles of cheap liquor.
</P>
<P>
   Unger, who played the chief Canadian do-gooder in ``The
Hurricane,'' holds ``Luminous Motion'' together even as her
character's life falls apart. The film's coherence, and its
emotional power, depend on her ability to play in effect two roles
at once. She has to show us both what Philip sees and what he
refuses to acknowledge: the tender, funny resourceful mother, and
the damaged, lonely woman casting about for stability. Unger
accomplishes this with amazing understatement, and without a trace
of pity or sentimentality. Her voice is gravelly and slow, and her
face seems always on the verge of melting into sleep. Toward the
end of the movie, she's barely awake, and her languorous exhaustion
takes on a tragic dimension.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy is revealed obliquely, through Philip's playful,
quicksilver temperament. Like his mother, though, the boy is not
quite what he seems. He appears to suffer from auditory and visual
hallucinations, receiving first telephone calls and then surprise
visits from his vanished father (Jamey Sheridan). When Philip and
his mother briefly settle down with a kindly carpenter named Pedro
(Terry Kinney), the apparitional father, like the ghost in Hamlet,
instructs his son to kill the usurper. But then once the real Dad
has returned, Pedro's shade appears to goad Philip toward murderous
Oedipal vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   At least, I think that's what happens. With cunning agility,
``Luminous Motion'' tiptoes along the narrow boundary between
fantasy and reality. We're never sure whether what we see is taking
place in the physical world or in Philip's mind. And while the film
respects both his emotions and his perceptions, it also leaves open
the possibility that he is suffering from a serious mental illness.
Is this surrealism or schizophrenia? Either way, the film sustains
a delicate counterpoint between childlike wonder and deep,
inconsolable melancholy. It's a bit like ``The Sixth Sense,'' but
without the melodramatic comfort of the supernatural. Its horror,
like its humor, comes from close to home, from the primal bond
between mother and son.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LUMINOUS MOTION'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bette Gordon; written by Robert Roth and Scott
Bradfield, based on Bradfield's novel ``The History of Luminous
Motion''; director of photography, Teodoro Maniaci; edited by Keiko
Deguchi; music by Lesley Barber; production designer, Lisa Albin;
produced by Anthony Bregman and Ted Hope; released by Artistic
License Films.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Eric Lloyd (Phillip), Deborah Kara Unger (Mom), Terry
Kinney (Pedro), Jamey Sheridan (Dad) and James Berland (Rodney).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 94 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1554EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WELL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      05-18 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WELL': BLAIR WITCH-TYPE DREAD INFUSES AN OUTBACK PUZZLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first half of ``The Well,'' the Australian director Samantha
Lang's beautifully creepy debut feature, is an efficient study in
the contrasting temperaments of two lonely women. Hester (Pamela
Rabe), who lives with her father on a desolate sheep station, is
the repressed one. We know this because of her long skirts and
buttoned-up blouses, her orthopedic shoes and her flat, colorless
hair, which she wears either severely plaited or gathered into a
bun like the one Anthony Perkins sported in ``Psycho.'' Her taste
in music runs to German lieder sung at dirge pace to the
accompaniment of an out-of-tune upright piano.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine (Miranda Otto), her wayward young housekeeper, is the
free spirit and resident life force. She loves loud rock music and
likes to dance around in knee-high boots and short gauzy skirts.
Her flaming red hair is the only splash of color on the dour,
Victorian psychic landscape.
</P>
<P>
   But Hester loves Katherine. Or at least she buys her expensive
gifts, excuses her from chores and learns, in her company, how to
laugh. Bred in flinty pioneer thrift, Hester begins to spend money
as if it were going out of style. She buys a brand-new silver
Toyota pickup and, once her father dies, sells her childhood home
and everything in it. Hester's disapproving financial adviser (Paul
Chubb) suspects that Katherine has bewitched her, but the unlikely
pair, along with two cookie tins full of cash, settle into a cozy
cottage and begin fantasizing about a trip to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Just as you begin to chafe at the obviousness of this setup, or
to settle in for another hour of glum psychological atmospherics,
Katherine runs over something _ which turns out to be someone _ on
a deserted dirt road, and ``The Well,'' with a neck-snapping jolt,
turns into the scariest exercise in cinematic sleight of hand since
``The Blair Witch Project.'' Soon there is a body to be disposed
of, and the deep, dry well in front of the cottage offers itself as
a practical solution and as a metaphor for the murky terror that is
about to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine begins to insist that the man in the well is alive and
that he has fallen in love with her. Surely she's come unhinged. Or
maybe Hester, who either believes Katherine or doesn't, has gone
over the edge. Or maybe you're the crazy one. Strange things begin
to happen, unless nothing is happening at all. The story, adapted
by Laura Jones from a novel by Elizabeth Jolley, is like a chain of
slipknots, drawing ever tighter until one by one they disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Lang brings this puzzle to the screen with mathematical
discipline and painterly emotion. She charges the smallest
interactions with unbearable tension and knows how to induce panic
by suggesting rather than showing. Like Peter Weir in ``Picnic at
Hanging Rock,'' she turns the empty, windy outback into an actively
sinister presence.
</P>
<P>
   Stumbling into ``The Well'' you feel you've awakened into
someone else's nightmare, and you emerge from it clammy with a
dread you don't quite understand. See it with someone you trust. Or
better, see it alone, since afterward you won't be able to trust
anything, least of all your own perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE WELL'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Samantha Lang; written by Laura Jones, based on the
novel by Elizabeth Jolley; director of photography, Mandy Walker;
edited by Dany Cooper; music by Stephen Rae; production designer,
Michael Philips; produced by Sandra Levy; released by Cowboy
Booking International.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Pamela Rabe (Hester), Miranda Otto (Katherine), Paul Chubb
(Harry Bird), Frank Wilson (Francis Harper), Steve Jacobs (Rod
Borden) and Genevieve Lemon (Jen Borden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 105 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
