<HEADER>
A9022 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-ROADTRIP-SPI &LR;      05-18 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ROADTRIP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIGINALITY LEFT BEHIND IN `ROAD TRIP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The poster for ``Road Trip'' features a collection of pretty,
young, undressed kids strategically concealed behind an unfurled
road map and a spaced-out (and thankfully fully dressed) Tom Green.
Smells like ``American Pie'' on wheels to me, only this time the
motivation isn't the pursuit of sex. It's the pursuit of a sex
tape.
</P>
<P>
   Nice guy Josh (the blandly good-looking Breckin Meyer from
``Go'') is an Ithaca University undergrad struggling to keep a long
distance romance alive with his high school sweetheart in Austin,
Texas. ``It isn't cheating if you're in different area codes,''
counsels his best friend E.L. (Seann William Scott, ``American
Pie''), a self-proclaimed expert on the unwritten rules of
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   So when Josh succumbs to the advances of pretty young co-ed Beth
(Amy Smart, ``Outside Providence''), he's satisfied that he hasn't
transgressed too badly.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some situations the rules don't cover, such as
videotaping the event and accidentally sending it to your steady.
(``That's not fair,'' whines Green. ``She gets to see the tape and
we don't.'') Thus the road trip, and all kooky characters, wild
adventures and petty larceny that entails.
</P>
<P>
   Is it funny? In one scene, a vindictive waiter drops French
toast down his underwear (front and back!) before serving it up to
a hapless traveler, who gobbles it down with gusto. It's your call.
</P>
<P>
   Deadpan comic Tom Green is on hand as the zoned-out narrator and
stay-at-home buddy, who likely won the role because he'll do
anything for a well-earned gross-out laugh, including drop a live
rodent into his mouth. Cute and charismatic Smart shows pluck and
panache in a thankless role as the ``other'' woman.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a familiar journey and director/co-writer Todd
Phillips (whose previous encounter with higher education is the
documentary ``Frat House'') sidesteps every opportunity to inject a
little edge or originality into it. There's some touch-and-go race
humor that barely squeaks under the radar of offensiveness, gags
about fat girls and horny old men and kinky sexual thrills, and a
few blatantly gratuitous nude scenes, but no surprises in the
inevitable coming of age rituals and inevitable happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Road Trip'' is sure to elicit giggles and hoots from crowds of
teenagers with its succession of gross-out gags and sexual humor,
but this is one teenage tour that never gets up to speed.
</P>
<P>
   Road Trip. Directed by Todd Phillips. Screenplay by Phillips and
Scot Armstrong. Cast: Breckin Meyer, Seann William Scott, Amy
Smart, Fred Ward, Tom Green. DreamWorks. 97 minutes. Rated R for
nudity, sexual situations, drug use and gross-out humor.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
