</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NSYNC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'N SYNC: The boys are back
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has the time finally come to take 'N Sync seriously?
</P>
<P>
   Ask anyone outside the quintet's target audience of preteen
girls and you'll probably get a decisive no. After all, these guys
are just clones of the Backstreet Boys, who themselves follow in
the R&AMP;B-flavored tradition of New Kids on the Block. If you've
heard one boy band, you've heard them all.
</P>
<P>
   Except that this boy band, which performs two sold-out concerts
at the National Car Rental Center in the days ahead, has managed to
break all the sales records for its latest release, No Strings
Attached.
</P>
<P>
   Since it hit stores in March, the album has held on to the No. 1
spot for seven weeks. (Don't be surprised if Britney Spears'
sophomore effort, Oops ... I Did It Again, finally knocks it off.)
In the first seven days, it sold more than 2.4 million copies,
marking the strongest week of sales by any artist throughout
history _ and more than doubling the total of the previous
record-holder (the Backstreet Boys, who else?). By the time the
Recording Industry Association of America _ the group that awards
those gold- and platinum-selling designations _ got around to
tallying the figures, the total had jumped to 7 million, a record
for a first audit.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, these guys, who got their start in the teen-pop
factory of Orlando _ they had the same manager as the Backstreet
Boys _ can't be that good. Or can they?
</P>
<P>
   The members of the group _ Lance Bass, 22; Joshua ``JC'' Chasez,
23; Joey Fatone, 23; Chris Kirkpatrick, 28; and Justin ``Curly''
Timberlake, 19 _ insist they're the real deal. But even they admit
the numbers caught them off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going to sell something, but not to that
(extent). We're very, very excited and thankful,'' says Fatone,
speaking during a telephone news conference last month.
</P>
<P>
   Bass, who heads his own production company, thinks the record
sales were due to tireless promotion (''We did, like, 50 million
television appearances'') and the fact the album was delayed for a
long time. The group's self-titled debut dates back to 1998. ``The
fans were just so hungry for something out there,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   _ More of the same
</P>
<P>
   No Strings Attached will offer few surprises to those familiar
with the boy-band formula. It's an album that mixes light-funk
grooves and broken-heart sentiments in a radio-friendly package.
Indeed, you can't tune to a Top 40 station without hearing the
first single, Bye Bye Bye, practically every 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Not that all the tunes are so wholesome. Take the case of
Digital Get Down, a song that seemingly explores the cybersex
phenomenon. In this age of online child predators, it's generated
some controversy. Did the band worry about the message?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really. That song was meant to be fun,'' Bass responds,
noting that it was written with a video concept about ``having a
party on the Internet.'' He insists the fans get the right idea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Artistic growth
</P>
<P>
   As for the artistry behind the album, the group feels that,
regardless of its critics, it's moved well past the bubble-gum
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``People now are starting to see that we enjoy the music,'' says
Fatone. ``It's not like we're just throwing something together to
sell the album. It's something we put our blood, sweat and tears
into.''
</P>
<P>
   And while boy bands have been the rage for the last few years,
resulting in some amusing parodies on television, 'N Sync's members
say the phenomenon must be placed in context.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone's taking the whole thing a little wrong,''
says Bass. ``As much as there are teen bands, there's the same
amount of rock bands, R&AMP;B groups, solo acts. ... I think a lot of
older people in the music industry are a little jealous that it's
working.''
</P>
<P>
   The band also points to the fact that it wasn't
``pre-assembled'' in the same way as other boy groups. ``We didn't
go through a boot camp or audition,'' says Bass. Indeed, 'N Sync
started out as an extension of Chasez and Timberlake's work
together on the Mickey Mouse Club (they were on the TV show the
same time as Britney Spears). The two tried to make it in
Nashville; when that failed, they returned to Orlando, hooked up
with the three other members _ Bass was the last to join _ and
began exploring some tight harmonic arrangements. By 1997, they had
a record contract _ and after exploding in Europe, they found a
place on the American pop charts, buoyed by a Disney Channel
special.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the band is starting to write its own material _ Chasez
contributed four songs to the new album _ which it offers as
further proof of its evolution. ``We're heavily involved in
everything,'' says Fatone, noting the band even helped design the
set for the No Strings Attached tour and oversaw production of the
T-shirts. ``You want something that's quality. You don't want to
give back to our fans a piece of crap.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about the concert itself? Given that the band was on
the road just last year _ it played MARS Music Amphitheatre _ it
wanted to take it to the next level. ``It's twice as big,'' says
Bass of the stage. Every song gets its own set of special effects.
Look for pyrotechnics aplenty, but Bass won't reveal any other
details, except to say ``we're going to get very close to everybody
in the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Given how large that audience has become, it should make for
quite a party.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
