<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-DINO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amazing animation saves so-so `Dinosaur'
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disney Pictures is crowing with justifiable pride over the
hyper-realistic digital images of prehistoric creatures in its
computer-animated summer feature, Dinosaur. But have you noticed
that no one is bragging about the intricacies of the movie's
screenplay?
</P>
<P>
   The film reportedly cost close to $200 million, when the price
of Disney's new digital studio is included in the total. Wasn't
there any money left over for writers with a few new ideas?
</P>
<P>
   Picture The Land Before Time crossed with Tarzan. An abandoned
iguanodon egg hatches, and the orphan reptile Aladar is raised by a
family of nurturing lemurs as one of its own. (Memo to science
teachers: Yes, Disney folks concede they are taking factual
liberties in suggesting that lemurs were around when dinosaurs
roamed the Earth. But these fuzzy monkeys are darned adorable, so
get over it.)
</P>
<P>
   After an earth-scorching meteor shower, the kind that might have
led to the extinction of these giant Barneys, the dinosaurs migrate
in search of their traditional nesting grounds. They trek through
desert that once was fertile land, almost dying of thirst. Of
course, it wouldn't be an animated feature if they did not make it
to the lush valley, but not before we learn a few lessons about not
being bossy, about sticking with the group and about lending a
helping foot to those who are old and slow.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there were a movie that would be better with the sound
turned down, this is it. Still, the visuals are awesome, so sit
back, scan the screen and enjoy. The detail work on the creatures _
both the scales on the dinosaurs and the hairs on the lemurs that
come along for the trek _ is beyond impressive, particularly as
they move and the textures are heightened with the play of light
and shadow. The reptiles look a little too rubbery, but otherwise
you will swear they are real.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the look so striking is the blend of photo-realistic
backgrounds, often digitally enhanced, then combined with the
computer-animated figures in the foreground. Typical of the
powerful cumulative effect is an early majestic shot where a
birdlike oviraptor, clutching the iguanodon egg that will become
our main character, soars over jagged cliffs to, alas, the sounds
of James Newton Howard's heavy-handed music track.
</P>
<P>
   True, these opening scenes are disconcertingly reminiscent of
Moses' harrowing voyage down the Nile in Prince of Egypt, if you
substitute a runaway egg for the baby in the bulrushes. Still, it
is the most involving, lyrical sequence in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the dinosaurs and the lemurs break the mood by
speaking. In English. The movie never quite recovers from this
strategic mistake. In the 60 years since the original Fantasia, the
techniques for depicting animated dinosaurs have made quantum
leaps, but are talking Carnotaurs and Styrachosaurs really
cinematic progress?
</P>
<P>
   With a tab of $200 million, Dinosaur presumably must appeal to
as wide an audience as possible, and that becomes its undoing.
</P>
<P>
   The vivid, violent battles between dinosaurs seem geared to
action-loving teens but are probably too intense for toddlers. At
the same time, the cute, cuddly interplay between the lemurs may
delight tots but will likely make the eyeballs of their older
siblings roll to the backs of their heads. And adults looking for
an interesting story are completely out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
