r e BC-HAMLET-DIRECTOR-TEX     05-18 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMLET-DIRECTOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW POSTMODERN VERSION OF `HAMLET' ISN'T FOR PURISTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In Michael Almereyda's contemporary version of William
Shakespeare's ``Hamlet,'' the melancholy Dane is no longer a Dane
but a New Yorker _ an aspiring filmmaker and the son of the slain
president of Denmark Corp. Hamlet spends a lot of time in the back
of limousines, the ``To be or not to be'' soliloquy plays out in
the action-movie aisles of an empty Blockbuster Video, and firearms
make their way into the climactic swordfight.
</P>
<P>
   And although this all takes place in the year 2000, everyone
speaks in Elizabethan dialogue and iambic pentameter.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it ain't for purists, and Almereyda isn't
apologizing for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare kinda jumped his grave a long time ago,'' the
laconic, 40ish director said during a Dallas stop. ``He can take
anything you throw at him. I think he won't be spinning in his
grave. He's beyond it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Almereyda should know. While researching his version of the
Bard's tragedy, he watched more than 20 film versions of
``Hamlet.'' They included a videotaped Ingmar Bergman stage version
starring ``Fargo's'' Peter Stormare, and a Christopher Plummer
version starring a young Michael Caine as Hamlet's friend, Horatio.
</P>
<P>
   Almereyda's own version _ which clocks in at under two hours,
relatively brief for this play _ stars Ethan Hawke in the title
role, as a confused and depressed young man obsessed with avenging
the murder of his father (playwright Sam Shepard plays the father's
ghost, who vanishes into a Pepsi machine). Hamlet knows that his
uncle, Claudius (Kyle MacLachlan), murdered his father, then
married Hamlet's mother (Diane Venora) and took over _ in this case
_ the family business. Hamlet spends most of the movie trying to
prove it and bring Claudius down, with disastrous consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Hawke brought some affectations to the role _ namely, a wool cap
and tinted, black-rimmed glasses _ making it look like he's
wandering through an early '90s music video instead of a
Shakespeare classic. This, Almereyda admited, isn't entirely
coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``One kind of contemporary Hamlet figure that made it personally
urgent for Ethan was Kurt Cobain,'' the director said, referring to
the Nirvana lead singer who killed himself in 1994. ``You think of
all the contemporary figures who have had promising lives cut
short, by suicide or some kind of violent death, and rock 'n' roll
people figure high on the list as Hamlet-like figures who had a lot
of promise and glamour but have a self-destructive streak, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with the play know it's littered with corpses,
and that vindictiveness grows as the deaths mount. Yet Almereyda
said that Hawke also brought an unusual perspective to the
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He insisted on the idea that the violence in the play should
be regarded (as unintentional) _ that Hamlet's failure to kill his
uncle isn't proof of weak character,'' Almereyda said. ``It's just
the opposite. (He knows it's) bad to kill people. There's nothing
in Shakespeare's work that suggests he thought murder was a good
idea. The way you wrestle with this issue is showing it as a
compulsion, as a command from your father, from your father's
ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing such familiar actors as Hawke, Murray and MacLachlan
speak Shakespeare's words in a 21st-century setting can be jarring,
as if the movie were dubbed into a foreign language. But Almereyda
said that feeling is inescapable for today's audiences, and would
affect any presentation of the Bard's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope (the language) has a kind of natural flow once you get
into it,'' he said. ``There's a kind of threshold where you have to
be patient and allow yourself to get used to it. But I find that
(problem) in almost any production of Shakespeare, whether it's
modern dress or not. The language is different; it's elevated and
ornate, and it's not what you hear walking down the street. But the
thoughts can be expressed in a more natural way than it's often
done. I didn't really want actors to be sputtering and declaiming.
I wanted it to feel more internal and intimate. And I got that, for
the most part.''
</P>
<P>
   Early reviews haven't always agreed. Some praise the movie's
``postmodern'' twist, while others lambaste the film as pretentious
revisionism. Almereyda said he's been more fortunate with early
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had luck in that the film has so far appealed to people
who don't know the play, and also (to) people from Shakespeare
societies,'' he said. ``I decided to be brave and show it to (two
groups of Shakespeare scholars), and they couldn't have been more
enthusiastic about it. I was kind of taken aback. Because they
recognized that it might be severely cut, but the heart of it draws
together a kind of an essence. It's really meant to be an attempted
``Hamlet,'' a collage of ``Hamlet'' and a way of talking about
``Hamlet'' in contemporary terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the arty talk, though, Almereyda does want to make
sure that moviegoers' rears stay in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to scare anyone out of the theater,'' he said.
``I hope the movie's accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
