r e BC-BRITNEYSPEARS-CD-TEX     05-18 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITNEYSPEARS-CD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MORE TIME, AND BADLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All you Britney Spears fans, stop right here.
</P>
<P>
   You're not going to like this review. You're going to hate this
review. You're going to call me and tell me that I'm an old coot
and I just don't understand that she's, like, the greatest thing
ever _ or at least since ``Total Request Live'' or whatever _ and
how lame I am and how cool her clothes are and ...
</P>
<P>
   Just stop. For both of us. Go play this CD again _ I know you
already have it. Trust me. It's better for all concerned.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of you, let me say that if it does nothing else,
``Oops! ... I Did It Again'' lives up to its title. From the
opening title track _ which is ``... Baby One More Time'' with
different lyrics _ to the end, ``Oops!'' is a Xerox copy of her
first CD, which has sold more than 7 million copies and made the
photogenic Louisiana teen the queen among the ever-growing roster
of cute-little-girl pop singers. The vanilla hip-hop beats, the big
choruses (during which Spears' vocals often conveniently disappear
into those of her background singers), the wide-eyed romance of the
lyrics _ it's all firmly in place and packaged with, again, photos
of cute lil' Britney with her usual tight clothes and
toothpaste-commercial smile.
</P>
<P>
   And as usual, Britney is busy with the boys. If she's not
telling a former beau that she's, she's so getting over him on
``Stronger,'' she's telling another that he should quit being
jealous on ``What U See (Is What U Get),'' and telling a third that
he needs to step up and declare his crush on ``Don't Let Me Be the
Last to Know.''
</P>
<P>
   This is hormone-charged teen angst at its most blandly
predictable. Coupled with Spears' featureless, thin voice,
``Oops!'' was bound to be just a rehash of the first CD.
</P>
<P>
   But two factors make it, if anything, worse than that: One is
``Lucky,'' in which a teen starlet by the same name garners all
sorts of fame but is still, gosh darn it, sad. This would seem to
be Spears' big ``Please don't think my life is perfect'' moment,
but you know, given that hers basically is, at least for a
teen-ager, I really can't work up any sympathy. Maybe when she buys
me a $1 million mansion in England to go with hers, I'll be able to
feel her pain.
</P>
<P>
   The other is a cover of ``Satisfaction,'' for which Spears, her
producers and her record company should issue an immediate apology.
</P>
<P>
   Look, it's real simple: Britney Spears came along at the right
time, with the right marketing campaign, the right body and the
right smile. She jumped on the gravy train _ one that, given her
weedy voice, she won't be able to parlay into more interesting
music. This is bloodless pop-by-committee _ but, just like acne and
New Kids on the Block, it won't last forever.
</P>
<P>
   I promise.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Britney Spears
</P>
<P>
   ``Oops! ... I Did It Again''
</P>
<P>
   Jive Records
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
