<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S UP WITH NEW NAMES FOR CAR COLORS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Simon once sang, ``These are the days of miracle and
wonder,'' and though in the auto industry it is engineering rather
than miracle that gives us our wonder, there is still room for
wonderment to emerge on its own in some instances.
</P>
<P>
   And in that vein, I wonder:
</P>
<P>
   --Why Saab, as it produces such fine cars and continues to give
them grace and horsepower, has yet to come out with an
all-wheel-drive vehicle. Volvo's gone there. Audi's gone there.
Porsche has harnessed its 911 Turbo with AWD. Everybody seems to be
going there, and as manufacturers manage to squeeze ever more
horsepower from high-revving, smaller engines, front-wheel-drive
cars, Saab's selling point in days gone by, can't handle the power
without torque steer. AWD is the way to go and Saab ought to be
going there with select models.
</P>
<P>
   --Why it works with consumers when manufacturers attach designer
or outdoor outfitter names to special models. We had the Eddie
Bauer Ford Explorer. Chevrolet's new Avalanche pickup truck/SUV has
a North Face model. And Subaru has just unveiled an L.L. Bean
Outback _ big jump from hunting boots to cars but they've done it.
If Volkswagen manages to produce a new version of the Microbus _ as
it is attempting to do _ can a Peter Max model be far behind? And
will some school bus manufacturer give us the Ken Kesey edition?
</P>
<P>
   --How Pat and Mary Brooks, both in their mid-50s, are doing as
they attempt to drive a 1949 Buick Super ``Woody'' Wagon ``Around
the World in 80 Days.'' The Iowa couple are in a fleet of 40
vintage vehicles that left London earler this week in what is being
called the first motor rally to circumnavigate the globe. They're
all due back in London on July 18. Where do you find Buick parts in
Rangoon?
</P>
<P>
   --Why everybody _ save Jaguar, thank the Lord _ seems to have an
SUV, or several SUVs, in the works. Even Porsche, apparently afraid
consumers will add a competitor's SUV to their garage as a second
car instead of a second Porsche, will build an SUV. I just don't
see it.
</P>
<P>
   --How car companies come up with the names of the colors in
which they'll bathe their cars. Volkswagen brings that to mind this
week with two new colors for the New Beetle: Vapor and Reflex.
Vapor is a variation of blue, and I guess I can see that. But
Reflex is a tint of yellow. VW is calling the new colors so cutting
edge that you will be able to order Beetles in these colors only
over the Internet. Vapor. Reflex. How long before we get an SUV
coated in Imposing, or an overpowered sports car called Skittish? I
saw a diaper-yellow Toyota MR2 Spyder recently that I'd definitely
call Recoil.
</P>
<P>
   --How many of the popular Chrysler PT Cruisers survive intact
and how many get the aftermarket treatment. Already, an aftermarket
outfit called Performance West has come out with a ``PT Bruizer''
that adds racing seats, mesh grille, and a supercharger attached to
the original engine that boosts it from 150 to 210 horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   --If Ford will ever get its act together on the Mustang Cobra,
ballyhooed and long awaited, but plagued by engine problems. Word
is, it will manage to produce around 300 SVT Cobra Rs _ billed as a
$55,000 match for the Porsche Boxster S and the ultimate Pony Car.
Not everyone is going to want to spend $55,000 on a Mustang, so
let's hope Ford gets its act together on the lesser model of the
Cobra.
</P>
<P>
   --And not to pick on Saab, but I still wonder why it never
produced the 900 Turbo 16 EV-1, which back in the mid-80s looked
like a cross between a Sonnett and a Datsun Z. It was a 2+2 with
nearly 170 horsepower _ and with added horsepower and AWD, would
look good even today as sports coupes abound.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
