<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BAPTIST-WOMEN (Undated) _ The Southern Baptists, America's
largest Protestant denomination, have drafted a statement declaring
that women should not be allowed to become pastors. The measure,
set for a vote in June, comes two years after the Southern Baptists
declared that wives should ``submit graciously'' to their husbands
_ a stand that prompted some congregations to quit. By RICHARD
VARA.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN-RITALIN (San Antonio) _ Researchers from the University
of Texas Health Science Center say the drug Adderall might be a
better choice for some hyperactive children than the more widely
prescribed Ritalin. By CINDY TUMIEL.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA (Houston) _ A prominent AIDS researcher has launched
a landmark clinical trial that will test 500 African children with
a new drug combination. Baylor College of Medicine pediatrician
Mark Kline has been a crusader for providing affordable AIDS care
in Africa. By TODD ACKERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   RAILWAY-KILLER (Houston) _ Jurors find admitted serial killer
Angel Maturino Resendiz guilty of capital murder in death of a
Houston doctor. The Mexican drifter, who has admitted killing eight
other people in Kentucky, Illinois and Texas, tells the judge that
he would rather die than spend the rest of his life in prison. By
LISA TEACHEY.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-EXILES (Washington) _ About 60 exiled Chinese dissident
leaders join several Democratic House members to oppose granting
permanent normal trade status to China. The dissidents say Beijing
will not improve its human rights record if the United States helps
the communist government get richer with broader trade deals. By
AUTIN ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   ABUDUCTED-GIRL (Washington) _ A tearful reunion between Laura
Garcia, 8, and her Texas mother has sparked hopes by the State
Department and child advocates for the return of 105 other American
children believed abducted and living in Mexico. ``The problem is
getting bigger and bigger, and we are not getting the kids back,''
says Guillermo Galarza with the National Center for Missing and
Exploited Children in Alexandria, Va. By GARY MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ It is a measure of First Lady
Hillary Clinton's growing confidence as a candidate that she was
willing to share the stage with her husband as she accepted the New
York Democratic nomination for U.S. Senate this week. Her advisers
had wanted him to stay away, fearing that he would upstage her. But
she is a star in her own right now even though she concedes she has
learned that being a candidate's spouse is a lot easier than being
the candidate. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CABINET (Washington) _ Bill Clinton's hard-charging,
scandal-scarred presidency was characterized by rapid staff
turnover at the White House. But surprisingly the two-term chief
executive enjoys the most stable Cabinet of the 20th century. Four
of Clinton's 14 Cabinet officers are on their way to serving the
full eight years of his tenure _ a record in presidential history.
By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   PELOSI-CHINA (Washington) _ After a decade of passionately
leading battles to force China to stop human rights abuses in
exchange for favorable U.S. trading privileges, Rep. Nancy Pelosi
next week faces her steepest uphill battle. That's when the House
takes up the contentious measure to grant Beijing permanent normal
trade relations and end the need for the lawmakers' annual renewal
of its trade status. By JUDY HOLLAND
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ With nimble-footed dexterity,
George W. Bush has soft-shoed his way with some success into
vineyards that once were considered the Democrats' sacred domain.
In doing so, he has seemed to transform Al Gore, who represents the
party that prides itself on its record of social and economic
reform, into a stodgy stand-patter. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
