</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAUR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DINOSAUR': JURASSIC LARK: REX OF THE CARTOON JUNGLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reputedly the most expensive animated feature film ever made,
``Dinosaur'' may also boast the longest, most crowded end credits
in the history of cinema. After the winsome reptilians and their
primate pals, paleontologically doubtful but ever so cute, have
wandered off into the Cretaceous sunset, the screen fills with
rapidly scrolling double columns of names, identifying the few
hundred people who labored to bring those extinct, eternally
fascinating beasts back to life.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly endless list of software designers, code writers
and technicians seems more like a matter for the Justice
Department's antitrust division than a roster of movie-making
talent, but this vast committee, superintended by the directors
Ralph Zondag and Eric Leighton, has used a lot of new-fangled
technology to work some gratifyingly old-fashioned magic.
</P>
<P>
   After learning that ``Dinosaur'' was filmed in a dozen
real-world locations, including Hawaii, Venezuela, Australia and
the Los Angeles County Arboretum, you may expect a disclaimer
vowing that no actual dinosaurs were harmed during production.
Marianne Moore once likened poems to ``imaginary gardens with real
toads in them.'' Walt Disney Pictures has spared no expense to find
real gardens and populate them with meticulously imagined,
computer-generated reptiles.
</P>
<P>
   From an initial close-up of ridged, rippling hide _ evocative of
a breathing, flexing piece of exquisitely textured high-end luggage
_ ``Dinosaur'' begins, in time- and market-tested Disney fashion,
with a breathtaking sequence, a visual and sonic extravaganza that
the rest of the movie never quite lives up to. Those scores of
animators and technical advisers have conjured a teeming pre-human
world, and the first minutes of the film present it in swooping,
eye-filling panorama.
</P>
<P>
   The experience is as luxuriant and intoxicating as a theme park
ride; more remarkably, it feels like a real movie, as if the
flights of giant birds, the stampede of herds and the ruminant
movements of leaf-eaters were all being captured by a camera,
rather than generated inside a computer.
</P>
<P>
   This long ersatz tracking shot follows the progress, airborne
and underwater, of a purloined Iguanadon egg, which at last alights
in a quiet island treetop populated by a clan of friendly lemurs.
At this point, the movie itself touches down in familiar territory
and pursues a narrative cobbled (by half a dozen credited writers
and story-hatchers) from previous Disney films. The egg hatches
into an orphan named Aladar, whose fate is the subject of a debate
between mommy and daddy lemurs almost identical to the argument
between Tarzan's adoptive gorilla parents. Maternalism prevails,
the stern paternal heart is melted, and soon Aladar is a frisky
adolescent capering with his young lemur friends and emoting in the
dulcet tones of D.B. Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   The young dinosaur's identity crisis is pre-empted by a giant
asteroid, which unleashes a barrage of lethal, spectacular effects,
including mushroom cloud, shock wave and firestorm. Don't worry:
This is a Disney film, and mass extinction would be far too
downbeat, but the lemur's leafy paradise is destroyed, along with a
great many lemurs. (Their deaths are carefully implied, rather than
shown, to minimize upset among the youngest viewers.) Aladar
manages to save his family, which includes the requisite gruff
patriarch (Ossie Davis), the wise, nurturing mother (Alfre Woodard)
and the wise-cracking juvenile sidekick (Max Casella, who can't
hope to match Rosie O'Donnell's rambunctious gorilla or Samuel E.
Wright's singing lobster in previous Disney family outings). They
soon stumble upon a herd of dinosaurs making their way to the
promised land _ that is, the nesting grounds _ where all the
diverse, noncarnivorous species will be joined in the circle of
life.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm ahead of the story. Along the way, the trekkers must
contend with predatory carnotaurs (only pedantic 6-year-olds will
object if you insist on calling them T. rexes) and the consequences
of ecological catastrophe as they cross a desert littered with
bleached skeletons and picked-over carcasses. Aladar befriends a
pair of kind, slow, elderly female dinosaurs: Eema, a folksy
Styrachosaur (Della Reese), and Baylene, a sweet, enormous
Brachiosaur (Joan Plowright). He develops a crush on a spirited
female Iguanadon named Neera (Julianna Margulies) and falls afoul
of her brother, Kron ( Wright in a growly turn) and his enforcer,
Bruton (Peter Siragusa).
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry between Kron and Aladar comes down to a disagreement
about survival tactics. Kron, a hard-core Darwinian realist,
insists that only the strong deserve to survive, and that weaklings
and slowpokes like Baylene and Eema should be sacrificed to the
greater good. Aladar, perhaps because he was raised by primates,
embraces more advanced theories of altruism and evolved
cooperation. The dispute is settled in a no-holds-barred saurian
alpha male smack-down, the outcome of which is hardly in doubt. In
a Disney movie, after all, good always triumphs over evil _ or, in
the moral idiom of the target audience, the nice ones beat the mean
ones.
</P>
<P>
   And the mean ones are pretty convincingly mean. Although nobody
knows what dinosaurs sounded like _ there is a rough consensus
among paleontologists that they didn't sound like D.B. Sweeney or
Margulies _ the soundtrack is full of plausibly reptilian (or
proto-avian, since it's now thought that they evolved into birds)
roars, bellows and coos. The reason to see this movie is not to
listen to the dinosaurs but to watch them move, to marvel at their
graceful necks and clumsy limbs and notice how convincingly they
emerge into sunlight or get wet.
</P>
<P>
   The state of the art evolves so rapidly that Aladar may soon
look as cheesy as Godzilla to the children already clamoring for
toys made in his likeness. Adults who grew up on traditional
animation may notice the seams between the computer-generated
figures and their real backgrounds and wish that the figures
themselves had more warmth and substance. But I'm loath to
contradict the opinion of the preschool cinephile and dinosaur
enthusiast in whose company I saw the movie. ``What did you think
of it?'' I asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary and cool and nice,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   What more could you want?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DINOSAUR'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ralph Zondag and Eric Leighton; written by John
Harrison and Robert Nelson Jacobs, based on an original screenplay
by Walon Green; visual effects supervisor, Neil Krepela; edited by
H. Lee Peterson; music by James Newton Howard; production designer,
Walter P. Martishius; produced by Pam Marsden; released by Walt
Disney Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   WITH THE VOICES OF: D.B. Sweeney (Aladar), Alfre Woodard (Plio),
Ossie Davis (Yar), Max Casella (Zini), Hayden Panettiere (Suri),
Samuel E. Wright (Kron), Julianna Margulies (Neera), Peter Siragusa
(Bruton), Joan Plowright (Baylene) and Della Reese (Eema). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes. ``Dinosaur'' is rated PG (Parental
guidance suggested). Younger children may be upset by the deaths of
several important characters and overwhelmed by scenes of
prehistoric mayhem and destruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
