<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9058 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     05-18 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH'S OLD SOFT-SHOE ROUTINE PUTS GORE ON THE DEFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, May 21)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the nimble-footed dexterity of Gene Kelly
singing and dancing amid a torrent of raindrops, George W. Bush
taps his way with confidence from one ideological camp to another.
In doing that, he often dismays his friends and disarms his foes.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, he overwhelmed his opponents in South Carolina's
Republican primary because pillars of the religious right believed
he stood as one with them and Pat Robertson in their opposition to
abortion in any form or for any reason. At the same time,
unreconstructed Southerners reveled in Bush's contention that
flying the Confederate flag, a last sad symbol of slavery, over the
state capital is nobody's business but theirs.
</P>
<P>
   When his visit to Bob Jones University ignited a bonfire of
controversy, Bush quickly claimed he was sorry he had not spoken
out against the school's religious and racial bigotry. He also
wrote to New York's influential Cardinal John O'Connor to deny that
he had any prejudice against Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush then donned the raiment of Republican moderate and won
enough delegate votes to clinch the party's presidential
nomination. Next, he soft-shoed his way with some success into
vineyards that once were considered the Democrats' sacred domain.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, he has seemed to transform Al Gore, the candidate
of the party that traditionally prides itself on its record of
social and economic reform, into a stodgy stand-patter.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Gore is cast in the old Republican role of
defender of the status quo. When Bush unveils an initiative _ as he
has done with taxes, education and Social Security _ Gore
undertakes the thankless task of saying no. He may be right, but he
sounds negative.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has latched onto proposals that Republicans have been
advancing for some time: school vouchers, the investment of Social
Security funds in the stock market and a massive tax cut similar to
President Ronald Reagan's 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On gun control, Bush has announced that he will make trigger
safety locks for handguns available across Texas and, if elected
president, throughout the nation. His initiative is a shrewd one
that may please some advocates of gun control, while not
displeasing the nay-sayers of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   On education, Gore appears to be defending the current,
oft-criticized public school system while Bush claims his plan
would give parents a greater choice in the education of their
children through taxpayer-supported vouchers that would permit them
to attend private schools, including parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gore argues that it is unconstitutional and wrong to use public
funds to enroll children in religious schools and that the better
course is to hire more and better teachers and improve public
school facilities. But his words do not appear to win voter
approval in the way that Bush's do.
</P>
<P>
   Yet under Bush's plan a lot of children could be disappointed.
They would discover that the facilities of private schools,
parochial or otherwise, are often limited and that most youngsters
will have to remain where they are while tax money provides the way
to possibly better schools for some of their friends.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Social Security, Bush advocates that younger
contributors to the 65-year old system be permitted to invest in
personal retirement accounts whose income would be derived from the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   That might be all right for individuals who understand the
erratic ways of the market and the fact that they can lose as well
as gain by investing part of their retirement income themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Would the federal government be willing to step in and reimburse
them for their losses? Or would they find themselves in their
sixties, seventies and eighties trying to live off far less income
than they had anticipated?
</P>
<P>
   Social Security was created by Franklin D. Roosevelt and
Congress in 1935, at the depth of the Great Depression when few
private businesses provided pensions for their employees. It has
been one of the greatest, if not the greatest, of programs created
by the federal government to help people.
</P>
<P>
   Where seniors once found themselves homeless and money-less,
they now can depend at least on the stipend from Social Security.
Millions of Americans have almost nothing besides Social Security
and Medicare to sustain them in their sunset years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many Americans like to gamble and take chances that
could lead to financial betterment, which is why they flock to
racetracks and buy lottery tickets. Many already are in the stock
market and doing quite well. But the market is not always going to
be as buoyant is it has been in recent years. The national economy
is certain to decline to some degree in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Before we leap we should look very carefully at where we're
going. Meanwhile, it might do Al Gore good to don some dancing
slippers and tap his way through the remainder of the campaign,
unveiling popular initiatives as he bounces along.
</P>
<P>
   Time is on his side. Election Day is more than five months away.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert E. Thompson can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
