u e BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT     05-18 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conan Doyle, on Holmes
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really terribly important after the war when all the
young men needed contacting,'' Sir Arthur Conan Doyle says rather
breezily on camera during a 10-minute address he delivers on a DVD
recently released by Focusfilm, a distributor in Ossining, N.Y. It
was 1926, and by his remarks and manner the writer clearly wants to
be done with his celebrated creation, the detective Sherlock
Holmes, and move on to matters that he considers more serious:
psychic experiences and communication with the beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The young men he refers to were killed during World War I.
Holmes, he seems to imply, would be better off laid to rest himself
if only the public would permit it. One gets the impression that
Conan Doyle agreed to speak about his detective only if he could
then devote most of his talk to spiritual matters. People are
convinced Holmes is alive, he says incredulously. Women propose to
him. As if to calm alarmists, he adds that of course he will go on
writing about Holmes and his ``rather stupid friend Watson.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same disc, part of a set of four, is ``Terror by Night,''
a Holmes adventure filmed by Universal during the '40s with Basil
Rathbone as the detective and Nigel Bruce as Watson. At 54 minutes,
it is the shortest of a dozen of Rathbone's Holmes films and takes
place entirely on a train as the detective reveals everything about
the theft of the fabled Star of Rhodesia diamond, including the
fact that it really wasn't stolen at all but remained in Holmes'
pocket throughout the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The detective brings off other nice surprises in three other
cases on the discs: ``Sherlock Holmes and the Secret Weapon''
(1942), ``The Woman in Green'' (1945) and ``Dressed to Kill''
(1946), which was Rathbone's last Holmes film. By then he had
played the role more than 200 times, not only on screen but on the
radio in ``The New Adventures of Sherlock Holmes.'' In those days,
stars walked over to the sound stage after they were finished on
the set. Nearly four hours of these broadcasts are on each disc,
with dozens of cases involving the likes of the unfortunate
tobacconist, demon barber, headless monk and guileless gypsy.
</P>
<P>
   Though aloof and inscrutable, Rathbone's Holmes is warmer and
less severe than Jermey Brett's in the BBC television series.
Gentle fun is made of Watson, a bumbler with old-school chums
called Stinky and the Major. Women are ravishing and dangerous in
the way they often were in '40s films, especially Patricia Morrison
in ``Dressed to Kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Rathbone naturally took to disguises, which are as plentiful as
trunks and caskets with false bottoms. In ``The Woman in Green,''
Professor Moriarty, Holmes' arch-enemy, reappears, played by Henry
Daniell, whom Rathbone called the most effective of the Moriartys.
</P>
<P>
   The movies come from the National Film Museum, a large archive
in Bangor, Me., that provides old film to producers and
distributors. As with many DVD's, the picture quality is only as
good as the original materials. ``They'd gone the gamut into
television release and other things,'' said Al Taylor, the
company's president. ``There were only old library prints so we had
to do a lot.'' It was enough.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Sleepy Hollow
</P>
<P>
   Heads roll and roll in Tim Burton's exuberantly dark and
expressionistic reworking of the Washington Irving story. Sent up
the Hudson River to investigate some killings, the squeamish
detective Ichabod Crane (Johnny Depp, left, with Christina Ricci)
encounters a horseman from hell (Christopher Walken), headless
himself, hacking a seemingly random swath through the
conspiratorial citizenry of Sleepy Hollow. Burton renders the
Irving story unrecognizable, but an ornate fantasy should make its
own rules, and, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``
`Sleepy Hollow' does that with macabre gusto.''
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Paramount. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 105 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: May 23.
</P>
<P>
   The World Is Not Enough
</P>
<P>
   From a traditional swift opening, Michael Apted's film lifts the
James Bond franchise onto a somewhat more mature plane. As Elektra,
Sophie Marceau gets slinky costumes and skiing and boudoir
sequences befitting an ally of the terrorist Renard (Robert
Carlyle). Conversely, Denise Richards seems barely out of high
school as a scientist whose expertise with plutonium is counted
upon to deliver the world from Renard. The elevation is provided by
007 himself. In his third Bond film, Pierce Brosnan ``bears
noticeably more resemblance to a real human being'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. MGM. $19.98; DVD, $34.98. 128 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Anywhere but Here
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Tumbleweeds,'' Wayne Wang's film follows a mother and
daughter on a cross-country escape. ``You're gonna die one day too,
Mom, just like the rest of us,'' the 14-year-old Ann (Natalie
Portman) says sarcastically to her mother, Adele (Susan Sarandon),
before the two leave Bay City, Wis. ``But not in this town,'' Adele
replies. For no good reason Adele has gotten it into her head that
life holds more promise in Beverly Hills, Calif. Being the more
mature of the two, Ann tries to be a teen-ager while acting as
anchor for a childish parent. As for Wang, he ``once again works
splendidly with actresses, and boy, does he have a lot to work with
this time'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Fox. $107.37; DVD, $34.98. 114 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Eye of the Beholder
</P>
<P>
   A peripatetic psychopathic killer (Ashley Judd) changes wigs and
aliases every few minutes on a deadly run from New York to Alaska.
On her trail, a British intelligence agent and surveillance expert
called the Eye (Ewan McGregor) always stays in the same hotel as
she does, pressing his ear to the bathroom tile to hear her
splashing around in the tub beyond the wall. The Eye also has
visions of the young daughter he hasn't seen in years, which leaves
him consumed with guilt, or so we are left to believe in Stephan
Elliott's ``impenetrable mess of a movie'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _2000. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77; DVD, $24.95. 102 minutes.
Closed captioned. Release date: May 23.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOURCE. Chuck Workman's stirring kaleidoscopic documentary
with dramatized readings reveals much about the Beat writers Jack
Kerouac, Allen Ginsberg and William Burroughs. (Even viewers who
know a lot about Kerouac may be surprised by his later talk-show
appearances.) Johnny Depp intones Kerouac, Dennis Hopper echoes
Burroughs and John Turturro puts fierce emotion into Ginsberg's
``Howl.'' Those interviewed include Ginsberg, Kerouac, Neal Cassady
and Norman Mailer, and music is provided by Philip Glass, Bob
Dylan, Dizzy Gillespie, Thelonious Monk and many others. ``However
well known the assorted Beat legends have become,'' Janet Maslin
wrote in The New York Times, ``there is a cumulative power to
seeing so many of them evoked so colorfully in a single film.''
1999. Winstar. $19.98; DVD, $24.98. 89 minutes. No rating. Release
date: May 23.
</P>
<P>
   THE MAN WITH BOGART'S FACE. A former cop (Robert Sacchi)
remodels himself to look like his favorite tough guy, and slides
into a Bogey-style case resembling ``The Maltese Falcon.'' Sacchi
is fine in Robert Day's film, adapted from Andrew J. Fenaday's
novel, and Victor Buono and Herbert Lom do nicely in the
``Falcon's'' Sidney Greenstreet and Peter Lorre roles. 1980. Fox.
$9.98. 106 minutes. PG. Release date: May 23.
</P>
<P>
   MESMER. Alan Rickman stars as the 18th-century Viennese
hypnotist and self-promoter in Roger Spottiswoode's film, written
by Dennis Potter. 1994. First Look. $24.98. 107 minutes. Release
date. May 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
