<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-CROOKS0519-COX     05-18 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-CROOKS0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Small Time' is a good time
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Remember the space alien in Woody Allen's
``Stardust Memories'' who advised him to make funnier movies?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the prolific director-screenwriter either just got the
message or momentarily ran dry of personal crises to base his
latest movie on.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, ``Small Time Crooks'' is a refreshingly
angst-free, lightweight entertainment, an unalloyed comedy that
will bring to mind his 1969 filmmaking debut, ``Take the Money and
Run.''
</P>
<P>
   For Allen is back as a schlemiel of a bank-robber wannabe, lowly
ex-con-turned-dishwasher Ray Winkler, who yearns to tunnel into a
New York bank, steal a couple of million bucks and flee to a new
life in Miami. But first he has to talk his manicurist wife,
Frenchy (a frumpy, shrewish Tracy Ullman), into giving him their
life savings for heist supplies. And get her to pose as a cookie
baker in a shop near the bank, while he and a band of truly stupid
accomplices drill loudly in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Italian caper picture ``Big Deal on Madonna Street''
that may have been Allen's inspiration, the crooks are completely
inept and soon caught. The first 20 minutes of ``Small Time
Crooks'' is all obvious humor, saved only by the performances.
Notably, there is Elaine May as Frenchy's dense cousin May, who
knows nothing about the bank job yet still gives them away.
Fortunately, Allen soon gets bored with this plot and shifts away
from it to focus on the consequences of Frenchy's extraordinary
success with her cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, she is franchising her recipes, rolling in dough and
indulging her excessive taste in clothes and furnishings. Steve
Kroft of ``60 Minutes'' even does a cream-puff feature on her
eccentric Sunset Farms corporation. Frenchy can buy anything but
what she really wants _ respect. She is courted by the board
members of opera societies and museums, who gleefully take her
money and laugh behind her back.
</P>
<P>
   Frenchy itches to become cultured, while Ray is content to watch
television at home in his underwear, so they drift apart.
Eventually, Frenchy encounters far bigger time crooks than Ray
could ever dream of becoming. A solicitous Hugh Grant educates her
in life's finer things in order to tap into her wealth, while her
accountant is simply an embezzler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Time Crooks'' is funny, not profound. Settle happily for
some amusing broad comedy and the message that money isn't
everything, so we should appreciate what we have.
</P>
<P>
   Appreciate Ullman, who blooms as she goes corporate, wearing
wacky Suzanne McCabe gowns with eccentric flair. The character is
too cartoonish to take very seriously, yet as she gets duped by
Grant, Ullman makes us care about her. Appreciate May, who has been
away from performing too long. Her ditsy, socially inept role is a
stock character, not far from the one May wrote for herself in ``A
New Leaf `` almost 30 years ago. But she gives each line a
delicious spin that continues to earn laughs, even when you can see
the joke coming from far off.
</P>
<P>
   No offense to Kenneth Branagh and Sean Penn, who have starred in
recent Allen features, but no one can deliver his dialogue quite
like he can. As Ray, he adds a blue-collar touch that feels a bit
forced, but Allen's comic timing is otherwise pitch-perfect, and he
plays off Ullman so well.
</P>
<P>
   His movies probably never will have wide appeal, but this one
should prove more popular than most of his releases of the past
decade. Allen used to make films influenced by the dour Ingmar
Bergman. As the banter between Ray and Frenchy suggests, as well as
the final line of the movie, ``Small Time Crooks'' is his homage to
``The Honeymooners.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
