<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUNCHKIN0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's no place like Oz
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ali Sharp does not know who the short man in the
white get-up is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see me in `The Terror of Tiny Town'? '' he asks. ``I
had seven parts in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he continues, his eyes growing wider with excitement as
the 12-year-old girl's grow wider with confusion. ``I played the
foreman of the ranch, the stagecoach driver, a member of the
sheriff's posse, a bad guy the sheriff's posse was chasing, a
double for two men when they mounted and dismounted horses, and I
was also singing in a bar scene.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee,'' says Ali, still clueless.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Swensen hugs her and goes on to meet the next person in
line at the Northcross Mall promotional event for ``The Wizard on
Ice.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ali is a bit confused, maybe it's because the producers of
this retelling of ``The Wizard of Oz'' didn't hire Swensen on the
basis of his star turns in ``The Terror of Tiny Town.'' They hired
the Pflugerville resident because 62 years ago he received the
greatest honor a midget actor knows: He was cast as a Munchkin.
</P>
<P>
   When someone tells Ali that meeting Swensen is huge _ he is one
of only 11 surviving cast members, all Munchkins _ she returns.
This time, Swensen demonstrates the ``German goose step march''
that he and the other Munchkin soldiers did right before Dorothy
followed The Yellow Brick Road.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Ali is amused. ``Wow, I'm not going to wash my hands
now,'' she says. ``No, I'm not going to take a bath. He hugged
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Swensen, all 4 feet 6 3/4 inches of him, has made another person
happy.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Austin, Clarence ``Shorty'' Swensen has never bragged
about his celluloid immortality. He never mentioned it to
co-workers during his 28 years as an electronic technician at the
University of Texas. Just once, when his three children were in
grade school, did he speak to a class about it.
</P>
<P>
   A minor role by all accounts, it has nonetheless made him a star
to the Oz world. There is one, you know. Oz, which this year is
celebrating its centennial as a fictional realm, is a hot
commodity. Oz memorabilia sells at inflated prices on eBay. The
International Wizard of Oz Club boasts 2,500 members and its own
Web site (www.ozclub.org). And America's three Oz festivals attract
hundreds of thousands of fans every year.
</P>
<P>
   Only eight years ago, when he started making public appearances,
did Swensen begin to embrace their attention. Why? ``It has enabled
me to see everything that is great and beautiful,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   LETTER OUT OF NOWHERE
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, the 19-year-old Shorty _ the nickname he got at Allan
Junior High _ was invited to join Stanley R. Graham's All Midget
Circus at the Texas Centennial Fair in Dallas. John and Winifred
Clifton of Austin, billed as the only midget couple in the world
with a midget child (Myrna, age 10), knew Swensen and put in a good
word. John Clifton, one of the original Buster Browns who traveled
the country making appearances for the shoe company, had a lot of
clout in the midget community.
</P>
<P>
   Swensen had little talent, so he sold tickets. He didn't see the
work as demeaning, like carnival freaks put on exhibit. Midgets,
many of them uneducated, had a hard time finding other work.
</P>
<P>
   The All Midget Circus folded a year later, when a string of
rainy days kept people away in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Swensen returned to Austin to try to finish high school. But his
academic career was interrupted by ``the letter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a round-trip train ticket in it,'' he says, still
surprised. All the midgets connected with the circus got the same
letters.
</P>
<P>
   He was instructed to travel to Los Angeles to ``be in a movie.''
It turned out to be ``The Terror of Tiny Town,'' an all-midget
Western now regarded as one of the worst films ever made.
</P>
<P>
   His second film was one of the best. MGM tried to find 300
midgets to dance and sing and protect Dorothy from the Wicked Witch
of the West, but could only locate 125. Children were used to fill
out the crowd shots.
</P>
<P>
   He earned $50 a week, $700 total. Toto, Dorothy's dog, had a
better agent; he got $125. ``I looked at it as just a job,'' he
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   If you look closely, you can spot Swensen in the Munchkin Land
scene when Dorothy gets in the carriage to head to Emerald City.
``We're marching behind the carriage, right to left on the screen.
I'm the first soldier on the fourth row, camera side,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He got to talk to Judy Garland twice, and she was ``nice. She
invited some of us to walk through her dressing room. We got a kick
out of that.'' He treasures an autographed picture Garland gave him
_ his only memento of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   During the filming, he got his third movie part, in ``Tarzan
Finds A Son,'' starring Johnny Weissmuller. This paycheck was even
bigger: $800. He played a chimpanzee.
</P>
<P>
   BACK TO AUSTIN
</P>
<P>
   After the limelight, Swensen returned to Austin to again pursue
a high school diploma. He was working for the National Youth
Administration when World War II broke out. He landed a job as a
radio technician at Kelly Air Force Base in San Antonio. One
weekend in 1941, the 24-year-old returned home one Saturday and
took in a movie at the Paramount. He was heading to the bus stop,
when he ran into his old colleagues the Cliftons and their daughter
Myrna, now 16.
</P>
<P>
   He talked to the Cliftons but couldn't keep his eyes off the
beautiful girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came home every weekend after that,'' says Myrna. They got
married in 1945 and had three daughters _ two are midgets _ who
have given them five grandchildren (none midgets).
</P>
<P>
   Swensen joined UT and remained there until 1973, when he moved
to a state job delivering in-house mail. He retired in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   All those years, and hardly a mention of his role in one of the
most celebrated films of all time. In fact, he can't remember when
he first saw the movie. It was several years after it was released.
``To me, it was just a movie. I had a small part and that was it. I
watched it and I thought it was a nice movie,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   At school, his kids never bragged about their dad's obscure
fame. Maybe a neighbor knew, but that was it.
</P>
<P>
   TIME AGAIN IN OZ Until 1989, when he was invited to attend the
movie's 50th anniversary in Liberal, Kansas. This was his first
contact with any of Munchkins since the making of the film. After
that, he was invited to the annual Oz celebrations in Chesterton,
Ind., and Chittenango, N.Y., the birthplace of Frank Baum, who
wrote the original ``The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'' 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go because of the kids that we meet. They bring a tear to my
eye and I begin to live it all again. And the adults who yell, `Oh!
There's a Munchkin! A real live Munchkin!' They get more excited
than the children,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   When Steven Cox, author of ``The Munchkins Remember'' and ``The
Munchkins of Oz,'' met Swensen in 1988 to interview him for the
first book, he was ``hesitant and suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't understand why anyone would be interested in a job
he had 50 years ago that lasted a few weeks. It's overwhelmed him.
He's surprised that people have become fans. None of the Munchkins
had any idea what the fascination was from the rest of the country
and the world,'' says Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Swensen now understands all the fuss. He and Myrna receive
all-expense paid trips to the three Oz festivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They treat us grand,'' says Swensen. ``It's probably the best
thing in the world that's happened to me, getting to meet the other
Munchkins at the festivals. `Munchkin' is a family name to us, you
know.''
</P>
<P>
   At the festivals, he sells autographed pictures of himself in
Munchkin soldier costume for $10. Cox says he's seen the pictures
sell for $50 on eBay. Myrna, who has been making beaded Christmas
ornaments for many years, started making Oz ornaments 10 years ago
and selling them at the festivals. The set of eight _ Dorothy,
Toto, Scarecrow, Tinman, Cowardly Lion, Glinda the good witch, the
Wicked Witch of the West and a Munchkin soldier _ sells for $44.
They go quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had offers to sell them on the Internet, but I can't even
keep up with the orders now,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   People have offered to sell them in collector shops and even
mass produce them, but she's turned them down. ``Then they're not
made by a wife of a Munchkin,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Swensen hopes to keep this up a long time. He's 82 but looks
much younger.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many more people he can make happy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because of the wonderful things he does.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
