<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAXAHACHIE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT ARCHITECTURE AND CULTURAL SCENE: WAXAHACHIE'S PLEASURES ARE
BOUNTIFUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAXAHACHIE, Texas _ For 10 or 15 minutes, I have been happily
admiring the orderly displays at the Ellis County Museum _ a
beautiful collection of silk and ivory fans from France and Japan,
antique china pitchers from England, Victorian dresses,
100-year-old quilts. But when two young backpackers wander into the
museum, which also serves as a visitors' center for this small
Ellis County city, I can't help but eavesdrop.
</P>
<P>
   They're looking for a nearby campground and, I presume, the
location of Scarborough Faire, the Renaissance festival that's been
held in the spring hereabouts for 20 years. But a museum volunteer
also takes time to tell them a little story about the majestic
courthouse in the square, half-obscured by scaffolding and security
fencing.
</P>
<P>
   She tells them the basics, that it's more than 100 years old and
undergoing a renovation. Then she adds that if they look carefully,
they should still be able to see the fantastic and grotesque
carvings decorating the sandstone and granite structure. Maybe it
isn't true, she allows, but local legend has it that the stone
carver who created these angry and evil creatures did so after
being spurned by a local woman, Mabel Frame _ and that the one
beautiful face was there only because the carver completed it
before she rejected him.
</P>
<P>
   The kids leave, charmed; later, sure enough, I see them standing
in front of the courthouse, peering and pointing. Waxahachie had
won a couple more fans.
</P>
<P>
   Day-trippers might come here first for Scarborough Faire or to
eat lunch and shop for antiques on the appealing square. But what
hooks them is the history. In addition to the 1894-built
courthouse, Waxahachie is home to more than 150 original Victorian
gingerbread houses, scattered throughout town like so many gorgeous
surprises, earning it the nickname ``Gingerbread City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a child, I didn't realize what a jewel we had
here,'' says Hilda Chapman, a Waxahachie native who owns the
Gingerbread Antique Mall in a renovated building where her father
once had a car dealership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost some wonderful old things, but we don't want to
lose any more. We have a very active historical society, and we've
been able to keep the ambience of the old town.''
</P>
<P>
   The homes, for the most part, date from around the turn of the
century, when Waxahachie, settled on the banks of Waxahachie Creek
in 1851, began to prosper from the cattle and cotton industries.
Though several have been turned into bed-and-breakfast inns, most
are still private homes; a few are open for perusing every June
during the Gingerbread Trail tour of homes. (This year's tour is
the weekend of June 3-4.)
</P>
<P>
   However, there's plenty to enjoy from outside. Take one or both
of the amazingly detailed, easy-to-follow driving tours prepared by
Historic Waxahachie Inc., and you'll see many of the town's
highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Like the aforementioned courthouse, one of the most beautiful in
the state. Currently closed for renovation, it's interesting for
its architecture alone _ the castlelike reddish stone structure,
embellished with turrets, towers and intricate stone carvings, cost
$175,000 when it was built.
</P>
<P>
   And the Chautauqua Auditorium, an octagonal amphitheater that
serves as a rare physical reminder of a nationwide literary and
scientific society popular from about 1900 to 1930. This
wood-shuttered building, one of only three remaining in the United
States, was once one of many across the nation that hosted summer
meetings that were one part entertainment, one part education.
Religious leaders, authors, musicians, actors and singers took the
stage here, drawing thousands; Waxahachie's auditorium, on the edge
of Getzendaner Park, was restored in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a string of lovely homes, some mansions, some
rather modest, in styles ranging from Queen Anne to prairie to
neoclassical revival. Drive slowly and stop to admire the details:
a frieze on a porch, a delicate wrought-iron fence, a set of fluted
Ionic columns, a formal garden in full bloom. It's no wonder that a
number of Hollywood movies have been filmed using Waxahachie homes
and businesses, including ``Tender Mercies,'' ``Places in the
Heart,'' ``Bonnie &AMP; Clyde,'' ``Square Dance'' and ``The Trip to
Bountiful.'' (The Waxahachie Chamber of Commerce publishes a
brochure that tells which buildings were used for which films.)
</P>
<P>
   And downtown, where you begin and end these driving tours, is
one of the best revival stories _ the Rogers Hotel, set to reopen
this summer after a massive renovation.
</P>
<P>
   When it opened in 1912, the hotel had a grand roof garden and
such modern amenities as hot and cold water in the private baths,
telephones, electric lights, and a dumbwaiter. But like many
small-town hotels, it fell on hard times; by the 1950s, at least
one guest recalled being met in his room by a bevy of bats. The
hotel closed in the '60s, and though there were sporadic attempts
at revival, perhaps as an apartment building or seniors housing,
most citizens had pretty much given it up for dead.
</P>
<P>
   Then Dallas investor Anthony Cimino, looking for property in
town to renovate, happened across the building. He wasn't really
looking to build a hotel, but that seemed the natural use for it;
the downstairs lobby had earlier been renovated into a casual
upscale restaurant, now known as the Crazy Horse Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, we just got excited about it in our family and
just kind of plowed ahead,'' Cimino says. ``We're just trying to
preserve as much of the original character as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Cimino hopes the hotel will begin accepting guests this summer
in 27 oversized, totally renovated rooms. The hotel had been empty
so long that virtually none of the remaining furniture or bathroom
fixtures was usable, says project director Herb Dowlearn. However,
they've saved numerous antique doorknobs, etched glass transoms,
etched iron radiators and heavy wooden doors and are trying to
incorporate them into the design. New furniture has been purchased
that matches the period, such as sleigh beds and marble-topped
dressers, Cimino says.
</P>
<P>
   Cimino was probably attracted to the property at least partly by
the factor that has attracted other new businesses in the past few
years _ the square's growing reputation as a unique place to while
away the afternoon, eating at one of the half-dozen interesting
little independent restaurants or browsing through a growing
selection of antiques shops and boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce and Julie Webb, whose Webb Gallery for self-taught and
folk artists is worth a drive to town all by itself, have been
there since the beginning of the renaissance. Their brightly
painted storefront, in a renovated old paint store just off the
square, is a light, airy space filled with hulking metal
sculptures, colorful primitive paintings, and such engaging
oddities as an intricate motorized carnival, built primarily from
toothpicks.
</P>
<P>
   The Webbs might not have expected much local support when they
moved from Dallas to the town in 1987, but then they've seen a lot
of change since then. And they like what they see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Across the board, things have gotten more culturally varied,
and we like the whole atmosphere, with the coffee shops and the
restaurants open downtown and people starting to move into the
lofts of some of the older buildings,'' Bruce Webb says. ``It's
definitely beginning to develop its own sense of community.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the kind of thing that brings daytrippers back, again
and again.
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9083 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CHILDREN-RITALIN-HNS &LR;      05-18 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-RITALIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDY SHOWS CHILDREN RESPOND BETTER TO RITALIN ALTERNATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CINDY TUMIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A study directed by a physician at the University
of Texas Health Science Center has concluded that a drug called
Adderall might be a better choice for some hyperactive children
than the more widely prescribed Ritalin.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the children in the study took only a single dose of
Adderall daily, and researchers said its overall performance was
better than methylphenidate, the generic version of Ritalin.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven Pliszka, chief of child and adolescent psychiatry at
the University of Texas Health Science Center, was the lead
investigator in the study published this month in the Journal of
the American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry. Funding
for the research came from Shire Richwood Inc., a subsidiary of
Adderall manufacturer Shire Pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 2 million children in the United States have
attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), which is marked by
symptoms that include inattention, distractibility and
hyperactivity. Stimulant-based medication long has been the primary
treatment for the disorder, and methylphenidate has accounted for
80 percent of the prescriptions written during the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Adderall, a mixture of two types of amphetamines, initially was
developed as a weight loss drug in the 1960s and later fell out of
use. The manufacturer revived it several years ago after tests
showed it was effective in treating ADHD. It has been used largely
for children who don't respond to methylphenidate.
</P>
<P>
   Pliszka's study is part of an effort by doctors to compare the
two drugs in controlled tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that we can use Adderall first,'' Pliszka said.
``Physicians and families should feel very comfortable about using
it. That's the main finding of this study.''
</P>
<P>
   The study involved 58 children who got Adderall, methylphenidate
or a placebo _ a harmless, unmedicated preparation _ for three
weeks. During that time, the children were evaluated periodically
by teachers and parents, using a scale that assessed whether their
behavior and attention problems were improving.
</P>
<P>
   Pliszka said the research showed both medications were superior
to the placebo and that Adderall performed better than
methylphenidate. Seventy percent of the children on Adderall also
were able to get by on one dose a day, eliminating the need for
midday medication, Pliszka said.
</P>
<P>
   That finding could be an important point for Shire, because new
drugs are entering the marketplace that are designed for once-a-day
dosing. Pharmaceutical giant Johnson &AMP; Johnson is seeking federal
approval for its new drug, Concerta, which will offer single-dose
convenience. The company expects to begin marketing the drug later
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ritalin is manufactured by CIBA-Geigy Corp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Cindy Tumiel by e-mail at ctumiel(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
