<HEADER>
A9086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     05-18 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, May 19. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ In a victory for the Clinton
administration, the Senate on Thursday narrowly killed a measure to
set a deadline for withdrawing American ground troops from Kosovo,
a proposal that also had drawn fire from Gov. George W. Bush. By a
53-47 vote, senators stripped a provision from a military
construction spending bill that would have cut off funds for the
5,600 U.S. forces in Kosovo by July 1, 2001, forcing their orderly
withdrawal unless Congress authorized the mission's extension. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BUSH (Austin, Texas) _ With his remarks in recent days on
China trade and Senate efforts to set a time limit on the Kosovo
deployment, Gov. George W. Bush has shown himself to be squarely in
a Republican tradition of internationalism and of favoring
presidential supremacy in the making of foreign policy. In short,
he has looked very much like his father. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   DOMINICAN-ELECT (Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic) _ The
runner-up candidates withdrew from the Dominican presidential race
Thursday, recognizing a first-round victory by a populist who
promises to spread the benefits of a four-year economic boom to the
poor. (Summary from wires) By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAG (Atlanta) _ After 38 years of conducting the state's
business under the Confederate battle flag, the two houses of the
South Carolina General Assembly voted Thursday to remove the flag
from the Capitol dome and their chambers. At noon on July 1, South
Carolina will become the last state to remove the old symbol of
secession from its seat of government. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE (Dateline TK) _ In a scathing report, the
Interior Department said the fire that destroyed more than 200
homes in Los Alamos was caused by numerous failures by Park Service
officials who started a fire to destroy underbrush. The officials
failed to properly plan for the fire, check weather and ground
conditions or coordinate and communicate with each other, Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt said in releasing the report Thursday. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   NH-DEATH-PENALTY (Concord, N.H.) _ With a vote by the New
Hampshire Senate on Thursday, the state Legislature approved a bill
to repeal the death penalty, something no other state has done
since the U.S. Supreme Court allowed the reinstatement of capital
punishment 23 years ago. But the 14-10 vote was two votes short of
the margin needed to override the veto that Gov. Jeanne Shaheen has
promised. (Summary from wires) By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KIMES-TRIAL (New York) _ Sante and Kenneth Kimes, an accused
mother-and-son team of con artists, were found guilty Thursday of
murdering a wealthy Manhattan widow as part of an elaborate scheme
to seize control her $8 million townhouse. Relying entirely on
circumstantial evidence, prosecutors convinced the jurors that the
Kimeses killed Irene Silverman, 82, in April 1998 and disposed of
her body. Mrs. Silverman's body has never been found, and defense
lawyers for the Kimeses insisted that their clients were scapegoats
in a vast conspiracy. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-TIMEWARNER (New York) _ Time Warner and Walt Disney Co.
have reached an agreement in principle that will end their
rancorous dispute over the cable carriage of television networks
owned by Disney, the Time Warner chairman, Gerald M. Levin, told
shareholders at the company's annual meeting Thursday. Neither Time
Warner nor Disney executives would discuss the specific details of
the agreement, saying that it needs to be committed first to
contractual language. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STRESS-WOMEN (Undated) _ For more than a half century,
scientific gospel has held that animals, including humans, respond
to stress by preparing to do battle or to flee, a physiological
syndrome commonly known as ``fight or flight.'' But in a newly
published report, a group of researchers asserts that females often
show a very different reaction to stress, one that revolves around
nurturing and seeking the support of others rather than aggression
or escape. This ``tend and befriend'' response, seen both in humans
and in animal species, may be based in hormonal differences between
the sexes, the researchers argue. And in a long ago world, it may
have conferred an evolutionary advantage, allowing females to
reduce the risk to their offspring and to themselves posed by
predators, natural disasters and other Pleistocene-era threats. By
Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
