<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9087 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-LINDA-McCARTNEY-REVIE     05-18 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINDA-McCARTNEY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO LET THIS BE?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Sun., May 21.) 
Our rating: 1 star 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, CBS gave us the life of ``Jesus''; this week, they
offer another story of someone best-known for cushy family
connections: ``The Linda McCartney Story.'' This may very well be
the most staggeringly unnecessary biopic in the history of the
genre. Let's face it: Paul has likely not been itching for a movie
about his late spouse, and Linda herself would no doubt be aghast
at the idea.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves only the most pathetically obsessed Beatles fan who
might be interested in this _ the sort who would buy Linda's
posthumously released CD, for example _ and that demographic
wouldn't even earn a decent rating for the Oxygen Channel.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of urgency to tell this story is apparent in every
tedious frame of the movie. For starters, the actors scarcely
resemble the icons they're playing. Elizabeth Mitchell plays Linda
_ who refers to herself early on as ``a divorced working mother,''
conveniently neglecting to mention, ``and heiress to the
Eastman-Kodak fortune,'' so we'll be more on her side. She's
certainly got the, um, blond hair part down pat.
</P>
<P>
   When Linda's in the middle of a photo shoot with a haggard bunch
of fellows allegedly portraying the Rolling Stones, I could only
hazard a guess that it was supposed to be Mick Jagger hitting on
her because that would've been most glamorous. (For a professional
photographer, Linda seems to fall unprofessionally into bed with
her subjects fairly easily: In addition to McCartney, the film
tallies up Jagger and Jim Morrison _ or at least some facsimile in
that they share the same number of arms and legs _ among her
conquests.) A woman referred to as ``Chrissie Hynde'' shows up only
for purposes of cheap name-dropping.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Paul McCartney (who, as played by Gary Bakewell, has
never seemed so, um, puffy) comes upon the picture, they fall in
love and live happily ever after. Well, almost: Their big trials
come when a music critic insults Linda's backing caterwauling at a
Wings concert, when Paul frets over non-existent financial woes and
when he's busted for pot possession in Japan. Hardly the sort of
problems with which we average viewers are likely to empathize.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Linda develops the cancer that took her life in
1998. Pointlessly, the film veers back and forth in time from the
Beatle days to her battle with the disease, which kills what little
momentum the story may have and doesn't really meaningfully develop
drama in her struggle to survive.
</P>
<P>
   For all we know, Linda McCartney was a kind and loving person
who just happened to be born into wealth and married even better.
But that doesn't automatically mean that such a life inspires any
compelling drama. If nothing else, ``The Linda McCartney Story''
tenders a chilling warning for all celebrities: No matter how
insignificant a level of fame you may achieve, there's going to be
a cynical filmmaker out there who'll make a crummy biopic of your
life when you die. Obscurity never seemed so good.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
The show: ``The Linda McCartney Story.'' &QL; 
What: Biopic of Beatle Paul McCartney's wife. &QL; 
The stars: Elizabeth Mitchell, Gary Bakewell, George Segal. &QL; 
Where: CBS (Channel 2). &QL; 
When: 9 tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
