A9089 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-ONLINE-SITE-OF-WEEK-L     05-18 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-SITE-OF-WEEK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIGMANIA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gigmania: ``The dynamic source for your live music scene,''
which lets you find rock, jazz and other concerts in 25 U.S. and
Canadian cities, including Los Angeles, San Diego, San Francisco
and even such smaller towns as Columbus, Ohio, and Louisville, Ky.
There also are separate sections for 32 more cities in Europe, Asia
and Australia. &QL; 
Where: www.gigmania.com &QL; 
What's cool: Choose a date and a city or search by artist or venue
and you'll get a wad of options. Travelers will love this site. For
instance, Gigmania tells me in my next Bay Area trip that I can
catch High Plains troubadour Freedy Johnston at Johnny Foley's
(he'll be at McCabe's Guitar Shop in Santa Monica on Memorial Day
weekend; you'll love the Kansan's cover of ``Wichita Lineman'').
Those sticking close to home will love being able to check out the
acts playing at their favorite club. A quick scan of the L.A.
listings turned up about 80 bands in a given night, at a nice
variety of joints. Each band is linked, where available, to their
own Website, to places to listen or buy their music, to occasional
show previews, band background, even archived live performances. &QL; 
Features: Lots of content from the online site of college radio
bible CMJ; contests at clubs around the country; interviews with
artists; tour and festival info; a modest discussion area; links to
live online performances; free downloadable tracks; even the
ability to submit your own band's tour information (and Website
link, etc.). &QL; 
You'll like this if: You have a thing for disreputable lead
singers, bleeding eardrums and overpriced beer. Or, for that
matter, you're traveling and want to get out of the hotel, or you
want to see when a jazz great like Joshua Redman is coming to town,
or want to figure out your schedule at a national treasure like the
New Orleans Jazz and Blues Festival. An excellent resource for the
live music fan, though alas, little here for the classically
minded. &QL; 
Think your Web fave is good enough for Site of the Week? Send your
suggestions to davidbloomearthlink.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
