<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-IMMERSION-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAUX PAS? GET OVER IT! 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Mass., Calif., France)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Editors: the 3rd take is a 425-word guide to schools in the New
York metropolitan area.) By CHARLES STRUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five years ago, at a stationery store on the Left
Bank, I picked up a copy of Paris Match, fished in my pants pocket
for some francs and walked toward the counter, a smile of fear
frozen on my face. As my brain locked, I croaked out this sentence
to the old woman at the counter:
</P>
<P>
   ``Je voudrais acheter le magasin, s'il vous plait.''
</P>
<P>
   The common word for magazine is magazine (mah-gah-ZEEN), not
magasin (mah-gah-ZAA). I had asked to buy the shop.
</P>
<P>
   So it went. For 10 days in Paris I was a helpless prisoner of my
past: four years of undistinguished high school French and one
semester at college. I could make my way through a French
newspaper, but conversation was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Until now. No longer the 98-pound-weakling of bilingualism, I
have persuaded myself that it is possible to function confidently,
perhaps even thrive, in another culture. I am a graduate of
language immersion.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, I have no immediate plans to do much more than order en
francais at a midtown restaurant. But others are looking forward to
a fresh round of business travel, or a summer visit to France or
Italy or Japan, and yearn to be more self-sufficient, even fluent.
For them, language courses like the one in which I enrolled,
offered by the Language Immersion Institute, function as an
introduction, a brush-up or a steppingstone to broader learning. A
friendly caution, however: in the elementary levels, a weekend in
another language can saute your brain, leaving you momentarily mute
and at least a half-sentence behind the person you're straining to
understand. At times it's like trying to do long division in your
head.
</P>
<P>
   My only previous encounter with immersion was a week at a tennis
camp in Massachusetts years ago. Possessed of an average hacker's
game at the time, I left the campus paralyzed by instruction. So
focused had I become on where to step, how to swing and what my
next shot should be that I couldn't hit the ball at all. Eventually
the reflexes returned, including some bad habits. But it was
demoralizing. Not so with French.
</P>
<P>
   In 15 hours of weekend conversation, the equivalent of one-third
of a semester, my classmates and I were continually coaxed to
struggle aloud. Mercifully, this was not like high school, where
teen-agers wince from embarrassment. I felt no trace of the angst
of my sophomore year, when my teacher _ a humorless woman who
looked like Howdy Doody with a gray wig and spoke French with an
Indiana twang _ aimed her intolerance up and down the rows like a
machine gunner.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we were tutored by Denise Springer, a native speaker
from the northeast seaside town of Berck-Plage in Flanders. A
master teacher who retired in December as a language professor at
the State University of New York at New Paltz, she happily
transformed our gaucheries into new lines of instruction. We were
applauded because we tried. It was OK to be ignorant. It was
acceptable to be clumsy. We probably set a record for the number of
sentences fractured per quarter-hour, but our persistence was
always rewarded, with more instruction and more encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a form of benign brainwashing,'' said Dr. Henry Urbanski,
the director of the institute, which he founded on campus in 1981.
The immersion technique isn't new, of course. In the 1960s, the
Peace Corps placed its volunteers in similar programs. Among its
most successful practitioners is the Defense Language Institute in
Monterey, Calif., which trains the military.
</P>
<P>
   Urbanski, a walking advertisement for immersion, was born in
Poland and speaks seven languages: English, French, German,
Italian, Russian, Hebrew and Polish. He learned some of them, he
says, by living in the country where the language is spoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a believer in learning the language when you have an
urgency to use it, when you need to, when you're totally immersed
in it,'' he said. But the program he established initially served
another purpose as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was chairman of the foreign language department at New Paltz
in the late '70s, which coincided with the time that language
requirements at colleges were being abolished,'' he said. ``We were
experiencing a drop in students and a consequent drop in faculty
members. I felt that we had some talented language teachers, and
they had no students to teach. That's when I decided there's people
out in the world who are no longer in school who need language
instruction.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is immersion?
</P>
<P>
   ``You exclude English for 15 hours in one weekend, and after a
while students develop more confidence,'' he said. ``They are not
afraid to speak and make mistakes and to try to communicate in the
language.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the key: making mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans,'' he said, ``hate to make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. So on a recent Friday evening, my classmates and I
left our pride at the door of the Dumont Plaza Hotel on East 34th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   We students, about 70 of us, and 10 or 12 instructors _ a fairly
typical gathering for Manhattan _ arrived at a hotel conference
room at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As individual classes go _ they range from 6 to 15 students _
mine was on the cozy side and fairly typical in its goals. Of the
six of us, four wanted to learn more French for touring the
country, one needed French for a doctoral program, and I was
curious to see whether I was facile enough to move beyond
irrelevant textbook phrases about le cahier, le stylo and mon
oncle.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, classes are held at the Dumont Plaza. The
institute also conducts weekend instruction at the State University
campus at New Paltz, at the nearby Mohonk Lake Mountain House and
at Mercy College in Dobbs Ferry. Instruction begins with Elementary
I and Elementary II (my level) and two intermediate levels. There
are also advanced immersion courses of two weeks and four weeks, at
New Paltz. Most students in the Manhattan program are commuters,
but some stay overnight at their own expense. Tuition was $295 for
the weekend, which included a welcome break for bagels and coffee
on Sunday morning. (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   We began drifting into our meeting room in twos and threes,
randomly filling seats and waiting to meet our teachers before
following them to one-bedroom suites that would serve as
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Urbanski's welcome was low-key. He urged us to shed our
inhibitions and expectations, recalling Heywood Hale Broun's
observation of his own language studies. Broun felt he had been a
good student, Urbanski said, but complained that ``when he got to
Paris he found that no one spoke intermediate French.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the instructors came forward to call the roll for
their classes. They rattled off greetings and room numbers and a
few phrases to lubricate us for what was to come.
</P>
<P>
   Mild panic swept the room, and someone who was dead serious
yelled out, ``I think I'd better switch to Level I.''
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   By 7:30 we were in our ``classrooms.'' My group was interrupted
several times in the first hour by late arrivals, until finally 10
of us crowded into the suite's sitting room. We received paperback
texts, introduced ourselves and talked in French about our jobs,
worked on vocabulary and conversation, and adjourned at 10 p.m.
With the exception of a few necessary instructions for the next
day, Mme. Springer spoke only in French.
</P>
<P>
   When we reconvened at 9 a.m. on Saturday, there were just the
six of us, the others having bailed out. (Most Friday night
dropouts tend to sign up for lower-level instruction either the
same weekend or at a future date, Urbanski said.) Our group was
set: Vicky Jeffers, a psychologist from Morristown, N.J.; her
friend Ann Elkas, a registered nurse from Chatham, N.J.; Mitzi
Pratt, a bookbinder from Martha's Vineyard, Mass.; Debra Schmidt
Bach, from Brooklyn, a curator at the South Street Seaport Museum;
and Cellen (pronounced SELL-in) Wolk, a landscape gardener from
Rockland County. They all knew I would be writing about our
experience.
</P>
<P>
   We were pretty well matched, but the consensus was that Mitzi
was the class genius. Her accent and pronunciation were quite good,
and her command of sentence structure was superior to ours. She had
spent some months working with a set of language tapes, and it had
paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't been to Europe for a while,'' she said, ``and then I
went to France last fall for the grape harvest, the vendange. It
was a great trip, and it inspired me to improve on the French that
I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Her childhood French instruction, she said, had begun in a
private, co-ed elementary school on the North Shore of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Of her weekend at the Dumont Plaza, Mitzi said later: ``I was
very nervous beforehand, but I had underestimated my ability. I had
this vision of us sitting in this room being forced to speak French
to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   That did happen. But most of the time we interacted with
Springer, or created conversations at her direction.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, we paired off and interviewed our partners
in French. Then we reported to the group. I learned that Ann was a
nurse who also volunteered at a domestic-abuse phone line. She has
three grown children, one of whom is married. She drives a Lexus
and lives in a two-story house with four bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Now try saying that in French. In full sentences.
</P>
<P>
   More grist for Mme. Springer, who stood by a large easel and
jotted down new words or phrases or verb forms with a marking pen.
Nothing escaped her interest.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, she gestured to an oversize handbag on the floor
near Vicky's chair. She referred to it as le sac, but then went on
to explain that its size qualified it for what Parisians call by a
slyly suggestive name that will not be repeated here. It is a
prostitute's bag, big enough for a change of clothes, makeup, etc.
Suddenly we were immersed not only in language but also in culture.
</P>
<P>
   Ann and Vicky were both relative newcomers to French. In school,
Ann had studied Latin and taken a year of Spanish. Vicky said she
had been a pretty fair student of German. ``I could think in
German,'' she said. ``I could read poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   Both had been to France recently and wanted to become more
comfortable with the language. So they enrolled together in a
weekly hourlong course in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't getting enough conversation,'' Ann said. ``I'm great
at visual learning, but my conversation is terrible. Just don't ask
me to go, impromptu, into a big conversation with you.''
</P>
<P>
   We all survived the day. But when we left the hotel at 6 p.m. on
Saturday, some of us displayed the telltale squint of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I drove home, my husband said I sat there like a lump, I
was so tired.'' Ann said. ``I said, `We're going out to eat, aren't
we?'''
</P>
<P>
   Food had been our salvation on Saturday afternoon, too. .
Springer, it seems, relishes lunchtime on an immersion weekend, and
her favorite restaurant is a Theater District fixture, Pierre au
Tunnel, on West 47th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Pujol opened the restaurant, on 48th Street, about 50
years ago, and it has remained in the family. Pujol's son-in-law,
Jean-Claude Lincy, greeted us, and a member of the staff cheerfully
put up with our attempts to order a tartine of this or a plat of
that. We kept up some snappy table patter about de Gaulle, French
socialism and Madame's wartime experiences in occupied France. But
mercifully the food arrived, and it struck us all that it was the
first time in hours that we had opened our mouths without having to
think. (We split the bill, in English.)
</P>
<P>
   The biggest event of the weekend, though, was the dreaded oral
report on Sunday. Mme. Springer had directed each of us to prepare
a five-minute presentation. We were permitted to write it out the
night before, but not to read from it in class.
</P>
<P>
   Vicky went first. Her report was on an American doughboy in
Paris in 1918 and the penniless French countess he married. They
eventually became her in-laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed that I could make the presentation and elaborate
spontaneously,'' she said later. ``I felt comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann talked about her work as a volunteer with the domestic-abuse
line. Cellen, the jardiniere, spoke lovingly about landscaping. It
turned out that Cellen had been a competent Spanish speaker after
having lived in Mexico years ago. But she had all but given up on
French.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had four years of first-year French in high school,'' she
said, adding that her mother, a French teacher, seemed to think her
daughter had no aptitude for language. After doing poorly in her
first French class, she repeated French I the next year. Then she
moved to a new school, and another French I class, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   With the prospect of a trip to Europe this summer, she chose to
try immersion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began dreaming in French,'' she said, after a day of class.
</P>
<P>
   Mitzi told us about a trip to ancient ruins in Peru. I tried to
describe a French cartoon character a friend had introduced me to.
Named Becassine, she is a chauvinistic Bretonne in regional apron
and cap whose exploits, chronicled in two dozen books, became
popular between the world wars. (I had hoped for extra credit.)
</P>
<P>
   Debra is working toward her doctorate at Columbia University in
the history of decorative arts, for which she must pass a French
comprehension exam in the fall. She described a visit to Paris
about 13 years ago, when she was in her 20s. ``On my way home one
night,'' she said, ``I gave my address to a taxi driver, but
apparently I didn't pronounce it properly. When I showed the
correct address, he started yelling at me.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, she said, she dreamed that people were shouting at
her in French. She awoke to find that they were: her hotel was next
to a noisy restaurant kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Which provoked a stern caution from Madame and may explain at
long last why the French become frustrated with Americans. It's not
because we take pratfalls in pursuit of fluency; it's because we
make the sounds wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' she said, ``if you don't pronounce it correctly,
the French simply won't understand you.'' It must have been
important: she said this in English!
</P>
<P>
   By 1:30 on Sunday, exhausted but triumphant and with just 30
minutes remaining, we realized that making mistakes had not been so
bad after all. We had stuttered and stumbled and persevered. Our
teacher was still smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Our valedictory was brief but pleasant. We read poems and sang
songs in unison and recited tongue twisters: ``Comment sont ces six
saucissons-ci? Ces six saucissons-ci sont six sous.''
</P>
<P>
   There were hugs for the teacher, promises to enroll with her
again and invitations to visit her in the Hudson Valley. A
valedictory of her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am moved by the fact that people come and spend a weekend,
people who have other interesting things to do,'' Mme. Springer
would tell me later. ``If you are intelligent, you are
self-criticizing, and it can work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never know exactly the level of the people when they
enroll. Some people think they are better than they are. But most
people are better than they think they are.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   IMMERSE YOURSELF IN A FOREIGN LANGUAGE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of places in the New York metropolitan region
that offer intensive language classes.
</P>
<P>
   BERLITZ: Various centers in New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut; (800) 457-7958 or www.berlitz.com. The centers offer
``virtually any language'' in four programs: ``Total Immersion''
(seven and a half hours a day for one to six weeks); individual
instruction; semi-private lessons (two students with one
instructor) and a group program. All are based on a conversational
approach. The most economical programs are two-month courses in
Spanish, German, French and Italian for groups of fewer than eight
students, meeting once a week for sessions of 2 hours and 15
minutes. Cost: $299.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHES HAUS AT NEW YORK UNIVERSITY: (212) 998-8660 or
www.nyu.edu/deutscheshaus. Monthlong classes in German at all
levels, meeting for just under three hours twice a week. Fee: $430.
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE IMMERSION INSTITUTE, JFT 916, State University of New
York at New Paltz, N.Y.: (914) 257-3500 or www. newpaltz.edu/lii.
Offers 20 languages, from American Sign to Yiddish, at elementary,
intermediate and advanced levels. Courses are offered in Manhattan
at the Dumont Plaza Hotel; Mercy College in Dobbs Ferry, N.Y.; the
Mohonk Mountain House in New Paltz, N.Y., and at the State
University of New York in New Paltz. Tuition for the weekend course
at all locations is $295; overnight lodging is extra.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN SOCIETY TOYOTA LANGUAGE CENTER in Manhattan:
(212)715-1256. Weekend courses in Japanese for students with some
or no previous experience. The next classes meet for four days on
two consecutive weekends: June 17 and 18 and June 24 and 25, from
11 a.m. to 4 p.m. Tuition: $235; members, $205.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SCHOOL FOR SOCIAL RESEARCH in Manhattan: The school offers
``One-Day Workshops for Travelers'' in French and Italian,
consisting of a six-hour class with lunch at a local restaurant
where students can practice; it costs $135, including lunch. The
school also offers ``Introductory Immersion'' and ``Intermediate
Immersion'' classes in French, Italian and Spanish, consisting of
12 sessions, each three and a half hours, Mondays through Thursdays
over three weeks; each costs $710.
</P>
<P>
   PARLIAMO ITALIANO LANGUAGE SCHOOL, 132 East 65th Street,
Manhattan; (212) 744-4793. A two-week ``Intensive Elementary I''
class in Italian is held for two hours a day, Monday through
Friday; the next session begins June 19 and costs $310 (for the 2
to 4 p.m. class) or $260 (for the 6 to 7:30 p.m. class). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
