<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL PUTS ARMS EMBARGO ON ETHIOPIA AND ERITREA 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The U.N. Security Council has imposed an arms
embargo on Ethiopia and Eritrea in the hope that it will spur the
two sides toward a resumption of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous vote near midnight on Wednesday, the council
barred all sales and deliveries of arms and other military
equipment to the two countries for 12 months _ or until
Secretary-General Kofi Annan is able to report that they have
reached ``a peaceful, definitive settlement of the conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   In return for Russian and French support, the United States,
which sponsored the resolution, had to drop additional sanctions
against Ethiopia, which began this phase of a three-year-old war by
attacking Eritrea, a former Ethiopian province, on Friday. The U.S.
delegation wanted to bar international travel by Ethiopian
officials, but other council members said this could hamper peace
talks, which have been taking place in Algiers. Algeria is the
current chairman of the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
   It took three days of hard negotiations for the council to reach
an agreement on how to deal with the war in the Horn of Africa,
which most members agree is pointlessly destructive. Eritrea and
Ethiopia were very close to agreement only a few weeks ago, but a
Security Council delegation that visited the area last week was
unable to dissuade the Ethiopians from reopening the war.
</P>
<P>
   A time limit on sanctions was demanded by Russia, France and
other council members, who say they have seen too many open-ended
embargoes imposed _ often at the behest of the United States _ with
no policy on what to do about the sanctions when they seem no
longer to be effective. The council is studying how to improve the
use of sanctions in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's ambassador, Sergey Lavrov, hailed the vote to put a
time limit on sanctions as a historical first for the council. The
Russians have been most critical of the embargo on Iraq, now in its
10th year, without an end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Nancy Soderberg, who handled the Ethiopian-Eritrean
sanctions debate for the United States, said after the vote that
the resolution was intended to bolster the Organization of African
Unity as it tries to restart peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it sends an unequivocal and strong message to the
parties to bring an end to this conflict,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1712EDT &QL; 
