<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-345&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIAN FORCES CAPTURE KEY TOWN IN ERITREA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-U.N.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELALO, Eritrea _ The geographically strategic town of Barentu
in western Eritrea has fallen into Ethiopian hands after heavy
fighting involving dozens of tanks and thousands of troops,
officials on both sides said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Ethiopian capture of Barentu, achieved overnight in a battle
fought across hilly, difficult terrain, sent hundreds of thousands
of Eritrean refugees streaming eastward Thursday in the general
direction of the capital, Asmara.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopian soldiers continued to chase retreating Eritrean troops
toward the larger town of Keren, northeast of Barentu.
</P>
<P>
   Each side claims to have inflicted more than 25,000 casualties
on the other since last Friday, when Ethiopia launched its current
offensive. There was no way to confirm either claim.
</P>
<P>
   For two years of the war, the fighting had been confined largely
to a sophisticated network of trenches along the nations' border.
But six days after Ethiopia mounted an offensive, the border
trenches were left empty as the war shifted firmly into Eritrean
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Barentu, which is about 45 miles from the Ethiopian border, lies
on a major supply route to the westernmost front of the war.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon Ethiopian jets streaked toward Barentu,
and smoke rose from the area. as the Ethiopian army advancing in
heavy fighting. Eritrean officials said Wednesday that their
soldiers had repulsed several assaults on Barentu but have since
said that the army had made a ``strategic withdrawal.''
</P>
<P>
   Yemane Gebremeskel, an Eritrean presidential adviser, said
Thursday, according to Reuters, that Barentu had been evacuated
before the army withdrew. According to Eritrean relief agencies, he
said, ``over 200,000 people from the Barentu area are heading
east.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Eritreans, the Ethiopian gains, which have emptied
several Eritrean towns in the path of advancing troops, confirmed
their worst fears. Eritrea, which until 1993 was the northernmost
province of Ethiopia, has always maintained that Ethiopia had its
eye on permanently taking back territory.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an effort to stop the fighting, the U.N. Security Council
late Wednesday night imposed an arms embargo on Ethiopia and
Eritrea to try to get them to resume peace talks. The council voted
to bar all arms and military equipment sales or deliveries to the
two countries for the next 12 months, or until Secretary-General
Kofi Annan can report ``a peaceful, definitive settlement of the
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   The war started in May 1998 as a dispute over contested spots
along the two nations' 620-mile border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethiopia says it wants to regain contested territory, but then
why do they keep trying to gain territory beyond the contested
territory according to the colonial maps?'' Yemane Gebremeskel, an
aide to Eritrea's president, said to the French news agency
Wednesday in the capital, Asmara.
</P>
<P>
   But Haile Kiros, an Ethiopian government spokesman, said the
nation's interest was purely in retaking land that it said Eritrea
invaded in 1998. ``Our intention is only to regain our territory,''
he said. ``The invading forces have to be pushed out.''
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a year of calm along the border, Ethiopia started
an offensive on Friday, saying it wanted a quick end to a war that
has drained its economy and complicated a food shortage that has
affected millions of people. While Eritrea has condemned Ethiopia
for reigniting the fighting and for reluctance in signing a peace
accord, Ethiopia has said Eritrea was the original aggressor and
needed to be punished.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa, government officials said
its soldiers had shot down an Eritrean MiG fighter jet after it had
bombed recaptured territory on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As Ethiopian troops poured Tuesday through Tokombia, a market
town on the way north to Bar entu, dozens of other Ethiopian troops
looted the town, whose residents fled during the fighting on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopian soldiers picked through the mud-and-thatch houses and
emptied shops in the main square. One soldier carried an umbrella
and a soccer ball; another carried two new axes and a bottle of
vegetable oil.
</P>
<P>
   Abdu Seid, a 22-year-old company commander, said that despite
appearances, no one was really looting. The soldiers were dirty
after all the fighting, he said, and looking for things they could
bathe with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to wash ourselves,'' he said. ``People have taken only
what they need,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
