<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9104 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w BC-ABDUCTED-GIRL-HNS &LR;      05-18 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABDUCTED-GIRL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S.-MEXICO CUSTODY CASE ENDS HAPPILY, BUT OTHERS LINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GARY MARTIN and SUSANA HAYWARD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A tearful reunion this week between Laura Garcia,
8, and her Texas mother has sparked hopes by the State Department
and child advocates for the return of 105 other American children
believed abducted and living in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is getting bigger and bigger, and we are not
getting the kids back,'' said Guillermo Galarza with the National
Center for Missing and Exploited Children, a nonprofit organization
in Alexandria, Va., that works with the State Department and once
used milk cartons to publicize missing children.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department reported in November that Mexico is the top
destination for parents who abduct their children to escape custody
disputes in the United States. Since 1991, at least 750 children
have been taken there.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Center for Missing and Exploited
Children, Mexico honors 3 percent of U.S. requests to return
abducted children. By contrast, the United States honors about 80
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries are signatories to the 1980 Hague Convention,
which established procedures for resolving international child
custody issues.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was abducted by her father in 1997 and taken to Rio
Bravo, Mexico, where she lived for three years like a fugitive. She
attended school sporadically and longed for her mother in Buda,
Texas, some 30 miles northeast of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Following publication of a newspaper account of the case, the
father, Joel Garcia, agreed to return the little girl to his former
girlfriend. The Laura rejoined her mother on May 15.
</P>
<P>
   Galarza said the voluntary return of Laura Garcia to her mother,
Norma Lua, is a great relief to the parents, family, social
workers and government officials involved. Joel Garcia also is the
father of Luna's 5-year-old son, who remained in the custody of his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some cases take up to five years,'' Galarza said. ``This was a
case that was handled by the State Department. It would have taken
awhile for the courts to take the case in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department often is forced to pressure the Mexican
government for help, officials and child advocates say. ``We will
continue to raise this issue with them, that we want more
returns,'' a State Department spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   There are 100 missing-child cases in which U.S. parents are
seeking help and have filed a complaint under the Hague Convention.
The State Department is investigating five other complaints where
children are being held in Mexico, for a total of 105 open cases.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican parents, meanwhile, are seeking help under the treaty to
have 131 children returned from abductors believed to be living in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Having different sets of laws in the two nations heightens the
problem with cross-border, parental child abductions, said
Guillermo Gutierrez, president of the National Foundation of Stolen
and Disappeared Children in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   While it is a federal crime in the United States, the kidnapping
of a child in Mexico by a parent usually is considered a family
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is that the laws don't coincide. In the United
States, abducting a child is a serious crime with serious
penalties, but in Mexico it's not,'' said Gutierrez, whose
nonprofit organization works with the Center for Missing and
Exploited Children in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez, in Mexico City, said a universal law respecting
children's rights and helping to streamline the process is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old boy who was caught in
a dispute between his Cuban father and relatives in Florida,
heightened awareness about cross-border custody cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
