<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9114 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WOODYALLEN-QA19-COX     05-18 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODYALLEN-QA19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Director Allen keeps low-tech profile when it comes to tools of
filmmaking
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woody Allen is asking for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you'll excuse me,'' he says. He has food in his mouth
and is making smacking noises as he chews on a thin slice of
toasted rye bread. It's all the midday meal he's going to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``My lunch was wheeled in on a cart,'' says Allen, 64, who's
ensconced in a Regency Hotel room in New York, promoting his latest
movie, ``Small Time Crooks,'' by phone. ``It was inedible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Crooks,'' opening today in metro Atlanta, is a light,
sometimes slapstick comedy, written and directed by Allen, about a
penny-ante ex-convict (Allen), his manicurist wife (Tracey Ullman)
and how a bungled bank robbery somehow leads them to millions of
dollars when her fresh cookies become as popular in New York as
anything ``Seinfeld's'' Soup Nazi ever ladled up. The movie's
co-stars include Michael Rapaport, Hugh Grant, Jon Lovitz and
Elaine May as May, the dingiest of dingbats.
</P>
<P>
   Allen recently _ and politely _ responded to a variety of
questions about his new movie, his co-stars and even, ahem, Mia
Farrow.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Many people are already comparing ``Small Time Crooks'' to
``Take the Money and Run.'' You see it that way?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I can see why one might think that, because the lead
character in both is a bank robber. But this is a comedy just for
laughs. ``Take the Money'' was a pseudobiography. This is a much
different personal story. And what happens to the character is very
different. This is a much more plot-driven character story. While
``Take the Money'' was a bunch of crazy jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Elaine May's character is classic Elaine May. Did you write
the part for her?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a crazy thing to do. It's hard to get Elaine. I've known
her for years, slightly. And it was presumptuous of me to think
that I could get her. I was very lucky. She could just as easily
have said no with one of her many excuses. When I made ``Take the
Money,'' I offered her a part. She called back and said, ``You
won't want me for this part because I'm wearing a neck brace.''
With ``Crooks,'' she said send over the thing and then said sure.
And I was lucky with Tracey (Ullman) as well. I didn't write it
with anyone in mind. When we thought of her, we got so excited
because we knew she'd be so funny. And then to cap the whole thing
off, there's Hugh Grant. When I thought of Hugh Grant I thought,
`Perfect: He'd be great to play the heavy and he's got a great
sense of humor.'
</P>
<P>
   Q: Early on there's this great scene with you and Tracey Ullman
on the roof with this bright sunset. Was that something you
planned, or did it just happen?
</P>
<P>
   A: We did plan the rooftop scene. But we originally wanted
Tracey's cookie shop to be called Rainbow Cookies. We felt that it
was too expensive to get a rainbow and put it on special effects,
and we knew we could get a sunset on the roof. There were a lot of
problems, though. Problems of lighting it. The sun falls fast. We
had to do the scene very quickly. In the end, we would have been
better buying the rainbow.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You never really use much in the way of effects. Aren't you
part of the digital age?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not a technological person. I don't have a computer. No
word processor. I type on a portable typewriter. And some of that
stuff is expensive. For me, the technological devices are only good
as tools for telling the story. And what's happened in many films
is that directors use these effects and they are so dazzling and
wonderful and in the end they do the films to show the technical
effect. It becomes the means to the movie. . . . To parade it, I
don't care about that. I'm not interested in it. I think the movie
should be about people and situations. So I use the technology when
I have to, but it's rare when I have to. . . . In ``Celebrity'' I
needed to do a skywriting sequence, and I certainly could not have
gotten it done in the sky. We'd still be shooting today.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about digital filmmaking and digital projection and all
that technology that's supposed to change filmmaking?
</P>
<P>
   A: I saw one example of (digital projection) that didn't look
great to me. When it comes out and if it's genuinely something that
you want to do, then great. But what I've seen of it (right now) is
no big deal. . . . I do think the technology will improve and do
away with projecting film. . . . And the digital colors will be
rich and beautiful. And you won't have to go through all the
indignities of seeing your movie being projected (incorrectly).
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, in a way, you're embracing the new technology now?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. What I'll do is continue to film conventionally. And (as
the technology improves), if I feel there is a use for it, I will
use it. Right now, a digital camera would have been no help to me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You used to not do many interviews. Now you're talking to the
press, doing a voice-over for ``Just Shoot Me,'' going to colleges
to promote ``Crooks.'' Why the change?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have to do a certain amount of promotion or I seem like a
louse. Especially when people come in and do work for me for
(practically) no money. I can't just not do anything. . . . I don't
relish these things. But I don't want to be a terrible person to
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read where Mia Farrow said she's wanting to mend fences
with Soon-Yi Previn.
</P>
<P>
   A: All fabrication.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about your competition at the movies this summer? You
thinking about seeing ``Mission: Impossible 2,'' ``Dinosaur'' or
``The Perfect Storm''?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. I've never heard of any of those titles. I would never
have the slightest interest.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what recent films did interest you?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the last six months, I enjoyed ``Magnolia.'' I enjoyed
``The Wonder Boys.'' I enjoyed ``East-West.'' Those were films I
like. Most of the other films I have no interest in at all. Those
films are for kids. It's the stuff I would have loved when I was 12
years old.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
