<HEADER>
A9115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CIRQUE-FILM-REVIEW-NY     05-18 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRQUE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOURNEY OF MAN': THE ASCENT OF MANKIND _ AN ALLEGORY IN 38
MINUTES 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The French-Canadian troupe Cirque du Soleil is
renowned for conjuring visual magic that fuses dance and the circus
arts in scenarios that often carry a mythical and spiritual charge.
And in the tableaus they have created for the new Imax-3D film
``Journey of Man'' they have compiled an all-engulfing sensuous
wonder book of aesthetic adventures with a light moral gloss.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Cirque du Soleil's acrobats leap, twirl and dive in
spectacular natural settings, you often have the sensation of
forsaking the everyday world and plunging into a strange,
paradisaical and slightly scary dimension of pure myth, with a
Gallic flavor.
</P>
<P>
   An ambitious dual allegory, the movie, which opens Friday at the
Sony Theaters Lincoln Square, roughly parallels the ascent of
humankind from caves into a civilized stateliness with symbolic
portrayals of the human life cycle from early childhood to old age.
As beautiful as the movie is, its brief 38-minute length prevents
it from having much impact as a sweeping allegory. Almost before
the movie begins, it seems to be over.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the film, directed by Keith Melton, written by Steve
Roberts and Peter Wagg, and narrated by Ian McKellen with a
high-toned hauteur, works as a series of enthralling tableaus that
seem almost to burst out of one another like visionary flashes from
an unusually vivid dream.
</P>
<P>
   The film begins with an illustration of the Big Bang theory of
creation, as an explosion of light and a pounded bass drum
introduce Cirque du Soleil percussionists painted and costumed as
Japanese taiko drummers performing in a court style that dates back
to the eighth century. As they play, an embryonic ``universal
child'' appears who at the end of the sequence is plunged into the
ocean to be ``born'' in an interpretive dance performed underwater
by a group synchronized swimmers with amazing breath control.
</P>
<P>
   Rocketing out of the water, the child lands in an enchanted
redwood forest (the movie's most magical sequence) where he meets
his ``instinctual guides,'' the Flounes, a pair of clownish
parental shamans who watch over him like silent guardian angels.
The tableau is dominated by yellow bird-like bungee jumpers who
leap from the trees like human yo-yo's. At first they seem scary.
But once the child has mustered his courage, they whisk him off
into a different world.
</P>
<P>
   Finding himself in a craggy arid canyon that suggests a
spectacular limbo (the sequence was filled in Valley of Fire State
Park in the Nevada desert), the child, now adolescent, looks up to
observes a muscular daredevil, poised on a pinnacle, deftly
manipulating a gleaming metallic cube. Inspired by his courage, the
boy eventually makes his way to the top of the canyon as the cube
bursts into flame and his elusive idol sails away into the
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop is an idyllic 17th-century garden in whose
reflecting pool two statues, floating on a giant lily pad come to
life, perform a precarious, slow-motion balancing act that
demonstrates an idealized yin-yang harmony (devoid of overt
eroticism) between man and woman.
</P>
<P>
   The movie takes a quasi-biblical turn with the arrival of the
evil Stiltman, a mildly satanic figure who tempts the young man
with a gold bowler hat symbolizing wealth and power.
</P>
<P>
   In the next scene, the man, surrounded by elegant luxury, is
entertained by the Banquine, a group of vagabond tumblers who try
to revive the spirit of his lost childhood. In the final chapter,
the now mature man, his youthful joie de vivre restored, reunites
with the Flounes and finds himself at the Brandenberg Gate in
Berlin surrounded by children whom he leads toward knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journey of Man'' may not impart much genuine wisdom. But it
conveys plenty of wonder while mostly avoiding any saccharine
preachiness. At its most evocative, you really do feel you've
stumbled into an enchanted realm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CIRQUE DU SOLEIL' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Journey of Man
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Keith Melton; written by Steve Roberts and Peter
Wagg; director of photography, Reed Smoot; 3-D and visual effects
supervisor, Peter Anderson; edited by Harry B. Miller 3rd; music by
Benoit Jutras; production designer, John Zachary; produced by Wagg
and Andre Picard; released by Sony Pictures Classics. At the Sony
Theaters Lincoln Square, 1998 Broadway at 68th Street.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Ian McKellen (Narrator), Nicky Dewhurst (Young Man), Brian
Dewhurst (Old Man), Anait Karagyezyan (Vagabond Girl), Chris Van
Wagnenen (Youth), Kenny Raskin (Man), Cully Smoller (Infant/Child)
and Mikhail Matorin (Cube Act).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 38 minutes. This film is rated G.
</P>
</TEXT>
