<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE     05-18 1513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    RESENDING FOR ALL NEEDING
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS _ TAKE 1
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's been a lot in the media about Sen. John McCain
finally endorsing Texas Gov. George W. Bush for president, but I
don't recall seeing anything about Bill Bradley doing so for Vice
President Al Gore. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: When Bradley quit the Democratic presidential race in early
March, he said he would ``support'' Gore and would campaign for
him. However, the former New Jersey senator pointedly did not use
the word ``endorse.'' Asked why, he told reporters: ``It's your
call.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also didn't release his delegates to Gore. Bradley had
412 delegates, compared to Gore's 1,424. ``They've been loyal
supporters and deserve to have their voices heard (at the
Democratic National Convention),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today, meanwhile, reports that a joint appearance between
Gore and Bradley may be in the works. Although Bradley hasn't
spoken to Gore since March 9 and the two sides have had a
``non-relationship,'' according to Bradley's staff, a Gore
spokesman said the campaigns are in ``close contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand there's a government Web site with safety tips
for foreign travel. Where can I can find it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The State Department posts information online at
http://travel.state.gov/travelwarnings.html; or you can call
202-647-5225.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been interested in the Lewis &AMP; Clark Expedition for
several years, and have visited many sites along the trail. Where
are their original diaries stored?
</P>
<P>
   A: They are kept in temperature- and humidity-controlled
conditions at the American Philosophical Society Museum in
Philadelphia, according to a spokeswoman for the Lewis &AMP; Clark
Center in St. Charles, Mo. They aren't available for public
viewing. Scholarly researchers may be able to see them, but only
under strict conditions.
</P>
<P>
   She added that a traveling Lewis &AMP; Clark exhibition is planned
``in a couple of years.'' It will have many artifacts, but details
aren't yet available. She didn't know its schedule, itinerary, or
even what it might contain. If you haven't seen anything about it
by the end of 2001, call the Lewis &AMP; Clark Center for information:
636-947-3199.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the name of the water that comes as a gel and can be
used in gardening? Where can I buy it?
</P>
<P>
   A: You may be thinking of Soil Moist, although it isn't exactly
what you're describing. It sounds like it would serve the purpose,
however. It's a granular product that can be added to pots. When
you water the pots, the granules form a clear gel that gradually
releases water into the soil.
</P>
<P>
   It's available in two sizes at gardening centers: 3 ounces for
$3.97 and one pound for $18.97. In summer, most container gardens
require daily watering, so the gels are ideal for when people are
away from home on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about tickets to the NCAA men's
basketball Final Four tournament in 2002?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ticket application information for the 2002 Final Four, March
30 and April 1 at the Georgia Dome in Atlanta, won't be available
until March 2001. NCAA spokeswoman Megan Wallace advises checking
online at www.ncaachampionships.com in late March 2001for further
information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has the U.S. Mint issued any state commemorative quarters so
far in 2000? It seems like I have seen two new ones.
</P>
<P>
   A: Right you are. The first issue of the Mint's 50 state
quarters program this year is for Massachusetts. It features a
design of the minuteman, the famous statue at The Minuteman
National Historical Park in Concord. The year's second quarter, for
Maryland, highlights the dome of the Maryland Statehouse. Next is
South Carolina, to be followed by New Hampshire and Virginia. The
Mint is issuing five new quarters a year over a 10-year period.
This is the second year of the program.
</P>
<P>
   If you're online, you can keep up with all the state quarters as
they're issued at www.usmint.gov/50states/.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who or what is Bandelier National Monument in New Mexico
named for? It hasn't been mentioned in all the reporting about the
disastrous fire around Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   A: The name comes from Adolph Francis Alphonse Bandelier
(1840-1914), a Swiss-American explorer, anthropologist and
archaeologist whose main interest was the Indians of the American
Southwest. He was an early advocate of ``participant observation,''
learning about the Indians not only by living with them and
studying their culture, but also by studying their artifacts and
the ruins on their land.
</P>
<P>
   One of his primary goals was to dispel white Americans' myths
about the Indians. The best way to do that, he concluded, was by
living with the Indians and then writing about them.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his research was published as ``Final Report of
Investigations Among the Indians of the Southwestern Portion of the
United States'' (1890 and 1892). In 1903, he joined the staff of
the American Museum of Natural History and later he lectured on
Spanish-American literature at Columbia University. In 1911 he went
to Spain, where he worked until his death.
</P>
<P>
   In 1916, President Woodrow Wilson officially designated the area
encompassing Frijoles Canyon as Bandelier National Monument. Many
archaeological sites, such as Shohakka Pueblo, Tsankawi and San
Miguel, are within its 50 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there any multi-state lotteries other than Big Game and
Powerball?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, one other: the Tri-State Lottery (Maine, New Hampshire
and Vermont).
</P>
<P>
   Q: President and Mrs. Clinton and Vice President and Mrs. Gore
all attended the funeral in New York for Cardinal John O'Connor.
When both the president and vice president leave Washington for an
occasion such as this, do they travel together on the same
aircraft? Or, for security reasons, do they travel separately?
</P>
<P>
   A: The White House declined to answer specifically whether they
would or would not have been aboard the same aircraft, or what the
policy might be. A spokesman who said he was speaking on
background, and not for attribution, said only that the two had
traveled together on some past campaign trips, but because each now
has a busy schedule, they travel separately more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are any free or inexpensive special events planned in
connection with the baseball All-Star Game, similar to the NFL
Experience during the Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The ``blockbuster'' event for the public, as promoters
call it, is the John Hancock All-Star FanFest, scheduled July 7-11
at the Georgia World Congress Center in Atlanta. It will include
interactive games, Major League clinics and seminars, autograph
sessions with players, displays of memorabilia, and other
baseball-related activities.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th annual FanFest, leading up to the 71st All-Star Game
July 11 at Turner Field, is described as ``the biggest single
baseball event in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any details about a class-action suit against
Sotheby's and Christie's auction houses?
</P>
<P>
   A: A federal judge in New York has granted class-action status
to about 60 lawsuits that charge the two auction houses with
colluding to fix prices.
</P>
<P>
   As reported by The Wall Street Journal, it's a blow to Sotheby's
and Christie's because the ruling, issued late last month by U.S.
District Court Judge Lewis Kaplan, allows plaintiffs seeking
millions of dollars in damages to avoid the expense and trouble of
separate trials.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan defined the class broadly as anyone who bought or sold
articles through the defendant auction houses from Jan. 1, 1993,
through Feb. 7, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Both auction houses are under investigation by the Justice
Department's Antitrust Division. At issue is whether the two
concerns colluded when, within weeks of each other, they changed
fees charged to buyers and sellers at auction. Together, the two
houses control about 95 percent of a $4 billion worldwide auction
market.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan has set a tentative trial date of February 2001 in the
event no settlement is reached earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We will be visiting D.C. in June and wonder about the status
of the restoration project at the Washington Monument. Will the
monument be reopened by then?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry, no. Initially it was scheduled to reopen by July 4,
but that won't happen, according to Donna Desormeaux of the
Washington, DC Convention and Visitors Association. The restoration
and refurbishment project is nearly complete, but the best estimate
for reopening is ``sometime later this summer.'' Until then, the
National Park Service recommends that visitors check out the
interpretive center on the monument's grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 202-789-7000; or online at www.washington.org/.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
