u a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE     05-18 1670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    RESENDING FOR ALL NEEDING
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS _ TAKE 2
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ... or online at www.washington.org/.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you explain the scoring system in baseball? What numbers
correspond to which positions?
</P>
<P>
   A: These are the numbers assigned to each defensive player's
position: 1, pitcher; 2, catcher; 3, first baseman; 4, second
baseman; 5, third baseman; 6, shortstop; 7, left fielder; 8, center
fielder; 9, right fielder.
</P>
<P>
   An out is noted by listing the numbers of the players who touch
the ball. For example, a ground ball that is hit to the shortstop
who throws it to first base for an out is noted as 6-3. A
short-to-second-to-first double play: 6-4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of other symbols are used in recording the events of a
game, and people may have their own variations. A strikeout is a K,
but if it's on a called strike, the K is reversed. Base hits are 1B
(single), 2B (double), 3B (triple) and HR (home run).
</P>
<P>
   Other common abbreviations include BB (base on balls), E
(error), FC (fielder's choice, meaning a fielder catches a ground
ball and tries to get a runner out instead of the batter; or the
batter does reach first base safely, but isn't given credit for a
base hit); HBP (hit by pitch); PB (passed ball); WP (wild pitch); S
(sacrifice bunt); SF (sacrifice fly); L (lined out); F (flied out);
and CS (caught stealing).
</P>
<P>
   Q: What ever happened to actor Paul Reubens, who played the
character Pee-wee Herman? He had some personal problems a few years
ago, but I haven't seen anything about him since. Is he still in
show business?
</P>
<P>
   A: He appears to be finished with the ``sabbatical,'' as he
termed it, that followed in the wake of his 1991 arrest and
conviction for indecent exposure in a Florida adult theater.
</P>
<P>
   After his conviction, CBS pulled his ``Pee-wee's Playhouse''
series off the air, and stores yanked Pee-wee toys off the shelves.
He was the punchline in countless jokes, and even he made a joke
about himself on an MTV video music awards program a few weeks
after his arrest. He stepped out of the public eye, building up his
``ET'' memorabilia collection, gardening, and spending time with
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Now he appears to be moving to regain his ruined career,
although taking it slowly. In 1995, he appeared in a recurring role
as a TV executive on ``Murphy Brown.'' He also had parts in the
films ``Dunston Checks In,'' ``Matilda'' and ``Mystery Men,'' and
finished a Dwight Yoakam-directed Western, ``South of Heaven, West
of Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   As he told an interviewer last year, he also plans to resurrect
Pee-wee in what he termed ``a semi-autobiographical movie . . .
about fame in our times. Pee-wee becomes famous and turns into a
monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the five most-populated countries in the world?
</P>
<P>
   A: In terms of population, the world's largest country is China,
with an estimated 1.25 billion inhabitants in mid-1999 (one-fifth
of the world's total population). India, which recently topped 1
billion, ranks No. 2. The next three, as listed in World Almanac
and Book of Facts 2000: United States, with about 273 million
people in 1999; Indonesia, 216 million; and Brazil, 172 million.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Reports about the funeral for Cardinal John O'Connor of New
York stated that there are eight remaining U.S. cardinals. Who are
they? Also, can you explain the hierarchy of the Roman Catholic
Church?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually there are seven active cardinals in the United
States, not eight, said David Early of the U.S. Catholic Conference
in Washington. They are Cardinals Anthony Bevilacqua, Archdiocese
of Philadelphia; Francis George, Chicago; James Hickey, Washington,
D.C.; William Keeler, Baltimore; Bernard Law, Boston; Roger Mahony,
Los Angeles; and Adam Maida, Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   There are three other American cardinals, but they are working
in the Vatican, Early added.
</P>
<P>
   The hierarchy (organization of the clergy by rank) starts with
the pope, or Holy Father, who is head of the Roman Catholic Church
and the highest member of its clergy. Below the pope, in decreasing
order, are cardinals, archbishops, bishops, priests, and deacons.
The pope and bishops are responsible for the pastoral governance of
the Church.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, between the two sacramental orders of bishop and
priest, you sometimes find monsignor, a purely honorary title
granted to certain priests in recognition of exceptional service to
the Church.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm confused about the Catholic practice for cardinals, such
as the late John Cardinal O'Connor of New York, to have the first
name before the title. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's simply Catholic tradition, explained Bill Ryan of the
U.S. Catholic Conference in Washington, but it isn't universally
followed. ``Sometimes it's Cardinal followed by the first and last
names,'' Ryan added. General newspaper style, however, is to put
the title before the name.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported on the title of cardinal in the Roman Catholic
Church, which sometimes appears before a first name, and sometimes
between the first and last names. Can you explain the origin of its
use in the latter way?
</P>
<P>
   A: It derives from an 18th century English custom, said Bill
Ryan of the U.S. Catholic Conference in Washington. Various nobles
_ such as Alfred Lord Tennyson _ rearranged their names and titles
for their own purposes. The practice was imitated by many courts in
Europe at the time, Ryan added, and survives to the present day,
although it's not common. As he explained earlier, it's not always
followed by the Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In baseball, what exactly is a balk?
</P>
<P>
   A: The purpose of the balk rule _ which was adopted in 1899 _ is
to limit what the pitcher is allowed to do in an attempt to pick
off a runner.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, it's pretty simple: When the pitcher is on the mound
and his foot is in contact with the rubber, he cannot fake one
thing and then do another. He cannot fake a pitch and then throw to
a base, or fake a throw to a base and then pitch. If he starts
either action, he must finish that action without hesitation or
alteration.
</P>
<P>
   The rule specifies many specific actions, but it is a judgment
of the umpire as to whether or not one action was started (and not
completed).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently printed a poem that starts off ``Monday's child
is fair of face,'' and so on through the days of the week. This has
started a controversy in my family, because we can't find out what
day of the week we all were born on. Is there any such thing as a
perpetual calendar? Calendar companies used to distribute them free
years ago, but I can't find any now, and I've been told that
they're no longer available.
</P>
<P>
   A: Check the World Book Encyclopedia, Volume C, and under
Calendar you'll find three tables showing the day of the week for
any year desired, 1753 to 2030. The letters in the Table of Years
refer to the first column of the Table of Months. The figures in
the Table of Months refer to one of seven columns in the Table of
Days.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, to find what day of the week Christmas fell on in
1900, you'd look for 1900 in the Table of Years. It's followed by
the letter a. Look for a in the Table of Months, and under
December, you'll find the number 6. In the Table of Days, column 6
tells you that the 25th day, Christmas, fell on a Tuesday in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   It's somewhat easier if you're online. Go to
http://dmarie.com/asp/history.asp?action &QC; process. Enter the date
you're interested in, press Go, and information pops up showing
which day of the week it was, the top news stories of the day, most
popular songs of the times, average house and car prices, and more.
Another good eternal calendar site is www.aia-and.com/eternal.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will Coca-Cola's million-dollar prize offer at Turner Field
in Atlanta be in effect during this summer's All-Star Game Home Run
Derby? What about during the All-Star Game itself?
</P>
<P>
   A: Atlanta Braves spokesman Glen Serra says Coke ended its $1
million reward in April for hitters who reached the Sky Field, in
the third deck in left field. No one ever did it, although on April
20 Andres Galarraga hit a towering shot that struck one foot from
the top of the foul pole, threatening to reach the ``unreachable''
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter soon will achieve the Gold Award from the Girl
Scouts. It's the highest honor Scouts can get. Who are some of
better-known recipients of this award? I'm having trouble locating
a listing of previous notable recipients.
</P>
<P>
   A: The reason you're having trouble is because there is no such
list. While many former Girl Scouts have gone on to become famous
in later life, records have not been kept showing which ones
received Gold Awards, said Ellen Christie-Ach of the organization's
New York office. It would be safe to conclude, however, that at
least some famous former Scouts achieved the Gold.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you print the words to the Molson beer commercial, ``I
am Canadian Joe''?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is the transcript of the commercial, ``Joe's Rant,'' as
performed by actor Jeff Douglas:
</P>
<P>
   I am not a lumberjack, or a fur trader.
</P>
<P>
   I don't live in an igloo,
</P>
<P>
   or eat blubber, or own a dogsled,
</P>
<P>
   and I don't know Jimmy, Suzie, or Sally from Canada,
</P>
<P>
   although I am certain they are really, really nice.
</P>
<P>
   I have a prime minister, not a president
</P>
<P>
   I speak English and French, not American
</P>
<P>
   I pronounce it ``about,'' not ``a boot''
</P>
<P>
   I can proudly sew my country's flag on my backpack
</P>
<P>
   I believe in peacekeeping, not policing
</P>
<P>
   Diversity, not assimilation
</P>
<P>
   and that the beaver is a proud and noble animal.
</P>
<P>
   The tuque is a hat,
</P>
<P>
   A chesterfield is a couch,
</P>
<P>
   And ``Z'' is pronounced zed, not zee, ZED
</P>
<P>
   Canada is the second-largest land mass,
</P>
<P>
   The first nation of hockey, and
</P>
<P>
   the best part of North America!
</P>
<P>
   My name is Joe, and
</P>
<P>
   I am Canadian!
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
