<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GUGGENHEIM-1900-ART-2     05-18 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUGGENHEIM-1900-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KITSCH IN SYNC WITH TREASURES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., France, Egypt, Italy, Portugal, Argentina)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Guggenheim's ``1900: Art at the Crossroads'' is a
wacky exercise in historical simulation, the excuse being a new
century. It is hard to remember the last time so many bad pictures
were in one place at one time, unless you consider eBay a place.
But the show no doubt will be as popular in New York as it was in
London. There is no underestimating the public's taste for kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good deal of excellent art mixed in among the dogs,
and sometimes what is best is not what you would expect, which is
partly the show's point. It tries to conjure up the situation in
art at the turn of the last century, when Picasso was a
little-known young Spaniard, and a French painter named Paul Chabas
won the gold medal at the 1900 Paris Exposition Universelle for a
vaporous confection of soft-core bathing beauties called ``Joyous
Frolics.'' We see Mondrian cheek by jowl with Albijn Van den
Abeele, Renoir with Anders Zorn, Kandinsky with Pal Szinyei Merse.
If you think you know who comes out on top in each case, you are
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   We're meant to look anew at a moment 100 years ago, when it was
not yet clear who would be the pioneers in the 20th century and who
would be forgotten. Thus recapturing innocence, we can make
connections between conservatives and avant-gardists, Americans and
Finns, one generation and another, which for the sake of
simplification or because of ignorance art historians have glossed
over or ignored.
</P>
<P>
   That's the idea, anyway. The lesson is simply that ``history is
messy,'' Simon Schama's phrase, which the catalog approvingly
quotes, although it might be more precise to say that the present
is messy while history, after historians have finished with it, is
always too tidy.
</P>
<P>
   It is useful to be reminded of this. But we ought to be careful
about taking ``1900'' too much at face value. This being a global
age, imagine an exhibition of current art that mixed selections
from the Venice Biennale with art made by members of the National
Academy of Design; work by star graduates from art schools in
Beijing, Los Angeles and Cairo; and examples by the leading
Argentine and Portuguese portrait painters, whoever they are. An
interesting cross section maybe, but would it fairly represent
where we are now in art, or would it be a hodgepodge of the sort
one could fabricate for any year during the last century or two?
</P>
<P>
   Here, for example, we find the young Picasso, Mondrian, Kupka
and Kandinsky, who, had they stopped painting in 1900, we can
presume would be ignored today. Kupka, soon to invent pure
abstraction, was painting frothy lunching parties for the 1900
Paris fair, retrograde art for the marketplace by someone with more
talent and imagination than what we see suggests (demonstrating
that one should be careful before writing off a young artist).
</P>
<P>
   It is vaguely interesting to be reminded of how Kupka, Picasso
and the others conformed to convention at the turn of the century.
But hindsight is why they are here, and it's of limited historical
value to note that at that instant they were outshone by more
successful artists whom they would soon eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   The show, with 250 paintings and sculptures filling the whole
museum, was organized by Robert Rosenblum, the art historian, now a
Guggenheim curator, who has written widely about old and new art.
His unconventional textbook on the 19th century puts many
once-famous, now-forgotten figures into the story line. The
exhibition extends this principle. Rosenblum assumes scholastic
neutrality about whether, say, Carl Wilhelmson is as good a painter
as Cezanne. They worked at the same time; they're both in the show.
We decide.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is laughably easy, but detractors will call this an
abdication of curatorial responsibility. You can bet that
traditionalist critics are charging up their computers to fight the
latest Armageddon of artistic standards at the Guggenheim.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind. The show provides compensatory rewards for its
schlock quotient and whatever might be unclear about its
inclusionary standards.
</P>
<P>
   There are discoveries, for example, and this is a reason to see
any show. Eugene Jansson was painting luminous scenes in an
Impressionist mode when Monet was painting London and the Seine,
and Jansson holds his own in a single picture of Stockholm Bay.
Ignacio Zuloaga, the flashy Spanish society portraitist, stands out
for a bizarre homage to Velazquez in the form of a portrait of a
dwarf, and he comes across as more daring than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Ferdinand Hodler, the important Swiss painter, can't be called a
discovery, but he emerges as an even more refined, luminous
innovator in this context. Likewise, Eugene Carriere, the Symbolist
who painted misty spiritualistic monochromes with the quality of
nighttime snapshots, proves to be a true original.
</P>
<P>
   Carriere, Zuloaga and others exemplify a widespread mood of
paranoia, pessimism and general fin-de-siecle angst, cutting across
nationalities, generations and styles. It isn't quite true that not
a single picture in this exhibition depicts the sun shining through
clear skies, but almost. These are literally dark works. Poverty,
religious fear, loneliness, sexual anxiety including homosexual
guilt, distrust of industrialization: They're the symptoms of a
psychic havoc wrought by Freud, late Victorianism, urban sprawl,
the reshuffling of social classes and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Who can deny that these artists had a reason to be glum?
</P>
<P>
   Two world wars later, after the bloodiest century in history, we
should regard them as visionaries. Even the glassy world of the
supremely retrograde academic William-Adolphe Bouguereau suggests a
desperation to escape from reality. One of the show's surprises is
simply reminding us that Bouguereau was still around when someone
like Maurice de Vlaminck was painting ``The Bar,'' a brash and
grotesque paean to modern night life, primed for hard times.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first exhibition to present a cross section of a
year from a century ago. The Orsay Museum in Paris did something
similar in 1993 about painting across Europe in 1893, a smaller
show, less flashy. That was an underappreciated experiment because
the time perhaps wasn't right. Exhibitions of old art, whatever
they're about, are successful only if they speak to the present,
and the value of ``1900,'' its drawbacks aside, is ultimately to
hold up a mirror to now.
</P>
<P>
   The situation for art in 2000 seems as hard to parse as it
clearly was 100 years ago. And 1900 was also an in-between moment,
a creative no man's land, despite everything that was going on.
Cezanne, Degas, Renoir and Monet were around, but they were no
longer new. That goes double for Bouguereau. Cubism was still a few
years off. Art has these difficult-to-define episodes, then moves
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   The show also proves that bad art can sometimes get a second
look, profitably. Because painting today encompasses camp without
guilt, it wouldn't be surprising if Leon Frederic's triptych ``The
Stream,'' with its Rubensian babies cascading through Alpine mist,
caught some contemporary artists' attention, if only for its sheer
hypnotic awfulness. I could imagine that John Currin, for example,
a fashionable painter now, might be intrigued by Frederic or by
Antonio Teixeira Carneiro, the Portuguese Symbolist, or even by
Bouguereau.
</P>
<P>
   It takes fresh eyes to see art turned on its head. Jean-Leon
Gerome, Bourguereau's conservative colleague, inspired Dali with
his ``Optician,'' a trompe l'oeil curio painted for a 1902 Paris
exhibition of advertising signs: a dog with a monocle is sandwiched
between a pince-nez with disembodied eyes and the fractured word
``O PTI CIEN.'' It is a pun on ``Au petit chien,'' meaning ``oh,
little dog'' or ``at the sign of the little dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Wordplay. Surrealism. No wonder Dali loved it. Rosenblum calls
the work an instance of unwitting prophesy: ``Who would have
expected the stuffy Jean-Leon Gerome, who railed against the
Impressionists at the 1900 fair, to produce a strange painting that
offered a preview of Dada and Surrealism?''
</P>
<P>
   One might put it this way: that artists, who are trained to
think unconventionally, often do not feel as constrained as the
rest of us by the verdicts of art historians, so they may sometimes
help us see what we dismiss too easily or refuse to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Patience is required. This show strains it. The weak-hearted and
modern-day culture Pharisees may never get past the shock of
confronting so much of the art that the abstractionists were
rebelling against in a great museum created as a shrine to
20th-century abstraction. Heathens have taken over the temple
again. Could there by any further blasphemy?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, yes. The traveling Norman Rockwell exhibition arrives
at the Guggenheim soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
