<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, May 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A weakening upper-level low, which spawned a swarm of tornadoes
in the Plains on Wednesday and more twisters across the Middle West
on Thursday, will move east from the Ohio Valley toward the Middle
Atlantic states on Friday. The depleted state of the upper-level
low will limit severe weather. Nonetheless, isolated damaging winds
can still occur east of the central Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   A low-pressure system over southern Ohio will ripple east along
a cold front, drawing moist air south of the front over a wedge of
cool air north of the front. As a result, cool rain will spread
slowly east over the central Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Widely separated thunderstorms, some with hail and damaging
winds, will erupt from northeast Texas to the Tennessee and lower
Ohio Valleys.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WET WYOMING
</P>
<P>
   At Casper, Wyo., nearly 70 percent of the 12 inches of average
annual precipitation occurs from late spring to summer. Most of
this growing-season precipitation falls from thunderstorms. On
Wednesday, 2.22 inches of rain deluged Casper as a potent
disturbance churned across the Rockies. Wednesday's rainfall
amounted to more than Casper's entire May average of two inches.
Like Casper, many towns that lie in the lee of the Rockies receive
a mere modicum of rain, on average, frequently rendered dry by the
lofty Rockies, which act like a shield against Pacific moisture. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
