<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-DISABLED-WARN19-COX     05-18 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-WARN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EASTWOOD SAYS LAWYERS EXPLOITING LAW FOR A FISTFUL OF DOLLARS
 &HT;    360&AMP;adds.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a noisy audience in wheelchairs on one side of
the issue and Clint Eastwood on the other, a congressional
subcommittee considered Thursday whether businesses should be
warned before being sued for violating the Americans with
Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   The current law ``is just not fair,'' Eastwood told a House
Judiciary panel.
</P>
<P>
   The actor and former mayor of Carmel, Calif., said he supports
the goals of the ADA, a decade-old statute requiring public
accommodations to be accessible to the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said unscrupulous lawyers are ``perverting the law''
by filing scores of lawsuits against small businesses and
collecting legal fees even if the problem is corrected as soon as
the owner learns of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``These lawyers cloak themselves under the guise they're doing a
favor for the disabled, when really they're doing a disservice,''
said Eastwood. The actor said he was hit with such a lawsuit and a
demand for $500,000 in legal fees concerning an alleged ADA
violation at his Mission Ranch Hotel and restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing of the Constitution subcommittee, Eastwood
testified in support of an amendment authored by Reps. Mark Foley
and E. Clay Shaw, both Florida Republicans. The legislation would
require that businesses be notified of an ADA violation and given
time to fix it before being sued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It simply says that, before filing a lawsuit against a
business for ADA access violations, let the business know it's out
of compliance and give them 90 days to clean up their act,'' said
Foley. ``If they don't, then by all means, sue.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the vocal observers in wheelchairs who crowded the hearing
room and hallway outside, though, sentiment was decidedly against
the change.
</P>
<P>
   With the amendment, business owners could just await a violation
notice _ that might not ever come _ before making their
establishments accessible to the handicapped, opponents told the
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary economic incentive driving voluntary compliance is
avoidance of litigation and the prospect of paying attorneys' fees
if the complaining party prevails,'' said Christine Griffin,
executive director of the Disability Law Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional adds follow.)
</P>
<P>
   However, Foley said the amendment is needed because lawyers are
exploiting the law set up to protect the civil rights of disabled
people. While the statute prevents disabled plaintiffs for
receiving damage awards, it allows fees for attorneys who file
lawsuits claiming violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ADA is being used by some attorneys to shake down
thousands of businesses from Florida to California,'' Foley told
the subcommittee. ``And they're doing it at the expense of people
with disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Donna and David Batelaan, a disabled couple who own and
operate a mobility equipment business in Lake Worth, Fla., said
they were sued _ without notice _ for having an improperly painted
handicapped parking spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cost us less than $100 to correct the infraction and $2,000
for attorney's fees,'' said Donna Batelaan.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Fields Jr., a West Palm Beach, Fla., attorney, said he
fought for the rights of the disabled for years and ``never thought
that I would be on the other side'' defending businesses. But he
told of defending the owner of a baseball card shop who had
promptly corrected his ADA deficiencies but was then hit with a
bill for $4,500 in attorney's fees and costs.
</P>
<P>
   He said 1,000 such suits have been filed in South Florida, and
predicted a national ``explosion of ADA litigation'' unless the law
is changed.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy K. Fields, the assistant Palm Beach County attorney, said
that the county commission had adopted a resolution urging Congress
to pass the ADA amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The commission acted after one law firm filed 38 lawsuits in two
weeks against ``longtime established mom and pop businesses'' who
were unaware of modifications they needed to make to comply with
the ADA. The suits were filed on behalf of a disabled Broward
County child and included cases against a liquor store and a pawn
shop.
</P>
<P>
   Once informed of their violations, most of the businesses
quickly tried to fix the problems, Fields said. ``They then
received demand letters from the plaintiffs attorney for $5,000 in
fees.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses warned that the law should not be weakened
because of actions of a few greedy attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The federal law has been on the books for a decade, pointed out
Frederick Shoz, owner of an ADA consulting company in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., so businesses have had plenty of time to come
into compliance. He said it is unfair to ask disabled people to
wait another 90 days when they encounter an illegal obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Subcommittee members said the issue presents a quandary.
</P>
<P>
   Some said it does seem unfair to file a lawsuit without warning
and charge legal fees to an unknowing small business owner who acts
quickly to comply with the law to provide proper access to the
disabled. However, without the threat of a lawsuit, there is no
incentive to provide the legal accessibility until receiving the
90-day notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very difficult issue to deal with,'' said Rep. Mel
Watt, D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
