<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     05-18 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `BATTLEFIELD EARTH,' starring John Travolta and Barry Pepper.
Directed by Roger Christian (PG-13, 117 minutes). In the year 3000,
beings from the planet Psychlo conquer Earth in only nine minutes
and reduce all humans to grunting illiterates. The chief nasty,
Terl (Travolta), devises a scheme to put the man-animals to work in
the gold mines for him. He sees potential in one cave dweller
(Pepper) and straps him to a machine that beams the wisdom of the
ages into his head. Little does Terl realize that by educating a
human, he is sowing the seeds of his own destruction. Sitting
through this film with its stock villains is like watching the most
expensively mounted high school play of all time. It may be a bit
early to make such judgments, but ``Battlefield Earth'' may well
turn out to be the worst movie of this century (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `CENTER STAGE,' starring Ethan Stiefel, Sascha Radetsky, Amanda
Schull, Peter Gallagher and Donna Murphy. Directed by Nicholas
Hytner (PG-13, 113 minutes). Hytner's film tracks the professional
and romantic travails of a group of young dancers at the fictitious
American Ballet Academy in New York. The script is a patchwork of
showbiz movie and romantic comedy cliches, and the acting rarely
rises above daytime soap-opera obviousness, but who ever went to a
dance movie to see good writing or realistic acting? The movie is
loaded with lively dance sequences, and Hytner films them
beautifully, especially the show-stopping finale, choreographed by
Susan Stroman and spiritedly danced by Stiefel, Radetsky and the
lovely Schull, who carries the movie with her energy and grace
(A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `COMING SOON,' starring Bonnie Root, Gaby Hoffmann and Mia
Farrow. Directed by Colette Burson (R, 91 minutes). Burson's
teen-age comedy was twice threatened with an NC-17 rating by the
MPAA, but this tale of a somewhat directionless high school
senior's quest for her first orgasm (and, incidentally, a spot at
an Ivy League college) is much less offensive than a lot of smirky,
cynical PG-13 fare. It is unusual to see the sexuality of young
women treated with such candor, and Burson's satirical view of
Stream, her heroine (Root), is leavened with respect. The movie
often loses focus, and the comic pace often flags. The real fun
lies not in following Stream's episodic travails but in watching
Hoffmann as her spoiled best friend and Farrow as her holy hippie
terror of a mother compete to see who can steal the most scenes
from the wan, earnest Root (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `EAST-WEST,' starring Sandrine Bonnaire, Oleg Menchikov and
Catherine Deneuve. Directed by Regis Wargnier (PG-13, 115 minutes).
After World War II the Soviet government undertook a propaganda
campaign to entice Russians living in the West to return home.
Alexei Golovine (Menchikov) and his French wife, Marie (Bonnaire),
the couple at the heart of Wargnier's sumptuous, moving historical
melodrama, are luckier than most of their fellow returnees, who are
killed or imprisoned on arrival. ``East-West'' chronicles Alexei's
ambivalence about their new life in a drab, depressing communal
apartment and Marie's desperate attempts to escape it. The film may
be faulted for dissolving the horrors of history in Hollywood-style
catharsis, but it also uses the resources of old-fashioned
emotionally emphatic filmmaking to shed light on forgotten history.
``East-West'' is a grand costume pageant, full of grandeur and
period detail, but it is also the portrait of a marriage under
extreme external and internal pressure, and a showcase for two
great film actresses: Bonnaire and Deneuve, playing an actress who
becomes aware of Marie's plight during a tour of the Soviet Union
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `FREQUENCY,' starring Dennis Quaid and Jim Caviezel. Directed by
Gregory Hoblit (PG-13, 100 minutes). ``Back to the Future'' meets
``Field of Dreams'' meets ``It's a Wonderful Life'' meets ``The
Sixth Sense'' in this entertaining but shamelessly sentimental
supernatural soap opera with a macho heart. Caviezel is a morose
young policeman who contacts his dead father, a heroic firefighter,
on a ham radio and contrives to save him from the accident that
cost him his life during the 1969 World Series. From here, the two
collaborate on changing other aspects of the past and on catching a
serial killer. There are enough testosterone tears to soak Shea
Stadium (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `GLADIATOR,' starring Russell Crowe, Joaquin Phoenix, Connie
Nielsen, Richard Harris and Oliver Reed. Directed by Ridley Scott
(R, 150 minutes). This movie is the answer to a question no one
bothered to ask: What would happen if someone decided to film the
imminent extreme football league as if it were a Chanel commercial?
Scott subjects action-packed bouts of mayhem and decapitation in
the Roman Colosseum to his glossy, inhuman directing style; it is
admirable but repellent. Crowe is the noble Roman general who ends
up fighting for his life. Crowe gives a performance with
ball-of-fire intensity, suffused with a movie star's impatience. He
holds the movie together, such as it is (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `HAMLET,' starring Ethan Hawke, Liev Schreiber, Julia Stiles,
Bill Murray, Diane Venora and Sam Shepard. Directed by Michael
Almereyda (R, 112 minutes). Almereyda has rooted his voluptuous and
rewarding new adaptation of Shakespeare's play in today's
Manhattan. The city's contradictions of beauty and squalor give the
movie a sense of place, and New York becomes a complex character in
this vital and sharply intelligent film. Often shaded in lush,
soothing hues of blue, ``Hamlet'' exudes an intoxicating masochism
in which half the cast is battling despondency and the other half
has the glint of imminent insanity. Here, the melancholy of Hamlet
(Hawke) over the death of his father is almost a state of grace: it
gives him a sense of purpose that the other characters lack. The
director's rigorous trimming has a boldness and vivacity that makes
this version exhilarating while leaving Shakespeare's language and
intent intact (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `I DREAMED OF AFRICA,' starring Kim Basinger and Vincent Perez.
Directed by Hugh Hudson (PG-13, 120 minutes). This screen
adaptation of Kuki Gallmann's memoir about her life in Kenya with
an adventurer husband and two children is little more than a
picturesque travelogue. Although the story is loaded with tragedy,
a stiff, expository screenplay and mostly weak performances keep it
from resonating. Basinger's spaced-out baby-doll Kuki and Perez's
petulant husband render this conservation-minded couple remote and
vaguely unsympathetic. That couldn't have been the movie's
intention (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `LOVE AND BASKETBALL,' starring Sanaa Lathan and Omar Epps.
Directed by Gina Prince-Bythewood (PG-13, 118 minutes). The
writer-director Gina Prince-Bythewood's feature-film debut, about
the romantic and competitive bond between the basketball players
Monica (Lathan) and Quincy (Epps), has an enchanting, lived-in
homeyness. Prince-Bythewood does a wonderful job of creating an
atmosphere for her characters _ particularly for the superb Lathan
_ but the movie fails to fashion a consistent narrative. It doesn't
seem to be about anything. But it is a promising first movie from a
filmmaker with a lot to offer. Who knew anyone could get a drama
out of Title IX, the federal law ensuring that girls get a chance
to compete in school sports? (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `TIME CODE,' starring Jeanne Tripplehorn, Saffron Burrows, Holly
Hunter and Stellan Skarsgard. Directed by Mike Figgis (R, 93
minutes). Figgis' astonishing new film, shot in a single day with
hand-held digital video cameras, tells four stories simultaneously,
in real time. ``Time Code'' is at once a mordant satire of the
hypocrisy and self-delusion of the film industry and an earnest
declaration of faith in the medium itself. In addition to its
technical innovations, which test the limits of the human eye, ear
and mind, the film boasts some brilliant improvisational acting
from its enormous cast. Especially fine are Tripplehorn and
Skarsgard, whose strongly emotional performances add a measure of
pathos. Whether ``Time Code'' will ultimately be seen as a bold
prophecy of the dawning visual age or as a passionate, gimmicky
curio is for the future to decide. At present, though, it is hard
to think of a more exciting demonstration of the inexhaustible
possibilities of film (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `28 DAYS,' starring Sandra Bullock, Viggo Mortensen, Steve
Buscemi and Dominic West. Directed by Betty Thomas (PG-13, 110
minutes). Bullock gives a creditable performance as Gwen Cummings,
a fun-loving New York writer ordered to visit a drug and alcohol
rehabilitation clinic after a drunken car accident. Veering
unsteadily between comedy and suds, the movie portrays Gwen's
fellow residents at Serenity Glen as a bunch of goofy caricatures
and confuses things further with its dime-store psychologizing. It
ultimately reduces the rehab experience to a zany (but mostly
unfunny) summer-camp farce (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `U-571,' starring Matthew McConaughey, Bill Paxton, Jon Bon
Jovi, David Keith and Harvey Keitel. Directed by Jonathan Mostow
(PG-13, 120 minutes). Mostow, whose previous film, ``Breakdown,''
was a marvel of B-picture minimalism, shifts from the wide-open
spaces to the cramped interior of a World War II submarine movie.
McConaughey, whose knotted-with-unease face makes it look as if he
is cramming for finals, is part of a secret mission to capture a
Nazi code-encryption machine and get it back to the Allies. He and
his crew have to do so on a Nazi U-boat they have hijacked. Mostow
does a fine job of building tension, given that he is working in a
minor genre whose climactic notes you will know if you have ever
seen a movie set on a sub (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `THE VIRGIN SUICIDES,' starring Kirsten Dunst, James Woods and
Kathleen Turner. Directed by Sofia Coppola (R, 97 minutes).
Coppola's directorial debut, adapted from Jeffrey Eugenides' 1993
novel about the self-destruction of five sisters in a 1970s
Michigan suburb, shows her to be a filmmaker with fine visual and
emotional instincts, adept at matching the book's hypnotic, sensual
black humor. The movie's best moments have an inspired feeling of
playfulness and freedom matched by Dunst's smart, beguiling
performance as Lux Lisbon, whose sexual awakening propels her and
her sisters to their doom. But despite Coppola's keen instincts,
and the beautifully understated acting of Woods and Turner as the
Lisbon parents, ``The Virgin Suicides'' is marred by the
self-conscious aestheticism and emotional detachment of its source
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `WHERE THE HEART IS,' starring Natalie Portman and Ashley Judd.
Directed by Matt Williams (PG-13, 115 minutes). Young Novalee
Nation (Portman) is terribly phobic about the number five, and
about five minutes into this astonishingly shameless melodrama with
its lower-class sweetheart heroine, you will start to feel exactly
the same way. The movie seems to be stuck with its own five
fixation, too, because a new character or situation is introduced
every five minutes, or so it feels, to keep things lively.
Abandoned by her boyfriend, Novalee gives birth in a Wal-Mart. She
later befriends a nurse ( Judd), a single mom with a passel of
children, and takes up photography. The audience doesn't get credit
for being able to track a character through life without the film's
being stuffed with enough nutty incidents _ a kidnapping,
catastrophic storms _ for an entire season of television
(Mitchell).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DRESDNER-JOBCUTS-NYT &LR;      05-18 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRESDNER-JOBCUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY'S DRESDNER BANK TO LAY OFF 10 PERCENT OF WORK FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Dresdner Bank AG, which abandoned merger
talks last month with Germany's largest bank, Deutsche, is expected
to announce plans on Friday to reduce its work force by 5,000
people _ about 10 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes as Dresdner, Germany's third largest bank, is
struggling to regain its balance after the collapse of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner, like most of Germany's other big banks, is under
tremendous pressure to reduce costs in its retail banking business.
Before calling off their planned merger, Dresdner and Deutsche had
planned to eliminate a combined total of 16,000 jobs and about
5,900 in the retail banking business.
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner executives knew they would have to consolidate
operations regardless of whether they merged with another bank. But
the severity of the anticipated job cuts, first reported Thursday
by Dow Jones Newswires, is far more than banking industry analysts
had foreseen.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts also would be the first concrete move by Dresdner's new
chairman, Bernd Fahrholz, who took over on May 1 after Bernard
Walter resigned from the top job.
</P>
<P>
   Fahrholz, who will preside over Dresdner's annual shareholder
meeting on Friday, will also be making his first extended
appearance in public and providing his first clues to his strategy
for putting the failed merger behind.
</P>
<P>
   Walter, who had negotiated the proposed merger with Deutsche
Bank, announced plans to quit the day after he called off the
merger talks in early April. Deutsche, which would have clearly
dominated the new institution, had insisted on gutting most of
Dresdner's investment banking subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Since the merger collapsed, Dresdner's stock has declined about
7 percent and closed Thursday at 45.31 euros, down two-tenths of a
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner has been fighting to halt a defection of investment
bankers who had been rattled by the near-shutdown of their
business.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say it must also reduce costs and find a way out of
its problems in retail banking. The problem is that unilaterally
shutting bank branches almost certainly means losing customers to
rivals with branches across the street.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the only institution under pressure. Deutsche Bank has
come in for scathing criticism for mishandling the negotiations and
for the way its top executives fought each other.
</P>
<P>
   And Commerzbank, Germany's fourth largest bank, has become a
target of almost daily takeover speculation. In the last month, a
Dutch investment group called Rebon NV has acquired a 17 percent
stake in Commerzbank.
</P>
<P>
   The man behind Rebon's investment is a former executive of
Dresdner Bank, Hans Georg Hoffmann, who has indicated that he wants
to facilitate some kind of merger between Commerzbank and another
institution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9135 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0519-COX     05-18 2661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Wearing their foreign affairs hats
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Visits with foreign leaders and discussion of foreign policy are
on the agendas for both presidential candidates next week. Al Gore
is to meet Monday with South African President Thabo Mbeki, who
will be on his first state visit to the United States. George W.
Bush also is expected in Washington on Monday for a speech to the
American-Israel Public Affairs Committee. He also plans to meet
Tuesday with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, said spokesman
Scott McClellan. Gore addresses the same organization on Tuesday.
Bush also is expected to meet with Mbeki later in the week, either
in Austin or Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE JUST THE THOUGHT OF HILLARY WILL KEEP HIM GOING
</P>
<P>
   As Rudy Giuliani edges toward fateful decisions on prostate
cancer treatment and his Senate candidacy, some of his key aides
and allies are predicting he'll stay in the race. The NYC mayor is
scheduled to appear on an hourlong MSNBC town hall tonight, and
Republican officials say it's unlikely he'd do so if he doesn't
plan to stay in the race against Hillary Clinton. Giuliani has
spent a lot of time closeted with senior advisers, including
campaign manager Bruce Teitelbaum, deputy mayor Joseph Lhota and
chief of staff Anthony Carbonetti. ``My guess is he is going to
run,'' the New York Daily News quoted one member of the mayor's
inner circle as saying. ``I can't see Hillary Clinton winning this
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   HMMM, NOW ABOUT THAT MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Weighing in the balance of Rudy Giuliani's decision on whether
to stay in the Senate race are the millions of dollars he has
raised. Nearly half of the $19 million has been donated by
out-of-state voters, many of whom answered solicitations because
they dislike his opponent, Hillary Clinton. Yet under federal law,
Giuliani may squirrel away every cent of the more than $9 million
he hasn't spent _ even if he drops out. That prospect irritates St.
Louis banker Michael Ross, for one. Ross contributed as much as
federal law permits to Giuliani's Senate race. Sure, he admires
Giuliani and wishes him well. But the $2,000 in checks he wrote to
the Friends of Giuliani account were for one purpose, he said:
keeping Clinton out of the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   TOGETHER AT BIRTH, SEPARATED AT COLLEGE
</P>
<P>
   One of George W. Bush's twin daughters plans to continue the
family tradition by attending Yale University in New Haven, Conn.,
while the other will stay home to study at the University of Texas
at Austin. The fraternal twins, 18, graduate next week from Stephen
F. Austin High, a public school. Barbara Pierce Bush, named for her
paternal grandmother, is going to Ivy League Yale. Her father
received an undergraduate degree from Yale in 1968. His father and
grandfather also were Yalies. Bush's other daughter, Jenna Welch
Bush, named for her maternal grandmother, will attend UT, the
state's largest university with more than 49,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   UN-CONVENTIONAL NETWORK WISDOM
</P>
<P>
   This may be the year conventions virtually disappear from prime
time for the big networks. During primary season this year, the
broadcast networks essentially ceded extended political coverage to
CNN, Fox News Channel and MSNBC. Expect more of the same for the
conventions. While ABC, CBS and NBC haven't nailed down their plans
yet, the bad memories of 1996's disastrous ratings and scripted,
sanitized conventions are still fresh. Conventions ``are no longer
news events,'' said broadcast consultant Andrew Tyndall. ``They're
propaganda events.'' The biggest media story four years ago was Ted
Koppel and his ABC ``Nightline'' crew abandoning the Republican
event, saying nothing newsworthy was happening.
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS PERCEIVE LESSER INFLUENCE
</P>
<P>
   Americans have little sense of power over the presidential
nominating process, with only one-fifth of them saying that voters
in the primaries chose George W. Bush or Al Gore as the nominees,
the latest New York Times/CBS News Poll shows. Seventy-five percent
favored a single national primary to the present system, where they
feel early states have too much influence. Respondents agreed that
voters had less influence over either party's choice than did
financial contributors and party leaders. For Bush, 21 percent
credited the voters, 26 percent said party leaders and 44 percent
said financial donors. For Gore, 20 percent credited voters, 48
percent said party leaders and 24 percent said financial
contributors. The poll's margin of error was 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   CAN NEVER HAVE TOO MANY AIDES
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's presidential campaign, getting ready for the
general election battle, has been expanding its senior staff _
including the hiring of a new deputy to chief strategist Karl Rove.
Chris Hennick, most recently a lobbyist with former GOP chairman
Haley Barbour's firm and who has been a political operative for
both the Republican National Committee and the Republican Governors
Association, joined the campaign this week.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH AND MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush met Microsoft founder Bill Gates several weeks
ago in Washington state, and when asked about the Justice
Department's antitrust action against the computer software giant,
signaled a sympathetic attitude. The candidate stated a preference
for ``innovation over litigation.'' Bush apparently also owns
significant share of Microsoft. The Times of London reported that
Bush's latest financial disclosure statement shows shares valued at
more than $100,000. Because the holding was purchased for a blind
trust, the Bush campaign said the Texas governor had been unaware
of the holding until he signed the disclosure forms a few weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ZONE OF PRIVACY ON ANNIVERSARY
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Al and Tipper Gore celebrate 30 years of a marriage
that has included the joys and strains of raising four children and
the emotional highs and lows of high-stakes political life. The
Gores will celebrate their anniversary at home in Washington,
according to aides. The couple had considered a getaway to Florida,
but that was scuttled after the vice president _ apparently without
consulting his wife _ agreed to allow a small pool of reporters to
accompany him on vacations.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT MAKES KEYES KEEP RUNNING?
</P>
<P>
   Since his surprisingly strong showing in the Iowa caucuses,
where he gained 14 percent of the vote, Alan Keyes has fallen off
the political radar screen and will not be elected president. So
why is he still running for president? His own campaign asked _ and
answered _ that question in a recent mailing to North Carolina
voters: There is a battle for the soul of the Republican Party, the
battle lines are forming, and those on the right side should cast
their votes for the conservative, anti-abortion rights activist.
But Michigan State University political science prof David Rohde
thinks Keyes runs simply because he wants to: ``He is in the public
eye more than he would be if he withdrew. He is getting his issues
in the public eye more. And, as long as he keeps on as an active
candidate, the media has some incentive, and some feel an
obligation, to cover him.''
</P>
<P>
   THE TAMING OF THE SHREWD
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party leaders in Colorado and Georgia have called on Pat
Buchanan, the leading contender for the Reform presidential
nomination, to resign from the party on the ground that he has been
spreading hate and intolerance and ignoring the party procedures.
Jim Mangia, secretary of the national Reform Party, predicted that
more states would move against Buchanan. Bay Buchanan, Buchanan's
sister and chief strategist, called the Colorado and Georgia moves
``much ado about nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   TRYING TO PLUG A BIG LOOPHOLE
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of senators led by Joseph Lieberman (D-Conn.)
and John McCain (R-Ariz.) introduced legislation to close a
loophole in federal tax and election law that allows nonprofit
groups to raise and spend unlimited amounts of money on political
campaigns with virtually no disclosure. Under Section 527 of the
Internal Revenue Code, groups like the Sierra Club and Republicans
for Clean Air can to raise and spend millions of dollars on behalf
of candidates, run TV ads and conduct telephone campaigns so long
as they don't explicitly advocate the election or defeat of a
specific candidate. The bill would require that such groups
register with the Federal Election Commission, disclose their
existence to the Internal Revenue Service, and reveal large
contributors and expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY'S GHOST HANGING AROUND
</P>
<P>
   ``Democratic discontent continues to register in uncontested
primaries,'' the Wall Street Journal notes. Al Gore is winning
easily, but Bill Bradley won 27 percent of the vote in Nebraska, 19
percent in North Carolina and 18 percent in West Virginia. In
contrast, John McCain's percentages in those Republican primaries
were significantly lower. That ambivalence also is being seen in
the polls. The latest Los Angeles Times poll found Gore taking 79
percent of Democrats, while George W. Bush nails down 91 percent of
Republicans. The difference may largely explain why Bush has led in
all but a few of this year's polls.
</P>
<P>
   PUTTING HOLES IN SCHWEITZER CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   With an uphill battle against Sen. Conrad Burns (R-Mont.),
Democrat Brian Schweitzer, has found another obstacle to overcome.
Schweitzer said that Voter Consumer Research, the same phone bank
company in Houston that made negative calls against John McCain in
South Carolina was making calls to Montana on behalf of Burns.
Schweitzer said Montana voters were asked if they were aware that
Schweitzer once worked in Libya, ``a known terrorist state.'' Yes,
he did once work in Libya, Schweitzer said, in 1980, as an importer
of U.S.-made farm equipment for farms being worked by Americans.
And if there was something wrong with that, he went on, ``whoever
is paying for this dirty trick push poll needs a civics lesson.''
The Burns campaign denied any knowledge or involvement.
</P>
<P>
   UNUSUAL COMBO OF OLD CHINA HANDS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush sought to reassure union workers that normalizing
trade relations with China will expand jobs and prosperity at home
and help spread freedom abroad. ``The stakes are high,'' Bush said.
``It will mean much lower trade barriers and enormous opportunities
for U.S. exports and more work and jobs for United States
workers.'' The issue puts Bush on the same side as the Clinton-Gore
administration in pressing for normalization of trade relations
with China, the world's most populous nation and a potential major
trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   PARTIES DOING THE HEAVY LIFTING
</P>
<P>
   Candidates let their political parties do much of the dirty work
in TV advertising, according to a new study that documents the
pervasive use of unregulated and increasingly popular ``issue
ads.'' Just 20 percent of the ads paid for by congressional
candidates in 1998 attacked their opponents, compared with 60
percent of those by political parties, according to the study,
released today. And two-thirds of issue ads were paid for by
political parties, with interest groups airing the rest. The study
was conducted by the Brennan Center for Justice at New York
University School of Law, an organization that advocates campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   COMING SOON: `THE AL GORE STORY'
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee is preparing to launch a
multimillion-dollar ad campaign designed to bolster Al Gore's
presidential campaign by introducing his biography to Americans.
The ad blitz, engineered by Gore's political team, could begin as
early as this month and end at the presidential convention this
summer, costing upwards of $10 million, according to Democratic
officials. The Associated Press said the ads were described by
several party officials as a discussion of Democratic issues that
give way to biographical material about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL SECURITY APOCALYPSE?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore told 10,000 senior citizens at an AARP convention in
Orlando, Fla., that ``we could see the end of Social Security as we
know it'' under George W. Bush's plan to allow private investment
of government retirement funds. Bush, campaigning a continent away
in Washington state, accused Gore of being ``mired in the past''
while he, Bush, leads by proposing changes to ensure Social
Security's future.
</P>
<P>
   A BUSY GUY _ HE'S NOT RETIRED
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush declined invitations to appear at the AARP
convention in Orlando either in person or on video. And AARP head
Horace Deets noted that Bush was the only presidential candidate of
either party to fail to appear at AARP-sponsored candidate forums
in Iowa, New Hampshire, South Carolina and Michigan. ``I can't say
they are snubbing us. ... They just haven't accepted a number of
invitations, and it's kind of hard to understand why,'' Deets said.
Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said scheduling problems prevented the
his boss from attending. Bush was campaigning in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL SECURITY IS SOCIAL SECURITY
</P>
<P>
   Claims by George W. Bush that 1.3 million federal workers have
an advantage in retirement income over private-sector workers is at
odds with what federal workers do _ and do not _ get when they
retire. Bush points to the federal retirement plan when he argues
that the Social Security program should include individual
investment accounts so that workers could invest in the stock
market and earn a higher rate of return. In fact, Hearst Newspapers
points out, most of the 2.4 million federal civilian workers pay
Social Security payroll taxes just like everyone else. They do,
however, also have a thrift savings plan _ similar to a 401(k)
retirement investment plan.
</P>
<P>
   SWIM THE DEEPEST RIVER, CLIMB _
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton broke two engagements to be by his wife's side
when she officially became the state Democratic Party's nominee for
Senate the other night. Clinton said that before they knew when
wife Hillary would speak, he had already committed to attending a
dinner for the Mexican American Legal Defense Fund and a campaign
event for the Senate Democratic Committee. He said he finally
canceled the MALDF event, telling the organization: ``I've been
with you folks a long time, and if you'll let me go hear my wife
give a speech, I'll do any event you want in America, anytime,
wherever in the future. And I told the Senate Democratic Campaign
Committee that the Senate campaign I was most interested in was
otherwise occupied tonight and I was going there.''
</P>
<P>
   GORE COMES OUT ON WOMEN'S ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   A week after feminist activists privately scolded Al Gore for
not getting his message out on domestic violence, Gore pressed
Congress to break a yearlong stalemate and reauthorize the Violence
Against Women Act, which provides funds to shelters for battered
women. ``This is the time to intensify our efforts with the goal of
eliminating violence in the home in any form,'' Gore said in a
statement e-mailed without fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   THE POSTMAN NEVER VOTES TWICE
</P>
<P>
   Oregon officials declared the nation's first test of an
all-mail-voting primary election an unqualified success, boosting
voter turnout to 50 percent, the state's highest level in a dozen
years despite a lackluster ballot. ``I think vote-by-mail is here
to stay,'' said Secretary of State Bill Bradbury. The turnout was
the highest for an Oregon primary election since 1988, when 55.1
percent of voters cast ballots. In the last primary election, two
years ago, 34.9 of registered voters participated. Vote by mail was
mainly responsible for the increase, said Bradbury.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
