<HEADLINE>
A 250-MILE YARD SALE COMES TO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Tenn., Ky.)   By DARRELL NORMAN   
 The Gadsden (Ala.) Times   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PAYNE, Ala. _ The second 250-mile yard sale along the U.S.
11 Antique Alley does not start until Friday, but Peggy and Terry
Bohannon have been at it all week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been putting out some things every day, so we'll be
ready,'' Peggy Bohannon said. Already the Bohannons and a few
friends had the parking lot in front of their store pretty well
covered with stuff. Four or five more friends were expected to set
up before Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry has had a lot of people calling, wanting to set up here,
but we decided to have just the ones we had last year,'' Peggy
said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale route covers U.S. 11 from Birmingham, Ala., to
Knoxville, Tenn. It was organized by tourism officials wanting to
duplicate the success of the 450-mile yard sale that extends from
Gadsden to northern Kentucky and draws tens of thousands to Lookout
Mountain Parkway every August. The first U.S. 11 sale last spring
drew a heavy turnout and more of the same is expected this year.
</P>
<P>
   The sale runs Friday through Sunday, but as they do for the
August sale, both vendors and shoppers got an early start.
</P>
<P>
   The Bohannons do not have far to cart their wares for the sale.
They run an antiques store in a red log cabin, separated by just a
parking lot from U.S. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The store is open infrequently, but this weekend the store and
every foot of space will be filled and ready for business. The
store is now packed with furniture, carpenter's tools, car tags,
moonshine jugs, a large parlor stove and hundreds of other things.
</P>
<P>
   A mile or two south of the Log Cabin, the grass had been freshly
mowed in a pasture on the east side of U.S. 11, and signs
advertised spaces for rent for the yard sale. Similar scenes can be
seen up and down U.S. 11 as vendors prepare for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gadsden, Ala., Timesis part of The New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
