<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-VINCENT-VENTRESCA-IN-THE-INVISIBLE-MAN-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOT TO BE GOOD-LOOKING: VINCENT VENTRESCA STARS IN `THE INVISIBLE
MAN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Vincent
Ventresca in a scene from ``The Invisible Man.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    A two-bit thief gets life in prison based on third-strike rule
and cuts one lulu of a deal with his hopelessly noble scientist
brother: Get out of jail free ... in exchange for playing guinea
pig for a government experiment involving invisibility.
 &HT;    But then all hell breaks loose. The experiment goes kablooey,
and said two-bit thief goes both invisible and nuts.
 &HT;    Welcome to ``The Invisible Man,'' the Sci-Fi Channel's latest
original series, a newfangled take on the classic H.G. Wells saga.
And meet Vincent Ventresca, who stars as the title character,
Darien Fawkes.
 &HT;    ``You don't really get the world of `The Invisible Man' until
the last five minutes of the pilot,'' Ventresca says, looking ahead
to the show's two-hour kickoff on June 9. ``What you've got is a
guy with a gland in his brain that makes him invisible, and now
what's he going to do with that power? Will he do good? Will he do
evil?
 &HT;    ``Then he's got the complexity that, if he stays invisible for
too long or if he doesn't get a shot, he'll go mad and release all
of his darkest inhibitions, thus releasing a psychopath into
society.
 &HT;    ``He then also has to deal with The Agency, this secret
government agency that's run under the auspices of the Department
of Fish and Game,'' Ventresca adds. ``They're going to give me the
counteragent as long as I do what they want me to do on a weekly
basis.''
 &HT;    What the agency wants Fawkes to do week in and week out, of
course, is to disappear for a while, infiltrate some cadre of
baddies and eliminate great threats against our great nation. By
his side _ and occasionally in his way _ stands Hobbes, Fawkes'
boss/partner, played by Paul Ben-Victor from ``The X-Files''
episode ``Tooms.''
 &HT;    ``The core of the show, I think, is the `48 Hours' relationship
between Fawkes and Hobbes,'' Ventresca says by telephone from his
Los Angeles home. ``And by `48 Hours,' I mean the movie with Eddie
Murphy and Nick Nolte.
 &HT;    ``Separately, we're pretty good at what we do,'' he says, ``but
together we make a really, really super team. I like that Hobbes is
unimpressed with my invisibility. He's more motivated on a fiscal
level, and hopefully we'll find out why he's hooked up with this
agency.''
 &HT;    The Indianapolis-born Ventresca, whose credits include the 1997
film ``Romy and Michele's High School Reunion,'' a recurring role
as ``Fun Bobby'' on ``Friends,'' a spot as a regular on the
short-lived sci-fi series ``Prey'' and a turn opposite ``Phantom
Menace'' star Jake Lloyd and ``Frequency's'' Jim Caviezel in the
upcoming independent feature ``Madison,'' hopes that ``The
Invisible Man'' is ... subversive.
 &HT;    ```Subversive' is one of those words you sort of know what it
means, but it's not until you stop and look it up that you really
know,'' the actor says. ```Subversive,' in the dictionary I read,
means to literally turn upside down.
 &HT;    ``Our pilot surprised me a couple of times,'' he says. ``You
think it's going to be this, and then something turns upside down.
It's not what you thought it would be.
 &HT;    ``That was my reaction, and I'm curious to see if other people
have that reaction.''
 &HT;    The Sci-Fi Channel has committed to the pilot and 12 subsequent
episodes, meaning that Ventresca will be disappearing for the
foreseeable future. And that's fine by him, even if he's admittedly
not the biggest genre fan on the planet.
 &HT;    ``It's not that much of a stretch,'' he says. ``Scientists
really are trying to create an invisible suit. That's a great thing
about the show _ the invisibility aspect is spelled out just enough
that, if you want to go on the ride, you can. And it doesn't insult
the audience.
 &HT;    ``You have to take some leaps, but even non-sci-fi shows ask you
to take some leaps.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Invisible Man,'' consult
the Sci-Fi Channel Web site at www.scifi.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
