<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9141 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-GLF-ARNOLD-PALMER-HNS     05-18 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ARNOLD-PALMER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `LION' OF GOLF SET THE STAGE FOR TODAY'S TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Pa.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAUL DOMINGUEZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Decades before a Tiger ruled the PGA Tour, a lion
named Arnold was the king of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the possibilities if Arnold Palmer were in his prime
now.
</P>
<P>
   What could a man with Palmer's All-American looks, charisma and
professionalism earn in today's market where athletes pitch
everything from mutual funds to Micatin?
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have won enough to buy the PGA Tour just on his
attitude alone,'' said Buddy Cook, Southwestern Bell Dominion
tournament director. ``He and Tiger Woods are similar in their
drive to excel. That's what makes them both successful.''
</P>
<P>
   If Woods is any indication, Palmer could earn twice as much as
he does now as golf's elder statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Woods earned $47 million last year while winning eight events
and pitching products such as Nike and American Express.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, 70, has not won a tournament since 1988 but he still
earned $19 million last year mainly through his golf-related
businesses and from pitching products such as Cooper Tire and
Pennzoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arnie, if he was in his prime (today), would probably be one
of the highest-paid (athletes),'' said Jim Reese, a sports
administration and facilities management assistant professor at
Ohio University. ``He is definitely going after a different target
market, but he is still very marketable.''
</P>
<P>
   Endorsements are just a portion of the money Palmer could have
earned.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has accumulated $13.9 million while winning 18 events
since joining the PGA Tour in July 1996. In comparison, Palmer won
60 titles and yet his total earnings on the PGA Tour amount to $1.8
million for a career that spans more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Just under $2 million? Woods surpassed that in his first five
PGA Tour events this year.
</P>
<P>
   When questioned about the possibilities, Palmer offered a warm,
friendly smile that has become as familiar as his unfinished swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't say I wouldn't think about that,'' Palmer said.
``It's hard to think about what might have been. If I had to do it
all over again, I would accept it if it turned out the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   While the thought of playing in his prime against today's top
golfers intrigues the competitive spirit in Palmer, he realizes he
would miss out on so much more.
</P>
<P>
   No, the PGA Tour is fine without him and his life is too
fulfilled to ever daydream about what could be.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he would miss out on all the great memories he has
accumulated over the years. He would miss out on all the great
experiences he enjoyed while competing in 724 PGA Tour events,
including his many battles with Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said he enjoyed a wonderful life with his wife, Winnie,
who died Nov. 20, 1999, after a lengthy battle with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour would not be what it is today without Palmer laying
the foundation in the '50s, '60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   The legend from Latrobe, Pa., is a key reason today's players
can earn millions annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the epitome of what golf is like,'' Cook said. ``He, and
Byron Nelson is the other person that quickly comes to mind. They
sure made it easier for the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer put golf in the national consciousness. He came along at
a time when television coverage of golf was still in its infancy,
and he became the game's first superstar.
</P>
<P>
   He did so with stirring victories and an ability to make his
fans feel like they were a part of each victory or loss. ``Arnie's
Army,'' as his fans were dubbed, were thousands strong, and yet
Palmer seemed to know each individual when he smiled or looked at
someone directly in the eye from inside the gallery ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just makes you feel that you're the one that's important,''
Cook said. ``I don't know how he does it, but he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got that charisma. He's like a magnet. His smile is so
genuine. He can look over at the ropes and smile like he's known
you for years, like you're his new best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer was also one of the first athletes to build a successful
career as a product pitchman. He began pitching Pennzoil in 1985
and helped make the product a household name, which led other
companies to recruit athletes in hopes of similar success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people that are the most successful in
endorsements as a pitchman or pitchwoman are the ones that avoid
controversy, and Arnie has been able to do that most of his
career,'' Reese said. ``He's been able to maintain a high level of
integrity in his life. There has never been an Arnie Palmer
incident. He has never pulled a Bobby Knight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
