<HEADER>
A9147 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-HNS &LR;      05-18 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRAINER UNFAZED BY POST POSITION FOR PREAKNESS FAVORITE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT GRAVES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Count trainer Neil Drysdale among those who will
tell you that post positions mean nothing in an eight-horse field
at the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale was smooth and calm Wednesday afternoon as he used the
sixth selection to pick post 7 for Fusaichi Pegasus, the
overwhelming favorite, in the draw for the 125th running of the
Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it means much, maybe nothing at all,'' Drysdale
said from the ESPN Sports Zone, where the field was drawn for
Saturday's race. ``You've got a quarter of a mile to the first
turn, so what difference does it make where you start?''
</P>
<P>
   Seven 3-year-olds will challenge Fusaichi Pegasus, the Kentucky
Derby champion who was made the 3-5 morning-line favorite for the
Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the field may be more significant than the choice of
post positions. The field is the smallest for the Preakness since
Hansel beat seven others in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Only four of the seven challengers for the Preakness, contested
at 1 3/16 miles, raced against Fusaichi Pegasus in the Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Joe Orseno's Red Bullet, one of the newcomers, will
start from post 4. Red Bullet, owned by Frank Stronach, was made
the second betting choice at 9-2 by longtime oddsmaker Clem Florio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing really well here, and the extra time off after the
Wood has done him a world of good,'' said Orseno, who is starting
his first Preakness horse. ``We have to take a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet has won three of his four career starts, the only
loss by 4 1/4 lengths to Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood Memorial. The
son of Unbridled, runner-up in the 1990 Preakness, defeated Derby
place finisher Aptitude in the Gotham.
</P>
<P>
   Snuck In, the Rebel Stakes winner and Arkansas Derby runner-up,
also makes his Triple Crown debut in the Preakness. He is trained
by Steve Asmussen and will be ridden by Cash Asmussen, the first
brother act in the history of this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's set up to fire his best shot,'' said John Cilia,
representing the owners, Ackerley Brothers. ``We just don't know if
his best shot is good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Snuck In was shipped to Churchill Downs for the Derby, but Steve
Asmussen said he wasn't pleased with his final work and kept the
son of Montbrook out of the Run for the Roses.
</P>
<P>
   Snuck In was 4-for-7 as a 2-year-old and in the money in every
start. He still has never been off the board in nine career starts,
five of them victories.
</P>
<P>
   The other Preakness newcomer is Hugh Hefner, a lightly raced son
of Bertrando who has run against California-breds in four of his
six career starts. His best finish in open company was a fourth
behind Dixie Union, Exchange Rate and Captain Steve in the Grade
III Best Pal as a 2-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Owner-breeder-trainer Edward Nahem, a friend of the colt's
namesake, selected the rail post with the fourth selection in the
draw, which was televised nationally by ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be on the lead,'' said Nahem, who is making his
first start in this race. ``I think we got to the bottom of him in
the Snow Chief (a second-place finish to Grey Memo), and that set
him up for the Preakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Bob Baffert, who won the first two legs of the Triple
Crown in 1997 and 1998 with Silver Charm and Real Quiet, is trying
to salvage a leg of this one after being shut out in last year's
classics for the first time in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take one more shot at it,'' Baffert said of
Captain Steve. ``We're here because our horse came back great from
the Derby. He ran so well for us. He just got run into a ditch by
Wheelaway.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve actually was in the lead in the stretch before
Wheelaway and jockey Rich Migliore came over and rammed them during
the stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer D. Wayne Lukas, who has won this race five times, said
he expects High Yield to run much better than his 15th-place finish
in the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus will try to become the first Preakness favorite
to win this leg since Timber Country in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
