<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATORS LAUNCH 'E-GOVERNMENT' PROJECT
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two senators launched a bipartisan effort Thursday
to give citizens more access to the federal government through the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Ideas the lawmakers said they would consider include naming a
government-wide ``information czar'' and expanding online ``G-Bay''
auctions to dispose of surplus federal property.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question we are faced with is not whether an electronic
society is emerging, and not whether e-government will become a
reality, but rather how it will occur and what form it will take,''
said Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., the ranking minority member on
the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was joined by Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., the panel's
chairman, in urging people to make use of a new Web site to help
legislators better cope with the digital future.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said the broad long-term goal was ``to allow everybody
to become openly and interactively involved in the process of
writing legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Both senators made it clear that neither had specifically
endorsed any of the 40 ``new ideas'' posted for discussion on their
new Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But in answering a reporter's question, Lieberman said the
creation of a federal CIO, or chief information officer, who could
offer the kind of centralized leadership over online issues widely
adopted by many large corporations, was ``worthy of
consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, on the other hand, voiced skepticism on the need for a
federal CIO. And a spokesman for the White House Office of
Management and Budget said that the agency's deputy director for
management ``already effectively serves as the federal CIO.''
</P>
<P>
   Both senators voiced enthusiasm over the prospect of adopting
more of the online lessons learned by the private sector to
strengthen federal services, cut operating costs, broaden citizen
involvement and, as their blurb on the Web site puts it, ``re-think
government processes.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers also raised the prospect of ``one-stop shopping''
through the Internet for those seeking multiple government permits.
They also cited the need to enhance online distribution of surplus
goods through online auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the General Services Administration's Federal Supply
Service, which makes purchases for most federal agencies, signed a
partnership with American Management Systems Inc. to form an online
auction site for surplus items. The cyberspace facility would
broaden the public auctions the GSA already holds, which raised
more than $260 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   At its new online site _ to be based on an Internet auction
system developed created by Ariba _ the GSA expects to auction off
up to $ 10 billion in government surplus items. It expects the site
to be up and running within six months.
</P>
<P>
   The ``new idea,'' as envisioned by the senators, would build on
this program to facilitate the distribution, free of charge, of
federal surplus goods to state agencies state, local governments
and qualified non-profit groups. Under the plan being reviewed at
their Web site, they could all ``be allowed to access the Internet
site themselves, to review what property is available.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: cct.georgetown.edu/development/eGov/
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
