<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, May 19, 2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds. Adds: LEWIS-JURORS, DRIVING-WHILE-BLACK
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRADE _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, seeking to apply
further pressure to Congress for passing a China trade bill next
week, trotted out Federal Reserve Board chairman Alan Greenspan
Thursday to give his support for the measure. But opponents, led by
key congressional Democrats, continued their vocal opposition and
promised to make this a vote-by-vote slugfest unlike any since the
NAFTA debate. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 7 p.m. EDT in (i) International and (w)
Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-STRAITSTRAIN _ In Taiwan on Saturday, Chen Shui-bian will
deliver his inaugural address as the nation's new president. Across
the Taiwan Strait in Beijing, Zhu Weidong will be paying close
attention. Zhu directs the political section of China's Research
Institute of Taiwan Affairs. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NRA-PREVIEW _ BELMONT, N.C. - A regular at Shooters Express,
Julia Reep has fired hundreds of rounds at the popular pistol
range. In nearby Charlotte, Doris Davis knows little about guns,
except that, last June, her daughter's ex-boyfriend shot and killed
her. A curtain raiser to the National Rifle Association's annual
meeting and exhibit, starting Friday in Charlotte. A series of
counter events is under way, hoping to raise awareness of gun
violence. ``The apathy is tremendous,'' said Herm Ziegler, chairman
of the Charlotte Coalition to Stop Gun Violence. . It is the South;
everybody is a redneck and owns a gun.'' (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-JURORS _ The judge calls it the ``hot seat,'' and the
first words out of the prosecutor's mouth are that he's sorry to
ask such personal questions and hopes not to be insulting.
Potential jurors in the Buckhead stabbings case are being asked
questions individually by a gauntlet of lawyers. Many say they have
loved ones who were gunshot victims or who are in prison. Some say
they don't trust the news media. The diverse group offers an
interesting cross-section of Fulton County and the jury selection
process highlights a number themes: weighing the importance of
civic duty against a rigorous work scheduled (some who say they
can't be impartial have been scolded by Judge Alice Bonner) and how
lawyers for both the defense and prosecution do all they can
through questions to disqualify a juror clearly in the other camp.
story to include demographics of fulton county. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DRIVING-WHILE-BLACK _ Racial profiling has become a hot topic
these days. Author Kenneth Meeks offers help for those most
vunerable to the problem in his new book, ``Driving While Black _
Highways, Shopping Malls, Taxicabs, Sidewalks: What to Do If You
Are a Victim of Racial Profiling. Locally, the ACLU and
organizations are seeing an increase in complaints. The ACLU, for
one, is about to launch an initiative this summer to get law
enforcement agencies to voluntarily collect data on the race of the
folks they stop and arrest. It also will continue to push for state
legislation on the issue. A proposed bill that would have
prohibited race-based traffic stops was narrowly defeated last
year. (Reid, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   DISABLED-WARN _ WASHINGTON _ Clint Eastwood and other witnesses,
including three from Palm Beach County, Fla., testify at a House
hearing on a bill that would give employers and others a chance to
remedy violations of the Americans With Disabilities Act before
being subject to a lawsuit. (Dart, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   E-GOVERNMENT _ WASHINGTON _ Senate Governmental Affairs Chairman
Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., launch
the ''E-Government Project'' on the Internet. The project is
designed to expand citizen access to government information and
services. (Glass, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAS _ WASHINGTON _ Despite an offer to make sweeping
changes at the School of the Americas at Fort Benning, there is a
push on Capitol Hill to close the school. Rep. Jim Moakley (D-Ma.)
is leading the charge, introducing a bill to close down the school
near Columbus and launch a congressional investigation of the
school that Rep. Cynthia McKinney calls the ``school of assains.''
The proposal is dividing the delegation with Reps. Saxby Chambliss,
Mac Collins and Sanford Bishop urging that the refashioned school
be allowed to stay in existence and McKinney and Rep. John Lewis
saying that it should be shut down. (Carr, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE-LABOR _ Organized labor's strenuous opposition to the China
trade bill in the Midwest is dampening enthusiasm for Vice
President Gore, whose presidential hopes hinge on strong labor
turnout in Ohio, Michigan and other Midwestern battleground states.
This week, steel workers are staging protests in the Canton, Ohio,
district of Ralph Regula (R-Ohio), who is undecided on the China
bill. We talk to rank and file union members about Gore in Regula's
district, a key swing district in the 2000 presdiential race.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
