<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With glowing reviews and some help from a Hollywood
legend, the Encores! concert series' production of ``Wonderful
Town,'' which had a brief run at City Center two weeks ago, may be
headed for Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Talks were under way this week between City Center officials and
several groups of producers, including Anita Waxman, Elizabeth P.
Williams and Fran and Barry Weissler, to move the musical to a
Broadway house in late fall. Rehearsals would probably begin soon
after the production's director, Kathleen Marshall, completes her
work as choreographer on ``Seussical,'' a new musical due in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be great for us and great for the company,''
said Judith Daykin, the president of City Center. ``But it's very
early in the talking stages.''
</P>
<P>
   What is known is that ``Wonderful Town'' would be a joint effort
of City Center and outside producers. Several people privy to
negotiations said that one of the quiet instigators and financial
backers of a Broadway run was Paul Newman, whose wife, Joanne
Woodward, is on the City Center and Encores! boards. Calls to
Newman's agent, Sam Cohn, were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderful Town,'' with music by Leonard Bernstein and lyrics
by Betty Comden and Adolph Green, follows two sisters from Ohio
loose in the big city. The show, with Rosalind Russell as the
wisecracking Ruth and Edie Adams as her younger, dreamier sister,
Eileen, opened at the Winter Garden in February 1953 and ran for
559 performances.
</P>
<P>
   In the Encores! incarnation Donna Murphy played Ruth and Laura
Benanti played Eileen. Reviewing the show in The New York Times,
Ben Brantley called the production a ``goose-bump-making
revelation.''
</P>
<P>
   Daykin said the Broadway version would ideally be staged in the
same stripped-down concert style as the City Center production,
with minimal sets, lighting and costumes. One area of concern for a
commercial run, however, is the size of the production's cast (32
actors) and its orchestra (30 musicians). Both those figures would
mean a large weekly overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a move to Broadway has a precedent in ``Chicago,'' the
hit revival that began as an Encores! concert in 1996. That show,
produced on Broadway by the Weisslers, turned into a giant
international hit, grossing more than $100 million in New York
alone and spawning nine other companies around the world.
</P>
<P>
   An Orphan No More
</P>
<P>
   Another musical long anticipated in New York has finally found a
home. On Nov. 7 ``Jane Eyre,'' John Caird's adaptation of the epic
Charlotte Bronte novel of a governess and heartache, is to begin
previews at the Brooks Atkinson Theater. An opening is planned for
Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The well-traveled musical, with a score by Paul Gordon, was
conceived in the early 1990s. It had a 1994 workshop at the
Manhattan Theater Club and a production in Wichita, Kan., a year
later.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996 it opened in Toronto in what was billed as a
pre-Broadway tryout. But a combination of mixed reviews and lack of
available theater delayed the move south.
</P>
<P>
   Then last summer the show re-emerged, selling out a two-month
run at the La Jolla Playhouse near San Diego, breaking box-office
records and receiving its best reviews to date. Still, no theater
was available.
</P>
<P>
   Now the show finally is expected to arrive, with Marla Schaffel
playing Jane and Mary Stout the comic Fairfax, as they have since
its early days. James Barbour is Rochester, Jane's love interest.
</P>
<P>
   Annette Niemtzow, who leads a four-member producing team, said
the long wait had been worthwhile. ``Given the situation where
everybody is so hungry for theaters,'' she said, ``we're just
thrilled to be getting our chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Clipping `Wings'
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting in the Wings,'' Noel Coward's 1960 play, is giving up
the ghost. The production, which its producers say recouped its
investment, will close on May 28.
</P>
<P>
   The closing comes as a small surprise because one of its stars,
Lauren Bacall, had recently announced a contract extension, while
its other star, Rosemary Harris, has just been nominated for a Tony
Award.
</P>
<P>
   But Leonard Soloway, a producer of the play, said that sales for
June ``looked disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking Charge
</P>
<P>
   Considering that ``Lydie Breeze,'' at New York Theater Workshop,
is about a group of friends involved in the establishment of a
utopian community, it seems fitting that the production itself
resulted from a ``let's put on a show'' mentality.
</P>
<P>
   The main cheerleader for the production was Elizabeth Marvel,
who plays the title character, the conflicted idealist at the
two-part cycle's heart. In January she arranged a casual reading of
the John Guare script by calling a group of friends. ``I said,
`We're not going to rehearse it, just read,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That reading was so successful that when another spring
production at the workshop was delayed, Marvel and her actors
jumped in. She invited Adam Guettel, a friend, to compose some
songs and asked her boyfriend, Bill Camp, to play a leading role.
</P>
<P>
   The production has received favorable reviews since opening on
Monday, the same day Marvel won an Obie Award for her work in ``A
Streetcar Named Desire,'' an earlier production at the workshop.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always hear about the disempowered actor, their fate in
other people's hands,'' Marvel said. ``It's just really wonderful
to experience it the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Return Engagement
</P>
<P>
   Blythe Danner will celebrate her 20th year acting at the
Williamstown Theater Festival in Massachusetts this summer,
appearing opposite Stephen Collins in ``Tonight at 8:30,'' a
collection of six one-acts by Noel Coward. Danner and Collins are
to perform in three of the plays, while Charlotte D'Ambroise and
Bill Irwin will appear in the other trio.
</P>
<P>
   Other casting for the summer season includes Sara Gilbert (late
of the television show ``Roseanne'') in ``Hot L Baltimore,'' Marian
Seldes in ``The Skin of Our Teeth'' and Eric Stoltz in ``Light Up
the Sky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
