<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RITA-THEATER-REVIEW-N     05-18 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RITA-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHEN THEY SPEAK OF RITA': AN INSULAR FAMILY CONFRONTS AN INCIPIENT
REVOLT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Potter family of Tremont, N.H., is awfully behind
the times. Asa, the father, is the county road agent, vigilant in
his neighborly functions of snow removal and the occasional
emergency rescue but inept as a politician and unable to use a
computer. His 19-year-old son, Warren, is a crack mechanic but he
cannot face the fact that his girlfriend, Jeannie, a promising
student, is going off to college in the fall. Rita, mother and
wife, is the kind of homemaker who keeps the coffee pot on and
instinctively salves every setback with fresh-baked cookies.
</P>
<P>
   In Daisy Foote's flawed but affecting new play, ``When They
Speak of Rita,'' which opened Wednesday night at Primary Stages,
trouble, of course, is a-brewing along with the coffee. The outside
world, a place where other people have money and travel and do
things without the circumscription that holds the Potters in place,
is both threatening and alluring, and the main conflict for all the
characters here is the devil you know versus the devil you don't.
</P>
<P>
   This may be an old story for most people but the Potters have
managed not to confront it until now, and their individual
resolutions of how to proceed as Tremont is yanked along at the
tail end of progress make effective kitchen drama. Rita (the
playwright's older sister, Hallie), who earns money cleaning houses
for newly arrived, wealthy city folks, dreams of being a caterer _
or anything but what she is. Reading in the newspaper about
accomplished Frisbee players, she marvels sadly, ``There are so
many things in this world that a person can be good at.'' Isolated
in their small town, and sealed off from one another in their
Yankee stoicism, the Potters are unprepared for Rita's desperately
impetuous revolt.
</P>
<P>
   In nine scenes stretching over 10 eventful months, Warren (Jamie
Bennett) starts his own garage and impregnates and marries Jeannie
(Margot White), who gives up college; Asa (Ken Marks) loses his job
in an election to an interloping newcomer and, not incidentally,
Rita runs off with her son's best friend, a sweet-tempered boy
named Jimmy (Ebon Moss-Bachrach) whose own parents are violently
unhappy and who has long sought solace in Rita's kitchen, a
modestly homey place (a perfect-pitch design by Jeff Cowie) where,
he tells her, she is ``a bright, shining star.''
</P>
<P>
   This central event is obviously crucial to the advancement of
the narrative but it is also the play's chief problem, at least as
Foote has written it here. All the characters are skillfully drawn
as long as they are expressing themselves obliquely and mundanely.
Asa, who is devastated when his wife leaves, cannot muster any
greater expression of affection when she returns than to say, ``I
missed your cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the heartbreaking norm, and the play is persuasive in
evoking an environment where such emotional strictures are
inviolable. But when Foote has them speak their hearts, as in a
scene in which Jimmy pours out his love for Rita and she responds,
the writing seems clumsily estranged from the rest of the script,
and the actors cannot help but be similarly so from their
characters. Their coming together is abrupt _ an explosion of
feeling that has been contortedly restrained _ but Foote has not
solved, in language, the credibility problem. You don't believe
Jimmy or Rita is capable of such things.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is much here that makes suspending disbelief
worthwhile, and much of that has to do with this being a family
play in more ways than one. Daisy Foote is the younger daughter of
Horton Foote, a proven master, as a playwright and screenwriter, of
small-town family implosions, and he has directed this play with
the quiet confidence of someone who recognizes a story that can
tell itself. Foote has said in interviews that the play is derived
from an interval decades ago when her father, who grew up in rural
Texas, the setting for many of his own works, moved the family to
New Hampshire, and his sense of the internal pressure building
inside a home translates northward seamlessly. The directorial
touches _ a door's timely slamming to punctuate the end of a
conversation, a motor running in the garage _ are infrequent and
beautifully orchestrated, giving the silence that surrounds the
dialogue in the Potter kitchen a powerful and subtle resonance.
</P>
<P>
   Foote has cast the play with care and skill, beginning with
Hallie Foote, his daughter and a frequent leading lady in his own
plays. As Rita, she is the image of rectitude fighting off
tremulousness. In the end, appalled by her own rashness and her
yearning still inarticulable, she is defined not by her
circumstances but by the fullness of her depressed character. Her
apology to Asa _ ``I'm sorry about everything, about everything
that's happened, about everything that I've done; I'm very, very
sorry'' _ is a brutal acknowledgment of defeat. Rita's nadir is the
high point of a skilled performance.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensemble around her, everyone is convincing, from Marks,
who allows Asa's undemonstrative presumption to unravel subtly into
helplessness, to White, who turns a teen-age girl into an earnestly
self-assured mediator, the family's best hope for emotional
guidance. Bennett, as Warren, the most competent and closed-minded
Potter, and Moss-Bachrach, a lanky young actor with a spectacularly
unruly haircut, who gives Jimmy the sincere and gentle charm of a
foolishly misguided boy growing up too fast, make their torn-apart
friendship a genuine loss. You end up caring about these people _
and the playwright _ even when they lapse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WHEN THEY SPEAK OF RITA'
</P>
<P>
   By Daisy B. Foote; directed by Horton Foote; sets by Jeff Cowie;
costumes by Debra Stein; lighting by Deborah Constantine; original
music and sound design by Fabian Obispo; production manager, Kai
Brothers; stage manager, Tina M. Newhauser; associate producer,
Seth Gordon; managing director, Margaret Chandler. Presented by
Primary Stages, Casey Childs, artistic director; and Herrick
Theater Foundation in Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Hallie Foote (Rita), Ken Marks (Asa), Jamie Bennett
(Warren), Ebon Moss-Bachrach (Jimmy) and Margot White (Jeannie).
</P>
</TEXT>
