<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9161 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-CABINET-$ADV2     05-18 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CABINET-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON HAS THE MOST STABLE CABINET IN 20TH CENTURY  
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, May 21)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton's hard-charging, scandal scarred
presidency has undergone endless staff turnover at the White House
but the two-term chief executive enjoys the most stable Cabinet of
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Four Cabinet officers are on their way to serving the full eight
years of his presidency _ a record in presidential history.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Clinton turns over the presidency to his successor
at inauguration ceremonies in January, the 27 men and women who
have led the 14 Cabinet departments at various times during his
presidency will have put in an average of 48 months on the job _
assuming no further Cabinet changes.
</P>
<P>
   Their job longevity far exceeds the record of recent
administrations.
</P>
<P>
   _ George Bush's Cabinet members averaged 31 months over four
years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ronald Reagan's Cabinet members averaged 38 months over eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jimmy Carter's Cabinet members averaged 28 months over four
years.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Richard Nixon-Gerald Ford Cabinet averaged 27 months over
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   _ The John F. Kennedy-Lyndon B. Johnson Cabinet averaged 37
months over eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars have to go back to the presidency of Woodrow Wilson
during the eight years straddling World War I to find a Cabinet
that comes close to the longevity of the Clinton team. The average
length of service of Wilson's Cabinet matches the 48 months
achieved by the Clinton Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton edges out Wilson in two other categories: the number of
Cabinet officers who served the full eight years and the median
length of service of Cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had a built-in advantage over Wilson in the number of
eight-year Cabinet officers because Clinton has 14 Cabinet posts
while Wilson only had nine.
</P>
<P>
   The length of service is in addition to the hallmark of
Clinton's Cabinet _ its diversity. Clinton has appointed more
women, blacks and Hispanics to his Cabinet than any president in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 27 men and women who have held Cabinet posts, 14 have
been white men, five have been black men, three have been white
women, two have been black women and three have been Hispanic men.
</P>
<P>
   Charles O. Jones, a retired political scientist at the
University of Wisconsin and a former president of the American
Political Science Association, says the stability of Clinton's
Cabinet stands in sharp contrast to staff turnover at the White
House where there have been six White House counsels, four chiefs
of staff and four press secretaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be surprising but Clinton's Cabinet has the greatest
longevity of any president in the last century,'' says Jones, who
compiled the comparative study. ``Clinton has achieved this
milestone despite impeachment and despite the scandals that have
afflicted his presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt,
Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala and Education
Secretary Richard Riley will have served eight years in their
posts, a record for any eight-year administration in the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Only three Cabinet officers served for eight years under Wilson,
Franklin D. Roosevelt and the combined eight-year term of John F.
Kennedy and Lyndon B. Johnson. Dwight D. Eisenhower had two Cabinet
officers serve for eight years; Ronald Reagan had one _ Housing and
Urban Development Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Cabinet's longevity came despite the onslaught of
investigations by court-appointed special prosecutors who looked
into the activities of five Cabinet officers over the last eight
years. The inquiries cleared three and indicted two _ yielding a
guilty plea by former Housing and Urban Development Secretary Henry
Cisneros and an acquittal for former Agriculture Secretary Mike
Espy.
</P>
<P>
   Jones says that Clinton achieved such unprecedented stability by
selecting executives who wanted the assignments to achieve specific
goals rather than as stepping-stones to higher posts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's keen interest in policy also boosted job satisfaction
for many Cabinet officers, encouraging them to stay on rather than
returning to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the fun of doing these jobs is seeing something happen
in your area of expertise,'' said Jones. ``It's satisfying for
these people to take proposals to the president and have him say,
`Yeah, I like that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reno sounded rhapsodic on May 13 when she described her job
satisfaction during her commencement address at Duke University
School of Law. Her 37-year career as a lawyer, she said, was capped
by her service as attorney general, a stint that ``has brought joy
and challenge and fascination to my life in dimensions and
intensity that I never dreamed was possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Rockman, a political scientist at the University of
Pittsburgh, said job satisfaction in the Clinton Cabinet was
probably heightened by the very scandals that engulfed the White
House. Those recurring problems distracted nettlesome White House
staffers, thus enabling Cabinet officers to operate independently
to develop and implement administration initiatives without White
House interference, Rockman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone back to the pre-Nixon era when Cabinet officers
were free to be the major formulators of policy in their areas of
responsibility,'' he said. ``The crises for this administration
have centered on the president, the vice president and the White
House, leaving Cabinet officers free to carry out their
initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior aides to several of veteran Cabinet officers agreed that
the White House staff's constant damage-control operations freed
the hands of Cabinet officers.
</P>
<P>
   A senior aide to Shalala said the health and human services
secretary has exercised wide leeway in her dealings with the White
House in the aftermath of the impeachment crisis because ``the
White House needed her in a way that they wouldn't have needed
her'' before the impeachment fight.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars and political appointees at the Cabinet departments
agree that Cabinet officers often become more effective the longer
they serve in their posts. Cabinet officers gradually expand their
impact beyond testifying on Capitol Hill and dealing with interest
groups affected by their department's policies to build personal
relationships with congressional leaders, seize control of the
career civil service and establish personal ties with key state
officials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
