<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-VICE-PRESIDENT     05-18 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-VICE-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN'S VICE PRESIDENT-ELECT IS WILLING TO SPEAK HER MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Annette Lu says Taiwan is an ``independent
sovereign state.'' She thinks President Clinton ought to invite the
leaders of Taiwan and China to hash out their differences at the
White House. And when asked whether there are two Chinas _ a
proposition that outrages Beijing and sends most officials here
into semantic contortions _ she does not miss a beat: ``I would say
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that the new government of the president-elect,
Chen Shui-bian, seems eager to silence its outspoken vice
president-elect?
</P>
<P>
   In an interview here on Monday, Lu, 56, offered opinions on
everything from relations between Taiwan and China to relations
between men and women. She was unrepentant about having described
the two countries in a previous interview as ``distant relatives
and close neighbors.'' That phrase drew a toxic reaction from
Beijing, which denounced Lu as a ``scum,'' bent on promoting
Taiwan's independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not do anything wrong, I did not say anything wrong,''
said Lu in a gentle voice by turns somber and playful. ``For China,
being such a big nation, to choose a woman to be the target. All of
a sudden, I became famous. I don't deserve that much.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Lu will be sworn in as Taiwan's first female vice
president. She is half of the team that swept the Nationalist Party
from power after more than a half century of rule. And by her own
reckoning, she is the first woman to be elected to a leadership
position in 5,000 years of Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
   With so much history hanging over her, Lu's description of her
career has all the elements of an epic narrative. A native
Taiwanese and feminist leader, she was once thrown in jail for 5
1/2 years by the Nationalist government, after being charged with
advocating Taiwan's independence. Now, on the eve of her
inauguration, she is being tarred by the Chinese leaders on the
very same issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've accused me of what the KMT accused me of 20 years
ago,'' said Lu, using the initials for the Nationalist Party's
Chinese name, Kuomintang. ``Twenty years later, the same party who
suppressed me is ready to have its regime transferred to me on
behalf of the freedom fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the new administration are quick to note that
power is being transferred to President-elect Chen, a careful
politician who has labored since the election in March to soothe
China's leaders on the question of Taiwan's independence. Although
Chen's party, the Democratic Progressive Party, formally calls for
independence, he says it is an unnecessary step.
</P>
<P>
   Since his election, Chen has proposed to lift limits on
Taiwanese investment in China and to discuss direct trade links
with the mainland. He has also steered clear of pronouncements on
the role of the United States in the standoff between the
countries. Lu's oft-repeated suggestion that Washington act as a
mediator has rankled senior officials in the new government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our forthcoming vice president spoke her mind again on this
issue,'' said the foreign minister-designate, Tien Hung-mao, in an
interview. ``The fact of the matter is, this is not official
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other people are harsher. ``She's a loose cannon,'' said Andrew
Yang, head of the Chinese Council of Advanced Policy Studies, a
research institute. ``She doesn't share the same political beliefs
as Chen Shui-bian. She sees herself as the guardian of the
Taiwanese independence movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for officials like Tien is that Lu regards foreign
affairs as her area of expertise. A lawyer with degrees from the
University of Illinois and Harvard, Lu has led Taiwan's
unsuccessful battle to be readmitted to the United Nations. Her
resume lists visits over the years to South Africa, Nicaragua,
Ireland and the Netherlands as prominently as her five election
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the campaign, people expected me to be
active in foreign affairs and mainland affairs,'' she said. ``It
all depends on where President Chen would like me to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Shiow-Jen Chang, a woman in Parliament who knows Lu, remembers
the energy and imagination that she brought to Taiwan's quixotic
effort to re-enter the United Nations. In 1997, Lu arranged for a
blimp with a flashing sign to fly over the U.N. building, while a
boat carrying another sign floated past on the East River and a
pro-Taiwanese crowd paraded on the street outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year she proposed a different way to enter the U.N.,''
Chang said. ``She doesn't care how people will react. She says and
does exactly what she believes.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, Lu has been the county magistrate of Taoyuan, an
industrialized area south of Taipei. Although she twice won the job
handily , Lu was unable to deliver Taoyuan for Chen. Political
analysts said Lu also did not help win women's votes for Chen. Her
only value, they said, was to shore up the pro-independence faction
of the Democratic Progressive Party, which views Chen with
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Chen's senior advisers are moving to marginalize Lu
even before she is sworn in. During Lu's interview on Monday, no
aides were present _ an odd practice for the future No. 2 official
of a country. And she said she would not be involved in the
drafting of Chen's inauguration speech because it will be subjected
to such intense scrutiny in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the PRC authorities to understand that it is useless to
target me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rumors that she was being frozen out, Lu said they
were planted by people, here and in mainland China, who want to
drive a wedge between her and Chen. The rise of an outspoken woman,
she said, was bound to ruffle feathers on both sides of the strait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the internal circle of power, they are not ready yet,''
Lu said with smile of someone who has been there before. ``But they
are getting ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
