<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      05-18 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCREET CHARM OF BUNUEL; BUILDING AN INCUBATOR; IN KEATON'S
FOOTSTEPS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ore.)  By DAVE KEHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Serge Silberman celebrated his 83rd birthday on May 1
by flying from his home in Paris to New York, where the next day he
attended a screening of ``The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie,''
the Oscar-winning 1972 film he produced for his friend and longtime
associate Luis Bunuel.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, May 1 was also the date in 1945 when U.S. troops
liberated the Nazi camp at Ludwigslust, Germany, where Silberman
had been transferred after surviving Birkenau (where his parents
died) and Auschwitz. ``I have had a horrible life and a wonderful
life,'' he said in his suite at the Carlyle, speaking in an English
colored by a complex assortment of European accents. ``It was like
being born again on my birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in France after the war, he abandoned his training as a
mining engineer and entered the movie business. By 1953 he had
become a producer; his subsequent credits include Jean-Pierre
Melville's ``Bob le Flambeur'' (1955), Jean-Jacques Beineix's
``Diva'' (1981) and Akira Kurosawa's ``Ran'' (1985).
</P>
<P>
   But it is Bunuel, the Spanish-born surrealist who died in 1983,
who remains the closest of his associates. ``He was older than I
was, but he was like a son to me,'' Silberman said, describing the
protective relationship that allowed Bunuel to realize five of his
best films: ``Diary of a Chambermaid'' (1964), ``The Milky Way''
(1969), ``The Phantom of Liberty'' (1974) and ``That Obscure Object
of Desire'' (1977), which will all be rereleased in coming months,
and ``Discreet Charm,'' which is playing at Lincoln Plaza Cinemas
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so generous, so nice, a truly beautiful human being,''
said Silberman of the man whose most famous image, from the 1929
``Andalusian Dog,'' graphically depicts a straight razor slicing an
eyeball. ``He was one way in life and another way up here,''
Silberman added, tapping his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the anarchic energy of his films, Bunuel led an
orderly life and made his movies the same way. ``He gave me the
scripts like a child turning in his homework, as if he were afraid
of what I was going to say,'' Silberman said. ``He would only shoot
exactly what was in the script. He was absolutely prepared. With me
he made everything in about 48 days. It took him one week to edit.
And when the first cut was done, the picture was finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Building an Incubator
</P>
<P>
   Another approach to producing is being developed at Madstone
Films on lower Fifth Avenue. The company's founders _ Tom
Gruenberg, a 25-year veteran of the film industry, and Chip Seelig,
a partner in Goldman Sachs _ say they hope to reinvent the entire
process. ``The idea we came up with,'' Seelig said, ``was to take
first-time directors, most likely young, and try to put them in a
very supportive, nurturing environment and see what comes out of
that process.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result 15 novice filmmakers will be put under two-year
contracts with annual salaries of $50,000, a benefits package and a
retirement plan. The resident filmmakers are expected to act as
creative catalysts for one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go back to the halcyon days of the '70s, with Spielberg
and Lucas and Coppola and Scorsese,'' Gruenberg said. ``They would
sit and talk about film for 10 or 12 hours a day. We felt that if
we could harness creative filmmakers and put them into an
environment where they could work and talk, and take away the
financial problems, we could raise the bar creatively.''
</P>
<P>
   To encourage group consultation, Madstone is offering a
financial incentive. ``In the two years you are working at
Madstone, you have a percentage of every film that we make,'' said
Seelig, so that at the end of the process the filmmakers will all
be sharing in one another's success.
</P>
<P>
   The company's new offices, at 85 Fifth Avenue, are being
designed to foster cooperation. ``We're trying to set
architecturally a very collaborative environment,'' said Eva
Kolodner, an independent producer (``Boys Don't Cry'') who has been
brought aboard as head of feature development and production. ``The
idea is that I can go write my script by myself, but at the end of
the afternoon I can sit down and sigh: `I'm having trouble with
this dialogue. Does anybody have any thoughts?'''
</P>
<P>
   Central to the concept is the relatively inexpensive digital
video equipment that has recently been developed. ``It's a digital
operation from start to finish,'' Gruenberg emphasized. ``We're
going to shoot digitally, and retrofit 50 theaters across the
country, and fill those theaters with digital content that we make
or acquire.''
</P>
<P>
   Madstone's business plan calls for films budgeted at $500,000 to
$1.5 million, a typical range for independent features.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask us, `Why digital?''' Kolodner said. ``You could
make a 35-millimeter feature for that budget. But it's a new art
form.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``People have a kind of flexibility in digital
that doesn't exist anymore in 35-millimeter, where you are
constrained by your budget. With digital you can shoot more, you
can take more chances, you can push the boundaries a little bit
more.''
</P>
<P>
   And where are these bright young talents to be found? ``Our
first kind of outreach is to film schools and film festivals,''
Kolodner said. ``But if people want to come to us, the real place
to go is our Web site, www.madstonefilms.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not a dot-com,'' Seelig said, with the emphasis of a
newly wary Wall Streeter. ``We just happen to have an Internet
address.''
</P>
<P>
   In Keaton's Footsteps
</P>
<P>
   An original piece of film scholarship has just been published by
The Santa Monica Press. In ``Silent Echoes: Discovering Early
Hollywood Through the Films of Buster Keaton,'' the author, John
Bergstrom, has gone over the major Keaton shorts and features with
a magnifying glass, identifying the original locations through the
tiniest of clues and presenting side-by-side-by-side comparisons of
how the various buildings, intersections, alleyways and landscapes
appear on film, in period photographs and today.
</P>
<P>
   The results are a sort of Proustian collage of time and memory,
biography and history, urban growth and artistic expression.
Bergstrom has traced almost every step of the celebrated chase in
``Cops'' (1922) through downtown Los Angeles. And he identifies the
locations Keaton used during the Manhattan production of ``The
Cameraman'' (1928). He also gives precise directions to the site in
Culp Creek Canyon in Oregon, where in 1927 Keaton staged the train
wreck in ``The General,'' though Bergstrom warns, ``The brambles
are sharp, the rocks are slippery, and the hike requires passing
along private property.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
