<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, May 19 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ In a victory for the Clinton
administration, the Senate on Thursday narrowly killed a measure to
set a deadline for withdrawing American ground troops from Kosovo,
a proposal that also had drawn fire from Gov. George W. Bush. By a
53-47 vote, senators stripped a provision from a military
construction spending bill that would have cut off funds for the
5,600 U.S. forces in Kosovo by July 1, 2001, forcing their orderly
withdrawal unless Congress authorized the mission's extension. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KIMES-TRIAL (New York) _ Sante and Kenneth Kimes, an accused
mother-and-son team of con artists, were found guilty Thursday of
murdering a wealthy Manhattan widow as part of an elaborate scheme
to seize control her $8 million townhouse. Relying entirely on
circumstantial evidence, prosecutors convinced the jurors that the
Kimeses killed Irene Silverman, 82, in April 1998 and disposed of
her body. Silverman's body has never been found, and defense
lawyers for the Kimeses insisted that their clients were scapegoats
in a vast conspiracy. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ELECT (Bogota) _ Developments in the wake of calls by OAS
monitors for a postponement of the May 28 runoff between President
Alberto Fujimori and challenger Alejandro Toledo. (Summary from
wires) By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE (Dateline to kum) _ In a scathing report, the
Interior Department said the fire that destroyed more than 200
homes in Los Alamos was caused by numerous failures by Park Service
officials who started a fire to destroy underbrush. The officials
failed to properly plan for the fire, check weather and ground
conditions or coordinate and communicate with each other, Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt said in releasing the report Thursday. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   TIPPER-GORE (Washington) _ More than a decade after she became
the very public face of parental outrage over the content of rock
lyrics, Tipper Gore is struggling with how much of a public face
she should be in the presidential campaign of her husband. In some
ways she seems to want to be the anti-Hillary, standing back in the
crowd as other women led the Million Moms March last weekend, or
avoiding altogether important campaign events of her husband. By
Katharine Q. Seeley.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT3,11.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-PREAKNESS-SEKIGUCHI (Baltimore) _ On Fusao Sekiguchi, the
flamboyant Japanese entrepreneur who only two weeks ago was a
stranger to the American sporting scene but who prompted
fascination at the Kentucky Derby with his long ponytail and
splashy entrance _ accompanied by four incandescently powdered
geishas _ to the winner's circle at Churchill Downs. By Joe Drape
and Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-MURDER (Emneth Hungate, England) _ Tony Martin, 55, was
a farmer with an obsessive fear of intruders who lived alone in a
debris-strewn farmhouse called Bleak House. Fred Barras was a
teen-ager with a long criminal record who lived 70 miles away. Last
August, it took only a moment for Barras, 16, to break into Bleak
House, and only a moment for Martin to shoot him. Barras bled to
death. And in April, it took a jury just nine and a half hours to
convict Martin of murder. But the case has set off an angry
national debate. Martin has become an unlikely hero to many Britons
who feel that the criminal justice system has gone too far in
penalizing victims rather than criminals. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
</TEXT>
