<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PELOSI-CHINA-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PELOSI FACES LOSS OF ANNUAL PLATFORM ON HUMAN RIGHTS IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, May 21)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the House approves permanent normal trading
status for China next week as expected, Rep. Nancy Pelosi will lose
her annual platform for highlighting Beijing's human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   For each of the last 10 years, Pelosi has led the charge in
Congress to pressure China to improve its human rights policies in
exchange for favorable U.S. trading privileges.
</P>
<P>
   She lost every one of those battles because Congress always
voted to renew China's U.S. trading status for another year.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she says, her efforts were not in vain because ``we
succeeded every year in putting the issue on the front burner.''
</P>
<P>
   If the House votes this week to grant Beijing permanent normal
trade relations (PNTR), it would put an end to the annual debate
over U.S.-China trade _ and it would blunt Pelosi's annual campaign
to focus attention on China's poor record on human rights,
environmental standards and trade accords. The Senate is expected
to quickly follow the House's expected approval.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, D-Calif., opposes permanency on the basis that it would
abolish any leverage that Congress has to pressure the Chinese
during the annual debate over 12-month renewals.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration says permanent trading benefits for
China would benefit American businesses. Republican voter counters
in the House say they have 150 GOP votes and pro-PNTR Democrats say
they are nearing 70 votes, putting the total close to the 218
needed for passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think neither side has the votes yet,'' Pelosi said last
week in an interview in her office. ``It will be a fight to the
finish.''
</P>
<P>
   She says some 30 House Democrats who voted in the past to renew
China's favorable trading status now oppose granting the permanent
normal trade relations (PNTR) to China.
</P>
<P>
   But she notes wryly that she is accustomed to being on the
losing side of the China human rights issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost every year, so it wouldn't be a shock'' to lose the
big vote for permanent normal trade relations, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jendrzejczyk, a human rights advocate with Human Rights
Watch, a nonprofit New York-based group, said Pelosi has earned ``a
great deal of respect for her commitment'' to human rights in
China. ``She has been one of the most outspoken and energetic
advocates.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 to 1994, Pelosi fought unsuccessfully to attach human
rights conditions to the annual renewal of China's trade benefits,
although she supported renewing the country's favorable trade
status.
</P>
<P>
   She broke with the administration in 1994 when President Clinton
decided to stop considering human rights issues as a condition for
renewing favorable trade relations with China. Since then she has
urged the total revocation of China's trade benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Pelosi has also sharply attacked China for
violating other trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strictly on the basis of trade, this is a bad deal,'' Pelosi
says, adding that China has often violated its trade pacts.
``There's no reason to think that China will comply now.''
</P>
<P>
   She says China has failed to keep promises to open its markets,
stop the piracy of intellectual property and end the export of
goods produced by prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   She also slams China for violating signed agreements on
proliferation of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi says she has lost the China human rights battle for the
past decade because ``we're up against some mighty forces.''
</P>
<P>
   She says China trade always wins over human rights issues on the
House floor because pro-China businesses and lobby groups hire
former Cabinet members to make the case to Congress. They ``weigh
in heavily on these issues when they speak. The public doesn't know
they are speaking as a hired hand of someone wanting to go into
business with the regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi says it's tough for her to win a lobbying battle against
the White House because the administration can win votes with
favors.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is doling out favors for votes,'' she says.
``The slogan of the day is `What do you want?'''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi admits her China human rights stance has forced her to go
against the wishes of many of her supporters in Silicon Valley. The
high-tech region near her San Francisco district is a fertile
source of campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said to them, it's hard for me to understand how any
industry that takes pride in the new, new thing, is resorting to
the old, old way of kowtowing to the Chinese regime.''
</P>
<P>
   She says her constituents in the Chinese-American community in
San Francisco have mixed opinions over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Pelosi says she feels strongly about human rights and won't
back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since I was young, I thought the best job in the world
would be to be the assistant secretary for human rights'' in the
State Department. She said she envisions that job would enable her
to ``be part of a policy that respects the dignity and worth of
every person.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, 60, said she first became concerned with human rights as
a teenager when she read the ``Diary of Anne Frank,'' a book about
a young girl who perished along with her family in the holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I first thought, how dare anyone do that to
anybody else? That was a jarring experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Another catalyst for her was the 1989 massacre of Chinese
students at Tiananmen Square, which she is reminded of daily by a
poster above her desk in her Capitol Hill office that is signed by
dozens of Chinese dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we ever won, it would have been wonderful,'' Pelosi says.
``But people always tell me `Money always wins, it's just a
question of how long you can keep the issue alive.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com
</P>
