<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9175 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-18 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HILLARY MOVES ON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is a measure of First Lady Hillary Clinton's
growing confidence as a candidate that she was willing to share the
stage with her husband as she became the official Democratic
nominee for U.S. Senate from New York this week.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her advisers had wanted him to stay away, fearing that
he would overshadow her. But those days are over, for good or ill.
</P>
<P>
   She is a star now in her own right with her own campaign, her
own public policies and her own identity. She even has her own
enemies, separate from his.
</P>
<P>
   Her ideological views closely track his, but they are not
identical. And as the campaign progresses, she will have to take
positions that resonate with New Yorkers rather than fit the
policies of a national administration.
</P>
<P>
   She has been properly mum during rival Republican New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's health and marital troubles. For once, a huge
political controversy has nothing to do with her or the rogue to
whom she is married. It's impossible for even the nutty paranoid
right to find some sort of Clinton conspiracy behind Giuliani's
problems. They are all his.
</P>
<P>
   There is some evidence that the novelty of a candidate who
doubles as first lady is beginning to pale as she is increasingly
being viewed simply as an ambitious female politician who wants to
be a U.S. senator. A recent New York poll shows that 37 percent of
voters surveyed have a favorable view of her, 35 percent dislike
her, 22 percent have mixed opinions and 6 percent haven't heard
enough to hold a view.
</P>
<P>
   It's not true, as conservatives have been claiming, that
everyone knows so much about her most voters have already made up
their minds to hate her. The campaign battle will be for the hearts
and minds of that conflicted and undecided middle.
</P>
<P>
   Poll analysts say the carpetbagger issue has shorter legs now
than it did originally. She recently completed a tour of every one
of the state's 62 counties and is demonstrating a good grasp of
local issues. It always seemed an exaggerated, transitory problem
anyway. Sophisticated New Yorkers readily embrace celebrities, no
matter their origin. And there's a gigantic precedent. Voters were
happy to overlook the fact that Democrat Robert Kennedy was a son
of Massachusetts and give him a U.S. Senate seat in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton's campaign got off to a rocky start with minor
boo-boos that raised questions about her inexperience. She has been
doing much better lately although she concedes that she has learned
the hard way that it was easier to be a candidate's spouse than it
is to be the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady told a congressional wives' luncheon here Tuesday
a few hours before she accepted the Democratic nomination in New
York that she now has a ``different perspective'' on the demands of
political life. She said she recalls with dismay all the times she
asked her husband, ``Why did you wear that?'' or told him, ``If
only you had said this or done that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could take it all back,'' she sighed with an impish
grin. Nobody asked her if now Bill Clinton generously returns the
favor by critiquing her performance on the stump as well as all
those snappy pantsuits she favors.
</P>
<P>
   The basic lesson, she said, is that the only way to cope is to
``be yourself'' although she added to laughter that being herself
means she is now ``a lot blonder than when I arrived in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid sounding Pollyannaish about a political spouse's
comparatively relaxed life _ we know that hers at least has not
been easy at all _ Hillary Clinton described her initiation on the
evening of her husband's 1992 election into the intense glare
focused on a president's mate.
</P>
<P>
   It was cold outside in Little Rock, she recalled, So she put on
thick black stockings with her outfit to keep warm while she
listened to his victory speech.
</P>
<P>
   She was shocked the next day to discover the stockings had
become a big issue. She found extensive journalistic commentary,
ranging from accusations of bad taste to what she described wryly
as ``a sinister view of what it all meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Her advice to the congressional wives: ``Develop a thick skin''
and don't take criticism too personally.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton doesn't have a good record of following her own
advice, being known for her relatively translucent sheathing. But
for the time being at least she is being disciplined in pursuit of
a goal she obviously wants very much.
</P>
<P>
   It is not she but Giuliani who has temper tantrums and
irresponsible outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens now in the Senate race, the outcome is likely
to be close. That's okay. No candidate should expect to have the
job handed over on a platter, whether the purpose is to prove a
first lady is qualified to run for elective office or the purpose
is to prevent her from extending the Clinton name in active public
life.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
