<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9182 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BKO-ASSAULT-HNS &LR;      05-18 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-ASSAULT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HIGH SCHOOL ATHLETE SAYS JAIL TIME INTRODUCED HIM TO GOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trims)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRENT ZWERNEMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Tony Limon is home, for now safe in the only
shelter the 18-year-old has known, quoting Scripture and petting
his puppy Daisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked the Lord to send me home,'' Limon said, his voice
cracking a bit. ``And I'm home.''
</P>
<P>
   Limon's hand, now gently scratching behind the ears of a
grateful Great Dane, doesn't seem to belong on the same thin arm as
the one that brutally bashed an opponent's face during a high
school basketball game in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Now out of prison, Limon is under house arrest while appealing
his five-year sentence for attacking Brent Holmes during a South
San-East Central game a year ago January.
</P>
<P>
   Limon, a Hispanic, will no longer discuss the racial jabs
reportedly traded between the teams before his assault on Holmes,
who is black, only saying they're now against everything he
believes.
</P>
<P>
   Limon dropped Holmes with a sucker punch so vicious that he
twisted and crashed face-down near the free throw line as blood
oozed on the court and his body squirmed in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take responsibility, and I have sinned against God,'' Limon
said of the attack. ``Because I had no right to hit anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Mark Luitjen sentenced Limon to five years in
prison in February.
</P>
<P>
   Because no one had ever served jail time for an assault that
took place during a game, national attention came to focus on San
Antonio, South San High School and its players and coach.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months into his sentence, Limon says a fellow inmate
at the Garza West Unit in Beeville approached him and demanded he
help beat up a black man.
</P>
<P>
   ``In prison, you have to make a stand, and prison is the most
racist place I've been,'' Limon said. ``You either sat at a black
table, a white table or a Hispanic table when you ate. I had to
make a stand to almost everybody there, because I saw a black
person as my brother _ as a creation of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Limon split three months between the Bexar County Jail in San
Antonio and the Beeville prison unit, and the experience behind
bars seems to have changed his life.
</P>
<P>
   He now wields Scripture like he once wielded a chopping elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jail was a theme park compared to prison,'' Limon said.
``Prison was hell, and I wouldn't wish it upon my worst enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't relax in prison, because you're never safe. You have
guys in there who are never going to see freedom again, and they
wouldn't waste two thoughts of killing someone over a bag of
chips.''
</P>
<P>
   Limon, clutching a tattered Bible brand new only three months
ago, believes the ordeal _ from the impulsive assault to his
imprisonment _ is all part of God's plan for his redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I figured, man, cut me some slack,'' Limon said of
Luitjen's surprisingly stiff sentence. ``Who gets five years for
elbowing a guy in a basketball game? Who else has ever gotten that?
</P>
<P>
   ``But I figure I've been chosen, because this has never
happened. The Lord said, `Tony, here's the Bible. Learn.'''
</P>
<P>
   The judge weighed Limon's prior arrest for a burglary a couple
of months before the assault _ for which he received probation _ at
the sentencing, dispelling the idea that only the assault on Holmes
landed him in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two weeks ago, Luitjen agreed to let Limon post bond
while his appeal is pending. But the judge imposed limits on the
release.
</P>
<P>
   The house arrest restricts Limon to staying between the
thresholds of his family's small three-bedroom home on San
Antonio's South Side, and an electronic monitoring device around
the ankle keeps track of his every movement.
</P>
<P>
   While Limon's mother, Olivia Ramey, draws comfort from her son's
new inclination for nonstop proselytizing, Limon also knows some
old friends may duck at his first hint of Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've been a leader all of my life, and in the past I've
led my friends to nightclubs and high school parties and things
like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm going to lead them to God.''
</P>
<P>
   South San basketball coach Gary Durbon, named in a lawsuit by
the Holmes family who contend that Durbon taught violent strategy
to his players, is skeptical of Limon's and his mother's sudden
embrace of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has, fantastic, because he needs it bad and she needs it
bad,'' Durbon said. ``But if they're just claiming this to get the
public's sympathy, then shame on 'em for blasphemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Limon said Durbon should study his Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blasphemy is saying God is not real,'' Limon said. ``Blasphemy
is cursing God. I say I believe in God. Is that cursing God?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to understand what we're saying before we say
it. As for Coach Durbon, I pray for him every night.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Limon knew little of the Bible before his sentencing. Now its
edges are frayed and pages are loose. ``I don't go anywhere without
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's no problem under the conditions of his house arrest, and
his confinement to home after three months of imprisonment is
heaven on Earth for Limon.
</P>
<P>
   Limon said his new faith protected him in prison. On the fourth
night in the county jail in February, Limon said he dropped to his
knees and quietly uttered this plea: ``Lord, I've sinned against
you and I'm sorry. I don't even know how to pray to you, and I
don't even know what I'm saying. I just know that I need help, and
I know that I've done wrong in my life. But I'm asking you to come
into my life. I open my heart to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Limon said the prayer changed him forever, and it armed him
spiritually for his transfer to the Beeville prison in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other prisoners thought my faith was fake at first,''
Limon said. ``They wanted me to fight, but I said I'm not going to
fight against a guy just because he's black. He's a creation of
God. I told them you do what you have to do, but my Lord says he
will contend with those who contend with me. And Isaiah 54:17 says
no weapon raised against you shall prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Limon has big bills to pay, starting with several thousand
dollars in medical expenses he owes Holmes and thousands more in
attorney fees. The appeals process that could take up to a year
could lead to a resumption of the sentence, a trial by jury or
probation.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Limon wanders the hallways of his home, reading and
preaching the Bible to friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope at some point the judge will allow Tony to go out and
get a job, and maybe enroll in some college courses,'' his lawyer,
Carlos Uresti, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``More importantly, I know Tony wants to go to church. I think
the judge wants to make sure everything gets settled and Tony gets
all his affairs in order, and then at some point he'll allow him to
go to church and school and work.''
</P>
<P>
   Limon was released last week after his attorneys filed the
appeal and the motion for the $30,000 bond, which allows Limon to
remain free while his appeal is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Limon said his plans, no matter how the appeal turns out, will
center on ``serving the word of the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Lord wants me to dig ditches, I'm going to dig ditches
in the name of the Lord. If he wants me to go to college, I'm going
to come home and do my homework in the name of the Lord.
</P>
<P>
   ``God was calling me for a long time, and I ignored him. I'd
been going against the will of God all of my life. I pursued
worldly stuff and material things, but now I have my Bible in hand
and I think, man, I'm blessed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
