<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9185 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-POPLIFE-1stLEDE-WRITE     05-18 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPLIFE-1stLEDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER-IN-LAW OF ALL VISITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: Repeating to insert clarifying references to Mrs. K-Doe
in grafs 14, 15, 18, 19, 20) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ This is a city where anything can happen: a jazz
parade might suddenly strike up a march in a quiet residential
neighborhood at 1 a.m., or in the middle of the afternoon a tourist
restaurant could be invaded by masked gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   For six years Ernie K-Doe's Mother-in-Law Lounge, a corner bar
opened by this '60s rhythm-and-blues singer, has been a perfect
embodiment of New Orleans unpredictability: every visit to K-Doe's
shrine to himself is an adventure. But nothing in my experience
interviewing musicians or spending time at the Mother-in-Law Lounge
could have prepared me for what happened there this month.
</P>
<P>
   In the history books the 64-year-old K-Doe, whose original name
was Ernest Kador Jr., is known for recording the No. 1 hit
``Mother-in-Law'' followed by several regional successes. But to
the denizens of New Orleans today he is a bona fide character,
brimming with unpredictable energy and an unharnessed ego that has
led him to nickname himself the Emperor of the Universe. He is a
golden oldie who has lifted himself off the skids with the support
of a new wife, the opening of an off-the-beaten-track bar and
tireless dedication to the musical temple that is himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't but two of us left,'' he said one night behind the bar
at the Mother-in-Law Lounge. ``James Brown and K-Doe.''
</P>
<P>
   In his performance at the New Orleans Jazz and Heritage
Festival, which ran from April 28 to May 7, K-Doe strung his old
hits together in a set that ran 20 minutes shorter than the time
allotted to it. Wearing a canary yellow suit with rhinestones and
stitched music notes, a feathered yellow crown and a flowing yellow
cape with the words ``Emperor Ernie K-Doe'' emblazoned on the back,
he announced songs with lines like, ``Here's another million-seller
by Ernie K-Doe: I never miss.'' His voice was rough, ragged and
tended to flatten out, but he nonetheless put on a blaring, madcap
R-and-B performance that held the audience gleefully rapt.
</P>
<P>
   And the performance didn't stop at Jazz Fest. He and his wife,
Antoinette (who is also his seamstress, backup singer and manager),
made sure that the music continued each night at the Mother-in-Law
Lounge. On a typical night there K-Doe stays behind the bar. In the
front of the room there is a jukebox filled with Ernie K-Doe
recordings from the '50s on. When a patron plays one of K-Doe's
songs, the legend himself will usually pick an old brown taxicab
microphone off the back counter and sing along.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will he karaoke, but he will also talk to his own voice
on the CD, making comments like, ``Tell 'em, K-Doe,'' or ``I'm
cocky, but I'm good.'' Occasionally, in a small room in the back,
K-Doe's flesh-and-blood mother-in-law can be seen watching
television, oblivious to the havoc in the bar.
</P>
<P>
   For the nights of Jazz Fest, K-Doe brought in a dapper-looking
lounge performer named Rico Watts, who plays at the bar on Sundays,
to accompany him on synthesizer and drum machine. It was on one of
those nights that a photographer and I visited to prepare this
column about K-Doe, who sat at the bar running his long, ladylike
fingernails through his suspiciously elaborate long black hair. We
requested permission for an interview and photographs, and he and
his wife were only too glad to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   While on break between sets, we walked out to K-Doe's touring
van, with his name emblazoned on the side surrounded by stars, and
talked. He spoke of wanting to let the record labels know that he
was actually free and looking for a deal, and then proceeded to
recite several of his favorite immodesties, including his assertion
that ``there are only three songs that will last until the end of
the earth.'' Those songs are: ``Amazing Grace,'' ``The
Star-Spangled Banner'' and ``Mother-in-Law.'' Because, he observed,
``there will always be mothers-in-law.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, we headed back into the bar to take photographs and
watch him perform his second set. During his last number, the
racial unity song ``Black Boy, White Boy,'' he stopped singing and
looked directly at me. ``I was good to you, wasn't I?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You sure were, K-Doe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then why are you trying to record my show?''
</P>
<P>
   I looked down at my lap: the recorder I had used to tape our
conversation was sitting there, though, of course, it hadn't been
turned on since the interview. Suddenly, the music stopped and Mrs.
K-Doe came roaring from behind the bar, demanding that the tape be
handed over. ``We aren't playing any more music until you give us
the tape,'' she shouted.
</P>
<P>
   I offered to let them hear the tape to prove that there was
nothing but interview on it. But Mrs. K-Doe wouldn't hear any of
it. And I wasn't going to relinquish the tape especially since it
included other interviews I had conducted in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock the door!'' she barked at a man who was either a
heavy-set regular or a security guard. ``Nobody's getting out of
here until he hands over the tape.''
</P>
<P>
   The standoff took an unexpected turn when Mrs. K-Doe called the
police. She screamed that they would force me to hand over the tape
as well as the film, because she had decided that she wanted the
film as well. As an R-and-B singer coming up in the '50s and '60s,
K-Doe was no doubt cheated out of his fair share from his music,
which may help explain why they thought I was trying to make a
bootleg of the show to sell for personal profit at some sort of
K-Doe black market swap meet.
</P>
<P>
   In addition the K-Does had been extremely exhausted and busy the
weeks of Jazz Fest, with Mrs. K-Doe staying up all night to make
costumes and cook for her husband's concerts, parties and
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour of surreal negotiations outside the club with two
police officers (which included a search of the photographer's bag
for more K-Doe bootleg tapes), Mrs. K-Doe calmed down, and no
arrests were made. ``I'm sorry this misunderstanding happened,'' I
told her and pointed out to her that the article I intended to
write would let more people know about K-Doe and their bar.
</P>
<P>
   She barked back: ``This man is a legend. He doesn't need any
publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he's going to get it anyway, and don't let this tale
discourage you from dropping in. Take it from someone who will
probably never be allowed to enter the Mother-In-Law Lounge again,
my visits to New Orleans won't be the same without it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
