<SLUG> BC-TV-FOX-SEASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCI-FI DRAMAS AND LAUGHS FOR FOX'S NEW SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Making the most sweeping changes of any broadcast
network, Fox announced a new prime-time lineup for the next
television season Thursday that introduces seven dramas and two
comedies.
</P>
<P>
   The roster is heavy with new science fiction entries, one of
which Fox hopes will emerge as the replacement for ``The X-Files,''
which is now scheduled for what is presumably its last year after
its settlement this week with its creator, Chris Carter, and its
star, David Duchovny.
</P>
<P>
   Duchovny, whose Mulder character will be abducted by aliens in
Sunday's season finale, agreed after long negotiations to return
for half of the episodes next season. As part of the deal, Fox
settled Duchovny's lawsuit against the company. He had charged that
he was deprived of potential profits on the sales of the show's
repeats.
</P>
<P>
   Duchovny's partner, played by Gillian Anderson, will spend the
first part of next season hunting for Mulder, and then in the last
11 episodes they will be reunited, after which they will wind down
to a finale for the characters _ if not the series _ next May.
</P>
<P>
   Fox hopes that by then one of its new dramas will be ready to
fill the 9 p.m. Sunday spot. Carter has one entry in the
sweepstakes, ``The Lone Gunmen,'' a spinoff of ``The X-Files''
featuring a strange threesome of computer hackers: Langley, Byers
and Frohike. That series is one of two that Fox is announcing as
part of its fall schedule, even though they won't begin until
January.
</P>
<P>
   The other is simply being called ``The Michael Crichton
Project,'' and the writer of ``Jurassic Park'' is still working on
the script, with no details available yet.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Crichton and Carter, Fox has lined up other well-known
producers for its new shows, including David E. Kelley, James
Cameron, Gregg Hale (the creator of the ``Blair Witch Project''),
Darren Star and Marcy Carsey and Tom Werner.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley's show ``Boston Public'' is about the faculty at a public
high school in suburban Boston, the area where both of his other
shows, ``Ally McBeal'' and ``The Practice,'' are set. Kelley is so
highly regarded that he secured the spot on Monday leading into
``Ally McBeal,'' even though he has not shot a pilot for the new
show, which is not even cast yet.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron, in his first effort since the phenomenally successful
``Titanic,'' has created a series called ``Dark Angel,'' a
futuristic thriller about a genetically enhanced teen-ager trying
to escape her military handlers in the Pacific Northwest in the
early 21st century. It stars Jessica Alba.
</P>
<P>
   Hale's ``Fearsum'' will be an overt attempt to scare the wits
out of viewers the way ``Blair Witch'' did. In this one, the
operator of an underground Web site discovers e-mail from his dead
brother and seeks to track him.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the sci-fi contenders has only a tangential
connection to a great producer. ``Night Visions'' clearly owes a
lot to the late Rod Serling in its effort to create a horror
anthology that recalls ``The Twilight Zone.'' The show promises
scary tales with bizarre twists.
</P>
<P>
   Star will not be competing with the terror entries, but his new
series, ``The Street,'' is intended to bring to mind his other hit,
HBO's ``Sex and the City.'' This is the male version, with a batch
of young turks from Wall Street on the prowl for money and women.
</P>
<P>
   The Carsey-Werner production company is behind Fox's
highest-profile new comedy, ``Don't Ask,'' in which John Goodman
returns to weekly television as Rex, a single father with
teen-agers who takes in the family of his irresponsible friend
David. What David doesn't know is that Rex is gay.
</P>
<P>
   The other new comedy is ``Schimmel,'' a vehicle for the stand-up
comedian David Schimmel, who plays a family man who cannot help
being startlingly abrasive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Fox schedule:
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY: ``Boston Public,'' ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY: ``That '70s Show,'' ``Titus,'' ``Dark Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY: ``Don't Ask,'' ``Schimmel,'' ``The Street.''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY: Movies (until January), ``The Lone Gunmen''; The
Michael Crichton Project.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY: ``Fearsum,'' ``Night Visions.''
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY: ``Cops,'' ``Cops'' (repeats), ``America's Most
Wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY: ``Futurama,'' ``King of the Hill,'' ``The Simpsons,''
``Malcolm in the Middle,'' ``The X-Files.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
