<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS-HEAT RIVALRY OUT FROM BEHIND RILEY SHADOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pat Riley is finally saying it out loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough's enough,'' he sighs. ``Twenty-two times. I'm tired of
looking at them. I really am.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night will make 23. In each of the last four years,
Riley's Miami Heat have faced Jeff Van Gundy's New York Knicks in
the Eastern Conference playoffs. They went seven (the maximum) in
1997. They went five (the maximum) in 1998. They went five (the
maximum) in 1999. They have now gone five in 2000, and if history
holds up its end of the bargain, the Knicks will win in Madison
Square Garden and we will all jet back to Miami for another
winner-take-all affair in the American Airlines Arena Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After 22 games, the tally is 11-11. What more do you need to
know? Only this: in those 22 games, the visiting team has won 10.
Venue doesn't mean very much when veteran teams are so evenly
matched.
</P>
<P>
   It is fashionable to label the Miami-New York games as eyesores.
If you're a fan of up-tempo, easy-on-the-eyes basketball, their
games are not for you. In all this time, a team has broken 100 only
once, and then not by much (Miami, 101-90 in Game 7, 1999). The
composite average score of the 22 games is 89-79. Fast breaks not
emanating from turnovers lead the 11:00 news.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes these games really are tough on the eyes. Teams go
long stretches without scoring. There is often a lot of grunting,
groaning, and growling, but very little finesse. We know that the
Lakers and Trail Blazers are watching all this with contempt. Shaq
is already on record as saying nobody in the East remotely matches
up with either one of the Western finalists, and most observers
agree.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains that one of these teams will soon be in the
Eastern Conference finals, and either has a very good chance of
taking out the Indiana-Philly survivor. The stakes are high, and
so, too, is the intensity level. For what we have here is nothing
less than the best legitimate old-time rivalry in professional
basketball, and perhaps in all of American professional sport.
</P>
<P>
   When it started three years ago, it was all about Pat Riley. The
New York fans framed it in terms of revenge against the coach who
had not only jilted the team, but who had classlessly done so by
fax. For all we know the Knick players and higher-ups likewise
approached the rivalry with Riley in mind.
</P>
<P>
   It did not take long for the rivalry to develop its own flavor.
The 1997 series featured the brawl, the disastrous suspensions
imposed on the New York players who left the bench and Miami taking
full advantage of the circumstance to overcome a 3-1 series
deficit. A year later the Knicks, down, 2-1, in a best-of-five, won
Game 4 in New York and Game 5 in Miami. Last year they slugged it
out in alternating fashion, with New York again prevailing in
Miami, this time on Allan Houston's Golden Bounce shot at the
buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   It's another year later, and not much has changed. They're still
alternating victories, and we still have the same story lines.
There are intriguing matchups (e.g. Latrell Sprewell-Jamal
Mashburn, Houston-Dan Majerle and, of course, Patrick Ewing-Alonzo
Mourning). There are major injury concerns on both sides. There is
nightly discussion of turnovers, offensive rebounds, and finding a
way to get to the line.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, the Riley factor overshadowed everything,
since both teams were perceived to be Riley creations. You don't
hear that so much anymore. People now know who Jeff Van Gundy is.
Sprewell and Marcus Camby have also been added to the mix. It's no
longer all about Riley.
</P>
<P>
   No, it happens to be about a growing mutual respect. The Knicks
and Heat have evolved into the Tony Zale-Rocky Graziano or Muhammad
Ali-Joe Frazier stage of their relationship. They now have a
tremendous shared history. The players may hate the other team as
an entity, but they no longer regard the individual players on the
opposing side as ogres. Each player knows that his compatriot on
the other side is a competitor. There isn't a player on either side
who has not bought into his coach's defensive phliosophy. These
guys are all too smart as athletes not to recognize what is going
on here. They all know that they are making NBA history now.
</P>
<P>
   We talk all the time about the lack of rivalries and the lack of
continuity in modern professional sport. So let's celebrate what we
have in the Knicks and Heat. They are engaged in an ongoing
relationship that now stacks up against the best of Boston and
Philly, Boston and LA, or the wonderfully spicy Boston-New York
rivalries of the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever this ends _ and doesn't logic call for a Game 7? _
expect to see a lot of hugging and hand-shaking and back-patting.
These players respect what each other stands for. It's all about
the true nobility of sports competition, whether the average final
score is 125-124 or 80-79. Pat Riley knows better than anybody. He
may be sick of looking at the Knicks, but he's not sick of the
competition. It is, in fact, what drives him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
