<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9200 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-LAURA-BOS &LR;      05-18 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LAURA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV STATION IN A BIND AFTER SELECTING `DR. LAURA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On one side are angry gay activists who insist that
radio talk-show host Laura Schlessinger, known as ``Dr. Laura,''
shouldn't be granted a TV platform to air views they see as
dangerous to gay people.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side are free-speech advocates who worry that there
may also be a danger _ of censorship _ in the efforts to block
Schlessinger's syndicated TV talk program.
</P>
<P>
   Caught squarely in the middle is WCVB-TV (Channel 5), which
didn't anticipate the controversy now engulfing it when the station
agreed to air Schlessinger's show this fall.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond Boston, there are growing signs of trouble for the
outspoken talk-show host. Procter &AMP; Gamble, one of the largest and
most powerful advertisers on television, decided this week to pull
its ads from her upcoming TV show. Then Thursday, United Airlines
announced it would drop ads for her radio show from its in-flight
magazine because of her remarks about homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Channel 5 got a flurry of phone calls Thursday, a slight
majority of them opposing Schlessinger, after the Globe reported
that Channel 5 is now uncertain whether it wants to air ``Dr.
Laura'' after all. No such uncertainty afflicts those who weighed
in Thursday in the dispute over Schlessinger, who has referred to
homosexuality as ``deviant'' behavior and a ``biological error''
for which ``reparative therapy'' is advisable.
</P>
<P>
   To Boston attorney and First Amendment specialist Andrew Good,
the issue is Channel 5's responsibility, as a federally licensed
broadcaster, to present ``a wide range of views, including
controversial views.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's protected speech,'' said Good. ``What (critics) are
saying is, `I don't want to hear it, and I don't want anyone else
to hear it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But to Steve Spurgeon of the Gay &AMP; Lesbian Alliance Against
Defamation, which is leading a national campaign to get TV stations
to drop the show, the issue is that her ``defamatory rhetoric''
creates the belief that gays ``can be dismissed as `errors.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has a First Amendment right to a television show,''
said Spurgeon. ``It's about the platform that she gets. I daresay
if you insert any other minority slur of your choice in the
references she makes to gays and lesbians, no one would be talking
about the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlessinger did not respond Thursday to a request for comment,
and officials of Paramount Television Group, the production company
behind ``Dr. Laura,'' could not be reached. In March, Schlessinger
said she was sorry that ``words that I have used in a clinical
context have been perceived as judgment.'' Paramount has previously
pledged to explore social issues on the show without ``contributing
to an environment of hurt, hate or intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth A. Cheng, Channel 5's director of programming, said
the station has still not decided among three options: not airing
Schlessinger's TV program, relegating it to a less prominent time
slot, or airing it in a high-profile morning slot as originally
intended.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng said the station believes that choosing not to carry the
program ``is an option that we have as a broadcaster.'' However,
the station does have a one-year deal with Paramount Television
Group, which could seek to enforce its contract with Channel 5.
Losing a station in Boston, the No. 6 TV market in the country,
would be a blow to the show.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the legal questions, Channel 5 is in an extremely awkward
position in terms of public relations. Known for its liberal
editorial positions, with a record of, in Cheng's words, ``being a
friend to the gay and lesbian community,'' the station now runs the
risk of antagonizing that community, along with other viewers who
may find Schlessinger's views offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But Schlessinger also has many fans, who would likely take a dim
view of Channel 5 if the station pulled the plug on her show. Cheng
noted that the show Paramount promised was one that focused on
family life. ``Do we agree with some of the things she is purported
to have said? No,'' said Cheng. ``But that's not what the show is
about. It's not about gays and lesbians.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheng acknowledged that ``it gives us pause'' to see Procter &AMP;
Gamble bailing out, but said viewer response will be the key
factor. ``We're very in tune, we're very concerned, we're going to
be very judicious in this,'' she said. ``We're keeping an eye on
it, and we're going to listen to our viewers.'' Cheng declined to
say how much Channel 5 will pay to run the program.
</P>
<P>
   Sentiment has run 2-1 against Schlessinger in the more than 100
calls, letters, and e-mails Channel 5 has gotten in the past two
weeks, according to Channel 5 spokeswoman Caroline Waddell.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey Montgomery, one of the organizers of a protest planned
for Wednesday at the Park Street MBTA station, said Channel 5's
reputation is on the line. ``For me, this isn't about Dr. Laura (as
much as) it's about the local community and Channel 5,'' said
Montgomery. ``When the `Chet and Natalie station' is showing `Dr.
Laura,' it adds a certain imprimatur.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Spurgeon, GLAAD has met with executives at seven of
the largest TV stations that plan to air the new show, and asked
them not to air it. Several have expressed ``concern'' about airing
the show, he said. The group is also slated to meet with
representatives of Channel 5.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some people have already formed an opinion on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just trash,'' said Wendy Kaminer, a fellow at the
Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study. ``It's the ravings of a
highly prejudiced woman. She's not a `doctor.' She's a pop
psychologist. And as far as I'm concerned, not a very responsible
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Arline Isaacson, cochair of the Massachusetts Gay &AMP; Lesbian
Political Caucus, argued that ``much of what (Schlessinger) says is
hate speech, whether she intends it that way or not.'' Isaacson
asked: ``Why in the world would a respectable television station
want to taint their reputation for respectable discussion by
providing a forum for egregious bigotry?''
</P>
<P>
   But others said foes are walking a slippery slope of censorship
in trying to deny Schlessinger a TV platform, and noted it might
pave the way for efforts by other groups to stifle shows whose
content they find objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Chieppo of the Pioneer Institute for Public Policy
Research, while saying he doesn't agree with Schlessinger's views
on gay issues, added: ``I don't think we want to be in a situation
where anyone who espouses views that are not popular in a
particular area, that those views are censored.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcry from gay organizations is the latest example of
advocacy groups weighing in to sway decisions on the nation's most
powerful medium. Last year, the NAACP blasted the major TV networks
for a lack of diversity in prime time, and won pledges of more
diverse casts, writers and producers. When ``Ellen'' star Ellen
DeGeneres took her character (and herself) out of the closet in
1997, ABC was denounced by Moral Majority leader Rev. Jerry Falwell
and other Protestant ministers.
</P>
<P>
   In general, television has become more receptive to gay themes
in the last couple of years. Programs like NBC's ``Will &AMP; Grace''
and the WB's ``Dawson's Creek'' feature gay characters in leading
roles, prompting relatively little outcry, especially compared to
the ``Ellen'' controversy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
