<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BOMBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEP TOWARD JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By 1963, the push for civil rights had turned parts of America
into a battlefield. From 1940 through the 1960s, more than 50
bombings shook the city of Birmingham, Ala., according to FBI
files. No one died until Sept. 15, 1963, when dynamite planted
under the 16th Street Baptist Church exploded, killing four black
girls _ Denise McNair, 11, Addie Mae Collins, 14, Carole Robertson,
14, and Cynthia Wesley, 14.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing's message seemed clear: There would be no peace. The
country might lean toward racial equality _ the March on Washington
had been only weeks before _ but some people were determined to
burn progress to the ground. The name Birmingham became a synonym
for tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1977 that Robert Chambliss was tried and
convicted of murder for the bombing deaths. Authorities believed
three other men were also involved, but couldn't make a convincing
case. One of them died in 1994. This week, authorities lifted the
case from history books, charging Thomas E. Blanton and Bobby Frank
Cherry with murder.
</P>
<P>
   This merciful step toward closure still dredges up old grief and
weariness. It is a grotesque failure of humanity when children end
up as casualties in a just campaign. It is painful but important to
tell today's children of this historic assault that happened less
than a lifetime ago.
</P>
<P>
   Months before the bombing, Martin Luther King warned that
violence could profoundly disrupt the country, making people
sacrifice the fight for equality in order to achieve ``the absence
of tension.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ``Letter from Birmingham Jail,'' dated April 16, 1963,
King wrote: ``I have almost reached the regrettable conclusion that
the Negro's great stumbling block in his stride toward freedom is
not the White Citizen's Counciler or the Ku Klux Klanner, but the
white moderate, who is more devoted to `order' than to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Decades later, it is still too soon to rest, to declare the work
of civil rights done. But these new arrests show a country bravely
struggling for order _ as long as it is based on justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
