<SLUG> BC-DEAF-MECHANIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAF MECHANIC DISPUTES UNITED'S DECISION TO GIVE HIM JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Being deaf hasn't kept John ``Skipper'' Sprague from
flying planes, riding motorcycles, or graduating from college. And
it didn't stop United Airlines from offering him a job as an
aircraft mechanic at Logan Airport.
</P>
<P>
   But after United's upper management in San Francisco learned a
deaf mechanic was being hired in Boston, the company quickly
withdrew its job offer -- insisting that it wasn't safe for Sprague
to be out on the tarmac at a busy airport.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Sprague, 38, an experienced aircraft mechanic who now
works for another airline, fought back, testifying in federal court
about the devastation of reaching his ultimate career goal, only to
be told he couldn't do the job because he was deaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just can't see from my own background experience what I'm
capable of doing,'' said Sprague, 38, of Grafton, using sign
language as an interpreter stood in the middle of the courtroom,
translating. ``I was on cloud nine when they offered me the job and
then totally crashed when they withdrew it. I feel like I need to
stand and fight for this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprague's wife, Susan, and his two daughters, Danielle, 10, and
Lauren, 8, who are also deaf, sat in the spectator section,
offering smiles of encouragement and following the testimony
through the interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague is suing United Airlines for discrimination under the
Americans with Disabilities Act. He is urging US District Judge
George A. O'Toole Jr., who is presiding over the non-jury trial, to
order United to give him the job at Logan.
</P>
<P>
   In an April 18, 1997 letter to Sprague that came just 10 days
after he had been offered the aircraft mechanic's job at Logan, a
United official rescinded the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``While a sincere effort was taken to make an accommodation on
your behalf, further reveiw by higher management determined this
could not be done related to safety issues,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, United gave Sprague a job as a shop mechanic in San
Francisco, working indoors on engine parts. After 15 months of
commuting home to his family every weekend, Sprague said he quit
when he realized the company would never give him a chance to work
at Logan. Today, he works as an aircraft mechanic for AirTran in
Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   When the trial began last week, attorney Douglas Dexter, who
represents United, told the judge that the company didn't believe
Sprague could communicate with the air traffic tower or with other
mechanics and pilots and feared his deafness could pose a serious
problem in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   But Sprague recounted how United officials seemed impressed by
his accomplishments during his job interviews. He earned a degree
in aircraft maintenance from Wentworth Institute in Boston, is
certified as an aircraft mechanic by the Federal Aviation
Administration, and worked on planes at the municipal airport in
East Taunton for 13 years before applying to United. He also has a
pilot's license.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague, who uses two digital hearing aids, said he can hear
aircraft noise. He communicates on the noisy tarmac through hand
gestures and with a pager that sends written messages within
seconds. He also uses the pager to send e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying earlier in the trial were two deaf aviation
mechanics, one who works on military aircraft in Jacksonville,
Florida, for the US Department of Defense, and the other who works
for Southwest Airlines in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Sprague's co-workers and former supervisors also took
the stand to attest to his reputation as an excellent mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Jane Alper, who represents Sprague, asked him, ``Is
there anything that other AirTran mechanics are able to do that you
are not able to do because of your hearing loss?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague said he met with Don Nielsen, a United official, in San
Francisco back in 1997 and urged him to reconsider hiring him at
Logan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke using my own voice,'' Sprague testified. ``I said, `If
I work with you one or two days, I will get to know you and you
will get to know me, and we will get to work together as a team.
Everything will go smoothly.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
