<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERESTING RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan faces complicated crosswinds as he and the
Federal Reserve raise interest rates to keep the economy from
overheating. Tuesday's half-percent increase in the federal funds
rate, to 6.5 percent, put it at a level not seen since 1991. Many
forecasters believe it is not the final hike, because it may not
have much impact on the exuberance that has troubled Greenspan for
so long. But other issues, domestic and international, will have to
play a role in Federal Reserve thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on Europe is high on the list. Rising interest rates
affect more than the willingness to borrow in private markets to
finance expansion. High interest rates make the dollar more
attractive in international currency exchange markets, and the
dollar's strength against the euro, Europe's new multinational
currency, is impressive. The euro, which was valued at about $1.18
when launched at the start of 1999, tumbled as low as 87 cents. A
brief rally from that figure ran into fresh trouble right after the
Federal Reserve's action.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's fall has perplexed observers. The European economy is
strong except for a high unemployment rate _ over 10 percent _ but
the social effect has been dampened by unemployment compensation
and other support programs. Inflation is low. Efficiency is
gradually improving. But the European Central Bank has been
reluctant to raise interest rates, still below 4 percent, to help
bolster the euro. This makes imports, more expensive for Europeans
_ complicating life for American exporters at a time when chronic
trade deficits are a worrying factor.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's policy has been an attempt to address problems like
inflation before they occur. At some point, higher rates will slow
down the American economy and impact others around the world as
well. The danger, especially with stock markets still at levels
that could spawn selling and disturb consumer and business
psychology, is that a downturn might be fairly sharp. Better to
ease up on the constraints before that occurs than after; it is
harder to restart an economy than to slow it down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9211 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-PEACE-BOS &LR;      05-18 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIMBLE CANCELS UNIONIST VOTE ON COALITION GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a setback to the Northern Ireland peace process that
was resurrected just two weeks ago, Ulster Unionist leader David
Trimble canceled Thursday plans to have his party vote Saturday on
returning to a power-sharing local government with Sinn Fein, the
IRA's political wing.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble said he needs more time to sell his skeptical followers
on the idea of rejoining the government in return for the Irish
Republican Army's promise on May 6 to allow its hidden arsenal to
be inspected by international observers.
</P>
<P>
   While the Irish and British governments sought to downplay the
significance of the postponement, it was a sharp blow to optimism
that had swept Northern Ireland after the IRA made its surprise
offer to let international arms inspectors verify that its secret
arms dumps are sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Britain had planned to restore the power-sharing government on
Monday. In February, over the objections of the Irish government,
Peter Mandelson, the British government's top official for Northern
Ireland, suspended the home rule assembly after just 72 days when
unionists vowed to walk out because the IRA had refused to turn in
any of its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Initially furious, Sinn Fein officials softened their stance
when they learned that Trimble had publicly backed accepting the
IRA's offer.
</P>
<P>
   Martin McGuinness, Sinn Fein's chief negotiator and a former IRA
chief of staff, said, ``I welcome this positive recommendation from
David Trimble, that he is prepared to go for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Ulster Unionist sources denied they were stalling in an
attempt to win more concessions, such as preventing changes to the
name and badge of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the overwhelmingly
Protestant police force that is to be fundamentally reformed under
the Good Friday Agreement of 1998 that grew out of the peace
process. The Unionists, who seek to keep Northern Ireland as part
of the United Kingdom, said Trimble is convinced the IRA's offer
marks a genuine confidence-building gesture, even though it falls
short of the unionist demand that the IRA hand over some weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble told Ulster Television that he had won unspecified
concessions from the British on police reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is only appropriate that we take time to speak to
the community, to speak to the party, and for people to have the
opportunity of making an informed decision,'' Trimble said. ``We
have now made a degree of progress, so I believe that we can meet
the concerns of those in the party and the community who want to
see a fair deal on policing.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as the IRA's refusal to turn in or destroy any of its
weapons is driven in large part by a desire to avoid a potentially
bloody split in the organization, Trimble is also at pains to avoid
splitting his party, the largest in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   There are deep divisions within the 850-member Ulster Unionist
Council, the party's decision-making body. Among that number is a
sizeable minority that has always been opposed to the Good Friday
Agreement, the compromise between pro-British unionists and
pro-Irish nationalists that is aimed at ending a 30-year conflict
that has killed some 3,500 and maimed tens of thousands more.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Trimble got the support of just 58 percent of the
council for his decision to form a power-sharing government that
included Sinn Fein before the IRA began disarming. Trimble sold the
compromise on the premise that, once two Sinn Fein members were
part of the government's 12-member cabinet, the IRA would begin
disarming, or at least declare uneqivocally that its war was over.
</P>
<P>
   But the IRA and Sinn Fein objected when Trimble unilaterally set
a Feb. 12 deadline for the IRA to disarm or or at least pledge to
begin. Trimble said the deadline it was the only way he could get
his council to back the compromise, and both sides dug in their
heels.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government had functioned smoothly and largely
without rancor for 72 days, Mandelson suspended it, saying the
action would make it easier to restore the power-sharing government
than if the unionists walked out and collapsed it.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble's vulnerability in his own party was underscored in late
March when just 57 percent of the party council voted for Trimble
in the face of a leadership challenge by a 68-year-old Presbyterian
minister, Martin Smyth, a vehement opponent of the Good Friday
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   While Irish nationalists of all stripes seem to accept that the
IRA can only go so far, they are less understanding of Trimble's
difficulties, and are especially critical of the British
government's efforts to shore up Trimble.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein, the moderate Social Democratic, and Labor Party and
the Irish government have all insisted this week that the British
government cannot unilaterally water down the proposed reform of
the Royal Ulster Constabulary as a sop to the unionists, even if
that sop was just to relent on changing the name or badge of the
force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
