<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9212 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-BUSHBILL-BO     05-18 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BUSHBILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN POLICY MISCHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Acting as the presumptive Republican presidential candidate,
George W. Bush properly chastized senators of his own party for
backing a provision in a military spending bill that would have set
a deadline of July 1, 2001, for withdrawal of US troops from
Kosovo. Fortunately, the amendment was defeated in a Senate vote
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On substance, the amendment was bad policy. In a lucid warning
about the folly of legislating what she called a ``premature''
withdrawal from Kosovo, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
cautioned Wednesday that senators supporting the measure were
``playing with fire.'' Albright was not indulging in hyperbole when
she said: ``In the Balkans, signs of impatience can be
misinterpreted as symptoms of weakness. We cannot afford that in a
region where weakness attracts vultures.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, with justification, also objected to the measure on the
grounds that it distorts the balance of executive and legislative
powers in a matter of foreign policy. A statement issued by the
Bush campaign said: ``Governor Bush views it as an executive
overreach on powers of the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Bush's intervention noteworthy is that it illuminates
the point at which a tussle over constitutional prerogatives
intersects with partisan politics. Many Republicans in Congress
have taken out their political enmity toward President Clinton by
seeking to thwart foreign and security policies of his
administration. Arms control treaties have been rejected, funds for
the United Nations withheld, and peacekeeping obligations
short-changed.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Kosovo deadline, the Senate is proposing to cut $1.7
billion in foreign spending, including a senseless reduction of
funds for destroying Russian nuclear warheads and a 35 percent cut
in a program to help provide North Korea with energy _ part of a
crucial deal to reward Pyongyang for halting its nuclear weapons
program.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should certainly defend its power of the purse. But
Bush has done the country a favor by reminding the Senate that a
delicate balance must be preserved between the White House and
Congress in foreign policy and that an excess of partisan mischief
can harm the national interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-TRADE-0519-CO     05-18 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRADE-0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON INTENSIFIES CAMPAIGN FOR CHINA TRADE BILL: 'WE'VE STILL
GOT A ... FIGHT'
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Locked in his biggest trade fight in seven years,
President Clinton on Thursday hauled out Washington's most
authoritative economic voice _ that of Fed chairman Alan Greenspan
_ to add gravitas to the White House push for strengthening
commercial ties with China.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's proposal facing a do-or-die vote next week in a
sharply divided U.S. House of Representatives, the president also
plans to appeal directly to the American people for support in a
televised address from the Oval Office Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton lobbied a handful of undeclared House members on the
issue Thursday after he signed into law two bills aimed at
strengthening U.S. trade ties with African and Caribbean nations.
He met privately with several members of the Congressional Black
Caucus _ where Clinton hopes to pick up four or five votes on the
China issue _ but the White House press office had no further
details on the meetings late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton remained hopeful, though, of persuading as many as a
dozen undeclared House Democrats to support his China initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Clinton wants Congress to approve so-called
permanent normal trade relations, or PNTR, for China. That would
end a 20-year practice by which Congress extends favorable trade
terms _ virtually unfettered access to the rich U.S. market _ to
China on a year-by-year basis.
</P>
<P>
   PNTR is seen by Clinton as an essential compliment to China's
agreement last November to reduce impediments to its fast-growing
market in exchange for membership _ as early as this fall _ in the
135-nation World Trade Organization, or WTO, the Geneva-based court
of global commerce.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of House members scheduled a press conference for
Friday morning to announce their support for PNTR. It is Clinton's
highest-stakes trade initiative since he won support from a
reluctant Congress for the North American Free Trade Agreement, or
NAFTA, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Although privately, some administration officials and their
congressional allies were optimistic about the vote, other
supporters remained publicly cautious, saying they still lack the
218 affirmative votes needed for House passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Momentum is building,'' for PNTR, Clinton said, ``but we've
still got a challenging fight.''
</P>
<P>
   To help press his case, Clinton invited Greenspan to stand by
his side before White House reporters Thursday morning in the Rose
Garden, where the influential Federal Reserve Board chairman gave
his unqualified endorsement to the president's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outcome of the debate on permanent normal trade relations
with China will have profound implications for the free world's
trading system and the long-term growth potential of the American
economy,'' Greenspan said. ``I believe extending PNTR to China, and
full participation by China in the WTO, is in the interest of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the economic benefits, deepening and extending
commercial relations between the United States and China ``will be
a far stronger vehicle'' for promoting individual rights and
respect for the rule of law in China, Greenspan said, ``than any
other alternative of which I am aware.''
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of internal debate, the White House announced
Thursday morning that Clinton would make a nationally televised
address on the China deal. But CBS and ABC said Thursday they will
not carry the speech, despite the White House request. NBC will air
a live broadcast of the five-minute address, as will CNN.
</P>
<P>
   And, said White House aides, former President Jimmy Carter has
been working the phones on Clinton's behalf, telling more than a
half-dozen undecided Democrats that strengthening U.S.-China trade
ties will help promote human rights and democratic reform in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was asked if he would help in making some calls to some key
congressional folks, which he did,'' said Carter's spokeswoman,
Carrie Harmon. ``He does feel strongly about the China trade
bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotions run high, as well, for opponents of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Some fear that knitting the U.S. and Chinese economies more
closely together will drive down wages and job opportunities for
American workers. Others contend the increased commerce with China
only emboldens the ruling Communist Party, and discourages
political reform and attention to human rights concerns. Still
others contend that China is bent on a strategy of exporting, but
not importing, large volumes of goods, an argument buttressed by
the lopsided U.S.-China trade gap _ $69 billion last year alone, in
China's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think public opinion clearly understands that it is not wise
to give the 'Good Housekeeping Seal of Approval' to a regime which
has time and time again proven itself deficient in terms of human
rights, labor concerns and environmental concerns,'' House Minority
Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., told reporters Thursday on Capitol
Hill. ``This is a fundamental issue of fairness and human rights
and freedom and decency, and it's a tough issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has vowed to oppose the bill when it comes up for a
House vote as early as next Wednesday. Gephardt predicted a close
vote, as do White House aides.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is slated for a June vote in the Senate, where
it is expected to pass easily.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed into law Thursday the Trade and Development Act
of 2000, passed by Congress last week. The legislation included two
separate bills _ the Africa Growth and Opportunity Act and the
U.S.-Caribbean Basin Trade Partnership Act _ as well as a handful
of other trade-related provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The main acts, though, reduced U.S. barriers to imports from
Africa and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the event to press further for House approval next
week of PNTR for China, saying that surging imports have been one
factor in the country's nine-year economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our exports and our open markets have given us the longest
expansion in our history, with low inflation,'' Clinton said.
``This bill reaffirms that position, and I hope it will be
reaffirmed next week, when Congress votes on permanent normal trade
relations with China.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.chinapntr.gov (the view from the White House)
</P>
<P>
   www.aflcio.org (why organized labor opposes PNTR)
</P>
<P>
   www.hrw.org (human rights in China)
</P>
<P>
   www.uschina.org (the view from U.S. business interests)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
