<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9216 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CHINESE-EXILES-HNS &LR;      05-18 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-EXILES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHINESE DISSIDENTS OPPOSE TRADE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ About 60 exiled Chinese dissident leaders joined
several Democratic House members Thursday to oppose a controversial
bill granting permanent normal trade relations to China. They said
more trade would only make China's communist government richer and
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Without freedom, ``the money you give to China all goes to
dictators,'' said Richard Long, an exiled activist from Beijing who
now publishes an e-mail political newsletter here. ``The people
don't benefit,'' added Long, speaking at a news conference on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Roeder, spokeswoman for Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., a
leading supporter of the permanent trade deal, called Long's claim
``ridiculous.'' She said that under the new agreement American
entrepreneurs would be freer ``to be directly in touch with the
Chinese people (and not) have to go through the Chinese
government.''
</P>
<P>
   The exiles and the lawmakers who oppose the bill cited Beijing's
censorship of information and its harsh treatment of political and
religious opponents.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Whip David Bonior, D-Mich., and several other
lawmakers joined the Chinese exiles in hoisting a 200-foot chain,
which they said represented imprisoned human rights, religious and
labor leaders in China. The activists also displayed signs listing
names of victims of the bloody 1989 Tiananmen Square crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Bonior predicted China's government will continue to jail
dissidents if it wins permanent trade status.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this deal may protect intellectual property, it will do
nothing to protect intellectual freedom,'' Bonior said. ``While
this trade deal may lift tariffs, it won't pry open the door to a
single prison cell.''
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to vote on the contentious issue next
week, and the vote is still too close to call although momentum has
been building on the pro-trade side. If the measure passes, Senate
approval is expected next month followed quickly by a triumphant
signing by President Clinton, who has lobbied extensively for the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two decades Congress has annually reviewed
America's trading status with China and granted Beijing the same
low tariffs it gives most other nations. Although Beijing has
selectively reduced tariffs on some U.S. products, it has
maintained higher levies on others such as cars and farm products.
</P>
<P>
   But in order to gain admission to the 135-member World Trade
Organization (WTO), which oversees international commerce, Beijing
has agreed to lower tariffs for all nations that grant it permanent
trade status.
</P>
<P>
   China's acceptance into the WTO is almost assured.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-China deal would cut Beijing's tariffs on U.S. goods
significantly while Chinese goods would continue to flow into the
United States under the same low tariffs that exist now. Trade
proponents say that if Congress does not approve the permanent
agreement, China might continue charging high fees on many American
goods while granting other nations lower tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists have joined organized labor and
environmental groups to oppose the permanent status bill. They say
China's lax labor and environmental standards would give its
producers advantages over American companies and cost jobs in this
country. They also say that by ceasing the annual trade review, the
United States would forfeit the only leverage it has to change
China's human rights policies.
</P>
<P>
   Bonior said the deal would not ``provide us with any structure
to guarantee people their freedoms or a decent wage either in China
or here in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers at the rally were Democrats Nancy Pelosi and
Lynn Woolsey of California, Marcy Kaptur and Stephanie Tubbs Jones
of Ohio and Bill Pascrell of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
