<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9218 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      05-18 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, May 19. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ In a victory for the Clinton
administration, the Senate on Thursday narrowly killed a measure to
set a deadline for withdrawing U.S. ground troops from Kosovo, a
proposal that also had drawn fire from Gov. George W. Bush. By a
53-47 vote, senators stripped a provision from a military
construction spending bill that would have cut off funds for the
5,600 U.S. forces in Kosovo by July 1, 2001, forcing their orderly
withdrawal unless Congress authorized the mission's extension. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE (Santa Fe, N.M.) _ In a scathing report, the
Interior Department said the conflagration that destroyed more than
200 homes in Los Alamos was caused by numerous failures by Park
Service officials who started a fire to destroy underbrush. The
officials failed to properly plan for the fire, check weather and
ground conditions or coordinate and communicate with each other,
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said in releasing the report
Thursday. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
