<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-COUNCIL-NYT &LR;      05-18 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-COUNCIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BUSH SPEECH REMAINS A MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BUSH-ADS)  
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Council for National Policy is a little known
group whose members are often very well-known and very
conservative. There are radio personalities like Oliver North and
James Dobson, and religious broadcasters, including Pat Robertson
and Jerry Falwell. There are business leaders like Holland Coors,
and members of Congress, including Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and
Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It is the sort of group a Republican presidential hopeful would
presumably want to address, which is exactly what Gov. George W.
Bush did last October when the council held a two-day conference in
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But what exactly did Bush say?
</P>
<P>
   Skipp Porteous has certainly tried to find out, though as yet
without success.
</P>
<P>
   Porteous is national director of The Institute for First
Amendment Studies, a watchdog group from Massachusetts with about
3,000 members nationwide that tries to watch the Council for
National Policy. He regards the council as a secretive umbrella
group plotting strategy for the Republican right.
</P>
<P>
   The council says such talk is silly. They call themselves a
nonpartisan educational foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The council does like its privacy, though. The group holds three
meetings a year, all behind closed doors. Security guards shoo away
any interlopers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, though, Porteous said his group has planted a
spy in several meetings, even making national news when the
institute's newsletter, Freedom Writer, reported a speech in early
1998 in which Dobson accused congressional Republicans of betraying
evangelical voters and threatened to abandon the party.
</P>
<P>
   But Porteous, who is a licensed private investigator, found his
group shut out when the council gathered in San Antonio. Eager to
know what Bush might say in private to conservative leaders,
Porteous sent off for audiotapes of the conference. The council
sells audiotapes of conferences to members only, but the institute
had obtained an order form from the company, Skynet Media, that
handles the recording.
</P>
<P>
   So when a package arrived earlier this year, Porteous thought
success was at hand. Except that the tape of Bush's speech was not
included. ``If he's speaking at meetings,'' Porteous said, ``the
American people should know what he has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton C. Blackwell, the council's executive director, said all
guest speakers are asked for permission to include their remarks in
the tape set and that the Bush campaign had declined. Blackwell
said other speakers over the years had also declined, though he
would not name anyone who had. In some cases, the speeches are
included in the council's publication, Policy Counsel, which is
distributed to libraries and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush entourage said they preferred that the tape not go
out, though I could not see any reason why they shouldn't,''
Blackwell said. He added, ``It was a standard speech, basically the
same one. Basically everything he said, he's said before, and I've
heard since.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes said he addressed the council about two years ago
and discussed ``the life issue in detail'' as well as taxes and
Social Security. He said he never considered excluding his remarks
from tape set of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just assume everything I say may be held against me,''
said Forbes, who joined the council a few months after his speech.
He added: ``At that stage, I appreciated that somebody wanted to
disseminate what I said.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said if anyone
was ``hoping to hear something that the governor would say that he
hasn't said publicly, then they're on a wild goose chase.'' He
declined to characterize the speech, saying ``when we go to
meetings that are private, they remain private.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Fleischer said, ``as far as we know, there is no
tape.''
</P>
<P>
   But Curt Morse, president of the recording company, Skynet
Media, said he has a copy and one was provided to the campaign
after the speech. ``Maybe they lost it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He offered to make them a copy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
