<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9223 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HILL-HOLLIDAY-BOS &LR;      05-18 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILL-HOLLIDAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERTINO LEAVING HILL HOLLIDAY; SHAKEUP PUTS CONNORS AT THE HELM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fred Bertino, the man who some thought might eventually
succeed Jack Connors as chief executive of Hill Holliday Connors
Cosmopulos, said Thursday he is leaving the Boston ad agency to
join a smaller shop.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hill Holliday announced a ``reorganization'' of the
agency under Connors following its merger last month with Goldberg
Moser O'Neill, or GMO, a San Franciso ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   Under the reorganization, June Blocklin and Michael Sheehan will
serve as presidents of Hill Holliday's Boston office.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Connors engineered the sale of Hill Holliday to
the Interpublic Group of Cos., a New York conglomerate known as IPG
that owns a slew of ad agencies and public-relations firms, for a
reported $115 million in stock. At the time, he agreed to stay on
with the agency he cofounded for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Connors hinted that he has no plans to quit and retire
to Florida any time soon. ``I love what I do,'' said Connors, who
will soon turn 58.
</P>
<P>
   One of the many ad agencies IPG owns is GMO. In April, IPG
announced that GMO would be merged into Hill Holliday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Connors said IPG could move at least one more of its
many ad agencies under Hill Holliday's management.
</P>
<P>
   Together Hill Holliday and GMO project annual billings of $1.2
billion and employ nearly 1,000 people in offices in Boston, San
Francisco, and New York. Hill Holliday now claims to be it one of
the 15 largest ad agencies in the country.
</P>
<P>
   With 1999 billings of $827 million, Hill Holliday was the second
largest ad agency in New England last year.
</P>
<P>
   The merger and the prospect of more mergers necessitated a
reorganization, said Connors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Fred to take over all creative (duties) outside the
Boston office,'' said Connors, referring to Bertino. ``Fred, who's
an extraordinary talent, decided he didn't want it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bertino, his departure is voluntary and amicable;
after 10 years at Hill Holliday, it was time for a change, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bertino, Hill Holliday's president and chief creative officer,
plans to join the newly opened Boston office of Dallas-based Square
One, one of the largest independent agencies in the Southwest.
Bertino will be president and a partner of Square One East and will
have an equity position in the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Bertino will be succeeded at Hill Holliday by Blocklin, who had
held the title of executive vice president and director of
advertising services, and by Sheehan, who abruptly left Hill
Holliday last year.
</P>
<P>
   During Bertino's 10 years at Hill Holliday, the Boston shop
evolved from a regional ad agency into a national player.
</P>
<P>
   Square One may face the same challenge today that confronted
Hill Holliday a decade ago. Square One is a small, regional agency
looking to take its business to the next level. According to
Adweek, it had $84 million in billings last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great ride,'' said Bertino, 42, of his decade at
Hill Holliday. ``But I felt like this was a natural time to make a
move. . . . I think it's good to change and challenge yourself
every five or 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertino is widely regarded as a creative talent. But running a
newly bulked up agency with more mergers on its dance card may
require a different skill set _ an MBA-type, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bertino may not be a world-class manager when it comes to
running a multi-office, billion-dollar ad agency,'' said Skip Pile
of Pile and Co., a Boston consulting firm that helps manage ad
agency reviews. ``But he's a marquee-level, top-tier creative
talent. He knows how to motivate people, and he's terrific at
winning new business.''
</P>
<P>
   At Square One's Boston office, Bertino will be reunited with
Jamie Mambro, a Hill Holliday alumnus who has a national reputation
as a creative talent. The Bertino-Mambro combination ``holds a lot
of promise'' for Square One, Pile said.
</P>
<P>
   At Hill Holliday, the reorganization also establishes a
corporate management team that will oversee operations at the three
agency offices and will report directly to Connors.
</P>
<P>
   The team includes Joe Norberg as chief operating officer, Stever
Aubrey as general manager and executive vice president, and Laurel
Rossi, who as an executive vice president will be in charge of
``integrated strategic marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stressing that he has no plans to retire, Connors said a
possible successor could likely come from this management team; the
names Blocklin and Sheehan should also be included on any list of
possible successors, Connors said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill Holliday's clients include Fidelity Investments, Cisco
Systems, and Dunkin' Donuts. Square One's clients include Miller
Brewing Co. and Dr. Pepper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
