<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCULPTOR CHOSEN FOR THE VENICE BIENNALE; STEINBERG GIVES A RUBENS
TO ISRAEL MUSEUM; A LEONARDO DA VINCI WILL BE SOLD AT SOTHEBY'S,
AND AN EARLY WHISTLER GOES TO CHRISTIE'S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Wash., France, Italy)   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The much-admired sculptor Robert Gober will represent
the United States at the 2001 Venice Biennale. Known for his
surreal and perfect re-creations of body parts and everyday objects
like sinks, urinals and drainpipes, he relates his work to the
explicit and social-political art of the late '80s and early '90s
in oblique and illusive ways.
</P>
<P>
   Gober, 46, lives in New York City. He was selected by the Fund
for U.S. Artists at International Festivals and Exhibitions, a
public-private partnership of the National Endowment for the Arts,
the U.S. State Department, the Rockefeller Foundation and the Pew
Charitable Trusts after curators and contemporary-art museums
nationwide were asked to propose candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The curators of Gober's installation are James Rondeau,
associate curator of contemporary art at the Art Institute of
Chicago, and Olga Viso, associate curator at the Hirshhorn Museum
and Sculpture Garden in Washington. The installation is to consist
of eight sculptural works: seven designed specifically for the four
galleries of the United States pavilion, and one currently on view
in the Whitney Biennial.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the new sculptures will be variations on a large piece
of white Styrofoam that Gober found on the beach near his studio on
Long Island. ``They will be cast in bronze,'' Rondeau said. ``The
process of translation from the actual object to the symbolic is
always at play in Gober's work.'' Rondeau added that the sculptures
make loose reference to the theme of water, which has been
important to the artist.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition in Venice will be the first major site-specific
installation of Gober's work since one at the Museum of
Contemporary Art in Los Angeles three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   RUBENS FOR THE ISRAEL
</P>
<P>
   Saul Steinberg may be selling much of his furniture at Sotheby's
next week ( and a stash of Old Master paintings through Richard L.
Feigen, the Manhattan dealer, but he has decided to give the Israel
Museum in Jerusalem an important Rubens.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, ``Death of Adonis (With Venus, Cupid and the Three
Graces),'' dates from around 1614. Steinberg bought it in 1982 from
Jeffrey H. Loria, the Manhattan dealer. The painting is monumental
in scale _ about 7 by 11 feet _ and depicts Ovid's tale of the
death and lamentation of Adonis.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second Rubens to enter the museum's collection. The
first, ``Romulus and Titus Tatius'' (circa 1630-34), was bequeathed
to the museum in 1986 by Sam Weisbord, a Los Angeles collector. The
one Steinberg has given is larger and far more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of years ago we talked to Saul about our desire to
build our Old Master collection,'' said James Snyder, director of
the museum. ``This is a signature, mature painting and our first
major Rubens.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the museum began renovating its European art
galleries. It also initiated a drive to encourage benefactors to
strengthen its Old Master collection. Last year it received
Poussin's ``Destruction and Sack of the Temple of Jerusalem''
(1625-26) as a gift from the Rothschild Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said the Rubens would go on public view in about a week.
</P>
<P>
   SKETCHES BY LEONARDO DA VINCI
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the finest Old Master paintings and drawings
have been sent to auction in Manhattan for sale recently, Sotheby's
in London has made some important discoveries that will be included
in its July sales.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, the Old Master drawings department announced
that on July 5 it would auction a sheet of unpublished drawings by
Leonardo da Vinci.
</P>
<P>
   In 1878, members of the Calando family, Paris collectors, bought
the sheet at auction. It has been in the family ever since and has
remained unknown and unpublished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they realized how rare drawings like this are,''
said Gregory Rubinstein, director of Sotheby's Old Master drawings
department in London. ``Apart from the listing in the Paris sale
catalog, no image or other details of the drawings have been
publicly seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The double-sided sheet depicts Hercules holding a club. Several
other pen-and-ink sketches depict an executioner, whirlpools and a
device for blocking the flow of a river.
</P>
<P>
   The work, expected to sell for $640,000 to $960,000, was seen by
Prof. Giulio Bora, a leading authority on Leonardo, who confirmed
that the sheet was by the artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study sheet, with its series of rapid sketches,''
Rubinstein said, ``contains so much of the essence of Leonardo's
art: the seamless transition between art and science; sketches of
waterworks combined with a heroic figure study; the free use of
whatever drawing medium was most appropriate to the task in hand;
and the surprises that the artist constantly springs on us.''
</P>
<P>
   AN EARLY WHISTLER
</P>
<P>
   The cover of Christie's catalog for its sale of American
paintings next Thursday features an early Whistler, ``Harmony in
Gray: Chelsea in Ice'' (1864), a landscape of figures against the
Thames embankment. The painting, estimated at $2.5 million to $3.5
million, comes from descendants of Denys Sutton, an English
collector.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's hung the Whistler with its Impressionist and
post-Impressionist art right before last week's sales, hoping to
lure collectors whose taste is more European to consider buying a
serious American painting. ``Whistler was a great late-19th-century
expatriate painter, and like Sargent and Cassatt, he appeals to
both types of buyers,'' said Paul R. Provost, head of Christie's
American paintings department.
</P>
<P>
   While early Whistler landscapes like this one are rare on the
auction market, some experts say the painting's muted palette may
not make it a popular choice. There has not been one like it for
sale at auction since 1987, when Sotheby's sold ``Variations in
Violet and Green'' (1871) for about $2 million. It is now in the
Musee d'Orsay in Paris.
</P>
</TEXT>
