<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran plans brisk growth through 2001
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although AirTran Airways has slowed deliveries of its
new Boeing 717 jets for financial reasons, the airline plans to
significantly accelerate growth starting later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's second-largest carrier, which has grown little in the
past two years while a new executive team stabilized the company,
will boost seat capacity 12 percent in the second half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That will be followed by a 15 percent capacity increase in 2001,
Chief Executive Joseph Leonard said at the carrier's shareholders
meeting Thursday. Those growth rates are three or four times the
industry norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``After stabilizing the company, we think it is now positioned
for strong and sustained growth,'' Leonard told an audience of
about 50 shareholders at the Georgia International Convention
Center.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran will add one or two new destinations later this year
from its Atlanta hub, and two to four a year for the next two
years, Leonard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be looking for cities where prices are high and
service is weak,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More growth will be accomplished through added frequencies on
existing routes, and by adding point-to-point flights between
destinations outside Atlanta, Leonard said. For instance, this year
AirTran has opened three new nonstop routes to Florida from
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The growth will intensify AirTran's competition with
Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines, which handles about 80 percent of
traffic at Hartsfield International Airport. It comes after five
consecutive quarterly profits for AirTran, which until 1997 flew as
ValuJet and struggled for survival after a 1996 crash in the
Florida Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran began buying 717s last year to replace its aging DC-9s
and 737s. But this week it disclosed a slowdown in deliveries
negotiated with Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier, which now flies 10 of the new twinjets, had agreed
to buy a total of 50 by 2002. Under the new plan, those deliveries
are stretched out through 2003. To meet its growth goals, AirTran
will also slow the rate at which it replaces its older planes,
retiring one DC-9 for every two 717s delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching out 717 deliveries reduces financing costs and
deposits associated with buying the new planes. That will improve
cash flow and help AirTran refinance $230 million in debt coming
due in 11 months, Leonard said. He said he is confident the
refinancing will be done on schedule, calling it the top issue
facing management.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard also said AirTran will launch a new ad campaign in July
and that it is generating 23 percent of bookings at its Internet
site, airtran.com, helping to lower processing costs. Most big
airlines' Internet bookings are in the single digits.
</P>
<P>
   In his discussion of growth plans, Leonard said the airline
hopes to build a new hangar at Hartsfield and that it is making
itself available to other carriers as a code-share partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be a very attractive partner for anybody who doesn't
have a major presence in the Southeast,'' he said, adding that no
pact is imminent. Earlier this year, AirTran approached Northwest
Airlines and its foreign partner, KLM, about such a partnership but
was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   A few shareholders expressed frustration about AirTran's stock
price, which has remained stubbornly below $5 a share despite the
carrier's profits and improved outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody more frustrated with the stock price than the
management team,'' Leonard said. He said high fuel prices this
winter torpedoed airline stocks just as AirTran's was poised to
take off but that ``sooner or later the market will take care of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
