<HEADER>
A9230 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-LABOR-COX     05-18 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LABOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    China trade stand threatens Gore's labor support
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH CANTON, OHIO _ Armed with leaflets denouncing unfettered
trade with China, shop steward Jerry Warfield stood outside the
Hoover vacuum factory here and braced for the onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 p.m., the factory's gates opened and disgorged a stampede
of plant workers, who paused just long enough to grab one of
Warfield's leaflets _ a form letter addressed to Rep. Ralph Regula
(R-Ohio).
</P>
<P>
   After the rush, Warfield vented his frustrations over the
Clinton administration's proposal to grant permanent trade
relations with China, which Congress considers next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill, as far as I'm concerned, pretty much destroys
manufacturing,'' said Warfield, a 26-year employee of Hoover
Appliances. About Vice President Al Gore, who supports the accord,
Warfield pursed his lips and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be hard for me to vote for him,'' said Warfield, a
staunch Democrat. ``I don't like (George W.) Bush. And if Gore's
position on some of these issues don't change, it'll be hard for me
to vote for him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Warfield's sentiments, echoed by other rank and file union
members here, bode ominously for the vice president. The support of
organized labor is critical to Gore's election prospects,
particularly in the industrial Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Senior labor leaders and rank and file members, even those
strongly supporting Gore, said they are uneasy about trying to turn
out union votes for Gore after the vice president so vocally
supported legislation they believe could kill their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting harder and harder to tell them, the working
folks, to vote for someone who has done something against their own
interest,'' said Bill Burga, president of the Ohio AFL-CIO, who is
supporting Gore. ``Well, the voters are going to say the hell with
it, we aren't going to support these people who voted against us.
We just won't vote, or vote for a third party or throw it away
somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokeswoman Kathleen Begala minimized the the impact of the
disagreement with organized labor on China, saying labor voters
understood that Gore will not agree with them on every issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on the issues that are vitally important to these folks
and many other folks, Al Gore is right on them, and George W. Bush
is wrong on them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of President John Sweeney, the 13 million
member AFL-CIO is waging the most aggressive campaign to defeat the
China trade bill since Congress passed the North American Free
Trade agreement in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would end the annual review of China's human
rights record in deciding whether to grant the country low tariffs
for imports to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Union members are writing letters to wavering members of
Congress, working phone banks and delivering anti-trade literature
to plant gates in more than 30 congressional districts across the
country. Here in eastern Ohio, the AFL-CIO is targeting Regula and
Rep. Tom Sawyer (D-Ohio), two undecided members.
</P>
<P>
   The most intense lobbying is being conducted by the AFL-CIO's
three large industrial unions _ the Teamsters, the United Auto
Workers and the United Steel Workers _ and, to a lesser extent, the
industrial locals of the electrical workers union, which represents
the 2,300 hourly workers at the Hoover plant.
</P>
<P>
   Problematic for Gore is that these unions are heavily
concentrated in Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan, Indiana and Wisconsin
_ toss-up states where the presidential election between Gore and
Bush could be decided.
</P>
<P>
   Union voters comprised 46 percent of Ohio's presidential primary
this year, according to exit polls. They voted for Gore 74 percent
to 22 percent over former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Labor turnout in November may very well hold the key to Gore's
chances of defeating Bush, and could also determine the Democratic
Party's bid to reclaim the House.
</P>
<P>
   While Sweeney and the AFL-CIO endorsed Gore last October, both
the UAW and the Teamsters withheld their endorsement because of
their anger over Gore's position on trade.
</P>
<P>
   The two unions, with 2.2 million active members combined, have
also sent signals they are willing to look at alternatives to Gore.
Two weeks ago, UAW president Steve Yokich met privately with
consumer advocate and presidential candidate Ralph Nader in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before that, at a boisterous rally involving 5,000
Teamsters in Washington, Teamsters President James Hoffa shared a
platform with Reform party candidate Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Both Buchanan and Nader, who have a strong anti-trade message,
have the potential to siphon votes away from Gore. At a labor rally
in Canton, Ohio, on Wednesday, steel worker Richard Cordes showed
up wearing a yellow ``Buchanan 2000'' button.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have a third choice this year,'' Cordes said.
Mike Mathis, the Teamsters political director in Washington, said
the 2000 elections could wind up like 1994, when union voters
stayed home and Republicans wrested control of the House for the
first time in four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats ``are in for a rude awakening,'' Mathis said. ``The
local leadership is upset about this. For them to take time to
campaign for somebody and entice their memberships to get involved,
it's a lot of time for them. They are going to be less likely to do
it for a Democrat who voted wrong on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Much hinges on the outcome of the voting next week. If the
legislation is defeated, it will be much easier for union members
to forget about Gore's support of it.
</P>
<P>
   If it passes, then steel worker union members such as Richard
Hiles, who plans to help Gore in Canton, have their work cut out
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many months do we have? Four? Five?'' said Hiles, glancing
around for a calendar. ``Hopefully, this will be old news by
then.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
