u a BC-AMERICAS-COX     05-18 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School of Americas fends critics' plans for closure
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new name and mission at the School of the
Americas could not stave off attacks Thursday as congressional
critics tried unsuccessfully to shut down the controversial
military academy located at Fort Benning.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Moakley (D-Mass.) introduced an amendment to the
Defense Authorization bill that would close the school and assign a
congressional task force to determine whether the U.S. government
should train soldiers from Latin America. It was defeated by a vote
of 204-214.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1949, the school near Columbus has taught Latin American
soldiers how to fight insurgencies. The school is controversial
because, critics say, a number of its graduates have violated basic
human rights in their native countries.
</P>
<P>
   Heeding those concerns, the Pentagon has recommended that the
academy change its name to the Defense Institute for Hemispheric
Security Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Defense Department is recommending that the
school expand its charter to include civilian personnel and require
a minimum of eight hours of instruction on preserving human rights,
the rule of law, due process and the role of the military in a
democratic society.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, an independent board to oversee the school and
its curriculum would also be created.
</P>
<P>
   The changes have the blessing of Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and Secretary of Defense William Cohen. Both the House and
Senate Armed Services Committees have backed the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But Moakley said those changes would amount to little more than
``putting a perfume factory on top of a toxic waste dump.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Cynthia McKinney was the only member of the Georgia
delegation to vote for closing the school. John Lewis (D-Ga.) did
not vote but expressed support for closing the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always supported the amendment to close the school,''
Lewis said. ``I think it should be closed because of its history
and some of the people who have been associated with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sanford Bishop (D-Ga.) and Georgia Republican Reps. Saxby
Chambliss and Mac Collins were among those strongly defending the
school Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Military-to-military exchanges are an integral component of
American foreign policy and provide valuable education and
training,'' Chambliss said. ``These exchanges increase cooperation,
help professionalize militaries and teach them the role of the
military in democratic civilian societies.''
</P>
<P>
   Army Col. Glenn Weidner, who runs the Fort Benning school, said
that fewer than 1 percent of the school's 60,000 graduates have
been linked to crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our opponents continue to trot out half-truths about the
school being responsible for a small number of graduates,'' Weidner
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic, Weidner said, because the main thrust of the school
is to educate military and law enforcement officers to prevent
human rights violations and to foster a dialogue so they will adopt
American values.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Georgia's senators support the Pentagon plan to overhaul
the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of these reforms is to produce a more professional
military
</P>
<P>
   culture in Latin American countries,'' said Sen. Max Cleland
(D-Ga.), a co-sponsor of the Senate version of the Pentagon reform
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Unrest in countries such as Equador, Columbia and Venezuela is
evidence that continued engagement by the United States is
necessary to stabilize the region, Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.), a member of the Senate leadership,
agrees. The school is critical to improving relationships and
maintaining peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school performs a valuable mission for the entire
hemisphere,'' Coverdell said. The critics of the school should be
satisfied that a dozen investigations have found the school in
compliance with U.S. law and foreign policy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
