r t BC-AQUARIUM-TOUR21-COX     05-18 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AQUARIUM-TOUR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S. Carolina aquarium so realistic it's uncanny
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ We are standing at the edge of a blackwater
swamp at twilight.
</P>
<P>
   Firefly flares dance among the dark stands of nearby trees.
Cypress knees press up from the muck of the bottom. A cool fog
blankets the swamp's surface, engulfing the low-hanging Spanish
moss and dead wood. And bullhead, skink and shortnose sturgeon _
looking for all the world like dinosaur fish _ riffle the dark
water here and there, suggesting a shadow life below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hear that?'' asks Chris Andrews, cupping an ear to discern the
croaking of ... something uncertain. A frog perhaps. Or something
larger?
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it?'' my son Josh asks, seeking refuge behind my
knees. ``It's OK,'' I tell him. ``It's just make-believe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But what's making that noise?'' he asks, summoning all the
courage a 5-year-old can muster. ``It's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Even within the safe, secure and dry confines of this
spectacular exhibit at the South Carolina Aquarium, the Blackwater
Swamp _ the third stop on visitors' self-guided tour _ the illusion
of this engineered reality is powerful. You can't see the cooling
coils chilling the room. Or the fog machine kicking out mist. Or
the speakers and wires tucked among the cypress.
</P>
<P>
   But what you don't see is making you feel chilled and alert _
very alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what it's like to be in a blackwater swamp at
dusk,'' says Andrews, 47, the jovial director of the new aquarium,
during a recent tour of the $69 million facility. ``Those
fireflies? Fiber optics. And the sounds of the frogs and insects
are piped in to give you the sense of what it's like.''
</P>
<P>
   The point, of course, is not simply to frighten or dazzle.
Andrews wants aquarium visitors to feel what it's like to be knee
deep in a blackwater swamp _ to immerse themselves in the
experience _ so that it stays with them when they leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do this kind of clever representation,'' he says,
taking in the exhibit with a sweep of his hand. ``But it's nothing
compared to the real thing. We want people to come here and get a
taste of it _ maybe where it feels safe and where they can bring
the kids and learn something about the habitat. But then we want
them to go out to the real thing and see it for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, that's the mission _ and magic _ of the aquarium,
which opened this weekend on Charleston Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The facility replicates a variety of South Carolina habitats and
ecosystems, all designed to educate visitors about the state's
natural diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina is just remarkable,'' Andrews says. ``It is so
lush and semitropical in places, and biologically very diverse. We
have a great range of animals and plants here to (represent) that.
It's not just a big fish tank.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibits have been assembled with painstaking attention to
detail. Only fish native to the Carolina bays are seen swimming in
the aquarium's bay exhibit. Only birds you'd find in the state's
mountain forests are chirping in the exhibit of that name. And only
plants that populate a real coastal marsh grow out of the
prefabricated muck.
</P>
<P>
   The tour begins at the Riverside Terrace entrance, a stunning
waterfront platform overlooking the harbor. Visitors then move
through a series of multimedia exhibits in six major galleries
showcasing the key regions of the South Carolina Appalachian
Watershed: the Mountain Forest, Piedmont Plateau, Coastal Plain,
Saltmarsh, Coast and Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   As visitors follow a mazelike trail from one gallery to the
next, they mirror the path that a hypothetical raindrop might take
on a journey from the mountain streams of the Appalachian highlands
to the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  PHONE/WEB:
</P>
<P>
   843-720-1990, www.scaquarium.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HOURS:
</P>
<P>
   Spring: Through June 30,
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.-5 p.m. daily.
</P>
<P>
   Summer: July 1-Aug. 31,
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.-7 p.m. daily.
</P>
<P>
   Fall: Sept. 1-Oct. 31, 9 a.m.-
</P>
<P>
   5 p.m. daily.
</P>
<P>
   Winter: Nov. 1-Feb. 28, 10 a.m.-5 p.m. daily.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ADMISSION: $18 for adults; $12 for students and senior
citizens; $7 for children 4-12; free for children 3 and under.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Tate writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
