<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9238 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-PROUST21-COX     05-18 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PROUST21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weighty bio wends through life of late bloomer, his great work
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 21.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you know the conventional wisdom about Marcel Proust _ i.e.,
he was a mousy hypochondriac who only left his bed to gather gossip
at society parties _ then you're liable to panic when presented
with this new biography. Yikes: 810 pages! Are we to be dragged
through an inch-by-inch itinerary of the writer's hermetic,
cork-lined bedroom?
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the richness, the fullness of Proust's life was
strictly inside his head. He set that inner life to paper with
breathtaking brilliance. An eccentric asthmatic who in his adult
life rarely woke before sunset or fell asleep before dawn, Proust
spent 13 years completing his 15-volume, semi-autobiographical
opus, ``In Search of Lost Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Proust was everything that, say, Ernest Hemingway wasn't _
frail, hypersensitive, verbose, sometimes filling a page with a
single sentence. Someone has probably already written the parody
``Papa and Marcel on Safari,'' which would have the Frenchman
wearing his all-season fur coat in tropical heat, whining and
chattering so busily that he doesn't notice an elephant about to
stomp him. But the truth is that Proust has a place with Hemingway,
Joyce and Faulkner as fearless trailblazers in fiction during the
first three decades of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, biographer William C. Carter, a professor of French
at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, has enough appreciation
of Proust's soaring mind to make up for the tedium of the writer's
daily regimen. Yes, ``Proust'' does start lethargically, but it
gathers force. It's diligently researched and written _ if not with
flair, exactly, then with a probing intelligence worthy of its
complex subject.
</P>
<P>
   Born to a wealthy doctor and a mother to whom he was obsessively
attached (as his ``Search'' makes clear), Proust lived with his
parents until well into his 30s. He knew early that he had a gift
for writing but was apparently too ill, with asthma and shaky
nerves, to make a timely career start.
</P>
<P>
   Or was he just too lazy and childish? Or was closeness to his
childhood self essential to Proust's ability _ through the magic of
the warm tea and famous madeleine cake _ to recapture his earliest
years with such vividness and wonder?
</P>
<P>
   Proust could be as repellent as he was appealing. To some he was
the most loyal of friends, writing tributes to them in the Paris
journals on any pretext; to others he was a society toadie, fawning
over salon hostesses. He paid waiters to be his spies and sniff out
scandals. He was so attached to a male brothel that he helped to
pay for its furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Carter brings to life not only Proust but his times: the
Parisian belle epoque of artistic ferment, affluence and joie de
vivre. Sarah Bernhardt, Andre Gide, Claude Debussy and Jean Cocteau
make their interesting appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the detail Carter brings, it's still mysterious how,
and why, Proust finally grew up, conceived his literary mission and
threw himself into it, at about age 40. Perhaps when he became too
ill to even attend soirees, he was sobered and steeled by his
disease _ as, say, Franklin D. Roosevelt was by his polio. Proust's
portraits of society life become sharply satiric in ``Search'' _
little battlefields of pettiness compared with the profound
beauties he describes so memorably in nature, art and relationships
of love.
</P>
<P>
   Carter describes well Proust's ``intimate voice ... pouring into
the listener's ear the rich music of his enchanting, nocturnal
musings.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Proust makes his life turn, and his great book takes shape,
length is no longer a deterrent in the biography. In some ways
we're even left hungry to know more: the unknowable sources, and
secrets, of genius.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BIOGRAPHY
</P>
<P>
   Marcel Proust: A Life. By William C. Carter. Yale University
Press. $35. 810 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A searching treatment of a bizarre genius.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert is a feature writer at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
