<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9240 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-CHARLETSON21-COX     05-18 1684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARLETSON21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The inns and eats of Charleston
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 21.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ The dust never settles in this beguiling
coastal city.
</P>
<P>
   Even as residents cheer the opening of the South Carolina
Aquarium _ a marvel of modern architecture looming over the harbor
_ their longstanding commitment to historic preservation remains
paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Quicker than you can say she-crab soup, a former military school
building becomes an all-suites hotel, another musty warehouse opens
as a trendy restaurant or a rundown mansion is reborn as a
distinctive inn.
</P>
<P>
   Horse-drawn carriages packed with sightseers roll slowly through
neighborhoods where once-stately homes reclaim their former
grandeur as young families invest money and lots of sweat equity.
</P>
<P>
   That ``everything old is new again'' vibe is what makes the city
of 80,000 so inviting to the 3.7 million people who visit each
year.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Charleston is busy setting the stage for the annual
Spoleto Festival USA and an influx of families visiting the new
aquarium. And with the town's reputation as a gastronomic mecca
growing ever stronger, it seems like a restaurant opens every
month.
</P>
<P>
   As sure as sweet grass basket vendors ply their trade in the Old
City Market and carriage drivers crack lame jokes about their
horses' city-mandated ``diapers'' being ``emission control
devices,'' visitors this spring and summer will find some hot new
spots as well as some reliable favorites.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent visit to the historic peninsula, we scoped out
the best bites and great places to spend the night. Here are just a
few of your options:
</P>
<P>
   Sweet dreamsa
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wentworth Mansion: When cotton was king, Francis Silas Rogers
was one of the kings of cotton. The wealthy merchant built his
dream home, this Second Empire-style manse, in 1886 at 149
Wentworth St. Since opening as a 21-room inn in September 1998, the
spectacular 24,000-square-foot mansion has been welcoming
discriminating guests who luxuriate in the trappings of the Gilded
Age.
</P>
<P>
   Exquisite architectural details include Tiffany windows,
hand-carved marble fireplaces, carved plaster ceilings and
moldings, colored mosaic floor tiles in the reception hall and
hardwood floors. Topping the four-story inn is a cupola, reached
via a spiral staircase, that provides a 360-degree view of the
city. (See how many church steeples you can count!) The rooms
include king beds clothed in rich linens, fireplaces, large
bathrooms with separate showers and Jacuzzi tubs.
</P>
<P>
   Wine is served in the afternoon in the library; cordials after
dinner. A European-style breakfast _ a lovely spread of freshly
baked breads, fresh fruit, cold cuts and smoked salmon, cheeses and
such _ is served in the sun room.
</P>
<P>
   Such indulgence does not come cheap. Tariffs are $295-$695.
</P>
<P>
   1-888-466-1886; www
</P>
<P>
   .wentworthmansion.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Holiday Inn Historic District: Open since last summer, this
126-unit hotel with deluxe rooms and suites looks not the least bit
like its former incarnation, the Quality Inn Heart of Charleston,
which was gutted to its frame before extensive interior and
exterior renovation began. With a pool and on-site restaurant, it's
a good choice for families. And its location at Calhoun and Meeting
streets is close to the visitors center, the aquarium and the
market. Summer rate is $169.95 double occupancy. 125 Calhoun St.
</P>
<P>
   1-877-805-7900.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On a tight budget? You'll need to look outside the historic
district, where even moderate accommodations such as the Best
Western King Charles Inn, Days Inn and the Hampton Inn are in the
$150-$200 range in the summer (and more during Spoleto). For help
in finding lodging, contact the Charleston Area Convention and
Visitors Bureau (see information at end of article).
</P>
<P>
   Great eatsa
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Circa 1886: The Wentworth Mansion's restored carriage house
opened last fall as an elegant dining room under the supervision of
chef Patrick Ramsey. The grilled beef tenderloin ($26) _
beautifully presented on wild mushroom and foie gras ragout with
haricots verts, chateau potatoes and sauce Diane _ was one of the
best plates of food I've ever eaten. A salad of riesling poached
pear, Danish blue cheese, bacon cracklings and toasted walnuts on
spinach with a warm bacon vinaigrette ($7.75) and a dessert of
pan-fried angel food cake with peach ice cream and warm berry
compote ($6.95) were memorable. 149 Wentworth St.
</P>
<P>
   1-888-466-1886.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  McCrady's Tavern: The story goes that George Washington
quaffed a pint at this tavern built in 1778 by Edward McCrady. Too
bad he missed out on chef Michael Kramer's grilled double-cut pork
chop with sweet potato puree, buttermilk onion rings and apple
cider glaze ($16). It's a perfect example of how Kramer puts a
gourmet spin on a Southern standard. I'm still thinking about the
salad of balsamic grilled pears, red onions, toasted pecans and
Maytag blue cheese ($8) and an exemplary creme brulee ($7). Under
new ownership, McCrady's reopened last summer after an extensive
six-month renovation. The 222-year-old building has been redesigned
with a sleek modern look that complements the brick walls, exposed
beams, massive fireplaces and hardwood floors. Oversize, colorful
oil paintings of fruits and vegetables and a photo-realistic view
of Charleston's rooftops grace the walls. 2 Unity Alley.
843-577-0025.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High Cotton Maverick Bar &AMP; Grill: As in ``fish are jumpin' and
the cotton is high.'' Or maybe as in ``stepping in high cotton.''
For that's what it feels like in this upscale saloon that opened in
November. It's a red-meat kind of place with mahogany woodwork,
brick walls and heart pine floors. Manly men and their ladies may
wish to share a 44-ounce porterhouse for two ($60). Chef Jason
Sholz's no-nonsense menu also features game _ South Carolina squab
($22) and venison medallions ($24) _ along with veal, lamb, pork,
fowl and seafood prepared on the grill or rotisserie. 199 E. Bay
St. 843-724-3815; www.high-cotton.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hank's: With its faded hand-painted signs on the facade, this
seafood restaurant in a turn-of-the-century warehouse a block off
the market looks like it has been here for years. Truth is, it
opened in February 1999. The ambience recalls a Charleston fish
house of the '40s with white-jacketed waiters serving chef Frank
McMahon's Lowcountry classics and innovative Southern seafood. We
are intoxicated by the very thought of Seafood a la Wando, a
melange of crab, shrimp and scallops in a great onion and
mushroom-studded cream sauce laced with sherry and served over
fried grits. Entrees from $13.95. 10 Hayne St. 843-723-3474.
</P>
<P>
   Two old favoritesa
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Magnolia's: Since introducing his ``Uptown/Down South'' fare
to Charleston a decade ago, chef Donald Barickman has defined _ and
refined _ the concept of the new cuisine of the Old South.
Barickman's menu relies on locally available ingredients such as
McClellanville lump crab meat, Wadmalaw Island-grown greens,
Clemson blue cheese and Carolina plantation rice. If one menu item
says it all, it's the Down South egg roll with collard greens,
chicken, tasso, spicy mustard and peach chutney ($8.25). It was one
of our starters as we lunched on shrimp, crab and avocado salad
with lemon vinaigrette ($9.50), spicy shrimp and sausage with tasso
gravy over creamy white grits ($9.95) and yellowfin tuna salad on
croissant ($8.95). The dinner menu features such stick-to-your-ribs
entrees as veal meatloaf with mashed potatoes and tobacco onions
($15.25), sauteed crab cakes with black beans and rice and summer
squash ($19.95) and grilled salmon with a Parmesan herb crust,
served with collard greens and red rice ($18.50). 185 E. Bay St.
843-577-7771.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Slightly North of Broad: Or ``SNOB,'' as locals call it. This
so-called maverick Southern kitchen has been packing crowds in the
19th-century warehouse since 1992 for chef Frank Lee's inventive
take on Southern food. We love this place of faux-finished walls,
painted chandeliers, bold, colorful fabrics and wrought iron _ set
off by brick walls, a 15-foot ceiling and exposed heart-pine beams.
We considered such tantalizing entrees as sesame-crusted tuna with
nori rolls, house-made kim chee, cucumber salad, miso, pickled
ginger and wasabi ($9.50) and grilled pork tenderloin with hoppin'
John, seasonal greens and sweet pepper relish ($8.75). But we
settled on lighter fare: a grilled scallop salad ($10.95) and a
cleverly prepared sauteed chicken salad with country ham, blue
cheese, Granny Smith apples, pecans and arugula with balsamic
vinaigrette ($7.50). A tasty Key lime tart ($5) finished off lunch
in fine style. 192 East Bay St. 843-723-3424.
</P>
<P>
   Great stuff coming up a
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Spoleto Festival USA: The annual arts explosion of 110-plus
performances and literary and visual arts is Friday through June
11. 843-722-2764, www.spoletousa.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Masterpieces in Gold and Paper: Faberge at Middleton
Place'': The Forbes Magazine Collection of Faberge objets d'art and
historic documents will be exhibited at the Middleton Place house
museum and the Edmondston-Alston House July 24-Nov. 12. The exhibit
contains 31 Faberge works including jewelry and three Imperial
Easter eggs created for the last two czars of Russia. Also on
display will be 14 documents chronicling American history from the
Stamp Act of 1765 to Lee's note to Grant requesting a cessation of
hostilities to end the Civil War in 1865. 843-556-6020;
www.middletonplace.org.
</P>
<P>
   Getting therea
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  By air: A check of Travelocity.com showed the lowest current
rate for a nonstop flight on Delta is $206 with a 14-day advance
purchase and Saturday night stay.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  By car: It's 320 miles via I-20 east to Columbia, then I-26
east to Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   Informationa
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Charleston Area Convention and Visitors Bureau,
1-800-774-0006; www.charlestoncvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
