r l BC-FASHION-SHOOB21-COX     05-18 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SHOOB21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A STYLE CHAT WITH... Judge Janice Shoob
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 21.
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Judging from her clothes, Wendy Shoob doesn't wear
stuffy courtroom attire.
</P>
<P>
   The Fulton County Superior Court judge has her mother, Janice
Shoob, to thank for the little, spaghetti-strap black dresses, slim
skirts and tailored jackets she wears under her black judicial
robe.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 18 years, Janice Shoob, wife of U.S. District Judge
Marvin Shoob, has been designing classic suits, dresses, separates
and evening gowns under the label elan by Janice Paradies. She
works out of her home and tailors beautiful silk, linen, crepe,
cashmere and gabardine into made-to-measure clothing. Prices range
from $175 for a sleeveless shell to $699 for a silk and cashmere
evening gown. (For information: 404-233-8731).
</P>
<P>
   The clothes are quiet classics, but they shout style to her
loyal customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her clothes are distinctive, and they fit,'' says longtime
client Jackie Lassiter, a consumer consultant. ``I love how she
lines her jackets and pants with colorful silks. She adds beautiful
buttons to jackets, too. And the designs are timeless. I bought a
black-and-white dotted silk dress this spring and it goes with
jackets she designed for me six years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, writer Marylin Johnson caught up with Janice Shoob at
her daughter's office.
</P>
<P>
   Q:When and how did you get into the ``rag'' business?
</P>
<P>
   A: I had two older sisters and was always reworking their
clothes for them while growing up in Druid Hills. Also, during the
'50s, I did some modeling and in 1962 opened the Casual Bazaar
boutique in East Point. But a fire closed the shop in '73, so I
stayed home to play tennis and do wardrobe consulting. In 1982, I
had a client who couldn't find anything she liked in the stores.
She asked me to design several suits, which she liked. Other
friends asked me to make their clothes. I was hesitant at first to
go into business, but my son Michael said, ``Go for it. You are
always cheerleading for everyone else. It's your turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Q:How has your business evolved?
</P>
<P>
   A: I started out with one dressmaker and myself. And one client
has grown to 50. I went from having two fashion showings around the
pool of my house for clients and their friends to several small
shows each season in my home workroom for women only. Today, my
niece Jodie Skorecki is my assistant; she helps with the designs,
fittings and billings. And two dressmakers, Karen Meyers and Cindy
Ganoe, make the samples and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What are your sources of inspiration?
</P>
<P>
   A:My glamorous memories, old fashion books and movies.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Key to current success?
</P>
<P>
   A:Since I'm a cottage industry, I can stay small and be
flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Designer you most admire?
</P>
<P>
   A:Givenchy.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Clothing style you most abhor?
</P>
<P>
   A:Midcalf length. It cuts you at an awkward place on your leg.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Your personal motto?
</P>
<P>
   A:If you are fortunate, you share with others.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes fo rthe Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
