<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9243 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-WESTON21-COX     05-18 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WESTON21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Be comfortable playing up your attributes, author advises
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 21.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Style is not about getting noticed, it's about being remembered.
</P>
<P>
   That's the mantra women of all shapes and sizes should say to
themselves, says Michele Weston, author of ``Learning Curves:
Living Your Life in Full and With Style'' (Crown Publishers, $24).
</P>
<P>
   During a recent stop in Atlanta to promote her book, Weston said
she wants to help full-figured women like herself see their own
power and beauty so they can find self-love and acceptance. Part of
that spiritual journey is realizing they can wear whatever style
and color they want, as long as it's flattering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so busy asking everybody's opinion of what we look like
that we forget to ask ourselves,'' says Weston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a great bustline, play it up. If you have
beautiful hands, take care of them. Make sure you put your best
foot forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Weston, 38, doesn't mind telling her age. But don't ask her
weight or dress size.
</P>
<P>
   ``What size am I? My size,'' she replies. ``The right size for
me, right now, this minute in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As fashion and style director of Mode magazine, one of the
hippest magazines on the market for plus-size women, Weston knows
her stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Whether a woman is a size 12, 14, 16 or larger, Weston says
seven basic pieces will get her through any season looking sharp.
Those items are a single-breasted blazer, a narrow skirt of any
length that celebrates her curves, a simple dress, a classic white
shirt, a great pair of trousers, any garment in matte jersey
because it can be worn year-round and a twin sweater set for
versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``For summer, look for fabrics that let you breathe and be
comfortable,'' she advises. ``And if you're a person that loves
color, there's a lot of color out there this season that can draw
your eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Lippincott, spokeswoman for Lane Bryant, one of the
leading retailers of fashion-forward clothing for full-size young
women, says ``bare looks are very, very hot for summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for T-shirts with cutout backs, handkerchief tops with
skimpy ties, Capri pants, shirts with three-quarter-inch sleeves,
camisoles with built in bras, short skirts and sun dresses with
lingerie straps.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you say `bare,' it doesn't mean you have to walk out with
every part of your body showing,'' says Lippincott. ``You choose
the part and then buy the article of clothing that accentuates that
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Tips from ``Learning Curves'' on how to accentuate the positive:
</P>
<P>
   ACCENTUATING THE POSITIVE
</P>
<P>
   Tips from ``Learning Curves'':
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BUST
</P>
<P>
   To accentuate: Wear V-necks, lower necklines or clingy knits.
</P>
<P>
   To play down: Crew neck tops, high necklines and minimizer bras.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ARMS AND SHOULDERS
</P>
<P>
   To accentuate: Wear sleeveless, strapless or spaghetti-strap
dresses and tops.
</P>
<P>
   To play down: Structured jackets, small shoulder pads, cardigan
sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WAIST
</P>
<P>
   To accentuate: Wear belts, fitted tops and tuck in shirts.
</P>
<P>
   To play down: Long tunic tops, men's shirts worn out, A-line
skirts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HIPS
</P>
<P>
   To accentuate: Wear knits, narrow or bias cut skirts and
dresses.
</P>
<P>
   To play down: Wear dark colors on the bottom, longer skirts and
fabrics that don't cling such as lightweight wools and linen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  LEGS
</P>
<P>
   To accentuate: Wear short skirts, dresses and skirts with slits,
nude stockings and Capri pants.
</P>
<P>
   To play down: Dark stockings or sheer opaques, longer skirts and
dresses, trousers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For hot summer fashions and styling advice
see: www.modestyle.com
</P>
<P>
   www.lanebryant.com
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
