<SLUG> BC-SC-AQUARIUM21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A sparkling new aquarium in Charleston, S.C., offers best of all
watery worlds
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 21.
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charleston, S.C. _ The most striking attraction at the new South
Carolina Aquarium is the one that isn't surrounded by glass.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Atlantic bottlenose dolphins perform elegant water ballet
several times an hour. Playful sea otters make cameo appearances.
And coastal birds swoop and soar above visitors' heads, while
turtles paddle through shallow waters at their feet.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the aquarium's most striking attraction isn't an
exhibit at all. It's Charleston harbor, which surrounds the
facility on three sides _ enveloping visitors and giving new
meaning to the phrase ``natural setting.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just one of many distinguishing features that make the
South Carolina Aquarium, which opened this weekend, a unique
addition to the historic city's tourist draws _ and a worthy
destination for families and nature lovers throughout the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other aquarium in North America has this kind of approach,
where it opens up to a working harbor,'' notes Chris Andrews, the
aquarium's energetic director.
</P>
<P>
   From the waterfront terrace, you can see dockworkers at
Charleston Port Terminal _ barely a stone's throw away _ offloading
some of the $47 million in goods the dock handles daily. And as
sailboats and cruisers zip past, you can watch construction crews
carry out other elements of Charleston's burgeoning waterfront
redevelopment _ an initiative that mirrors similar harbor face
lifts in Boston and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   But the South Carolina Aquarium's spectacular riverfront
entrance is only the beginning of the experience here. What's
inside this high-tech fish tank and natural-history museum is also
dazzling.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 exhibits in six major galleries showcase the wide
variety of plant and animal life native to South Carolina's
Appalachian watershed _ from cool mountain streams to ocean reefs
miles offshore. Displays range from a small tank of jellyfish to a
massive 330,000-gallon central aquarium with hundreds of species.
Some 10,000 animals call the aquarium home _ from tiny shrimp and
dainty angelfish to a 50-pound cubera snapper.
</P>
<P>
   The aquarium was 14 years in the making; its opening caps a
knotty history of planning, funding and development. In preparing
the site for construction, for instance, city officials discovered
toxic wastes from a coal gasification plant.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the city, state and federal government _ and the
utility responsible for the contamination _ came up with the $69
million in mostly public funding needed to clean up the site and
build the facility. And today, this stretch of Charleston
waterfront is a showcase for a significant environmental success
story.
</P>
<P>
   The private nonprofit organization that operates the aquarium
projects 1 million visitors a year. They will encounter a facility
that has combined, and expanded upon, some of the best elements of
the nation's most prominent aquariums.
</P>
<P>
   Like Chattanooga's Tennessee Aquarium, the Charleston facility
replicates a variety of ecosystems _ but goes further by depicting
specific South Carolina habitats, with native plants and animals.
Like aquariums in Boston and Baltimore, it sits on the waterfront _
but takes greater advantage of its location by providing an
open-air harbor-side terrace. And like Miami's Seaquarium, the new
aquarium promotes interaction with wildlife _ but offers more for
younger visitors, with many ground-level exhibits for toddlers to
examine and manipulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every new aquarium that opens steals from the best of the
others, but the trick is to bring something unique to it,'' says
Andrews, 47, a native of Bath, England, who worked at the London
Zoo and Baltimore's National Aquarium before coming to Charleston
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the South Carolina focus, another distinguishing feature
is the aquarium's science-education program. It meets the minimum
testing requirements for math and science for South Carolina
elementary and high school students, says spokeswoman Tara Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``What good cities do is increase the education and edification
of their citizens,'' says Charleston Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. ``We
are building this for our citizens, and most especially for every
child in South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   A primary goal, he adds, is for each aquarium visitor to leave
``with a new set of environmental goose bumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews knows it will take goose bumps for the South Carolina
Aquarium ``to show people why they should care about the natural
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you touch people's emotions, all the science in the
world won't make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Tate writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
