<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If Sprint's deal fails, BellSouth in spotlight
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should regulators move to block the WorldCom purchase of Sprint,
BellSouth would watch closely_ but it might just stay a spectator.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's interest had to be piqued when news broke Thursday
that Justice Department staff is apparently recommending rejection
of the deal. After all, BellSouth threw $100 billion on the table
in October in what proved a failed bid to win Sprint, only to be
outgunned when WorldCom raised its offer to $115 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Jeff Battcher declined to speculate one way or
another. ``We don't comment on our own deals, much less somebody
else's.''
</P>
<P>
   But if that acquisition falters, shouldn't BellSouth reopen the
checkbook? Maybe, but a lot has changed.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth in October seemed to see Sprint as one big bet. It
seemed the deal in a flash would have reshaped BellSouth into a
national player that could compete with the likes of AT&AMP;T, Bell
Atlantic and _ of course _ WorldCom. BellSouth would have Sprint's
national wireless unit and its network of high-speed lines _ an
Internet backbone. Sprint's long-distance unit was alluring as
well, since BellSouth expected to have approval for long-distance
within months.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Now, BellSouth seems to need different things _
and maybe even to be different.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few months, BellSouth has forged a deal with SBC to
merge wireless businesses and buy whatever new licenses are needed
for a national offering. BellSouth has announced plans for a
tracking stock to represent its Latin American unit. In Europe,
BellSouth inked an alliance with KPN Telecom, promising an expanded
presence.
</P>
<P>
   The company most recently announced plans to deliver television
and other digital services via satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Even what hasn't changed seems to speak against a merger:
BellSouth is still not permitted in long-distance and may not be
until next year. Buying Sprint would require either a creative
arrangement or a prolonged wait to enjoy all its fruits.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Sprint also comes with some baggage that is only
moderately attractive. For instance, it has a large but slowly
growing local phone unit, some of which borders BellSouth turf.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, BellSouth has proved willing to gamble. And Sprint's
high-speed lines remain especially enticing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't rule out another BellSouth bid,'' said analyst Jeff
Kagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the timing was right and the value was there for
the shareholders, I think they could make another go of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
