<SLUG> BC-FINSTER-FEST19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ailing Finster bounces back for folk art fest
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUMMERVILLE, Ga. _ Howard Finster, who has used his folk art to
preach about getting ready for God before he gets ready for you,
has faced death in the face this spring. And the score is: Finster
1, Death 0.
</P>
<P>
   The 83-year-old artist developed double pneumonia after a March
speaking engagement at New York's Museum of American Folk Art. ``I
thought he was gone,'' Beverly Finster said of her father's third
subsequent hospital visit, following an insulin reaction. ``He's
grown a lot weaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for his prodigious output _ more than 46,000 numbered
works since 1976 _ Finster was unable to paint anything for five
weeks. Nor could he make appearances at Atlanta's Dogwood and Inman
Park festivals or his usual Sunday visits to Paradise Gardens, the
folk art environment here that is considered his greatest creation.
</P>
<P>
   All of which sounds dire, except when you check in on Finster
himself, busily painting a wooden cutout of a giant Coca-Cola
bottle in his studio one afternoon this week. Sporting a healthy
glow, if walking unsteadily with a cane, he pauses during a nonstop
preach-a-thon to extol the virtue of direct sun daily. ``You're
looking pale, kind of German,'' he informs a visitor, sunnily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fixing to leave this here world,'' he goes on to state
matter of factly. ``I've got a limited distance left to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   But before he checks out, he says, he has work to do, trying to
restock Paradise Gardens' gallery and readying for this weekend's
Howard Finster Fest.
</P>
<P>
   He wearies just thinking about the endless line of autograph
seekers. ``I don't look forward to nothing at this point,'' Finster
harrumphs, before quickly adding, ``but I'll try to be there for
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard
</P>
<P>
   Finster Fest
</P>
<P>
   Sixty folk artists show and sell their works.
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m.-6 p.m. Saturday-Sunday. $5 adults, $2 children. Paradise
Gardens, three miles north of downtown Summerville. 1-800-
</P>
<P>
   346-7837 or www.finster.com.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Pousner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
