<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9249 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-UPFRONT19-COX     05-18 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-UPFRONT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Series hype aside, networks jockey for advertising billions
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Drew Carey walked out onto the stage of Radio City
Music Hall this week and passed judgment on the spectacle that
brought his audience of advertisers, ad buyers and TV station
managers together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, this is like hype with a capital `YPE,''' Carey cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it is. This week, the six broadcast networks announced
their fall schedules in a dizzying round-robin of high-profile
presentations and parties. Television viewers themselves are
secondary in this process; the target is the advertising community,
which in the coming weeks will spend between $7 billion and $8
billion on the 2000-2001 television season. Much of that will come
from big-bucks companies _ the Coca-Colas, General Motorses, Kodaks
and beer makers.
</P>
<P>
   The money is spent upfront, before the season begins in the
fall. Hence, the announcements are known in the industry as ``the
upfronts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideal way would be for every advertiser to see every
show,'' said David Marans, a senior partner at J. Walter Thompson
advertising agency. ``But this is the shortcut method. We get more
of an understanding of the concept behind the scheduling.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertisers also get the royal treatment. The networks go
all out: NBC rented the Metropolitan Opera House to make its
announcement Monday; ABC took over Radio City Music Hall on
Tuesday; CBS made its presentation at Carnegie Hall on Wednesday,
then moved the whole shebang of several hundred people to Tavern on
the Green for a party with CBS stars. Radio ``shock jock'' Howard
Stern showed up at the classy restaurant (wearing sunglasses
indoors), but you could hardly get near him for all the young media
buyers lined up to pay homage. There was sushi and prime rib and
cameo appearances by the likes of David Letterman, Faith Hill and
WWF wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   Billions of dollars are at stake, many high-powered people are
here, yet one of the main things to do at the upfronts is stand in
line to get your picture taken with TV stars. At ABC's party
Tuesday night under a tent behind the New York Public Library, the
longest line was for ``NYPD Blue'' with Dennis Franz and newcomer
Henry Simmons, who plays hunky detective Baldwin Jones. Heather
Locklear and Charlie Sheen of ``Spin City'' (Sheen replaces Michael
J. Fox in the fall) drew big crowds as well. NBC didn't muster up
any of the cast of ``Friends'' (despite their multimillion-dollar
contract renewal deal) or ``ER,'' but the Polaroid groupies didn't
mind because the casts of ``Will &AMP; Grace'' and ``The West Wing''
were on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd much rather be fishing,'' admitted Ryan Stiles, who stars
in ``The Drew Carey Show'' and ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you gotta do it. ABC pays us good money.'' That was about
all he had time to say, as he was yanked back for another picture
with his ``Carey'' castmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little strange,'' WB star Jamie Foxx said. ``But I'm
very good at schmoozing _ that's what this business is about.''
</P>
<P>
   The slightly surreal upfronts are only a small part of the very
big business of selling TV advertising. In the season that draws to
a close next week, the six networks reportedly took in almost $17
billion in advertising revenue, a record. Sales for the coming
season are expected to top that. A 30 second spot runs from $80,000
for a low-rated show to $400,000 on an ``ER'' or ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire.'' In addition, it is an election year, which means
lots of political advertising, and an Olympic year, which benefits
only NBC but will push overall spending even higher. Plus, dot-com
companies, most of which didn't exist a few years ago, continue to
pump millions into TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   All this despite the broadcast networks overall declining
audience. For years, the networks have been fretting about
``erosion'': the slow drop-off of their audiences as viewers surf
over to upstart networks (Fox, the WB, UPN), cable networks, or
turn to home computers, the Internet and video games. This season
the combined Nielsen ratings of ABC, CBS and NBC were up slightly,
but virtually all of that increase was because of one show: the
unstoppable phenomenon ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' Regis
Philbin's game show is expected to generate more than $400 million
in ad revenue next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' remains the elephant in the living room of
network TV. CBS President Leslie Moonves fantasized Wednesday about
taking out a mafia contract on Philbin's life, but Ray Romano, star
of ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' had another idea. In a quick
stand-up routine for advertisers Wednesday at Carnegie Hall, Romano
joked that he had pitched CBS on the one show that could beat
``Millionaire'': ``Who Wants to Spank a Supermodel?''
</P>
<P>
   New shows are introduced with about five minutes worth of clips,
and already some deals were being made, said J. Walter Thompson's
Marans. But most of the ad buyers will wait until next week, when
the networks will send them the full pilot episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually wait to see them, but then it goes very fast,''
said Jennifer Leavans, national broadcast manager for Round Two
Communications, an ad-buying agency. ``We'll make most of our buys
in a week or two, usually based on time slot and potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Time slot is key. ``The Steven Weber Show,'' a new NBC comedy,
will rake in mega-bucks because it will air after ``Friends,'' and
is therefore almost guaranteed a large audience.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't really matter whether the ad buyers like the shows
they're buying time on. ``It's all about serving the clients'
needs,'' said Mike Callahan, a negotiator for ad agency Mindshare.
``Personally, I like Yasmine Bleeth,'' he added, making it clear by
his expression that he was referring to the former ``Baywatch''
actress, who wore an extremely tight copper bodysuit to NBC's
party, rather than her new show, the soap opera ``Titans.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor do many advertisers care that much about content, said
Jessica Reif, media analyst for Merrill Lynch. ``Some of them care
about what's surrounding their message in the medium,'' Reif said.
Extreme shows, such as ``The Jerry Springer Show'' and ``WWF
Smackdown!'' (UPN's pro wrestling show), don't bring in advertising
revenue commensurate with their ratings, but most prime-time shows
don't raise eyebrows. The days of advertisers trying to influence
content are largely over, Reif said.
</P>
<P>
   So the biggest unanswered question of the upfronts is this: Why
aren't they on television? The medium seems to put on everything
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be one of the highest-rated specials of the year,''
said Marans. ``Twenty million people would die to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there's a lot here the average viewer wouldn't enjoy:
a parade of network suits spinning like mad, talking about
demographics and using terms like ``over-indexing,'' which
basically means a show is doing really well.
</P>
<P>
   But with Letterman telling jokes as he did at the CBS
presentation Wednesday, along with David Copperfield doing magic
tricks and Faith Hill singing a gospel number, or with Hank
Williams Jr. rocking out on ``Are You Ready for Some Football?''
accompanied by a dozen dancers in hot pants to promote ABC's
``Monday Night Football,'' the networks probably could have grabbed
a few ratings points.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
