<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9251 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-310&AMP;ADD-     05-18 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-310&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN LEADER SAID TO PLAN NO SHIFTS THAT WOULD ANTAGONIZE
BEIJING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ On the eve of an extraordinarily sensitive
transfer of power here, Taiwan's soon-to-be foreign minister said
the new president, Chen Shui-bian, would make no sudden shifts in
Taiwan's policy toward China and would continue to send soothing
signals to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chen Shui-bian will not give China any easy excuse to
retaliate with force,'' said the minister, Tien Hung-mao, referring
to the closely watched inaugural address that Chen will deliver on
Saturday. ``It's going to be a very conciliatory kind of speech.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tien also warned outsiders not to expect any dramatic
overture from Chen, who swept the Nationalist Party from power in
March after a half-century of rule. Having won with less than 40
percent of the vote, he said the president-elect did not have a
mandate to shake things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the fundamental principles that our country stands for, he
will not make a concession,'' Tien said. ``He cannot. He's not
mandated to make a concession.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes it very unlikely that in the speech, or in the near
future, Chen will grant Beijing's demand for reopening negotiations
across the Taiwan Strait: that Taiwan accept the idea that it and
the People's Republic are part of a single China. Since his
election, Chen has said he is willing to discuss the concept of
``one China,'' but will not accept it as a precondition for talks.
</P>
<P>
   China has repeatedly warned that if Taiwan veers toward
independence, it will use force to take the island. With Beijing
likely to scrutinize Chen's words, Tien said the president-elect
was putting the passage of the speech that deals with China through
endless drafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope there will be enough of a way out for China to say,
`At least Chen Shui-bian did not say that. He met our minimum
criteria for continuing,''' Tien said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The deadlock between Taipei and Beijing on ``one China'' has
brought relations to one of their tensest points in years. China's
leaders were rattled by the election of Chen, whose Democratic
Progressive Party formally espouses independence. Chen has said
such a step is unnecessary, but recent remarks by his vice
president, Annette Lu, have led China to unleash threats.
</P>
<P>
   Tien denied a recent report that the new Taipei administration
had requested that the United States play a more active role in
mediating the dispute. He also played down recent remarks by the
new head of Taiwan's Mainland Affairs Council, Tsai Ying-wen, in
which she expressed hope that Washington would be a ``facilitator''
of new talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been happening for many years,'' Tien said, referring
to frequent discussions about cross-straits policy held in the
United States. Those talks, though not official, bring together
Taiwanese, Chinese and American scholars and former government
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Tien, who is the chairman of a policy research institute, said
that as foreign minister he would push for more such exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a political breakthrough, Tien said he counted
on flourishing economic ties between Taiwan and China to bridge the
gap. Shortly after the election, Chen proposed to lift the ban on
direct trade, transportation and postal service between the two
countries. He also said he would consider lifting strict limits on
Taiwanese investment on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Although Taiwanese companies are not allowed to invest more than
$50 million in any single project in China, there are an estimated
35,000 Taiwan companies with operations there. Businesses are
pushing to be allowed to invest in Chinese infrastructure projects,
investment that is now prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs that business people are starting to be
subjected to the same pressure as politicians like Chen. The
Chinese government recently summoned the local representatives of
Taiwanese companies with ties to Chen and his party to warn them
that their mainland operations would be penalized if they were
perceived as advocating independence for the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are pressuring a lot of businessmen to verbally express
their loyalty to the `one China' principle,'' Tien said.
``Taiwanese businessmen will have to come to a decision whether it
is worth it for them to make a political concession to make a few
extra dollars in China.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Taiwan's leading industrialists, Stan Shih, visited
Beijing two weeks ago to try to assure the Chinese authorities that
he planned to steer clear of the independence debate. Shih,
chairman of the computer maker Acer Inc., is a longtime supporter
of Chen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been worried by unnecessary political pressure from the
Beijing authorities,'' said Rick Lei, the president of Acer's
digital services division, who accompanied Shih on the trip. Acer
recently obtained a license to run a test of an Internet-access
service in mainland China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
