<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9252 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-JURORS-COX     05-18 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-JURORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ray Lewis jury pool cross-examined on `hot seat'
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One potential juror described how he was falsely
accused of fondling a girl. One talked about his wife being raped.
Another had to recount his two DUIs.
</P>
<P>
   This week in the courtroom of Fulton County Superior Court Judge
Alice D. Bonner, stories of regular people _ not an NFL star _ are
the stories that count. One by one, potential jurors for the
Buckhead stabbings case have been grilled by as many as four
lawyers at a time and sometimes the judge herself.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes irritated, often fidgeting and usually stone-faced,
jurors sit in what Bonner calls the ``hot seat,'' the middle chair
of the jury box. To shield their identities, they are referred to
only by designated numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and defense lawyers have qualified 32, enough
prospective jurors to pick a 12-person jury. But questioning
continues so they can get six alternates for the anticipated
month-long trial.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner expressed frustration late Thursday at the pace of
questioning and expected length of the case, saying, ``This trial
should last one week in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Some potential jurors have been quizzed for 45 minutes,
explaining their opinions about law enforcement, professional
sports, O.J. Simpson's acquittal and rap music.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate, a stagehand who likes old Westerns, wondered
aloud toward the end of his inquisition what could be worse:
serving on this jury or keeping a dentist's appointment next week
to get a tooth pulled.
</P>
<P>
   With testimony expected to begin Tuesday, the trial of All Pro
linebacker Ray Lewis, Reginald Oakley and Joseph Sweeting is
expected to provide up to a month of grand courtroom theater. But
this week the spotlight is on the trial's most important audience _
those who will be picked to decide whether the defendants are
guilty of killing two Decatur men on Jan. 31 after a night of
post-Super Bowl partying.
</P>
<P>
   TV courtroom dramas highlight emotional closing arguments and
blistering cross-examinations. But to attorneys who try cases for a
living, victory depends on picking the right jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most important process in a criminal trial,'' Atlanta
criminal defense lawyer Brian Steel said. ``Most people think this
isn't a big deal. But this is everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, jury selection is a time to plant ideas in jurors'
heads before they hear a single witness, Steel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical,'' said District Attorney Paul Howard, who
starts off apologizing to each potential juror for the personal
nature of his questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case we have a football player, and you have to look
for someone who is not enamored or intimidated by that,'' Howard
said Thursday during a courtroom break. ``That's important because
this is America and we as a society pay a lot of attention to
people in entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   While about four dozen Fulton residents who have been questioned
do not constitute a representative sample of Fulton's 750,000
residents _ 53 percent black and 45 percent white. But they do
offer a snapshot of mindsets and life experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Many have loved ones who were gunshot victims or are serving
time in prison. Many don't trust the news media. Some have great
faith in law enforcement. Some have no trust in it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Many said they enjoy TV crime shows. ``COPS'' is a big favorite.
</P>
<P>
   This prompted lawyer David Wolfe, who represents Oakley, to ask
one juror if he thought it would be appropriate if TV aired a
program that showed the police arresting the wrong man. ``They can
call the show `Oops,' '' Wolfe said.
</P>
<P>
   While some folks are clearly eager to serve on the high-profile
case, several, like Juror 21, were surprised at the serious task at
hand. ``This is my first time (in jury service); I was anticipating
something a lot lighter, like maybe traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Several tried everything they could to wiggle out of it. Bonner,
who excused jurors for family emergencies, has had little sympathy
for other perceived woes.
</P>
<P>
   One college student complained about the imposition and said she
would be ``resentful'' if chosen as a juror. ``I don't think she
has a mature attitude,'' said Bonner as she excused the young woman
from the pool.
</P>
<P>
   A technology consultant complained jury duty would hurt his
business, making him incapable of giving the defendants a fair
trial. Bonner promptly excused him, but not before firing a parting
shot: ``We'd be in trouble,'' she said, if more citizens ducked
their civic responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   While jury selection offers a glimpse into the lives of everyday
people, it also allows observers _ and the opposing side _ to glean
glimpses of trial strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, the defenses seem to be:
</P>
<P>
   _ people were drunk, the victims' group picked a fight and Lewis
tried to be a ``peacemaker''.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sweeting was defending himself and his friends, especially the
women with him.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oakley was knocked senseless by a champagne bottle and in no
shape to kill anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the defense will be able to eliminate 12 potential
jurors. Prosecutors can ``strike'' six.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers like what they see in the jury pool. Initially,
the defense asked Bonner for additional jury strikes. But
Wednesday, they waived that request, so prosecutors wouldn't get
extra strikes too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can certainly understand that,'' Bonner said.
</P>
<P>
   Juror No. 38 said of Lewis, ``He's a good football player; You
got to respect him.''
</P>
<P>
   This same juror said he believed ``half of the police in Atlanta
are dirty.'' He was asked very few questions by defense attorneys.
Prosecutors tried to get him stricken, but Bonner refused.
</P>
<P>
   One older woman had both a godson and grandson murdered and
appeared to be a prosecutor's dream juror _ until she was asked
what she remembers most about the case. ``He (Lewis) was at the
scene but he actually didn't do it,'' she responded.
</P>
<P>
   Howard tried to get Bonner to remove her for cause. The judge
disagreed and prosecutors must now use one of their six strikes to
keep her off the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Another, a young man, said he didn't like sports or defense
lawyers. ``It's not right a lot of guilty rich people go free,'' he
wrote in a questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' team asked Bonner to strike him. She refused. Now Lewis's
team must use a strike on him.
</P>
<P>
   One juror said ``You can't judge a book by it's cover,'' and
Juror 35 was certainly an example of that.
</P>
<P>
   The man, a white, older middle-aged Sandy Springs man appeared
to be a prosecutor favorite when he told of his initial reaction to
news about the killings: ``Obviously, at 4 a.m. the parties were
probably drunk or on drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis attorney Ed Garland then asked what he thought about
people being out in Buckhead at that hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was with them,'' he said. It was the only time Ray
Lewis has laughed during the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
