<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GEORGIA-ECONOMY0519-C     05-18 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-ECONOMY0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Farewell forecast: Growth to slow
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mortgage rates approaching 10 percent and a sluggish
stock market over the next two years will chill the nation, but
that will seem doubly true for the red-hot Atlanta economy, Georgia
State University economist Donald Ratajczak said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta and the rest of the nation probably won't enter a
recession unless there's a stock market crash or slowdown in
economic growth around the globe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it may feel like the local economy has slowed to a crawl
after so many years as being one of the fastest-growing in the
nation, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good times (in Georgia) have been so good that this return
to more normal economic behavior will appear as if the economy has
stopped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown will result from the Federal Reserve's turn toward
a tighter money policy this week, he said. The Fed raised a key
borrowing rate by a half percentage point Tuesday after several
previous quarter-point increases, and signaled that more rate
boosts are likely.
</P>
<P>
   In his final forecast as head of GSU's Economic Forecasting
Center, Ratajczak predicted that Georgia's economy will still grow
by a healthy 4.5 percent this year and by less than 3 percent next
year. Ratajczak has headed GSU's economic forecasting center for 27
years.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted the nation's economy will grow by a robust 5.1
percent this year but slow to a little over 3 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   The economy in Georgia and its leading city will slow more
dramatically than the nation's economy, he said, and it will be the
first time in a decade that the state's economy will lag the
nation's.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's economy grew by 5.5 percent last year, GSU estimated,
while Atlanta accounted for almost three-fourths of the 149,000 new
jobs in the state last year.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's job growth will drop to about 124,300 this year and
78,800 next year because of corporate restructurings at Coca-Cola
and other companies, slowing residential construction and starting
a shakeout in the overbuilt retail industry, GSU's economists
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta home builder John Wieland said he has already seen a 10
percent drop in sales by his firm, which last year sold 800 homes
with an average price of $340,000. ``I wouldn't be surprised to see
the market drop 20 percent'' within three months, said Wieland, who
is also chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The drought in Georgia will also hurt farm incomes and cause
scattered bank closings and weak farmland prices in rural Georgia,
said Ratajczak.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia's job growth should still be enough to keep the
apartment and condo market hopping, said Ellen Burnstein, senior
consultant at Dale Henson Associates, an Atlanta multifamily
residential market analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a lot of jobs,'' she said. ``The demand for apartments
is still there as long as employment stays high.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Turner, an agent with Re/Max of Atlanta, said he
probably won't notice a slowdown in home sales for another month
because most clients already have locked in lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   But if mortgage rates top 9 percent, he added, his home sales
will probably drop off 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the nation's home buyers and other consumers will soon
feel deceleration's grip since the Federal Reserve has ``lost
patience'' with small rate boosts of a quarter percentage point,
said Ratajczak.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed will ``get into the dramatic area,'' said Ratajczak, if
it repeats this week's action by raising rates twice more by a half
percentage point each.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a mistake the Fed has a history of repeating, he
added, by not waiting long enough for earlier rate boosts to take
effect before piling on more draconian measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like taking two aspirin for a headache, then 10 minutes
later, taking two more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed ``knows its history, too,'' said Wieland. ``I think
the Fed is sensitive to that issue. Hopefully ... it won't overdo
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratajczak predicted that mortgage rates will hit 9.5 percent by
early next year and that real interest rates (after inflation) will
be about 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At that level, the U.S. economy historically declines at least
for a quarter, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ratajczak also predicted that the stock market, as measured by
the Dow Jones industrial average, will rise only about 5 percent
this year, compared with 20-plus percent gains in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   When interest rates rise that high, it's ``very difficult for
stock market values to rise significantly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
