<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New fall TV schedule
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David E. Kelley will do to high school teachers next
fall what he's been doing to lawyers for years: turn them into
heroes and clowns, examining them through his own strange vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston Public,'' a comedy-drama with a large interracial
ensemble cast set in a Boston public high school, will be Kelley's
next series venture for Fox. It will air at 8 p.m. Mondays in the
fall, making it a companion piece to Kelley's ``Ally McBeal.''
There's even the possibility of crossovers between the shows, since
``Ally'' is set in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of five new series Fox announced to advertisers at the
New York ``upfronts.'' The others:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dark Angel'' (9 p.m. Tuesdays) is a strange looking
futuristic thriller that looks as if it blends ``Blade Runner''
grunge with ``X-Files'' paranoia. It stars Jessica Alba CQ and was
created by James Cameron (''Titanic'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Don't Ask'' (8 p.m. Wednesdays) stars John Goodman
(``Roseanne'') as a divorced, gay father.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Schimmel'' (8:30 p.m. Wednesdays) is loosely based on the
life of stand-up comedian Robert Schimmel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Street'' (9 p.m. Wednesdays) is from Darren Star,
creator of ``Melrose Place'' and ``Sex in the City.'' It's a drama
about the personal and professional lives of young Wall Street
hotshots and stars Tom Everett Scott (``That Thing You Do'').
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for midseason are ``The Tick,'' a comic-book adventure
starring Patrick Warburton (``Seinfeld'') as a clueless crusader,
and ``The Lone Gunmen,'' the ``X-Files'' spinoff about the three
geeky paranoids who help and hinder Mulder and Scully on that show.
</P>
<P>
   And Mulder and Scully were on hand Friday, in the form of David
Duchovny and Gillian Anderson. As previously reported, ``The
X-Files'' will return for an eighth season, but with Duchovny in a
limited number of episodes (Daily Variety reports 11). Fox
Television Entertainment Group chairman Sandy Grushow said that
Mulder will be abducted in the season finale that airs Sunday
(5/21), and will be missing when the season opens next fall. Scully
will be paired with a new partner, but Mulder will return some time
into the show's run.
</P>
<P>
   `The guy network'
</P>
<P>
   UPN also announced its new fall lineup Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proud to be known as the guy network,'' said CEO Dean
Valentine, who saw his network surge in the ratings this season by
adding ``WWF Smackdown!'' ``Somebody needs to stand up for the
high-testosterone American male.''
</P>
<P>
   That somebody is UPN, which adds:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Freedom'' (8 p.m. Fridays), an action-adventure drama about
a future in which the military has taken over the United States,
and a band of former soldiers become freedom fighters. It features
lots of Hong Kong film action stunts, such as balletic slo-mo
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Level Nine'' (9 p.m. Fridays), another action-adventure
series, this one about cops who fight cybercrime.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Girlfriends'' (9:30 p.m. Mondays), a sitcom about several
affluent African-American women, led by Tracee Ross, Diana's
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Hughleys'' (9 p.m. Mondays), the sitcom starring D.L.
Hughley that ABC dropped and UPN picked up. ``I'm glad to have a
job, I ain't gonna lie,'' Hughley said Thursday at UPN's upfront
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   UPN also confirmed that next season, the seventh, will be the
last for ``Star Trek: Voyager.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
