<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9259 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-STRAITSTRAIN-CO     05-18 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-STRAITSTRAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taiwan to inaugurate chief amid `one China' strife
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In Taiwan on Saturday, Chen Shui-bian will deliver his
inaugural address as president of the Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu Weidong won't be there.
</P>
<P>
   But, across the Taiwan Strait on the Chinese mainland, he will
be paying close attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the Taiwan issue is becoming more important, more
urgent, more complex, more complicated and more sensitive,'' said
the director of the political section of China's Research Institute
of Taiwan Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, like the leaders of his government, takes an uncompromising
stance toward Taiwan. He has kept a wary eye on Chen and his
Democratic Progressive Party for years. And he's not swayed by the
conciliatory gestures Chen has made to the mainland since his
election March 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, he is a separatist,'' said the scholar, speaking
through an interpreter. ``He has advocated for Taiwan's
independence.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Taipei mayor's election as president is the most
significant development in the past half-century of cross-strait
relations, Zhu suggested, and it has made relations between China
and Taiwan ``more unpredictable'' than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Before Chen's election, China issued a White Paper declaring it
would not wait indefinitely for Taiwan to reunify with the
mainland. Blood could flow if the island balked, political and
military leaders warned.
</P>
<P>
   With Chen's inauguration nearing, Beijing has pumped up the
pressure. A Hong Kong daily reported this week that a central
government task force was considering deadlines for reunification.
If no progress is made by 2003, the paper said, the task force
might ask the National People's Congress to decide whether force
would be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, China's People's Daily editorialized that ``no
lasting peace'' is possible unless Chen embraces the ``one China''
principle and accepts ``the fact that Taiwan is part of China.''
And the China Business Times threatened that ``war in the Taiwan
Strait will be difficult to avoid'' if Chen's speech ``inclines
toward Taiwan independence.''
</P>
<P>
   China's menacing behavior has been condemned from abroad, and
the heightened cross-strait tensions appear to have flared at an
unfortunate time for Beijing's other pressing interests. While
issuing war threats, the government is also seeking closer trading
status with the United States and Europe. A critical vote on
granting China permanent normal trade relations is scheduled in the
U.S. House next week.
</P>
<P>
   A stony-faced Zhu insisted his government will stay the course
on the Taiwan issue, however. Bristling at what he called
``malicious actions'' against China by ``some elements in your
country,'' he lashed out at the House vote in February to deepen
America's military ties to Taiwan. That measure has been placed on
a back-burner in the Senate, but, if the bill ever does become law,
Zhu said, ``it will do great harm to bi-lateral relations. ... The
Chinese government is really watching with vigilance about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, Americans are involved deeply in the Taiwan
issue right now,'' he added sternly. ``This is not a wise choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's president-elect, who began his political career as a
lawyer defending democracy advocates, has said he is willing to
discuss the ``one China'' principle but will not commit to it in
his inaugural address because Taiwan lacks consensus on its
relationship with China. Even so, Chen predicted this week, his
inaugural address will not give Beijing any excuse to find fault.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, for one, will be a tough audience, however. He doubts that
Chen, who won election with just under 40 percent of the vote, will
try to declare independence formally. But he sees Taiwan pursuing
de facto separation from China while dragging its feet on
re-unification.
</P>
<P>
   China controlled Taiwan for only four years in the 21st century,
between the end of Japanese occupation of the island and the advent
of Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalist government in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   But to Zhu, only a traitor to China would consider giving up the
claim to ownership. ``Chinese people and Chinese leaders cannot
accept that the territory of the country become smaller,'' he
argued.
</P>
<P>
   With Hong Kong and Macau back under Chinese control, resolving
the Taiwan issue has taken on new urgency, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to regain control over the prosperous island already
has hampered plans for the nation's overall economic development,
he said. And China also considers Taiwan vital to its national
security: ``It is a strategic post for the international community.
That's why during the Cold War the Americans called Taiwan the ...
unsinkable warship.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu _ whose institute is part of the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences think tank _ said repeatedly that he speaks for ``1.2
billion Chinese people,'' all of whom favor reunification and a
quick resolution of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion is not so easily measured, but the government's
bellicose attitude does appear to be playing well, at least on the
streets of Beijing. A taxi driver, soft-drink vendors, a peddler
and retirees out for a walk with their grandchildren all agreed
that Taiwan should reunite with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong press has reported China may engage in military
exercises and step up its propaganda campaign against Taiwan if
Chen fails to accept the ``one China'' concept.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's military, meanwhile, has been placed on a state of
``heightened alertness'' for the inaugural period.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu declined, however, to discuss what he called ``hypothetical
questions'' about China's likely response to Chen's speech.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, he said, his government is ``adopting a stance
to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   The scholars with his institute and other research institutions
focusing on Taiwan ``hope this issue can be resolved peacefully,''
Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he added, ``the better the military preparations are,
the more possible it is that reunification takes place.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
