<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-COLUMN-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTING UP A LESSON IN CHINA TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 21)  
 By TOM REDBURN 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meandering through a flea market in Shanghai, China, earlier
this year with Craig Smith, The New York Times' new correspondent
there, I stopped at a stall that was selling cheap cigarette
lighters with pictures of Mao Tse-tung pasted on them. Flick one
open, and it plays the tune of ``The East Is Red.'' I don't smoke,
but I couldn't resist buying a handful.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, another merchant offered hundreds of hand-painted
posters from the days of the Cultural Revolution. I bought one
dated 1976, showing a smiling Mao leading a parade of workers and
students into the promised land. We bargained a bit before settling
on a price of about $5.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about capitalism, but you must admit it has a
marvelous way of turning even the most violent and earthshaking
upheavals into safe, salable kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   That, above all, is why it is worth continuing to encourage
Beijing to move along the path toward freer markets, private
investment and open trade. Karl Marx (remember him?) said it as
well as anybody in, of all places, the Communist Manifesto:
</P>
<P>
   ``The bourgeoisie, by the rapid improvement of all instruments
of production, by the immensely facilitated means of communication,
draws all nations, even the most barbarian, into civilization. The
cheap prices of its commodities are the heavy artillery with which
it batters down all Chinese walls, with which it forces the
barbarians' intensely obstinate hatred of foreigners to
capitulate.''
</P>
<P>
   What does this have to do with today's debate over China?
Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   The choice facing Congress this week over granting China what is
called ``permanent normal trade relations'' _ part of a deal to
admit China to the World Trade Organization _ turns on conflicting
views of how to best induce change in China's authoritarian regime.
</P>
<P>
   On one side _ opposed to normalizing trade _ are those who argue
that Congress should vote every year on China's trade status, thus
maintaining outside pressure on Beijing to respond to complaints of
human rights abuses. The annual vote should not be given up, they
say, because it is Washington's only stick for persuading China to
ease repression and to free dissidents. Treating China as a normal
trading partner, they say, will just entrench the current regime
and encourage its belligerence.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing that view are those who believe that change inside
China can exert greater leverage for reform than any diplomatic
pressure. Through broader trade and contact with the outside world,
the Chinese people will be exposed to the full range of Western
life, from the sublime to the ridiculous. In the end, the
temptation will prove irresistible. Treat China as a normal
country, this side argues, and it will eventually turn into one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Openness is a two-way street,'' Nicholas Lardy, a senior
fellow at the Brookings Institution, said last week in a telephone
interview from Beijing. ``Already there are thousands of foreigners
living in China and interacting on a daily basis across a very
broad spectrum. That will only grow as China joins the WTO. At the
same time, tens of thousands of the most promising Chinese have
gone to the West as students. They've come back _ often to very
high positions in government, banking and business _ changed for
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Visited China for the first time this year. But even without an
earlier point of reference, it was clear that though the economy
remains very basic, the country has changed immensely in the last
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as the early 1980s, nearly everybody in Shanghai,
the most Westernized city in China, still wore the famous blue Mao
suits. Only top officials had cars; everyone else pedaled bicycles
or rode buses. Lights were dim. Public restaurants and private
enterprises barely existed. Architecture seemed frozen in a
pre-World War II time warp. Today, everything is different: jeans
and khakis are ubiquitous; cars and taxis compete with bikes on
crowded streets; glass-sheathed skyscrapers abound; Shanghai throbs
with activity day and night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to forget,'' Lardy said, ``how much change has already
occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   As private enterprise spreads and markets open to real
competition from domestic and foreign companies alike, tens of
millions of Chinese are shedding their dependence on the state.
They are richer and freer. It's not democracy, but it is the first
step toward a genuinely pluralistic society.
</P>
<P>
   That is just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``China now feels competitive heat across continents and
oceans,'' Robert Wright wrote in a recent issue of The New
Republic. ``It must face the same logic the rest of the world
faces. In the age of the Internet, even more than in the age of
industry and print, granting enough liberty for cutting-edge
prosperity while denying political liberty is a tall order.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
