<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-GRASSROOTS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTOM FISHING IN THE CLASS B REAL ESTATE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Conn. Texas, Okla., Calif., Wash.)   (For release Sunday, May 21)  
 By JOEL KOTKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fresh out of New York University Law School, Andrew Segal moved
to Texas in the early 1990s to seek his fortune. Although he
started with an inheritance of roughly $1 million, he felt that New
York was too tough and expensive a place to build his own business
empire.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he went looking where the pickings seemed easier,
moving first to Dallas, where he bought some ``see through'' office
buildings left virtually vacant in the aftermath of the oil crisis
in the early 1980s. Yet as the real estate market improved there,
he had to dig deeper for new opportunities, and began buying aging
office buildings along Houston's downtrodden and dangerous Main
Street.
</P>
<P>
   This made some locals think he was out of his mind _ or at least
a very gullible outsider. ``At the time,'' Segal recalled, ``it
looked like it was just another holdup on Main Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, his strategy of buying old, unwanted office buildings seems
more like a stroke of genius. In the last five years, his Boxer
Properties, based in Houston, has bought some 70 of them, 17 of
which are of pre-World World War II vintage, in a string of cities
that also includes Baltimore, Hartford, Dallas and Tulsa, Okla.,
not to mention Hempstead, N.Y. Nearly all the deals have proved
successful, with occupancy rates, rents and property values
doubling, tripling or rising even more.
</P>
<P>
   Segal, 33, appears on the verge of becoming a veritable king of
the once-disdained niche of so-called class B urban office space.
His method is simple: He buys older buildings, fixes them and puts
signs on them offering space for rent. As word gets around of the
improved conditions in the buildings and of the low rents, which
are sometimes as little as half those offered by fancier landlords
nearby, the tenants come and stay.
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneur, whose low-cost business style includes
extensive traipsing from Baltimore to Tulsa and places in between
on budget flights, seems to have seized the right niche at the
right time. According to statistics from Reis Inc., a New York real
estate information firm, class B vacancy rates nationwide have
dropped to roughly 11 percent from nearly 20 percent on average in
1995. In some key urban centers, like San Francisco and Seattle,
the rates are as low as 3 percent. Even in such long distressed
markets as Tulsa, Baltimore and Houston, they have dropped by as
much as half.
</P>
<P>
   Segal credits the recovery of this niche in the last five years
to broader changes in the economy. The burgeoning of Internet,
media and related businesses like advertising has not led to huge
growth in demand for space in the new shiny class A high-rise
buildings that have typically attracted more traditional,
white-collar companies. Instead, many new-economy concerns have
moved into older, funkier spaces. To some extent, this trend
reflects the tastes of these nouveau companies. Though they may
have originally been lured by the lower rents, they also see these
older buildings _ some of them stunning examples of Art Deco or
Beaux Arts architecture _ as a reflection of their sense of
themselves as creative, non-hierarchical and unconventional.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Segal notes, the appeal of such buildings is not
unconditional. They often require upgraded telecommunications
infrastructure and central air-conditioning systems, fresh paint,
and sometimes the removal of outdated features like carpeting over
hardwood floors to make them as functional as their more modern
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In many cities, such structures also benefit by being located in
or next to districts that are attractive to the young people
critical to the operation of many information era companies. Unlike
high-rise buildings, these structures _ often less than eight to 10
stories _ were usually built to accommodate ground-level businesses
that open to the street. They also tend to have more light, and
therefore less of the ``concrete canyon'' coldness characteristic
of many 1950s downtown areas.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the country, districts dominated by class B
buildings, like Deep Ellum in Dallas, Boston's Leather District,
Lower Manhattan and San Francisco's South of Market, have
re-emerged first as magnets for artists and denizens of hip clubs
and cool restaurants before becoming hotbeds of Internet and other
new-media activity. That, plus the presence of nearby loft and
other residential spaces, also helps create the kind of vibrant,
24-hour-a-day, seven-day-a-week environment sought by dot-com
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where the single people are, where you go to a bar to
meet them,'' Segal said. ``That's what makes it work. In Houston
there are few places for people to walk around and promenade;
downtown is the exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, he said, the movement of the Web-related companies
into these districts enhances their appeal for more traditional
white-collar companies that he called ``dot-com wannabes'' _ those
advertising agencies, publishers, fashion design companies,
executive recruiters and even small law firms that seek out the
latest ``cool'' space to impress both clients and prospective
employees with their new-economy savoir faire.
</P>
<P>
   Other pioneers include Richard Kirshenbaum, founder of
Kirshenbaum Bond &AMP; Partners in New York, an ad agency that prides
itself on being hip. Kirshenbaum Bond moved from midtown to Lower
Manhattan more than a decade ago, in part to identify with the
image of the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are in a traditional area, you say you are a
traditional business,'' Kirshenbaum, 40, said in his art-filled
headquarters on Hudson Street. ``It's taking risks, but we're a
young agency and the area has sprouted up. It's having your own
point of view and knowing your own mind.''
</P>
<P>
   For Segal, who tends to be a bottom-fishing King of the B's,
markets like New York, San Francisco, Seattle and Boston, where
class B rents can now reach $50 a square foot, have become too
pricey. He prefers places like Tulsa, where he has bought seven
prewar structures in the recovering downtown area, Kansas City,
Mo., and Baltimore. Space there can still be rented for as little
as $10 a square foot and class B buildings bought for $1 million or
less.
</P>
<P>
   Segal is the first to acknowledge that these markets barely
exist on the radar screen of big-name speculators and real estate
investment trusts. He sees that as a plus. ``I think the market
will reward places that are cheaper and still offer a unique urban
experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   These second-tier markets, he added, offer him the chance to
duplicate the kind of windfall he has enjoyed on Houston's Main
Street, now that downtown Houston itself may be getting a bit too
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   With the $525,000 he spent in 1996 to buy two 70-year-old office
buildings in the city, he has made money two ways. Last year, he
sold his 711 Main Street building for $2.1 million to a condominium
developer. Each of the 40 lofts at the location, he estimates, is
now worth more than the entire building was five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the other Main Street building, which he still owns, the
rental income has soared as commercial tenants have flooded in. The
vacancy rate at the building, near 80 percent in 1996, has dropped
to the single digits. New Web companies, including SalvageSale.com,
have moved in, helping to push rents from $6 a square foot to
closer to $15, a big increase since 1996 but still $5 or more
cheaper than nearby class A structures.
</P>
<P>
   The ancillary growth of restaurants and clubs around the area,
said Charlie Wilson, SalvageSale.com's president, has greatly
enhanced the value of the space _ a phenomenon seen in other cities
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different, it's cool and it has history,'' said Wilson,
32, whose company now occupies 10,000 square feet in the building.
``If you're going to be in Houston, this is where we want to be.''
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
