<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-JORDON-ECONOMY-$ADV21     05-18 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDON-ECONOMY-$ADV21-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOINING THE FREE-TRADE CLUB: JORDAN CLEANS UP ITS ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 21)  
 By WILLIAM A ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Mohammed A. Halaiqah trip to Seattle last
November was to have been the culmination of his career. As
Jordan's most experienced trade negotiator, he had spent five years
arduously preparing for his country's entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   After a thorough and painful overhaul of its tariffs and
investment rules, putting domestic industries like pharmaceuticals
at risk, Jordan was finally poised to become the WTO's next full
member. As the only country scheduled to join the group at its
Seattle summit, it hoped to attract worldwide publicity _ and
American investment in the high-technology industries it sees as
the key to its future.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't to be. Halaiqah (pronounced ha-LI-kah) was stunned to
find himself trapped in a hotel lobby as the police fought
protesters with tear gas and rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting something, but we didn't expect it to be so
fierce,'' he said. ``We were literally besieged in the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   The chaos outside and policy clashes inside the meeting forced
Jordan off the suddenly truncated Seattle agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting for that big moment, we felt that Jordan was the
victim of the contradictory interests of these different groups,''
said Halaiqah, now Jordan's minister of industry and trade.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, at its Geneva headquarters, the WTO ratified
Jordan's entry, making it the 136th member and just the seventh
Arab state to join. While Egypt, the United Arab Emirates and
several North African nations are members, many Jordanian trading
partners, including Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Syria and Kuwait, are not.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan won some important concessions: Agricultural subsidies
can be maintained at their current high level for a 10-year
transition period, and majority ownership of retailers is still
reserved for local investors.
</P>
<P>
   Most barriers to foreign investments and products must be phased
out, exposing many Jordanian companies to international competition
for the first time. For an economy that still depends on potash,
used in fertilizer and chemicals, from the Dead Sea for the bulk of
its export income, exploiting the opportunities of WTO membership
will be a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO membership was granted almost exactly a year after
Jordan's new king, Abdullah II, had summoned Halaiqah for a
briefing on the effort to join the WTO. The king, whose father,
King Hussein, had died just two months earlier, was determined to
make economic growth his focus.
</P>
<P>
   The king was convinced that Jordan needed to open up quickly.
Per capita income had been declining. Money sent home by Jordanians
living and working in the Persian Gulf states had dried up after
the 1991 gulf war, and sanctions against Iraq _ Jordan's biggest
trading partner _ reduced trade to a trickle.
</P>
<P>
   As the king saw it, Jordan's only alternative _ a quick foreign
capital influx from privatization sales and high-technology
industrial development _ would require strict adherence to
international trade rules.
</P>
<P>
   Halaiqah told King Abdullah during their April 1999 meeting that
after more than four years of talks, Jordan was still far from
complying with WTO demands. After the Seattle assembly, he warned,
the organization would begin a new round of global trade
liberalization, raising membership hurdles higher.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to move quickly: ``There was a lot of sympathy
for Jordan after the death of His Majesty King Hussein, and I
thought that we should take advantage of that,'' Halaiqah said.
</P>
<P>
   So King Abdullah gave Halaiqah an ambitious order: Get Jordan
into the WTO in time for Seattle. For his part, the young king
promised to ram through the balky legislature a whole new set of
trade and investment laws. They had only six months.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As Jordanian officials concede, it would have been hard to find
a country that was a less likely candidate for such a rapid
turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Fuzzy law and lax enforcement had made Jordan a capital of
counterfeiting and patent piracy. Software, books, videos, cassette
tapes _ all were produced and sold without copyright permission or
royalty payments, often for export to neighbors. Media and computer
industry lobbies in Washington and Brussels put Jordan near the top
of their lists of intellectual property violators. Governments
friendly to Jordan warned that without drastic changes, WTO entry
would not even be considered.
</P>
<P>
   Most problematic were prescription drugs. By estimates of
Jordan's own pharmaceutical industry, at least 15 percent of its
patented drug output was manufactured without the patent holders'
consent. Foreign analysts said the proportion was far higher.
American drug companies calculated that Jordanian piracy cost them
$25 million to $50 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pharmaceutical companies here were living in cuckoo-land,
thinking that you could keep on stealing and stay in business,''
said Bassem I. Awadallah, the chief economic adviser to King
Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   But with more than 4,000 employees and $140 million in export
sales, the drug companies were one of this small economy's few
growing sources of skilled jobs and foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
   Mazen S. Darwazah, the president of the Jordanian Association of
Pharmaceuticals Manufacturers, says few of these companies are
prepared to compete under WTO rules, which make patent infringement
grounds for costly trade sanctions. ``Half of them will close down,
and the families of 2,000 breadwinners will be out on the street,''
he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Darwazah acknowledged, his own company, Hikma
Pharmaceuticals, is a potential model. Specializing in generic
drugs on which the patents have expired, and with modern production
facilities, Hikma exports to 30 countries from plants in sites
including Eatontown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have recognized that in order for us to survive, we need a
niche,'' he said. ``The world is run by the big corporations,
whether we like it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   But few companies have the capital or technological
sophistication to manage this transition, he said. Many Jordanians
cannot afford imported medicines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make Jordan a safe haven for intellectual property
rights, we know that health care prices will rise dramatically,''
Darwazah said. ``People are willing to sacrifice for three or four
years, but then they expect Jordan to get the benefits the
international community has promised.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Jordan became one of the few Middle Eastern
nations to be removed from the U.S. Commerce Department's watch
lists of intellectual property violators. Its new patent
protections are lauded by former critics in the computer and
pharmaceutical industries. In March, dozens of American executives
traveled to a Dead Sea resort to hear King Abdullah itemize
incentives for software and telecommunications investors. Jordan
offers high-technology companies a significant but underemployed
pool of English-speaking engineers and technicians.
</P>
<P>
   With WTO membership in hand, Jordan is now negotiating
free-trade pacts with Europe, having already reached agreements
with other Arab states. Jordan's main goal now is a free-trade deal
with the United States, an advantage already enjoyed by Israel and
the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanian officials know from their Seattle experience that any
free-trade proposal will meet resistance. Halaiqah is still irked
by the contentions of American demonstrators that they were
defending poor countries like his against the predations of the
global trading system _ a system Jordan had labored to join.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the fears of environmentalists, of labor, but
they should do their homework,'' he said. ``No country has
benefited more from international trade than the United States.
These people cannot speak on behalf of the world, and certainly not
on behalf of developing countries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
