<HEADLINE>
OWNER OF FUSAICHI PEGASUS NO STRANGER TO EXTRAVAGANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Book title in 10th graf is cq)  
 By JOE DRAPE AND HOWARD FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In July 1998, Fusao Sekiguchi traveled from Japan to Lexington,
Ky., with a horse on his mind: an extraordinary one listed as Hip
No. 228 at Keeneland, Ky., race track's annual yearling sales. This
was a regally bred colt, the equine equivalent of a Rembrandt
painting, and he was no secret; he had been targeted by a
multinational group of bidders from the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The group's members had banded together rather than risk driving
up the price by bidding against one another. But Sekiguchi wanted
it more. He outbid that group and everyone else, paying the
extremely high price of $4 million for the colt that he would later
name Fusaichi Pegasus. He says now that he would have paid whatever
he had to in order to get the horse _ and in fact, he had financial
backing from some partners, whom he had to repay within 10 days, to
ensure that he came out on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I own it entirely now,'' he said. ``I am sure, though, that
many others would like to come forward and offer to buy a piece of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sekiguchi has no plans for the moment on sharing the horse.
Fusaichi Pegasus scored an overpowering victory in the Kentucky
Derby and is the odds-on favorite in Saturday's Preakness Stakes at
Pimlico Race Course in Baltimore. If he wins, he will then try to
become the first horse in 22 years to capture racing's triple crown
at the Belmont Stakes in New York on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a dazzling payoff for Sekiguchi, the flamboyant
Japanese entrepreneur who only two weeks ago was a stranger to the
U.S. sporting scene, but who prompted fascination at the Derby with
his long ponytail and splashy entrance to the winner's circle at
Churchill Downs, where he was accompanied by several incandescently
powdered geishas.
</P>
<P>
   Sekiguchi, 64, won his prized colt the same way he has lived his
life and made his career in Japan: with extravagance, daring and
creativity. In Japan, he is a member of a loose class of men who
are referred to as ``bubble gentlemen,'' a label attached to those
who built dizzying individual fortunes in the booming 1980s. It
also implies that the source of one's wealth is never quite clear,
though signs of it are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   He collects modern and vintage racing cars, and two of them _ a
blue 1935 Bugatti and a blazing red Formula One-style machine built
by his own engineers _ grace the lobby of his new company _
Venture-Safenet _ near Tokyo Bay. He orchestrates spectacles to
welcome company recruits, last year importing matadors from Spain
and bulls from Mexico, another year renting a disco, piling $100
million yen (about $921,000 at Thursday's rates) on the stage and
exhorting his new charges to ``aim high and be a player.''
</P>
<P>
   With his bold charcoal pinstripes or the yellow leather jacket
he donned at one Louisville soiree, Sekiguchi projects the role of
a Hollywood classic perhaps from the Los Angeles of ``Chinatown''
or the Las Vegas of ``Casino.'' ``I am a rebel,'' he said of his
style. ``It is true that I always take care of my appearance, but
my attitude is not always appreciated by others.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Sekiguchi wrote a book titled ``Challenge to Japan
Dream,'' which became a best seller and offered a vision for
success different from the country's traditional approach. That
devoting a career to one company was not the only way to succeed
and even the world's most formidable corporations sometimes needed
help from outside problem solvers. In 1974, he started a business
called Meitec that trained engineers and then leased them out to
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrepreneurs are not well received in Japan,'' said Gen. Bill
Dyke, a retired general who first met Sekiguchi in 1987 when he was
commander of the U.S. Army in Japan. ``People who sign on with a
company and keep their head down are better regarded. He wanted to
move people around, which is a pretty novel concept for Japan. He
had this promoter's flair that also didn't go over well.''
</P>
<P>
   If this high-tech temp service seemed very American, it was for
good reason. Sekiguchi says he has been fascinated and appreciative
of western culture since the age of 10, when American GIs occupied
his hometown as World War II was coming to an end. They fed him.
They told him stories about the States _ including one about the
Kentucky Derby. In 1992, according to Dyke, Sekiguchi donated $2
million to the USO.
</P>
<P>
   Not unusual for Sekiguchi, he followed up this extravagant
gesture with a quieter one. At a dinner honoring Sekiguchi at the
Madison Hotel in Washington, D.C., he insisted that a glass of milk
and a Hershey bar be placed at each setting. When it was his turn
to speak, he spoke of the U.S. soldiers who confounded his and his
community's expectations by bringing food and aid to his town. ``He
said what he remembered most was the milk and chocolate,''
remembered Dyke, who was a USO board member. ``So he asked
everybody to toast with the milk in thanksgiving for their
kindness. There wasn't a dry eye in the place.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Sekiguchi headed down the high dollar horse path
that would cost him his position in the business he built and
launched him on this current Triple Crown campaign. He had been
involved in horse racing in Japan since the early 1970s, but
decided to increase the level of his participation. He asked Dyke
to find him a representative in Kentucky to establish a U.S.
presence. So Dyke introduced him to John Ward, a third-generation
horseman from Lexington, who, with his wife Donna, is a successful
breeder and trainer.
</P>
<P>
   The Wards showed Sekiguchi central Kentucky horse farms, the
Kentucky Derby Museum and most memorably, feted him at sundown with
Japanese food on the lawn of the famed Calumet Farms overlooking
the gravestones of seven Kentucky Derby winners _ including the
1941 Triple Crown winner Whirlaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was moved,'' Ward said. ``He believes in history and
tradition, but he also was able to say where he wanted his horse
business to be in five years: the top.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an expensive climb, as Sekiguchi found out
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the year he won his first important race, the Japan
Derby with Fusaichi Concorde, the Meitec board did something seldom
done in the staid Japanese business culture _ they ousted him.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? His love for expensive horses. The new president,
Mitsuo Otsuki, told a leading newspaper, the Asahi Shimbun, that
Sekiguchi had told him he wanted ``to invest 1 billion yen or more
in the horse racing business.''
</P>
<P>
   Sekiguchi said, ``They were afraid that I was becoming too
powerful, that I was getting too big, and that they couldn't
control me,'' Sekiguchi denied he wanted the company to invest in
his hobby.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, a Nagoya district court ruled it was justified for
the Meitec board to demote Sekiguchi _ though it ruled he was due
back pay _ and cited the horses, as well as his lavish spending, as
reasons. Both sides are appealing to a higher court. A lawyer for
Meitec, Jun-ichi Tsutsumi, said that Sekiguchi was, in effect,
draining the company of its resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Sekiguchi was earning 27,500,000 yen per month at the time
he was ousted, in 1996,'' Tsutsumi said, which about $253,000 a
month at Thursday's exchange rates and three quarters of what the
entire board of directors was making at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was awful. He had just bought seven yearlings for
$5.75 million at the Keeneland sale. He was forced to return them
for resale and promised Keeneland officials that he'd would make up
any shortfall. It was substantial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handled the transaction responsibility and expeditiously.
It is why the people at Keeneland have welcomed him back,'' said
his Washington-based attorney Anthony Bisceglie.
</P>
<P>
   Until Sekiguchi returned to Keeneland in July 1998, he had
little profile on the U.S. racing scene.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That all changed when he forced the deep-pocketed and
willing-to-use-it consortium of Satish Sanan of Florida-based Padua
Stables, John Magnier of Ireland's Coolmore Stud and Michael Tabor,
a former betting shop owner in England, out of the bidding for
Fusaichi Pegasus. The name Fusaichi (pronounced foo-sah-eech-ee) is
a combination of part his given name and the Japanese phrase for
``No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bisceglie said, there have been numerous inquiries about
purchasing part of the colt _ who on the strength of the Derby
victory is far more valuable than his purchase price _ from the
leading stud farms across the world. Still, Sekiguchi shows no
indication of selling. So far he's allowed trainer Neil Drysdale
make all the decisions about his superhorse.
</P>
<P>
   But, as he demonstrated recently in Japan, he can be a
strong-willed owner. He believed one of his trainers, Seiki Tabara,
was appearing on television too much and threatened to take horses
away from him. ``It is the owner's role to be out front,'' he said,
which is another against-the-grain notion in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Sekiguchi also prefers to keep his own financial situation a
mystery. He said he owed his entire fortune to a ``major capital
gain'' when he sold the 38 percent of Meitec he owned for 18
billion yen, or about $166 million at Thursday's exchange rates. He
wouldn't say how much he was worth. ``That might create tax
problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sekiguchi concedes the new company he started in 1997,
Venture-Safenet _ in the same outsourcing niche he pioneered in
Japan with Meitic _ has yet to soar to Pegasus heights. He
acknowledged reports that the company is badly extended and losing
money. ``We don't have any profits,'' he said of his 1,200-employee
operation. ``This company lives from my own capital. I am spending
my own money here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still he is intent on putting on a good show. To spend a couple
of hours with a sole geisha, for example, can routinely cost $500
and extend as high as $3,000. In an interview in his office in
Tokyo this week, however, Sekiguchi shrugged and said he had no
idea what it cost to bring two geisha, a maiko (a trainee) and
their oka-san, or ``mother'' to Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel any stress about the price I paid for this,'' he
said. ``But I was nervous about what would happen if I lost. The
press would just be talking about the money I had spent. I had to
think only of winning, and having the three women there was
intended to be part of the performance.''
</P>
<P>
   He won't be in Baltimore at the Preakness Saturday when his big
horse tries to race one step closer to the Triple Crown. He is busy
trying to build a business, the trip is taxing and, as appreciative
he is of America, he doesn't like to venture too often from home.
His daughter-in-law, Yukari, who manages the 40 horses Sekiguchi
currently races, will represent him.
</P>
<P>
   Sekiguchi barely suppressed a sigh and explained his Triple
Crown experience is as hard as it is glorious.``In the U.S., when I
won, everyone congratulated me,'' he said. ``Here, in Japan, people
just turned their heads and looked away.''
</P>
<P>
   But this horse, he said, makes it all worthwhile. ``When I laid
my eyes on the colt,'' he said, ``I knew he was going to be a Derby
winner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
