<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 PERSONALS: Giuliani Gets Grief Over Sinatra Plan 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mayor  &UR; Rudy Giuliani &LR; 's proposed statue of  &UR; Frank Sinatra &LR;  in Times
Square is not meeting with universal approval in New York, New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The Business Improvement District of the 'hood is upset, says
New York magazine, because it feels the proposed monument, on a
traffic island in the middle of the square, would interfere with
many events that traditionally take place there. The monument was
planned to be near a place where Sinatra first performed
professionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``That place is so precious to us,'' the group's  &UR; Brendan &LR; 
 &UR; Sexton &LR;  told the magazine. He suggested that the monument be
movable so that it could be pushed out of the way for rallies and
gatherings. ``Times Square is at the point where every free scrap
of ground is priceless,'' said Sexton. ``Mobility would certainly
help.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; OVERHEARD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A commoner spying  &UR; Mike Nichols &LR;  in the hallway of a Los
Angeles hotel recently asked, ``How are you, Mr. Nichols?'' reports
Premiere magazine. ``Why would you ask me that?'' Nichols replied.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Art Alexakis &LR; , front man for the rock group Everclear, was
U.S. Rep.  &UR; Lynn Woolsey &LR; 's guest recently, testifying to a
congressional subcommittee about the need to prosecute those who
don't pay child support. Spin magazine, which covered the event,
called it ``typically dreary.'' ``Look, the hearing was pretty
boring,'' Alexakis acknowledged &UR;  &LR; later to the magazine's reporter,
``but would Spin be covering child support if I weren't there?''
</P>
