<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EUROPE-345&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE REGULATORS RAID COCA COLA OFFICES IN BRUSSELS AND LONDON 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investigators from the European Commission raided Coca-Cola's
office in Brussels, Belgium, early Thursday as well as the office
of the company's largest bottler, in London, expanding an inquiry
into Coke's marketing practices that began last summer.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are many of the methods Coke uses to bolster sales of
its soft drinks: contracts that prohibit competitors' products,
sales incentive programs and discounts for certain customers. Last
July, investigators seized documents from the offices of Coca-Cola
Beverages in London; the offices of Coke's principal German
bottler, Coca-Cola Erfrischungsgetranke, and Coca-Cola Nordic
Beverages in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   By bringing Coca-Cola Enterprises into the investigation,
regulators seem intent on examining the entire European operation.
Coca-Cola Enterprises, based in Atlanta, bottles Coke products in
France, Britain, Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg, and
controls about 70 percent of Coke's bottling in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the European Commission said its inquiry ``aims
to assess whether CCE's distribution practices may constitute an
abuse of a dominant position in violation of EU competition
rules.'' It added that the investigation focused on the Belgian and
British markets, and began after complaints were received by the
commission. Pepsico and Virgin Cola have acknowledged that they
complained to regulators about Coke, setting off the investigation
in July.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola said it was cooperating with the authorities. ``We are
confident that our actions are in compliance with all national and
European regulations,'' said the company's spokesman, Rob Baskin.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the bottler, Coca-Cola Enterprises, confirmed
that regulators had entered its offices in London and Brussels.
``We are disappointed that the European Commission felt the need to
execute a dawn raid,'' said the spokesman, John H. Downs Jr.
``However, we are not surprised that the commission included our
European operations since it has a continuing investigation into
the Coca-Cola system.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The investigators remained at the Coke offices throughout the
day, examining files and removing documents that pertained to the
inquiry, which has no deadline. ``The length of investigations
depends largely on complexity of cases, and on whether the
commission's suspicions turn out to be justified,'' the commission
said in its statement.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Coca-Cola Enterprises disclosed that its profits
were falling, citing a flood of cheaper products into Britain, the
bottler's second-biggest market. European Union law permits
companies based in one country to import products from other member
nations, so the bottler cannot prevent the flow of soft drinks from
countries like Spain or Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Downs said there was ``no connection'' between the cheaper
imports and the European Union's inquiry into Coca-Cola
Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's new chairman and chief executive, Douglas N. Daft,
has pledged to improve the company's battered image in Europe as
well as its conduct there. Coke's efforts in recent years to buy
Orangina and the Cadbury Schweppes brands ran into trouble from
regulators on competitive grounds, with the plans ultimately
scuttled or trimmed back. Last June, Coke recorded its biggest
product recall in company history after people in Belgium said they
felt ill after drinking Coke products; the recall cost Coke $200
million and cost Coca-Cola Enterprises $103 million.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Italian authorities fined Coke $16 million over the
practices of Coca-Cola Beverages, a bottler in which Coke holds a
majority stake. The authorities objected to several of the
bottler's practices, including discounts to retailers carrying
Coca-Cola products exclusively and year-end bonuses to wholesalers
carrying only Coca-Cola. The investigation began in 1997 after
complaints from Pepsi and an Italian supermarket chain, Esselunga.
</P>
<P>
   Daft told the British and American Chamber of Commerce earlier
this month that ``1999 e was a pretty tough year for Coca-Cola,
particularly in Europe.'' He added, ``We've said the series of
setbacks we suffered last year served as a clear wake-up call for
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
