<HEADER>
A9283 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ABC-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-18 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABC-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: ABC SEEKS YOUNGER AUDIENCE FOR SOAP OPERAS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is increasingly common for marketers to focus advertising on
teen-agers and 20-something consumers in the hope of developing
shopping patterns that become lifelong buying habits. Now the ABC
television network is joining the ranks of advertisers like Kraft
Foods and Procter &AMP; Gamble with an ambitious campaign intended to
stimulate demand among consumers 16 to 24 for four of its own
``products'': daytime soap operas.
</P>
<P>
   The four ABC soaps, which include mainstays like ``All My
Children'' and ``General Hospital,'' are suffering declines in
viewership as millions of women work outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are there fewer potential viewers at home in the
afternoons when the daytime dramas are broadcast, but younger women
coming home from school or after-school jobs find no mothers or
grandmothers there to fill them in on when Luke met Laura. As a
result, the interest among those younger viewers in episodic drama
is increasingly being satisfied at night rather than during the
day; the WB network has capitalized on that with prime-time series
like ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Felicity''
and ``Roswell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a genre that built its success on generational
viewing,'' said Angela Shapiro, the New York-based president for
the ABC Daytime division of the network, owned by Walt Disney Co.
``We're looking for more and more ways to bring in younger viewers
so they'll be there for us in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if they're not tuned in by 25, fuhgeddaboudit,
as a character on that nighttime soap ``The Sopranos'' might say.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the daytime genre, you have shows that last for decades, so
once viewers get hooked, they watch through the ages,'' said Marc
Berman, media analyst for the Mediaweek.com unit of VNU USA, who
writes The Programming Insider, a daily e-mail newsletter. ``You
don't see that in any other day part.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the biggest problem is to build the franchise, to get new
viewers to watch the soaps,'' he added. ``Otherwise the audience
will be older women glued to the set.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABC Daytime effort, by M/K Advertising Partners in New York,
carries the theme ``Plunge in this summer,'' to encourage sampling
of the soaps while viewers are out of high school and college. The
television, print, poster and postcard campaign, with a budget of
$7 million, was researched for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love the genre because it has a really loyal following,''
said Karin Henderson, principal and executive creative director at
M/K. ``So we wanted to find aspects that might draw in somebody who
was unfamiliar with these soaps.'' The others are ``One Life to
Live'' and ``Port Charles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the ending of certain shows appealing to this audience is
an opportunity for us,'' she added, referring to the wrap-ups of
two nighttime soaps on Fox Broadcasting, ``Beverly Hills 90210''
and ``Party of Five.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign concentrates on certain core elements, said
Henderson, who also worked on campaigns for ABC Daytime with her
business partner, Mary Beth Weil, at Grey Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dialogue is great, so we use that,'' Henderson said. ``The
talent is appealing and the story lines can be a little outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there's the aspirational value to the viewer: `I want to
be like that. I want to look like that.' You're seeing someone more
relatable to yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   So all the ads present younger cast members from the four soaps,
shot in delectable black and white to look their tastiest. Each is
identified with a word meant to define or describe the character he
or she plays; the pithy labels include ``Rebel,'' ``Vixen,''
``Hottie,'' ``Gutsy,'' ``Smooth,'' ``Player'' and ``Virgin.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads use character names rather than the names of the actors,
perhaps because the actors portraying the characters come and go
but the characters remain soap stalwarts. For instance, the ads
running with the label ``Rebel'' identify the young man as Lucky
Spencer of ``All My Children''; the actor shown is Jacob Young, who
recently took over the part from Jonathan Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   In the commercials, the actors speak and behave in character.
Young preens and says: ``Rules? I don't play that game.'' Erin
Hershey, who plays Alison Barrington on ``Port Charles,'' the
character identified as ``Trouble,'' prances, slaps herself on the
rump and declares: ``Watch and learn, kids.''
</P>
<P>
   And David Fumero, who is Cristian Vega on ``One Life to Live,''
lives up to his designation, ``Hottie,'' by smoldering into the
camera and asserting: ``Trust me. I know exactly what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to convince younger viewers that ``the stories,'' as
many soap fans call their shows, are easy to begin following; are
worth watching day after day, week after week; and are a fun summer
escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a daunting task,'' Henderson said, ``but we've always
approached daytime advertising by going after the available viewer.
As erosion in viewership has occurred, we need to try and attract a
different viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials begin running Friday night on the ABC broadcast
of the 27th annual Daytime Emmy Awards and will continue through
the summer on prime-time shows that are intended for teen-age and
younger female viewers, like ``Making the Band'' and ``Sabrina the
Teen-age Witch.'' The print ads will run in magazines like Allure,
Cosmopolitan, Entertainment Weekly, Glamour, Marie Claire,
Seventeen, Soap Opera Digest and Teen People.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be ads on the ABC Web site (www.abc.com) under
the breathless rubric ``Summer-sational Hot Teen Site.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing is admirable,'' Berman, the analyst, said,
``but I don't know if it will help that much. Even in summer, it's
difficult to reach the young, who are traveling, at the beach and
working, not necessarily home.''
</P>
<P>
   One benefit of the campaign, he added, is that it may persuade
younger women to start taping episodes of soap operas or watching
them on SoapNet, a new cable television network from ABC and Disney
that presents reruns of the shows.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the members of the boy band 'N Sync could take turns
playing Lucky on summer Fridays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
