<SLUG> BC-R-DISNEY-TIMEWARNER-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER, DISNEY REACH TENTATIVE RESOLUTION OF CABLE DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING for all needing.)   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time Warner Inc. and Walt Disney Co. have reached an
agreement in principle that will end their rancorous dispute over
the cable carriage of television networks owned by Disney, Time
Warner chairman Gerald Levin told shareholders at the company's
annual meeting here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Time Warner nor Disney executives would discuss the
specific details of the agreement Thursday, saying that it needs to
be committed first to contractual language. But one executive with
knowledge of the agreement said that it was ``completely an
economic deal,'' meaning that it would not specifically address
Disney's demands for assurances about the pending merger between
America Online and Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Disney had raised concerns that the new company would deny
access on the Internet or cable television to competitive providers
of entertainment and information.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks to the shareholders, Levin said that the deal was
a result of direct negotiations between Robert Iger, the president
of Disney, and Richard Parsons, the president of Time Warner, and
that they had reached what he called a handshake agreement. A Time
Warner spokesman, Edward Adler, later labeled it as a ``telephonic
handshake.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at both companies said senior executives' refusal to
discuss the details was a result of the previous bitterness that
has surrounded the negotiations. The bitterness led to Time
Warner's decision to take Disney's ABC stations off its cable
systems on May 1. Time Warner had declined a Disney offer of a
one-month extension in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The move proved calamitous for Time Warner. The company was
criticized by consumers, editorial pages and politicians in New
York and Washington. Time Warner restored the service one day
later, agreeing to an extension until July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the effects of that fallout, Levin said in his
remarks at the annual meeting that Time Warner had apologized to
consumers and regulators for terminating access to ABC stations.
Then he added that the companies had reached an agreement in
principle to resolve what he called their commercial dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The executive with knowledge of the deal said that Levin's
careful language was an indication that the resolution will deal
solely with the financial details of Time Warner's agreement to
continue carrying the ABC stations, and will not specifically
address Disney's concerns about the merger with AOL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this agreement is an enormously positive step,'' the
executive said. ``Whether it's the last step or not, time will
tell.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Disney executives challenged some aspects of the merger in
meetings with both congressmen and representatives of the Federal
Communications Commission last week. Though Disney did not ask the
FCC to block the merger itself, Disney did request that it issue
certain directives that would insure that competitors receive the
same full access to consumers that any AOL or Time Warner company
receives after the two companies merge.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's worries about whether a combined AOL and Time Warner
would wield too much control over access to both the Internet and
cable distribution became a factor in what had been long-standing
negotiations over how Disney would be compensated for the
transmission on Time Warner cable systems of the ABC stations that
Disney owns.
</P>
<P>
   Disney had backed off a deal that was near completion when the
AOL merger was announced. Time Warner charged that, after the
merger announcement, Disney greatly increased its financial
demands, to a point where it would have cost Time Warner another
$300 million over 10 years. Disney disputed that figure.
</P>
<P>
   The money was to come to Disney in fees for carrying cable
channels that Disney owns, including the Disney Channel, the Soap
Channel and Toon Disney.
</P>
<P>
   The rancor escalated into the showdown at the beginning of the
month, when Time Warner pulled ABC off the air in such cities as
New York, Los Angeles, and Houston. ABC reacted by placing
advertisements in many papers for consumers to purchase satellite
dishes to circumvent Time Warner's cable service. ABC agreed to pay
the cost of the dishes.
</P>
<P>
   That move greatly angered Time Warner officials, who said Disney
was directly threatening their business.
</P>
<P>
   But there were indications early this week that the two sides
were getting closer because the ads for ABC's satellite deal were
pulled from newspapers starting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this week, Time Warner reached agreement with NBC
for transmission of that network's stations. ``That move sort of
isolated ABC,'' said a Time Warner executive. ``It helped move
things along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
