<SLUG> BC-AIDS-THIRD-WORLD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST OF INEXPENSIVE DRUGS MAY IMPROVE AIDS TREATMENT IN AFRICA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TODD ACKERMAN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Houston researcher's campaign to change the AIDS
battle in the Third World has launched a landmark clinical trial
that will test Botswana children with a drug combination uniquely
suited to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor College of Medicine pediatrics specialist Dr. Mark Kline
and other team members Thursday announced the latest chapter in
their effort to bring affordable AIDS care to Africa, home of 70
percent of the world's HIV-infected population.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest trial of AIDS treatment for children ever
undertaken on the African continent,'' said Kline, whose AIDS work
in the last four years has taken him to Africa, Romania, Mexico and
Panama. ``It combines drugs that are safe, effective and dirt cheap
_ drugs that could represent potentially health-restoring and
life-prolonging treatment to millions of Africans.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial is being funded by Bristol-Meyers Squibb Co. as part
of its $100 million Secure the Future initiative, a five-year
project training AIDS specialists, strengthening community
prevention and treatment programs and setting up research trials in
five southern African nations. The $100 million includes $5 million
for the new trial.
</P>
<P>
   The overall project, begun a year ago, was born of frustration
that the long-term care and research that has brought great
advances in the United States has never been tried in Africa
because AIDS treatment is too expensive for most patients. AIDS
kills 6,000 people a day in Africa and has orphaned 15 percent of
children in the worst-affected cities.
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter of the populations of the nations in the
project _ South Africa, Botswana, Namibia, Lesotoho and Swaziland _
live with HIV/AIDS and their general life expectancy has dropped
from the 60s to the 40s.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Meyers, Kline and other team physicians made the
announcement of the new clinical trial at a Chicago interfaith
breakfast where clergy from 30 denominations were asked to support
the project. Members of their congregations may ``adopt'' a child
for $1,000, money that would be matched by Bristol-Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   The project has already brought African doctors to Houston _ one
attended Thursday's breakfast _ and Houston doctors to Africa for
training purposes. Drug-combination therapy, previously unavailable
in Africa, can be dangerous if not administered properly.
</P>
<P>
   The new trial consists of two antivirals _ stavudine and
didanosine _ and hydroxy urea. The latter drug interrupts cellular
activity and would by useless by itself, but it helps suppress the
AIDS virus when used in conjunction with other drugs. A daily dose
of hydroxy urea costs only 78 cents and stavudine and didanosine
are also relatively inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the drugs have been approved by the U.S. Food and
Drug Administration, but as a combination they have been studied
sparingly, mostly in Europe, with adults. The combination has never
been studied with children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pivotal first step in learning how best to treat
pediatric HIV and AIDS in a resource-limited environment,'' said
Kline. ``It should also mark a first step in building the capacity
for Botswana health-care workers to stage future trials concerning
issues of critical health importance.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial of 500 children, administered and monitored by Baylor
and Botswana hospital staff, is scheduled to begin July 1 and last
two years. If it is successful, Kline said, it will become standard
treatment in many Third World settings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
