<HEADLINE>
OATES KNOWS HE'S RIGHT ONLY IF RANGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Texas Rangers closer John Wetteland had
thrown 56 pitches Friday and Saturday, and there was little doubt
he was unavailable during Sunday's game against the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   There was also little doubt manager Johnny Oates was doing the
right thing when, with a 6-5 lead, he left Francisco Cordero in the
game to pitch the ninth inning. Cordero gave up home runs to Troy
Glaus and Scott Spiezio to lose the game, but, given all the
options, leaving him in still seemed the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   All that was needed was confirmation from Oates that Wetteland
was indeed unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' Oates couldn't resist saying, ``I want to even out
my mail. It's been overwhelmingly against bringing him in lately,
so I wanted to give people the chance to write me about not
bringing him in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully he was joking, but perhaps the manager is growing
weary of constant questions about his pitching staff. If so, it's
somewhat understandable.
</P>
<P>
   CBS newsman Dan Rather once said the president of the United
States should hold a news conference once every week to 10 days as
a way to maintain trust between the leadership and citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   Said Rather: ``The critical point is that the president must
stand up, stripped of all his protection, and field questions
coming at him from various directions in an unprepared context.
Thus, the viewer can see how he reacts to the unexpected when he
catches a snowball, and, sometimes, what he really thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager of the Rangers, unlike the most powerful man in the
world, does not have the luxury of waiting seven to 10 days between
news conferences. Every single day, Oates has to do not one, but
two, news conferences _ before and after each game _ plus two radio
shows and one television interview. Every single day.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't include occasional interviews with opposing
television and radio reporters, out-of-town writers, national
outlets, columnists and other assorted media. On any given day,
Oates could be asked 30 to 50 questions about his team, none of
them coming from general manager Doug Melvin or owner Tom Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   Few people are scrutinized more fiercely than the manager of a
major-league baseball team, especially when his pitching is going
bad. And right now, given the state of baseball, the great
preponderance of postgame questions directed at any manager are
about pitching. After all, what more is there to say about Ivan
Rodriguez except he's the best catcher in the known universe.
</P>
<P>
   Used to be you'd ask about a particular bunt, hit-and-run or
pinch hitter, or the lack of those. But that was in a 3-2 game.
When it's 8-7, and it's all about bashing, who cares if the manager
had Jason McDonald bunt or not. The Rangers usually score anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Oates' biggest headache is how to use his pitching
staff, particularly his bullpen. It's become a touchy subject
because even when Oates makes the extremely logical move, it
doesn't always work. And whether it does or doesn't work, an
explanation is almost always requested after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have taken the philosophy that it doesn't matter what move I
make, because if it doesn't work out right, it's the wrong move,''
Oates said. ``I'm not going to beat myself up trying to defend the
move you know is the right one, but it turns out to be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there is no right move, not when Tim Crabtree busts a
95 mph fastball in on Jose Canseco's fists, breaks his bat and
watches the ball bloop into left field for a single. Not when Jeff
Zimmerman breaks off one nasty slider after another, then throws a
fastball in some utility infielder's eyes and it's hit into the
seats in left field.
</P>
<P>
   Being a pitcher right now is not easy. But being a manager
handling the pitching might be even worse. There are no easy
answers, but there are always an endless stream of questions that
have to be asked.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, how about that Pudge Rodriguez? nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
