<SLUG> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORECASTERS SAY WEATHER LOOKS GOOD FOR SHUTTLE LAUNCH 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Forecasters on Thursday promised perfect
conditions for a change as NASA readied the shuttle Atlantis for a
weather-delayed repair mission to the international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis, with a crew of seven astronauts, is scheduled to blast
off from NASA's Kennedy Space Center Friday at 5:12 a.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   Three times late last month, high winds at the shuttle's
emergency runways in Florida, Spain and Morocco spoiled otherwise
trouble-free launch attempts. Three days ago, the shuttle's liftoff
was bumped again by 24 hours when winds grounded another rocket
vying with Atlantis for the use of military radar tracking
equipment here.
</P>
<P>
   Weather is crucial for this mission's five-minute launching
periods. The timing of the shuttle's liftoff is constrained by the
orbital motion of the space station, which is whipping around Earth
at 5 miles a second and at an altitude of 206 miles.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, shuttle weather officer Ed Priselac wiped away even
a slight concern earlier this week that fog in Florida would
threaten the dawn liftoff. Conditions at emergency runways in
Europe, Africa, California and New Mexico also looked favorable,
ready for a shuttle if it suddenly was crippled as it climbed to
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The countdown is going very smoothly,'' reported NASA's Dave
King, director of ground processing for the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew plans to dock with the uninhabited first
components of the new station late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The linkup will kick off five to six days of intense activity as
astronauts replace failing power storage batteries, repair a
communications antenna and attempt to raise the altitude of the
orbital outpost by nearly 27 miles. During a lengthy spacewalk, two
astronauts plan to secure a wobbly external cargo crane.
</P>
<P>
   All of the activities are intended to prepare the station for
the arrival of the long overdue Russian crew module in July; the
first resident crew of astronauts and cosmonauts late this year;
and a U.S. research module by early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Construction has been stalled since the first two modules were
joined in Earth orbit in December 1998, largely by Russian
financial problems that have raised doubts about that country's
commitment to the project.
</P>
<P>
   The logjam should disappear, though, with the arrival of the
Russian crew module, according to NASA's Robert Cabana, the station
program's manager of international operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to build this station,'' he said. ``It's going to
happen. I think when you see more hardware in orbit and get a crew
on board, people will develop a lot of belief in this program.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
