<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9298 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-KIMES-TRIAL-ART-NYT &LR;      05-18 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIMES-TRIAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER AND SON CONVICTED OF MURDERING WEALTHY NEW YORK WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 19, 20 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A mother and son described by prosecutors as a
prolific and pitiless con artist team were convicted Thursday of
murdering a wealthy widow as part of an intricate scheme to steal
her Upper East Side town house.
</P>
<P>
   The convictions of the mother and son, Sante and Kenneth Kimes,
was a triumph for Manhattan prosecutors who brought a rare type of
murder case: one in which the body was never found, and one built
entirely on circumstantial evidence. Prosecutors said it was the
first case in New York, and one of only a handful in the nation, in
which murder convictions were won without a body, a witness, a
confession or any forensic evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators said that the pair's murder of the widow,
Irene Silverman, was just one of a number of crimes they had
committed: By the time the Kimeses arrived in New York in June
1998, they had left behind what investigators described as a huge
mosaic of fraud, theft, arson and murder that reached across the
country, as far away as Hawaii. ``They are the most ingenious, evil
con artists we've seen in a long time,'' a senior law enforcement
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews and a review of court records revealed a story of a
tyrannical mother and a malleable son caught in a love-hate
relationship, living a life of scams and aliases.
</P>
<P>
   After reaching Thursday's verdict, jurors called the evidence
against the Kimeses overwhelming and said their first vote for a
murder conviction was unanimous even though the body of the victim
has never been found. Silverman was last seen on July 5, 1998, and
the Kimeses were charged with murder in December 1998 in an
indictment that outlined a plot involving disguises, false
identities, tapped telephones, forged deeds, false addresses and
burglaries.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors said the most damning pieces of evidence presented by
prosecutors during the three-month trial were 14 notebooks with
detailed lists and notes written by Sante Kimes. Prosecutors
contended that the notes pointed to an elaborate scheme to murder
Silverman and steal her $7.7 million Upper East Side town house.
During the four days of deliberations, the jury said there was no
real dissension on the most serious charges of murder.
</P>
<P>
   Sante Kimes, 65, blinked, rocked forward slightly and then sat
motionless as the first of a total of 118 guilty verdicts for her
and her son were read aloud in a packed courtroom in the Manhattan
Criminal Courts Building Thursday afternoon. Kenneth Kimes, 25, who
struggled to contain his emotions throughout the trial, winced and
swallowed as the first guilty verdict, on a charge of murder, was
read.
</P>
<P>
   As the jury forewoman continued announcing guilty verdict after
guilty verdict, Kenneth Kimes turned to his mother, said ``Mom,
it'll be OK,'' then frantically talked with his lawyers. The
Kimeses were found guilty of murder, robbery, burglary, criminal
possession of a weapon, forgery and eavesdropping. They both face
25 years to life in prison and will be sentenced by Justice Rena K.
Uviller of state Supreme Court on June 27.
</P>
<P>
   Sante Kimes' compulsive note-taking, which she continued
throughout the trial, appeared to be her downfall. In the
notebooks, she repeatedly wrote reminders like ``get s.s. No.,''
``get keys,'' ``get signature'' and ``get checks.'' Her lists
included items like: ``when goes to sleep,'' ``blood type,'' ``what
kind of movies does she like?'' ``any exits in her apt.?'' ``is
there a burglar alarm in her apt.'' and ``help there on weekends?''
On another list, she wrote, ``get Lincoln,'' ``practice'' and
``park close,'' references to the Kimeses' plans for murdering
Silverman and disposing of her body.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept writing `get her Social Security number.' They had
in there, `need Social Security of Silverman','' said Michael
Alvarez, a juror who lives on the Upper East Side and is a
librarian. ``There was a lot of evidence, so for us, it wasn't that
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses' lawyers said they would appeal the verdict, but
their clients' legal troubles are only beginning. They now face
trial in Los Angeles in the fatal shooting of a longtime friend and
former business partner of Sante Kimes' late husband. If convicted
in that case, Kenneth Kimes, who is charged with being the gunman,
could face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after the verdict, a visibly stunned Sante Kimes
called the 118 guilty verdicts a ``temporary setback.'' She
predicted that she would win her appeal and insisted that she and
her son had been framed by police. ``I want to cry out for help to
anyone in the country who believes in justice to help us, help
us,'' she said, as tears welled in her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hardy, a defense lawyer in the Silverman case,
complained that a ruling by Uviller prevented Sante Kimes from
taking the witness stand in her own defense. He said that the
ruling would be the main basis for the defense's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made it impossible for her to testify and have the jury
see her testimony as having any integrity,'' Hardy said.
</P>
<P>
   When they were arrested in midtown Manhattan shortly after
Silverman's disappearance on an unrelated warrant for passing a bad
$14,000 check in Utah, the Kimeses were carrying Silverman's keys,
passport, Social Security card and bank books. They also had what
prosecutors said was a forged deed selling Silverman's $7.7 million
mansion at 20 E. 65th St. to their off-shore corporation, for only
$395,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Alvarez, a man who traveled with the Kimeses to New York,
testified that Kenneth Kimes announced, ``This would be a good
place to hide a body'' while they were driving through New Jersey,
and that the Kimeses wished each other ``good hunting'' when they
entered the city. But the most chilling evidence was the notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman's home, which friends said was the center of her life,
now sits empty. Its lone resident is Silverman's longtime
caretaker, Mengistu Melesse, a soft-spoken man whom jurors called
one of their favorite witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman left all of her property, including her town house, to
the Kobe Foundation, a nonprofit charity she established to honor
the work of her mother, an embroiderer, and others in the field.
What will become of the mansion is up to the foundation's board,
according to lawyers administering Silverman's estate.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, one of the jurors, said he was struck by the way
Silverman's employees said she treated them and how they spoke of
her.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Hansen, a close friend of Silverman's who was with her on
the night before she disappeared, said she was overwhelmed by the
guilty verdict, but still haunted by the loss of a spirited woman
who rose from a working-class family to become a generous host and
benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it's a bittersweet victory. Irene is gone,''
Hansen said in a halting voice. ``Just put a note in there about
how much we all love Irene. She was a remarkable woman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
