<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9305 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-RIDGE-HNS &LR;      05-18 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RIDGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENNSYLVANIA GOVERNOR HIGH ON BUSH'S LIST FOR A RUNNING MATE &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush
on Thursday said he is seriously considering Pennsylvania Gov. Tom
Ridge as his running mate, despite Ridge's support for abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans opposed to abortion consistently express opposition
to Ridge, especially after his recent suggestion that the
anti-abortion plank be removed from the national Republican
platform.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supports the plank.
</P>
<P>
   But Ridge's name keeps turning up repeatedly as leading Bush's
short list of potential picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll consider Tom Ridge. He's a friend of mine. He's been a
good governor of Pennsylvania, and he's under serious
consideration, as are a lot of other people,'' the Texas governor
said Thursday during an interview on Fox News.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Parro, executive director of the Republican National
Coalition for Life, said Bush would risk losing his base support if
he chooses Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ridge has a terrible record on right-to- life issues,'' Parro
said. ``Many of us would be unable to support the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Parro said many Republicans would either not vote or shift to
Reform Party candidate Patrick Buchanan if Bush selects an
abortion-rights running mate. But Parro said the Republican Party
rules make it unlikely that anti-abortion activists could do
anything at the Republican National Convention to block Ridge's
selection as a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP convention will be in Philadelphia this summer. The
state's 23 electoral votes are important to a national Bush victory
strategy. Pennsylvania went Republican in each presidential
election of the 1980s but has twice given Democrat Bill Clinton a
plurality in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge's name keeps surfacing because several other potential
running mates have taken themselves out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   Former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, who is heading the vice
presidential search for Bush, recently told shareholders of
Halliburton Co. that he intends to stay on as CEO rather than take
a job in any new Bush administration, including vice president. And
Sens. John McCain of Arizona and Connie Mack of Florida have said
they are not interested.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on Fox News Thursday, Bush all but ruled out retired
Gen. Colin Powell as a potential running mate. Bush was scheduled
to meet with Powell Thursday in Austin as part of a promotion for
Powell's ``America's Promise, The Alliance for Youth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take him (Powell) for his word when he said quite
adamantly that he does not want to be vice president,'' Bush said.
``I understand that, but I sure hope I can count on his support.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush described Powell as a ``great, distinguished citizen'' whom
he might want in a Bush administration in a Cabinet position.
Powell was chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff during the Persian
Gulf War under Bush's father, former President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Other possibilities include former American Red Cross President
Elizabeth Dole; Govs. Christie Whitman of New Jersey, John Engler
of Michigan, Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin and Frank Keating of
Oklahoma; Sens. Fred Thompson of Tennessee, George Voinovich of
Ohio and Chuck Hagel of Nebraska; and U.S. Reps. Jennifer Dunn of
Washington, John Kasich of Ohio and Deborah Pryce of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bush sent a letter to 450 Republican leaders
nationally, asking them for input into his vice presidential
selection, both on individuals and issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give a very thorough look and make a solid
decision,'' Bush said. ``I'm going to make a decision based on
these principles: Who can be the president? Do we share the same
philosophy, which is do we trust individuals as opposed to trusting
the federal government? And can we get along?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
