<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9307 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-TIPPER-GORE-ART-2TAKE     05-18 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIPPER-GORE-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPPER GORE PROTECTS HER PRIVACY ZONE, IN A VERY PUBLIC WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Mich., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT3 and NYT11 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here is one difference between Tipper Gore and
Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's Million Mom March on behalf of gun control,
Clinton, wearing a light spring pant suit and straw hat, was so
busy working the crowds, she created rally gridlock. Gore, wearing
a white T-shirt tucked into her blue jeans, marched arm in arm with
other women, without an entourage and relatively unheralded.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, of course, is first lady, a candidate for Senate, and
an international celebrity. But, if any political wife in America
has been presumed to be her heir, and has had an opportunity to
study Hilary's example up close, it is the fellow blonde baby
boomer who rode the bus with her and their husbands in the 1992
presidential campaign and who broke into a spontaneous dance-like
hug with her at the 1992 Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   But the two women's different styles at the march provided a
vivid contrast between their current approaches to their public
roles. Clinton's high-stakes political ambition has thrust her into
a public life with very little private space. Gore, on the other
hand, appears somewhat reluctant and ambivalent about her public
role yet firm in her conviction that she can maintain a zone of
privacy _ a phrase that Clinton coined _ even if her husband Al
happens to be running for president.
</P>
<P>
   One person who knows them both put it this way: ``Hillary went
as a candidate; Tipper went as a mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, 51, has spent nearly half of her life as a political wife.
She has had plenty of opportunity to consider what may lie ahead if
her husband, who has been vice president for seven years and is the
presumptive Democratic nominee, becomes president. But, she said
with some trepidation in a recent interview, ``It's a whole new
territory for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is reluctant to talk about the public-private balancing
act, but campaign aides say she is fearful of how a presidential
campaign might consume her family life. At times the Gores'
26-year-old daughter, Karenna, seems more comfortable in the public
spotlight than her mother. ``She wants to maintain her
individuality,'' one of the vice president's aides said about his
wife. ``That will be a struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that even as the campaign heats up, she hopes to
continue doing a number of things that she does now with relative
anonymity _ traveling in a van at night searching out the homeless
and encouraging them into shelters, or going with her husband to
the movies in actual movie theaters, rather than sitting in a
private screening room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still been able to do that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's mixed feelings about her public and private lives may
stem from her very public role as the voice of parental outrage
over the sexual and violent content of rock music lyrics, a
self-styled crusade in the mid-'80s that earned her the enmity of
many in the music industry. Frank Zappa branded er a ``cultural
terrorist'' and dismissed her effort as a ``housewife-hobby
project.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore still defends those efforts, which led to the recording
industry placing warning labels on records with explicit content.
``Music labeling has been going on long enough now that it's just
part of the cultural tableau,'' she said. ``The generations change
and people who might have had a different opinion understand it
now, actually appreciate it and actually use it.''
</P>
<P>
   But while she insists on her privacy _ Friday is their 30th
wedding anniversary, an occasion that her husband has trumpeted on
the campaign trail, but that she has insisted be spent privately _
she also lives a public life.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, for instance, she appeared on stage at RFK
Stadium and played the drums in front of 45,000 people at a concert
on the eve of a gay-rights march on Washington. (Gore played the
drums in a girl band, the Wildcats, in high school, and is surely
the only candidate's wife to have played with members of the
Grateful Dead.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asked to do it and I believe in the cause,'' she said in
the interview of her appearance. ``And I thought, yeah, it'll be
fun. It's a continuation of my commitment to have fun on the
campaign trail.''
</P>
<P>
   How much fun she is actually having is not clear, nor is her
precise role, which seems to be a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   She campaigns separately from her husband, adapting to each
occasion and generally steering clear of policy. She provides what
campaign advisers say is a much-needed human, down-to-earth
dimension to the legendarily stiff vice president.
</P>
<P>
   She frequently talks to youth audiences and, having disclosed
last year that she fought her own battle with depression, the
conversations often touch on the darker side of teen life. On
Wednesday, she represented her family at the funeral for the son of
Rep. Bart Stupak, D-Mich. The 17-year-old had committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent speech in Virginia to the parents of gays and
lesbians, Gore talked in a soft hesitant voice about the need for
``unconditional love.'' But she also advocates on behalf of her
husband's causes. At an organized labor event last week in
Cincinnati, she called for equal pay for women.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign advisers say Gore has ``a seat at the table'' but this
is more figurative than literal. She is not involved in the
campaign's day-to-day tactical discussions or strategy conference
calls, they say. But she is perceived as a valuable asset who can
cover the so-called secondary media markets, and when she travels
she is given poll numbers and strategy analyses for guidance. Her
real value, say those who know her well, is helping him relax and
keep the family priorities in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Gore does not much like questions that ask her to describe how
she would see her role as first lady or how she would compare
herself to Hilary Clinton, but from all indications, she would be
in the more traditional mold.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last year with The Associated Press, Gore said:
``With four children and aging parents, I find that I only spend so
much time on issues that I care about, and I spend a lot of time on
keeping the family together.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's counterpart on the Republican side of the presidential
race, Laura Bush, has also seemed somewhat uncomfortable in the
spotlight. She was a reluctant participant in his first political
race, in 1978, and was not eager for him to run for governor of
Texas or for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's appearances on the campaign trail have subsided since her
husband effectively wrapped up the nomination in March. In
February, she campaigned on 20 of 28 days of the month in 22
states. By April, that had been scaled back to 10 days. ``We expect
to be back in action fairly soon,'' said Camille Johnston, Gore's
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just by her very nature, she would like to remain a private
person,'' Johnston added. ``But she expects to be on the trail, she
expects people have questions about her family,'' she said. ``It's
not a matter of trying to be a public person without opening up and
shedding some light on yourself; it's about maintaining a line of
privacy _ certain things she'd like to be able to keep private.''
</P>
<P>
   Unusually, the traditional campaign role of chief family
helpmate sometimes seems to be occupied by her oldest daughter,
Karenna Gore Schiff, 26, who graduated from Columbia Law School on
Tuesday. Schiff has emerged as an influential adviser to her
father, particularly regarding her generation of young
professionals. And the vice president appears keen on grooming her
for a life in politics.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, and especially during this campaign, the vice
president has sent mixed signals about what he views as private,
often reaching in to the family's private archives to help define
and soften his image.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1992 convention, he talked extensively about his son's
near-death experience; at the 1996 convention he discussed his
sister's death from lung cancer. When he and his son hiked up Mount
Ranier last summer, reporters were not informed of the outing until
the two had safely reached bottom. But before the Washington state
primary this year, his campaign used the trek in a political
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Troy, a professor of American history at McGill University
and author of a book about presidential couples (``Mr. and Mrs.
President, from the Trumans to the Clintons,'' University Press of
Kansas, 2000), said that much of Tipper Gore's life was ``poignant
and frustrating'' but also a bit disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a searing experience in the '80s with the crusade
against the cultural pollutants in Hollywood, and she was badly
abused,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``If Tipper Gore really wants her privacy, she
should have told Al to run for president of the Kiwanis Club.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
