<SLUG> BC-STATES-CARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER TURNS STATE STREET LEADERSHIP OVER TO SPINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Marshall N. Carter stepped down Thursday as chief
executive of State Street Corp., handing the reins to his deputy as
the financial giant's earnings and stock price are soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Carter will remain chairman until year's end.
</P>
<P>
   President David A. Spina, a 31-year veteran of the company, was
named chief executive. At 57, he knows the ropes at the investment
firm like no outsider could, investors said. But he has big shoes
to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who turned 60 last month, is deeply respected on Wall
Street. He has overseen vast growth in his nine years as chief,
including embracing State Street's investment management business
and pushing its use of technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to see Marsh leave. He's been extraordinary,'' said
Tom Theurkauf, an analyst with Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods in New York.
He said Carter's announcement came as something of a surprise,
sending the stock down briefly but then up 50 cents for the day, to
$112.9375.
</P>
<P>
   The board's choice of Spina to replace Carter was seen as a sign
that the company's current, successful strategy would continue. Of
Spina, Theurkauf said, ``He's had a long, distinguished track
record at the bank. I think he'll be well-received.''
</P>
<P>
   If this were a war, Carter might be declaring victory and
planning his trip home. He said passing the torch at this juncture
fulfilled his commitment to stay at State Street for eight to 10
years and paved the way for fresh talent and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company has to continually remake itself to stay at the
top,'' Carter said, noting that he's leaving the company in good
shape. ``We're seeing significant challenges ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's decision to retire disappointed many business people in
Boston. A former Marine and decorated Vietnam war hero, he is a
leading figure in Boston financial circles, with local charities
and arts groups, and holds sway in Washington, D.C. as well. He is
a close friend and supporter of US Senator John McCain, who
recently pulled out of the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he had no immediate plans to take another job. There
is speculation he could be appointed to a political job in the next
presidential administration. He has worked in politics before, as a
fellow in the Ford White House. He has deep ties to political
leaders through his military service, during which he won a Purple
Heart, Bronze Star, and the Navy Cross, and rose to the rank of
major. His father was the second-in-command of the Central
Intelligence Agency during the Cuban missile crisis under John F.
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Carter co-wrote a book on Social Security reform, which
was used in Congressional discussions of the controversial issues.
Carter takes a nonpartisan view on the subject but believes
strongly that the system needs to be overhauled, both to protect
the country's financial standing and to make workers more
comfortable in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's announcement appeared to be largely personal. Since age
16 when his father urged him to attend West Point, Carter has been
either in the military or at work. An engineer by education, he
became a banker at Chase Manhattan within days of his discharge
from the Marines. He said he left Chase one morning in 1991, and by
afternoon was in his office as president of State Street. He became
chief executive the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Said Carter, ``I've been operating on somebody else's schedule
for 44 years.'' He said he plans to continue teaching courses, as
he now does at MIT, Babson, and Harvard. And he wants to become
more deeply involved in nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   He can claim credit for overseeing the company's growth from
$912 billion under custody to $6.2 trillion, and its managed assets
from $66 billion to $720 billion. State Street has also grown
vastly overseas under his watch.
</P>
<P>
   What Carter has not relished, he said, is keeping up with Wall
Street's quarterly demands. He complained about the pressure to
report short-term gains rather than to be strategic. But he even
battled that giant, laying out a plan in the early 1990s to spend
millions on technology. Wall Street punished him short term,
battering the stock. But the move positioned the company to handle
complex global transactions at a rapid-fire pace.
</P>
<P>
   Spina emphasized that he would be making no changes to the
company's core strategy but continuing its current path. Major
objectives on the horizon, he said, include growing the company's
business in Europe, building strategic alliances across its
business lines, and exploiting the Internet in terms of services to
customers and investment houses.
</P>
<P>
   Said Spina, ``I see no reason why we can't go head-to-head with
the dot-coms and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Spina, who joined the company as a credit analyst, making
business loans, is only the third chief executive to lead the
company in 25 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
