<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-WORLDCOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPT. OPPOSITION SEEN AS ROADBLOCK TO WORLDCOM AND SPRINT
MERGER  
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The staff of the Justice Department's antitrust
division recently recommended that the government block the
proposed $115 billion merger of WorldCom Inc. and Sprint, people
involved in the matter said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation was made in a ``fact memorandum'' sent to
Joel I. Klein, the assistant attorney general in charge of the
antitrust division, who has scheduled a series of meetings with
government lawyers and company executives to decide whether to
accept the memorandum's findings. The talks are expected to last
through most of the summer and may lead to negotiations over what
assets the companies need to divest themselves of to satisfy
regulators' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The findings threaten to unhinge a deal that was questioned by
federal officials even before it was officially announced. But
company executives say they hope to convince Klein and officials at
the Federal Communications Commission that the deal should
nonetheless be approved. They contend that the long-distance
telephone market is changing so rapidly that it defies a
conventional antitrust analysis that relies heavily on reviewing
market share. The companies say they hope to convince Klein that
the telephone market is changing so profoundly because of the
development of the Internet and its ability to be used as a
telephone service that it would be impossible for one phone company
to truly dominate.
</P>
<P>
   But if the memorandum submitted to Klein is any indication, the
companies face an uphill struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts and antitrust experts have said that, absent
significant divestitures, they expect both the Justice Department
and the FCC to object to the deal, which proposes to merge the
nation's second-and third-largest long-distance telephone services.
Sprint executives have said that the company will sell its Internet
backbone as part of the deal, although government officials have
indicated that will not be enough of a divestiture to satisfy them.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is also under review by the European Commission, which
last month warned of antitrust problems.
</P>
<P>
   The fact memorandum critical of the merger was prepared by
Stephen M. Axinn, an antitrust litigator from New York who was
retained by Klein to review the deal. People involved in the review
said the memorandum concluded that the proposed merger would
violate federal antitrust laws. If the deal were approved, it would
mean that the merged companies and AT&AMP;T, the largest long-distance
carrier, would control about 80 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   But executives from WorldCom and Sprint say the Justice
Department should not rely solely on an analysis of market share
because the industry is changing so rapidly, particularly as the
Internet offers new hope as a vehicle for telephone service. They
also say that one of the clearest signs that the long-distance
market is changing so quickly is the decision by AT&AMP;T to rely less
on its long-distance business and instead transform itself into the
nation's largest cable company.
</P>
<P>
   The news that Axinn was preparing to oppose the deal was
reported on Wednesday by Scott C. Cleland, a telecommunications
analyst at the Legg Mason Precursor Group, who has long predicted
that the Justice Department would block the deal. After similar
views were published Thursday in The Wall Street Journal and The
Washington Post, the shares of both companies slid, with Sprint
dropping $1.75, to $56.25, and WorldCom falling $2.4375 to
$39.5625.
</P>
<P>
   The companies maintain that it is impossible for one company to
dominate the telecommunications market.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we signed the merger deal we knew the government would
take the traditional long-distance market into account in its
consideration of the deal,'' said Peter Lucht, a spokesman for
WorldCom. ``We believe that the dramatic changes affecting the
telecom industry, including technology, the competitive landscape
and consumer demand, will lead the DOJ to decide that this merger
should be approved.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's possible objections to the deal arose even
before the merger was announced by senior executives. Moments
before a news conference by the companies' top executives, William
E. Kennard, the chairman of the FCC, issued a statement asking
``How can this be good for consumers?'' Kennard, who normally
refrains from discussing pending deals and has not blocked a single
large telecommunications merger, also said that the companies would
``bear a heavy burden to show how consumers would be better off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department also signaled that it was skeptical of
the merger when it hired Axinn rather than rely on its in-house
staff, which has approved the vast majority of telecommunications
and other mergers before it. Axinn has spent months amassing a huge
record of evidence that would be the legal backbone to any court
challenge to the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-00 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9317 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-NY-GIULINI-BOS &LR;      05-18 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULINI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURELY, THEN, WE'LL KNOW BY TOMORROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
(itals) 
 
  Estragon: ``He should be here.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Vladimir: ``He didn't say for sure he'd come.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Estragon: ``And if he doesn't come?''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir: ``We'll come back tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Samuel Beckett, ``Waiting for Godot''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vladimir is the press corps. Estragon is the
Republican Party. For three weeks now, they've been sitting on the
road to the US Senate, waiting for this Godot named Rudolph
Giuliani to come along and tell them what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, word comes down that the mayor hasn't made up his
mind whether he's running for the U.S. Senate _ come back maybe
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   They come back tomorrow, and it's the same story. Over and over
and over.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the mayor himself came out and said he would have to
think it over ``tomorrow and the next day,'' then he'd decide.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, he appeared once more and said, ``I have not made
a decision. . . I don't believe I'll make a decision today.''
</P>
<P>
   Last night, he sat for an interview with NBC television
correspondent Andrea Mitchell, at a long-scheduled town-hall
meeting. Certainly, many predicted, this would be the occasion for
an announcement.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani repeated that he still has not made up his mind
about the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Several politicos were heard chanting, before and after the
event, ``I really think it's going to happen tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will.
</P>
<P>
   It has to happen soon. The state Republican Party will hold its
convention May 30. If the candidate is not going to be Giuliani,
someone else has to get out on the campaign trail by then.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as Vladimir says in Beckett's dark, absurdist play,
``Charming evening we're having.''
</P>
<P>
   Estragon: ``Unforgettable.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir: ``And it's not over.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Hillary Rodham Clinton comes into this production is not
clear. The polls show absolutely no erosion in the mayor's support,
either since he announced that he had prostate cancer or, more
recently, that he has taken up with another woman and is separating
from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a teary announcement from his wife _ blaming their
failed marriage on a previous affair the mayor had with his former
press secretary _ the race is still a tie.
</P>
<P>
   And, as in Beckett's play, the Godot character is the focus of
all attention, while all the mere mortals running around _ Hillary
Clinton, for example _ count for naught.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been invisible through all this,'' George Arzt, a
leading Democratic political consultant, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican notable said of the state Democrats, ``They need an
enemy, but they don't have one. They need a message, but they don't
know what it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   And as long as Godot-Giuliani keeps everyone wondering what he
will do, the Democrats are as paralyzed as the press and the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Estragon: ``Let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir: ``We can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Estragon: ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir: ``We're waiting for Godot.''
</P>
<P>
   Estragon (despairingly): ``Ah!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the buzz was that the mayor certainly would not run,
his treatment for cancer would be too onerous, his personal
pressures are too great, he'll drop out tomorrow, the next day, the
day after that.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the buzz has been that the mayor will run, he's going
to treat his illness with radiation pellets, which means he'll be
back on his feet in days, he'll declare he's running tomorrow, the
next day, the day after that.
</P>
<P>
   Some wonder if the back-and-forth is, at least in part, the
mayor's manipulations.
</P>
<P>
   Arzt, who has worked with the mayor as well as several
Democrats, said, ``This is a man who likes nothing better than
torturing reporters and the state Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has invited several state Republicans to attend the
town hall meeting _ clearly a sign that he's running! The state
party chairman, William Powers, has dispatched aides to the
convention site to set up the big ``Rudy'' banners _ another Go
signal, clearly!
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the psychoanalytical clues. One former Giuliani
employee said Thursday, ``If he doesn't run, what's going to be his
legacy? That he was kicked out of politics by a skirt.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and his spokesmen laugh off all these complexities.
``It's a simple matter,'' said one person who calls himself a
Giuliani adviser. ``If he thinks his medical treatment will allow
him to run, then he'll run. If he thinks it won't, then he won't.
All the other stuff is absolutely extraneous.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, Thursday ended the way all of Vladimir and Estragon's
days end:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(itals)
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir: ``Well? Shall we go?''
</P>
<P>
   Estragon: ``Yes, let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   (They do not move.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
