<HEADER>
A9322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-NYT &LR;      05-18 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA LEONE'S WOBBLING GOVERNMENT TALKS OF PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By NORIMITSU ONISHI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Sierra Leone's minister of justice sat
in his office Thursday and spoke of the need for reconciliation _
even with the warlord Foday Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Sankoh's surprise capture sparked popular calls for
his prosecution or execution, the justice minister, Solomon Berewa,
who led the government's negotiations for a peace accord that has
all but collapsed, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are angry, they are annoyed, they have been
suffering for long. But the role of the government should be to get
people to realize that vengeance would not bring peace. What we
need more than anything else is reconciliation. That cannot be
watered down at all.''
</P>
<P>
   When Berewa was asked specifically whether reconciliation
applied to Sankoh, whose men have killed 19 unarmed civilians,
taken 500 United Nations peacekeepers hostage and thrust this
country back into civil war, all since the beginning of this month,
he said, ``To everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered government of Sierra Leone has not said what it
plans to do with Sankoh, who remained in government custody
Thursday, or what kind of role, if any, he will have in the
country's future. The peace accord signed in July 1999 had granted
him amnesty for his actions before then, and had promised him a
role in a power-sharing government.
</P>
<P>
   But Berewa's comments Thursday underlined the weakness of a
government that is at the mercy of outside forces _ despite
statements by the United Nations and Washington that it is up to
the government to make decisions regarding Sankoh and the existing
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the government finds itself in a situation similar
to one it was in last year when it reluctantly signed the peace
accord with Sankoh's group, the Revolutionary United Front. At that
time, the government had no real army of its own. Nigeria, which
was leading a West African peacekeeping force in support of the
government, said it was pulling out its troops. Western nations,
led by the United States, pressed the government to make a deal
with Sankoh, considered by many to be a war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the government still lacks a real army, and its
protection depends on two warlords with their own interests, as
well as the United Nations and British troops. How the government
treats Sankoh, how strongly or weakly it can move forward from the
1999 accord, will depend greatly on foreign commitment.
</P>
<P>
   The government has said Sankoh was planning a coup and preparing
to traffic in diamonds, and it holds him responsible for the 19
deaths outside his house, but it has not said whether he will be
charged with those crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The government ``has to consult with a lot of subregional
partners who have been working very hard to bring peace to Sierra
Leone,'' Berewa said. ``The government cannot unilaterally decide
to change any term of the agreement without due consultation,
though the population would like it to do otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   The people of Freetown, deceived so many times by Sankoh and
terrorized by a campaign of amputation by the rebel group, seem
opposed to any reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.N. should be given a different, stronger mandate,'' said
Elizabeth Alpha-Lavalie, an outspoken member of the national
legislature. ``They should be able to enforce peace. We have not
been treated fairly by the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems certain is that outside nations' commitment to Sierra
Leone will have to increase once the dust settles here, even if all
parties agree to restart the peace effort. If the remaining 270
U.N. hostages are released and fighting between pro-government
forces and the rebels stops, the estimated 45,000 combatants will
have to be disarmed again. About half had disarmed before the
recent rebel uprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe we can have a voluntary disarmament next
time,'' said a United Nations military observer who was involved in
the disarmament process. ``It will have to be enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the city's newspapers and talk radio have been
filled with comments expressing anger at any sign of accommodation
toward Sankoh. And in a turn that seemed to allow the public to
vent its frustration, anger was directed at the Rev. Jesse Jackson,
President Clinton's special envoy for Africa, who began a peace
tour of West Africa Thursday with a stop in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Jackson said Sankoh should be coaxed back into
politics and could play a positive role in the hostage crisis. The
comment was not too different from what the government has been
saying. But perhaps Sierra Leone, the world's poorest country, did
not want to hear it from the world's richest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot help believing that the Rev. Jackson is a
collaborator of Foday Sankoh _ that he has a hidden agenda,'' said
Abu Mbawa Kongonba, an American-educated member of the national
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   And so, because of the hostility directed at Jackson, his
mission to bring peace to Sierra Leone will probably not include a
stop in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   But along with the emotion focused on Jackson, there lurks a
simmering anger against the United States. It is the country that
endorsed the peace accord, and its secretary of state, Madeleine
Albright, made a point of visiting Freetown _ touring its amputee
camp and meeting Sankoh last October _ in a well-orchestrated show
of support for this forgotten country.
</P>
<P>
   To many Sierra Leoneans, Britain's involvement in the crisis has
made America's absence even more conspicuous. ``The American
diplomatic support has been very strong,'' said Berewa, the justice
minister. ``But that is not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Berewa, whose government was chosen in 1996 in an election
considered free and fair, added: ``The Americans are good at
criticizing countries that do not practice democracy, but this
country had set itself on a course toward democracy. So we believe
that we are a good candidate for American assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we are saying is we do not expect U.S. marines to fight
and die here. Perhaps that's too much to expect from America. But
they could come and help us with so many things _ technical advice,
equipment, transportation. The obligation is moral.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
