<HEADER>
A9340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SC-FLAG-NYT &LR;      05-18 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA VOTES TO REMOVE CONFEDERATE FLAG FROM DOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Miss.)   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After 38 years of conducting their state's business
under the Confederate battle flag, the two houses of the South
Carolina General Assembly voted Thursday to remove it from the
Capitol dome and their chambers. At noon on July 1, South Carolina
will become the last state to remove the old symbol of secession
from its seat of government.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate vote was 37-8; the House vote was closer, 66-43.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, Jesus, thank you,'' state Sen. J. Verne Smith, a
white Democrat , said on the floor of the Senate, reflecting that
body's relief after so many years of fatigue and bitterness over
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill, which Gov. Jim Hodges, a Democrat, said he would
sign as early as next week, will not put an end to the racial
division that the flag has caused. To capture the support of the
flag's backers, the bill calls for a smaller version of it to be
flown atop a 30-foot pole in front of the Capitol, next to a
slightly taller monument to slain Confederate soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   That setting as well is too prominent for most of the 26 black
members of the House, only four of whom voted for the measure. The
NAACP has said it will not lift its tourism boycott of the state,
and may even expand it to discourage filmmaking and organized-labor
events in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Black officials are by no means unanimous in opposition,
however. Six of the seven black senators voted for the bill, and
several joined their white colleagues in calling the vote a
historic moment for race relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now all of South Carolina can be a part of a great day, of a
great coming together of our citizens,'' said state Sen. Robert
Ford, a black Democrat. ``All of us should be proud, and I think
the coming together of the members of the General Assembly should
be the coming together of every citizen in South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   The flag has flown on the dome, beneath the American and South
Carolina flags, since 1962, when it was raised by the Legislature,
then all-white, for a Civil War centennial and to send a clear
message of defiance to the growing civil rights movement. Over the
years, leading blacks, many elected officials and one former
governor, David Beasley, have repeatedly called for its removal as
an offensive reminder of the slavery era, while white lawmakers
have kept it flying as an emblem of Southern heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The issue reached a fever pitch in the last year, after the
NAACP announced its boycott and the presidential candidates weighed
in, with the Democratic contenders calling for the flag's removal
and Republicans declining to take a position.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle, which has recently overshadowed almost every other
policy issue in South Carolina, became so intense because it
perfectly embodied a large political gulf between the races there
that has persisted since Reconstruction. Blacks have long felt that
they are barely tolerated as political equals, and have seen every
reference to ``Southern heritage'' as scarcely veiled nostalgia for
the days of white supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That flag represents the Confederacy that enslaved, exploited,
murdered, raped and killed our people for over 300 years,'' said
Rep. Joseph H. Neal, a black Baptist minister, in explaining
Thursday why he and others would not vote to move the flag to the
Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   White legislators, on the other hand, maintained that the flag
was a legitimate expression of reverence for ancestors who died
fighting for the South, and said they resented being lumped
together with Klansmen and other racists who have embraced the flag
for their own purposes. But many made clear as well that they had
chafed over the years at the growth of affirmative action and other
policies sought by black residents, and considered the flag a last
remnant of a vanishing nobility.
</P>
<P>
   Many formerly hard-line flag supporters voted for the bill,
partly because they believed the flag's presence was hurting the
state economically, and because they considered the Confederate
monument to be an acceptable alternative setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was equally hard for both sides to take this step,'' said
state Sen. Glenn F. McConnell, a Charleston lawyer who owns a
gallery that sells Confederate memorabilia. ``Both sides had to
bleed on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a few flag supporters in the House who opposed the
plan tried to make the flag's new position even more prominent by
raising the height of the flagpole to 30 feet, 10 feet higher than
called for in the original compromise, forged in the Senate. This
last act of defiance, which the Senate was forced to swallow
Thursday for the sake of passage, helped persuade the NAACP to
continue its boycott. Kweisi Mfume, the organization's president,
said on Tuesday that the move was a ``slap in the face'' to those
who wanted to end racial division in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Hodges, who had long pushed for any compromise that would
move the flag off the dome, predicted Thursday that the boycott
would soon fizzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be differences about the final resolution,'' he said
in an interview, ``but what people will remember at the end of the
day is that the flag came down. Like other states, we're moving the
flag to a historical monument, and we will no longer be the only
state with the flag on our dome. And I think people will see that
as a major step forward for South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   The brunt of national attention on the Confederate issue is now
likely to turn to Georgia and Mississippi, both of which
incorporate the Southern-cross design of the battle flag in their
own state flags. Efforts have begun in both states to change those
flags in legislative sessions next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
