</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTS FLARE AS BELGRADE TAKES CONTROL OF TV STATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ About 20,000 people gathered again
Thursday night to protest the Serbian government's seizure of the
main opposition television station here, Studio B, but as they were
dispersing, policemen in riot gear charged them.
</P>
<P>
   There were clashes with the demonstrators, some of whom then
threw stones and homemade firebombs at the police, who responded in
turn with truncheons and a lavish use of tear gas. At least 19
people were hurt, beaten by the police, and ambulances picked them
up at City Hall, where once again opposition political leaders
conferred with one another but did not address the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   There were smaller rallies Thursday night in other Serbian towns
controlled by the opposition, including Kragujevac, Nis, Cacak,
Smederevo, Uzice and Novi Sad. In Nis, protesters reportedly beat
some local legislators of the Socialist Party of Yugoslavia's
president, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, the continuing absence of the leader of the Serbian
Renewal Movement, Vuk Draskovic, became a topic of increased
discussion. Belgrade is controlled by Draskovic's party, and the
seizure of Studio B, which the Serbian government said had called
for insurrection, is interpreted as a direct attack on Draskovic.
</P>
<P>
   A Draskovic adviser, Predrag Simic, said Thursday night that
Draskovic was engaged in high-level discussions with foreigners.
Spasoje Krunic, head of the Belgrade City Council, said Draskovic
was in ``a safe place.''
</P>
<P>
   But politicians from other parts of the opposition said
privately that Draskovic was still in Montenegro, Serbia's restive
sister republic, fearing arrest or an attempt on his life. During
the NATO bombing last year, Draskovic criticized the Democratic
Party's leader, Zoran Djindjic, for having gone to Montenegro when
he felt his life was threatened by the government. But Thursday
night, Djindjic refused to comment on Draskovic's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that one reason opposition leaders chose not to
speak to the crowds on Wednesday night or Thursday night was
because they had nothing new to say, and had not agreed on a
strategy, said Dragan Kopcalic, the former leader of the Democratic
Party's Belgrade branch. ``Few people really believe in these
leaders,'' he said. ``This is a serious moment, but there is no
serious political concept of how to motivate people.''
</P>
<P>
   But some opposition leaders and analysts believe that the
protests could grow, given the heavy-handed actions of the
Milosevic government and the high level of frustration among an
impoverished populace.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic is pressing the opposition leaders for a more
aggressive response to the crackdown on Studio B and the
independent radio stations B2-92 and Radio Indeks, he said in an
interview Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have rallies for a few more days,'' Djindjic said.
``But we must find a new concept to increase the pressure on the
regime, and the tool are the city halls we control throughout
Serbia. We've lost Studio B, but we have the other city halls, and
we must invest them in order to create the pressure to regain
Studio B and radicalize the situation with widespread protests and
civil disobedience.''
</P>
<P>
   But Djindjic's efforts to do just that have failed in the past,
and Draskovic's party is not convinced, its officials say, fearing
that the central government could respond by taking over control of
Belgrade's government. In fact, Krunic said, a meeting of the
Belgrade city assembly was postponed Thursday when the leader of
the nationalist Radical Party, Deputy Prime Minister Vojislav
Seselj of Serbia, showed up with scores of heavily armed
bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   For Belgrade's people, Thursday brought a total absence of
independent broadcast news. Studio B ran government material, B2-92
frequency played music, and Radio Pancevo, the reputable station of
a nearby town, was cut off, its transmitter to Belgrade seized by
the police.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the war last year, when B2-92, then called B-92 was
taken over by the state, there was Studio B and Radio Pancevo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there's nothing, only silence,'' said Roksanda Nincic, a
reporter for the independent weekly Vreme. ``I spent the morning
trying to get on to the Internet to find out what happened a
kilometer from my house.''
</P>
<P>
   Veran Matic, the editor in chief of B2-92 and head of an
association of independent media, said that the station was putting
news on the Internet, and that the BBC was retransmitting news by
satellite to some 30 local radio stations and 17 local television
stations in Serbia. But the stations could not be heard in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown has included restrictions on the ability of the
popular tabloid Blic to print its normal press run. Blic's
reporters and editors had been locked out of their offices, which
are in the same building as Studio B, but were allowed to return
this afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
