<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9347 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-1STLD-WRI     05-18 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REJECTS DEADLINE FOR WITHDRAWING GROUND TROOPS FROM KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (expands 12th graf to describe mission's purpose and identify other
countries involved) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a victory for the Clinton administration, the
Senate on Thursday narrowly rejected a measure to set a deadline
for withdrawing U.S. ground troops from Kosovo. Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas had also criticized the measure, and influenced a number
of votes against it.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 53-47, senators stripped a provision from a
military construction spending bill that would have cut off funds
for the 5,600 U.S. troops forces in Kosovo by July 1, 2001, forcing
their withdrawal unless Congress authorized the mission's
extension.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, several of President Clinton's cabinet
officers waged an all-out campaign to defeat the measure, phoning
wavering senators and sending military commanders to Congress to
warn of the dangers to U.S. troops and Washington's commitment to
the NATO operation if the measure passed. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said he would recommend that Clinton veto the legislation if
it passed.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was close enough, and important enough for the
administration, that Vice President Al Gore presided over the
roll-call, prepared to cast a tie-breaking vote if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have been forced to withdraw in this manner would have
demoralized our allies and emboldened those in the region who favor
violence as a solution to their disputes,'' Gore said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen of the 55 Republicans voted for a Democratic amendment
to strike the withdrawal language from the $8.6 billion military
construction spending bill. At least two or three Republicans,
including Thad Cochran of Mississippi, said they were swayed by the
opposition of Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad Bush said what he said, because it showed this was
not aimed at this president in particular,'' Cochran said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Bush criticized the provision, calling it a
``legislative overreach'' that would tie his hands if he became
president. Thursday, a spokesman for Bush, Scott McClellan, said,
``The Senate made the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation revealed the restiveness in Congress over
America's open-ended commitment in Kosovo and Bosnia, which so far
has cost $20 billion. It also stoked the smoldering debate over
competing prerogatives: Congress' constitutional power of the purse
and the president's authority to send U.S. forces to far-flung hot
spots.
</P>
<P>
   In several hours of heated debate Wednesday and Thursday, both
sides accused the other of jeopardizing the safety of U.S. troops,
America's commitment to its European allies and the long-term
security of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent of the amendment is to restore congressional
oversight over the Kosovo mission,'' said Sen. Robert C. Byrd of
West Virginia, the provision's chief Democratic sponsor. ``Of
course, the administration doesn't like it. They want a free hand
to participate in military adventurism whenever and wherever they
please. They don't want to hear a peep out of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics said imposing an arbitrary deadline for withdrawal
would send a dangerous signal of uncertain U.S. resolve to
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, and undermine the unity
and morale of NATO's peacekeeping operation, which involves forces
from Britain, France, Germany, Italy and other nations, in and out
of Europe. They have been in Kosovo since NATO bombed Yugoslavia
early last year to protect Albanians in the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would precipitate a year of dangerous uncertainty and
wavering commitment to our allies,'' said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich.,
a leading foe of the provision and sponsor of the amendment to kill
it.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen Republicans joined 38 Democrats in supporting Levin's
decisive amendment, while 40 Republicans and seven Democrats
opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Levin's measure also eliminated a second contentious provision
to withhold 25 percent of the military's funds in Kosovo this year,
unless the president certified by July 15, 2000, that the European
allies were meeting their commitments for reconstruction aid,
police officers and assistance with food and medicines in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Without the presidential certification, the measure required
that money could be spent in Kosovo only for an orderly withdrawal
of U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The defeated provision's chief Republican author, Sen. John W.
Warner, R-Va., the chairman of the Armed Services Committee,
remained undaunted after Thursday's vote. Warner vowed to offer the
provision as an amendment to the Pentagon's budget bill for fiscal
year 2001 when that legislation reaches the Senate floor in the
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the House approved, by a vote of 264-153, a
amendment similar to the Senate's. But the House version gives the
president until April 1, 2001, nearly nine months longer than the
Senate, to certify that the European allies are meeting their
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   The House version actually sets even higher standards than the
Senate provision. Under the House measure, for instance, the allies
would be responsible for 50 percent of reconstruction aid; the
Senate version required at least 33 percent. The House version
would require allies to pick up 90 percent of the new civilian
police in Kosovo; the Senate version required at least 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the allies are providing 63 percent of the police and
are close to providing 75 percent of basic human aid, the White
House said. The United States has pledged 15 percent of the total
financial support to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The director of the White House Office of Management and Budget,
Jacob J. Lew, said Thursday that the allies use different
bookkeeping practices, which ``could prevent certification of
numeric burden-sharing shares.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitment of American forces aboard should not rest on
mechanical formulas and record-keeping technicalities,'' Lew said
in a letter to the Senate Democratic leader, Tom Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   Lew said he would recommend that Clinton veto any bill that
contained the burden-sharing provisions, setting up a clash between
the administration and both chambers of Congress, if Warner carries
out his plan to tack the measure onto the Pentagon budget bill.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It seemed almost certain Thursday night that the fight over U.S.
military involvement in the Balkans would not end with Thursday's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no long-term plan for Kosovo,'' complained Sen. Trent
Lott, the majority leader, who supports imposing the deadline on
withdrawal. ``We don't know how long we're going or how much it's
going to cost. Commitments are not being fulfilled by the
Europeans, and that's unacceptable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
