<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTING BROTHER AGAINST BROTHER
</P>
<P>
   Trying to foment a bit of sibling discord, Vice President Al
Gore's campaign on Thursday circulated a newspaper article by Gov.
Jeb Bush of Florida that seemed to contradict a plan by his brother
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas to allow taxpayers to invest some
Social Security payroll taxes in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   In an April 18 op-ed piece in The Tallahassee Democrat, Jeb Bush
argued that, because of the stock market's volatility, the state
pension system should put part of its $12 billion surplus in a fund
that would be reserved for a downturn. ``It makes sense that we
take the surplus we have now and place it in a reserve that is not
affected by changes in the market,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides said that suggested that the Florida governor wants
to withdraw some pension funds from the stock market. A spokesman
for Jeb Bush said the Gore campaign had misread the article.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLING UPHILL IN INDIANA
</P>
<P>
   With a Presbyterian church as his backdrop, David Johnson, a
Democrat who serves as a policy adviser to Gov. Frank L. O'Bannon,
cast himself as a champion of Hoosier values this week in beginning
his campaign to unseat Sen. Richard Lugar, a Republican seeking a
fifth term. Johnson declared it was ``time we have a new senator
who will put these values into action,'' as he stood outside the
Indianapolis church where his father was once pastor.
</P>
<P>
   It will be an uphill battle for Johnson, who has raised $412,000
in contributions. Lugar has amassed $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Paducah, Hopkinsville and Bowling Green, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ Washington
</P>
</TEXT>
