u a BC-TV-DR.-LAURA-NYT &LR;      05-18 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DR.-LAURA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISERS SHUN DR. LAURA'S SHOW AS GAY PROTEST GROWS  

</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG and STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, the Paramount Television studio has been left out of
the riches of daytime talk television as shows starring Oprah
Winfrey and Rosie O'Donnell became wildly popular.
</P>
<P>
   So, last spring, top Paramount executives jumped at a chance to
produce a talk show starring Dr. Laura Schlessinger, the
conservative advice-giver whose radio show is the
second-highest-rated talk show in the nation. They scheduled it for
September and sold it to stations covering 96 percent of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But now they are facing an increasingly vociferous protest by
gay advocacy groups, who are angered by what they say is
Schlessinger's anti-gay message. The protests are getting results.
This week, the nation's second-largest advertiser, Procter &AMP;
Gamble, announced that it was dropping plans to sponsor the TV show
and would stop advertising on her radio program because of the
controversy generated by the protests.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, United Airlines said it would not run any more
advertisements for the radio show in its in-flight magazine. A week
ago, the Canadian Broadcast Standards Council issued a condemnation
of Schlessinger's radio commentary and recommended that stations
censor any anti-gay remarks by her.
</P>
<P>
   Gay activists have complained about her descriptions of
homosexuality as ``deviant'' and derivative of ``biological
error.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlessinger, who declined to be interviewed about the protest,
has said in articles and broadcast commentaries that her statements
are being taken out of context. She has said that while she opposes
homosexuality and a ``gay activist agenda,'' she does not oppose
gays.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount executives said they were standing behind the program,
which they maintained would carry positive messages about family
values and would not promote ``hate, hurt or intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   The reactions to the protests reflect the growing political and
economic clout of gays.
</P>
<P>
   It has been far more common for mainstream marketers to listen
to activists on the right like the American Family Association,
which assert that they represent millions of consumers, than to
activists representing gays, a smaller group.
</P>
<P>
   About the only time that gay activists have won a big, visible
victory came two decades ago when their protests and boycott led
Florida citrus commissioners to end an endorsement contract with
the singer Anita Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Boycott threats from conservative activists have proved mostly
powerless _ as when the sales of the Clorox Co. a decade ago were
unaffected by a boycott called by the family association for
sponsoring shows with content it viewed as objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   But the conservative organizations have achieved results by
generating controversy about a TV series or individual episode that
dissuaded marketers from buying commercial time in the first place,
rather than withdrawing commercials they had already agreed to run.
</P>
<P>
   That worked for two years to keep most mainstream advertisers
off ``NYPD Blue'' despite strong ratings in the initial two
seasons; only after seeing how that large viewership kept watching
the series week after week did large advertisers climb aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Controversy is in general something advertisers want to
avoid,'' said Howard Buford, president and chief executive at Prime
Access in New York, an agency specializing in campaigns aimed at
gays. ``The idea of advertising is to pull people in, not drive
people away, so when a topic is divisive or polarizing, you want to
stay away.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason advertisers would begin to listen to gay activists
about what upsets them is a result, Buford said, of ``the fact that
there's a very different picture now of who is gay and what it
means.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Tyler, a gay activist who was a co-founder of a Web site
that has rallied opposition to the Schlessinger TV show
(www.stopdrlaura.com), said one reason the anti-Schlessinger forces
were gaining momentum so quickly was that the Internet was enabling
the organizers ``to get out our messages instantly, reaching
millions of us in our own communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Stopdrlaura.com was the brainchild of a small group of
activists. But now, established gay and lesbian organizations like
the Gay and Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation are marshaling
their forces to join the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Schlessinger has said that while gays are ``entitled to love and
respect as are all human beings,'' homosexual activity is
incompatible with Scripture. She has said she supports the concept
of therapy for gays who wish to change their sexual orientation.
She supported a ballot proposition in California that outlawed
same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Procter &AMP; Gamble, which spends more than $2.6
billion a year in advertising for brands like Tide, Pampers and
Crest, could lead to defections by other advertisers because the
company is a pacesetter among the mass market advertisers that buy
most of the commercial time during syndicated talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount executives said Thursday that no other sponsors had
pulled out. Despite trepidation expressed by some station managers,
they said no local stations had moved to drop the show.
</P>
<P>
   The show is said to have offended employees at all levels of
Paramount, and some of the studio's executives want it dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The producer of ``Frasier,'' David Lee, who is openly gay, said
Thursday that he had repeatedly asked his studio to call off the
show, but to no avail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
