u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-ART-NYT &LR;      05-18 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFLICTING VIEWS HINDER DISSIDENTS ON CHINA TRADE VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT21 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As political jockeying on a China trade bill
entered an intensive final stretch, both the Clinton administration
and its opponents claimed crucial backing Thursday from persecuted
democracy leaders in China and in exile.
</P>
<P>
   The dueling claims are possible because the dissident community
is sharply divided over whether China should have permanent trade
ties with the United States, a decision many see as the most
important test of U.S. policy toward China since 1989, when Beijing
ordered a bloody crackdown on democracy protesters.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the bill's backers say that it appears headed for
passage, both sides are continuing to fight for every vote in the
House, where scores of lawmakers remain undecided.
</P>
<P>
   In newspaper opinion pieces and lobbying calls on Capitol Hill,
Chinese democracy leaders are expressing opposite views about
whether permanent normal trade relations will increase or retard
human rights and political freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting messages have largely neutralized the
dissidents' impact on the vote, lawmakers said Thursday, and appear
to have driven a new wedge between opposition leaders who have long
tended to fight among themselves instead of unifying against the
Beijing government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment Congress says `yes' to permanent normal trade
relations is the moment that China stops listening to what the
United States says about human rights,'' said Wei Jingsheng, one of
China's best-known dissidents, who spent 18 years in Chinese prison
before becoming an exile in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Wei, 50, said he moved temporarily to Washington from New York
so that he could lobby full-time to defeat permanent trade ties,
one of the Clinton administration's top foreign policy priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional opponents of the trade bill staged a rally on
Capitol Hill on Thursday in which they introduced several dozen
Chinese workers, student leaders and veteran activists who urged
Congress to vote down permanent trade ties.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton is also pointing to support from well
known opposition leaders in China and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   He has cited on opinion piece written by Dai Qing, a
Beijing-based human rights and environmental activist. He asked
Martin Lee, a leading Hong Kong democrat who supports permanent
trade ties, to help him lobby Congress. And the White House has
distributed copies of a pro-trade message from what it called an
underground democracy activist in the Chinese province of Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
   Several Tiananmen Square student leaders, including Wang Dang
and Chai Ling, have also said that they support granting China
permanent trade status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that permanent normal trade status, with its
implication of openness and fairness, is among the most powerful
means of promoting freedom in China,'' Dai wrote in an essay
published in The Los Angeles Times. Dai is best known for seeking
to stop China's giant Three Gorges Dam construction project and for
investigating corruption within the ruling Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration Thursday sought to build momentum for
the vote after two congressional committees strongly endorsed the
measure Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Clinton intends to make a short, prime-time
television address on China on Sunday night. But of the major
national networks, only NBC has agreed to grant air time to the
president, while CBS, Fox and ABC declined, network officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly unusual move, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan joined Clinton in the White House Rose Garden to lend his
support. Though Greenspan has weighed in on legislation before,
especially on fiscal and financial matters, the Fed chairman
usually maintains impartiality on White House foreign-policy goals.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, who was asked to speak out on China trade by Treasury
Secretary Lawrence H. Summers, said he supports the bill on
economic grounds. He said the trade bill would have ``profound
implications for the free world's trading system and the long-term
growth potential of the American economy.''
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, some Democratic and Republican lawmakers were
still scrambling to secure Republican leadership support for a new
congressional-executive human rights commission to monitor China
and advise Congress and the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to create the commission is seen as essential to
rounding up support for the trade bill among the large number of
undecided lawmakers in both parties, many of whom say they are wary
of sacrificing their annual review of China's trade status unless
they create a new forum to monitor human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders have already agreed to support
one part of the so-called Levin-Bereuter proposal, a provision that
would help guard against sudden surges of imports from China.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican leaders Wednesday night were still discussing
whether to include language authorizing a human rights commission
in the trade bill. Democrats are insisting that the trade and human
right measures must be considered together in one package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our colleagues are concerned that if the commission
moves only in parallel legislation that it could falter and not
become law,'' said Rep. Doug Bereuter, R-Neb., who co-sponsored the
proposal with Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters scheduled a press conference for Friday morning to
unveil details of the new legislative package, and Congressional
aides said they expected several undecided lawmakers to announce
their support for the trade bill at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitol Hill rally was intended to refute White House claims
that Chinese opposition leaders support elevated trade ties.
Participants argued that by ending the annual trade review,
Congress would sacrifice the only real leverage it has over China's
behavior toward its own citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``China will never change unless it's under pressure,'' said
Wang Xizhe, a gray-haired veteran of the opposition movement who
now lives in the United States. Wang wrote an influential essay
criticizing the excesses of the Cultural Revolution in 1974 and had
been in and out of prison for nearly 25 years before he fled China
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He said that without the annual review of China trade status,
Beijing authorities might never have released him from jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate in Congress each year was one of the few things to
lift my spirits when I was in jail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged a deep split in the dissident community and
he criticized exiled Tiananmen Square student leaders who support
the trade bill as naive. ``Some of us understand the Chinese people
and some of us do not,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
