<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9374 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BUCKLEY-HONORARY-DEGR     05-18 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCKLEY-HONORARY-DEGREE-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YALE WILL HONOR ITS MOST FAMOUS CRITIC, WILLIAM F. BUCKLEY JR. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT36 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ William F. Buckley Jr., a founder of modern
American conservatism who 49 years ago accused Yale of rejecting
God, is returning to campus on Monday _ this time to accept an
honorary degree from the university he has so devoutly castigated.
</P>
<P>
   After the university's Class of 2000 graduates, Yale officials
will award Buckley (Class of 1950) a degree that recognizes his
influence on political thought and his career as an iconoclast,
which began a half-century ago with a withering attack on his alma
mater.
</P>
<P>
   In ``God and Man at Yale: The Superstitions of `Academic
Freedom,''' published in 1951, Buckley assailed Yale for drifting
from its Christian foundations and teaching unalloyed liberalism in
its classrooms. The uproar that followed made the book a best
seller and catapulted Buckley, then just 25, to national
prominence.
</P>
<P>
   The book so scandalized university officials that they appointed
a committee, led by the president of the Union Theological Seminary
in New York, to look into Buckley's allegations, said Gaddis Smith,
a Yale professor of history. In November 1951, McGeorge Bundy, a
stalwart of Yale's liberal establishment, published a scathing
indictment of Buckley in The Atlantic Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Though Buckley, 74, has ventured back to Yale since then, the
honorary degree is the first signal that he and the school he
eviscerated so famously have patched up their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Bill Buckley, Yale became a symbol of the liberal
establishment that the conservative movement wanted to destroy,''
said Sam Tanenhaus, a contributing editor at Vanity Fair who is
writing a biography of Buckley. ``These enemies are now embracing
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The honor is supposed to be a big secret. Lawrence J. Haas, the
university's spokesman, would neither confirm nor deny that Yale
planned to give Buckley a degree, citing the school's tradition of
keeping the names of honorarians under seal until graduation day.
</P>
<P>
   But friends of Buckley _ and even Buckley himself, tacitly _
acknowledged Thursday that he would be given, and would accept, the
degree. ``What he told me was: `It's true. God has finally returned
to Yale,''' Tanenhaus said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Massie, the Pulitzer Prize-winning author and historian
who, despite divergent political views, has remained close to
Buckley since their Yale days, helped bring the university and its
most famous critic together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Yale is giving Bill a degree is very
significant, but I think we should do it their way,'' Massie said.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted via e-mail, Buckley initially responded by writing,
``Sorry _ tacent satis laudant,'' a Latin phrase meaning ``silence
is praise enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he wrote a second note: ``I HATE being coy, but what am I
supposed to do? There are heavy deposits over the years of
Yale-incited/encouraged/tolerated criticisms of me and my work, so
maybe we can leave it at that, that if it's true, Yale is
transcending itself.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Buckley's torment of Yale began as an undergraduate, when he
helped found a student group that published Lux et Veritas, a
conservative campus magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, as the Cold War and communism consumed American
political debate, Buckley published a book defending Sen. Joseph
McCarthy, who had categorically denounced scores of prominent
citizens as communists.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley went on to start National Review, a conservative
magazine, in 1955, and the television program ``Firing Line'' in
1966.
</P>
<P>
   But it was ``God and Man at Yale'' that remained his signature
achievement, one that catapulted American conservatism from an
obscure movement populated by isolationists, protectionists and
bigots into mainstream politics.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Buckley was the most prominent and visible member of our
class, as I suppose he has been ever since,'' Massie said.
``Everybody was aware of what Bill was doing and what he thought,
and many of us admired him even though we didn't agree with his
views.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who referred to Buckley as ``an old friend'' and to the
book as ``a juvenile attack on Yale,'' said it was intended as a
warning to other prominent alumni.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's impact on Yale was positive,'' said Smith. ``It
made Yale re-examine itself and pay more attention to the alumni
than it had in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley has returned to Yale before. As early as November 1972,
he gave a speech to more than 400 people gathered at the Yale
Political Union. In October 1990, Buckley joined the Yale Chamber
Symphony Players for a recital at Battell Chapel on campus, where
he performed a harpsichord solo. In 1996 and 1997, he taught two
popular seminars on English composition. Last winter, he spoke at
an alumni dinner held by the campus newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Buckley is no longer a polarizing figure on campus. Asked
about him, only about half of the dozen Yale undergraduates
interviewed Thursday said they knew much about him. And none of the
four bookstores surrounding campus carry ``God and Man at Yale.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason a student would buy that book is to give it as
a gift to a grandparent,'' said Lynn Winningham, a sophomore
history major who works at Atticus Bookstore &AMP; Cafe across the
street from the university.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Kagan, 21, said he had read ``God and Man at Yale,'' but
disagreed with the book and with Buckley. ``I think he's an
articulate fool,'' Kagan said. ``He's the emblem of Old Yale _ he
comes from privilege and doesn't seem to know he comes from
privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon Brandler, 20, also a history major, said he was
``empowered by the fact he cringes and recoils at what Yale has
become.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a symbol of how much Yale has changed in the last 40, 50
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Buckley influence persists at Yale. Smith recently
taught a class called ``Yale and the External World'' that used
Buckley's famous book as a reference, and Smith is now writing a
book on the same topic. And every now and again, an editorial
appears in The Yale Daily News from a student lambasting or
praising Buckley's intellectual groundwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lack of faith in ourselves, and generalized disrespect
for religion, might be what Buckley feared 45 years ago,'' wrote
one student, Aaron Honn, in a February 1996 editorial. ``It is up
to us to make sure that there is always a place for God at Yale.''
</P>
<P>
   The place that Yale is officially making for Buckley is well
deserved, Tanenhaus said. ``Bill has become a kind of humanist,
which perhaps he wasn't before,'' he said. ``Politics has changed,
Yale has changed and Bill has changed. They have all converged at
this moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
