<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ELSTER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELSTER COULD BE READY SATURDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Kevin Elster returns to game action today. It's just
not the game he thought he'd be playing.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did heavy rains and a tornado threat force the
cancellation of the Dodgers' game Thursday with the Chicago Cubs at
Wrigley Field (it was rescheduled as part of a doubleheader Aug.
25), it altered the Dodgers' plans for Elster.
</P>
<P>
   Elster, who went on the disabled list with a pulled right groin
May 5 (retroactive to May 4), couldn't get his final test because
of the wet grounds, so he'll do that in a simulated game today in
Miami before the Dodgers face the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, Elster will be activated for Saturday's game
and regain the starting shortstop job. Alex Cora, despite playing
well in his two weeks with the Dodgers, is expected to be sent to
Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Elster will get his prep work by facing right-hander Orel
Hershiser in a simulated game, designed to keep Hershiser somewhat
fresh during his inactivity in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we have the simulated game, I'll hit in that and go in
the field and play the position and do that kind of stuff,'' Elster
said. ``I feel fine. I wasn't able to get on the field (in
Chicago). They want me to run the bases.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said it's unlikely Elster would be
activated for today's game because they want to give the groin time
to rest.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Elster changes the complexion of the Dodgers, both
in the lineup and defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Elster, 35, provides the power and experience the 24-year-old
Cora couldn't, but the trade off is in athleticism and range at
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Batting eighth in the lineup, Elster is hitting .250 with six
homers and 17 RBI, but he walked 14 times and had a .378 on-base
percentage as he extended innings to get to the pitcher to the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Cora hit .321 with a pair of RBI and had a .367 on-base
percentage, but he was used in an exclusive platoon situation with
switch-hitting Jose Vizcaino. He had hit .394 with Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never came across my mind that I had to impress people,''
Cora said. ``The way I'm looking at it, the level of player is
different, this is the major leagues, the best players in the
world. I knew it wouldn't be the same as the minors, but I didn't
worry about that. It's a different uniform. Instead of the ugly red
(of the Dukes), it's Dodger Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers don't want to send Cora down, but they also want him
to play regularly and that isn't possible with Elster returning.
The Dodgers are also limited because of player options. It's a
tough decision, but one general manager Kevin Malone loves having
after experiencing a lack of flexibility last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Whomever is sent down), it's not a reflection on anyone's
performance,'' Malone said. ``We're glad we're in (this position)
from a management standpoint, but I feel for the player, especially
when someone shows they can perform up here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
