<HEADLINE>
THANKS TO RAINOUT, JOHNSON CAN SHUFFLE ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Dodgers right-hander Eric Gagne's last start was May
7. Thanks to the rain that postponed Thursday's game against the
Chicago Cubs, it'll be a few more days before he makes his next
one.
</P>
<P>
   The game was rescheduled as part of a doubleheader Aug. 25 at
Wrigley Field beginning at 11:05 a.m. But because the game never
got started, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson altered the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Chan Ho Park will open the series today against
Florida. Lefty Carlos Perez was pushed back a day and will start
Saturday, instead of Gagne. Right-hander Kevin Brown will keep to
his usual five-day cycle and pitch Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with righty Darren Dreifort scheduled for Monday,
Gagne (0-2, 4.30) slides into the Tuesday spot against the
Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you do?'' said Gagne, who pitched 3 innings Sunday in
relief. ``It's not that bad. I have plenty of rest and a throwing
program. (The long layoff) can't be an excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   It's part of the Dodgers' commitment to Perez. Other than the
seven runs in 1 innings he allowed in his Sunday start, Perez has
had good results for the past month. He's 3-2 with a 5.93 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at Sunday as being a big concern because
everybody has a bad outing,'' Malone said. ``I hope he gets back on
track this weekend and he'll be able to win five in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE FROM THE MELEE: Included in the many videos and photos sent
to New York from Tuesday's fight between the Dodgers and fans at
Wrigley Field is a still photo taken from Chicago's Fox Sports
camera in center field.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Fox Sports spokesman, the camera didn't catch the
beginning of the altercation because it was panning the field. But
the still image, once enlarged, shows a fan reaching over the brick
wall next to the bullpen with his hand behind catcher Chad
Kreuter's head, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter is at the center of the Major League Baseball's
investigation because he was the first to go into the stands. He
did so after a fan allegedly hit him in the back of his head and
took his hat.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, executive vice president of baseball operations,
said it's inappropriate for a player _ under every circumstance he
could imagine _ to go in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Because of pending legal problems, Kreuter isn't commenting on
the situation. However, Kreuter's agent, Scott Boras, isn't pleased
with the focus of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're focusing on a response to an assault,'' said Boras.
``If we eliminate an assault, we don't have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the players association is keeping a close watch on
the investigation, being headed by vice president of on-field
operations Frank Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   MEETING, LAS VEGAS: Representatives from the Dodgers will travel
to Las Vegas for a two-day meeting next week to gather more
information regarding a multiteam spring-training complex in the
desert.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and five other teams met with Las Vegas officials in
March, but there hasn't been much movement on the issue. However, a
bill that could generate $7 million worth of funding for Vero
Beach, Fla., and Indian River County to keep the Dodgers in
Dodgertown has already passed through the House and Senate in the
Florida legislature and is awaiting Gov. Jeb Bush's signature.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is expected to sign the bill within two weeks, and the
Dodgers are hopeful to have a long-term answer to their
spring-training home in less than a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you continue to meet, it's going to get more
detailed,'' said Dodgers senior vice president of communications
Derrick Hall. ``We have to get serious so (if) the Florida bill
gets signed, we have two things to look at so we can make a
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Dodgers are the front team in the Las Vegas project,
they are the only organization that is definitely attending the
meeting. Representatives from the Texas Rangers might also be
there.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Malone said center fielder Devon White, on the
disabled list with a partially torn left rotator cuff, remains two
to three weeks away in the most optimistic estimation. ...
Right-hander Mike Fetters (right elbow inflammation) is scheduled
to throw a bullpen session today, but he remains a week to 10 days
away from being activated, Malone said. ... Fetters, White and
reliever Gregg Olson will also be examined again when the team
returns to L.A. after the weekend. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
