<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DEFENDERS GET TOO CLOSE FOR COMFORT
</HEADLINE>
  By IRA BERKOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Allan Houston was played so closely by Dan
Majerle Wednesday in Game 5 of the Heat-Knicks playoff series that
it appeared he'd know if Majerle had eaten onions on his steak for
his pre-game meal, or had radishes in his salad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't tell,'' Houston said Thursday at a gathering of the
team at SUNY-Purchase to discuss strategy for Friday night's
ultimate, or penultimate, series game. ``But then,'' added Houston,
with a pause and a shrug, ``I wasn't trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, truly, had other things on his mind. Like trying to
scrounge a few unoccupied inches to get liberated for a jump shot.
In fact, at some points, Houston darted around the court looking as
if he had grown a second head, one that mightily resembled Dan
Majerle.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Majerle hit a couple of late game-deciding shots,
but did so with such difficulty _ one 3-point shot was drilled from
so far away it would have been fair to award him four points _
illustrates the ferocious intensity, the delicious drama, the, yes,
Dear Diary, sheer power, beauty and magic of the entertainment of
this series between these two fabled rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The Hatfields and McCoys never had it so good. Troy and Greece
might have looked on in envy. The Heat and the Knicks have played
10 straight desperately fought playoff games over two years and no
team has won back-to-back games. If the Heat, ahead in the series
3-2, accomplishes this feat Friday night, it moves on to the
Eastern Conference finals. The Knicks hit the beach. If the series
runs true to form, the seventh and final game will be played Sunday
in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   It has been heard in assorted precincts in New York that this
series is less than artistic. ``Ugly,'' actually. Beauty, however,
is in the eye of the beholder, as Voltaire, or Yogi Berra or
somebody said. And what is beheld here is some of the best
basketball that can be played, and under the most extreme
circumstances. Every possession is contested, every step is often
met by a counterstep, every loose ball is pounced upon like a purse
on a sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the Knicks in Game 5 had only seven turnovers and the
Heat 10, when those teams average about 15 turnovers a game during
the regular season. And the turnovers come not so much on a ball
dribbled out of bounds, but on a steal (Latrell Sprewell, for one,
had four steals Wednesday). And considering that every time someone
takes a shot he is covered like scaffolding, the shooting
percentages (42 for the Knicks, 40 for the Heat in the series, and
47 and 42, respectively, in Game 5) are superb. The Knicks,
moreover, shot 54 percent in the second half of the last game, and
still lost!
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so evenly matched,'' said Jeff Van Gundy, the Knicks
coach. ``We've got good players, good character and both teams want
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams want to win so badly that Patrick Ewing, bad back,
aging knees and sometimes suspect ego, is willing himself to battle
with heart-rending vigor. And both teams want to win with such lust
that Tim Hardaway, who is playing on a left foot that makes him
wince with pain when he cuts, is driving to the hoop and opening up
generous scoring opportunities for his team. (And, as a side
virtue, also allows the substitute point guard, young Anthony
Carter, to play with more confidence).
</P>
<P>
   Some, even like Van Gundy, may complain about the paucity of
Knicks rebounding. But Miami is a taller team, and, except for the
too frequent vanishing trick of Marcus Camby, is scrambling for the
ricochets. Van Gundy, in his heart, understands. And the thing
always to expect when these two teams meet in the playoffs is the
unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   One day the Heat shoots free throws as though aiming at a moving
target. Then Carter, a refugee from the Atlanta playgrounds, hits a
game-winner that soars from behind the basket, the ball looking,
for a moment, like it was a bag of peanuts flung from a vendor in
the nearby aisle. Then Charlie Ward woke up the other morning and
thought he was Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in the middle of this thing,'' said Sprewell,
``it's hard to appreciate it like a fan. But, as a player, this
kind of hard fighting is fun. It's what you dream about as a kid in
the playgrounds. It's exciting to compete on this level. In the
playoffs the stakes are higher than the regular season, every play
is crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy, meanwhile, had his car destroyed when a large amount
of thrust emitted from one engine of the private plane carrying the
team from Miami to Westchester and lifted his Honda Civic and
caused it to roll over several staff and player cars. How did he
feel? ``Who cares,'' he said. ``We lost. If we had won, I'd have
been happy to walk back from Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about playoff intensity.
</P>
</TEXT>
