<SLUG> BC-BIKERS-UNION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIKE MESSENGERS WHEEL AND DEAL FOR UNION VICTORY  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco bike messengers, who have long
complained of hard work, low pay and scant benefits, scored a rare
win this week as workers at one delivery company agreed to the
first union contract in nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than deal with a unionized workforce of 38
messengers, that company, UltraEx, said Thursday that it will
respond by selling off its San Francisco operation to local
managers.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how these moves will affect efforts to unionize the
Bay Area's courier services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will tell,'' said Howard Williams, an UltraEx messenger
and former president of the San Francisco Bike Messenger
Association. ``We hope it will advance things in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Other couriers watched closely as UltraEx bargained with union
representatives for nearly nine months in what both sides termed
``very tough'' negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Pecker, an International Longshore and Warehouse Union
agent who led the talks on behalf of messengers, said he is
confident that other couriers will now feel emboldened to seek
union representation.
</P>
<P>
   But Sal Grassia, chief executive officer of UltraEx, said owners
of other firms will similarly resist unionization. ``They're very
concerned about this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   UltraEx workers voted 22 to 1 to ratify a union contract _ the
first time a San Francisco messenger company has done so since the
Teamsters briefly represented workers at a now-defunct service in
the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The contract takes effect June 1.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ILWU, UltraEx bike messengers will see
commissions for each delivery rise from about 38 percent of each
bill to 40.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Foot messengers will see raises of between 80 cents and $1.50 an
hour, while drivers will be guaranteed 41 percent commissions. All
messengers will receive printouts of delivery bills so they can
verify their commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Bike couriers will receive $7 a day to maintain their equipment,
and drivers will be reimbursed for parking, bridge tolls and
mileage.
</P>
<P>
   UltraEx also agreed to give messengers a floating holiday each
year and to include domestic partners in employee health plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a first contract, that's a big milestone,'' said
Peter Olney, ILWU's director of organizing. ``We're already
actively organizing at other companies.''
</P>
<P>
   However, industry sources said it won't be easy to bring other
companies into the union fold. While San Francisco's bike
messengers have been most vocal about the need for representation,
they represent only about 15 percent of the courier business.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of BIKERS19 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Vehicle drivers comprise the majority of messengers, and they
have been less eager to confront employers through collective
bargaining. That's because the drivers make more money than their
cycling counterparts due to the longer distances traveled and
larger delivery bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have to prove to the rest of the industry that we can
be a viable, union-organized company,'' UltraEx's Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   But Grassia, the company's CEO, described his employees' embrace
of the ILWU as an act of ``betrayal and disrespect,'' and said
UltraEx had already provided workers with ``one of the best
benefits packages in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The average messenger at UltraEx is making $14 an hour,'' he
said. ``That's a lot of money. We're not talking about skilled
labor here. We're not talking about computer wizards.''
</P>
<P>
   The average messenger, who must bring an array of skills to
traversing frequently hostile terrain in the shortest possible
time, might dispute that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Grassia said the only thing that UltraEx employees have
gotten for their trouble is ``monthly dues and another layer of
bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that while UltraEx will still operate in San Francisco,
its union-represented messengers will belong to a new company, to
be called Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ILWU officials said they are hopeful that an outfit called
Professional Messenger will be the next courier service to seek a
union contract and are looking as well at DMS Corp., where
messengers staged a weeklong strike for higher wages in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more strikes,'' the union's Olney predicted.
``The strike is once again our friend.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
