<SLUG> BC-JDS-RETIRE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FIBER-OPTICS EXECUTIVE OPTS TO RETIRE  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ JDS Uniphase chief executive Kevin Kalkhoven
abruptly retired Thursday, saying he was burnt out from putting in
years of 100-hour weeks at the San Jose fiber-optics parts maker,
which has quietly become one of the heftiest tech companies in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been nine years of high-intensity activity (and) it
has been a fairly stressful environment,'' Kalkhoven, 55, said in a
conference call with analysts, adding that he has spent only about
six full weekends at home on the Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Kalkhoven, a veteran computer company executive who grew up in
Australia and England, said his doctor advised him to take a
medical leave because of his high blood pressure, but he decided to
step aside instead. He said he plans to remain with JDS as a
part-time consultant, but will also start a venture-capital fund to
invest in communications startups and work with some private
endowments and trusts.
</P>
<P>
   Jozef Straus, 53, who has already been running the company's
day-to-day operations as president and co-chairman, will take
Kalkhoven's place as chief executive. Charles Abbe, the company's
senior operating officer, was promoted to president and chief
operating officer. JDS Uniphase shares, which have soared more than
fivefold over the past 12 months, slipped $5.96, to $86.56,
yesterday on concerns about the management change.
</P>
<P>
   But Straus, known for sporting a beret, also has a strong track
record in the industry, analysts pointed out. Straus co-founded and
ran JDS Fitel, the Canadian fiber-optics components manufacturer
that San Jose's Uniphase merged with last year. JDS Fitel had
revenues of $227 million for fiscal year 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jozef Straus has a proven track record of being able to build
a big, strong optics company,'' said PaineWebber analyst David
Wong. ``The new regime will be just as good as the old regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Straus said he plans to remain in Ottawa, but executives said
the company will keep its second headquarters in San Jose. ``I will
be moving on planes left and right,'' Straus said during the call.
</P>
<P>
   The change comes at a time when JDS and other fiber-optics
components-makers are struggling to keep up with demand from
telecommunications equipment-makers like Nortel Networks and Lucent
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel and Lucent's customers, phone companies and Internet
service providers, are rapidly bolstering their networks by using
packets of light instead of electrons to move mountains of data at
lightning speeds. JDS has ridden that wave.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which had only about 1,000 workers a year ago, now
claims 13,100 employees and a stock market value of $70 billion,
slightly behind Yahoo's $72 billion, but well ahead of better-known
local brands like the Gap, Wells Fargo and eBay.
</P>
<P>
   And Chief Financial Officer Anthony Muller said there's no sign
of a slowdown. He predicted sales will jump 80 percent during the
next quarter, compared with the same period a year ago, up from the
75 percent growth forecast just a month ago. JDS is the largest
independent maker of fiber-optics components, including tiny lasers
smaller than the tip of a ballpoint pen, used to make optical
networks.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the company agreed to spend $15 billion buying E-Tek
Dynamics, another fiber-optics partsmaker in San Jose. Although the
deal is undergoing heavy scrutiny by the U.S. Justice Department,
Kalkhoven said he is optimistic it will go through.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Kalkhoven, who spends his free time piloting a
small jet and skiing, said he is looking forward to some rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to take some time to get what's left of this body
in some shape that vaguely resembles humanity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
