<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEGASUS' NOT YET READY FOR HIS CLOSE-UP
</HEADLINE>
  By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Despite his trainer's best efforts, all eyes fell on
Fusaichi Pegasus Thursday as the Kentucky Derby winner stretched
his legs at Pimlico Race Course and cantered on the track in his
first exercise for Saturday's Preakness Stakes. The trainer, Neil
Drysdale, shielding his star right up to the starting gate, even
said he would saddle Fusaichi Pegasus in the inside paddock before
the race to avoid the crowd in the outside saddling ring.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus has had a history of balky and unpredictable
behavior, although he comported himself with professional calm in
the Derby. Still, Drysdale was taking no chances. He elected to
avoid the Preakness Barn behind the grandstand where his horse's
seven rivals are stabled, and instead chose to keep him in Barn 7,
across the track on the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale, a cultivated Englishman and a man of few words,
reported that he had studied tapes of the Derby extensively and
agreed that Pegasus ``did have a very clean trip.'' When he was
asked if he was concerned that the other jockeys would try to make
things more difficult for his horse, he replied: ``No.'' Why?
``Because he's got an outside post.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus drew the No. 7 post in a field of eight, and
was made the 3-5 favorite. His trainer suggested that he should be
closer to the lead than in the Derby, where he was 15th rounding
the first turn. But was he confident?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never confident,'' Drysdale replied. ``I might be
optimistic, but not confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment, the last horse to arrive at Pimlico for the
Preakness, made it in at 9:15 a.m. Thursday after a van trip from
Belmont Park in New York that started at 4:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The colt, third in the Arkansas Derby and third in the Kentucky
Derby, had an uneventful trip. His trainer, Todd Pletcher, who
started four horses in the Kentucky Derby, arrived Thursday
afternoon from Ocala, Fla., to tend his one horse in this race.
</P>
<P>
   One new story line involves Snuck In, second in the Arkansas
Derby, who is trained by Steve Asmussen and will be ridden by the
trainer's brother, Cash Asmussen, a top jockey in Europe for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cash will be flying in from France later today,'' Steve said
Thursday morning. ``This will be my first starter in a Triple Crown
race, and it's great my brother can ride him. He rode one of my
first winners when I started training about 12 years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
