<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: REFORMERS' MAJORITY
</P>
<P>
   Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, intervened hours
before the hard-line Guardian Council was to decide whether to void
the results in Tehran parliamentary elections held last February
because of fraud. He advised the council only to invalidate boxes
where it found discrepancies but to endorse the election of those
candidates whose victories were certain. Pro-reform candidates won
29 of Tehran's 30 seats, giving reformers a majority in the
290-seat Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: DELAY IN ULSTER
</P>
<P>
   Hopes of restarting the suspended power-sharing government in
Belfast next week were dashed as the Ulster Unionist leader, David
Trimble, called off a Saturday meeting of his ruling council that
was to take up an Irish Republican Army offer to permit inspection
of its arms dumps. Trimble believes he needs another week to
persuade his party to support a decision to go back into the
government with Sinn Fein, the political allies of the IRA. The
meeting will now be held on May 27.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: ANOTHER SMOKING BAN
</P>
<P>
   The newly appointed health minister, Umberto Veronesi, a cancer
specialist, presented a plan to ban smoking in all public places,
including bars and discos. Veronesi faces an uphill battle.
Parliament passed laws banning smoking in all public places in 1975
and again in 1996. They are widely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: FUND FOR JEWS
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel said Austria will start examining
ways to create a new compensation fund for Jews stripped of
property under the Nazis. Schuessel said he had discussed the
proposal with his deputy, Susanne Riess-Passer of the far-right
Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: DEAD HEAT
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida and Vicente Fox, the two leading
presidential candidates, are in a virtual tie, and in recent days
both have lost ground to the man in third-place, Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas, according to a national poll published by the newspaper
Reforma. Labastida was favored by 42 percent, Fox by 40 percent and
Cardenas by 16 percent, according to the poll, based on interviews
with 1,547 potential voters in 32 states. The margin of error was
2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: GENERAL JAILED
</P>
<P>
   An army general who was made a high-ranking security official in
Chiapas state was sentenced to eight years in jail for criminal
negligence in the December 1997 killing of 45 Indian villagers.
Gen. Julio Cesar Santiago Diaz was posted only a few hundred feet
away from the site when the shootings were taking place and did
nothing to stop them, the attorney general said. Two other senior
state security officials received the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: HESITANT DONORS
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has appealed for $1.8 million to assist
hundreds of thousands of drought victims in the country's southern
provinces, but so far donors have contributed little money, many of
them criticizing the Taliban for spending too much on war.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: TAX RESISTANCE
</P>
<P>
   Retailers are planning a strike against plans to tax them,
presenting Gen. Pervez Musharraf, the nation's leader who seized
power in a coup last year, with the same problem his elected
predecessor, Nawaz Sharif, faced when trying to implement a similar
revenue plan.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: U.N. LAND PROGRAM
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is offering to help Zimbabwe design a land
redistribution program without the political tension and violence
that has led to recent illegal seizures of farmland. Agreement to
resolve the problem peacefully is necessary if Zimbabwe hopes to
get help from foreign donors, the organization said.
</P>
</TEXT>
