 RAISE OFFER TO JANITORS IS HALF OF REQUEST  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The 12 contractors that employ the unionized
janitors on the Peninsula and in the East Bay are willing to pay
for raises totaling $1.60 per hour during the next five years,
according to a union spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Announced in private negotiations on May 12, but made public
Thursday, the offer would come as a 40-cent raise in the first year
and 30-cent raises in each of the following four years.
</P>
<P>
   The contractors also proposed introducing a two-tier system that
would exclude from the wage increases new janitors who work in
buildings smaller than 200,000 square feet, union leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   The offer is less than half as much as the janitors had
proposed. The union will make a counteroffer in coming meetings,
said union analyst Isobel White.
</P>
<P>
   Most union janitors in the area represented by Service Employees
International Local 1877 now earn $8.04 an hour. The union and
contractors have been negotiating since March 16 for a new contract
that would take effect when the current contract expires May 31.
</P>
<P>
   The raises _ for about 5,000 area janitors _ would cost $61
million during the contract period, according to the contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though similar janitorial negotiations in San Diego and Los
Angeles recently resulted in strikes, the Greater San Francisco Bay
Area Maintenance Contractors remain optimistic in reaching a
peaceful, though costly, settlement with their employees,'' the
contractors said in a statement released by their negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the janitorial contractors did not return
phone calls yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The union had also proposed that employers take over workers'
payments for their family health benefit plan, which recently
increased to as much as $80 a month from about $30. White said the
union was disappointed that the contractors' proposal did not
address that issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're giving us a wage increase that they know very well
will be eaten away by the increase in our health benefit costs,''
White said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
