<DOCNO> NYT20000518.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9407 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ASSEMBLY-DEMS-315&AMP;     05-18 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ASSEMBLY-DEMS-315&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. ASSEMBLY SPEAKER WINS SUPPORT IN BID TO KEEP HIS JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The speaker of the state Assembly moved swiftly
to put down a revolt within his chamber Thursday, retaliating
against renegade lawmakers and enlisting the support of influential
union officials and party leaders to shore up his power base.
</P>
<P>
   The actions by the speaker, Sheldon Silver, D- Manhattan, came a
day after the second-most-powerful member of the Assembly, Michael
J. Bragman, announced that he would attempt to topple the speaker
in a vote next week. Silver immediately stripped Bragman of his
position as majority leader, cut his $34,500-a-year stipend and had
him locked out of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, a veteran assemblyman from the Syracuse area, is one of
the few Democratic leaders in the Assembly with enough broad-based
support among moderates, conservatives and a handful of liberals to
be seriously considered as a replacement for Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman on Thursday gave no indication that he intended to back
down, insisting that he had amassed enough support to unseat Silver
and, in the process, deprive New York City of the powerful
speaker's office for the first time in a quarter-century. Bragman
also released a strongly worded statement denouncing Silver's
leadership as self-serving, secretive and aloof.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman's maneuvering touched off turmoil within the chamber's
Democratic caucus, as lawmakers representing a broad range of
regional, ethnic and ideological interests jockeyed for the most
favorable position throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it was difficult to say who would prevail, in
part because many lawmakers declined to speak openly about where
their loyalties were, for fear of ending up on the losing side when
the tally was finally called. That said, Silver had managed to pick
up the support of key members of the Assembly by day's end,
strongly improving his prospects for survival.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Silver wasted no time in trying to reassert his control over the
chamber's increasingly fractious Democratic majority. He stripped
two lawmakers who sided with Bragman of their leadership titles and
then cut their annual pay by $12,500 each. Silver's surrogates
warned that other members ran the risk of losing their committee
assignments and other valuable perks if they joined the coup
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the intrigue on Thursday took place within the
Capitol's stone walls. Silver spent much of Wednesday night and
Thursday on the phone reaching out to some of his core supporters _
most notably Dennis Rivera, president of 1199, the politically
potent hospital workers' union, and Randi Weingarten, president of
the United Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday afternoon, Rivera offered his support
for Silver, crediting him with pushing several important measures
through the Legislature, including a plan to provide health care
coverage to hundreds of thousands of uninsured New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   He also sharply criticized Bragman and his supporters, saying
their actions hurt Democrats at a crucial moment. He said it was
important that party leaders present a united front in the campaign
to elect Hillary Rodham Clinton to the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are baffled by this,'' said Rivera, who is an influential
force within the Democratic Party. ``This smells of the crude
politics of insiders who are more interested in their political
careers than in the public good.''
</P>
<P>
   The toppling of a sitting speaker is a rare event in the
Legislature, and Bragman's threat left the Capitol in a state of
shock and confusion. The anxiety was even expressed by some
Republican leaders of the state Senate, who worried that such
dissension would eventually spread to their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The day was also filled with speculation over what prompted
Bragman to strike now. One theory had it that Silver had weakened
himself politically by attempting to block state Comptroller H.
Carl McCall's unofficial candidacy for governor in 2002 in favor of
Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of housing and urban development.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has built strong support with Democrats across the state,
and many members of the Assembly were angered by Silver's actions.
But Thursday, McCall, along with other Democratic officials,
strenuously denied that gubernatorial politics had anything to do
with the turbulent events of the last 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   McCall also sought to dismiss rumors that he had a role in
trying to topple Silver, rumors that have been fueled by the chilly
relationship between the two men over the years. ``It is not useful
for me to be involved in this in any way,'' he said, adding that
the timing of the coup attempt was bad given the need for Democrats
to unite in the current political season.
</P>
<P>
   The more likely explanation for Bragman's action was the role
played by Thomas J. Manton, the Queens Democratic leader. Manton
has had a long-running feud with Silver, and he recently offered to
deliver the borough's 15 Assembly members to Bragman provided he
moved quickly to topple Silver, according to people involved in the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Manton has accused Silver of encouraging Walter F. McCaffrey, a
New York City councilman, to wage a primary challenge against an
incumbent assemblyman, Joseph Crowley of Queens. Crowley is a close
ally of Manton.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Thursday night at the Queens County Democratic
Organization's annual dinner in Queens Village, Manton defended his
role in the coup attempt. ``Sometimes you have to fight the good
fight,'' he said to 400 guests. ``You can't let your members be
abused or not respected. When you are right, you fight. You don't
surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Bragman and Silver camps spent the day conducting head
counts. Many people expect that Silver will prevail in the end, but
they acknowledged that it was dangerous to dismiss completely
Bragman's chances, however dim.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Silver appeared to be consolidating his hold on the
Assembly by day's end, securing the support of some of the
chamber's most influential members, including Herman D. Farrell
Jr., the Democratic leader in Manhattan; Clarence Norman Jr., the
Democratic leader in Brooklyn; and Roberto Ramirez, the Democratic
leader in the Bronx. The support from these lawmakers strengthened
Silver's chances of survival.
</P>
<P>
   A speaker is traditionally chosen by the majority party's
members in an election held behind closed doors at the start of a
newly elected Legislature's two-year term. When a candidate emerges
with a majority _ in this case, 50 of the 98 Democrats _ the full
Assembly is convened and the members of the majority party unite
behind that candidate in a formal vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
