<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Health Giant Agrees to Fine To Settle Part of Fraud Case
</P>
<P>
   Columbia/HCA Healthcare, the nation's largest health care
company, has agreed in principle to pay $745 million in civil
penalties to resolve a portion of the government's inquiry into
whether its success was achieved in part by defrauding federal
health programs.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the settlement would be the largest health care
fraud settlement ever obtained by the Justice Department, exceeding
the next highest by more than 50 percent. But the deal does not
close the sprawling investigations into Columbia/HCA, some of which
have lasted more than seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Chief of JDS Uniphase Steps Down
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase, the component manufacturer for fiber optic
equipment, said that Kevin Kalkhoven had retired as co-chairman and
chief executive. Kalkhoven, 55, is succeeded by Jozef Straus, 53,
who has been co-chairman, president and chief operating officer
since the company was formed 18 months ago through the merger of
JDS Fitel and Uniphase. Shares of JDS Uniphase fell $5.75, to
$86.75.
</P>
<P>
   EPA Pressed 3M on Scotchgard
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency said that it had pressed
Minnesota Mining &AMP; Manufacturing to come up with a solution after
the company's tests did prove that a chemical compound used in
Scotchgard and other household products could pose a risk to human
health and the environment. The EPA account differs from that of
3M, which said that it had voluntarily decided to stop making the
chemical by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Falter in a Technology Slump
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks slumped as investors became concerned about
developments at several companies. The Nasdaq composite index fell
106.25 points, or 2.9 percent, to 3,538.71. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index dropped 10.59 points, to 1,437.21, while the Dow
Jones industrials rose 7.54 points, to 10,777.28.
</P>
<P>
   MetLife Prepares to Enter Banking
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since Congress eliminated barriers last fall
that prevented banks and insurance companies from intermingling
their businesses, a major insurance company, MetLife, said that one
of its units was taking steps to go into full-service banking.
</P>
<P>
   ABC to Promote Its Soap Operas
</P>
<P>
   The ABC television network is introducing an ambitious
advertising campaign intended to stimulate demand among consumers
16 to 24 for four of its daytime soap operas _ ``All My Children,''
``General Hospital,'' ``One Life to Live'' and ``Port Charles.''
The ads present younger cast members from the four soaps. Each is
identified with a word meant to describe the character, including
the ``Rebel.''
</P>
<P>
   Competing Social Security Plans
</P>
<P>
   Social Security is slowly going broke, Vice President Al Gore
and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas agree, but they differ on the
solutions for fixing it. Gore would channel the benefits of the
federal budget surplus into the system. Bush would establish
private investment accounts through which workers could seek higher
returns on their contributions to the retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   European Inquiry Into Coke Widens
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the European Commission raided Coca-Cola's
office in Brussels as well as the office of the company's largest
bottler, in London, expanding an inquiry into Coke's marketing
practices that began last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner Bank to Lay Off 5,000
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner Bank, which abandoned a merger with Deutsche Bank last
month, is expected to announce plans Friday for reducing its work
force by 5,000 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
