<HEADER>
A9413 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NABISCO-NYT     05-18 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE SUITORS SAID TO HOLD TALKS ON DEAL FOR NABISCO
</HEADLINE>
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Cadbury Schweppes, the big British confectioner and
beverage company, and the French global foods giant Groupe Danone
have held talks about possibly making a combined bid for Nabisco
Holdings, executives close to the negotiations said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have been feeling each other out, according to one
of the executives, but no decision has been made to proceed with a
combined takeover proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fact that two of Europe's leading food companies are
talking to each other about collaborating to acquire Nabisco's food
business is the latest example of globalization in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   It coincides with another big international food takeover
attempt, a $19 billion proposal to buy Bestfoods, the maker of
Hellman's mayonnaise and Skippy peanut butter, made by Unilever,
the British-Dutch consumer products giant.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco, the maker of Ritz crackers, Oreos and Grey Poupon
mustard, has effectively put itself up for sale by running an
auction for control of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cadbury Schweppes and Danone had made independent bids
during the auction's first round for parts of Nabisco, according to
the executives.
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury Schweppes and Danone are considering joining forces
because it would allow each company to acquire the parts of Nabisco
that strategically fit best.
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury Schweppes is most interested in Nabisco's confectionary
business, including LifeSavers and Breath Savers.
</P>
<P>
   Danone, the world's largest biscuit company but one that is
lacking any major brands in the United States, wants to acquire
Nabisco's cookie and cracker business to add to its biscuit
portfolio, which includes Lu and Britannia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power of the sum of the parts could improve their
chances,'' said Jaine I. Mehring, an analyst at Salomon Smith
Barney. ``But these deals are hard to pull off.''
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury Schweppes and Danone would be competing with several
other interested suitors including Philip Morris, which owns Kraft,
and the financier Carl C. Icahn, who said last week that he would
be willing to pay about $22 a share or $6.5 billion for the Nabisco
Group, which owns 80.6 percent of Nabisco Holdings. Analysts have
said the company could be sold for more than twice that amount.
</P>
<P>
   The Nabisco Group is the remnant of what was once RJR Nabisco
and retains certain liabilities from its tobacco days. The prospect
of continuing litigation has depressed its stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Steven F. Goldstone, the company's chairman,
announced that he was breaking up RJR Nabisco, which was once the
object of a fierce takeover battle that symbolized Wall Street's
excesses in the 1980s. He sold the R.J. Reynolds' international
tobacco division for $8 billion to Japan Tobacco, spun off the
domestic tobacco business as R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, and left
Nabisco shares in what was renamed the Nabisco Group.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Icahn, who has tried unsuccessfully to buy RJR
Nabisco four times, argued that the food business would still be
subject to tobacco-lawsuit liability and that it made more sense to
spin off the food business and leave the tobacco company as part of
the Nabisco Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
