r s BC-RAC-HADDOCK-COLUMN-LA     05-18 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HADDOCK-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARN HOPING FOR A JUMP-START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richie Hearn is hoping this month's Indianapolis 500 can
jump-start his racing career.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Pasadena (Calif.) High graduate raced in the
Indianapolis 500, he finished third, the top rookie in the field in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he's back with a new team and trying to recapture
some of that magic from four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his podium finish, Hearn looked like a rising
star in Indy racing. Unfortunately, while Hearn shined at Indy, the
open-wheel racing world was scarred by civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Hearn finished well in a depleted field at Indy in 1996. Most of
the top drivers were essentially banned from competing as
Championship Auto Racing Teams _ the governing body of the FedEx
Series _ and Indianapolis Motor Speedway owner Tony George were
engaged in a bitter battle.
</P>
<P>
   George was looking to make a safer and slower racing circuit.
CART wanted to stay the course with faster, more powerful racing
machines. Out of this contrast in philosophies the Indy Racing
League was born, with the Indianapolis 500 as its crown jewel. And
CART drivers and owners were left to either follow George's new
rules or not compete at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   Many CART owners chose not to compete. Hearn's team owner, John
Della Penna, was one of the few CART owners who wanted to run at
Indy in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Hearn and Della Penna struggled through three
disappointing years on the CART FedEx Series. Before the 2000
season started, Della Penna released Hearn from his contract and
decided to sign Brazilian Norberto Fontana.
</P>
<P>
   Without a team and his future dim, Hearn was approached by Pagan
Racing Team owner Allan Pagan before an IRL race at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   He offered Hearn a chance to race at Indy, something Hearn has
wanted to do since his first taste in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for anyone to want to race here,''
Hearn said. ``Every year I watched it on TV. I was very upset, and
I wanted to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Pagan offered Hearn a chance to return to Indianapolis,
Hearn jumped at it.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Hearn given an opportunity to return to auto
racing, but he was driving for a team that finished second in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Ward, who drives for A.J. Racing, finished second for Pagan
Racing in two events in 1999, at Indianapolis and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Pagan Racing had a strong car for Indy last year, it
is struggling this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are not looking good out there,'' Hearn said of his
team's Dellara Aurora. ``We're the slowest car out there.''
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's practice session, Hearn was the 37th-fastest
car at 213.935 mph. Scott Sharp turned the fastest lap in 223.936
mph. The top 33 cars qualify for the May 28 race.
</P>
<P>
   And his team has been unable to make adjustments to get the car
up to speed. Still, Hearn plans to make the most of his time at
Indianapolis, as this might be a one-shot deal with Pagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not planning anything more than this race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   HORNADAY'S TEAM FINED, PENALIZED: The crew chief and owner of
Ron Hornaday Jr.'s No.3 NASCAR Busch Grand National Division
Chevrolet were penalized and fined Monday for rules violations
during the Hardee's 250 at Richmond International Raceway on May 5.
</P>
<P>
   Crew chief David Lackey was suspended until June 7 for using an
illegal fuel mixture in the car during qualifying. Team owner Ron
Alexander was fined $10,000 and penalized six points in the owner
standings.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHWEST SERIES: The NASCAR Featherlite Southwest Series heads
to Pikes Peak International Raceway in Colorado for Sunday's
Sunstate Equipment Company 100.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Woodside of Saugus, Calif., and Greg Pursley of Newhall,
Calif., have already posted victories this season on the Southwest
Series. Other area drivers, including Bob Lyon of Agua Dulce,
Calif., are hoping Pikes Peak will lead them to victory lane. This
is the first time the Southwest Series has competed at Pikes Peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, we've always done pretty well when we've gone
some place new,'' Lyon said, a Southwest Series veteran with three
career wins. ``When the series went to Tucson Raceway for the first
time, we won.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest Series will accompany the NASCAR Craftsman Truck
Series race Sunday at Pikes Peak.
</P>
<P>
   IRWINDALE SPEEDWAY: Walt Johnson of Sun Valley won the USAC
Three-Quarter Midget feature Saturday night at Irwindale (Calif.)
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   In other action, James Weston of Goleta won the NASCAR Late
Model feature, Jeff Green of Long Beach won the NASCAR Super Stock
feature and Kenny Smith of El Monte won the MSRA Pro-4 Modified
feature. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
