<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-WOMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN BAPTIST PROPOSAL SAYS BIBLE ALLOWS ONLY MEN TO BE
PASTORS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors: the Rev. Cathe Nixon is cq) 
 
By RICHARD VARA 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) The Bible allows only men to be church pastors,
according to a proposal announced Thursday by a key leadership
committee of Southern Baptist churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``While both men and women are gifted for service in the church,
the office of pastor is limited to men as qualified by Scripture,''
the proposed revision to the Southern Baptist Convention's Baptist
Faith and Message doctrinal statement says. It will be voted on
next month at the denomination's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that for the vast majority of Southern Baptists
this is a shift in belief,'' said the Rev. Richard Land, president
of the convention's Ethics and Religious Liberty Commission. ``The
Bible, in the New Testament, has specifically forbidden a woman
from assuming the office of a pastor of a local congregation.''
</P>
<P>
   If adopted, the proposal would have the effect of strongly
discouraging Southern Baptist congregations from calling women as
pastors. But it could not legally prevent them from doing so,
because such congregations are self-governing.
</P>
<P>
   Land, who is based in Nashville, Tenn., emphasized that the
revision does not prohibit women from ministries such as teaching
in seminaries or even leading a convention agency. ``It does not
preclude women from being called to full-time ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   But a pastor is the spiritual head of a church.
</P>
<P>
   The ban on women pastors is consistent with positions the
conservative-controlled convention has articulated throughout the
past 20 years. But adding it to the doctrinal statement sparked
criticism from moderate leaders and women ministers.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is among several recommended by a 15-member
committee appointed last year by the convention's conservative
leaders to review and update the denomination's basic statement of
faith. In addition to stands against abortion and euthanasia, the
recommendations call for Southern Baptists to ``oppose racism,
every form of greed, selfishness and vice, and all forms of sexual
immorality including adultery, homosexuality and pornography.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Baptist ancestors of a mere generation ago could not have
imagined the need to address the issues of abortion, homosexuality,
euthanasia and all manner of deviant and pagan sexuality,'' said
the Rev. Adrian Rogers, a pastor from the Memphis, Tenn., area who
chaired the committee. ``We answer with a clear word of biblical
correction.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctrinal statement, last revised in 1963, will be voted on
at the denomination's annual meeting in June in Orlando, Fla. It is
not binding on the convention's 15.9 million members in 41,000
churches, which are autonomous and independently call pastors to
serve. But convention agency and seminary employees are bound to
support the statement if required by supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction is one of sadness in that I and several female and
male ministers feel differently on this issue,'' said the Rev.
Cathe Nixon, minister to children at Willow Meadows Baptist Church
in southwest Houston. ``I truly believe in God's grace and God's
call and I think that it extends to all, no matter race or
gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon is an associate pastor at the 400-member church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, (the ban) is not new,'' Nixon said. ``It keeps
rearing its ugly head from time to time. I think scripturally that
God created male and female equal.''
</P>
<P>
   Few women serve as pastors in Southern Baptist churches,
although their numbers are growing in other Protestant
denominations. Of an estimated 1,000 women who have been ordained
in the Southern Baptist church, only 50 to 100 are believed to
serve as pastors. The others are associate pastors, educators or
ministers of music. Nixon estimates 10 other Southern Baptist women
are ministers in Houston but none are pastors.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The proposed revision) is evidence the Southern Baptist
Convention is controlled by white male fundamentalist pastors,''
said the Rev. Daniel Vestal, leader of the moderate Cooperative
Baptist Fellowship based in Atlanta. The fellowship is part of the
national Southern Baptist group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that statement is based on a bad interpretation of
Scripture. It is based on an insensitivity to the Holy Spirit and I
believe an unwillingness to see what God is doing in the world
today,'' said Vestal, a former Houston pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Also disagreeing with the proposal is the Rev. Cynthia Clawson
Courtney, co-pastor with her husband, the Rev. Reagan Courtney, of
Tarrytown Baptist Church in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all about power,'' Cynthia Courtney said. ``That whole
thing is a power struggle, about men who want to be in charge of
everything. If it hadn't been for women in the Baptist church, the
church would not be here.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the statement banning women from
pastoring implicitly accepts women as being ordained for other
pastoral roles such as chaplains. The denomination, the largest
Protestant group in the United States, has been criticized for
hewing to traditional roles for women.
</P>
<P>
   An amendment to the doctrinal statement in 1998 called for a
wife to ``submit graciously'' to her husband's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
