r s BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-18 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL HAIL THE CONQUEROR, SORT OF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif _ John Shirreffs enjoys a slightly different
view of Fusaichi Pegasus than other trainers who have run horses
against the Kentucky Derby champion.
</P>
<P>
   He, alone, has the view from the front.
</P>
<P>
   A Shirreffs-trained colt named David Copperfield has been the
only horse to finish ahead of Fusaichi Pegasus, the odds-on
favorite to win the Preakness Stakes in Baltimore on Saturday and
move within a Belmont victory of the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``A footnote to history,'' Shirreffs said with a bittersweet
smile Thursday morning outside his Hollywood Park barn.
</P>
<P>
   David Copperfield and Fusaichi Pegasus were making their racing
debuts when they went into the starting gate for a 6-furlong sprint
for 2-year-olds at Hollywood Park on Dec. 11. Each drew strong
support from handicappers, David Copperfield going off at 7-2 odds
because of his pedigree (Halo is his sire) and Shirreffs'
reputation for winning with a high percentage of first-time
starters, Fusaichi Pegasus at 3-1 because of his breeding (Mr.
Prospector) and his $4 million auction price.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, neither was the betting favorite, that honor going
to Bob Baffert-trained first-timer Tribunal (2-1), who'd recorded a
series of fast workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rumor on the backstretch was that (Neil) Drysdale had a
monster,'' Shirreffs recalled.
</P>
<P>
   After Shirreffs entered David Copperfield in the $33,000 race,
he looked at the entry list, and there was the monster.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, ridden that day by Victor Espinoza, and David
Copperfield, ridden by Eddie Delahoussaye, both trailed pacesetter
Hoover Tower for one-quarter mile. Fusaichi Pegasus, at the rail
after breaking from post 1, moved up inside to challenge for the
lead on the turn and was in front turning into the stretch. David
Copperfield came to him on the outside and they kicked clear of the
other eight horses.
</P>
<P>
   The two were five lengths in front of the field as David
Copperfield outfought Fusaichi Pegasus to win by a neck. Tribunal
finished eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were head-and-head at the top of the lane,'' Shirreffs
said. ``David Copperfield, in that situation, is a very game
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirreffs said he concentrated on watching his own horse during
the race and didn't form an impression of Drysdale's monster. But
he has had plenty of opportunities to size up Fusaichi Pegasus
since then.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after that losing debut, Fusaichi Pegasus went off
as a 1-5 favorite and won by two lengths, beginning the five-race
winning streak that includes dominating victories in the Wood
Memorial and Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's quite a horse,'' Shirreffs said. ``I always thought his
problem would be the big crowd at Churchill Downs. He handled that
so well, I think he's got a real good chance to maybe sweep it (the
Triple Crown). That puts him up with Secretariat and Citation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the distance will be a problem,'' he said of the
Preakness' 1 3/16 miles _ 110 yards shorter than the Derby _ and
the Belmont's 1 miles. ``I don't think the competition will be a
problem. I think it's a matter of the attrition and whether running
three times in five weeks will catch up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirreffs said he knew Fusaichi Pegasus was special when he saw
the colt finish out strongly to beat The Deputy in the San Felipe
Stakes at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   Now he roots for Fusaichi Pegasus _ not because that colt's
success is flattering to David Copperfield but because ``I like
Neil (Drysdale), and he's a California horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, David Copperfield, a brown colt built like a
linebacker, has not kept pace with the horse he defeated four
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth in an allowance sprint at Santa Anita in January, he
bounced back to win a mile race at the same level in March, and
went into the California Derby at Golden Gate Fields on April 15
with a chance to earn a trip to the Kentucky Derby. But he pulled
Delahoussaye to the lead prematurely and finished third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had he won, we would have gone to Kentucky with him,''
Shirreffs said. ``But he didn't settle into the race.''
</P>
<P>
   So Shirreffs is shopping for an allowance race to use as a prep
for the $100,000 Cinema Handicap, to be held on the Hollywood Park
turf course June 10. David Copperfield is bred to run well on turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still expect big things out of David Copperfield,'' his
trainer said.
</P>
<P>
   June 10 is the day of the Belmont, the day Fusaichi Pegasus
could go for the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of wonder what went wrong, why we're not at least
competing,'' said Shirreffs, who had several Derby prospects in
December. ``You always say, `Maybe if I'd done (ital)this(endital)
a little differently.' But I think the horse has to develop. Horses
develop at different times.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirreffs and David Copperfield face uncertain futures. Marshall
Naify, the owner for whom Shirreffs has trained privately since
1994, died recently at age 80, and the 30 horses are expected to be
dispersed at auction.
</P>
<P>
   Shirreffs, a soft-spoken 54-year-old, will have to seek new
clients. David Copperfield will probably have a new trainer. But
one thing they'll always have is the distinction of beating the
Derby winner. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti is a Daily News columnist. His horse racing column
appears on Friday. He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
