<SLUG> BC-RAILWAY-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAILWAY KILLER CONVICTED, ASKS FOR DEATH PENALTY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After being convicted Thursday of capital murder in
the death of Dr. Claudia Benton, Angel Maturino Resendiz told the
judge he would rather be executed than spend the next 40 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've decided that injection is better than spending life in
jail, so I want to do that,'' he said, with the jury out of the
courtroom. ``I'm 41, plus 40 years is 81, and I might not make it
all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors convicted Maturino Resendiz of murdering Benton in her
West University Place home in the Houston area on Dec. 17, 1998.
Now they must decide whether to sentence him to death or life in
prison, which requires that he serve at least 40 years before the
possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   Moments before the verdict was announced, Maturino Resendiz
looked at his mother among the courtroom spectators. She patted her
chest twice and began breathing heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Showing no emotion, Maturino Resendiz stood as jurors were
polled about their decision. His mother looked up and wept quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of other victims embraced. Benton's husband, George,
sitting in the front row, looked at Maturino Resendiz and nodded
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz, who said he was an angel on a mission from
God to destroy evil people, has confessed to six slayings in Texas,
two in Illinois and one in Kentucky from 1997 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   He had pleaded not guilty by reason of insanity to Benton's
murder. To acquit him, jurors would have had to believe Maturino
Resendiz suffered from a mental disease that prevented him from
knowing his actions were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Before testimony began in the punishment phase of the trial,
Maturino Resendiz asked to speak with state District Judge Bill
Harmon, then told him he wanted the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon and Harris County District Attorney John B. Holmes Jr.
reminded Maturino Resendiz that presenting no case and not
cross-examining prosecution witnesses might actually earn him
jurors' sympathy and persuade them to sentence him to life.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz responded, ``I've got some plans for that.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, including his defense team, knew what the comment meant.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of the unusual hearing, defense attorney Allen
Tanner said to Maturino Resendiz, ``I'm still going to try to talk
you out of that. Is that OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz replied, ``I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon told Maturino Resendiz he could change his mind at any
time.
</P>
<P>
   Wary of Maturino Resendiz's remark about his ``plans,'' bailiffs
stood within two feet of him every time his attorneys stepped away
from their table or a weapon was produced for evidence. Another
bailiff guarded the exit nearest the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Opening the punishment phase, prosecutor Devon Anderson told the
jurors they must now answer two questions: Is Maturino Resendiz a
continuing threat to society, and are there any mitigating
circumstances why he should not be put to death?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've heard the defendant's excuses,'' she said. ``But we're
going to tell you about the (nine victims) ...
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is a career burglar who's developed a taste
for murder and rape.''
</P>
<P>
   John Benton, the victim's brother-in-law, tearfully recounted
the day his brother was told about the murder while visiting him in
Arizona with the couple's twin daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to do. I just screamed. ... He was beside
himself,'' John Benton said, weeping openly. Several jurors cried
throughout his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   He said his brother and nieces never returned to the home where
Dr. Benton died while struggling fiercely for her life. Maturino
Resendiz bludgeoned her with a statue, stabbed her in the back,
then raped her as she lay dying.
</P>
<P>
   The family lived in a friend's townhouse until the girls
finished the school year, then moved to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never lived in that house again,'' John Benton said. ``He
never returned to work (in the oil industry) ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say he's lost, but he is. He's got two girls.
He wakes them up in the morning. He makes them breakfast. He sends
them to school and waits for them to come home from school,
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Obeying their client's request, defense lawyers gave no opening
statement and cross-examined no witnesses. Tanner made only a few
technical objections for the record.
</P>
<P>
   An appeal is automatic, but Maturino Resendiz has told his
lawyers he does not want one.
</P>
<P>
   Facing an overwhelming amount of physical evidence, such as
fingerprints and DNA linking Maturino Resendiz to each scene,
Tanner has acknowledged his client is the killer.
</P>
<P>
   But he called on experts to testify that Maturino Resendiz is a
paranoid schizophrenic who suffered delusions he was ``half angel,
half man,'' was drawn to his victims by a sense of evil and was
forced to kill them because it was ``God's will.''
</P>
<P>
   The state countered with experts who said no matter how strange
Maturino Resendiz's religious beliefs, he knew right from wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz surrendered to Texas Ranger Drew Carter in
July at the Mexican border after an international manhunt. Before
that day, Maturino Resendiz had continued to kill, often taunting
police at each scene by leaving newspaper articles about himself in
plain view and placing a toy train at one.
</P>
<P>
   The state is expected to call about 20 more witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
