<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9543 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-COLONIAL-HNS &LR;      05-18 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
FORT WORTH _ A self-described ``underachiever'' because of his
putting, Keith Clearwater could be a poster boy for the PGA Tour.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The poster would read: Don't let this happen to you.
</P>
<P>
   Clearwater, twice a winner on the PGA Tour, including at the
1987 Colonial, disappeared from the golf world for so long, people
thought he was retired. Fame was fleeting, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   After dealing with an inclination to bulk up his body in the
early 1990s, the death of his father-in-law and that dreaded
flatstick in the past few years, Clearwater found himself back in
the limelight Thursday after a first-round 67 left him solidly
entrenched in the second-place logjam at the MasterCard Colonial on
a windy, threatening day.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable part about it is Clearwater remembered the way to
the limelight. It had been awhile since he had seen it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has kind of been my unfortunate story,'' he said. ``In my
opinion, I've been a significant underachiever because of a poor
putter.''
</P>
<P>
   That fickle club has caused Clearwater much aggravation in his
career. Not to mention some embarrassment that he's living through
this year.
</P>
<P>
   He's a full-time resident of the Buy.com Tour, which is the
underling of the PGA Tour. It's not a pleasant place for somebody
who has $2.2 million in career earnings on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very humbling experience,'' Clearwater, 40, said.
``It's a pride issue with us (guys who have had success at the PGA
Tour level). You're like, `Oh joy, I get to play here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fact of the matter is that you better shut up and
perform. Or else you'll belong here (on the Buy.com). Until you do
something to change it, that's where you belong.''
</P>
<P>
   He's trying to change it this week. Clearwater would be leading
the tournament if not for an eagle-2 at the sixth hole by John
Cook, who carded a 4-under-par 66.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clearwater, Cook has seen better days. He called his 2000
season terrible and is just happy to have a chance to be in the
hunt at a tournament. But if Cook thinks it's tough struggling on
the PGA Tour, try surviving at the bottom-feeder level.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put the top 30 guys (from the PGA Tour) onto the
Buy.com Tour, there'd be a bunch of guys missing cuts,'' Clearwater
said. ``Making cuts is not easy. You only have 55 players (plus
ties) making the cut. The depth isn't as good on the Buy.com Tour.
But there are a lot of good players.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearwater showed his play still functions well at the PGA Tour
level. He hasn't made a cut since 1998, missing all seven times he
entered events last year and going 0-for-3 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, he got to 3 under par with birdies at each of his
final three holes. He put a knock-down 6-iron inside 10 feet at the
par-3 16th, then hit a 9-iron on the 17th and sand wedge on No. 18,
both to 12 feet. That he made the putts was the surprising
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's allowing me to be competitive is that the putter has
been working,'' Clearwater said. ``And that hasn't been the case
for a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Clearwater's game hasn't been a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm No. 1 in scoring on the Buy.com Tour and No. 1 in overall
statistics on the Buy.com Tour, so my game is good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't far off, although in this week's statistics, he
was No. 2 in both categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing great golf out there,'' he said. ``I was
second in Shreveport, and should have won by 20, quite honestly.
This is not a shock. I don't have any doubt that playing a full
year on the Buy.com Tour, I'll regain my (PGA Tour) card. And
that's the No. 1 goal. I also don't think it would be a stretch to
come here and play well for four days and have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, it took only one day for Clearwater to play well and
win at Colonial. That year, rain washed out the Saturday action and
there was a 36-hole finale set for Sunday. Clearwater shot 64-64
and won the tournament with a huge rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a momentum golf course,'' he said. ``It'll keep you
honest on some holes and others you can take advantage. Sometimes
the perfect play is hitting it 40 feet (and taking par).''
</P>
<P>
   Clearwater's history has taken some strange turns. He bought two
Gold's Gyms early in the '90s and got on a weightlifting kick that,
some say, destroyed his golf swing. Clearwater doesn't believe
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '92, when I was doing the most lifting, I had my best
year,'' he said. ``I was in the top 25 on the money list (22nd) and
if I had putted well, I'd have won eight times.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearwater's more recent past hasn't been as fun. He lost his
father-in-law, Jim Starley, to leukemia a year and a half ago. For
more than a year before that, he and his wife, Sue, cared for
Starley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically took myself away from golf,'' Clearwater said. ``I
really just decided this year that I still had a lot I wanted to
accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't elaborate, Clearwater said he had some ``silly''
goals and the words ``Ryder Cup'' slipped out of his mouth once. He
has a long way to go to qualify for the 2001 American team. But if
he continues to play like he did Thursday, anything's possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get all the way back,'' he said. ``I'm not out
here just to make money. I truly feel my best 10 years are in front
of me.''
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, they can't be much worse than the past few
have been, as long as the putter cooperates.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
