</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS LOSE ADVANTAGE AS FLYERS CROWD BRODEUR
</HEADLINE>
  By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The home advantage the New Jersey Devils
took away from the Philadelphia Flyers in Philadelphia over the
weekend went back down the New Jersey Turnpike Thursday night as
the Flyers came up with a 4-2 victory to take a lead of 2-1 in
their Eastern Conference final series.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had the territorial advantage for the most part
before a sellout crowd at Continental Arena, but they were stymied
by Brian Boucher, the Flyers' rookie goaltender, who had 27 saves,
including a number that were spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher was beaten only by Claude Lemieux and Scott Niedermayer,
who scored from the slot with a crowd in front of the Philadelphia
net with 4 minutes 1 second left in the game. The Flyers got the
goal back when Simon Gagne went around defenseman Brian Rafalski
with 1:49 remaining to close out the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Recchi, Keith Jones and Rick Tocchet also scored for the
Flyers against Martin Brodeur, who had 17 saves and failed to match
Boucher's performance.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils played without the injured center John Madden, their
top defensive forward, and were also hampered by turnovers as they
suffered their first loss in the last nine games at home.
</P>
<P>
   A turnover by Vladimir Malakhov led to the first goal by the
Flyers, just 2 minutes 57 seconds into the game. The Devils' lanky
Russian defenseman lost the puck to Recchi just outside the New
Jersey blue line, creating a 2-on-1 break with John LeClair, who
returned Recchi's pass for the goal from close range to the right
of Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   Malakhov redeemed himself somewhat just under two minutes later
with a precision pass from out of his zone to Lemieux, who was
streaking through the neutral zone. Lemieux entered Philadelphia's
zone by splitting two defensemen and beat Boucher over the stick
from between the circles for his third goal of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers went to the net with authority later in the period,
and got a goal for their efforts. Jones barreled into Brodeur in
the crease and converted a rebound from a shot by Keith Primeau
that hit Brodeur on the chest and dropped in front.
</P>
<P>
   Following that score, with 5:46 left in the period, the Devils
had two good opportunities before intermission but Boucher denied
Petr Sykora from point-blank range by sprawling to his left and
Scott Gomez at his left doorstep when Gomez tried to jam the puck
past him.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher made a huge save during the first power play in the game
for the Flyers. Just 12 seconds after the first intermission,
Lemieux was caught high-sticking Recchi. Patrik Elias, one of the
penalty killers for the Devils, broke away alone shortly before the
penalty expired and tried to deke Boucher with a move from right to
left. Boucher found himself on his back to Elias' right. He
appeared to be at Elias' mercy, but he stretched out his right arm
and covered the puck with the back of it. Elias looked at the
scoreboard screen when a replay of the action came on and shook his
head in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet extended the Flyers' lead to two goals with his third
goal in two games. It came 7:15 into the middle period, shortly
after the Flyers killed their first penalty in the game. Taking a
pass from Primeau down the right flank, Tocchet fired a shot from
the right circle that hit Brodeur inside his right leg before
hitting the net.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams played without key centers injured in Game 2. Madden
missed the game for the Devils because of a knee injury that will
keep him out indefinitely. His place was taken by Steve Brule, who
made his NH L debut.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said before the game that he selected Brule over Steve
Kelly as a replacement for Madden because Brule was good at
faceoffs. But Brule lost seven of the nine faceoffs he took in the
first two periods, including four of five in the first.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers, already playing without their superstar center Eric
Lindros, who is out with a concussion, were also without center
Daymond Langkow, who sustained a concussion when he was hit in open
ice by Scott Stevens Tuesday night 39 seconds after scoring what
turned out to be the winning goal in Philadelphia's 4-3 victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
