<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-18 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9546 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RANGERS-CANSECO-TEX     05-18 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-CANSECO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANSECO SOUNDING UPBEAT ABOUT FUTURE WITH RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1996 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ Fortunately for Keith Clearwater, he earns a living
by playing golf, not predicting its outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after posting a 67 in Thursday's opening round of the
MasterCard Colonial, Clearwater dismissed himself as an
afterthought in the proceedings. Swirling winds, which reached 25
mph, were dying, and Clearwater envisioned bushels of birdies for
those who followed him down ``Hogan's Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone's going to shoot 6 under, and everything I'm saying is
going to be shuffled into the recycle bin,'' said Clearwater, the
1987 Colonial champ.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   It took a chip-in eagle by John Cook, playing in one of the
final three groups of the day, to bump Clearwater from a share of
the top spot on the Colonial leader board.
</P>
<P>
   Cook emerged from a blustery day at refurbished Colonial with a
66, almost six strokes below the average score (71.7) posted by the
110 starters in Thursday's opening round. Cook stands at 4-under
par, a stroke ahead of an eight-player group that includes
Clearwater, Davis Love III, Phil Mickelson and David Toms.
</P>
<P>
   Cook is two strokes ahead of a five-player knot at 68 that
includes Irving resident Joel Edwards, Frank Nobilo and Rocco
Mediate. Cook is one of 25 players _ 10 morning starters, 15
afternoon starters _ who broke even-par 70 on a course that has
received a $3.5 million face-lift since the final putt dropped at
the 1999 Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   The makeover included 18 rebuilt greens and several repositioned
fairway bunkers. The result? Cook's 66 matched the highest score
posted by a first-round leader at Colonial since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, who collected 15 pars, two birdies and an eagle, said he
was pleased to play a bogey-free round amid the swirling gusts. The
new greens, he said, were firm and created a guessing game on
approach shots when combined with intermittent winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to pull the right club out there,'' said Cook, who
began his round at 1:20 p.m., roughly an hour after Clearwater
finished. ``The afternoon (starters) didn't get the wind that the
morning guys did, but the wind really baked out the greens. When
you put this golf course with firm greens, low scores aren't going
to happen very often.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course has stood the test of time without making it so no
one can play it. It defies all of today's architectural standards.
It doesn't have to be 8,000 yards long, with forced carries over
bunkers, to make it difficult. I'm not that surprised by the
scores. You're not going to make many birdies around here. You have
to eliminate the `others.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In golf parlance, ``other'' is a score above bogey on a given
hole. Cook had none of those. That is why he got so much mileage
out of his chip-in for eagle at the sixth hole. Cook's 9-iron from
127 yards landed 12 feet short of the pin, rolled up to the pin and
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way this year's been going, I expected it to hit the pin
and bounce off the green,'' said Cook, who ranks 169th on the money
list ($46,231) and has not finished higher than 22nd at a PGA Tour
event this season. ``When it went in, I thought, `There we go.'''
</P>
<P>
   The shot allowed Cook to climb all the way to the top of a
leader board on a day when several headliners stumbled. Masters
champ Vijay Singh failed to post a single birdie in a round of 73.
That matched the score of Justin Leonard and Mark O'Meara, a pair
of former British Open champs, as well as Fort Worth native Hunter
Haas, the nation's top-ranked amateur. Fort Worth resident Mark
Brooks struggled home with a 75. Ben Crenshaw, a two-time Colonial
champ, ballooned to a 77.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't ask Len Mattiace, a member of the 3-under group, to
explain the soaring scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought scores would be lower,'' said Mattiace, whose round
included a 30-foot putt to save par and a 45-footer for birdie.
``When you played downwind shots, the ball would bounce and run.
When you played into the wind, the green would be receptive.''
</P>
<P>
   But the trick, said Toms, was reading the new greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a tip from a local caddie who told me not to play as
much break as you might see,'' said Toms, who needed just 28 putts
during a round of 67. ``I thought the greens were perfect. But I
don't think they're breaking as much as they look like.''
</P>
<P>
   They broke enough Thursday to provide Clearwater, a member of
the Buy.com Tour, an extended stay on the Colonial leader board.
Barring rain, Cook said he expects no major changes in the final
three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a golf course where you have to make a bunch of
birdies to win,'' Cook said. ``They've got new greens. But par is
still a good score around here.'' nn
</P>
